<HEADLINE>
PEREZ PUT ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Carlos Perez's troubled season officially ended Tuesday
when the Dodgers' exiled left-hander was placed on the 60-day
disabled list with a deep bone bruise in his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were hoping to put Perez back in the starting
rotation after one more minor-league start. But he was struck on
the right leg by a line drive 10 days ago and the club decided he
was in no shape to pitch again this season.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who had the worst season of his five-year major-league
career, finished 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA. He was optioned to Triple-A
Albuquerque on July 28 and made four starts. But he never regained
the command or velocity that made him a quality starter for
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had hoped to get him one more start at Albuquerque and then
evaluate him in September,'' manager Davey Johnson said. ``But when
he hurt his leg, it put him so far behind. There was no reason to
bring him back at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, signed to a four-year, $15.5 million, never got on track
this season. He was 0-7 at Dodger Stadium and his fastball rarely
reached the mid-80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would be the first to tell you he was not prepared for this
season,'' Johnson said. ``He had some other issues, but he did
nothing to adjust this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he seemed to be doing some good things at Albuquerque. He
was the first one to the ballpark and he seemed to be enjoying
baseball again.
</P>
<P>
   __ More moves:In addition to the Perez decision, the Dodgers
recalled right-hander Jamie Arnold, infielders Juan Castro and Alex
Cora from Triple-A. The club also purchased the contract of
left-hander Jeff Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold spent most of the season with the Dodgers, posting a 2-3
record and 4.91 ERA in 32 games. He made three starts for the
Dodgers but was sent down Aug. 23 and went 0-2 with a 9.53 ERA for
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Castro and Cora played for the Dodgers in 1998 but did not make
the big leagues this season. Castro, perhaps the best defensive
player in the organization, signed a two-year, $400,000 contract
last winter but was not a good fit, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased with him in spring training and I even
think he'll hit in the big leagues,'' Johnson said. ``But he was a
right-handed bat on a team with too many right-handers.''
</P>
<P>
   Cora, brother of former big-league second baseman Joey Cora, did
not make the majors this year after breaking his right hand during
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   __ Floyd wants out, sort of: Florida's left-handed-hitting left
fielder Cliff Floyd, who has drawn interest from the Dodgers, was
scheduled to return to the Marlins lineup Tuesday after missing 10
weeks with a torn right Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   But when Floyd arrived several minutes late for a pregame
workout, he was benched by manager John Boles. Floyd also opened
the season on the disabled list after surgery on his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   He is in the first season of a four-year $19 million contract
after having 22 homers and 90 RBI in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd is angry but will not demand a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Boles) wants to scratch me for that, fine,'' Floyd said.
``I've had it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick hits: Dodgers starter Eric Gagne is one of four
Canadian pitchers in the big leagues. The others: Florida's Ryan
Dempster (Gagne's opponent Tuesday night), Texas reliever Jeff
Zimmerman and Angels injured right-hander Jason Dickson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
