<HEADLINE>
CITY STRIKES DEAL WITH PIPELINE COMPANY ON SAFETY IMPROVEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olympic Pipe Line Co. has agreed to extensive testing,
monitoring and safety improvements to win the right to repair the
10-mile section of line through Bellingham, Wash., closed since a
deadly explosion in June.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-month agreement with the city of Bellingham puts
restrictions on Olympic that are tougher than what federal
regulators require.
</P>
<P>
   Tests using water pressure, for example, will be performed at
such high levels that failures may be likely. The company also will
have to install at least three new valves and employ a second
leak-detection system.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic also has committed to study the idea of moving the
pipeline outside the city limits.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is rare among pipeline companies and municipal
governments. In Washington state, most local governments have
franchise agreements with pipelines. In a few places in the
country, especially those that have had serious accidents, local
governments restrict development near pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   But Bellingham _ located about 80 miles north of Seattle in
Whatcom County _ may be alone in extracting what it has from
Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   Bellingham Mayor Mark Asmundson told reporters Tuesday that the
agreement should better ensure the safety of local residents. The
agreement, he said, ``truly is what every community deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another action that we have taken to show people we are
willing to do whatever it takes to show that we have a safe
pipeline,'' said Fred Crognale, Olympic's president.
</P>
<P>
   Bellingham's negotiations with Olympic might inspire similar
attempts by other cities. The pipeline goes through Redmond,
Bellevue, Renton, Seattle and several other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Bellevue, for example, already has asked Olympic for maintenance
records and will be paying close attention to Bellingham's
agreement, said Tony Perez, franchise manager for Bellevue.
</P>
<P>
   Crognale said Olympic is willing to hear other cities out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to have conversations with them all,'' Crognale
said. But he said the circumstances in Bellingham were unusual.
There was the June 10 accident, and Olympic's franchise agreement
there had expired.
</P>
<P>
   Only the federal Office of Pipeline Safety has the authority to
allow Olympic to resume using the upper 37 miles of its pipeline.
That section has been closed since the catastrophic accident in
Bellingham on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic has 400 miles of pipeline in Washington state, running
from the Arco refinery at Cherry Point to the Columbia River. Three
other refineries also pump gasoline, jet fuel and diesel fuel into
the line.
</P>
<P>
   Bellingham, as well as most other local governments, paid little
attention to the pipeline until June 10. On that day, the 16-inch
line in Bellingham ruptured, sending 277,000 gallons of gasoline
into creeks. The fumes and subsequent fire killed an 18-year-old
man and two 10-year-old boys.
</P>
<P>
   A federal criminal investigation is looking for violations of
the Clean Water Act in the accident. Other federal investigations
are trying to determine a cause of the accident and what can be
done to prevent similar mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   Bellingham's franchise agreement with Olympic expired in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement reached Tuesday was the result of two months of
negotiations. They began shortly after the city submitted a list of
demands to Olympic on July 19.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the negotiations resulted in Olympic agreeing to
do things it had already committed to do or was being ordered to do
by regulators. However, the city has in several instances insisted
on tougher standards.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which Bellingham's City Council must approve,
will run through May 4 of next year. It covers getting the pipeline
ready to operate, and also governs the first weeks of operation.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear when the upper 37 miles of pipeline will reopen.
</P>
<P>
   But once it does, Olympic has agreed to reduced operating
pressure through Bellingham.
</P>
<P>
   As an extra safety precaution in the first week of operation,
the pipeline will run only diesel and jet fuel. Those fuels are
less volatile than the gasoline that exploded June 10.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has agreed to use three different types of
internal inspection devices to check for corrosion and deformities
after the upper 37 miles has opened. It also will have an outside
safety audit 180 days after the line is opened.
</P>
<P>
   Before opening the line, Olympic has agreed to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Hydrostatic testing. That involves putting water into the
10-mile section of pipeline in Bellingham at high pressure to test
for weak spots. Olympic last tested in this way in the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   A consultant to the city said he expected that test to result in
a failure. But Crognale is not so sure that there will be a
failure. The test will take four weeks to set up, perform and
evaluate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Surge analysis. Federal regulators already have asked for
these tests, which look at how pressure can build up in the
pipeline in different situations.
</P>
<P>
   The tests are important because pressure in the line built up on
June 10 when valves downstream closed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Review the computer system that operates and monitors the
pipeline. The computer system, which crashed June 10, has already
been the subject of federal orders and Olympic improvements. The
company, for example, is increasing computer processing power by
750 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Install a new leak-detection system. Olympic has such a system
as part of its computer network. The additional system would be
able to detect major leaks even if the computer was down.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulations do not require pipelines to have leak
detection.
</P>
<P>
   _ Study moving the pipeline. Such a move might prove costly and
technically difficult, Crognale said. It also would present
problems when it comes to getting government permits for a new
location. If it is feasible, Olympic would have to move the line in
five years, Crognale said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
