<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BULLPEN COLLAPSES IN LOSS TO GIANTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Turk Wendell's slide continued Tuesday night as the
spirited relief pitcher blew yet another game. With the Mets
leading the San Francisco Giants by one run in the eighth inning,
Wendell allowed consecutive doubles to Rich Aurilia and Doug
Mirabelli, the seventh and eighth batters in the Giants' lineup, to
jump-start what became a mess of a finish for the home team in the
Mets' 7-4 loss at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The winning run was allowed by John Franco, who relieved Wendell
after Mirabelli's double, but was credited to Wendell, giving him a
line of three hits and two earned runs in two-thirds of an inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in his last four outings that Wendell
crumbled. Last week, he gave up a grand slam to Ken Caminiti in a
6-2 loss to Houston, then, two nights later, was charged with three
runs in a 5-2 10th-inning loss to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wendell was the losing pitchers, his problems were
shared by his teammates, as three pitchers followed him from the
bullpen in the final two innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets used a total of eight pitchers, breaking the franchise
record of seven pitchers used in a nine-inning game. The Mets used
eight pitchers once before, but that was in a 24-inning game
against Houston on April 15, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets dropped to 3 1/2 games behind Atlanta, which defeated
St. Louis by 3-2 in the National League East Division race and lost
a half-game of their wild-card lead on the Cincinnati Reds.
Cincinnati split a doubleheader with the Chicago Cubs to move 3 1/2
games behind the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wasted start for Rick Reed, who made his first
appearance since being placed on the disabled list with a strained
middle finger on his right hand on Aug. 9, and a wasted opportunity
for the Mets, who briefly took a lead after being down by 3-0. Reed
blew through the Giants in the first two innings, but his lack of
control combined with San Francisco's power resulted in a three-run
third.
</P>
<P>
   The poor performance damaged Reed's chances of gaining a place
in the Mets' postseason rotation _ if there is a postseason for
this team _ despite his deceiving 10-4 record. With Valentine
employing a six-man rotation the rest of the way, Reed, who has
benefited from terrific run support, is in line for three more
starts. But with Bobby Jones back in the mix, that number could
shrink.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine had to go to his bullpen early, and the pitching staff
wilted. The seven Mets' relievers allowed six hits and four runs
over the last five innings.
</P>
<P>
   While Wendell had the hardest time, Franco also was hit hard in
his second appearance since returning from the disabled list on
Saturday. He entered in the eighth with the game tied at 4-4 and
Brent Mayne on second base. Two batters later, the Mets were down
by 5-4 as Franco surrendered a run-scoring single to Marvin Benard.
After getting Charlie Hayes to ground out to end the inning, Franco
was lifted after Bobby Bonds lined a single off the right field
wall at the start of the eighth. He gave up two hits and one earned
run in two-thirds of an inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' pitchers were not the only ones who seemed to be
absent for much of the game. Starting opposite Reed was the Giants
right-hander Joe Nathan, a rookie who is 5-3 with a 3.58 earned run
average in 13 major league appearances, eight as a starter. Matched
against Nathan for the first time, the Mets appeared baffled. They
went hitless through the first four innings and got only two balls
out of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Pratt changed that in the fifth by doubling off the base of
the wall in center field to score Roger Cedeno, who had walked. It
was the Mets' first hit of the game and a precursor of things to
come in the sixth. Trailing by 3-1, the Mets scored three runs on
the strength of the hitting of John Olerud, who doubled to score
Edgar Alfonzo (walk), and Darryl Hamilton, whose single scored
Olerud. Hamilton scored later on a fielder's choice to short by Rey
Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   Reed started well, setting the Giants down in order in the first
inning and striking out Jeff Kent and Ellis Burks to begin the
second. He walked J.T. Snow and gave up a single to Rich Aurilia,
but averted trouble by striking out Doug Mirabelli.
</P>
<P>
   Reed had four strikeouts at that point, but he was crushed in
the third. Nathan, of all people, started Reed's undoing by opening
the inning with a double to right field that went over Cedeno's
head. Marvin Benard followed with a single that sent Reed to third,
and Hayes knocked a grounder to Alfonzo at second base. Realizing
it was a pitcher on third, Alfonzo nailed Nathan at the plate to
save the run.
</P>
<P>
   The Giant's pitcher proved to be a gamer by charging hard into
Pratt, but the Mets' catcher held on to the ball, if not his
senses. Shaken up in the collision, he needed a five-minute break
and a few warm-up pitches before returning to play.
</P>
<P>
   With Benard and Hayes on, Reed walked Barry Bonds before Jeff
Kent cleared the bases with a double to center field that touched
the wall on one hop and put the Giants ahead by 3-0. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
