</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE TAKES THE LOSS AS ROYALS DOWN YANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ David Cone embraces responsibility readily,
as if it were a privilege. If a teammate makes an error and Cone
then gives up a run-scoring hit, Cone blames himself. If he loses a
game by 1-0, he will say he should have pitched better.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone might have felt like passing around some blame Tuesday
night, for he was victimized time and again by the actions of
others, from Vice President Al Gore to catcher Jorge Posada to
second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, in losing, 6-3, to the Kansas City
Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams was in the starting lineup Tuesday night, but
the Yankees have plans to send him back to New York on Wednesday, a
day earlier than the rest of the team, so that he can have his sore
left (nonthrowing) shoulder tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we might do it so we can have him for Friday,'' said
manager Joe Torre, referring to the day the Yankees begin a
three-game series against Boston, a division rival. ``We'll do all
that stuff tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams will undergo a magnetic resonance imaging scan, in an
effort to determine what is causing the inflammation that hampers
his swing. He initially injured his shoulder attempting a diving
catch in a game in June and has played through pain, and he even
went on an offensive binge in late July. But the shoulder has
bothered him on this trip and it is apparent it is effecting his
swing, particularly when he swings at pitches high in the strike
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Players will sometimes take a shot of cortisone to reduce
inflammation and to function better. And given that Williams does
not appear to be seriously injured, it figures that at some point
between now and the start of the postseason, Williams will get a
shot to help his swing.
</P>
<P>
   Williams batted third Tuesday night in a lineup stifled by the
Royals' Jose Rosado, a left-hander, like the Anaheim pitcher who
shut down the Yankees Monday, Jarrod Washburn. The Yankees had
runners on base in every inning and just couldn't get the big hit.
</P>
<P>
   Cone's bad day actually started Monday. When the Yankees are
ready to complete a series in one city and travel to another, they
will send the next day's starting pitcher ahead, on a commercial
flight, so he can get a full night's rest. Cone was supposed to fly
here, his hometown, on Monday, have a leisurely evening and prepare
to pitch Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Because of flight cancellations, however, Cone had to travel
from one airport to another in the Los Angeles area before finally
giving up in frustration and deciding to travel on the team's
charter flight.
</P>
<P>
   There was another problem: Gore flew into Los Angeles
International Airport late Monday evening, delaying the Yankees'
charter and other planes. The Yankees' team bus did not pull up to
the team hotel until 4:50 a.m., and by all accounts, Cone was not
pleased. He looked tired when he arrived at Kauffman Stadium
Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Cone walked Johnny Damon, Kansas City's first batter, and Damon
stole second base and moved to third on a bunt. Carlos Beltran
grounded sharply to first, the second out of the inning, and Damon
had to hold at third. Rather than throw Jermaine Dye a good pitch
to hit, Cone walked the Royals' cleanup hitter, and went after Mike
Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   The count was two balls and one strike and with Cone's right
foot against the pitching rubber, he stared in for the sign from
Posada. The Yankees' catcher flashed a sign, Cone nodded quickly in
assent and almost simultaneously began to draw his hands together.
But when Posada flashed another sign, Cone hesitated and shook his
head. Chuck Meriwether, the first-base umpire, called a balk, and
Damon walked home from third base with the first run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals added a second run in the third inning, and though
Cone had relatively good stuff _ his fastball was 88 to 90 mph _ he
was laboring, throwing 66 pitches through three. At a time when
Torre and Mel Stottlemyre, the pitching coach, are trying to limit
the stress on Cone's arm and prepare him for the playoffs, it was a
pace he could not maintain for long.
</P>
<P>
   Cone walked Beltran with one out in the fifth. Dye then hit a
ground ball between Shane Spencer in right field and Williams in
center. Beltran was running hard all the way from first; Spencer
cut the ball off perhaps 30 feet in front of the fence and threw it
to the infield, to the relay man Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   Beltran would have stopped at third in most circumstances. But
Rich Dauer, the Kansas City third-base coach, waved Beltran around
third and homeward and he scored easily with a slide, an unusual
play with just one out. Knoblauch's throwing woes are hardly a
secret, and like sharks sensing a kill, third-base coaches won't
hesitate to exploit a perceived weakness. (Knoblauch did not have a
good game in the field. He dived for several balls, and though they
appeared to be well within his reach, he wasn't able to catch them
or even knock them down.)
</P>
<P>
   Cone was replaced after five innings, having thrown 106 pitches.
The Yankees could not rebound against Rosado, and Cone was stuck
with his eighth loss in 19 decisions. His record is 2-4 since the
All-Star Game break. But in 10 starts since the break, Cone has
allowed three earned runs or fewer in eight starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have been in first place comfortably for more than
two months, but are suddenly within range of the Red Sox in the
American League East. Going into Tuesday night's action, the
Yankees led Boston by 6 1/2 games, and the Red Sox will be in
Yankee Stadium for three games over the weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
