<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-LEAVE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN GLAD TO BE OUT OF FRAY IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM PERRIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ When Sue Mackley left East Timor in a
jam-packed Australian military cargo plane Tuesday, she wasn't
quite sure how to feel.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old former Overland Park resident was relieved to
get out of the violence-racked territory alive, but she also was
concerned for the East Timorese people she left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going to somewhere safe, but I felt complete
guilt and betrayal,'' Mackley said from Darwin, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   She had traveled to East Timor as a representative of the
International Federation for East Timor, a U.N.-accredited group
that monitored a referendum on the territory's independence from
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was overwhelmingly in favor of independence, but
violence broke out after election results were released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mackley, a Chicago resident, has family in the Kansas City, Mo.,
area, including her father, Jim Mackley, and mother, Sandra
Hanshaw, both of Overland Park. She called them from Darwin on
Tuesday to let them know she was safe.
</P>
<P>
   Mackley lived in Overland Park for about seven years until 1984,
when she moved to Atlanta. She graduated from high school there the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 she graduated from the University of South Carolina, and
she later spent time working in France, Russia, the Czech Republic,
Slovakia and Cambodia before moving to Chicago in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Mackley became interested in East Timor more than three years
ago. She quit her job as a software developer early last month so
she could travel to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, she worked with a lobbying group to stop
arms sales to Indonesia because of its policies and actions in East
Timor. However, her role in East Timor was to be a neutral election
monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be professional and diligent about your job,''
Mackley said. ``The best way to credit your organization is by
being impartial.''
</P>
<P>
   In East Timor she was part of a team of five persons sent to
Vikeke, a mountainous town of about 45,000 residents. She spent 2
weeks living with a family there before leaving Saturday in
anticipation of post-election violence.
</P>
<P>
   The group had planned to flee to the territorial capital city of
Dili but ended up in another city, Baucau. The group was among 50
persons _ 10 from Mackley's organization, 40 from the United
Nations _ holed up in a two-story building in Baucau on Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-independence militia members fired at the building, on and
off, for about 90 minutes before a U.N. convoy took Mackley and her
colleagues to the airport Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Their plane was surrounded by members of the Indonesian
military, but it was allowed to take off without incident.
</P>
<P>
   Mackley isn't sure what her group will do next, but she's
willing to do whatever she can to help East Timor gain
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go back in (to East Timor) as necessary, if that's the
best way to help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
