<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDBANC-ACQUISITION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLD BANC TO ACQUIRE 10-BRANCH BANK COMPANY BASED IN FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Gold Banc Corp., the quickly expanding
Leawood, Kan., bank holding company, on Tuesday announced plans to
buy a 10-branch bank company based on the west coast of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gold Banc will pay $91.4 million in stock to acquire American
Bancshares. American is based in Bradenton, Fla. It has about $485
million in assets.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes about a month after Gold Banc announced it would
pay about $65 million in another tax-free stock swap to buy Union
Bankshares Ltd. of Denver. That company's Union Bank &AMP; Trust has
seven locations and $340 million in loans and other assets.
</P>
<P>
   If the two deals close, they will give Gold Banc assets of more
than $2 billion. American and Union will continue to operate under
their current names.
</P>
<P>
   Gold Banc is paying $18.18 a share for American Bancshares.
American's stock closed Tuesday at 13 7/8, up 1 7/8. The number of
Gold Banc shares paid will be based on an average price of Gold
Banc's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Gold Banc, which went public in November 1996, has expanded by
acquiring small community banks and financial services companies.
Gold Banc's stock closed Tuesday at 10 3/4, down 1 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gullion, Gold Banc's chairman and chief executive, said
that by expanding in fast-growing metropolitan areas, Gold Banc
should be able to achieve above-average earnings growth, without
relying solely on acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is one of the best banking markets in the U.S., and
Manatee County, where American is based, has been the
second-fastest-growing county in the U.S. since 1986,'' Gullion
said. ``In some of our rural markets, we can't get that kind of
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next 10 years, some baby boomers will take their
significant wealth and head to the Sun Belt states, Gullion said.
Gold Banc wants to stay ``in front of the money'' with money
management and brokerage services for customers in that area and
for any of its customers who might move to that area.
</P>
<P>
   Buying a bank as far away as Florida poses an operating
challenge for Gold Banc, said Erick Reim, an analyst with U.S.
Bancorp Piper Jaffray in Minneapolis. But Gold Banc's technological
sophistication makes it manageable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gold Banc is very technologically advanced, with significant
back office support,'' Reim said. ``This should make the
consolidation easier.''
</P>
<P>
   American has not been as efficiently run as it might have been,
Reim said, and has not focused on products that generate fees. So
while it appears Gold Banc is paying a significant premium for
American's stock, there should be plenty of opportunities to
enhance the company's profits beyond the usual consolidation
savings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gold Banc reported in July that its net earnings increased 22
percent, to $3.4 million, in the second quarter. Net earnings per
diluted share increased 18 percent, to 20 cents a share. Last
year's earnings were restated to include the effect of
acquisitions. If the results had not been restated, this year's
second-quarter earnings would have increased 147 percent and
earnings per share would have increased 54 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 0102EDT &QL; 
