r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      09-08 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-SMOKING DRIVE: ACTIVISM WITHOUT A NEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ One of the most nerve-racking jobs on the
planet must be running a restaurant in Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   As if coping with a tight labor market isn't tough enough,
there's always a contingent of elected city officials wanting to
run your business for you.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that the smoking issue apparently was resolved
in a manner generally acceptable to most. When smoking foes are
determined to impose their vision of a perfect world on everyone,
the issue isn't resolved until the world as they can control it is
smoke free.
</P>
<P>
   While the latest bid to give the city more control over public
smoking options would affect only about 20 percent of the city's
restaurants, the question that needs asking is why this has
re-emerged as an issue.
</P>
<P>
   There are no doubt many Johnson Countians who support such an
effort because they find smokers loathsome and their secondhand
fumes repulsive. Even so, where's the conflict?
</P>
<P>
   If you eat out regularly in Overland Park, you'd probably be
hard put to remember a recent instance when you've witnessed
smokers and anti-smokers clashing at a restaurant serving both.
This absence of rancor apparently indicates that the current
smoking ordinance is working as everyone had hoped: Restaurant
operators decide what's in their best business interest. Slightly
more than half allow smoking, apparently in a way satisfactory to
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   This state of harmony, however, isn't good enough for some
council members. They want to turn the screws a bit tighter by
banning smoking at all food-service establishments without bars
unless separately ventilated areas are provided for smoking
patrons. At restaurants with bars, smoking would be restricted to
within 10 feet of the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking foes may justify these efforts as necessary to protect
the public from the health threat of secondhand smoke. The
secondhand smoke ruse, however, has been discredited as an exercise
in junk science.
</P>
<P>
   This reality has unfortunately been ignored by anti-smoking
crusaders, whose primary leverage is pushing the public-health
dimension of their campaign. In fact, theirs has always been more a
moral crusade than a health crusade. Inventing a health threat from
passive smoke and thus a need to protect nonsmokers from smokers
has been the key to success.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, in a country that traditionally has prided itself on
tolerance and a democratic approach to governance, smoking has
created an exception to these centuries-old norms. As unfortunate
as this recent embrace of intolerance is, though, it still doesn't
justify legislating on the basis of personal crusades.
</P>
<P>
   Just because elected officials perceive their position as
morally right or well-intentioned doesn't justify legislating
personal feelings into law. Moreover, citizens who encourage such
behavior by elected officials put their own personal liberties at
risk down the road. When legislators take this approach, it's a
form of tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   The criterion for legislation should be whether there's a
compelling need. In the case of Overland Park's restaurant
situation, smoking and nonsmoking restaurant patrons seem to have
arrived at a mutually satisfactory accommodation. Given this,
what's the point?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
