<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ASIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT TO JOIN FIBER OPTIC VENTURE IN ASIA
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Expanding the reach of advanced fiber optic communications in
Asia, the Microsoft Corp., Global Crossing Ltd. of Bermuda and the
Softbank Corp. of Japan have agreed to form a $1.3 billion joint
venture to build a new communications web stretching from Japan to
Malaysia, executives close to the agreement said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The companies intend to announce the venture, to be called Asia
Global Crossing, as soon as Wednesday, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has been moving at a moderate pace to extend its
dominance in computer software into the communications world. Until
now, most of Microsoft's communications efforts have appeared
focused on local markets. Two years ago, the company invested $1
billion in the Comcast Corp., one of the nation's biggest cable
television companies. In January, it invested $500 million in NTL
Inc., one of Britain's largest cable television operators.
</P>
<P>
   But the new venture with Softbank, the media and Internet giant,
and Global Crossing, the upstart long-distance carrier, appears to
be Microsoft's first move into the fast-growing market for
long-distance and international communications services. Propelled
by the Internet and deregulation, entrepreneurs and old state
monopolies alike are betting that new communications pipes can be
filled almost as quickly as they are built.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Global Crossing will contribute to the new
venture its 57.75 percent stake in an undersea fiber optic cable
called Pacific Crossing 1, which is scheduled to begin operating
between Japan and the West Coast of the United States by January.
The minority investors in Pacific Crossing 1 include the Marubeni
Corp. of Japan, the trading concern, and Kokusai Denshin Denwa,
Japan's dominant international telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Softbank and Microsoft have each agreed to
contribute $175 million in cash to the venture and to buy a joint
total of $200 million worth of communications capacity over the
next three years, executives close to the deal said.
</P>
<P>
   The three partners have assigned the new venture an initial
value of $5 billion. So the investments by Softbank and Microsoft
will garner each company a 3.5 percent initial stake in the
operation, with Global Crossing controlling the other 93 percent.
But Microsoft and Softbank stand to make a substantial profit on
their investments if the venture succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The three partners intend to offer stock in the new venture to
the public, and if the value of the operation exceeds $5 billion,
the equity controlled by Microsoft and Softbank will rise.
According to executives close to the deal, Microsoft and Softbank
could each come to control 19 percent of the new venture if its
total value reaches $7.5 billion, making each such stake worth $1.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The venture intends to use the $350 million in cash contributed
by Microsoft and Softbank as part of a $1.3 billion project to
build a new international fiber optic network called East Asia
Crossing. By the end of next year, the companies intend the new
system to link Japan, Taiwan, Singapore, Hong Kong, Malaysia and
the Philippines. By June 2001, the system is meant to also reach
China and South Korea. Eventually, the three partners would like to
expand as far south as Indonesia and as far west as India. The new
network will initially link with the older Pacific Crossing 1 cable
in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Global Crossing renegotiated its deal to acquire
the Frontier Corp., formerly Rochester Telephone, in light of the
fact that Global Crossing's stock has lost more than half its value
since that deal was announced in the spring. Shares of Global
Crossing fell $2.0625 Tuesday, to $20.3125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
