<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG STILL FUMBLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC tailback Frank Strong might have wanted
sympathy from his teammates after two fumbles against Hawaii.
Instead he got nicknames.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fumbleitis. Fumblerooski. Those were a couple names,'' Strong
said.
</P>
<P>
   Strong's season couldn't have started any worse. After fumbling
three times in 37 carries last season, he hoped to show the coaches
that he could be trusted to hold on to the ball. But in six
carries, he fumbled twice against Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nightmare,'' Strong said. ``It's always tough when you
make a mental error. Whatever, you're doing, it just keeps coming
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, Strong has been bothered by a deep thigh
bruise that has caused his knee to stiffen the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make excuses, but it had an effect on the
mental aspect of the game,'' Strong said. ``I didn't get hit in a
while, so I wasn't used to contact.''
</P>
<P>
   None of that will matter if Strong doesn't demonstrate he can
run without fumbling. Coach Paul Hackett reiterated his position on
the matter Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real simple. Don't fumble,'' Hackett said. ``How much is
too many? I'm not going to be stupid. If there's a problem that
becomes alarming, you have to reduce a guy's opportunity to carry.
There's a concern clearly. (But) I thought that was real good work
today.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick start: Freshman wide receiver Kareem Kelly had an
impressive debut, with 104 yards receiving on five catches. But
Kelly was hardly among those surprised by his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people didn't expect much from me because I'm a
freshman,'' Kelly said. ``But I had a real good training camp. The
game was pretty cool. I can't get content though. But I thought it
was a real good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly also hoped his 43-yard, over-the-shoulder reception
dispelled the belief he has questionable hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard that a lot,'' Kelly said. ``That my hands were a flaw.
I heeded what people thought about me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Soward's sick: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward did not practice
Tuesday because he had the flu.
</P>
<P>
   __ Arbet, Pierson out: Freshman cornerback Kevin Arbet, who
started the Hawaii game, has a badly sprained ankle and will likely
miss the San Diego State game. Freshman fullback Chad Pierson also
has an ankle sprain and is not expected to be available for San
Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Return to paradise: Hawaii has already made inquiries to USC
about returning to Honolulu for another game, perhaps in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   __ Players of the game: USC coaches selected offensive lineman
Jason Grain as the offensive player of the game. Cornerback Kris
Richard was the defensive player of the game. Kicker David Newbury
won the honor for special teams.
</P>
<P>
   __ Stat fix: After USC reviewed game films, wide receiver
Windrell Hayes was credited with six receptions. The postgame stats
in Hawaii gave him seven. His yardage total (80) remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   __ Touchdown total: USC's six rushing touchdowns were the most
by a Trojans team since they had six against Oregon State in 1976.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
