r p BC-BRADLEY-HOMETOWN-2NDT     09-08 0226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-HOMETOWN-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRYSTAL CITY, Mo. _ before he'd quit.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley was more than just a great shot. He was sometimes
second-guessed for passing the ball instead of taking a shot
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had a team beat, he'd quit shooting,'' Haley said.
``He'd give it to me or whoever hadn't scored that many points.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bradley was a gifted passer. ``He'd hit you in the head if
you were not prepared for it,''Haley said.
</P>
<P>
   Still others talk about how Bradley's back yard was the daily
gathering spot for kids from all over town. ``It didn't matter
where they came from as long as they were well-mannered,'' Bond
said.
</P>
<P>
   Once, when Bradley held a party at his home, he invited the
whole school instead of issuing invitations and risk leaving anyone
out.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is a perfect mix of his mother and father, Bond said.
From his father, he learned patience and a need for privacy. From
his mother, Bradley picked up nonstop energy.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at the White Grill restaurant on Tuesday morning, Jack
Geiler, a resident for 74 years, looked a visitor in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   With all the trouble the country has had with President Clinton,
Bradley would be ``more like a god,'' Geiler said. ``You never hear
anybody say anything against him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
