<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANALS08-KWALTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANALS OF SCOTTSDALE DEFEATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEXA HAUSSLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Scottsdale voters dashed developers' wishes Tuesday to
transform the Arizona Canal's south bank into a watery wonderland
in a surprise finish to a campaign in which backers outspent the
opponents 70-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   Voters were rejecting by a 54 percent to 46 percent margin plans
for the Canals of Scottsdale, a $653 million, 27-acre museum,
retail and entertainment complex downtown near Fashion Square that
was to be partially publicly funded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any paid volunteers. We simply had hard-core
volunteers who said, `We're taking our city back,' '' said Lois
Fitch of Save Old Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, who collected campaign funds by putting jars on the
counters of stores that would be wiped out by the development, had
said they were fighting to keep the soul of Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Developers had pitched it as the best deal the city could
possibly make to clean up a deteriorating part of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised that the citizens couldn't see the advantage
of this, I think they thought it was a tax issue and it wasn't,''
said Stan Castleton, an Anaheim developer and a partner in the
project.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of the project would have been paid for with sales
taxes collected in the development under a state theme park law
that Scottsdale would have been the only Arizona city to use.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout of about 31,221 was 27.4 percent, and at least 13,465
voters cast early ballots.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Canals project was heavily backed by the city's power
structure, including Mayor Sam Campana, and the defeat could pose a
problem for the next redevelopment plan the city has in mind.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 2, voters will decide whether the Ellman Cos.,
financially backed by Canals developer Excel Legacy Corp. of San
Diego, can also use a tax incentive to rebuild Los Arcos Mall as a
$624 million Phoenix Coyotes hockey arena, entertainment and
conference complex.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the Canals project, Great for Scottsdale, Great for
You!, gathered Tuesday at one of Scottsdale's swankiest new spots:
The Sanctuary nightclub that sits in the shadow of the Scottsdale
Galleria, the center of a years-long debate over downtown's
rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   But they were a solemn crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't win the will of the people. It's a shame,'' said
Bill Heckman, campaign chairman. ``We offered a fantastic plan.
It's been rejected. We have no plan B.''
</P>
<P>
   An overhauled version of the Galleria _ remade into four museums
_ was slated as the centerpiece of the Canals project, which would
include about $200 million in public funding.
</P>
<P>
   The winners gathered at Madison's on Stetson, one of the 40
businesses that would have been wiped out by the Canals project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the citizens of Scottsdale could not be bought,''
crowed an exuberant Tom Silverman, a downtown hotel owner and a key
member of Save Old Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Chapparo, who owns a Sixth Avenue beauty salon that would
have been torn down, said, ``I have 10 employees. I just didn't
know where I was going, what I was going to do, and I am
thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   The election wound down last week with the developers'
announcement that Dan Harkins would locate a new and improved
version of the historic Cine Capri theater in the Canals project, a
plan that now goes back to the drawing boards.
</P>
<P>
   Also, opponents filed an eleventh-hour lawsuit by that raised
questions about the project.
</P>
<P>
   A group of downtown Scottsdale merchants claimed in the suit
filed Friday that the city violated city ordinances and state laws
when it expanded the boundaries of the redevelopment district that
includes their businesses in the Canals project.
</P>
<P>
   The Fifth Avenue, Sixth Avenue and Stetson Drive Merchants
Association were asking a judge to invalidate the boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Those opponents, including several downtown merchants organized
as Save Old Scottsdale, had argued that the plan would siphon
dollars from the state treasury and force out shopkeepers who have
added to the Western character of downtown Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   They also said they were outmatched by the developers. The
developers, led by Excel, gave at least $838,000 to the campaign
and were the sole contributors. In contrast, opponents raised about
$12,000 in individual contributions in the four months before the
election. &QL; 
Alexa Haussler can be reached at (602) 444-7481 or at
alexa.haussler(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4064 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-RACE-RIOT-2NDTAKE-KAN     09-08 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-RIOT-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULSA, Okla. _ the first shot.
</P>
<P>
   There was a scuffle. A burst of gunfire. Panic. ``The race war
was on, and I was powerless to stop it,'' McCullough later said.
</P>
<P>
   Violence raged all night and through the next day. Angry whites
descended on the Greenwood district. The first fire broke out an
hour after midnight. By dawn white men filled cars that roared down
the streets, ``guns blazing indiscriminately,'' writes Ellsworth,
who is white.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. James Robertson dispatched the National Guard and declared
martial law. By noon all of Greenwood was in flames, including the
new Mount Zion Baptist Church, where armed blacks were barricaded.
One thousand surrounding homes, 31 restaurants, 24 groceries and
eight medical offices burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star sent a reporter as soon as the first
reports hit the wire services. ``Races at War,'' the newspaper's
early afternoon edition declared June 1, 1921. ``Death Toll is
50?''
</P>
<P>
   A later edition: ``Death Toll Reaches 74,'' nine whites and 65
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Star's final edition that day told of a city
``blood-drenched and blackened by incendiary fires.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Major Charles W. Daley of the police force this afternoon
estimated the dead at 175. He believes a number of Negroes were
burned to death when their homes were swept by fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Confusion over the casualty count persists.
</P>
<P>
   Official sources eventually set the death toll at 36. Local
history books have cited figures ranging from 33 to ``some nine
whites and 68 blacks.'' Several books on Tulsa history ignored the
riot altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth and others working with the riot commission now think
the toll may have reached 300. They base this on a variety of
incomplete records and unconfirmed reports. They are dealing with
nearly eight decades of hearsay and horror stories.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the days after the riot, the Tulsa World acknowledged
rumors of widespread carnage and cover-up:
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who will always believe that truck loads of
Negro bodies were dumped into the Arkansas River or buried in a
mythical trench or piled into a building which was later set on
fire....There is not a shred of truth'' to the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: In the riot's wake, thousands of black
Tulsans were rounded up and interned at sites throughout the city,
ostensibly for their own safety. Countless others jammed into
trains or automobiles and fled for good.
</P>
<P>
   The black exodus included the family of Joyce Walker Hill, who
has lived in Kansas City, Kan., ever since. She was 11 when the
riot occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Her father's six-bedroom home was destroyed. Her mother was
seven months pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the son her mother was carrying traveled to Tulsa
with Hill to attend a public meeting of the riot commission. ``I
wondered why it took so long to find out these things,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just never talked about it. All we knew is that the house
burned down. I guess my father thought that talking about it would
just frighten us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, the young man whose arrest sparked the melee, was said
to have moved to the Kansas City area, as well. The assault case
was dropped when alleged victim Page declined to press charges.
</P>
<P>
   Essie Beck, 85, eases herself into a Victorian chair beneath a
chandelier at the Greenwood Cultural Center. She gently sets her
cane against her thigh.
</P>
<P>
   The camcorder begins taping. Beck's testimony, along with
accounts of 64 other known survivors of the riot, will be reviewed
by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a little girl, I was frightened,'' Beck tells
interviewer Gates. ``We had to run to try to stay out of the way
(of the violence). We'd hide behind trees...hide behind gardenia
bushes, hide behind little rocks....
</P>
<P>
   ``There were airplanes in the sky that seemed to be shooting and
dropping things on the rooftops.... We were ducking and dodging to
get to the park. My mother was able to keep five children together.
Of course, we were crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Her account of aircraft is echoed by other survivors. Historian
Dick Warner says it is not known who manned the planes. Also
uncertain is whether they were attacking or just flying
reconnaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Beck recalls the fretful months that followed, when her family
lived in a Red Cross tent on the ashes of their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, yes, there were nightmares. Lots of nightmares.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinney Booker is 86.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and four brothers and sisters were up in the
attic,'' the retired English teacher says. ``We knew there was
shooting and killing going on outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard some men come into the house and say to my father,
`...Do you have a gun?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The next thing Booker says he heard were Papa's pleas _ ``Please
don't set my house on fire'' _ as he was taken away and led to an
internment camp.
</P>
<P>
   The intruders torched the place, anyway. Booker and his family
managed to escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon as we got outside, my sister said to me _ she was 6 _
`Kinney, is the whole world on fire?' I said, `I don't know, baby,
but we're in lots of trouble.' That scene I'll remember forever.
Pretty horrible to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa's story isn't all horrible.
</P>
<P>
   Sympathetic whites, especially those in the Red Cross, fed and
dressed the wounds of black refugees. A white oil tycoon who
employed Booker's father as a driver helped reunite and shelter the
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kinds of things help you understand that all white
people weren't evil,'' Booker says.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Greenwood proved resilient. Hundreds rebuilt, with
no help from the city. In fact, city officials tried to convert the
burned-out area into an industrial park. The Tulsa Tribune in 1921
reported that, because of the proposed building requirements, ``it
is believed impossible that the Negroes will again build homes
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Greenwood district is still alive in 1999. Ironically, the
Tulsa Tribune is out of business.
</P>
<P>
   And the rest of the city is finally talking about an event that
past generations _ white and black _ declined to discuss aloud.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971 the Tulsa Chamber of Commerce refused to publish a 50th
anniversary story about the riot. Author Ed Wheeler gave the
article to a regional magazine, Impact, co-owned by a black Tulsan
named Don Ross. According to Ross, ``both blacks and whites got on
my case for causing trouble. I had violated the conspiracy of
silence going on for 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross, now a state representative, in 1996 drafted the bill
creating the riot commission. He says the response has been
``overwhelmingly wonderful.'' A story told only in whispers when he
was a Tulsa teen in the 1950s has drawn worldwide press.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nothing else comes of this, the most laudable thing is that
we're willing to confront the past,'' he says. ``It was my
generation that had to tell the story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 0118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4063 &Cx1f; kan-z
r p BC-BRADLEY-HOMETOWN-2TAK     09-08 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-HOMETOWN-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY RETURNS TO CRYSTAL CITY, MO., ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRYSTAL CITY, Mo. _ Most Americans know Bill Bradley as the
brainy East Coaster who attended Princeton, played for the New York
Knicks and represented New Jersey in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday Bradley returns to Missouri and the hometown he
left 38 years ago to launch a new phase in his uphill, but
unquestionably competitive, campaign for the presidency. The task:
Tell America who William Warren Bradley really is.
</P>
<P>
   Townspeople say Crystal City, a well-kept, tree-lined town of
4,000, about 30 miles south of St. Louis, is the perfect place to
do just that.
</P>
<P>
   It was here that Bradley, now 56, grew into his role as the
proverbial all-American, a real-life Jack Armstrong, who starred in
sports and academics at Crystal City High School and became a
legend that burns brightly to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Here, he is more than the local kid who made good. He is the man
who became a Rhodes scholar, a best-selling author, a gold medal
winner in the Olympics and a three-term senator. Never once,
friends say, did he embarrass himself or the town he now frequently
mentions on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he learned here during his first 18 years he's never
forgotten,'' said Bob Freese, 63, who knows Bradley well. ``He has
a real fondness for this area. His foundations are here, and he's
never forgotten that.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents say they are not bothered by the notion that Bradley,
an only child, visits only sporadically these days. His father,
former president of the Crystal City State Bank, died in 1994 and
his mother, a strong-willed, energetic homemaker, passed on a year
later.
</P>
<P>
   Townspeople don't seem to mind that Bradley will benefit
politically by renewing his ties with Crystal City or the pivotal
swing state of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Friends point out that Bradley owns a 158-acre farm in town and
that the limestone family home on Taylor Avenue still has the
basketball hoop out back where Bradley honed his feathery jump
shot. The shooting stroke helped him average 35 points a game as a
high school senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame him one bit,'' said Larry Sabato, a University
of Virginia political scientist. ``George Bush Sr. was
simultaneously from Connecticut, his birthplace of Massachusetts
and from Texas. He had, like, five or six home states.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley critics exist. Edward Graham of nearby De Soto
recently wrote a scathing letter to the editor in the Jefferson
County Leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bill Bradley ever becomes president, I'll eat a taco shell
hat,'' Graham wrote. ``The local gush is nauseatingly mindless. The
editorial hype is pure tripe. Who is buying the high-dollar
consultant spin that Crystal City is the source of the values
Bradley holds today?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, returning to one's roots has become part of the theater
of presidential politics. Dwight Eisenhower had Abilene, Kan. Bill
Clinton spoke of Hope, Ark. And Kansan Bob Dole, of course, made
regular use of Russell to highlight his small-town roots.
</P>
<P>
   Most Crystal City residents give Bradley a pass. He did, after
all, move away from here after high school and made his career on
the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The main regret is that Democratic politicians in Missouri
chased Bradley out of the state in the late 1970s when he was
considering where to begin his political career. The Democrats
wanted Bradley to start small and work his way up. Bradley had
other ideas and opted for New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost him,'' Freese said.
</P>
<P>
   The rest is history, and Bradley hopes to make some more as he
takes aim at Al Gore and seeks to become the first candidate to
defeat a sitting vice president for his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is scheduled to speak at noon Wednesday on the steps of
his old high school. The school band will play, and a third-grade
class will lead the Pledge of Allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Then the assembly moves indoors to the old gymnasium that has
changed little since Bradley played. The wooden bleachers still
pull out from the wall, and the baskets swing down from the
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Outside is a case that holds trophies from Bradley's basketball
exploits, including one commemorating a second-place finish in the
1961 state tournament. Alongside is Bradley's retired jersey _ a
white uniform with a red No. 52 outlined in black trim.
</P>
<P>
   In the gym, long-time friends will tell their best Bradley
stories.
</P>
<P>
   One will be Elmer Earl Smith, who taught Bradley physics and
chemistry in high school. Smith said he planned to recount how
Bradley, as Student Council president, once offered to help him
find the student who had stolen a chemistry exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `As president, I thought perhaps I should volunteer
to help you,' '' Smith recalled. The teacher wound up not needing
Bradley's help to find the thief.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the thing that amazed me,'' Smith said, ``was that at that
young age, he was willing to stick his neck out and really and
truly do what he thought the right thing was.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends recall how Bradley's mother, Susie, worked to keep their
only child from getting a big head. If he won a race, recalled
Hardeman Bond, Bradley's aunt, Susie would remind him that his
victory was due to his longer legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd tell him he had an unfair advantage, that he couldn't
help but win,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   His father, a staunch Republican, wanted Bradley to do more in
his life than just play basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When are you going to get a real job?'' he once asked his son
after he had played a few years with the Knicks, Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Haley, Bradley's high-school basketball teammate, recalled
how Bradley worked on his jump shot. He would shoot 10 shots from
the corner, then move around the perimeter. He would have to hit 10
straight shots from each spot before he'd quit. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
