<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAGNE IS STELLAR IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Out of the black hole of the Dodgers minor-league system
came a bright light Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Gagne, a 23-year-old right-hander from Double-A San
Antonio, had a major-league debut that certainly will be remembered
long after the Dodgers' 2-1 loss to the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 13,644 at Pro Player Stadium witnessed a sterling
performance that included six scoreless innings and just one walk.
But in a season in which the Dodgers farm system has been ridiculed
repeatedly for losing records and a lack of prospects, Gagne
represented much more than one great night.
</P>
<P>
   He is a symbol of hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell those guys down there that I am proof that you
can get here,'' said Gagne, who will start Sunday against the New
York Mets. ``A lot of people have said things about the minor
leagues, but there are plenty of guys who can play. They can look
at this and know there is a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gagne overcame a one hour and 26 minute rain delay at the start
with a composure that teammate Ismael Valdes did not have the night
before. Gagne gave up just two singles and did not allow a batter
to reach second. Four of his eight strikeouts came on called third
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne even got a single in his first major-league at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first batter, I was totally comfortable,'' Gagne
said. ``I was much more nervous waiting around for the game to
start than I was out on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Gagne said he could have pitched longer, but manager Davey
Johnson wanted him to go out on a positive note.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne knew, perhaps better than anyone, that he was in for a
tough night against Marlins' starter Ryan Dempster. They were
roommates on the 1993 Canadian Junior National Team. Tuesday night
marked the first time since July 28, 1973 that two Canadians
started against each other in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were close then, but we haven't stayed in close touch,''
Gagne said. ``That's how it is in baseball. But Ryan is still the
same tough pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempster allowed four hits in seven innings. The Dodgers had
runners aboard in the first five innings but stranded nine runners
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne and Dempster were gone by the time Florida scored two runs
in the bottom of the eighth against Matt Herges (0-1). The Marlins
scored their first run on a one-out RBI triple by Alex Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   After Herges struck out Mark Kotsay for the second out, Kevin
Millar grounded off Eric Karros' glove at first for an error to
score Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers got a run in the ninth on an RBI pinch single by
Devon White, but that was it. The Dodgers have now dropped two to
the Marlins after sweeping the Cubs in Chicago. It didn't matter.
The Dodgers postgame clubhouse was electric because of Gagne's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Gagne, Mike Judd and Robinson Checo were
question marks in the minors. Now, they are considered pitchers who
can push for starting spots in next year's rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what we have been trying to build all season,''
general manager Kevin Malone said. ``You need to have flexibility.
The only way to have that is develop players.''
</P>
<P>
   Gagne has made the biggest impression. He was the Texas League
Pitcher of the Year with a 12-4 record and 2.63 ERA. He led the
league with 185 strikeouts, was second in ERA and third in
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew before tonight that I could get out major-league
hitters,'' Gagne said. ``I have a lot of confidence and this was my
chance. It was a great night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
