<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDICAPPING NFL RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picking the eventual Super Bowl champion is easier than a Falcon
hailing a hooker in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   First you eliminate all teams that have never been to a Super
Bowl. First-timers won three straight between 1984 and 1986 (49ers,
Bears, Giants), but none since. Then you eliminate all teams that
have never won a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Then you get rid of all teams that have changed cities in the
last two decade (four of them), have new coaches (six of them), are
employing suspect quarterbacks (most of them), or have 10 or more
players with rap sheets.
</P>
<P>
   If you have no teams left over at this point, you begin
preparing for the basketball season.
</P>
<P>
   Truthfully, there hasn't been a surprise winner of the Super
Bowl since Bill Parcells' second New York Giants team, and in
hindsight, it doesn't seem surprising. We know more about Parcells
and the Buffalo Bills now than we did in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   And when one factors in the importance of quarterbacks to Super
Bowl champs, and the lack of good quarterbacks in the league today,
the NFL has fewer candidates than the Republicans. It's quarterback
theories like this which keep Dan Marino and Miami a candidate each
year, despite the city having hosted three Super Bowls since the
Dolphins' last appearance (1985).
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'd love a real surprise NFL champ, or a people's
champ. Maybe an ugly-looking team that wins games with defense
(Tampa Bay), or a team without stars (N.Y. Giants), or a team that
dares to be different (Jacksonville).
</P>
<P>
   All one can predict about the NFL right now is that very little
can be predicted. I have 31 teams and 31 questions, 32 if you
include when L.A. will get an expansion team, 2003 or 3002.
</P>
<P>
   Divisionally-speaking, here come the questions and brave, naive
answers:
</P>
<P>
   NFC West questions:
</P>
<P>
   Can Atlanta's Chris Chandler stay healthy? Did New Orleans'
Ricky Williams sign a bad contract? Will the Rams' Torry Holt be
rookie of the year? Can George Seifert rebuild Carolina in a year
and embarrass the 49ers in the process?
</P>
<P>
   Answers:
</P>
<P>
   In assessing the Dirty Birds, please invoke the law of averages.
Chandler is even money to break something, and the Falcs won nine
games by eight points or less last season. That won't happen again.
Until Steve Young retires, the 49ers begin each season the team to
beat.
</P>
<P>
   Williams signed a weird contract, but his biggest mistake
(besides that wedding gown in ESPN Magazine) was being drafted by a
team with two Billy Joes at quarterback. Holt could be this
season's Randy Moss if he had someone to throw him the ball.
Seifert will find it was easier inheriting a team with Super Bowl
talent than a four-year-old expansion team with old players.
</P>
<P>
   Division champ: Frisco.
</P>
<P>
   NFC East questions:
</P>
<P>
   If there's a Mets-Yankees World Series and a Giants-Jets Super
Bowl, will New Yorkers secede from the union in celebration of its
greatness? Will Dallas' Michael Irvin be a character witness at
Jerry Jones' trial for leaving the scene of an accident? Will
Washington's Brad Johnson turn Viking fans seven shades of purple?
Is Arizona's Jake Plummer the new Montana? Will the Eagles be
demoted to the World League?
</P>
<P>
   Answers:
</P>
<P>
   The givens here are that the Cowboys won't repeat last year's
trifecta of losses to the Raiders, Bears and Saints; the Redskins
will be better with Johnson; Plummer won't lead the Cards to seven
wins by three points of
</P>
<P>
   or less like he did last year; and Andy Reid will be fired
before most people realize he's the Eagles coach.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 season represents the Cowboys' last hurrah. The Giants
may be the most non-descript team in the league, and for some
reason, that's appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Division champ: Dallas. Wild card: New York.
</P>
<P>
   NFC Central questions:
</P>
<P>
   Will Jeff George ruin the Vikes through osmosis? Will an exodus
of talent send the Pack back to the pack? Can Tampa Bay find an
offense its defense can be proud of? Will Barry Sanders stay in
London and play in the World League? Will Bears fans be patient
with Cade McNown?
</P>
<P>
   Answers:
</P>
<P>
   Yes, no, yes, no, maybe. Chalk me up as a Viking doubter on the
strength of Randall Cunningham not repeating his
I-sold-my-soul-to-the-devil season and the George virus infecting
the franchise. Speaking of unholy pacts, is there a luckier person
in football than Packers coach Ray
``happiness-is-seeing-Philly-hit-by-nukes'' Rhodes?
</P>
<P>
   If Cunningham can mount a stunning comeback, then there's hope
for Trent Dilfer, who is supported by good rushing and defense. The
only question in Detroit is when Bobby Ross gets fired, week eight
or week 16. Chicagoans are reminded it took McNown a season-plus to
hit his stride at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Division champ: Green Bay. Wild cards: Minnesota, Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   AFC Central questions:
</P>
<P>
   Would Jacksonville's Mark Brunell be the consensus league MVP if
he faced his defense twice a season? Will Steelers' QB Kordell
Stewart star in the sequel to The Crying Game? Will Art Modell dare
make the Ravens' Nov.7 road trip to Cleveland? Will the Tennessee
Titans invoke memories of the New York Titans? Is Cincinnati coach
Bruce Coslet the Marion Campbell of the '90s?
</P>
<P>
   Answers:
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville would clinch the division by November 1st if not
for 10 divisional games and the spectre of the Steelers getting a
comeback year out of Kordell and Jerome Bettis. Don't bet against
the Browns winning more games than the Ravens, who believe they can
rebuild around QB flops Scott Mitchell and Tony Banks.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were known as the Titans their first three seasons. At
least New York is big; what exactly is the relevance of Titans in
Tennessee? Campbell was 17-51 in two separate stints as the Falcons
head coach. Coslet's career record is 43-62. How do guys like this
keep their jobs?
</P>
<P>
   Division champ: Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   AFC East questions:
</P>
<P>
   Are we really supposed to believe the Jets are Super Bowl
timber? Does Miami's Tony Martin send his shirts to be, uhh, dry
cleaned? When will Buffalo trade Rob Johnson? Does Indianapolis
deserve a quarterback as good as Peyton Manning? Will Bob Kraft
stop counting his stadium money long enough to fire Pete Carroll?
</P>
<P>
   Answers:
</P>
<P>
   The Jets seem to have the best package, but we've never seen a
Parcells team run from the front of the pack. It's safe to say
Jimmy Johnson regrets taking the Miami job and being stuck with a
legendary quarterback who doesn't fit his style. Anything short of
a Super Bowl will send Marino to co-star in the next Ace Ventura
sequel, and Johnson back to his fishing boat.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo gets kudos for having two capable starting quarterbacks
at a time when one is never enough. But they'll likely trade the
ex-Trojan quarterback if they get a good offer. Here's the real AFC
East conundrum: In a division with quarterbacks like Drew Bledsoe,
Manning, Marino, Doug Flutie and Johnson, we're to believe Vinny
Testaverde will win the division?
</P>
<P>
   Division champ: N.Y. Jets. Wild cards: Miami, Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   AFC West questions:
</P>
<P>
   Did Mike Shanahan take more out of his Raiders experience than
anyone suspected? Aren't the Chiefs acting more like the Raiders
than the Raiders? Does Mike Holmgren really think he's going to win
in Seattle with Jon Kitna? Did Mike Riley really think coaching the
Chargers was a step up from Oregon State? Does Al Davis really
believe anyone in California cares where his Raiders play?
</P>
<P>
   Answers:
</P>
<P>
   In the next episode of Star Wars, Shanahan will play the Anakin
Skywalker-Darth Vader character. Dumping on Bubby Brister the way
he did indicates Davis didn't give Shanahan enough time to develop
his dark side. The Broncos are still good enough to win this
division with any quarterback. The Chiefs began to cannibalize
themselves last season. Ex-Raider aide Gunther Cunningham is a good
man, but he inherited a team in descent.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren will build his Seahawk dynasty via defense and Ricky
Watters, especially now that he's dumped Joey Galloway. Holmgren
went 9-7 in his first three seasons as Packers head coach. Riley
obviously misjudged his career: If he goes 6-5 in Corvallis, he's a
hero. If he goes 4-12 in San Diego, he's fired.
</P>
<P>
   Division champ: Denver. Wild card: Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the Raiders are concerned, I urge them to return to
L.A. and agree to play in a new stadium in Carson. Because if ever
a team was born to play on a toxic landfill, it's the Raiders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
