<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALK LANDS TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ The team that could justify stamping Murphy's Law
on its letterhead is about to boldly heckle its own standard of
doom.
</P>
<P>
   For the Los Angeles Clippers, today figures to be a bit dicier
than a bad hair day.
</P>
<P>
   Today is when David Falk, the Lex Luthor of player agents, lands
in L.A. for his dreaded date with Clips owner Donald T. Sterling.
They are scheduled to meet at a neutral site. Falk is expected to
ask Sterling to extend the contract of Maurice Taylor, Falk's
newest big-name client, for the NBA maximum of $70.9 million over
six years.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling is expected to bite his lower lip, click his heels, and
say no.
</P>
<P>
   Falk, according to sources who have seen the dailies, will ask
the Clippers to trade Taylor, one of the league's coveted, young
power forwards.
</P>
<P>
   Or else.
</P>
<P>
   The team's alternative would be to refuse, force Taylor to play
for them this season (the last on his three-year contract), then
risk losing him without compensation to free agency.
</P>
<P>
   So, with the lesser of two evils looming, the Clippers may
investigate the market and attempt to deal Taylor. Taylor will be
paid ``just $1.367 million this season, so in order to bring back
any ballpark value (go ahead and exhale), Falk may be needed to
help broker a more sophisticated deal.
</P>
<P>
   This still would be considered a defeat for the franchise, but
with Sterling unwilling to open up his checkbook and let the good
times roll, it could be time for the team's basketball-acquisitions
department to cut its losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Clipper good (and unrelated) news could involve the
signing-and-trading of in-limbo point guard Sherman Douglas, who
just spent one overweight-and-injury-plagued season in L.A. But
Indiana Pacers coach Larry Bird is a Douglas fan (going back to
Sherm's days in Boston), and wouldn't argue if the team moved one
of his point guards Mark Jackson or Travis Best to Toronto to get
Douglas. The Raptors, in turn, would send power forward/center
Kevin Willis to the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers would complete the circle by sending Douglas, who
seems to inspire very little interest for an L.A. encore from Clips
officials, to Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news? According to a league source, new Raptor Antonio
Davis is an old Pacer, and is encouraging his new team to insist
upon acquiring Jackson rather than Best from the Pacers. But the
Pacers, the source said, would rather unload Best. That, as they
say around NBA campfires, could be a deal-buster, the Best-case
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   In Willis, the Clippers could have an aggressive, 7-foot veteran
(he turned 37 years old two days ago). In a perfect world, he would
replace the departed Lorenzen Wright as the insurance policy for
young center Michael Olowokandi and a spot replacement for Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   But if Taylor is moved, Willis would have an opportunity to suit
up with the Clips and be a frequent offensive option something he
has been accused of not minding.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING AN EARLY CAMP
</P>
<P>
   After losing 41 of 50 games last season, the Clippers and Coach
Chris Ford decided that the best way to prepare for next month's
training camp is to have a voluntary pre-training camp.
</P>
<P>
   So on Tuesday morning, five Clippers showed up at the Veteran's
Park SportsComplex gym for brtually repetitive shooting and
footwork drills.
</P>
<P>
   The roll call: Prized rookie Lamar Odom, point guard Troy
Hudson, guard Charles Smith, power forward Brian Skinner and backup
center Keith Closs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
