<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ISRAEL-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A BOLD RULING IN ISRAEL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Sept. 8,
1999:
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Supreme Court acted bravely and correctly Monday in
banning the Shin Bet security service from using physical coercion
to extract information from terrorism suspects. The judges
acknowledged that their ruling might make it more difficult for the
authorities to prevent and combat terror. But they wisely gave
precedence to the principles that distinguish Israel from most of
its Mideast neighbors, mainly the rule of law and respect for human
dignity.
</P>
<P>
   The court specifically banned certain interrogation techniques,
all of them repugnant. They include violent shaking, which causes
the head to whip back and forth, risking grave injury, as well as
shackling prisoners in painful positions and denying them sleep for
long periods. The judges acknowledged that Israeli courts might
choose not to punish Shin Bet agents for using coercion in
emergency situations. But the judges ruled that even in such
situations, coercion would be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   If it wished, Israel's parliament could negate the court's
ruling by passing new legislation specifically giving Shin Bet the
authority to use such techniques. Prime Minister Ehud Barak has
already suggested he wants to find a way to facilitate
interrogations in emergency situations. But legislators should let
the court's decision stand. The forms of interrogation it prohibits
are, as the judges noted, excessive and unjustified. Coercion
sometimes produces useful leads. But it can also produce unreliable
information as detainees seek to avoid further pain by offering
whatever answers they think their questioners want.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of a terrorism threat unequaled in any other
democracy, Israeli courts long gave the security service wide
latitude to extract information by physically coercive methods. In
1987 a government commission officially endorsed this kind of
interrogation, and the ruling has been renewed repeatedly since
then. But more recently political opinion has begun to change, and
Monday's court ruling was warmly welcomed by such leading figures
as Yossi Beilin, the current justice minister, and Dan Meridor, who
held that job in the early 1990s under Yitzhak Shamir.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has been surrounded by enemies and threatened by terror
since its birth. In the eyes of its founding generation, those
conditions amply justified extraordinary methods like violent
interrogation. But things have begun to change. Israel has peace
treaties with Egypt and Jordan and is again engaged in serious
negotiations with the Palestinians. In tandem with these changes,
Israel has more leeway to embrace the legal and human rights
standards of less threatened democracies. Monday's ruling marks a
healthy step in that direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
