A4079 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CISNEROS-NYT &LR;      09-08 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CISNEROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE CISNEROS PLEA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, September
8:
</P>
<P>
   It was reasonable for Attorney General Janet Reno to recommend
that an independent counsel investigate whether former Housing and
Urban Development Secretary Henry Cisneros lied to federal agents
conducting a background check in his confirmation process in 1993.
Now the expensive, overly protracted investigation has ended in a
negotiated wrist-slap for Cisneros. That seems an appropriate
outcome for a case in which a Cabinet officer had clearly erred but
the prosecution was apparently unable to prove all its charges.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of jury selection Tuesday, Cisneros reached
agreement with independent counsel David Barrett to plead guilty to
one misdemeanor count of making a false statement to Federal Bureau
of Investigation agents. Cisneros will pay a $10,000 fine but faces
no jail time and no probation. He was accused of lying to FBI
agents about how much money he had given to a former mistress after
their affair in the late 1980s became public.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett had obtained an indictment against Cisneros on 18 felony
counts of conspiracy, false statements and obstruction of justice.
But his case suffered from the fact that his star witness, Linda
Jones, the former mistress, is serving a 42-month federal sentence
for fraud and money-laundering in a separate case. She had hoped to
reduce her jail time by testifying against Cisneros. But the
prosecutors would have had a hard time presenting her as a credible
witness since she had repeatedly lied about altering secret tapes
she made of telephone conversations with Cisneros that were a
crucial part of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Still, public officials cannot be permitted to lie in background
investigations, and Cisneros has now acknowledged wrongdoing. That
may be the one lesson to be drawn from a case that should have been
settled in less than the four years it took.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
