<HEADLINE>
SEGUI'S FEELINGS FOR M'S STILL RUN DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Since trading David Segui, the Mariners have tried
eight different players at first base. For temporary replacements,
they have turned to regular catcher Dan Wilson, second baseman
David Bell and right fielder Jay Buhner. Privately, they admit to a
serious need at the position.
</P>
<P>
   How about David Segui?
</P>
<P>
   He's a free agent at the end of the season _ and amenable to the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Segui, in town for the first time since his July 28 trade to
Toronto, turned pensive when the subject was broached before
Tuesday night's game at Safeco Field. He spoke slowly and quietly,
carefully measuring each word. He talked about loyalty to the Blue
Jays, while at the same time admitting to deep, emotional ties to
the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been traded before, but it's never been as hard as it has
been here,'' said Segui, now with his fifth big league team.
``Toronto has first crack, but Seattle is a very close second, if
they're interested. I love playing for Lou (Piniella). I feel like
part of the city and the community. I'm still baffled why we didn't
get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners traded Segui for then-minor league relievers Tom
Davey and Steve Sinclair. The team said the reasons for the deal
were: 1) the club had an obvious need for pitching help; and 2)
Segui appeared difficult to re-sign in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the veteran player said the only thing he was pushing
hard for was a contract extension covering four years, and he might
have considered taking less. In four years, Segui, 32, plans to
retire and be a full-time parent to his two young kids in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to sign a three-year deal and have to find
another team for one year,'' he said. ``My dad finished his career
with the Mariners and I wanted to do the same. I had valid reasons
for a four-year deal. But three would have been OK.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Mariners apparently were willing to make a fourth
year possible if Segui met certain playing time criteria, according
to a source.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners wouldn't comment on Segui, but don't appear to be
interested in reacquiring him.
</P>
<P>
   Segui, who maintains a Seattle residence, says Mariners fans
have treated him better than anyone else. He received countless
letters from them after the trade. People stopped him on the street
Tuesday to tell him they missed him. Signs at Safeco Field Tuesday
night offered similar messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, as players, really appreciate that,'' he said. ``We're
human beings. It's easy to forget that. My time in Seattle was all
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   REINFORCEMENTS: With Class AAA Tacoma finishing its season
Monday, the Mariners called up three more players Tuesday, pitchers
Brett Hinchliffe and Sinclair and outfielder Shane Monahan. All
were with the M's earlier in the season.
</P>
<P>
   To rejoin the club, the trio had to fly from New Orleans to
Memphis to Seattle, arriving at the ballpark at 5:30 after
Monahan's wife drove them from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE FARM: Top prospect Ryan Anderson finished his third pro
season with a flourish, striking out 12 and permitting just three
hits over seven inning in Class AA New Haven's 6-3 victory over
Binghamton. The 6-foot-10 lefty compiled a 9-13 record.
</P>
<P>
   At Class A Wisconsin, normal catcher Craig Kuzmic played all
nine positions in a 3-2 win over Beloit. Kuzmic, 22, finished up on
the mound in the ninth inning, using knuckleballs only to strike
out the game's last batter and earn the save. He was 1-for-4 at bat
with a run scored.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
