A4083 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLA     09-08 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUSTRATED CAREW TAKES WOES PERSONALLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels management has made it clear
that nobody's job is safe after this season, that everyone will be
evaluated. Including a seven-time batting champion.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Carew is in his eighth season as the Angels' hitting coach,
and despite the kind of year the team's had, he hopes it isn't his
last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, I want to be back, but it's out of my control,''
Carew said. ``I'm not going to go around and worry about it or
think about it. It's their decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Carew calls this season his most frustrating as a coach. That's
because Carew takes his hitters' failures personally, like he's the
one in the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   And there has been a lot of failure. Going into Tuesday's game
against the White Sox, the Angels offense ranked last in the
American League in batting average, runs, hits, total bases,
doubles, stolen bases, slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still keep working,'' Carew said. ``It doesn't stop me from
doing what I'm supposed to do. It's why we are teachers _ when it
gets tough, you don't back off. It's just been one of those years
where things didn't click.''
</P>
<P>
   __ My name is. . .: The Angels had a few new faces in the
clubhouse Tuesday, as the team promoted catchers Bret Hemphill and
Steve Decker, pitcher Steve Mintz and outfielder Jeff DaVanon.
</P>
<P>
   DaVanon was one of the three minor-leaguers acquired in the deal
that sent Omar Olivares and Randy Velarde to the Oakland A's.
DaVanon hit .326 with six homers and 19 RBIs in 34 games for
Triple-A Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's culture shock in a lot of ways,'' said DaVanon, 25.
``It's a whole different world. Everything's a little better. Here
it's unbelievable. Everything is first class.''
</P>
<P>
   DaVanon's father was an infielder for the Angels in 1973. The
elder DaVanon, who hit .245 in 41 games in '73, gave his son some
advice: ``He told me to take a deep breath before my first
at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Reinforcements: A couple more of the Angels' minor-league
coaches joined the major-league staff Tuesday, as Leon Durham and
Tom Kotchman arrived in time to help out with pregame workouts.
Durham was a coach at Triple-A Edmonton and Kotchman was the
manager at Single-A Boise.
</P>
<P>
   __ Slow recovery: Tim Salmon, still bothered by a strained lower
back, started at DH for the second game in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no hurry to put him back in the outfield,'' interim
manager Joe Maddon said. ``We'll check on a daily basis to see how
he feels. We just want to have his bat in the lineup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
