<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4094 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-LA-NFL-LADN     09-08 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LA-NFL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. CITY COUNCIL APPROVES END RUN FOR NFL TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV AND STEVE DILBEK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With a week before Los Angeles must submit a plan
for bringing professional football to the city, the City Council
has left open the prospect of using public money to improve parking
at Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Despite broad criticism of public financing of the deal, the
council Tuesday rejected on a 6-8 vote an effort to require voter
approval of using any tax money to help draw a National Football
League team to the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The debate renewed bitter rivalries, as Councilman Joel Wachs
vowed to revive an initiative drive to require a public vote if any
tax dollars are spent on a football team. A similar conflict
erupted over the use of taxes to build the Staples Center, and
Coliseum supporters are proposing the same financial arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the public has higher priorities for their tax
dollars, whether it's books in schools or more police officers,''
said Wachs, who had first suggested the initiative during debate
over the Staples Center. ``I don't think they want it going to
billionaire sports owners.''
</P>
<P>
   But Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas, whose district includes the
Coliseum, said the council action means members are open to
negotiations with the NFL over the use of public money as long as
it is limited to incremental tax revenue generated by the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are saying we are willing to negotiate to complete a deal
to bring professional football back to Los Angeles,'' Ridley-Thomas
said.
</P>
<P>
   Voting in favor of a public vote were council members Hal
Bernson, Laura Chick, Nate Holden, Mike Hernandez, Joel Wachs and
Rita Walters. Voting against it were John Ferraro, Mike Feuer, Ruth
Galanter, Jack Goldberg, Cindy Miscikowski, Alex Padilla, Nick
Pacheco and Mark Ridley-Thomas. Councilman Rudy Svorinich Jr. was
absent.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL set Sept. 15 as a date for Los Angeles to come up with a
specific proposal. The owners are scheduled to meet a week later.
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said the league would not comment on
the council's action Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the expansion committee has been appraised of that and
any other details and developments, we'll have something to say on
Thursday,'' Aiello said.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL expansion committee is scheduled to meet in Washington,
D.C., on Thursday morning to review the expansion situation in Los
Angeles. Three high-ranking members of the NFL met privately last
week in Southern California with each of the four groups vying for
the area franchise _ the Coliseum, Carson, Anaheim and Hollywood
Park _ to get an update on each site's expansion situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were doing a lot of listening and asking a lot of
questions to get an understanding of what's there, so they can
report at the expansion meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carson project was originally championed by former Hollywood
superagent Michael Ovitz, who later developed plans for the
Coliseum when the league selected Exposition Park as its Los
Angeles expansion site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is, until we hear from the NFL that it has
officially abandoned the Coliseum, that is where our focus
remains,'' said Ovitz spokesman Mark Fabiani. ``And we have not
heard that from the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ovitz group was not invited to participate in the NFL's
meeting with Carson officials last week.
</P>
<P>
   The new Coliseum plan involves what is called incremental tax
financing to pay for construction of a new parking structure. That
means any new tax revenue generated by a professional football team
would be used to pay off bonds issued to build more parking.
</P>
<P>
   Sufficient parking is a key requirement for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   While the council did not reject the tax revenue proposal, its
members also refused to say they fully support the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the council was saying was to let's take a look at this
and let it come back to us to examine,'' Ridley-Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Other council members heard a different message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are saying to the NFL, we welcome you here to play in the
Coliseum, but don't look for any public money,'' Chick said. ``This
is not only about public dollars, but also a firm belief we should
be spending our time, energy and our dollars on fixing what's
broken in this city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time to send this strong message to the NFL: It's
time to stop playing games and start playing ball in the
Coliseum.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernson said he didn't believe the council should close any
doors.
</P>
<P>
   What we're doing with the NFL is negotiating ``and one of the
tools is being able to play a good game of poker,'' Bernson said.
``It is very clear the public is against using any tax money to
bring the NFL to Los Angeles. They should shoulder their costs and
not shake us down.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to recognize is that this is no longer about
sports. It's about business.''
</P>
<P>
   Feuer said he is concerned about the council taking an action
that would preclude other options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want us to shut off dealing with an array of
permutations that could come before us,'' Feuer said. ``There might
be something that would be to the city's advantage and we should
look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
