<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4101 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLAN     09-08 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOPER'S DEBUT ROCKS WHITE SOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Years from now, Brian Cooper won't easily
forget what happened with the first batter he faced in his
major-league debut with the Anaheim Angels on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Singleton belted a 1-2 pitch from Cooper into the
right-field seatsfor a 1-0 Chicago White Sox lead. But it's what
Cooper did AFTER giving up the homer that will be memorable for the
25-year-old right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper didn't allow another run the rest of the evening, going
seven innings to earn the victory in the Angels' 14-1 win before
16,867 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who went to Glendora High School, Citrus College and
USC, gave up four hits, struck out three and walked four as the
Angels won their second in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the win, the Angels were mathematically eliminated from
postseason play because the Boston Red Sox, who lead the AL
wild-card race, also won Tuesday. Last season, the Angels were not
eliminated until the second-to-last day of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper got help from the Angels offense, which hasn't been very
supportive of its pitchers this season. The hitters did the bulk of
their damage in two innings _ they scored six in the fourth inning
and six more in the eighth. White Sox starter Mike Sirotka (8-13)
got the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad led the Angels offense with four of their 12 hits.
Jim Edmonds and Garret Anderson had two hits apiece and Tim Salmon
hit his 13th homer of the year, a three-run blast in the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper might have been rattled a bit after allowing the leadoff
homer to Singleton, walking the next hitter. But he settled down
from there. He helped himself defensively, starting 1-6-3 double
plays in both the third and fifth innings. Edmonds saved a run for
Cooper in the first inning, diving and catching a sinking liner to
center field hit by Paul Konerko with a runner on second.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper had a losing record and an ERA over seven last season at
double-AMidland, causing him to wonder about his baseball future.
But the development of a changeup keyed a rise through the
organization this season and was big in Tuesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   He retired the side in order only once _ the sixth _ but allowed
only three White Sox baserunners to get into scoring position after
Singleton's homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels broke the game open in the fourth inning. Edmonds
opened with a single and Sirotka walked both Salmon and Mo Vaughn
to load the bases. Troy Glaus drove in the first run of the inning
with a sacrifice fly and Anderson followed with an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Trent Durrington doubled home a run, Gary
DiSarcina singled in two more and Erstad added an RBI single to put
the Angels up, 7-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
