<HEADER>
A4113 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      09-08 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMERS HIGHLIGHT M'S VICTORY OVER JAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Two of the premier power hitters in the American
League homered in the fifth inning at Safeco Field Tuesday night.
For sheer grandeur, Shawn Green's blast outdid Ken Griffey Jr's.
But for significance in the Mariners'
</P>
<P>
   7-4 victory over the Toronto Blue Jays, Griffey's mattered most.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's two-run, opposite-field home run came with two outs,
extended the Mariners' lead and gave the center fielder sole
possession of the American League home run lead with 43.
</P>
<P>
   Green's homer in the top of the inning, however, was the one
39,709 fans may remember best. Facing M's rookie Gil Meche (6-4),
the Blue Jays right fielder crushed his 37th of the year off the
windows of the Hit It Here Cafe in right. The official measurement
_ 395 feet _ seemed low, but the blast made Green the first player
to homer off the stadium restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never played here before, so I didn't know it was
special,'' said Green, who has never homered off the Hard Rock Cafe
at Toronto's SkyDome. ``I noticed in batting practice that balls to
the gaps didn't go anywhere. I thought people were exaggerating,
but it is a pitcher's park.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but that hasn't kept Griffey from hitting 10 home runs
at Safeco. His shot Tuesday night followed a sacrifice fly by David
Bell that had given the Mariners a 4-3 lead. It also made Toronto
lefty David Wells Griffey's all-time favorite home run server.
Wells has surrendered seven of Griffey's 393 career homers, more
than any other pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Griffey stood out on defense. He made all three
putouts in the inning, finishing with an over-the-shoulder Willie
Mays special to rob Shannon Stewart at the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing he does amazes me anymore,'' said left fielder Charles
Gipson. ``I've seen him change his batting stance and hit a home
run. I've seen him turn around and hit right-handed in batting
practice and hit a home run. I've seen him make catches over his
shoulder. I've seen him steal a lot of bases. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' other Mr. Everything lately has been Edgar
Martinez, who celebrated Player of the Week honors by going 3-for-4
to raise his average to .342, his highest since mid-April. The
designated hitter batted .500 last week, with four homers and nine
runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   His first hit Tuesday night was a one-out single in the second,
and Jay Buhner followed by reaching on an error. After a Mike
Blowers strike out, Russ Davis came to bat.
</P>
<P>
   Davis hit the first Safeco home run on July 17 and added another
homer in Kansas City July 29. But he had none in August, enduring
the first homerless month in his four-year Mariners career. Tuesday
night, he buried Wells' first pitch deep into the M's bullpen for a
three-run homer, tying his career high of 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was all hands,'' said hitting coach Jesse Barfield. ``A
lot of guys complain about balls not carrying well here, but a line
drive's a home run anywhere in the world. ... You hit it on a line,
it'll go.''
</P>
<P>
   The home run was evidence of the quiet progress Davis has made
recently. The third baseman was batting .227 on Aug. 29, but is
13-for-31 (.419) since.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' 3-0 lead was in danger in the fourth. Former
Mariner David Segui, who was cheered in his first game at Safeco
Field since being traded July 28, hit a leadoff double. From left
field, former teammate Gipson wagged a finger at Segui, playfully
warning him not to test his arm.
</P>
<P>
   But with two outs, Segui tried to score on a single by Darrin
Fletcher. Gipson, who recently missed seven weeks with a separated
shoulder, threw him out at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since my shoulder got hurt, I know people have been
second-guessing my arm,'' Gipson said. ``I was waiting for an
opportunity. It had to be an old friend in David, but I'll have
bragging rights tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Also owning bragging rights soon: Jose Mesa. The Mariners closer
saved his 32nd game with a perfect ninth inning, and his next save
will equal Mike Schooler's 10-year-old club record for saves in a
season.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
