<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4115 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      09-08 1891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO PULL PLUG ON WOODY ... AND LOU, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Despite the fact that they are 56-year-old natives of
Florida who played in World Series and were Yankees general
managers ousted by George Steinbrenner, Lou Piniella and Woody
Woodward are not twins separated at birth.
</P>
<P>
   But after seven years together as baseball commanders of the
Seattle Mariners, it has become difficult to distinguish which of
them gets the credit and which gets the blame.
</P>
<P>
   Though they long have been friends and colleagues, in recent
times they have quietly suggested that the other is more
responsible for the club's dearth of quality pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella is irked by criticism that he's hard on young pitchers,
claiming he hasn't been given enough major league arms. Woodward is
persuaded that the talent has been sufficient, but the pitchers
have been underused or unappreciated, as evidenced by the success
of so many after leaving Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   One thing they can agree on privately is that they've been
stymied by an ownership largely unwilling to provide resources to
compete at baseball's top level.
</P>
<P>
   Whether ownership, the manager or the general manager has had
the greater role in Mariners travails, what is indisputable is
that, despite the club's prominence in local sporting culture, it
has won more than 85 games in a season only once in the seven-year
regime of Woodward and Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's 11-year term is the longest among current major
league GMs. The tandem tenure with Piniella is exceeded only by GM
John Schuerholz and manager Bobby Cox with the Braves and GM John
Hart and manager Mike Hargrove with the Indians _ clubs with
considerably more to show for themselves this decade, even before a
possible World Series meeting next month.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, meanwhile, have won one playoff game since '95 and
are going nowhere next month.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989 under Woodward (he arrived at midseason of 1988), the
Mariners have won 49 percent of their games. Piniella is at 52
percent since his appointment in '93 _ not bad by major league
standards, but weak considering the team's company.
</P>
<P>
   Only after baseball subdivided in 1994 to provide the Mariners
with just three mostly average rivals in the American League West
did the club win division titles, in 1995 and '97.
</P>
<P>
   Results in '98 and so far in '99 have amounted to a squandering
of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The prime culprit: A failure to develop, keep or acquire
pitching sufficient for contention.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the failure is the move from the Kingdome to the
Guilty Pleasure, a new ballpark friendliest to the aspect of
baseball where the Mariners historically have been poorest.
</P>
<P>
   The decade of pitching flops and this season's abrupt
reinvestment in arms for the new ballpark mandate more switches
this off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners should begin with a new manager and general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners need baseball leadership with some history and
touch with pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Though the club's sudden stockpiling of young arms has turned
the season into one long audition _ a club-record 27 pitchers used,
including 14 rookies, with more to come _ the sudden overload isn't
as impressive as it looks, for two reasons:
</P>
<P>
   -- No pitcher from the farm system has developed into a
significant contributor in Seattle since Erik Hanson (1988-93);
</P>
<P>
   -- Other than being forced to deal superstars Ken Griffey Jr. or
Alex Rodriguez, the Mariners have few position players at any level
to fill holes created by the trades for pitching or losses from
attrition. That means they will have to trade pitching for
pitching, because the free-agent market this off-season is thin.
</P>
<P>
   Think about this: The Mariners last week had to bring back Mike
Blowers, cut from his Japanese team, to play first base _ the
eighth player to do so since David Segui's July trade, prompting
more thoughts of Abbott &AMP; Costello routines instead of wild-card
chances.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise storehouse is depleted, because so many trades
have failed to fill voids, while creating their own.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's losing record when it comes to pitching deals and
Piniella's inability to bring out much from young or average
pitchers have left the Mariners dealing from weakness as the club
approaches the latest pivot point in club history _ the attempt
this winter to keep Junior and A-Rod in Seattle long-term.
</P>
<P>
   Trading either or both superstars becomes a stronger temptation
for a club in need of multiple fixes. The problem is that such a
deal means sacrificing either the greatest player of his era in
Griffey, or Rodriguez, perhaps baseball's glamor answer to Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   By this off-season, the team can't get well enough fast enough
to make much more than promises to the two stars. And failure to
resolve the Griffey and Rodriguez situations by Opening Day 2000
will cast a bleakness over the season far worse than the
debilitating Randy Johnson trade watch of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward and his top aide, vice-president of player development
Roger Jongewaard, have been solid spotters of young pitching
talent. But a glance around the major leagues reveals many of them
are pitching respectably elsewhere: Dave Burba, Shawn Estes, Mike
Hampton, Matt Mantei, Joe Mays, Jim Mecir, Jeff Nelson, Ron Villone
... the list is long and painfully familiar to Mariners fans.
</P>
<P>
   Over the holiday weekend, Boston reliever Derek Lowe put up two
saves against the Mariners, while catcher Jason Varitek homered
three times as the wild card-leading Red Sox won three of four
games. They were traded from Seattle in July 1997, for much
lamented relief pitcher Heathcliff Slocumb.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the veterans from outside the organization whose
stays in Seattle ended for reasons other than being a decent major
league pitcher: Mike Jackson, Sterling Hitchcock, Andy Benes, Terry
Mulholland, Omar Olivares, Tim Belcher. They remain solid
contributors, the kind so long missing here that the Mariners this
season were forced to put the bulk of their starting rotation upon
three rookies.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, all teams have former players who flourish
elsewhere. Some amount of baseball success can be attributed to
right place, right time, or just plain luck, as opposed to
managerial brilliance or talent-sniffing acumen.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the talent drain was not the responsibility of Woodward
and Piniella, but budget decisions from ownerships petrified by
baseball's economics.
</P>
<P>
   Well-funded teams such as the Mets, Yankees, Dodgers and Braves
can afford to squander talent occasionally because the cupboard is
plentiful. But for most of their 23 years, the Mariners have posed
themselves as a have-not, usually surrendering their top homegrown
talent to richer clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, despite an impressive fan base and a lucrative new
park, trades this season have unloaded so much salary that the
current payroll value is under $40 million, well into the bottom
half of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, spending on player salaries is no guarantee of a
championship, as flops this season by the Dodgers, Angels, Orioles
and Rockies attest. But the old bromide still prevails _ not
spending heavily virtually guarantees no championship. Remember,
this year's low-budget darlings, the A's and Reds, haven't won
anything yet.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mariners have spent money, it hasn't been done wisely.
The nadir of the Woodward-Piniella regime was last year's bullpen,
which had the AL's highest payroll and its highest earned-run
average, and became a national baseball joke. To improve the 'pen
this year, more resources were exhausted, and it's still
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Mariners have had their No. 1 starter go
haywire in three of the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Johnson was lost for much of the year with a back
injury. In 1998, it was his head. The decision not to lock him up
with a long-term deal distracted The Big Unit into an 8-10 record
before he was traded to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Jeff Fassero flopped, a victim of elbow surgery and
a contract-year brain cramp. Part of Fassero's trouble that
preceded his waiver was, in his own words, a fear of failing to
fill Johnson's role as the ace _ yet another casualty of the Big
Unit botch.
</P>
<P>
   Though Mariners bosses are rightfully proud of the performance
of the players acquired for Johnson, the fact is they still don't
have a proven No. 1 pitcher, and probably won't unless they trade
Griffey or Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   In the Johnson mess and some other pitching failures, Piniella
has been as much victim as perpetrator. And this year, if he had
full seasons from Rodriguez, Carlos Guillen, Jay Buhner, Butch
Henry, Mark Leiter and Paul Abbott, the Mariners would be much
closer in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, what team doesn't have injuries? And what divine
baseball grace says the Mariners deserved improbably creditable
years from rookie starters Freddy Garcia, John Halama and Gil
Meche?
</P>
<P>
   They all came to Seattle as almost ready-made major leaguers.
Will they stay that way?
</P>
<P>
   That is the ultimate question dictating Piniella's fate. He's on
his fourth pitching coach in seven years, having flailed almost
helplessly trying to make average pitchers out of Ken Cloude, Bob
Wolcott, Dave Fleming, Salomon Torres and a host of other
youngsters who have flickered in Seattle, then flamed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throw strikes,'' Piniella always demands. Well, no kidding?
</P>
<P>
   Piniella's umpire outbursts that are so ejectibly amusing also
reflect much of the way he works with his pitchers _ emotionally,
not analytically. Too many good arms have come and gone through the
organization to suggest it's merely coincidence that none have
flourished here.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the club's sudden investment in pitching, and the good
fortune of three talented rookies, the staff ERA remains the worst
in the AL, as well as club history. Lately, production from the
cannibalized offense has slumped.
</P>
<P>
   This call for big change is not made easily. Piniella and
Woodward aren't dumber now than when they were hailed in 1995. A
champion as player and manager, Piniella has more than 1,000 career
victories with three clubs, handles well the difficult tasks of
managing the clubhouse and the media and remains a popular figure
here for many.
</P>
<P>
   The travails of other top managers such as Davey Johnson, Jim
Leyland and Tony La Russa suggest again there is no formula, system
or personality type that assures managerial success.
</P>
<P>
   But Piniella's contemptuous impatience and volatility with
youngsters, and his record with pitching, are of little virtue
where the franchise has chosen to live: in a vast, pitcher-friendly
ballpark that was built at extraordinary cost based on owner
promises of contention _ not auditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome expectations _ it's a good thing,'' said Piniella
recently. ``This is a baseball town now.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Woodward can be proud of their roles in making it such.
</P>
<P>
   But a two-season flop and a seven-season failure to find,
develop and keep good pitching make Piniella and Woodward, with a
dubious assist from ownership, a baseball version of the Kingdome _
good for the time, and a victim of change.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
