<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 03:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4126 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BBA-REDSOX-A'S-BOS     09-08 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX DRAW FIRST BLOOD
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-REDSOX-A'S-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By GORDON EDES 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The polite thing would be to say that the
Oakland A's blinked first when faced with their moment of truth
against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   But that wouldn't begin to describe how completely the A's came
unhinged Tuesday night at the sight of the Red Sox, who pounced at
the first scent of weakness in this wild-card showdown en route to
a 5-3 win.
</P>
<P>
   The A's, playing their first meaningful game in seven seasons,
had hoped to take on the look of a playoff-bound team. Instead,
they showed up with shirttails untucked, shoes scuffed, and flies
at half-mast against the Sox, who took a four-game lead in the
wild-card race with 23 games left.
</P>
<P>
   The A's were as completely undressed as the naked intruder who
performed handstands on the field in the ninth inning while wearing
nothing but a baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone started yelling, so I expected that somebody was
running on the field, but I didn't expect that,'' said Derek Lowe,
who registered his third save on this trip. ``I got the heck out of
the way. You don't know what people like that are going to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was karaoking, making these noises, backpedaling, all kinds
of things. But he may have calmed me down. I'd just thrown four
balls in a row, and they may have been getting some momentum. That
took it away from them. I got to throw a few extra warmup pitches,
got out of my rut, and cleared my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one too many adult beverages, right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland shortstop Miguel Tejada dropped a popup hit by leadoff
man Jose Offerman, the first in a dumbfounding series of mistakes
that led to five Boston runs in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox failed to score after that inning, leaving five runners
on base in the last three innings, but won behind Tim Wakefield and
another collaborative bullpen effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, a season-best 19 games over .500 after winning for the
fourth time in five games on this 12-game excursion, are now as
close to the first-place Yankees (5 1/2 games) as they are to
fading wild-card contender Toronto, which lost to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   There was one ominous note for the Sox. Shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra was replaced in the eighth inning by rookie Donnie
Sadler. He was reported to have sustained a bruised left ankle; he
fouled a pitch off his ankle on his first at-bat. An inning before
being removed, while Jimy Williams was making a pitching change,
Garciaparra had trotted in from his position and talked at length
with the Sox manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fouled that ball off his foot . . . but he'll be OK,''
Williams said. ``Their team doctor came and checked him. We'll try
to use some common sense tomorrow the best we can.'' Don't be
surprised to see Garciaparra sit Wednesday afternoon. With an off
day Thursday he would have two days off prior to the Yankees series
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first inning was over, A's right fielder Matt Stairs
had overthrown the cutoff man twice, both times putting runners in
scoring position. Third baseman Olmedo Saenz threw wide of first
baseman Jason Giambi, pulling him off the bag on Wilton Veras's
infield hit. Tejada jugged a feed on a force play at second,
erasing any chance at a double play.
</P>
<P>
   And A's starter Gil Heredia, who threw a complete-game win
against the Sox three weeks ago in Fenway Park and issues fewer
walks per nine innings than any pitcher in the American League,
walked Troy O'Leary and hit Mike Stanley in succession.
</P>
<P>
   Heredia also gave up an RBI double to Reggie Jefferson, who had
knocked in just four runs since the All-Star break but was
nominated by Williams to replace the slumping Brian Daubach; an RBI
single to Garciaparra, who has hit in 10 straight games; and an RBI
single to Trot Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Veras also was credited with an RBI on his infield hit. The Sox
sent 10 batters to the plate, the first time they batted around in
the first inning since June 26, when they scored 11 runs against
the White Sox in Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, restored to the rotation when the Sox decided there
would be no miracle from Ramon Martinez this season, took full
advantage of his five-run cushion, striking out seven of the
overeager A's in the first three innings.
</P>
<P>
   The A's, who had a runner on second and no out in the first and
runners on first and second with no out in the second and failed to
score either time, finally broke through in the fourth against
Wakefield, who walked the first three batters to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   After a discussion with pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, Wakefield
kept the damage to a minimum. Ben Grieve hit a sacrifice fly for
one run, and ex-Sox batterymate Mike Macfarlane singled home
another, but Wakefield retired Rich Becker on a bouncer to second
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield stranded Randy Velarde on third in the fifth, and
breezed through a 1-2-3 sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Heredia, saddled with four unearned runs in the first inning,
checked the Red Sox until departing with one out and one on in the
seventh. Third-base umpire Mike Everitt lent unwitting assistance
to Heredia's cause when he ruled that left fielder Grieve had made
a shoestring catch of O'Leary's sinking liner, when in fact the
ball bounced at least a half-foot in front of Grieve's glove.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had two runners on in the third inning, but Offerman
lined out to end the threat. They had two on with one out in the
seventh, but reliever Tim Worrell retired Stanley on a fly ball and
struck out Varitek.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
