<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 03:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4127 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LEVIS-CEO-SFCHRON &LR;      09-08 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVIS-CEO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LEVI STRAUSS HIRES NEW CEO FROM OUTSIDE ITS GENE POOL  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For only the second time in its 146-year
history, Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. has tapped a nonfamily member to run
the venerable San Francisco company.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Haas, 57, the great-great-grandnephew of company founder
Levi Strauss, said Tuesday that he will relinquish his chief
executive title on September 27 to Philip Marineau, a highly
regarded PepsiCo executive. Haas will remain chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Marineau, 52, who is credited with making substantial inroads
against Coca-Cola as the head of Pepsi's North America operations,
joins Levi's at a difficult time. The jeans maker is expected to
post a net-loss year because of higher-than-expected costs related
to plant closures, according to sources close to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Global sales, which fell 13 percent in 1998 and 4 percent in
1997, are expected to decline steeply again this year _ between 10
and 12 percent, one source said. That would bring 1999 sales to
$5.6 billion or less, a precipitous fall from the company's 1996
peak of $7.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's said in January that it was looking for a new chief
operating officer who also might hold the president's title to
replace then-president and COO Peter Jacobi. Haas had planned to
groom the incoming executive for two years and then retire, he said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Marineau, who was CEO and president of Pepsi's $11 billion
North America division, refused to come aboard for anything less
than the top post. ``I've done enough training,'' Marineau said in
a telephone interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Haas said Tuesday that he is proud of his accomplishments, which
include include ``10 years of unprecedented profitability and
shareholder value creation,'' the introduction of the Dockers and
Slates brands and progressive workplace policies such as
domestic-partner benefits. Still, with the downturn in the last two
years, he is leaving day-to-day management of the company with a
besmirched record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given his absolute druthers, I think he would rather have
waited two years and turned it around'' himself, said one person
close to Haas. But the chance to hire Marineau was too good to pass
up. ``I think Bob had to swallow hard and say, `OK, let's make him
CEO,' '' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is an admission by the board of the company and
perhaps Bob Haas himself that it is best for him to be in an
oversight capacity and let an operator from outside . . . be in
charge of making the day-to-day decisions,'' said Isaac Lagnado,
president of New York's Tactical Retail Solutions, a consulting
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Lagnado and others credited Haas with leading the company
through a successful leveraged buyout in 1985 and a second stock
buyback in 1996 that put the company's ownership in even fewer
hands. When Haas came aboard, sales totaled just $2.6 billion. The
real problems didn't start until two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the company's reversal of fortunes, ``people who
invested in the company during the original buyout still have made
10 to 20 times their money,'' noted board member Warren Hellman, a
San Francisco investment banker.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his tenure, Haas was ``an outstanding CEO,'' Hellman
said. ``Ultimately you can judge a CEO not only on the job he does
but on how well he chooses a successor.''
</P>
<P>
   As a private company, Levi's executive-recruitment efforts were
hampered by its inability to provide stock options. But Marineau is
getting a very sweet pot, said people close to the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is able to turn this around, he will be quite a wealthy
guy _ even wealthy by Internet standards,'' said one person close
to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Marineau will be paid an annual salary below $1 million; with
bonuses, his annual compensation will hit seven digits, a source
said. The real payoff, if Marineau manages a strong turnaround,
will come in three to five years, when he stands to receive tens of
millions of dollars in cash incentives tied to earnings and other
targets.
</P>
<P>
   The only other nonfamily member CEO was Robert Grohman, who ran
the company _ not very successfully _ from 1981 to 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Haas said he has no regrets about hiring someone outside the
family. No other family members are in active management of the
company, although Levi Strauss' descendants exercise firm control
over the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue to me is not about family versus nonfamily,'' Haas
said. ``The issue is about competency. This is a large, complex,
global business and just because your DNA pool happens to have Levi
Strauss as an ancestor really isn't a qualification for running
this company.''
</P>
<P>
   Marineau was chosen because he is a ``strong brand-builder,
somebody who has had experience in situations like this in renewing
the luster of strong brands,'' Haas said.
</P>
<P>
   Haas also described Marineau as a team-builder who will run
Levi's in the humane fashion it is famous for.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier stint at Quaker Oats Co., Marineau boosted sales
of Gatorade by more than 50 percent, and held off advances from
rival sports drinks introduced by Coke and Pepsi, said Manny
Goldman, beverage research coordinator for Merrill Lynch Global
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really pays attention to the details,'' said Goldman, who
has followed Marineau's projects for some 15 years. ``At Gatorade
he took something and made it into a fabulous brand. In the case of
Pepsi there was a complete turnaround,'' with Pepsi now gaining on
Coke for top market share in supermarket sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he has a super opportunity to take this wonderful brand
(Levi's) and do something with it,'' Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Marineau will have to quickly learn the ins and outs of
the rag trade, one analyst says Marineau's earlier consumer-product
experience is relevant.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Reiter, president of Herbert Mines Associates, a New York
headhunter specializing in retail, said Marineau's experience is
relevant because Levi's ``needs to reinvent themselves, and
beverage companies are continually reinventing themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
