<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
P.J. LOCKS HORNS WITH MOOSE'S
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ In the shadows and back alleys of North Beach,
they're whispering tales of P.J. the Pirate.
<P>
   P.J. Carlesimo haunts North Beach by night and has for the last
couple years _ ever since he started coaching the Oakland (aka:
Golden State) Warriors and found himself in need of frequent
unwinding, decompression and/or detoxification.
</P>
<P>
   Carlesimo is the coach who was choked by one of his players,
Latrell Sprewell, creating the only nonboring basketball news to
come out of Oakland in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   P.J.'s M.O., FYI, is to hold court at frequent, semi-impromptu
late-night dinner outings with many pals in N. Beach restaurants,
drowning his basketball sorrows in marinara.
</P>
<P>
   Now he and a few friends are in the process of buying Adolfo's,
a hip restaurant that wasn't quite hip enough to stay in business
and went arrividerci about two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   So P.J.'s bringing it back to life, but naturally he needs
people to run the place, so he snatched the GM from Moose's
restaurant, a former college chum, and P.J. eventually might wind
up spiriting away some other key Moose troops.
</P>
<P>
   Good restaurant help is hard to come by, and some say Moose's
antlers are glowing red over the defections.
</P>
<P>
   One Moose loyalist has a suggested name for P.J.'s new joint:
Machiavelli's.
</P>
<P>
   (Another suggestion: If P.J.'s restaurant needs someone to kill
the chickens, Sprewell's the man.)
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE IT wouldn't be fair to suggest that D.A. Terence Hallinan
adopt as his re-election campaign slogan: ``Keeping our jails
crime-free.''
</P>
<P>
   But a recent Chronicle story points out that Hallinan has the
lowest batting average among county D.A.s in terms of putting away
bad guys and gals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing his failing score at convictions,'' says Regan McMahon,
``makes me wonder if he shouldn't have been sent to mandatory
summer school for prosecutors.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallinan, still fuming over The Chronicle story (and he hasn't
even seen the cheap shots printed above), was overheard at
McCormick &AMP; Kuleto's the other day, talking about publishing a
weekly D.A. newsletter detailing his criminal-fanny kicking.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND SCHOOLS meltdown update: Amazing as it seems, some
Oakland public school teachers opt to seek teaching jobs elsewhere,
at fancy schools where they have stuff like textbooks and toilet
paper.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, often these sinking-ship-jumper-offers, even if
they apply early, don't get hired elsewhere until July or August,
whereupon they resign their Oakland jobs, leaving Oakland
shorter-handed than it already is.
</P>
<P>
   My spies say George Musgrove, Oakland's interim superintendent
of schools, warned his teachers last week that everyone who resigns
after July 1 faces punishment. Musgrove will ask the state Board of
Education to suspend that person's teaching credential for one
year.
</P>
<P>
   That'll teach teachers not to apply in Oakland. And it will also
do wonders for the state's drastic teacher shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Cute kicker: A few Oakland teachers who resigned in May and June
might also get their credentials yanked for a year because the
woman in personnel who handled resignations resigned, and none of
the letters of resignation can be found.
</P>
<P>
   That's right: The dog ate their letters of resignation.
</P>
<P>
   OVERHEARD by keen-eared Bob Lacey, at the next lunch table at
the Miramar Beach Restaurant in Half Moon Bay:
</P>
<P>
   He: ``Did you read the article in today's Chronicle about
Attention Deficit Disorder?''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``Not all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Rimshot, please.)
</P>
<P>
   TIGER WOODS has inspired a legion of minority youngsters to take
up golf, and at Harding Park Monday I chatted with one of those
people.
</P>
<P>
   The bright young Asian American man told me he took up the sport
seriously two years ago after watching Tiger win the Masters, and
now he says he's close to breaking 80.
</P>
<P>
   The young man looked familiar. Sure enough, it was Michael Yaki,
the boyish S.F. supervisor, who helped the city set up Tiger's
two-day coaching clinic for inner-city kids.
</P>
<P>
   And for all the photo-op-type staginess of the event, once Tiger
ditched the suits and got down in the driving-range trenches with
the kids from the 'hood, it was hard to be a cynical observer.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger spent time with the kids, really showed 'em stuff. It was
a touching scene.
</P>
<P>
   I'd hate to saddle Tiger with a goody-goody image, but in sports
he is the anti-Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   As for supervisor Yaki's claim that he is close to breaking 80:
Big deal. I don't play much golf, but I've already broken way more
than 80 clubs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
