<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 03:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4130 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUSH-IMMIGRATION-SFCH     09-08 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IMMIGRATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUSH BLASTED FOR COMMENT ON IMMIGRANT COSTS  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who came to
California last week to strengthen his hand among Latinos, is now
facing fallout over his claim that the federal government has no
role in paying back states for costs of illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   The statement not only stirred up anger from at least one rival
presidential candidate _ but also immigration experts who said
Bush's statements appear counter to his own actions as the governor
of Texas, a border state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in an interview with The Chronicle last week, was
specifically asked if he would reimburse California for the
estimated billions of dollars the state spends annually on services
and education for illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said the GOP front-runner. Asked for a reason, Bush
said, ``Because that's not a federal role, in my judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats both expressed surprise, noting that
Texas _ under Bush's own administration _ has tried to recover such
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Former California Gov. Pete Wilson, a Republican, waged a
three-year court battle to force the federal government to
reimburse California for $15 billion to cover the accumulated costs
of providing a public school education, medical care and other
services to 1.7 million illegal immigrants. In 1997, a lower court
ruled that the issue was a ``political question'' to be resolved by
the Congress and the president; the U.S. Supreme Court let that
decision stand.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Mueller, communications director for GOP rival presidential
candidate Steve Forbes, seized on Bush's comments Tuesday, saying,
``Clearly, Gov. Bush doesn't seem to understand the problems _ or
where that responsibility lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Forbes) believes that defending the borders of the U.S. is a
federal responsibility _ so there is a responsibility to reimburse
states like California feeling the impact of illegal immigration,''
said Mueller. ``Based on Mr. Bush's record as governor, apparently
what he's saying is what's good for the people of Texas is not good
for the people of California.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, Democratic Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa
was equally critical. ``It's hard to believe that Gov. George W.
Bush would hold the taxpayers of California responsible for
services provided to undocumented immigrants as a result of
decisions made beyond their control by the federal government,'' he
said in a statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign declined official comment Tuesday. But Bush
supporters in California pointed out that the governor has had very
strong positions on border control issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The benefits aspect is not as simple as `will you or won't you
reimburse?' There are three areas: incarcerate, medicate and
educate,'' one supporter said. ``The California Legislature has
made decisions on what benefits, if any, they will subsidize. ...
It's not just a federal issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted in The Chronicle interview that Texas has a more
effective border control effort with its successful program called
Operation Hold the Line; he also said he does not support federal
benefits to illegal immigrants, except in emergency cases.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments nonetheless underscored some potential political
pitfalls for the GOP front-runner, who has promised a strong
campaign in California and is scheduled to return to Silicon Valley
in late September. The Texas governor has made strong Latino
outreach a cornerstone of his campaign and has repeatedly
emphasized good relations with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But critics noted Bush's statements, in an interview Thursday
before his appearance at the Latin Business Association, appeared
to conflict with statements made earlier in his administration.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, his press secretary, Karen Hughes, issued a statement
regarding Bush's support of a legal appeal by Texas Attorney
General Dan Morales to recover $1.34 billion spent by his state on
incarceration and education of illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair to the taxpayers of Texas to stick them with the
bill when the government fails to enforce immigration laws,''
Hughes said to reporters then.
</P>
<P>
   Since Wilson lost his battle in the courts, U.S. Senator Dianne
Feinstein has ``fought long and hard for more funding,''
specifically through the State Criminal Alien Assistance Program,
which reimburses states for the costs of incarcerating criminal
aliens, said her spokesman, Howard Gantman, Tuesday. ``It has been
an important issue to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Gantman cited a letter from border state legislators to the U.S.
Senate in July of this year _ signed by both Republican U.S.
senators from Texas, Kay Bailey Hutchison and Phil Gramm _ urging
the federal government to deliver a full appropriation of $500
million to states to pay for services to illegal immigrants held
for various criminal convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Trounstine, director of communications for California
Democratic Gov. Gray Davis, said while California `has not taken a
position seeking reimbursement for the cost of education...(the
state) has a very strong position seeking reimbursement of hundreds
of millions for the cost of incarcerating illegal immigrants..held
in county and state facilities while they're awaiting
deportation.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Stein, executive director of the Washington-based Federation
for American Immigration Reform, called Bush's statements ``totally
irresponsible ... (because) that sort of policy creates a
groundswell of antagonism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, immigration is the federal responsibility _
whether it is to control the border or assist communities in
handling the impact,'' said Stein. ``If states are given no
protection and no financial support for the costs, then the federal
government has no incentive to control the borders.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comment also ``sets the tone for what the immigrant
rhetoric is going to be for (Bush's) administration,'' said Luis
Arteaga, who heads the California-based Latino Issues Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Voters deserve to know ``what his position is on immigration _
legal and undocumented _ and what really he sees for the federal
government, and whether he's willing to pay up,'' said Arteaga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 0335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
