<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTIONS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR RE ELECTED BY WIDE MAR GIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT KOSSAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix Mayor Skip Rimsza cruised to an easy re-election
Tuesday, with unofficial results showing him scoring a sweeping
victory over chief rival Randy Pullen.
</P>
<P>
   Pullen, a real estate consultant who formerly had supported
Rimsza, appeared to benefit from hotelier Steve Cohn's mocking
attacks on the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, voters stuck with the incumbent. With all
the votes counted, unofficial results gave Rimsza 59 percent of the
vote to Pullen's 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very gratifying,'' Rimsza said Tuesday night at a
celebration at his house in northeast Phoenix. ``We tried to focus
on the positive things for Phoenix, and it's exciting to see the
voters appreciated it.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was applauded by a crowd that included his friend,
Richard Olsen, a Realtor, wearing a painted-on white mustache.
</P>
<P>
   The mustache was a joking reminder of signs put up by Cohn
featuring Rimsza with a milk mustache and the slogan ``Got
Milked?'' _ a reference to Cohn's view that Rimsza had backed a
hotel deal that was bad for the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did that (the painted mustache) to put a smile on Skip's
face,'' Olsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Pullen asserted that he ran a `hard, good campaign`` and that
his poor showing in mail-in vote totals indicated he lost because
he ran out of time to overcome Rimsza's name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the numbers tell me is once we got the message to the
people, they were responding,`` Pullen said.
</P>
<P>
   Two minor candidates in the mayoral race, Patrick Dardis, owner
of a small vending machine company, and longtime activist Anthony
Abril, were lagging far behind the two front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Pullen got his biggest boost not by scoring
ideological points on Rimsza but from hotel owner Cohn's relentless
anti-Rimsza publicity machine.
</P>
<P>
   But voters weren't won over by his message, choosing instead to
retain Rimsza, a former real estate salesman who joined the City
Council in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn, an owner of the Crowne Plaza hotel downtown, leaped into
action against Rimsza after the mayor piloted a city deal to help
build and finance a downtown Marriott that Cohn says would ruin his
business.
</P>
<P>
   After Cohn funded a petition drive for a referendum on the
issue, Rimsza and the council dropped the first deal, then voted
8-1 on June 30 to seal a second Marriott deal with an ``emergency
clause,'' which prohibits a public vote.
</P>
<P>
   The move kicked up public protests, also helped along by Cohn.
</P>
<P>
   He funded a new petition drive for a public vote on the hotels,
two lawsuits and several hundred of the ``Got Milked?'' signs. Cohn
also paid for a radio ad urging residents to vote for anyone but
Rimsza.
</P>
<P>
   Pullen jumped into the race minutes after the June vote, calling
the use of the emergency clause ``a subversion of the public
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Pullen's candidacy surprised just about everyone, particularly
since Pullen, 50, had been part of Rimsza's ``in'' crowd.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime Phoenix business insider, Pullen even had made a $300
donation to the mayor's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Though Pullen opposed the Marriott vote, he himself had sought
city help for a hotel project earlier this year, when he and two
partners unsuccessfully sought $5 million in city incentives to
build a $50 million Jacksonian Hotel near Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Pullen's campaign began poorly when he released a list of
impressive movers and shakers that he said were supporting him,
only to have many of the biggest names on the list angrily deny
that they favored Pullen.
</P>
<P>
   Pullen said he ``misunderstood the level of their support.''
After that, much of his support appeared to come out of his own
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Pullen's campaign explored two themes: excessive crime in
Phoenix and Rimsza's arrogant use of the emergency clause to stop
public votes on big-ticket items, such as the Marriott and the
controversial Sumitomo Sitix plant in northeast Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Pullen pledged that the emergency clause would not be used
improperly on his watch.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders have long stated that a third large downtown hotel
is the key to successful redevelopment. Pullen contended that the
city must expand Civic Plaza, giving it enough room for major
national conventions, to guarantee enough business for three
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Pullen also asserted that crime in Phoenix remains out of
control. He blames mostly an influx of drugs and dealers, saying
that a stronger, more organized effort is needed to root them out,
including more and better-equipped police with more power to
determine the best ways to clean up the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, he said, the city needs more and better-equipped
police officers with greater leeway to use effective methods to
clean up the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Rimsza was elected mayor in 1994 in a special election after
former Mayor Paul Johnson resigned to run for governor. Rimsza was
re-elected in 1995 to a full four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Rimsza sees himself as CEO of a vast corporation, successfully
delivering services smoothly and efficiently to his customers.
</P>
<P>
   He vigorously defended his support of the emergency clause,
saying that a public vote, with an uncertain outcome, could have
killed the deal for a hotel critical to the downtown's future.
</P>
<P>
   Rimsza campaigned on his goals for the next four years: saving
open space, improving public transit and equipping the police
department with a crime-fighting computer network. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 0444EDT &QL; 
