<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY - No. 442 - September 8, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. JUDE LAW : LAW OF THE LAND British actor Jude Law has a
penchant for dark, challenging roles, playing an alcoholic cripple
in ``Gattaca'' and a hustler in ``Midnight in the Garden of Good
and Evil.'' He may finally find mainstream fame with his next role,
alongside Gwyneth Paltrow, Matt Damon and Cate Blanchett in ``The
Talented Mr. Ripley.'' By James Fallon. From Women's Wear Daily.
750 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 2. LL
COOL J : FROM THE STREET TO THE SCREEN His name is James Todd
Smith, but fans know him as LL Cool J - one of rap's
longest-running stars (15 years and over 20 million CDs sold,) and
an emerging actor. His stage name, taken as a teenager, stands for
Ladies Love Cool James. In ``Deep Blue Sea,'' he plays an amiable
shark-fighting chef, but the biggest role he's undertaken is in the
just-released drugs and crime movie, ``In Too Deep,'' in which he
plays an evil millionaire who goes by the name of God. In this
film, the ladies will not love cool James, nor will the men. It may
seem unlikely that LL Cool J should play such a hard character as
he is one of the hip-hop world's good guys. By Jim Sullivan. BPI.
1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
JAPANESE POCKET MONSTERS TAKE OVER AMERICA'S YOUNG The new Japanese
invention for children proves equally intriguing to parents : It
sends 3- to 11-year-olds bounding out of bed at the crack of dawn,
eager to start the day. It's not a high-tech alarm clock. It's a
``Pokemon'' which is short for ``pocket monster.'' ``Pokemon''
finished the 1998-99 season as the No. 1 children's show in the
United States. The animated series concerns the quest to capture
all 150 species of pocket monsters, which range from fuzzy and cute
to things that look like escaped mutants from ``Star Wars.''
``Pokemon'' has achieved its hit status without displays of
bloodshed or weaponry, or even sophisticated animation. By Laurel
Graeber. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
ALESSANDRO NIVOLA BUILDS CAREER THE OLD-FASHIONED WAY Actor
Alessandro Nivola made a big splash as Nicolas Cage's brother in
the action hit ``Face/Off.'' Now he has three major films on the
way. In ``Best Laid Plans,'' he and teen queen Reese Witherspoon
play lovers in jeopardy. Nivola follows that with ``Mansfield
Park,'' based on the Jane Austen novel, and then makes his singing
debut for director Kenneth Branagh in the ambitious musical version
of Shakespeare's : ``Love's Labours Lost.'' By Joshua Mooney. BPI.
1,000 words + photo.
</P>
<P>
   5. NOAH WYLE : FROM 'ER' TO KOSOVO Noah Wyle, ``E.R.'s'' dashing
Dr. John Carter, spent the first two weeks of his summer in Kosovo
as a guest of the group Doctors of the World. Wyle visited refugee
camps and observed medical teams at work, spending most of his time
in one tent city where six doctors cared for about 12,000 refugees
fleeing ethnic purging. ``It was unbelievable. I've never seen such
acts of heroism in aid of such acts of senseless brutality. I came
back shaken to the core,'' says Wyle. By Christopher Loudon. 1,200
words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
KEVIN BACON GOES SUPERNATURAL Kevin Bacon has never had a psychic
experience but he's not a firm disbeliever. ``I'm totally open to
it,'' he says. ``If there are spirits out there that want to
contact me ... I'll sign autographs.'' His scary new movie ``Stir
of Echoes'' is the latest and creepiest in a series of horror films
this summer. Bacon performs one manic, over-the-top sequence which
is drawing comparisons to Jack Nicholson's work in ``The Shining.''
By Ian Spelling. 900 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
HEATHER LOCKLEAR VS. THE TELETUBBIES Heather Locklear, one of the
most famous blondes in Los Angeles, says she can't compete with the
children's TV show ``Teletubbies''. The greatest challenge of TV's
favourite vixen (''Melrose Place,'') is dealing with her young
daughter's insistence on watching the Teletubbies. By C. Pearlman.
1,100 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
SUDDENLY SINGLE : A TOUGH YEAR FOR BROOKE SHIELDS ``It's been one
of the roughest years of my life,'' says actress Brooke Shields. In
the last few months she has survived a series of difficult personal
experiences which, in combination, might have felled a less
balanced individual. By Ivor Davis. 1,300 words + photo. (N/A Great
Britain and Australia.)
_____________________________________________________________ 9.
KEVIN COSTNER For the love of a game called acting, Kevin Costner
insisted that director Sam Raimi let him fall apart in his new
baseball movie ``For Love of the Game, `` in which he plays an
aging superstar baseball pitcher who, during the course of one
final game, reflects on his life, his love and his losses. In many
ways, Costner is like his character, a man who appears to have it
all. Although he is a superstar millionaire with all the trappings
of success, Costner says there are still many days when he feels
very alone. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo.
