<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Wednesday, Sept. 8, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-CHOICE (San Francisco) _ One in four children across
California and the nation have left their neighborhood schools in
favor of magnet, charter or voucher programs, despite lax oversight
and scant evidence of academic success, according to a two-year
study released Wednesday by a UC-Berkeley and Stanford University
think tank. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   STUN-GUN (San Francisco) _ A 13-year-old eighth grader faces
felony charges as well as possible expulsion from school after
allegedly using a stun gun on another student. By ULYSSES TORASSA
and SARAH YANG.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LEVI-STRAUSS (San Francisco) _ With the appointment of PepsiCo's
Philip Marineau to lead Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., the closely held,
family-owned company has finally let someone from outside its ranks
run the 149-year-old jeans manufacturer. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-AIR (San Francisco) _ With the integration of Reno Air and
its 25 aircraft just now kicking in, American Airlines is expanding
its north-south service on the West Coast in the hopes of selling
more lucrative west-east tickets. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EMBALMING (Mechanicville, N.Y.) _ Col. Elmer E. Ellsworth _ the
first Union officer killed in the Civil War _ will go down in
history as the first American ever to be embalmed. By DENNIS YUSKO.
</P>
<P>
   LEG-PAIN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Some 8 million Americans have
peripheral vascular disease, or PVD, which is characterized by
intense pain in the legs and calves. Many people confuse the
symptoms with arthritis, muscle spasms or being out of shape. But
PVD is potentially more dangerous than many of the aches and pains
that people associate with aging. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-UPN (Undated) _ Dean Valentine is upbeat. He's confident.
He's spewing numbers. A lot of other people may be thinking ``Dead
Man Walking,'' but Valentine is having no part of it. So much for
the theory that UPN, the network where he's president and CEO, is
about to disappear in the Viacom-CBS merger. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The topic was ``Has the Bay Area
lost its edge?'' as Michael Krasny put it. His KQED radio talk show
was about whether artists and bohemians can survive here anymore.
Short answer: No. Longer answer: Only if they issue stock in a hot
new Internet start-up called sfboho.com. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I went to the Giants-Phillies
game just to watch a few innings and to say goodbye to baseball at
Candlestick Park. Although most of them were cold, I'd spent many a
night and day in the ugly concrete stadium. I had some memories,
felt a wisp of sadness that, next season, pretty little Pac Bell
Park in downtown San Francisco would make baseball fans forget
Candlestick on even its best days. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   HUEY-LONG (Danville, Calif.) _ Sept. 8 was the 64th anniversary
of the assassination of Huey P. Long, the ``Kingfish'' who ruled
Louisiana, hoped to be president and remains one of the most
compelling and controversial politicians this country has ever
known. By CYNTHIA BASS
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIAL-HUMBUG (Santa Maria, Calif.) _ The uproar over the
millennium is a gigantic crock, unworthy of serious discussion.
There will be an avalanche of millennium T-shirts, caps, movies,
bumper stickers, songs, television specials and anything else that
can turn a fast buck. The millennium is manufactured news, a
non-story about a concocted event that isn't going to change
anything. By DONALD G. SMITH.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIAL-DATE (San Ramon, Calif.) _ OK, I get the point.
Despite the big hoopla over the next New Year's Eve, I am now fully
aware that the new millennium doesn't actually begin until 2001.
The purists who insist on the 2001 date don't care that the rest of
the world is caught up in millennium fever, or that we are excited
because we will soon get to write a 2 instead of a 1. They don't
care that we want to party. By EILEEN MITCHELL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4344 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA09-COX     09-08 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA: Donations from Ohio ease life on South Dakota
reservation
 &HT;    (With photos, locator map.)
 &HT;    By Cathy Mong
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEYENNE RIVER RESERVATION, S.D. _ Dianna Longbrake was admiring
a pair of Reeboks that fit her almost perfectly and looked like
new. ``We were up at 6 a.m. waiting for this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The jogging shoes were just one of the finds Longbrake was
celebrating this week among miles of rolling prairie at the home of
Delores Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first day of the Miami Valley (Ohio) Council for
Native Americans clothing distribution, compliments of generous
Ohioans.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the man who brought the donations from suburban
Ohio to the South Dakota reservation involves many spiritual as
well as physical journeys. Guy Jones, the Dayton-area council's
director and a native of the reservation, led the caravan of trucks
and cars that arrived Sunday with hundreds of bags of clothing and
school supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Although residents here are among the poorest in the country, it
is an area rich in pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do is put it all on the ground,'' Jones said.
``Everything has to touch the ground first. Once it touches the
ground, we no longer own it. Being that it doesn't belong to
anyone, it isn't charity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need these things,'' said Longbrake, a teacher's
aide at Takini School, which serves children from Bridger, Red
Scaffold and Cherry Creek, S.D. ``This is how we stay afloat.''
Takini, translated, means ``survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the clothing she will choose from among the piles will
outfit her three sons for the entire school year.
</P>
<P>
   Longbrake said that while making ends meet is a challenge, it is
the life she and her husband have chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're out of something, you just do without,'' she said.
``You pay bills and whatever is left is what you have. McDonald's
is a treat,'' and it's a two-hour trip to the nearest one, in
Pierre.
</P>
<P>
   She said her family is not ``into the hassle, the fast pace'' of
mainstream America, ``but there are things we take for granted,
like the river, the clean air.''
</P>
<P>
   Survival can be difficult, but Celastis Belt said she and her
husband wouldn't live anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I'm born and this is where I'm raised,'' she
said. Even so, the 58-year-old admitted it would be nice to be able
to buy enough propane for heating and to pay her electric bill.
</P>
<P>
   She said her focus is more on fulfilling her spiritual rather
than materialistic needs. ``The Bible says, `Ask in my name and you
shall receive it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Belt said the southern portion of the reservation is neglected
by the U.S. Bureau of Indian Affairs. That is due in part to its
sparse and widely dispersed population. There are fewer than 8,000
people on the 3,500-square-mile reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's distribution was very small in comparison with those
coming up in Eagle Butte and McLaughlin. That doesn't matter to
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched as a boy tried on a coat,'' Jones said. ``As long as
one person found something he needed, that's what we're doing this
for.''
</P>
<P>
   'They want to be Indian'
</P>
<P>
   This is the seventh year the caravan, led by Jones, a
43-year-old Lakota Indian, has set up distribution sites to some of
the nation's most isolated and neediest people.
</P>
<P>
   On Pine Ridge Reservation, about 90 miles south of the Cheyenne
River Reservation in the Badlands, per capita income is about
$3,100; it averages $4,478 on all other reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it is the Ohioans who feel the benefit of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people teach us what it is to give,'' said Arlene
Mendenhall, 60, a five-year volunteer with the council. ``It is a
very humbling experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakota, more commonly known as Sioux, are deeply connected
to their land. It is one of the reasons the Ohioans return year
after year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have nothing,'' Mendenhall said. ``Coming from our
culture, you just can't understand why they stay. Then you get to
know them, and you get to know they want to hold on to what they
have. They want to be Indian.''
</P>
<P>
   Delores Buffalo hosted the weary Ohio travelers at her home in a
valley alongside the Cheyenne River in Bridger.
</P>
<P>
   They pitched tents and lived among the 30 or so families there.
Buffalo's daughter, Mary, helped with the cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Buffalo, 38, lives in Philip, about 40 miles south of
Bridger. The 1,000 or so people in town sometimes get on her
nerves, so she and 2 1/2-year-old daughter Amanda climb in their
1978 Ford LTD and pay a visit. ``There, at my mother's house, you
can hear the coyotes at night. You can hear the owls.''
</P>
<P>
   The truckloads of donations make the difference for people
living in such sparsely populated places as Little Eagle, Promise,
and Messiah, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   People like Mary Buffalo, who used the donations to clothe
Amanda all year and only recently had to buy additional shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I receive my SSI check for $500 on the 1st of the month, and
by the 2nd, we're maybe setting with $40 in the bank,'' Mary
Buffalo said.
</P>
<P>
   That's after paying $125 for her two-bedroom apartment, which is
government subsidized, and other monthly bills. Food stamps cover
the groceries, but shopping in Philip is more expensive than
driving 86 miles to Sioux Falls.
</P>
<P>
   But Mary Buffalo isn't complaining. ``My mother and father
taught us to appreciate what we have. I lived by that,'' she said.
``If you don't have the money for it, let it go. Someday, if you
are to have it, you will get it. Don't wish for more than you
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Buffalo's moving to Philip placed her among people who did
not necessarily like having her there, despite the town's proximity
to reservations. ``I have faced discrimination but I've fought my
way up to where I feel like an equal. These people know me for my
anger,'' she said. ``I don't back down. I am comfortable with who I
am, a full-blooded Sioux Native American woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Changing attitudes Guy Jones, who leads these treks from Ohio
back home to the reservation every year, has logged a leap or two
on his own personal journey, shedding anger, fear, shame and guilt,
which he calls the stepping stones of prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like people,'' Jones said. ``I wouldn't have been
talking to you 20 years ago. The reason I hated (whites) was
because I was shameful of who I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is married to a black woman, Angela Jones, a caseworker at
an addiction center and a Jefferson Twp. , Ohio, trustee. They have
one son, Dakota, 10.
</P>
<P>
   Jones left the reservation after graduating high school in 1974;
at school, he had been one of only a few non-white students. He had
attended Indian schools in early grades but made the decision to
enroll in the public school in order to survive.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating he took odd jobs in 37 states, changing light
bulbs in a Texas stadium, driving cattle in Oklahoma. ``I felt the
need to experience the world,'' he said. ``I saw the good side of
America, I saw the bad side of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones made friends with all peoples, he said. ``I was on my way
East, on a bus, and I had a two-hour layover in Dayton. I met a man
and it was the first time a white person was civil to me,'' Jones
said. It was 1981. ``I thought, if there's one, there's gotta be
another.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was in Dayton that he learned of contributions that
his culture made to civilization. ``I thought, this is a good area
to do something. I can change some stereotypes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones will resign Sept. 30 as executive director of the
organization he founded, but he has no intention of walking away
from the group or its focus on education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to expand what is going on,'' Jones said. ``I want the
next generation to be able to sustain itself and be a part of the
economic growth so many see in this country. Maybe by taking
computers, by taking books to the reservation, we will open the
mind of a child. If you open a child's mind, then someday, maybe, I
won't have to make this trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Mong writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
