A4347 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-GENETIC-SEEDS09-COX     09-08 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENETIC-SEEDS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Terminator gene protects seed company's investment
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, FLA. _ Gene-altered crops represent a giant new
market for seed companies, but they also pose a vexing business
problem.
</P>
<P>
   How is a company to protect its investment when seeds grow into
plants that produce more seeds?
</P>
<P>
   Today, farmers who buy commercial seeds altered to resist pests,
herbicides or viruses must sign papers agreeing not to collect and
save seeds for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Seed companies aggressively remind farmers that it's illegal to
save gene-altered seeds, which are patented.
</P>
<P>
   But a more foolproof method is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   A Mississippi seed company and the U.S. Department of
Agriculture are jointly developing technology for what is referred
to in the industry as the ``terminator gene.''
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, it sterilizes seeds, ensuring that farmers will come
knocking for more seed each planting season.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rissler, senior staff scientist for the Union of Concerned
Scientists, calls the technology ``an elegant little piece of
genetic engineering'' that allows a seed to develop normally, while
killing the embryo that would germinate and grow into a plant.
</P>
<P>
   This new genetic technology _ officially called the Technology
Protection System _ is not expected to be ready for commercial use
until 2005.
</P>
<P>
   But Rissler and others worry that it will put control of the
seed market in the hands of a few large companies.
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto Co., a pioneer in the gene-altered seed business, is
buying Delta and Pine Land Co., which holds the patent on the
terminator technology with the USDA.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists warn that the trait for seed sterility might travel,
via pollen, making the seeds of neighboring plants sterile.
</P>
<P>
   Some farmers just don't like the idea.
</P>
<P>
   As Kevin O'Dare, an organic farmer in Vero Beach, puts it: ``Man
and seeds go back a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Waresh writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
