<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4352 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-AIRLINE-ANNIVERSARY09     09-08 1473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-ANNIVERSARY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fliers paying price for lower fares
 &HT;    By Tom Blackburn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Have a good flight?
</P>
<P>
   This summer, it was better not to ask.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers were nasty. The flight attendants were surly. The
gate agents were brusque. And the bad news was, your flight was
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   So what did you expect to get for low fares? A stateroom and a
valet?
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years into the era of airline deregulation _ the United
States will observe the anniversary but not celebrate it on Oct. 24
_ the flying public is in the clutches of Procrustes and Hobson.
</P>
<P>
   Procrustes was a mythical Greek who seized passersby and either
stretched their bodies or trimmed their legs to fit them into his
bed. Hobson was a real British livery-stable owner who made his
customers take the horse nearest the door, regardless of which one
they wanted to rent.
</P>
<P>
   Seat size differs slightly from airline to airline and by type
of plane, but Procrustes works for all of them. Seats are less than
17 inches wide and 31 to 34 inches apart. They don't recline as far
as they used to. If they did, you'd be looking up the nostrils of
the passenger behind you. And he would spill coffee on you as he
tried to get it to his lips without moving elbows locked to his
ribs by his seatmates.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're thinking of using the restroom, forget it. Flight
attendants block the aisle with the drink cart while they pass out
trail mix. The restroom probably is occupied anyway. The coach
cabin on the new Boeing 737-800 has two toilets for 140 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   An obstructive cart set off Patricia Lemerise of Miami on Aug.
5. She got into a shouting match with flight attendants, so police
in Boston met her at the gate and carted her off to jail for five
hours. American Airlines banned her for life. ``The customer is
always right'' is inoperative.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hobson decides whether, when and what you eat on a flight.
Canny passengers bring their own provisions and leave behind sticky
or suspicious-looking substances that there isn't time to clean up
when planes have to be turned around quickly for their next leg.
</P>
<P>
   Procrustean seats and hunger are only the middle stage of a
journey that starts with standing in lines and ends with a 1-in-200
chance that the luggage is lost or damaged. Business travelers may
fly 200 times in a year or two, making it even money that sometime
they will be in Detroit while their clothes fly on to Denver. Mr.
Hobson also picks out your airline for you. It's Delta 90 percent
of the time if you fly from Cincinnati, U.S. Airways 87 percent of
the time from Pittsburgh and Northwest 82 percent of the time from
Minneapolis-St. Paul. Those are their hubs, and they defend them
from interlopers. If you don't like it, drive.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists long ago showed that hostile behavior arises when
rats are frustrated and crowded. Even laboratory rats eat something
better than trail mix.
</P>
<P>
   If people were of uniform size and behaved as ducks do in a
shooting gallery, loading 150 or 200 of them aboard an airplane
would be easy. But they aren't. They have needs and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The passenger blocking the aisle while pushing a 200-pound bag
that clearly won't fit into the overhead rack once attended a
business meeting in yesterday's underwear because his checked bag
was lost. The mother pushing the two-seat stroller that won't fit
anywhere needs to get two small children from Gate C29 to Gate A27
in 30 minutes for the connecting flight if her plane is on time.
Which it may not be.
</P>
<P>
   More than three flights in 10 arrived late in June. One day in
May, in one airport (Newark), Continental burned off 31,000
passenger hours with takeoff delays. In this long summer of
waiting, the Federal Aviation Administration has been updating its
flight radar, with predictable glitches. The airlines would like to
blame the FAA for everything. But Europe's airlines and airports
have been experiencing the same delays, an ocean away from the FAA
radar.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's balky radar or stormy weather, the hub-and-spoke
system magnifies delays. There may be clear skies between South
Florida and Dallas-Fort Worth. But if Mr. Hobson decides the only
way to get there is by changing in Atlanta to a flight that
originates in Chicago, you need to be concerned about Chicago's
weather. That's the case whether you hope to fly in that plane or
are on another flight waiting for inbound passengers from Chicago
to transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Many people have anxieties about travel in general or flying in
particular, and when the nicotine-addicted fliers lost their
pacifiers on smoke-free planes and airports, it added to tensions
that would exist under the best conditions. Air travel these days
doesn't offer the best conditions, which would be a stateroom and a
valet.
</P>
<P>
   Deliver us from the wrath of cranky and rerouted passengers,
cried flight attendants last year. Their prayer was heard. Now the
airlines allow their personnel to cop an attitude before the
passengers start. In Philadelphia, gate agents practically dare
anyone to try to board before they call his row number.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the airlines boarded 641 million passengers, most of
them repeaters, of course. But eight in 10 American adults have
flown, up from 65 percent in 1979, when the federal government
stopped telling airlines where they must fly and what they could
charge. Passenger miles more than doubled. More significantly,
planes flew 62.97 percent full in 1979 but at 70.86 percent of
capacity last year.
</P>
<P>
   That means the middle seat in the row is more likely to be
occupied. In surveys, passengers tend to be happier with their
flight when that seat is empty. The first 1,000-passenger airplane
is on the drawing boards (at Airbus). No word yet on how all those
passengers will be assembled and herded in and around the nation's
airports, or where they will be stacked when flights are delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Airports have opened more shops and restaurants to help trapped
travelers while away the hours. But none of that gets them from
here to there. Airlines still advertise the mystique of flying, but
they are common carriers with vulgar customers and the amenities of
a Bolivian intra-city bus.
</P>
<P>
   That's what passengers get, however, for a decision that usually
starts with low fares. If you call an airline or travel agent, what
do you mention? The lowest available fare. What do company travel
offices look for? The lowest available fare. Several Internet sites
promise they'll have the lowest available fare; no site specializes
in seeking the best food or the widest seats. Competition in the
industry means: the lowest available fare.
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation does keep fares low _ if you live in the right
places and fly to the right destinations. A landmark study found
that fares in constant dollars are lower today than after President
Carter signed the deregulation law for 21 of 25 routes over 800
miles and 14 of 15 routes over 1,100 miles. But in 16 of 25
markets, fares actually have increased for flights under 700 miles.
Low fares are common from New York to Palm Beach International
Airport. Trips with less demand _ say, West Palm Beach to
Tallahassee _ often cost more than flights of twice the distance.
It's the difference between bus service and cab fare.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines lost money holding down fares after deregulation.
That's not common knowledge. But lately, investment advisers, in
the course of advising on computer stocks, have nervously pointed
out that running airlines, and railroads before them, hasn't been
very profitable. As with computer stocks, profits were made
building, selling or merging. Profitable hospitality and shipping
businesses have been created around airlines, but making money by
flying passengers proved difficult.
</P>
<P>
   By 1994, the major airlines that make up the Air Transport
Association had lost a cumulative $4.867 billion since 1947. They
became profitable again in 1995. To get profits, they cut down on
space, on meals, on personnel and even cut down on air. Yes, they
reduced air circulation by half on their planes in the mid-1980s,
increasing vagrant germs while banning sidestream smoke. They
learned to match smaller planes with less-traveled routes and run
them through hubs instead of offering direct flights. That makes
passengers do part of their trip by foot from concourse to
concourse.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines that are making money aren't about to change any of
that. If cheap is the goal, Procrustes &AMP; Hobson set the standards
of hospitality. The airlines can afford to wait until everyone gets
tired of hearing everyone else talk about how miserable their
flight was.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Blackburn writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
