r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS09-TAKE     09-08 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS09-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of 2 takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is the emergency number 911 used nationwide?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. It's the system to reach Emergency Medical Services in
nearly half the United States, but the telephone number can vary
from community to community, according to a spokesman at the
Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The winner of the $116 million Big Game jackpot Aug. 3
actually got $60 million because he chose Cash Option. What
happened to the other $56 million?
</P>
<P>
   A: The advertised jackpot for Big Game is its estimated
annuitized value over 26 years, or the total cumulative amount a
winner would receive if he or she took the prize in annual payments
over that period. When Big Game jackpots are paid out over 26
years, the first annual payment is cash. For the remaining 25
years, the lottery buys U.S. government treasury securities, which
earn interest and mature annually. That annual return is the amount
winners receive each year.
</P>
<P>
   If Thomas ``Randy'' Kerfoot of Chattanooga, Tenn., the Big Game
winner Aug. 3, had elected to have his prize money spread over 26
years, it would have totaled $116 million. But he chose to have the
prize paid immediately, so he got $60 million (actually reduced to
$40 million after taxes).
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent editorial column reported on a judge who overturned
rules of the Federal Communications Commission regarding privacy of
telephone records. What is the name of the judge, and what is the
address?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was a three-judge panel of the 10th Circuit Court of
Appeals in Denver. The two who voted to overturn the FCC rules are
Judge Deanell Reese Tacha and Judge David M. Ebel. Judge Mary Beck
Briscoe was the dissenter. You can write to any of them at this
address: U.S. Court of Appeals for the 10th Circuit, Byron White
U.S. Courthouse, 1823 Stout St., Denver, CO 80257.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The hoarding of pennies and subsequent shortage in some
places have been widely reported . Apparently some merchants are
having problems. Since lots of people consider pennies a nuisance
anyway, has any consideration been given to simply removing them
from circulation?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although this issue comes up occasionally, the Treasury
Department says it has no plans to stop production of pennies. Even
if it wanted to do so, such a change in the nation's monetary
system would require congressional authorization.
</P>
<P>
   In its defense of keeping the 1-cent piece, the U.S. Mint cites
a 1976 study of possible consequences if their production were to
be halted and the coins removed from circulation. Problems, the
study concluded, would be a potential inflationary impact and
possible difficulties collecting sales taxes. A majority of state
revenue collection departments, retail companies and commercial
banks strongly objected to the idea of eliminating the penny.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of Ann Stock, at one time the Clinton White
House social secretary? I haven't seen her name in the news lately.
</P>
<P>
   A: Stock left her White House position in 1997 after 4 1/2 years
to become vice president of institutional affairs at the Kennedy
Center in Washington. She was replaced by Capricia Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Stock's latest project, outside of her Kennedy Center duties,
dovetails nicely with her background at the White House, which
included overseeing some 2,000 social events, ranging from intimate
teas to South Lawn picnics to state dinners. She and Walter Scheib,
whose experience includes being executive chef at the White House,
have compiled a cookbook, which isn't yet out. Royalties from the
book will benefit a nonprofit organization in the same way Hillary
Clinton's book, ``It Takes a Village,'' did, she told The
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The book is said to include recipes and party-planning tips
focusing on what Stock described as the Clinton White House's
``fresh, uniquely American style of food and entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the baseball standings in the sports pages, Atlanta was
listed as being 3 1/2 games ahead of New York. Where does the half
game come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: Half-game differences in standings occur when teams have
played an uneven number of games. For instance, if the Braves were
84 and 50 (a total of 134), and the Mets were 80 and 53 (a total of
133), the Braves would have a 3 1/2-game lead. For each game won or
lost, a team either gains or slips a half game.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any danger in using a cell phone while filling your
gas tank? I recently overhead a station attendant telling someone
not to talk on his phone.
</P>
<P>
   A: Fires at gas stations ignited by sparks from cell phones have
been reported, but they appear to be nothing more than the latest
urban myth. No such fires have been substantiated, said Shawn
Steward of BellSouth Cellular Corp. ``There's no way it would be
possible for a cell phone to create sparks that would ignite
gasoline vapors,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some gas station chains apparently plan to put a
warning label on some of their pumps ``basically to cover
themselves in case something could happen,'' Steward said.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Chronicle reported recently that some Canadian
newspapers had reported an incident in a tiny mining community in
British Columbia. According to the story, a man was torched when a
spark from his phone ignited gas fumes while he was filling up. In
the typical manner of urban myths, reports quickly surfaced about
similiar incidents in Indonesia, Finland and Australia. But all
appear to be hoaxes.
</P>
<P>
   David McKinney, spokesman for the Shell/Texaco marketing
consortium Equilon Enterprises, told the Chronicle that his company
will not post warnings to cell phone users. ``We have no reason to
believe it's a safety issue,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When the American flag is flown with the flag of another
country, on what side of the Stars and Stripes does the other flag
go?
</P>
<P>
   A: When the viewer is facing the flags, the U.S. flag should be
on the left.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the strongest earthquake recorded since the beginning
of the use of the Richter scale?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sources disagree. According to The Weather Almanac, the
largest earthquakes of record were rated at magnitude 8.9. But the
almanac observes that magnitude determinations may vary with the
observatory, equipment and methods of estimating. For example, the
Alaska quake of March 27, 1964, was described variously as 8.4, 8.5
and 8.6 by different stations.
</P>
<P>
   World Almanac 1999, meanwhile, lists a magnitude 9.2 for the
1964 Alaska quake, and 9.5 for a series of quakes in Chile in May
1960 . World Almanac also lists these other major earthquakes:
April 1905, Kangra, India, 8.6; August 1906, Valparaiso, Chile,
8.6; December 1920, Gansu, China, 8.6; March 1933, Japan (site not
specified), 8.9; and August 1950, Assam India, 8.7. The magnitude
numbering system named for American seismologist Charles Richter
wasn't developed until 1935, so earthquakes before that are
estimations based on intensity data.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Articles on the 1993 Branch Davidian incident near Waco,
Texas, said 80 members of the sect, including leader David Koresh
and 20 children, died in the fire that consumed the compound. Isn't
it true that some of the people died from gunshots?
</P>
<P>
   A: Apparently three people, all children, died from gunshots.
But there may never be clear answers about the exact number because
so much of the evidence was destroyed in the April 19, 1993, fire.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the fire, a Justice Department official, Carl
Stern, said three bodies had gunshot wounds, raising speculation
that the cult members had shot themselves or were shot by other
cultists. Then a report issued in October 1993 by the Justice
Department confirmed the same figure, saying three children had
been shot fatally in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Straw polls or straw votes are in the news lately. Can you
explain the meaning?
</P>
<P>
   A: A straw vote is an opinion poll, an unofficial vote taken to
ascertain the relative strength of political candidates or the
general trend of opinion on a given issue. The book ``Picturesque
Expressions: A Thematic Dictionary'' explains the ``straw'' part of
the term by saying that in the 19th and early 20th centuries in the
United States, informal polls were taken by handing out a piece of
straw to each of the voters, who would break the straw to signify a
``nay'' vote, or leave it intact to signify approval.
</P>
<P>
   A somewhat cynical evaluation of the validity of a straw vote
was offered by O. Henry in 1913: ``A straw vote only shows which
way the hot air blows.'' A straw vote can have consequences,
however. In the nonbinding Aug. 14 Republican straw vote in Iowa,
former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander's poor showing prompted him
to drop out of the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   End take 2
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
