<HEADER>
A4358 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS09-TAKE     09-08 1843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS09-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take one of two takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him: q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: The September issue of GQ magazine mentions former presidents
and their football careers. It states that Jimmy Carter was a
college football player. I know he attended Georgia Tech and the
Naval Academy, but I didn't know he played football. What can you
tell me?
</P>
<P>
   A: Carter attended Georgia Southwestern College and Georgia Tech
and graduated from the Naval Academy in 1946. It was at the academy
where his ``short-lived football career'' occurred, said Carrie
Harmon, spokeswoman at the Carter Presidential Center. He was on
the ``under-140-pound team,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about the eye surgery Atlanta
Braves pitcher Greg Maddux had?
</P>
<P>
   A: Maddux, who was nearsighted, underwent laser eye surgery on
July 9 at Emory Vision Correction Center. It enabled him to shed
both the glasses he often wore off the field, and the contacts he
wore while pitching. He was back on the mound less than 48 hours
after the surgery, pitching against the Boston Red Sox in a game he
won, allowing one run in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux said he had the procedure done for personal reasons, not
in hopes that it would improve his pitching, but in fact he said
he's now more comfortable on the mound. He added that until the
surgery, he pitched in contacts because they gave him better
peripheral vision than glasses. But he said the contacts were
constantly irritating his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is George W. Bush, the frontrunner for the Republican
presidential nomination, George W. Bush Jr.? If he doesn't use the
Jr., is it intended to confuse older voters into thinking he is
George Bush Sr.?
</P>
<P>
   A: He isn't a junior, so there's no ulterior motive. His full
name is George Walker Bush. His father's full name is George
Herbert Walker Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An item about Sen. Strom Thurmond's recent release from a
hospital said he was accompanied by his wife, Nancy. I thought they
were divorced. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: They're separated, not divorced, but remain on ``friendly
terms,'' said John DeCrosta, Thurmond's spokesman. At last report
the senator lived in Washington and Nancy Thurmond lived in Aiken,
S.C. Thurmond (R-S.C.) married his first wife, Jean Crouch, in
1947. She died of a brain tumor in 1960. He married Nancy Moore, a
former Miss South Carolina, in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond, 96, who had successful surgery for an enlarged
prostate, was released Aug. 30 from Walter Reed Army Medical Center
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The newspaper recently listed three singers who will be
inducted into the Country Music Hall of Fame this month. Can you do
a favor for country music fans and list all the members?
</P>
<P>
   A: Glad to. The first Hall of Famers _ Jimmie Rodgers, Fred Rose
and Hank Williams _ were elected in 1961. Here are the others, by
decade:
</P>
<P>
   1960s: '62, Roy Acuff; (none in '63); '64, Tex Ritter; '65,
Ernest Tubb; '66, Eddy Arnold, James R. Denny, George D. Hay and
Uncle Dave Macon; '67, Red Foley, J.L. Frank, Jim Reeves and
Stephen H. Sholes; '68, Bob Wills; '69, Gene Autry.
</P>
<P>
   1970s: '70, Bill Monroe, and the Original Carter Family; '71,
Arthur Edward Satherley; '72, Jimmie H. Davis; '73, Chet Atkins and
Patsy Cline; '74, Owen Bradley and Frank ``Pee Wee'' King; '75,
Minnie Pearl; '76, Kitty Wells and Paul Cohen; '77, Merle Travis;
'78, Grandpa Jones; '79, Hubert Long and Hank Snow.
</P>
<P>
   1980s: '80, Connie B. Gay, Original Sons of the Pioneers, and
Johnny Cash; '81, Vernon Dalhart and Grant Turner; '82, Lefty
Frizzell, Marty Robbins and Roy Horton; '83, Little Jimmy Dickens;
'84, Ralph S. Peer and Floyd Tillman; '85, Lester Flatt &AMP; Earl
Scruggs; '86, Wesley H. Rose and Whitey Ford; '87, Rod Brasfield;
'88, Roy Rogers and Loretta Lynn; '89, Cliffie Stone, Hank Thompson
and Jack Stapp.
</P>
<P>
   1990s: '90, Tennessee Ernie Ford; '91, Felice and Boudleaux
Bryant; '92, George Jones and Frances William Preston; '93, Willie
Nelson; '94, Merle Haggard; '95, Jo Walker-Meador and Roger Miller;
'96, Patsy Montana, Buck Owens and Ray Price; '97, Harlan Howard,
Brenda Lee and Cindy Walker; '98, George Morgan, Elvis Presley,
E.W. ``Bud'' Wendell and Tammy Wynette.
</P>
<P>
   The three for this year, to be inducted Sept. 22 during the
telecast of ``The 33rd Annual CMA Awards'' of the Country Music
Association, are Dolly Parton, Conway Twitty and Johnny Bond.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The shutdown of the Russian space station Mir made me wonder:
Whatever happened to Buran, the Soviet version of America's space
shuttle?
</P>
<P>
   A: At last report the VKK, or Vozdushno Kosmicheskiy Korabl, was
being used as a tourist attraction in Moscow's Gorky Park. It was
opened as a flight simulator there in 1996, with ``passengers''
paying $35 for a 40-minute simulated flight complete with space
food. Buran (meaning Siberian snowstorm) actually was the name of
the maiden orbiter, but was transplanted to the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The crewless craft, which used an expendable booster instead of
main engines, was launched into space for the first, and last, time
Nov. 15, 1988. Controlled by autopilot, it made two orbits before
landing at the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan. Beginning in
1989, shortages of funds caused long delays in further development
of the Buran program, and in 1993 work on the program ended.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read that movie ratings have been changed several times
over the years. When did they start, and what have they been?
</P>
<P>
   A: The voluntary rating system replacing the old Hays Production
Code was introduced on Nov. 1, 1968. It called for four rating
categories: G (general audiences, all ages admitted); M (mature
audiences, all ages admitted, but parental guidance suggested); R
(restricted, with children younger than 16 not admitted without an
accompanying parent or adult guardian, later raised to children
younger than 17, but varying in some jurisdictions); and X (no one
younger than 17 admitted).
</P>
<P>
   The Motion Picture Association of America said it discovered
early on that most parents regarded M as sterner than R, so to
remedy the misconception, M was changed to GP (meaning general
audiences, parental guidance suggested). That was subsequently
changed to PG: parental guidance suggested.
</P>
<P>
   More adustments followed. In 1984, PG was split into PG and
PG-13, with the latter indicating films with a higher level of
intensity than PG. In 1990, a further revision was adopted to
provide explanations of why a film was rated R, and after that
explanations were added in the PG and PG-13 categories. When the X
category was changed that same year to NC-17 (no children 17 or
younger), it also was accompanied by an explanation. The ratings
are still G, PG, PG-13, R and NC-17.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were the religious affiliations of our early presidents?
</P>
<P>
   A: Let's take the first 10: George Washington, Episcopalian;
John Adams, Unitarian; Thomas Jefferson, no specific denomination;
James Madison and James Monroe, both Episcopalian; John Quincy
Adams, Unitarian; Andrew Jackson, Presbyterian; Martin Van Buren,
Dutch Reformed; and William Henry Harrison and John Tyler, both
Episcopalian.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How long is protection afforded past presidents and their
wives or widows? May they refuse this protection if they choose to,
especially a widow?
</P>
<P>
   A: Secret Service protection is provided for the life of an
ex-president, as well as for a widow. While either a former
president or a widow certainly could refuse it, the only one who
actually has done so is Richard Nixon, said Pete Sepp of the
National Taxpayers Union. He added that in 1998, President Ford
lobbied to stop a move in Congress to limit the period of Secret
Service protection and some of the retirement perks available to
former presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I occasionally see references in the news to a ``land-grant
university.'' Exactly what is that?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a school endowed under the Morrill (or Land-Grant) Act
of 1862, which was sponsored by Rep. Justin Morrill (R-Vt.). Under
the act, Congress granted every state 30,000 acres of land for each
senator and representative it had in Congress. The land was to be
sold, the proceeds invested, and the income used to create and
maintain a college for agriculture and the mechanical arts.
</P>
<P>
   The act came about because in the mid-1800s people had clamored
for colleges to teach the finer points of farming and
manufacturing. When it was passed, the act added military science
and tactics to the proposed farming and manufacturing curriculum.
Altogether, the states and territories received 11.3 million acres
of land. Congress added money to its gifts through the Second
Morrill Act of 1890 and an amendment in 1907.
</P>
<P>
   While not all states used the land-grant money as planned by the
act, with some giving money to state universities to finance new
agricultural and mechanical departments and a few giving the money
to private colleges, the education value of the land-grant program
is considered invaluable. Today, all states and Puerto Rico receive
federal grants to help support land-grant universities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that the woman in Antarctica who discovered a
lump in her breast, necessitating an emergency drop of medical
supplies, is the only doctor there. During my last tour of duty in
Antarctica in 1972, there was a doctor at Pole Station and at
McMurdo. Does McMurdo no longer have a doctor in the
``winter-over''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both McMurdo and South Pole stations still have physicians,
said Peter West of the National Science Foundation. But there are
several practical reasons why one doctor can't assist the other.
First, the two stations are roughly 800 miles apart. Land travel
between them is impossible because no roads exist, and the stations
are separated by the transantarctic mountain range. Second,
aircraft operations aren't conducted during the austral, or
southern, winter because of the extreme cold and the effects of the
temperatures on hydraulic and other critical systems. Third,
there's total darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Because of concerns about the weather conditions, and because
air traffic control and accompanying electronic aids to aircraft
navigation are extremely limited, no landing of an aircraft has
ever been attempted at the Pole during the austral winter in the
history of the U.S. program. The recent drop of supplies was
accomplished by an aircraft flying from Christchurch, New Zealand.
It was accompanied by a tanker for mid-air refueling.
</P>
<P>
   The National Science Foundation, by the way, operates the U.S.
Antarctic Program with logistical assistance from the Air Force,
the Air National Guard, and Antarctic Support Associates, a private
contractor in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   (END TAKE 1 OF TWO TAKES. MORE.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
