<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAUSAGE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LINKS TO THE PAST: Company continues a 5-generation family art
of making sausage
 &HT;    (EDS: Photos available.)
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ No matter that warm, summer-like days may linger
through September. Patio dining is passe for the rest of the year.
The appetite calendar has flipped from hamburgers on the grill to
sausage.
</P>
<P>
   It's a funny thing about Dayton, Ohio, with its mostly German
roots. The sausage-makers, along with the brewmeisters, have all
but vanished. But to the south, in Cincinnati, a city with a
similar heritage _ and a Porkopolis nickname _ the art of making
sausage is still revered.
</P>
<P>
   Doubt it? Visit Cincinnati's Findlay Market, 110 W. Elder St.
While many of the meat vendors there sell sausages they purchase,
Kroeger &AMP; Sons Meats dominate the sausage scene, turning out as
many as 60 varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Mike and Mark Kroeger are the fifth generation practicing the
art of charcuterie. They grew up with hands-on experience under the
tutelage of their immigrant father Paul, a master sausage-maker who
opened his shop in Findlay Market in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   When they were boys, they dropped their school books as soon as
they got home and headed to the garage, where their father had set
up a sausage kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd go home and help Dad. That was the way it always was,''
says Mike.
</P>
<P>
   The sausages they made then were traditional German varieties _
fresh metts (called bratwurst in much of the rest of the country),
smoked metts and their version of bratwurst _ the mild, finely
ground pork and veal sausage native to Northern Germany and
synonymous with Cincinnati. They made lunchmeats and even head
cheese, using all the odds and ends and trimmings. But it was a
secondary business, a way to use every scrap from the meat-cutting
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us it has changed,'' says Mike. Since they took over the
business in 1994, making sausage has become their primary industry,
with meat sales second. And they no longer use trimmings, instead
ordering special ingredients for their links.
</P>
<P>
   Mike, 33, and Mark, 28, stepped in when their father became too
ill to continue. They saw sausage-making as a special niche. But in
the early years of their stewardship, they amassed debt and needed
to establish a cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   That's when they developed their first specialty sausage, the
Vidalia Onion Sausage, a juicy selection with big chunks of onion
and Parmesan cheese in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was born out of necessity,'' Mike says.
</P>
<P>
   And it was a surefire winner.
</P>
<P>
   To this day it is the best-selling sausage in a lineup that also
includes two popular versions of andouille and a coarse
Chicago-style Italian sausage. Others include both fresh and smoked
kielbasa, smoked bierwurst and four kinds of venison sausage. The
brothers also make seasonal sausages such as bockwurst, weiswurst,
duck sausage and even a corned beef sausage made for St. Patrick's
Day. And in a nod to the fat-phobic consumers, they offer about a
dozen varieties made with chicken breast.
</P>
<P>
   All are made in old-world style, which means the brothers don't
use binders, colors, extenders or artificial preserves. No dried
milk or water is added. And, in a nod to new-world tastes, they
emphasize leanness.
</P>
<P>
   Not all their experiments have been successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest failure was a soy-based vegetarian sausage,'' Mike
says. The texture was so bad they didn't even try to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   But the specialty sausages put them in the black again, and they
went from making 200 to 300 pounds a week to 900, then to 1,300
pounds. They still run out on busy Saturdays and are in the market
for equipment to expand their capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Next up in their plans is getting licensed to sell wholesale.
When that happens, probably next spring, Kroeger sausages might be
available a little closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Kroeger and Sons Meats at (513) 651-5543.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
