A4363 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-FINDLAY-MARKET09     09-08 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FINDLAY-MARKET09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cincinnati landmark is making a comeback
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ In its heyday, Findlay Market was ``a happening
place,'' says Mike Kroeger, who still sells sausage in the market
house.
</P>
<P>
   The market in Cincinnati's Over The Rhine district dates to
1852. Despite a renovation of the market house 25 years ago, the
decline of the neighborhood took its toll. Vendors in the
deteriorating buildings around the market house closed. Quality
slipped to bare basics and suburbanites no longer made the trip
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Kroeger said, the city made a commitment and a revival
began. Buildings were acquired and restored. Long-term plans call
for temporarily moving market house vendors into the renovated
storefronts after the first of the year, then expanding the market
house to allow year-round produce stands. Farmers sell home-grown
produce on Saturdays in a new open-air market shed in the parking
lot. The renovation eventually will extend to the other side of the
market square.
</P>
<P>
   The change is being felt inside the market house, as well, where
the vendors who stayed are adding specialties. While vendors
selling traditional meats dominate the market, this also is the
place to find everything from Goetta to rabbits, breast of lamb to
Cajun bacon and, of course, a wide variety of sausage. At the
Krause meat stand, imported deli meats are the draw.
</P>
<P>
   Well-established merchants such as Silverglades offer imported
cheese at one end of the market house and a vast array of olives at
the other.
</P>
<P>
   The international cheese selection, cut to order, ranges from
French Gaperon and Vermont Goat's Milk Blue Cheese to English
Stiernmeister, Irish Smoked Blarney and Dutch Goat's Milk Gouda.
</P>
<P>
   The Elder Street storefronts still house a few vendors,
including the Heist Poultry shop, which dates to 1850, and
Mediterranean Imports, a spice-and-nut house that is a good place
to find pine nuts priced as low as $6.50 per pound for Chinese
imports and up to $17.99 for Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the market house, the buildings are mostly
boarded up, but the Saigon Market remains, and Mr. Pig's barbecue
draws a steady line of hungry shoppers. While the market has
limited hours, all the vendors are open 7 a.m. to 6 p.m. Wednesday
and 6 a.m. to 6 p.m. Friday and Saturday. It is most active _ and
crowded _ on Saturday when produce in the market shed is an added
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   FINDLAY MARKET is open 7 a.m. to 6 p.m. Wednesday and from 6
a.m. to 6 p.m. Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Directions: Take Interstate 75 to the Western Avenue/Liberty
Street exit; the first cross street at the bottom of the ramp is
Findlay Street. Turn left and go about 10 blocks. The entrance into
the parking lot is between Elm and Race streets. On Wednesday and
Friday there is usually parking available on the nearby streets.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
