<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-OF-WINE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TASTE OF WINE: A little bit of this and that
 &HT;    (EDS: Note italics and email address _ replace (at) with
ampersand.)
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Tips 'n' sips to tide us through the approaching
autumn:
</P>
<P>
   _ Dorothy J. Gaiter and John Brecher, who co-author a wine
column for The Wall Street Journal, have come up with an intriguing
idea. They've proclaimed Sept. 18 ``Open That Bottle Night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as though every person in America has one special
bottle, with special memories, hidden away somewhere, waiting for
that one perfect moment to open it,'' they write. But too often,
that moment never comes. And too many of those ``special'' wines
were never meant to be aged a long time anyway. They're not getting
any better. And (ITALIC) you (END ITALIC) aren't getting any
younger.
</P>
<P>
   Gaiter and Brecher's advice: ``Don't wait for a special occasion
to open the wine. Make the wine itself the special occasion.
Prepare a feast around the wine, open it and toast the terrific
person who gave you the bottle'' or the circumstances around which
you received it.
</P>
<P>
   That way, they reason, the wine just might be wonderful no
matter how it tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a darn fine idea to me. The Journal columnists
invited readers to share their stories of the wine and occasion. We
can do the same. Even if your ``Open That Bottle Night'' isn't
Sept. 18, let me know how it went by e-mailing me at
markfisher(at)coxohio.com or dropping me a line at Mark Fisher,
Dayton Daily News, 45 S. Ludlow St., Dayton Ohio 45402. We'll share
the best stories in a future column.
</P>
<P>
   _ From the ``Don't-delve-too-deeply-into-the-family-tree''
department:
</P>
<P>
   Chardonnay and other prestigious grape varieties that make some
of the noblest wines of France _ from such places as Champagne and
Burgundy _ originated from a peasant grape variety scorned by most
winemakers for centuries and once banned from France, according to
a genetic researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Meredith, a professor at the University of California,
Davis, told the Associated Press that her research concluded 16
premier wines of France were originally produced by the genetic
pairing of the classic Pinot variety with the obscure, humble
Gouais blanc grape, apparently a black sheep of sorts in the
viticultural circles.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers used classic DNA profiling techniques now widely
used to link parents and children, or to connect a suspect with
specimens from a crime scene. Meredith is the senior author of a
study that appeared Friday in the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   Wine experts were said to be ``surprised and amused'' that wines
held in such high regard, such as chardonnay and gamay noir, had
such humble origins, the AP said.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the heartland of America, we don't drink prestige,
right? We drink wine, no matter what side of the genetic tracks the
grapes were born on. Even, sometimes, chardonnay. With that in mind
. . .
</P>
<P>
   Wine of the week: Penfolds 1998 Koonunga Hill Semillon
Chardonnay, $7.99. This lip-smacking white wine from southeastern
Australia will make Indian summer easier to endure. It's a blend of
68 percent semillon and 32 percent chardonnay, fresh, fruity, not
overly oaked, with everything in the proper balance and a decent
price to boot. Why yes, you may freshen my glass.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
