<P>
   AIRLINE-ANNIVERSARY _ Have a good flight? This summer, it was
better not to ask. The passengers were nasty. The flight attendants
were surly. The gate agents were brusque. And the bad news was,
your flight was canceled. Twenty years into the era of airline
deregulation _ the United States will observe the anniversary but
not celebrate it on Oct. 24 _ the flying public is in the clutches
of Procrustes and Hobson. (Blackburn, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-CLEMENCY _ FALN clemency controversy ought to be a
lesson to the Clintons. As long as Hillary is politicking for U.S.
Senate seat, Clinton enemies will attach the darkest motives to any
action Bill takes with implications for New York, including the
possibility of clemency for Jonathan Pollard. Clinton should leave
such decisions to his successor. (Atlanta Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-TIMOR _ The violence in East Timor is no less a case
of ethnic cleansing than the earlier horrors of Bosnia and Kosovo.
U.S. caution on intervention is understandable, but we should be
putting far heavier pressure on Indonesia than we are now. If
Jakarta won't clamp down on thugs, then it should other countries
to do so. (Atlanta Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-CAMPAIGN _ The need for campaign-finance reform.
(Atlanta Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WALMART-COMMENT _ The coming of Wal-mart in England won't
destroy the villages and countryside because rules over there will
prevent the chain from destroying main streets of small towns.
England has much tighter control over development, slowing down
sprawl. (Page, Atlanta Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Everybody loves to give pregnant
women advice, wanted or not. Everybody loves to throw pregnant
women showers, willing or not. So I suppose it was inevitable that
somebody would find a way to combine the two. Recently, I attended
a baby shower at which advice-giving took the place of shower
games. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Throughout history, mice and
their hefty cousins have been outsmarting humans. Thus the
expression, ``What the world needs is a better mousetrap.'' A
Princeton University scientist has done the opposite. He has
invented a better mouse. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
