<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4405 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE09-COX     09-08 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    September dates let you try the unusual
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   September has finally arrived and with it some special dates
that may inspire you to even greater heights in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some, along with related Internet sites we hope will
spark your culinary imagination.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Today: In 1850, California was admitted to the Union, bringing
with it the beginnings of famed California cuisine. Interestingly,
one of the first recorded cookbooks to be published in California
was ``How to Keep a Husband or Culinary Tactics.'' You can find the
historic recipe for boiled orange pudding from this rare book at
marketreport
</P>
<P>
   .com/historical1.htm. For a wonderful snapshot of just what this
rich and varied cuisine of California is all about, see
www.windjammer.net/users/isg
</P>
<P>
   /coloma/sesquin.htm. Also see the California Cuisine Food
Pyramid at www.avoinfo.com
</P>
<P>
   /nutrition/nutr58.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Today also is the birthday of fast food giant Col. Harlan
Sanders. To pay homage to the man who changed America's
chicken-eating habits, you could go to KFC for a bucket or you
could try to crack his secret by trying the copycat recipe at
southernfood.about.com/library/ccrec
</P>
<P>
   /blcc34.htm?pid &QC; 2757&AMP;cob &QC; home.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 11-20: The Jewish High Holy days of Rosh Hashana and Yom
Kippur are celebrated. For the story and traditions associated with
these days, plus traditional recipes, see www.holidays
</P>
<P>
   .net/highholydays/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 13: Say Happy Birthday to Hershey founder Milton Hershey
by visiting the chocolate company's Web site and maybe coaxing
yourself into making a fabulous chocolate desert. See
members.aol.com/acalendar/September
</P>
<P>
   /Hershey.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 16: This is Mexican Independence Day. For the story of
Mexican Independence, see www.mexonline.com/person1.htm. And for
some mouthwatering south-of-the-border recipes, see Big Mama at
www.mexconnect.com
</P>
<P>
   /mex/sml/gwbigmamaindex.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 22: The birthday of the ice cream cone. Like many
Italian immigrants who came to America in the late 1800s, Italo
Marchiony operated a pushcart. His portable lemon ice business
became so successful that he soon had a fleet. On Sept. 22, 1903,
he applied for a patent for a cone-shaped mold that he made out of
paper to hold his tasty delicacy. One year later, at the St. Louis
World's Fair, Syrian pastry concessionaire Ernest Hamwi was making
a wafflelike, cone-shaped Persian pastry called ``zalabias'' when
he gave some to a nearby ice cream vendor who had run out of
dishes. The rest is history. For more on ice cream cones, see
www.fspronet.com/iccone.html. If you want to try your hand at the
original zalabia, see a recipe from a Middle Eastern cookbook at
www
</P>
<P>
   .eskimo.com/(tilde)jefffree/recipes/zalabia
</P>
<P>
   .htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 26: The birthday of John Chapman, aka American folk hero
Johnny Appleseed. Chapman was known to wear a cooking pot for a hat
as he preached throughout Indiana and Ohio in the early 19th
century and planted apple seeds for settlers who would follow. For
a lovely poem that evokes the spirit of September and Johnny
Appleseed, see www.zoomnet.net/(tilde)petecol/septemb.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 29: This is Michaelmas. Top off the month with a grand
feast that honors the Archangel Michael, the patron saint of
artists, grocers, knights, mariners, policemen, soldiers and the
sick. Celebrated since the sixth century, the feast's centerpiece
traditionally is goose. British legend has it that in 1588 Queen
Elizabeth I was dining on goose on this day when she learned of the
defeat of the Spanish Armada, after which she decreed that
``hereafter goose shall be eaten on this day.'' Tradition also
dictates that the bones be made into Michaelmas broth to be eaten
the next day. Angel food cake is a must for some Episcopalians.
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of dozen fabulous recipes for roast goose,
including sinful Roast Goose With Molasses Glaze and Apricot
Stuffing, see soar.berkeley.edu
</P>
<P>
   /recipes/meat/poultry/goose/.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Apple Roll-Ups
</P>
<P>
   Makes 5 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This easy dessert will help you celebrate Johnny Appleseed's
birthday and Mexican Independence Day, both this month.
</P>
<P>
   1 can (21-ounce) apple pie filling
</P>
<P>
   10 flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Spoon a scant 1/4 cup of the apple filling on each tortilla and
roll up. Place, fold down, in a 9-by-13-inch baking dish. In a
saucepan over medium heat, combine butter, sugar, cinnamon, nutmeg
and vanilla. Cook and stir until butter melts and sugar dissolves,
4 to 5 minutes. Pour mixture over roll-ups and set aside for about
2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Place roll-ups in oven and bake for
30 minutes. Cool 10 minutes. Serve warm with vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (2 roll-ups without ice cream): 690 calories, 5
grams protein, 23 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 30), 119
grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 505 milligrams sodium, 5 grams
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
