<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4406 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP09-COX     09-08 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pleat foil into a pan for these cookies
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tricia Caudell's request for the Accordion Cookies her
mother used to make was kindly answered by Joan D. Mattson of
Grayson, Ga., who sent a copy of the original that won Pillsbury's
top $25,000 prize in 1958. Gerda Roderer of Berkeley, Calif., won
the money and the honors with her family recipe four years after
moving to the United States from France.
</P>
<P>
   We tested the unusual cookies, which are baked in a ``pan'' made
of accordion-pleated aluminum foil, and found they lived up to
Caudell's memory: ``When they're cooked, they are crunchy on the
outside, soft on the inside ... similar in taste to madeleines.''
</P>
<P>
   The original directions suggest varying the flavoring used. We
tested with toasted hazelnuts and dipped one end of the cooled
cookie in a chocolate glaze.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Accordion
</P>
<P>
   Treats
</P>
<P>
   Makes 48
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25 minutes per sheet
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 10 minutes per sheet
</P>
<P>
   Folding the foil for a pleated temporary pan is the trickiest
part of this recipe. Tear off a piece a yard long, fold it in half
lengthwise, then pleat in 1-inch folds, like a fan. That leaves 16
spaces for cookies (don't use those on the ends), so you'll need to
bake in three batches. After removing the first batch, simply turn
the foil over to bake the second. After that, you can turn the
lengthwise fold inside out and refold, wash the foil or start over
with a clean sheet.
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups sifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped nuts, optional
</P>
<P>
   Cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar, icing or chocolate glaze (melt 1 cup
semisweet chocolate chips with 1 tablespoon solid shortening in
</P>
<P>
   microwave)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. In large mixing bowl, cream butter
and sugar. Blend in eggs, vanilla and salt and mix well. Add flour
and nuts, if using, and mix thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Fold 1 yard of heavy-duty foil in half lengthwise. Fold double
foil crosswise into 1-inch pleats to make an accordion-pleated pan.
Place on a baking sheet and spray with cooking spray.
</P>
<P>
   Drop a rounded teaspoonful of dough into each fold of the foil.
(Dough will spread during baking.)
</P>
<P>
   Bake about 25 minutes, until golden brown. Cool 10 minutes.
Remove cookies; turn foil over for next batch.
</P>
<P>
   If desired, sprinkle cookies with confectioners' sugar, frost
with icing or dip into chocolate glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie (with nuts and chocolate glaze): 78 calories, 1 gram
protein, 5 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 59), 8 grams
carbohydrates, 17 milligrams cholesterol, 45 milligrams sodium,
less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe request
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother made a dessert she called Spanish Creme. It
contained sugar, egg whites, yolks, milk, vanilla and gelatin. Does
anyone have this recipe?'' asks Anne Nelson of Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting the column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone number.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Send food news to Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. The
deadline is noon two Mondays before publication.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
