<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4411 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     09-08 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Striking a balance with Thai fare
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the bar at Tamarind, the superb Thai restaurant in
Atlanta, stand half a dozen bottles of beer, the six of them
representing the house's selections. One is Amstel Light, another
Sweetwater Ale and still another Sweetwater 420 Ale. There's
Heineken and Heineken Dark _ lagers both _ there's the distinctive
but little-known Thai lager called Singha.
</P>
<P>
   As selections go, it's neither wide nor unusual. But then, what
does one drink with Thai food?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you want something that will cleanse the palate and
not compete with the spices,'' says Jim Peck of Mac's Beer &AMP; Wine.
Sensible advice, but why not seek out something that complements
rather than competes?
</P>
<P>
   Thai cuisine, delicate and yet intensely peppery, has no obvious
partners. Its roots are Chinese and Indian, but the defining
touches _ lemon grass and lime, coriander and ginger root _ are
indigenous to Southeast Asia. So, too, are the peppers, among the
hottest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   At Tamarind, the menu gives fair warning: From one pepper to
four, you are advised whether a dish merely delivers ``a
stimulating `kick' to lips and tongue'' or whether ``management
accepts no responsibility for side effect.''
</P>
<P>
   A party of us ate at Tamarind recently, and no four-pepper
dishes were on the menu. Two peppers (``will set the lips and
tongue tingling'') was as hot as it got. Yum-Ped-Yang _ one pepper
_ is roast boneless duck with chili peppers, onions, cashew nuts,
lemon juice, pineapple chunks and sliced apples, and no wine in my
experience could mate with such a dish.
</P>
<P>
   But Singha, for mysterious reasons, harmonizes as if ordained by
nature, cleansing the palate with satisfying dryness.
</P>
<P>
   There is no particular reason why it should. It's not a ``Thai''
beer, after all, but a pale lager originally formulated by a German
brewmaster living in Thailand in the 1930s. It has the body of a
Dortmunder Export but crispness of a German-style pilsner, and a
surprising hoppiness (40 International Bitterness Units) for a
lager.
</P>
<P>
   Is it the hoppiness or the broader hop/malt profile that somehow
did the trick?
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the Heinekens, dull beers with or without food, would
have done it. And I don't see any point to light beer, so Amstel
Light would have been out of the question. That leaves the two
Sweetwaters, one an English-style bitter that won a silver medal at
the Great American Beer Festival two years ago and the other an
extra pale ale.
</P>
<P>
   The flagship Sweetwater Ale is quite a different beer from
Singha, yet it complements spicy dishes nicely. An English-style
bitter has an edge of hoppiness, but also a touch of malty
sweetness, less than a Scotch ale's and more than a pale ale's.
Paired with Thai dishes, the hops aren't enough to compete with the
peppers (they know better), but the malt has almost a soothing
effect.
</P>
<P>
   With beer as with wine, no one style is best, but some clearly
work better than others _ and others don't work at all. It doesn't
have much to do with the caliber of the beer.
</P>
<P>
   An assertive and justly celebrated beer such as Anchor Liberty
would not have made a happy marriage with those Thai chiles, one
strong personality clashing with another. On the other hand, a
bland mass-market lager would have been overwhelmed. The Sweetwater
420, an extra pale ale that makes no effort to dominate the palate,
has a clean, crisp companionability with most dishes, including
spicy ones. And a beer such as Redhook ESB would have much the same
effect as Sweetwater Ale, a bit of hoppiness balanced by a malty
backbone. So, too, would Dogwood's Breakdown IPA, a beer that has
more in common with a bitter than an IPA.
</P>
<P>
   Tuppers' Hop Pocket Pils, for my money the best pilsner
available in the United States (and better than any I've had in
Germany), might have complemented these dishes in the same way as
the Singha, the cleanness of a sturdy lager that's happy to get
along but isn't going to be pushed around. Then again, the Hop
Pocket is a big, complex beer, more assertive than the Singha, and
the last thing you want over dinner is a tug of war.
</P>
<P>
   PICK OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   The lagers of Germany are more numerous and better known, but
those of the Czech Republic occupy a special place. These are the
original pilsners, the straw-gold, dry style whose barely
recognizable descendants have spread to every corner of the globe.
The pre-eminent Czech beer, Pilsner Urquell (the name means
``Original Pilsner''), was first brewed 140 years ago and today is
as famous among lagers as Guinness Stout is among ales.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other Czech pilsners than Pilsner Urquell, just as
there other stouts than Guinness. Louny, brewed in the town of the
same name, is lighter-bodied than its better-known compatriate, but
it has the roundness and soft mouth feel you expect from a Czech
beer. You won't find many beers whose hops and malt are in better
balance.
</P>
<P>
   A Czech pils is not as dry or as crisp as a German pils, and its
nose will usually be more floral from Saaz hops. Staropramen,
another Czech beer, is drier than Pilsner Urquell but less complex.
Louny falls somewhere between the two, and combines the best
qualities of each.
</P>
<P>
   And there's something more: Pilsner Urquell is a beer I seldom
buy anymore. I've had too many that were oxidized and stale. The
Louny I've sampled has been remarkably fresh for imported beer. It
may be the most pleasant surprise among imports to arrive in the
Atlanta market in years.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
