<HEADER>
A4444 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MILLENNIAL-HUMBUG-HNS     09-08 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIAL-HUMBUG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR 2000: MUCH ADO ABOUT NADA 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DONALD G. SMITH  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MARIA, Calif. _ Here is something that troubles me about
1999. As we advance further into summer and fall, the feeling of
unease is going to increase because of the inevitable millennium
overhype.
</P>
<P>
   I believe the whole thing is a gigantic crock, unworthy of
serious discussion, but the hype continues. There will be an
avalanche of millennium T-shirts, caps, movies, bumper stickers,
songs, television specials and anything else that can turn a fast
buck.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium is manufactured news, a non-story about a
concocted event that isn't going to change anything. It is destined
to become the acme of inanity, an applied vulgarity exceeding the
combined intensity of a year-end automobile clearance, a Hollywood
funeral and a televangelist moving in for the kill. There is
nothing to look forward to because the crescendo will become more
tasteless as the year progresses.
</P>
<P>
   Elections, wars and natural disasters are legitimate news
because they change our lives. Even the seasons are worth noting.
</P>
<P>
   We dress and act differently, adapt our living patterns, even
change our attitudes. What is going to change when the clock ticks
off the seconds leading us out of 1999? Nothing. Absolutely
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   We will all be one day older, the sun will still rise in the
east, the freeways will be jammed at the rush hour, dogs will chase
cats, and small children still won't eat their vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   The point that all of the millennium buffs miss in that time is
endless and completely out of our control. Our attempts to label
and measure it are good for record-keeping and maintaining some
kind of order in human affairs, but there is no magic to any
particular date.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium business is a lot of blue steam, but this is not
going to register with those who believe that a power greater than
our own has given divine sanction to a man-made statistic.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that the end of one millennium and the consequent
beginning of another is no more blessed than the minimum wage or
the distance from home plate to the pitcher's mound. Jan. 1, 2000,
is no more or less of a date than Jan. 12 or April 17. It is merely
an artificial label for something that is going to happen with or
without the bells and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   Yet parties are planned _ and great celebrations to acknowledge
something that has no more significance than a license plate
number.
</P>
<P>
   What are these people celebrating? What is going to change after
the clocks tick off the millennium? Will the sun shine any
brighter? Will anyone be better looking, or smarter, or better able
to handle yesterday's problems? I think not.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``Much Ado About Nothing'' in modern dress, and those who
hope for something good to come from it are going to be profoundly
and permanently disappointed. They will not understand why nothing
happened.
</P>
<P>
   For my part, I will close my eyes on the night of Dec. 31 in the
spirit of one who goes to bed with a toothache. There is always the
hope that it will be gone in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Donald G. Smith, retired from the world of corporate
communications, is the author of ``People I Could Do Without.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4447 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-HUEY-LONG-HNS &LR;      09-08 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUEY-LONG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA `KINGFISH' MADE INDELIBLE MARK ON HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA BASS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Calif. _ Wednesday was the 64th anniversary of the
assassination of Huey P. Long, the ``Kingfish'' who ruled
Louisiana, hoped to be president and remains one of the most
compelling and controversial politicians this country has ever
known.
</P>
<P>
   Called a Bolshevik by some, fascist by others, the Kingfish
continues to be important even today as a classic case study of the
populist outsider coming to power.
</P>
<P>
   Huey (he consistently called himself ``Huey'' _ never ``Mr.
Long'') was born in 1893 in rural Winn Parish in north-central
Louisiana and spent his young manhood as a traveling salesman. Then
he became a lawyer at 21 after studying for just eight months. At
25 he was already in politics, a railroad commissioner taking the
side of the poor against the public utilities and large
corporations, especially Standard Oil.
</P>
<P>
   In 1928, as the anti-``plutocrat'' candidate, he successfully
ran for governor, his catchy slogan, ``Every Man a King, but No One
Wears a Crown,'' making him irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Long was despised and adored. His accomplishments
were legion. And he did, as promised, aid the poor _ and not only
poor whites, which was hardly the usual case in the South.
</P>
<P>
   He paved roads, built highways and bridges, supplied free
textbooks and founded a medical school; he set up night schools to
teach literacy, and he refurbished classrooms. He improved workers'
compensation. He even reformed the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   But he did all this at a price. He installed a political machine
whereby all state appointments, from judge to janitor, were
bestowed by his direct order. He skimmed 5 percent off the top of
every state employee's salary and put the money into a ``deduct
box'' to be spent at his personal whim. He hired and fired at will,
and he made it known that anyone who crossed him would never be
forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he established a fiefdom which replaced democratic
institutions and the rule of law with personal power. On one level,
it worked, but it worked at a terrible cost.
</P>
<P>
   In 1930, Long ran as a Democrat for the U.S. Senate. But he
didn't take his seat until 1932, when his own man was safely
installed as governor. By then the Depression was in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   Long proposed spreading ``the wealth of the land among all the
people.'' He soon was attacking President Franklin D. Roosevelt,
who had taken office in 1933, for not moving fast enough with the
New Deal. FDR responded by giving federal patronage to Long's
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Long vowed to give FDR ``unshirted hell.''
</P>
<P>
   And in 1934, he decided to make his move.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Long announced the ``Share Our Wealth'' plan (SOW),
a scheme to end the Depression by redistributing all America's
wealth so every family would have at least $3,000, plus a radio.
</P>
<P>
   Response was extremely favorable; SOW clubs sprang up
everywhere. Then Long went back to Louisiana. Although no longer a
state official, he rammed through the legislature dozens of laws _
an audacious performance, which, thanks to SOW, the entire nation
observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in old-fashioned American democracy,'' Long said.
``Only we've got to change it around some.''
</P>
<P>
   People started to buzz. In the spring of 1935, a poll showed the
Kingfish might get more than 10 percent of the vote in a national
election _ not enough to win the presidency but enough to help
Roosevelt lose it in the 1936 elections. FDR, rattled, initiated
some radical SOW-like legislation of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not good enough!'' Long roared in a series of well-publicized
filibusters.
</P>
<P>
   He took to the road and the airwaves. He was a charismatic
speaker; large audiences of potential voters responded with money
and cheers. Rumors of a third-party nomination started to spread.
</P>
<P>
   With Long's popularity soaring, Roosevelt continued to toss New
Deal money to his opponents, who by now were calling for a federal
investigation of the Kingfish's one-man rule. The senator, enraged,
returned to Louisiana and called for a special legislative session
to consolidate his power by kicking the New Deal out of Louisiana;
the state would use state money only for public improvement, and
his foes would be impotent.
</P>
<P>
   Told this was unconstitutional, he replied tersely, ``I don't
give a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Others did. Among his more minor demands was revision of a
judicial district housing an enemy judge who was gerrymandered out
of his place on the bench. The judge's son-in-law, Dr. Carl A.
Weiss, 29, waited for Long, who was surrounded by bodyguards, to
come out of the governor's office in the state capitol on Sept. 8,
1935. According to the official but still-controversial reports by
the Louisiana state police, Weiss shot Long once in the abdomen _
and was himself cut down in a fusillade fired by the bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss died. And so, 30 hours later, did the Kingfish. He was 42.
</P>
<P>
   What does Huey Long's life teach us? There are, after all, many
who argue that skirting the law may be justified if the outcome is
noble, and among Long's achievements are certainly some we would
all call noble. But the price was high. Achievement is no
substitute for democracy, and dictatorship is dictatorship no
matter how well it works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
