<HEADLINE>
THE END OF HITS, RUNS AND AN ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was the bottom of the 10th inning with two
outs and two men on. Several thousand people in Candlestick Park
looked to Giants infielder Bill Mueller for a game-ending run.
</P>
<P>
   He went down on a called third strike.
</P>
<P>
   An afternoon windstorm _ typical and symbolic of the 36-year-old
Candlestick Park _ had been in full blow for nearly an hour. The
first peanut shells had been levitated into eye-gouging projectiles
at 4:02 p.m., and I'd found myself wishing for sandbags to anchor
my scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   Red dirt from the Giants bullpen mound _ just three rows below
our box seats _ periodically pounded our eyes, teeth and pores.
</P>
<P>
   I stole a glance to the left at my friend Loysie, then to the
right at my friend Terri. My heart sank. It was nearly 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   We had been watching baseball for more than three hours. All of
us had places we needed to be. But Loysie and Terri sat like
statues in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   The truth stared me in my dirt-covered face: I may have spent
close to a decade covering professional baseball as a sportswriter,
but, compared to these two women, I barely qualify as an A-league
fan.
</P>
<P>
   Leave when the score is tied? When the San Francisco Giants
could win No. 13 out of their last 16 played? With the silly
expansion team, the Arizona Diamondbacks, still 6 1/2 games in
front? Not Loysie. Not Terri.
</P>
<P>
   I had come to the Giants-Phillies game just to watch a few
innings and to say goodbye to baseball at Candlestick Park.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of them were cold, I'd spent many a night and day
in the ugly concrete stadium. I had some memories, felt a wisp of
sadness that, next season, pretty little Pac Bell Park in downtown
San Francisco would make baseball fans forget Candlestick on even
its best days.
</P>
<P>
   Loysie and Terri will likely be there for the last Giants game
ever at the 'Stick _ Loysie especially since she and her husband
John have had season tickets since 1983. Both women had rearranged
their schedules this day so they could duck out of work early and
root for the home team; Loysie had set up extended daycare for her
two kids.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to marketing surveys and demographic analyses, baseball
executives are super-savvy these days about the makeup of what is
known at their ``fan base.'' But sometimes I wonder if they fully
appreciate the individual devotion and sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   When I sat up in the press box, it was easy to lump the fans
into a stomping, faceless horde that could not hear an organ run
without screaming ``Charge!'' Often, I reminded others that ``fan''
is short for ``fanatic,'' and what did THAT say about the kind of
lives such people lead?
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Terri and Loysie _ knowing that neither of them
needs to get a life because both have big, demanding, complex ones
_ I felt bad about all those smirking put-downs. Being a baseball
devotee may not be my cup of beer, but it sure agrees with a few
million other folks.
</P>
<P>
   Thank God, though, for Jeff Kent, who blasted a two-run homer
just over the right field fence in the bottom of the 11th, to beat
the Philadelphia team, 5-3. As I'd learned a couple of innings
before, Loysie had actually sat in her car outside the hospital
when she was in labor with her first baby, refusing to go in until
she heard the end of the Giants game on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   It was a regular season game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
