<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOLD RUSH YIELDS TO LAND ROVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The topic was ``Has the Bay Area lost its
edge?'' as Michael Krasny put it. His KQED radio talk show on
Tuesday was about whether artists and bohemians can survive here
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Short answer: No.
</P>
<P>
   Longer answer: Only if they issue stock in a hot new Internet
start-up called sfboho.com.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, we don't even think about an artistic cutting edge
anymore, if the Bay Area was ever on it. ``Edge'' now refers to
things technological. Clearly, many people are on edge about our
new economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on a different edge, whether you like it or not,'' said
a caller to the show who gave his name as Jeff. ``It began in the
'80s as developers built high-rises and began filling up the cities
and suburbs with a different kind of people. ... A city is only as
good as the people in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, we've got some very good Web designers, on-line investors
and upscale restaurateurs. Many dress like bohemians when they're
showing off.
</P>
<P>
   Most callers to Krasny's show weren't very sentimental about the
beats, hippies and musicians who made San Francisco famous. The
show quickly became a cry from aging hearts for all the other
things the Bay Area has lost.
</P>
<P>
   Affordable rents. Homes you can buy without making a mint in the
stock market. A middle class. A working class. Decent public
schools. Weird characters. A sense of fun. Neighborliness.
</P>
<P>
   Artists have felt the loss of these things as much as anyone,
and yuppies have taken all the lofts. Guidebooks may describe the
North Beach or South of Market neighborhoods as bohemian haunts,
but they've gone the way of Sausalito.
</P>
<P>
   An artist named Steven called in from West Oakland, saying it's
the only diverse place he can live for under $25,000 a year, and
he's nervous it's going upscale. ``How many artists can find new
enclaves?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The only other artist calling in was Gillian, who said, ``You're
talking like we're some kind of magic bullet (for cultural life). I
keep moving from warehouse to warehouse. I get up in the morning. I
have to pay my bills.''
</P>
<P>
   You can guess what appalled most callers.
</P>
<P>
   Greed. The Silicon Valley cult of becoming a millionaire by age
28. Mansions built to the lot lines. SUVs. Incredibly high rents
and home prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area, love paying the rent or leave it.
</P>
<P>
   Ann from Mountain View said she grew up in Palo Alto in the '50s
and '60s when that city had a diversity and democracy unheard of
nowadays. Butchers lived next door to scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disconcerting to me that I can't afford to move back
to the town I grew up in,'' she complained. ``It's really sad.
There's this kind of Silicon Valley arrogance that's driving people
out.''
</P>
<P>
   A caller named Marnie also lives in that former orchard known as
``the Valley of Heart's Delight.'' She said her neighbor's heart's
delight is building a 5,800-square-foot monster house next to her
small home.
</P>
<P>
   ``What ever happened to the virtue of modesty?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Economic modesty has disappeared in the '90s the way sexual
modesty did in the '60s. Being immodest was more fun in the good
old days.
</P>
<P>
   As a guest on the show, I wanly pointed out that the Bay Area
was built on greed for gold in the middle of the last century,
benefiting a few rich people to the detriment of the many.
</P>
<P>
   Things hadn't changed much. But rich people back then had much
more interesting displays of wealth. And the Land Rover hadn't been
invented.
</P>
<P>
   A caller named Adam said greed is an unavoidable human quality.
``I don't go around saying, `Palo Alto used to be this way.' I'm
Native-American, and my ancestors were slaughtered. That's just
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a few people talked about how the Bay Area has been turned
into a theme park for tourists and the rich, with the poor and
working class pushed out or against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Hughes, a trustee of the Marin County Foundation and a
guest on the show, talked about the ``Carmelization'' of Marin,
saying, ``Even our gas stations are cute.''
</P>
<P>
   They ought to be for the prices they charge.
</P>
<P>
   The astounding thing to me was that even callers in their 30s
and early 40s complained about how much the Bay Area has changed. I
thought that was the one job old people had to themselves, with no
threat of being replaced by younger people.
</P>
<P>
   A man named David who came to San Francisco in the 1980s, the
decade of the junk bond, complained about the rampant materialism
of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out here to play,'' he said. ``I came here to stay out
late at night, meet weird characters and hopefully become one
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's just another guy calling a radio talk show. Krasny
pointed out that maybe David came to San Francisco for the theme
park.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but it was a different theme park back in the good old days
_ even the good old days of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The admission fee wasn't $2,000 a month. If you were this high,
you could take the rides _ and high on anything, not just high on
greed.
</P>
<P>
   But what can you do? My motto is, ``No yuppie ever wrecked my
life except me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
