<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PATRIOTS, KEY ROOKIE IS WOODY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Attention has been focused on the other
Patriots rookies. Perhaps Michael Bishop has been most in the
spotlight, then Andy Katzenmoyer and next Sean Morey. Even Tony
George has grabbed his share of attention.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most important rookie of all has gone about his
job quietly and with little attention. The seventh-rounders have
Patriot fans arguing and debating, but their first pick in the
first round, center Damien Woody, absolutely must succeed. And so
far, Woody seems well on his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to see the whole picture now,'' said the rookie
from Boston College, ``and at the start of training camp, I didn't
see that.''
</P>
<P>
   No team in the NFL can do very well without a strong offensive
line, and Woody will be the anchor of the Patriots' unit. It is
daunting for a rookie, even more so for a center who must recognize
opponents' schemes and make blocking calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're counting on Woody, and he has to come through for us,''
said coach Pete Carroll. ``We're not counting on him to do
extraordinary things but just do a regular journeyman's load and
start building. He's done well enough that we feel OK.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Woody has been doing great,'' said his neighbor at left guard,
Heath Irwin. ``He's really come along incredibly through camp.
We're not too worried about Woody in there. I think it's working
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Woody has been seeing vanilla defenses from the four
opponents in exhibition games. It all changes Sunday with the start
of the regular season, when new games and tricks and ploys and
stunts will be thrown at Woody by the Jets, seeking to confuse the
youngster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can help him with some calls,'' said Irwin. ``But
pretty much everybody on the line knows where the calls are going,
and if he does call something that may not be right at the time or
maybe something that he hasn't seen, it can be changed by somebody
else. But Woody has been doing great.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody had been eased into the Patriots' system, with help from
his coaches, of course, but also teammates on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've never let my confidence fall,'' said Woody. ``They've
been helping me out a lot and it's made the transition (from
college) a lot easier for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Woody knows all too well, ``People are counting on me to
make the right calls and do the right thing. I think I'm in pretty
good shape right now as far as grasping the offense and mentally
I've really progressed a lot since the first day of camp. And
physically I think I'm doing OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the blocking calls ``is going a whole lot better now,''
the rookie went on. ``Things are coming to me now. I'm seeing the
whole defense and I credit a lot of that to (line coach Dante
Scarnecchia) and doing a lot of film work on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody knows the Jets will be coming at him with some ``funky
schemes, but that's sort of good in a way because I can anticipate
it,'' he said. ``I'll be able to jump on what they're trying to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, for instance, Woody came to practice an hour early
``and I went to watch films (of the Jets) by myself for an hour,
both from their preseason and from last year. And I'm starting to
get a feel for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, said Woody, ``I think I'm ready for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, the quiet rookie will mean more to the Patriots than any
loud debates about other rookies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
