<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BURNS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNOUT NO CONCERN WITH BRUINS COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- There's a cliche in sports that goes something like
this: When a coach heads into his third year behind the bench with
one team, there is a danger that players will stop listening to him
at some point.
</P>
<P>
   Ask coaches, general managers, and players where that adage
comes from, and no one knows. Is it because the shelf life of
coaches seems to get shorter and shorter? Is it because the
pressure and the money seem to be increasing all the time in an
industry in which the players have more and more power and the
coaches less and less?
</P>
<P>
   Pat Burns is heading into his third year with the Bruins. In his
first season, little was known about the brand-new squad, which was
full of kids. The team was coming off its worst season in 30 years,
and Burns, with a four-year contract, was doggedly determined to
turn it around. Last fall, Burns went into training camp with key
players _ top scorer Jason Allison, valuable defenseman Kyle
McLaren, and up-and-coming forward Anson Carter _ out of the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the holdout bug struck again; No. 1 goalie Byron
Dafoe is out in California, while left wing P.J. Axelsson and
defenseman Hal Gill are cooling their heels at their respective
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Burns recognizes this as an annual event and, just as he said
last year, he'll coach the players he has.
</P>
<P>
   When he was told that Indiana Pacers coach and former Celtic
legend Larry Bird planned to call it quits after three years, Burns
had a classic comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Bird's rich; I'm not,'' said Burns. ``So sorry, Larry,
I'd like to go for a long time. People have said (a certain number
of) years _ I've even said four years _ maybe was enough. Who
knows, if you're doing the proper things? The guys you have to
satisfy are ownership and management. When I hear that players
turned off, I'm wondering sometimes if it's not somebody else who
turned off. I get along fine with management here. Our ownership is
a great ownership because they don't meddle. I'd like to stay here
a long time. I'm starting the third year of a four-year deal, so
let's see what happens next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins president/general manager Harry Sinden practically
chortled when asked if he was worried about his players turning a
deaf ear to Burns's instruction at any point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of hard to tune out,'' said Sinden. ``I don't think
you can turn that switch. He gets their attention very easily. I'm
not worried about that with him. That's one of the reasons he got a
four-year contract. That's a long contract for a coach. I'm
thankful I have him to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   So once again, Burns will take a patchwork quilt into the
exhibition season, trying out new faces with varying degrees of
talent and experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we get into a situation where not everybody is here
again,'' said Burns. ``Am I comfortable? No, I'm not that
comfortable. We're going to have to see what kind of team we're
going to be able to put out on the ice. When you lose guys like Tim
Taylor (who went to the Rangers) and P.J. Axelsson, they were a big
part of our penalty killing, and it was No. 1 in the NHL. Dave
Ellett is gone (as the result of a buyout), and Ken Baumgartner is
behind the bench with me (as an assistant). All of a sudden, I look
down the bench, and they're not there anymore. We have to fill that
void.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest void continues to be in net. Dafoe remains out of
camp, and the news hasn't been encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goaltending is 75 percent of your team, and when you don't
have it, it's 100 percent of your team,'' said Burns. ``We'll give
some opportunities to guys like (John) Grahame and Robbie Tallas.
They're going to have to do it. Our penalty killing had a lot to do
with Byron last year, too. And Hal Gill is another one. Everybody
seems to forget that we had six or seven guys walk out of this
hockey team who have not been replaced yet.''
</P>
<P>
   As pointed as Burns was about his lack of a cohesive lineup, he
said he won't be getting involved in the front office's business.
He'll make the most of what he has, although if September turns
into October and November and Dafoe is still absent, it's hard to
believe Burns could hold his tongue. However, in Day 3 of training
camp in suburban Wilmington, Burns was putting a brave and
pragmatic face on things.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to move on. There's nothing you can do about it,'' he
said. ``You can't let it distract you. You have to go out and try
to find a way to win. That's my job, no matter who's in front of
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
