<HEADLINE>
`GET REAL' GETS DOWN IN DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
GET REAL 
Starring: Jon Tenney, Debrah Farentino, Christina Pickles, Anne
Hathaway, Eric Christian Olsen, Jesse Eisenberg 
On: Fox, Ch. 25 
Time: Wednesday at 9 
Rated: TV14 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' means to turn the family TV series into a
self-conscious, postmodern joke. Sure, Fox's spiffy new family
dramedy (a famedy?) relies on some very conventional TV storylines,
from Mom and Dad's strained marriage to 15-year-old Kenny's high
school crush. But the show eagerly reinvents these plot cliches
with the help of an arsenal of stylistic devices, including
relay-race voiceovers, allusions to other TV shows, and teens who
break the fourth wall to chat with viewers. It's an aggressively
innovative hour that has some of the spirit and non-gravitational
charm of 'toon-coms like ``Family Guy'' and ``The Simpsons,'' and
it will appeal to fans of the surrealistic tweaking that David E.
Kelley and ``Ally McBeal'' have made so popular.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind ``Get Real'' is that the best way to capture the
media-steeped chaos of an American family (white and affluent, of
course; this is network TV) is to be as boldly self-aware and
eccentric as possible. In the first few minutes of the premiere
episode, as the Green family chaotically readies itself for morning
lift-off, the characters say little as we hear their thoughts in
voiceover that leaps from character to character. We're smack
inside their group consciousness, from Mary Green's sexual fantasy
about her husband's business partner to 17-year-old Meghan's
musings on ``Get Real'' itself: ``I know what you're thinking: This
is another one of those smartass shows where the kids talk to the
audience like on `Dawson's Creek,' which, actually, come to think
of it, I'm not even sure does voiceovers.'' It's one of the
season's more engaging opening sequences.
</P>
<P>
   The premiere goes on to serve as a primer in the Greens of L.A.,
a family that is in as much turmoil as its mid-renovation kitchen.
Parents Mary and Mitch are too busy to deal with the death of
intimacy in their marriage; the usually overachieving Meghan
doesn't want to go to college; 16-year-old Cameron is a womanizing
narcissist; and young Kenny just wants to glimpse a woman's
breasts. The show has the same blueprint as ``My So-Called Life,''
with the moving back and forth between high school and home,
between class cliques and family issues. But, as Meghan rightly
tells us, ``Get Real'' is not as ``sturmy'' as ``My So-Called
Life,'' and its angst is almost always undercut by comedy and
irony. When Cameron is in a car accident and the show could be
headed into shmaltz, Meghan slyly notes, ``You think we're going to
kill my brother in the first episode?''
</P>
<P>
   The dramedic tone extends to Mary and Mitch's inability to
discipline their children. In one scene, Mary checks in on Cameron,
who's still sleeping. She stands beside his bed and pulls down the
sheet, and there he is _ naked beside one of his high school
girlfriends. ``Mom, this is Gaby,'' he says with a yawn, and
feckless Gaby reaches out her arm and says ``Hey Mrs. Green.'' And
as Gaby reaches to shake hands, the makers of ``Get Real'' amplify
the clinking sound of the many bracelets on her arm, a flourish
that drives home the sheer absurdity of the moment. It's a small
touch, but it's the sort of effect that ``Get Real'' uses to
maintain its buoyant atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Is ``Get Real'' too smart for its own good? Are there too many
sex jokes? Yes, some of the hip references are dated (did they give
Kenny his name in order to fit in a ``South Park'' bit?) and there
may be one too many breast bits. But ``Get Real'' is nevertheless
an ambitious, energetic venture, one that could develop into
something unique if it doesn't tire itself out too soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
