<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday,
Sept. 9. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   BILL _ Bill Bradley officially kicks off his run for the
Democratic nomination in his old hometown of Crystal City, takes
the press for a spin around his old stomping grounds. 25. Photos.
Steve Kraske.
</P>
<P>
   FIELD _ In the movie ``Field of Dreams'' the ghost of Shoeless
Joe Jackson emerges from a stand of corn and asks: ``Is this
Heaven?'' No such luck, Costner responds. But in the end the film
implies that the hereafter would have a hard time beating foul
lines stretching into a Midwestern cornfield. Fans charmed by the
movie's romance with baseball and farm life have come here ever
since, chasing ground balls and nostalgia on base paths. But this
piece of Iowa is Heaven no more. The field's caretakers _ Becky and
Don Lansing own the most of the infield and right field, Rita and
Al Ameskamp hold deed to left and center fields _ can't seem to get
along. In a conflict perhaps as American as the game the field
celebrates, the Lansings and Ameskamps peddle souvenirs out of
competing shacks and regularly settle scores at county zoning panel
meetings. ``It's a shame,'' said Don Lansing. ``It takes away from
the field and the fun for the fans.'' Scott Canon. 32. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   DAN _ Former Sen. Jack Danforth is expected to take the lead in
the investigation of the Waco mess. We look at the man and his past
as prosecutor and senator, try to gauge what kind of job he has and
how well he'll do it. Rick Montgomery and David Goldstein. 30.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush visits Adele Hall, of the
Hallmark Cards Inc. Halls, to pick up another one of his big
checks. We get a few minutes alone with him, plus he'll make some
remarks at the airport. Rick Montgomery. 25. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   ABORT: Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan and lobbyist Lou DeFeo will
sit down Wednesday and discuss their differences over the
partial-birth abortion bill. The unusual meeting comes one week
before the start of the veto session that could override Carnahan's
veto of the bill that creates the ``crime of infanticide.'' Will
Sentell. 25.
</P>
<P>
   MIDWIF: KU School of Nursing develops bi-state graduate nurse
midwife program to help reduce newborn death rate in the central
city and in rural areas. The program will increase the availability
of pre-natal care. Photo. Alan Bavley.
</P>
<P>
   GUS. Restoration of Gus Grissom's Liberty Bell 7 space capsule
begins today (Wednesday) at the Kansas Cosmosphere in Hutchinson.
John Petterson. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   OZ. Tent. The Oz theme park development plan calls for 3 million
plus visitors almost right out of the chute; do industry observers
find these projections realistic? Grace Hobson. 30. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BUS. Holdover. The National Transportation Safety Board recently
recommended stricter rules on the types of vehicles used to
transport children involved in school, Head Start and other
programs. The recommendations, if adopted, would phase out vans
often used by day-care centers and others, replacing them with
sturdier and safer school buses. Some Kansas City area school
districts already have made the change. 32. Robert A. Cronkleton.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   BLOCK _ H&AMP;R Block holds its annual meeting. By Gene Meyer, with
PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   STAFF _ ``How to Deal With Difficult People'' is the workplace
seminar that always attracts a crowd. Most leave without the quick
fix they sought. At Work column by Diane Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   WIGHT. He once was the biggest player ever for the Wichita State
basketball team. Now at 7-1 and 460 pounds, Paul Wight, a.k.a.
``The Big Show,'' is one of the biggest stars in professional
wrestling. Jason King. 30. Photos.
