<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ECONOMICS LESSON FOR RETURNING STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Good morning, class.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning, Mr. Nyh-hann.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To start our school year we'll take our annual back-to-school
quiz. Because I know some of the answers and you don't, I'll tell
you. But after today, it's your job to find the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, doing corridor duty, I heard a lot of you grumble about
the facilities here. How many here can guess the average age of a
school building in the United States? Approximately 42 years. A lot
of them are twice that. How many factories could stay in business
if they had to operate in a building built before your parents were
born? Not many, is the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many kids like you walk into those buildings every school
day? About 52 million, depending on the incidence of sniffles,
oversleeping, or hooky.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of you with younger brothers and sisters, how many
more classroom seats will be needed in the next seven years? About
2.3 million, to accommodate the baby boom and immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many new teachers will be needed over the next 10 years to
teach this growing population of pupils? Almost as many _ 2.2
million. Why do we need so many new teachers? Lots of teachers will
retire, get burned out, or leave teaching for higher-paying or less
stressful jobs doing something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is burnout a problem? Because in a lot of classrooms,
there are 28 or 29 or 30 or even more students. The bigger the
class, the harder the teacher's job of getting each kid to do his
or her best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do some teachers quit and look for other jobs? Because
there's a lot of stress involved in standing before five or six
classes a day, doing hallway or cafeteria duty, meeting with kids
after school, dealing with parents, writing, and reading the notes
that fly back and forth, then correcting homework and tests and
papers at night or on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it harder to teach than it used to be? Parents aren't
home as much. So kids are a lot more rambunctious as a rule.
There's a lot less discipline in the home. A lot of kids _ almost
half _ live with only one parent at home, because of divorce or
separation _ or even no parent in the house. A lot of families have
both parents out working, sometimes at two jobs apiece. The kids
watch TV, eat junk food, hang out. Crime experts say kids who get
in trouble tend to get in trouble between 3 and 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I don't want to embarrass anybody by asking which of you
comes from a family with no health insurance, so don't raise your
hand. How many children and teens lack insurance? Eleven million.
Half of them should be on Medicaid, which helps poor families, or
the Children's Health Insurance Program, which Congress passed two
years ago. But some states changed welfare rules, so uninsured kids
fell through the cracks. Till 1996, if your family was on welfare,
you automatically got Medicaid coverage, too. No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``With anybody working who wants a job, and this booming
economy, is education less important than it used to be? It would
be a huge mistake for you to believe that. Two out of three working
Americans earn less than $40,000 a year, which does not go very far
if you want a house, a car, a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now get out your pencil and paper and write these numbers
down. We're going to divide all 280 million Americans into five
groups of the same size, that's 20 percent of the population in
each fifth. The bottom fifth each year has to live on $8,800 per
household after taxes. That's $169 a week _ for everything. How
well can a family live on just $24 a day?
</P>
<P>
   ``The next lowest fifth live on $20,000 a year _ that's $55 a
day. If you put $20 worth of gas in your car, take someone to a
movie for $15, then go to McDonald's afterword, you're broke _ no
money for anything else that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The middle fifth live on $31,400 a year, that's $86 a day.
That's better _ but you better have health insurance for you and
your family. The second-highest fifth have $45,100 a year, good for
$123 a day. Most all of them have health insurance. Then there's
the fattest fifth, the 20 percent on top. They all have health
insurance, but a lot of them don't go to public schools either,
they go to private school.
</P>
<P>
   ``That household gets along on $515,000 a year, which works out
to $1,411 per day, which is the same as getting about $59 per hour.
In other words, the top fifth of households have as much money to
spend in three hours as the bottom fifth have to last a whole week.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that, boys and girls, is economics, and economics is what
determines who teaches you, how well, in what kind of a building,
for how much in taxes, and what kind of earning power you kids will
have in turn when you go to make a living. If it sounds
complicated, don't worry. You'll get to be very familiar with how
this works over the next 50 years. Try to remember this simple
rule: `You get what you pay for.' That's all for this first class.
Take a break. You'll need it. So do I.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
