<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4490 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MA-LABOR-SHORTAGE-ART     09-08 1538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-LABOR-SHORTAGE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES GET CREATIVE OVER LABOR SHORTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- After seven years of a robust economy and unemployment
at record lows, the labor market is drying up in virtually every
sector, from unskilled laborers to information technology
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage is so profound that local employers of every size
are going to extraordinary lengths to find workers. Raytheon Co. is
relaxing its button-down culture and deploying a squad of
executives, including its chief executive officer, to attract
employees, while Internet start-ups offer bounties and prizes for
referrals that lead to hires. Some Massachusetts restaurants
routinely bring in temporary workers from overseas to fill hiring
gaps.
</P>
<P>
   The worker drought has hit every region of the country. In
Nebraska, there is a shortage of meat packers. In Ohio, consumer
products giant Procter &AMP; Gamble has resorted to using a recruiting
firm to scour retirement homes in search of workers, some of whom
have been hired for entry-level jobs even though they are in their
70s and 80s. In Silicon Valley, the epicenter of the high-tech
revolution, bidding wars are common for talented software
engineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just getting tighter and tighter, and it is going to
continue,'' said Ryan Mason, Ohio area manager for Manpower Inc.,
the national recruiting firm assisting Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   The labor market is so tight that some economists say a recent
small decline in labor demand from a peak in 1998 may not signal a
slowing of the economy, but rather a surrender of sorts by
employers who have given up trying to fill jobs because qualified
applicants are too few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Dellaria Salons. With about 20 hair salons
in New England, the chain has the business and the credit to open
as many as 10 more stores, but is going ahead with just two because
staffing more than that is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of recruiting. We offer a 401(k), life insurance,
medical insurance, and our average hairdresser after two years
makes $35,000 to $40,000 a year plus gratuities,'' said Nino
Micozzi, president of Dellaria Salons. If they were available, he
says, he could hire 100 stylists ``tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   But they are not available, Micozzi says.
</P>
<P>
   Without stylists to cut hair, Dellaria is losing potential
business. The company estimates that each week about 1,800 people
are turned away from its 23 salons. With haircuts averaging $35,
the company may be forfeiting more than $3 million a year in
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are higher for edocs Inc., a Natick start-up that
develops and markets Internet-based billing and document
transaction systems, a market niche that analysts say could reach
$40 billion in revenues by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, the company has doubled in size to about 100
employees but needs to hire another 80 employees by year's end _ a
considerable challenge given the tough competition for qualified
personnel in information technology.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to using newspaper and radio ads, edocs officials
are considering running ads in movie theaters and are passing the
word around in area churches that the company is hiring.
</P>
<P>
   For every successful referral made by an employee, their spouse,
or a company vendor, the reward is $5,000. And the company, which
raised $22 million in venture capital funding in the last year, has
a pool of prizes, including two first-class tickets to Hawaii, that
it will give away in a drawing for employees who brought new
workers to the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Growth is critical to the success of edocs, which offers new
employees a competitive salary, good benefits _ including unlimited
paid personal days _ and stock options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure is not an option for us,'' said cofounder and
executive vice president Jim Moran. ``We will search high and low.
We have more people involved full time in recruiting right now than
we do in marketing. This is so key to us because without them we
won't grow as fast as we want and won't dominate the marketplace
without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even established corporate giants are trying to be as nimble as
possible in pursuit of employees. Raytheon, which hopes to hire
7,000 people worldwide and bring on an additional 2,000 employees
straight out of college, has introduced flexible work hours and
casual dress _ not just on Friday but all week long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize how tight the market is and how competitive it is
and we are trying to make Raytheon as attractive as possible,''
said spokesman David Polk from the company's Lexington
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to routine college recruiting, 90 key executives
have been assigned to strengthen ties with campuses to woo the best
and brightest. Each executive focuses on a single school. ``We make
it part of their job to build relationships with faculty, staff,
and students,'' said Polk. Raytheon chairman and CEO Daniel P.
Burnham is not excluded. His campus? The Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists say the hiring challenge facing Raytheon and
thousands of other companies is not likely to ease soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The labor market will stay tight as long as the domestic
economy keeps growing,'' said William C. Dunkelberg, chief
economist for the National Federation of Independent Business,
which represents about 600,000 small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In the Midwest, where meat-packing jobs and many other unskilled
jobs are going unfilled, it is the same story. ``I don't see the
job market demand easing because this is a national phenomenon,''
said F. Charles Lamphear, director of the Bureau of Business
Research at the University of Nebraska-Lincoln. ``There are
shortages all around the country and noticeable shortages in
attractive areas like the information management field. I think it
will go on for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   With jobs so plentiful and labor in such short supply, there is
concern in Washington and on Wall Street that wages will rise and
spark inflation, since price increases tend to follow payroll
increases. But a surprising benefit to the prolonged economic
prosperity, economists say, is that productivity gains have offset
much of the need to raise prices dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Former Labor Secretary Robert Reich, a Brandeis University
professor of social and economic policy, said there is also another
reason wage inflation has been held in check. ``Workers in the
1990s are aware of how easily they can be replaced, either by
technology, by lower-wage workers elsewhere in the country, or by
workers in other nations eager to offer their services for a
fraction of the prevailing wage in America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, anecdotal evidence suggests many workers at all levels
of the economy are reaping the benefits of a tight labor market _
demanding and receiving signing bonuses, stock options, more time
off, and better work schedules. Meanwhile, businesses seem locked
in a struggle to find and keep workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dan'l Webster Hearth 'n Kettle Management Group, with two
inns and eight restaurants from Weymouth to Cape Cod, has
increasingly relied on workers from Jamaica to help it through its
peak season. This year the number reached 30 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year we have to bring more and more,'' said Frank
Catania, vice president of the company. ``We bring them here in May
and they stay until November. They work as cooks, dishwashers,
chambermaids; a couple are bakers.'' Their prevailing wage is set
by the Department of Labor, with dishwashers earning about $8.50 an
hour and cooks $11 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, businesses move quickly to grab workers when
companies in their industries fail. Last month, Boston-based
SpeechWorks International Inc., a computer software company,
learned that a Canadian software firm had collapsed. SpeechWorks
spent $50,000 to fly 40 software engineers from the defunct firm to
Boston, where they were treated to dinners and harbor cruises _ all
in an effort to hire them. The company has yet to say how many
engineers have come on board.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the need for workers overcomes their apparent lack of
knowledge in a particular field. When Caldor declared bankruptcy
recently, the Massachusetts Extended Care Federation, a nursing
home association, wrote to the chief executive officer of the
Connecticut-based retailer expressing interest in helping laid-off
Caldor workers ``find their way into new careers.''
</P>
<P>
   In the supercharged economy of the 1990s, such stories are
common. But perhaps no employer faces a more daunting challenge
than the US Census Bureau. The bureau's goal is to attract 3
million applicants and from that pool hire hundreds of thousands of
temporary workers to help take the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   Some human resource managers think the goal is laughable, but
Janet Cummings, the bureau's assistant division chief for
recruiting, said the bureau will do what many employers have done
to fill the positions: pay top dollar. The going rate in New York
City will be as much as $18.50 per hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
