<HEADLINE>
HENDERSON GETS THE CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US Olympic softball team for 2000 will include eight
veterans from the 1996 gold-medal squad and at least one newcomer
whose name you might recognize: Danielle ``Harry'' Henderson, who
struck out 1,343 batters during her just-concluded All-American
career at the University of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't believe it,'' said Henderson Tuesday in San
Diego, where she and her new Olympic teammates will compete this
weekend in the US Olympic Cup. ``Press conferences, team meetings,
practices: I don't know when it's going to hit me. Maybe when I
come home.''
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old Henderson, from Commack, N.Y., is now an
assistant coach at her alma mater, to which she expects to return
Sept. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Olympians coming back to defend their title in Sydney
will be Dot Richardson, the 37-year-old second baseman and
orthopedic surgeon. The seven remaining veterans are outfielders
Laura Berg and Leah O'Brien-Amico, first baseman Sheila Douty, and
pitchers Christa Williams, Michele Smith, Lori Harrigan, and Lisa
Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the team will be Henderson, outfielder Christie
Ambrosi, third baseman Jennifer Brundage, shortstop Crystl Bustos,
infielder Jennifer McFalls, and catchers Stacey Nuverman and
Michelle Venturella.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-member squad was announced Monday by the Amateur Softball
Association/USA Softball.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Henderson was a member of the US national team that
won gold at the Pan American Games, pitching two perfect games
while going 3-0, allowing just one hit and striking out 42 in 17
innings.
</P>
<P>
   For Elaine Sortino, the UMass softball coach under whom
Henderson compiled a 108-35 record and set an NCAA record last
season with 105 consecutive scoreless innings, it was a long night
waiting for the news after the three-day Olympic Trials ended
Saturday in Midland, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very, very hopeful,'' said Sortino, ``but in the
back of my mind I knew she has only been pitching since her junior
year of high school. In terms of years, she's really a neophyte.
Every week when she was here, you saw her get better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   When the phone call from Henderson finally came at 4:15 a.m.
Sunday, recalled Sortino, the player's first words were ``Coach,
will you be mad if I don't come back to work for two weeks?''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. ``We're so proud,'' said Sortino, who confessed she
still gets goose bumps just thinking about it. ``What else could
you do in our game that's better than being a pitcher on the
Olympic team?''
</P>
<P>
   As for Henderson, who capped her brilliant career at UMass by
winning the Honda Award as the nation's top collegiate softball
player, being the only new pitcher to be added to the roster from
'96 ``doesn't make me nervous, it makes me honored to be on the
same staff as players I've looked up to for so long. I'll be able
to learn a lot from them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Big weekend for Smyers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karen Smyers of Lincoln, Mass. will be one of six women
competing for Team USA at the Triathlon World Championship this
weekend in Montreal, by virtue of her recent third-place finish at
the North American Championships. The 1.5K swim-40K bike-10K run
will be contested at the 1976 Olympic rowing venue . . . Among the
finalists for the Women's Sports Foundation 1999 Sportswoman of the
Year are New Englanders A.J. Mleczko of Nantucket, a member of the
1998 gold-medal Olympic ice hockey team and 1999 national-champion
Harvard squad, and swimmer Jenny Thompson, a five-time Olympic
relay gold medalist and native of Dover, N.H., who last month broke
the world record for the 100-meter butterfly. Marla Runyan, the
1500-meter runner who made the World Championships final last month
despite being legally blind, is also among the 21 finalists, along
with Mia Hamm, Marion Jones, Juli Inkster, and Chamique Holdsclaw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
