<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENACIOUS REDSTONE SAVORS BIGGEST DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was classic Sumner Redstone. In front of a big media
audience, he rambled on with obvious enthusiasm and unbridled
superlatives Tuesday about the benefits of his latest and biggest
deal of all.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone, the man who once told the world that content was king,
explained why it was a master stroke to combine his Viacom Inc.
with CBS Inc. and its distribution empire in a deal valued at $37.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, most investors seemed to buy the story.
Shares of both Viacom and CBS traded higher on news of the merger
of the communications giants.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone is many odd things for a man worth $10 billion or so, a
serial name-dropper prone to inflating stories of triumph and
grabbing every chance to jab competitors, large or small.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the package also includes seemingly boundless
energy and optimism that would be remarkable in any person but is
truely striking for a 76-year-old man.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with shrewdness and vast experience, that tenacious
personality has helped Redstone build a string of Boston-based
drive-in movie theaters into one of the world's largest media and
entertainment conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime Newton resident who lives mostly in New York now,
Redstone is famous for a nonstop work schedule that stretches into
practically every waking hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known him for over 30 years, and he's as motivated or
more motivated than at any time in his life,'' said George Abrams,
a Viacom director and Redstone's personal attorney for more than
three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more success he's had, the more he wants to continue,''
said Abrams. ``I think Sumner will be running the company five
years from now, and 10 years from now if he can.''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably not what Mel Karmazin has in mind. The CBS chief
will become second in command at Viacom and the explictly
identified successor to Redstone when he no longer runs the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone's two closest deputies, Philippe Dauman and Thomas
Dooley, will give up their management posts at Viacom. His two
children, both directors of Viacom, have not held senior management
jobs at the company and were never seen as corporate heirs to their
father's job (daughter Shari Redstone runs National Amusements in
Dedham, which owns the family Viacom stock and operates Showcase
Cinemas, among other things).
</P>
<P>
   Redstone built a remarkable local reputation long before he
became a national and then global media figure. Growing up poor, he
graduated first in his class at Boston Latin and made it through
Harvard in 2 1/2 years. After a brief career as a lawyer, he
returned to his father's theater business.
</P>
<P>
   The famous local story that testified to Redstone's iron will
involved his survival during the 1979 fire at the Copley Plaza
hotel, where he hung on to a third-floor windowsill. Flames burned
his right hand until a fire-engine ladder rose to save him. Burned
on 80 percent of his body, Redstone took a year to recover from his
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, he made it to a national stage and went deep
into debt by spending $3.4 billion for Viacom Inc., a hodgepodge of
cable television assets that included some gems like MTV and
Nickelodeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the guts to go out and leverage up on Viacom when most
people thought he was crazy,'' said investment manager Mario
Gabelli, whose company is the largest institutional investor in
Viacom stock.
</P>
<P>
   But that was nothing compared to the $10 billion Viacom spent to
outduel Barry Diller in a contest to buy Paramount in 1993. Even
Redstone concedes he paid more than he expected because of the
bidding contest, but he insists that the deal eventually turned
into a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone's $8.4 billion acquisition of video rental giant
Blockbuster Entertainment Corp. in 1994 wasn't the highest-priced
piece of the Viacom empire, but it nearly turned out to be the most
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after the deal, Blockbuster was stumbling badly, and
analysts wondered if developing technology like video on demand
would kill the operation. Redstone flew to Dallas and personally
helped redirect Blockbuster toward a revenue-sharing arrangement
with film studios that put more tapes in the stores and helped
revive business.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom spun off part of Blockbuster to the public to reduce debt
last month. The company that Viacom bought for $5.4 billion plus
debt has a current stock market value of about $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom's merger with CBS is Redstone's biggest deal of all.
While many Walt Disney Co. shareholders rumble about their troubles
as owners of the ABC network, Viacom investors generally like the
CBS deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very positive event for CBS and Viacom
shareholders,'' said Roland Gillis of Putnam Investments, the
Boston mutual fund company that invests extensively in media
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Says Gabelli: ``It gives him scale to compete against the giant
companies being put together globally.''
</P>
<P>
   Insiders like Abrams think Redstone will be around for years to
come, as Viacom integrates the CBS business and expands the
company's reach overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for him to retire. He still has a vision of
what's possible out there,'' said Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
