<HEADER>
A4506 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CABLE-MODEM-BOS &LR;      09-08 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-MODEM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT CABLE DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A slowly bubbling national debate over whether and how
high-speed cable modem connections to the Internet should be
regulated promises to be a jackpot for lawyers and spinmeisters.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the wholesome proconsumer slogans being tossed around _
``Open access'' versus ``Hands off the Internet!'' _ some of the
nation's biggest, richest corporations are waging an epic battle
for billions of dollars in the 21st century economy.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a proposed November 2000 ballot question that would
require cable giants such as MediaOne to make their lines available
to all Internet service providers cleared a key hurdle in the Bay
State when Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly gave its supporters
the OK to start collecting signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits over the ballot question seem certain. But in the
meantime, expect to see increasing efforts to make ``open access''
a public issue _ particularly as state and local authorities rule
on transferring ownership of community cable franchises from
MediaOne to AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``As consumers, we should all want this debate to occur,'' said
Boyd Peterson, a telecommunications analyst with The Yankee Group
in Boston. ``The end result will be that the pressure is going to
increase on all the companies involved to roll out these high-speed
broadband services faster.''
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the debate are the Internet service providers
such as America Online, GTE, Baby Bells, and numerous smaller
firms, which all seek access to the high-speed cables beginning to
reach into millions of American homes. On the other are the
companies developing fast cable modem connections, particularly
AT&AMP;T, which is spending $100 billion to take over MediaOne and
cable giant TCI, and sees its rivals as freeloaders. Both sides
have ample funds to throw at advertising campaigns and lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne's RoadRunner and similar services offered in some
communities by RCN, Adelphia Cable, and FrontierVision promise
people an always-on connection to the Internet that can download
Web pages and other data up to 50 times faster than the standard
telephone modem.
</P>
<P>
   Already, MediaOne's inroads making RoadRunner available to more
than 1 million homes in Massachusetts and New Hampshire _ 70,000 of
which have signed up _ have pushed Bell Atlantic to promise to make
its faster Digital Subscriber Line service available throughout
eastern Massachusetts by year end.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, wireless telephone companies and satellite owners are
working at a torrid pace to perfect their own systems to provide
people with high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Either on the state ballot next November, in hearings before
local licensing boards, or perhaps in the Legislature,
Massachusetts residents and officials will have to decide which of
the following statements they agree with:
</P>
<P>
   --In the 1999 economy, Internet access should be regulated the
same way as access to the public telephone network. Cable firms
that have been handed local monopolies to build lucrative networks
can reasonably be required to make deals for ISPs to use those
lines to reach customers, just as Bell Atlantic has had to open
phone lines to rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Or:
</P>
<P>
   --Cable investors have risked billions of dollars upgrading
one-way television lines to carry two-way Net traffic, with no
guarantee they won't be croaked by DSL or wireless and satellite
links. Allowing freeloaders to hijack that investment is an illegal
seizure of private property and will chill investment in all
efforts to build faster Internet links.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Massachusetts ballot question, sponsored by Boston
venture capitalist J. Christopher Grace, would require companies
including MediaOne to allow ISPs to make deals to resell RoadRunner
access to their ports, on ``commercially reasonable terms . . . no
less favorable'' than what MediaOne offers to its affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's effort is modeled on local open-access provisions
enacted earlier this summer in Portland, Ore., and Broward County,
Fla., both of which AT&AMP;T has gone to court to overturn. Canada's
national regulators have also required open access to cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the fight has led to the creation of lavishly funded
lobbying groups on both sides, Hands Off the Internet, whose
backers include AT&AMP;T and Americans for Tax Reform, and the OpenNET
Coalition, started by AOL and now backed as well by MCI WorldCom,
Mindspring, and U S West.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Republican political consultant Charles
Manning is pressing the case for AT&AMP;T and Hands Off the Internet.
Grace's allies include former state consumer affairs chief Paula W.
Gold and publicist Thaleia Tsongas Schlesinger.
</P>
<P>
   The bonanza for the lawyers involved has only just begun. Just
in jousting over whether the open-access question should be
certified for the ballot, attorneys Thomas Kiley for the New
England Cable Television Association and Saul Schapiro for Grace
filed four rounds of letters with Reilly totalling 79
densely-argued pages.
</P>
<P>
   Showing how creatively and aggressively cable firms will seek to
fight the issue, Kiley even cited a 1924 Supreme Judicial Court
case upholding a Boston newspaper's right to refuse state
government advertising as a precedent for forbidding ``open
access'' to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Edward J. Markey of Massachusetts, the ranking
Democrat on the House telecommunications subcommittee, last week
spoke out for ``open, nondiscriminatory broadband access,'' saying
it is the key to fostering even greater Internet growth and price
competition for subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the argument has not swayed the chairman of the
Federal Communications Commission, William E. Kennard, who argues
that the best regulation for the Internet is no regulation, and
allowing a mish-mash of local access policies could create chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot regulate against problems that have yet to
materialize in a market that has yet to develop,'' said Kennard,
who notes that barely 1 million of the 40 million US internet users
have access to broadband links.
</P>
<P>
   ``While some consider cable to have a lead at this time, it is
premature to conclude either that such a lead will last or that its
current position amounts to a monopoly,'' Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said he agrees with top investment bankers who have
argued that FCC regulation of cable Internet connections ``would
chill investment in cable modem service, which in turn would reduce
the competitive pressure on local phone companies and others who
are currently investing in alternative means.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL, with 17 million customers, and other Internet service
providers fear that in time, cable companies could knock them out
of business. They say few people who have the choice would take a
56-kbs telephone connection when they could get a much faster link
through cable.
</P>
<P>
   RoadRunner customers can get an AOL account for an extra $10 a
month or subscribe to any other ISP. But the Oregon federal judge
who upheld Portland's open-access rule, Owen M. Panner, observed in
his ruling that ``few subscribers would pay twice for similar
services.''
</P>
<P>
   And in time, cable rivals fear companies such as AT&AMP;T and
MediaOne would restrict where Web surfers can go, forbidding them,
for example, from downloading movies over the Internet that would
cost $5 to see on a cable pay-per-view channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it creates an unequal playing field, a lack of
consumer choice, and ultimately higher prices for the consumer''
trying to get on the Internet, said J. Scott Marcus, chief
technology officer at GTE Internetworking in Burlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Cable companies say requiring them to let any ISP who wants to
hook up to their system could overwhelm limited transmission
capability and even force them to dump television channels to
accommodate demand. Critics call those technological concerns
vastly overblown, and GTE said a trial with a cable system it owns
in Clearwater, Fla., proves open access is doable.
</P>
<P>
   The cable companies' view of their Internet links could well be
compared to Ronald Reagan's on the Panama Canal: ``We built it, we
own it, it's ours, and we're not going to give it away.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's general counsel, Jim Cicconi, recently said AOL and its
allies are acting as if they ``can sit on the sidelines and let
someone else spend hundreds of billions of dollars and then reap
the gains with no investment cost. Our response is, if AOL wants a
cable network, it can go invest in one itself.''
</P>
<P>
   But Grace said, ``Do we in Massachusetts want 10 or 15 cables
running to every house? Is that their vision of Massachusetts, that
every street is being dug up all the time by companies trying to
install more wires? It just doesn't make any sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-VERMONT-ADOPT-ART-BOS     09-08 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-ADOPT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN VERMONT, HOMES FOR ETHIOPIAN ORPHANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTER, Vt. _ Rocking her granddaughter to sleep, Jayne
Gallagher could hear the raspy, televised voice of Vermont's
governor above the infant's soft breathing: ``Vermont has long been
known as the least diverse state in the nation. That is rapidly
changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Governor Howard Dean's words last year, part of a plea for
enlightened attitudes after several race-related incidents, must
have stirred something in Gallagher, who is white, because soon she
was overseeing an unusual merger of two very different worlds _ one
white and rural, the other African and war-torn.
</P>
<P>
   From the small town of Chester, where residents can drive along
country roads all their lives without encountering a black person,
Gallagher started the Ethiopian Adoption Project. Dozens of
families from across the whitest state in the nation have agreed to
adopt 60 children orphaned by Ethiopia's war with neighboring
Eritrea. Gallagher expects the first group of children to begin
arriving in Vermont by December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought: What a loving way to diversify Vermont,'' Gallagher
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her mission of mercy, though, has rekindled an emotional debate
over whether children are hurt when they are adopted across racial
and cultural lines. To Gallagher, it matters only that the
children, who have seen their parents die in what is being dubbed
as the world's bloodiest war, have a home and love.
</P>
<P>
   But Rudolph Smith, president of the Association of Black Social
Workers, fears that Ethiopians being brought to live in a culture
as white as Vermont will be stripped of their self-identity.
``Ethiopia is an African culture with black Africans, and Vermont
is a lily, lily white state,'' he said. ``You are going to have a
whole bunch of black children running around who don't know who
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermont's black population of an estimated 3,102 in 1997, which
has never tipped over 1 percent, could easily fit in Boston
University's Walter Brown Arena with room to spare. But as the
state experiences a small but noticeable increase of black and
Asian residents within the past decade, it has also begun to
grapple with race-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be easy,'' said Joe Kroll, whose adopted Korean
daughter Mei Lin, now 22, gives speeches on how hard it was to grow
up in a white world and retain her self-identity.
</P>
<P>
   Kroll, executive director of the North American Council of
Adoptable Children, based in St. Paul, said Vermont parents will
struggle with protecting their children and teaching them to
embrace their own culture. ``The sign of a successful interracial
placement is if the child has a strong and healthy self-esteem and
identity toward their own culture or race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite skepticism, even from adoption agencies that warned that
white families do not normally adopt African children, Gallagher
received dozens of responses within days of placing ads in the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Chatot was one of those callers. For three years,
Chatot and her husband, Paul, a nurse, have wanted to adopt a
child, but finances have prevented them from doing so. But shortly
after Chatot, 40, the mother of two teenagers, read in the
newspaper about Gallagher's efforts and the low cost of the
adoption, she accompanied Gallagher on a plane to Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was the right thing to do,'' said Chatot of her
plans to adopt a 4-year-old Ethiopian boy.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chatot, Gallagher, and school officials say they do not
see the color of a person's skin, Smith and even multiracial
adoption proponents say it is because they never had to: Most of
the schools in Chester have few if any minority children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vermont is not Utopia. There is a resistance and the lack of
acknowledgment that it could be racist,'' said one white mother
whose adopted daughter is black.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who asked not to be identified for fear of her
daughter being taunted more, said the child has had problems in the
school district. She said the family is considering moving from
Windsor County to a more diversified area.
</P>
<P>
   Black and Asian students have always stood out in Vermont.
Nearly 15 years ago, when 18 black basketball players from Boston
got off a bus at Green Mountain Union High School in Chester, it
sent dozens of white children to the school window in awe, said Jim
Collins, one of the school's administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher said her goal is to find adoptive families in Ethiopia
for the 20,000 orphans. Meanwhile, communities such as Chester,
Norwich, Brattleboro, and White River Junction, as well as some New
Hampshire towns, are working to bring a piece of Ethiopia to
northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   International festivals are being planned, a local therapist has
volunteered to counsel the families, and local Ethiopians have
agreed to make frequent visits to provide lessons on the African
culture, such as how to cook injera, an Ethiopian staple that
resembles a spongy bread.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 23 of nearly 60 Vermont families _ professionals,
working-class, and single parents _ have completed a state and
immigration process to adopt 29 children. Gallagher, who has used
her own money to set up the program and for travel, has a local
adoption agency called Adoption Advocates Inc. as the international
license holder. She is awaiting a license from The Children and
Youth Administration in Addis Ababa, the capital of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   According to an Ethiopian government spokesman, Ethiopians
prefer that their children remain within their own culture. ``But I
think we have to look at it from the interest of the babies. In
Ethiopia we have one policy: Adoptions are done for children that
do not have any choices,'' said Tsegay Wolde-Georgis of the
Ethiopian Embassy in Washington. ``The option between being adopted
by a loving family, whoever he is, and being a street child is a
very easy answer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kevin Christie, the only black school administrator in
Vermont and a resident of White River Junction, said racism can be
subtle and the old ways of thinking can be hard to shake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will probably be difficult for them,'' he said. But
Collins, the administrator who may soon have two Ethiopians at the
high school, which has only one black student registered this fall,
thinks it will help open the minds of the isolated rural students
who often hold stereotypes of people different from them.
</P>
<P>
   When Chatot, who works for a pregnancy program, traveled to
Ethiopia, she said the only difference she saw between Vermont and
Ethiopia was the extreme poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The children, who are living in an orphanage in Tigre, have
survived bombings but have watched their parents become victims of
the war. To remind herself of their plight, Gallagher brought the
tattered clothing of some of the orphans who struggle daily to keep
warm and fed.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, where many families make their living from farming,
the next day's meal can be as close as the backyard chicken coop.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, a fat child would be more discriminated against
than a person of a different race,'' said Gallagher, who will take
in two teenage boys.
</P>
<P>
   While that statement might seem naive in a country seemingly
obsessed with race, state officials such as Kathy Huit of the
governor's office said the comment embraces the accepting spirit
that has long been part of Vermont's history, the first state to
ban slavery in its constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vermont has prided itself on its history of tolerance,'' she
said. ``And the governor is making sure we look at the issue of
diversity. He's made it his commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Vermont can be accepting, but there is still that
element of ignorance,'' Christie said. The adoptive parents ``will
need support.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently he had several students prosecuted at Randolph Area
Vocation Center, where he is the administrator, for spray-painting
racial epithets on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Christie, whose wife is white, has 26 years of living in Vermont
to teach him how to survive in an all-white environment. He picks
his battles, and matter-of-factly drives three hours to his native
Hartford, Conn., to buy black hair-care products. Those skills were
passed along to his daughter, and he hopes Vermonters will pass
them to the new immigrants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4509 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-UPN-HNS &LR;      09-08 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-UPN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPN BOSS ISN'T WORRIED ABOUT THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dean Valentine is upbeat. He's confident. He's spewing numbers.
A lot of other people may be thinking ``Dead Man Walking,'' but
Valentine is having no part of it.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the theory that UPN, the network that Valentine
heads, is about to disappear in Viacom Inc.'s planned acquisition
of CBS Corp. Viacom is the parent company of UPN, Paramount
Television Group, Paramount Pictures and other ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom still says that unless the government has a
fairly major change of heart, UPN will be the biggest casualty.
That's because no one _ not even corporate giants like Sumner
Redstone of Viacom and Mel Karmazin of CBS _ can own two television
networks. The rules call for divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   So what's it going to be _ the Tiffany Network or UPN, the
country's sixth-ranked network in a four-network race? Both, says
Valentine, ever the optimist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel and Sumner are incredibly enthusiastic about the prospect
of owning two TV networks,'' Valentine said. ``They want this thing
to work. They're going to go to Washington and get a waiver.
They're committed to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would the Federal Communications Commission tell two people
who just merged $36 billion that the rules no longer apply to them?
Chances are they won't. But Valentine has an interesting theory on
why they will: Diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC, he said, wants television to better reflect the ethnic
makeup of the country. If you just woke up from a coma, you may not
be aware that this fall's TV season will look like ``The Waltons''
got themselves cloned. UPN is the only network that has launched
truly ethnic shows this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only one committed to that, the only one with
diversity in our programming, the only one committed to ethnic
casting. We're going to let that network die?'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   While UPN has certainly led the field in that area, the networks
got a proper scolding from the NAACP recently and are, in droves,
reworking many of their fall shows in an effort to provide minority
parts. Too little too late, surely, but the FCC may take that as
good faith.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if it allows Viacom-CBS to own two networks, that could
be a dangerous precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Valentine said he's excited about what his network is
primed to do, citing the fact that UPN is already making huge
ratings turnarounds in total viewers and prime demographics, with
only two of its five nights rolled out for the fall season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a buzz on Madison Avenue,'' he said, noting
that advertisers like the fact that UPN is going after young males,
primarily with action shows, wrestling and guy-oriented comedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real need for what we're providing,'' Valentine
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though some may doubt a need for ``WWF Smackdown,'' the deal
makes a lot of sense for CBS, which couldn't draw a young audience
if it ran an all-nude ``Touched By An Angel.'' With UPN as a
partner, CBS would then be much better represented demographically.
And that means a lot more money. And money is why this whole thing
got started.
</P>
<P>
   There are not going to be any answers soon about the
ramifications of this deal. But UPN certainly looks to be the
biggest casualty of the merger. Despite the early ratings success
that Valentine noted, UPN is still bleeding money in a very bad
way.
</P>
<P>
   The question for viewers is this: Can you do without ``Moesha''
or ``Dilbert''? Can the television industry afford to lose a
network that has the most African-American programming?
</P>
<P>
   Valentine is not worried about the future of his network. He
sees wrestling in the picture _ going strong, gaining viewers. He
sees ``Shasta McNasty'' debuting at the end of the month (and he
says it'll be a hit). And he sees a wide range of ethnically
diverse shows in the UPN tradition. Where others can't see a
future, he sees a need.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
