<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM TAPS CAPE   COD'S FRENCH CONNECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLEANS, Mass. _ The electrician's pipe and tobacco sit on a
roll-top desk as though he might retrieve them at any minute. The
old brass and wood instruments, with such odd names as
galvanometer, remain perfectly undisturbed. The yellowed calendar
is still turned to Nov. 26, 1959, when the place closed for good.
</P>
<P>
   For 68 years, employees of the Compagnie Francaise des Cables
Telegraphiques telegraphed news to and from France, from stock
trades to the German invasion of France, from this modest white
clapboard house. On overwhelmingly Anglophile Cape Cod, it was a
rare French outpost, and the raison d'etre of a tiny French
community here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still go in there and almost visualize my father sitting
behind the table tapping away,'' said Lucien Ozon, a retired police
lieutenant whose father, Clement, was a telegraph operator in the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   But the ham radio operators, descendants of the cable men, and
other volunteers who keep the French Cable Station Museum going
can't seem to interest the world in their quirky story. With no aid
from governments or nonprofit foundations, they get by on a minimal
budget, attracting just a few hundred visitors a year, far fewer
than the Marconi Wireless Station down the road in Wellfleet that
helped put the telegraph station out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest problem is just getting people to know we're
here,'' said Jerry Downs, chairman of the museum board and the
grandson of a 19th-century station operator, an Englishman named
Thomas Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the French connection in Orleans is a bigger deal on
the tiny island of St. Pierre in Canada's Gulf of St. Lawrence _
part of France despite its location _ than it is here. Thirteen
cable station workers came from St. Pierre, and when Orleans
residents visited the island in 1988, the mayor and other
dignitaries turned out to greet them.
</P>
<P>
   Now the museum is trying to raise its US profile, doubling
membership to 156 over the last year, attracting its first
corporate sponsor, and trying to convince anyone that will listen
that it is the steward of an important chapter in
telecommunications history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the high-tech industry of its day,'' Downs said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the French trailed their English rivals in a technology
race in 1879 when the French cable company completed a
trans-Atlantic telegraph cable from Brest, France, through St.
Pierre, to North Eastham. Initially, the only trained cable
operators were English, forcing the French to hire them. But within
a few years, the cable station was importing staff from St. Pierre.
</P>
<P>
   The cable company moved to downtown Orleans in 1891 after
workers' families complained that Eastham was too isolated. Four
cable men's homes were relocated to Orleans, becoming the
cornerstone of a French community of 40 or 50 people with such
names as Norgeot, Deschamps, and Ozon who still trace their roots
to St. Pierre.
</P>
<P>
   Ozon acknowledges that the French community here does little to
promote its heritage aside from the trip to St. Pierre. But he said
they are proud of the station's role in history and proud of the
French tricolor flag flying in front of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more interested in it now than I was 47 years ago, when I
first came here'' from St. Pierre as a child, Ozon said.
</P>
<P>
   Once, the Morse code messages transmitted from the station were
as important as the Internet is today, providing a secure line
during World War I for US commanders to communicate with President
Wilson and bringing word that Charles Lindbergh had completed his
solo trans-Atlantic flight to Paris in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   During the German invasion of France in 1940, French telegraph
operators got off one last message from Brest as German sailors
approached: ``Here Come the Bosch. God help us.''
</P>
<P>
   But the emergence of radio and wireless telegraphs eroded the
importance of cables. On Nov. 26, 1959, the Orleans crew signed off
for good with a ``Happy Thanksgiving'' and the operators walked out
the door without so much as tidying up the place.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the station sat empty, in part because of President
Charles de Gaulle's determination not to sell French assets. Museum
guide Laurence Gray, an engineer by profession, was turned down by
the French cable company in the 1960s when he inquired about buying
some of the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   DeGaulle ``said no French territory is going to be sold to an
American as long as I am alive,'' Gray recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Even after de Gaulle's death in 1970, however, Orleans residents
didn't want the building, repeatedly voting down money for the
purchase at Town Meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, 10 people came up with $40,000 to buy the station,
beating out an oil company that wanted to build a gas station, and
started the museum in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Today, aside from vintage photos, news clips, and assorted other
memorabilia, the cable station is virtually unchanged from its last
day of operation. The typewriter that rendered letters into Morse
code still works, as does the grandfather clock; the screws and
wires still sit in drawers carefully labeled in French and English.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have strict orders from the boss: Don't move anything,''
Gray said, referring to Downs. ``I would like to clean the place
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the museum couldn't afford to do much more than clean
the place up anyway. It relies on member dues and the occasional
inheritance, and Downs said the group spends so little money that
he doesn't even prepare an annual budget. Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   That's just fine with the telecommunications junkies who can
make sense of equipment labeled with descriptions such as
``potentiometer divider for capacitance test.'' In a world where
communications is changing rapidly, they marvel at a place that
stays the same.
</P>
<P>
   But Downs wants a larger audience, the kind of people who read
Yankee Magazine or want an indoor activity for rainy summer days,
but they are hard to reach without money for publicity or
professional management.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pride in their roots, many descendants of the cable
men have not pitched in at the station. Ozon says he is too busy
with his limousine business to be involved, while his brother,
Clement, admits he has not been in the station since it closed.
</P>
<P>
   As the volunteers reduce their museum hours for the fall, they
are grateful for the 360 or so visitors so far this year but are
convinced that they should be more popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly not state of the art,'' said museum volunteer
Henry Fales, sniffing the musty air. ``But you know what's nice
about it? This is one of the few museums you can come in and smell
the stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
