<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4515 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-PROFILE-KUMALO-2TAKES     09-08 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-KUMALO-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEARING WITNESS IN BLACK AND WHITE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WIL HAYGOOD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VATON, South Africa _ He'd rise early to catch the morning
light. It would just start rolling, waves and waves of it. It could
look so beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Then he'd march off into the awful pain of it all.
</P>
<P>
   The little kids being shot.
</P>
<P>
   The tanks smashing homes.
</P>
<P>
   The hordes of people being lined up and handcuffed because they
didn't have their passbooks. The police would grab you right from
the trains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to wake up very early and come to the train stations,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he'd rush into it having forgotten his own passbook _
the little book every black was forced to carry when traveling _
but he had to get his pictures. And when he was ghosting himself
into position, scuffing his knees, clutching his cameras and then
shooting, all the scariness and the numbing fear of it seemed to
just fall away.
</P>
<P>
   The outside world called it apartheid. To him, it was just life.
It was right outside the front door.
</P>
<P>
   He got Nelson Mandela _ sipping tea, grinning at home, just a
man _ before he vanished, sight unseen, and started rattling
history.
</P>
<P>
   He got Robert F. Kennedy atop an auto, extending a hand, leaning
from the hood of a car right there in Soweto. There's a skyful of
sky in the photo. It looks as if Kennedy has just dropped from the
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Click.
</P>
<P>
   He got two young black boys lying in the dirt in front of a
tank.
</P>
<P>
   Just two dead black boys to the white government.
</P>
<P>
   Click.
</P>
<P>
   Actually he couldn't get that photo published, at least not
right away. Just too explosive.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he had to blink the blood out of his own eyes. Yet
another ruffian from the security forces had slapped him with a
baton. The only thing to do was pull himself up, wipe away the
blood, and aim.
</P>
<P>
   Click, click.
</P>
<P>
   He got Muhammad Ali in the jungle and thought he was in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Alf Kumalo. He might be the greatest living
photographer in all of South Africa. The Italians think so.
Leonardo Arte publishers, based in Milan, has just published a
collection of his work. Its five decades worth of work. A man's
pictures; a man's life. Its titled, simply, ``Alf Kumalo.''
</P>
<P>
   Itala Vivan, a professor at the University of Milan who, along
with Enrico Dodi, has championed Kumalo _ has written a rather
eloquent forward to the book, the text of which is in Italian and
English. ``A more moving history book, perhaps, than any ever
written in words,'' she writes, ``moving as only images can be, by
the immediacy with which they strike the consciousness and their
deceptive physicality, their disquieting materiality.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The photographer's 70 years old now. He moves like a man walking
through water. But he's always moved slowly, say those who knew him
in the old days.
</P>
<P>
   A good amount of his work in the past was for The Star, in
Johannesburg. But he's a photographer for hire now, retired from
magazines and newspapers. Weddings are not beneath him. The bills
have to be paid.
</P>
<P>
   He spent a good deal of his youth in Alexandra, one of the
harshest of this country's townships. ``The worst gangsters came
from Alexandra,'' he remembers. ``They were called the Spoilers.''
</P>
<P>
   The white government rolled into Alexandra one day in the early
'60s and snatched up 20 of the Spoilers. Hanged every one of them
from the gallows over in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
   Kumalo's father was a builder, his mother a maid. There was
plenty of love in that house, but not one camera. After high school
he got a job as a clerk for a car company. ``That was a very good
job in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Photography intrigued him, so he bought a cheap camera. He
taught himself by reading instructions printed inside boxes of
film. ``I would follow the directions as to how much sunlight you
needed,'' he remembers. A lot of the photos were ruined. He was
learning. He bought an exposure meter. But natural light fascinated
him more than anything. So he tossed the meter. ``Even now,'' he
says, ``I don't like using flash very much. If I have to, I prefer
to bounce flash. You bounce it off the ceiling and use it.''
</P>
<P>
   He saved up enough money from his clerk's job to take a gamble.
The gamble was to quit and begin freelancing.
</P>
<P>
   There was a section of Johannesburg called Sophiatown. It was
all black. It was straw hats and satin skirts and horn blowing. It
was high culture. Sophiatown was the pre-Mandela Johannesburg that
the world never quite noticed. Kumalo took his cameras to
Sophiatown. He snapped musical events. He snapped folk at the
racetrack. He snapped lovers idling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a great market for private pictures,'' he says.
``Every Sunday I was occupied _ weddings, parties, social
functions.''
</P>
<P>
   He wore lovely tweeds, single-breasted suits. ``When I took up
photography, photographers used to dress in suits,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He found newspapers hard to crack. Then someone at one
publication, the Bantu World, saw his pictures and printed them. So
he cracked his way inside. ``To see your name in the paper was
very, very special.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1948 the National Party, a whites-only party, came to power.
It eventually split the country racially. Families were torn apart.
Blacks were sent on long voyages to other parts of the country.
Blacks were frequently detained for long periods without trial.
There were protests, but then men and women and children would
vanish. The darkness had begun. And it would deepen.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were young journalists,'' recalls Aggrey Klaaste, who
met Kumalo in the late 1940s in Soweto, ``apartheid was just
becoming a force. They had a prohibition against liquor. We drank
to defy the law. Many who drank were some of the best writers in
the country. There was a kind of Harlem Renaissance. Those guys
really put the booze away. Throughout all of this, Alf never
touched the stuff. We said, `Come on Alf, drink.' He didn't. He
took all the insults and just did his work.''
</P>
<P>
   His work was in the fields, exposing children working at hard
labor.
</P>
<P>
   His work was in the townships during the midnight raids.
</P>
<P>
   His work was sneaking into the mines to report on mine
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   He'd be walking around, and sometimes the trucks would appear, a
swirl of dust and police. The police would start checking
passbooks. He'd be arrested. There were times when, soon as the
officers would turn their backs, he'd walk away. He'd be dressed
beautifully. He looked like a preacher. You had to be cool. It took
nerves of steel.
</P>
<P>
   The African National Congress _ black men, Indians, women, a few
whites _ intended to fight apartheid in the courts. One of its
chief recruiters was Walter Sisulu. He brought in a young lawyer by
the name of Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   So the brewing had begun.
</P>
<P>
   Kumalo got himself a job at Drum magazine. Drum was avant-garde.
It had a wondrous team of writers and photographers. There were
poets who carried thick American novels under their arms. Jim
Bailey, liberal and white, founded Drum.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Kumalo, like every other black journalist and photographer
in South Africa, found himself in the thick of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible country, in terms of apartheid,'' he says,
``but you could walk anywhere with your cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   He won a car in a photography contest in 1963. It was an Austin
Cambridge. It was beautiful. He rolled everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   And he started hanging out with the young Nelson Mandela. It was
just a hunch. ``We didn't have too many lawyers,'' he says of
Mandela. ``I followed him more than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela started secretly raising money for the ANC. The
authorities went looking for him. He was here one moment, there the
next, impossible to find. Finally, a group of ANC officials were in
and out of court on charges of treason for five years, beginning in
1956.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great story to cover,'' says Kumalo. ``I actually
took a leave to cover it. That's why I still have my pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   They were finally acquitted in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
