u e BC-PROFILE-KUMALO-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     09-08 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-KUMALO-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 VATON, South Africa: ... in 1961.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They started calling Nelson Mandela ``the black pimpernel.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1961 ANC court victory was huge, but the National Party
would not relent. They brought more charges. They hunted Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963 he was tried again, along with other ANC stalwarts _
Sisulu, Govan Mbeki, Ahmed Kathrada, and Raymond Mhlaba among them.
Kumalo was there every day. He'd escort Mandela's mother to court.
Then he would go to work, clicking away.
</P>
<P>
   He got Winnie Mandela outside the courtroom _ looking elegant,
though pained _ wearing something flowery, wearing a felt hat,
carrying a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela and the others were convicted. Kumalo's photographs of
the trial were published around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The ANC stalwarts escaped the gallows, but not a lifetime on the
rocks at Robben Island, the country's infamous penitentiary.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela disappeared. Unseen and unheard from, he would turn into
myth.
</P>
<P>
   Kumalo kept shooting. ``He was very brave and resilient,'' says
Itala Vivan, the Italian professor who has steeped herself in South
African history of the period.
</P>
<P>
   For years and years, the world did not condemn South Africa's
misery.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the incredible thing,'' says David Hazelhurst, an
editor at Drum in those early years who worked alongside Kumalo.
``You didn't have world support.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazelhurst watched every day as the National Party tightened its
grip. Just to survive, a photographer had to be crafty. ``It was
incredible to me to work with someone like Alf Kumalo,'' he says.
``He's got charm but an iron courage behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kumalo was arrested at a demonstration in 1963. A policeman told
him to hold the damn cameras so that he could make another arrest.
Kumalo, handcuffed, bravely started clicking. He got the photos
published too.
</P>
<P>
   He wore shirts with a hidden pocket at the bottom of them. When
roughed up by police for his film, he'd hold his hands on the
camera and let slip out a meaningless role of film from under his
shirt.
</P>
<P>
   He kept negatives in several safe houses in and around Soweto.
He doesn't know how many might have been lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``People actually wanted me to leave photography for politics,''
Kumalo says. ``But I said, `What I'm doing _ documenting lives _ is
politics.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There were many arrests over the years. His first one was for
being caught in Johannesburg at night without his passbook. He was
with two colleagues. He wanted to whip the white policeman; his
friends thought he was crazy. After three days they were released.
</P>
<P>
   He loaded the cameras and started aiming again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Freedom was one big dream for the black South African
journalists. For many, getting to America was another. One of the
gifted young photographers who made it out was Ernest Cole.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, after several months of waiting, Kumalo got a visa for
America. You never knew why you were given a visa, or, if turned
down, why you were denied.
</P>
<P>
   He landed in New York City. ``America just blows your mind.''
Harlem sucked him in. He walked everywhere. He knocked on doors. He
knocked on the door of Gordon Parks, the great photographer and
film director. ``He gave me all kinds of books,'' Kumalo says of
Parks.
</P>
<P>
   He would travel in and out of America more than once during the
eclectic '70s. He was a maniac for jazz and tracked down Ornette
Coleman, Duke Ellington, Ella Fitzgerald. He snapped away. He got
to Louis Armstrong. He found the pianist Oscar Peterson giving a
concert in Central Park. ``Meeting those guys to me was very
special. I had read about them and they seemed out of reach. It was
lovely.''
</P>
<P>
   He knocked on the door of Miles Davis's Riverside Drive
apartment. A notice was on the door. It said if it's about
business, call the office. ``But I was so keen to see the guy I
pressed the bell. A lady appeared and said, `Can't you read?' ''
Kumalo told the lady to tell Davis that he had come all the way
from South Africa, and that he brought greetings from Hugh
Masekela, the South African musician. Davis sent back a note: ``You
and Hugh Masekela can go to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Miles was Miles.
</P>
<P>
   But the photographer moved on. In that noisy naked city, there
were a thousand people to see, a thousand photos to take.
</P>
<P>
   He got Ali fighting at Madison Square Garden in 1974. (He also
shot the celebrated Ali-Foreman battle that year in Zaire. ``It was
great,'' he says. ``It was an event put totally together by blacks.
I felt very proud. I had two seats for the fight. One at ringside,
and one up in the stands.'')
</P>
<P>
   He hung out with Aretha Franklin when she was giving a weeklong
concert at the Apollo in Harlem. Fell in love with Aretha.
</P>
<P>
   He found Ernest Cole, the South African exile, a boon buddy from
Johannesburg, and a great photographer in his own right, in Harlem.
They went out shooting together. They stopped in front of some
police officers. A fire in a building was raging. Kumalo started
snapping. He got close to a police officer with a gun hanging out
and thought he could get some kind of artsy shot of the gun.
``Ernest says to me, `Man, the police will shoot you here quicker
than they will in South Africa.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He went to Louisville _ uninvited and unannounced _ got himself
a room at the Y and photographed the funeral of civil rights leader
Whitney Young.
</P>
<P>
   He went down to Atlanta, to Martin Luther King Jr.'s church, and
started clicking.
</P>
<P>
   When Kumalo returned to South Africa, he could feel the anger as
never before. His country was about to erupt.
</P>
<P>
   He photographed the dead in Soweto during the 1976 student
uprising. In the end, more than 600 died.
</P>
<P>
   He got Steve Biko, the martyr, at one of those secret meetings
that could have gotten you whipped and jailed just for attending.
</P>
<P>
   The police raided the photographer's house in Soweto on several
occasions. One raid resulted in a three-year prison sentence _
something about taking unauthorized photos. The charges were
dropped on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes other photographers would follow Kumalo. They'd tell
one another they wanted to be there when he got killed, because
those were the days when photographers got killed. ``Alf would go
to the hostels and the police would chase him,'' says Klaaste,
Kumalo's colleague from the 1940s. ``He was absolutely brave.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He still prefers shooting in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   He still uses the Nikon F3.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to open a photography studio in Soweto. A place the
kids can come for training.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old war-torn country. It's rife with aches and pains.
And yet: ``I'm happy I was born here,'' Kumalo says, standing in
the garden of his fine home, 20 miles outside of Johannesburg, a
camera around his neck. A mere six years ago he would have been
arrested for being in this neighborhood at night. ``I'm happy I'm
African.''
</P>
<P>
   He's married to Modiegi, his second wife. In all, there are
eight children.
</P>
<P>
   He's never had an exhibition in America. He wishes for one.
</P>
<P>
   After the opening of his exhibiton in Milan, the curators _
Noris Lazzarini and Monica Fresco _ took Kumalo out to eat. His
photos that were hanging in the hall were normal, small
exhibition-size photos. While he was dining, Kumalo's photos were
replaced with life-size reproductions.
</P>
<P>
   Gazing around the exhibition hall upon his return, he was
stunned. He couldn't move. All the hard, blinding, desperate years,
right in front of him. His country's life; his own life. The old
photographer started weeping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
