<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4523 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-POTTER-ART-BOS &LR;      09-08 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-POTTER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGE OF HARRY POTTER BOOKS MAY CHANGE PUBLISHNG INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (f and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Beatles once owned the music charts 30 years ago, Harry
Potter books now dominate the Amazon.com bestseller list, holding
the list's top three spots at times over the last week.
</P>
<P>
   And that was before the third book in the series, ``Harry Potter
and the Prisoner of Azkaban'' went on sale at US bookstores today
(Sept. 8).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like this,'' says Terri Schmitz,
owner of the Children's Book Shop in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Created by author J.K. Rowling, Harry Potter may be more than a
fictional boy wizard whose adventures beguile children and adults
alike; the Potter books are also an Internet phenomenon, one that
may change the way books are marketed and sold, and one that has
given some British Internet booksellers an advantage over
brick-and-mortar rivals in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Cambridge, Mass., WordsWorth Books is ready for ``Harry
Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban.''
</P>
<P>
   WordsWorth is treating the book's release in much the same way
that other retailers once promoted the debut of a Michael Jackson
album or of Windows 95. For the first time in its history, plans
called for WordsWorth to open just after midnight to handle an
expected crush of Harry Potter fans.
</P>
<P>
   But some US readers already have the book, which has been
available in Rowling's native Britain for several months. They
bought their copies from on-line bookstores based in England, such
as the the British Web site run by Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Any US retailer that sold ``The Prisoner of Azkaban'' before the
official release date could be penalized. But such legal restraints
don't apply to purchases made by Americans at British on-line
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Some Harry Potter sales have been diverted from the
book's American publisher and US retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could mean an incredible loss of sales for us,'' says
WordsWorth general manager Sanj Kharbanda, though he still expects
the new Harry Potter to be a big seller for the store.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, publishers bought rights to a book country by
country, and a book could have more than one publisher.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, a publisher had a monopoly on a book within a certain
territory. But thanks to the Internet, a book can be almost
instantly available anywhere in the world, and readers in one
country can buy it from a Web site in another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Territorial rights no longer mean what they used to,'' says
Wayne ``Rusty'' Drugan, executive director of the New England
Booksellers Association. ``Either the law has to change, or
practices have to be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology has changed the playing field,'' laments chief
executive Avin Mark Domnitz of the American Booksellers
Association. The Internet is changing ``all the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter's success has been so extraordinary it's hard to
say what lasting impact it may have on international publishing and
on books that don't inspire similar zeal among readers.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like the Harry Potter phenomenon has ever happened
before, notes executive director Caron Chapman of the Association
of Booksellers for Children.
</P>
<P>
   Written by a first-time author who only a few years ago was the
British equivalent of a welfare mother, Harry Potter stories
``caught everyone by surprise,'' Chapman says.
</P>
<P>
   That won't happen again, she says. Better planning and more
foresight should prevent a recurrence of sales leaking away from US
retailers to British Web sites, she says.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Rowling's series _ ``Harry Potter and the
Sorcerer's Stone,'' ``Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets,''
and now ``Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban'' _ have been
published by Scholastic Inc. of New York.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago Scholastic was hinting about possible lawsuits
over Internet sales, but now it downplays the impact of Americans
buying Harry Potter books from British on-line retailers supplied
by Rowling's British publisher.
</P>
<P>
   At most, Americans bought 30,000 copies of the first two Harry
Potter books from British Web sites; taken in the context of more
than 3.5 million copies sold by Scholastic in the United States,
that's a mere pin prick, the company insists.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, stories about Americans hunting Harry Potter books down
on the Internet only add to the boy wizard's mystique and help
create a marketing buzz that boosts Scholastic's sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every book publisher should have such a problem,'' says
Scholastic executive vice president Barbara Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   It's the lag time between a book's British release and its US
release that gives British Web sites their opening. That lag time
was a year for the first Harry Potter book, seven months for the
second, and two months for the third.
</P>
<P>
   Four more Harry Potter books are planned, and those future books
will be released almost simultaneously in Britain and the United
States, Scholastic says.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Amazon.com makes no apologies for selling copies
of Harry Potter to US consumers at its British Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is comparable to an American tourist shopping at a
London bookstore, then bringing a book back home, says Amazon.com
spokesman Paul Capelli.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is operating in a global economy, and the Internet
is changing how things are done,'' Capelli says. ``As a retailer,
we operate within the law and do what's right. We will continue to
look to serve our customers as best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Internet has changed Harry Potter, Harry Potter has
changed the economics of selling children's books.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter has transformed Rowling into the rarest of writers,
an author of children's books who generates sales that a Tom Clancy
or a Stephen King might envy.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter has ``crossed gender and age,'' even adults are
enchanted, says Kharbanda of WordsWorth Books.
</P>
<P>
   Such best-selling authors as Clancy and King drive sales at
bookstores with a largely adult clientele. But a children's
bookstore relies more on perennials, parents buying childhood
favorites for their own kids _ ``Make Way for Ducklings,'' maybe,
or E.B. White's ``Charlotte's Web.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Charlotte's Web'' was the last book before Harry
Potter to spend more than a few weeks on the bestseller list,
according to the New York Times, and ``Charlotte's Web'' was a
bestseller in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   For bookstores aimed at children, the new Harry Potter book
should be a godsend. But because of the Internet, it doesn't seem
to be working out that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practically everyone I talk to already has the third book,''
says Schmitz of the Children's Book Shop.
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade, independent stores have been under siege,
first from superstores such as a Barnes &AMP; Noble with their coffee
bars and music sections. Then came the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon.com and superstores have really taken a toll,'' Schmitz
says.
</P>
<P>
   Superstores can offer lower prices, but Schmitz tries to offer
more expertise. Every member of her staff is a specialist in
children's literature, she says.
</P>
<P>
   So far, that formula has held up, but it doesn't help when some
Internet booksellers get first crack at selling a blockbuster such
as Harry Potter.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kharbanda, WordsWorth inspires nearly the same
devotion from its customers as Rowling does from her readers.
</P>
<P>
   But when British copies of ``The Prisoner of Azkaban'' can be
had on the Internet before the book goes on sale at US bookstores,
that devotion can be put to the test.
</P>
<P>
   Kharbanda says, ``Even customers who've been totally loyal to
Wordsworth just couldn't wait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
