A4525 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-PHILLIES-H     09-08 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PHILLIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PHILADELPHIA _ Lucky for the Astros the division championship isn't
determined on style points.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ken Caminiti hit a tie-breaking two-run single in the ninth
inning Tuesday night as the Astros won their fifth straight game,
beating the Philadelphia Phillies 8-6 before a crowd of 12,934 at
Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros increased their lead in the National League Central
to three games over second-place Cincinnati, which split a
doubleheader at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In what is developing into a nasty trend, the Astros spotted the
Phillies an early four-run lead for the second straight game. But
instead of needing runs in bunches, the Astros slowly chipped away
at the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took a 6-5 lead, their first of the game, in the
seventh, fell back into a tie a half-inning later and finally
needed some late-inning heroics from Caminiti and the bullpen to
improve to 5-0 on the current seven-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning covers up a lot of things. Tonight it covered up an
awful lot,'' said Astros manager Larry Dierker, whose club stranded
15 runners. ``I wouldn't nominate it for best game of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Phillies used seven pitchers and issued 11 walks
in losing for the 11th time in their last 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind by four runs in the third inning, the
Astros scored in five of the last six innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, Craig Biggio reached on a fielder's choice and
Matt Mieske hit a bloop single to shallow center field off Wayne
Gomes (4-5). One out later, Caminiti singled to right field for the
game-winning runs.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Powell (5-4) pitched 1 innings for the victory, and Doug
Henry got three outs for his 80th career save and first of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch hitting for Daryle Ward in the seventh inning, Ryan
Thompson hit his first home run of the season, putting the Astros
ahead 6-5 with his shot off Amaury Telemaco. It was the second
consecutive game the Astros had taken a lead on a pinch-hit homer,
following Russ Johnson's three-run blast that beat the Phillies on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia tied the game when reliever Jay Powell walked Kevin
Jordan with the bases loaded in the bottom of the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies outfielder Bobby Abreu went 2-for-3, which included his
20th home run of the season, and drove in four runs. Ricky
Gutierrez went 2-for-4 with two RBIs for the Astros. Tony Eusebio
and Caminiti also had two hits.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia built a four-run lead in the third inning with four
hits off Astros righthander Chris Holt, who left the game after
five innings with stiffness in his back. Marlon Anderson led off
with a single to left field, advanced to second on a wild pitch and
scored on a single by Alex Arias. Later in the inning, Doug
Glanville beat out an infield single, and two batters later, Abreu
launched a three-run homer to straightaway center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros sliced the lead in the fourth when Derek Bell hit a
two-out double and Phillies righthander Mike Grace walked Ward and
Eusebio to load the bases. Gutierrez lined a two-run single to
center field to pull the Astros within 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later, the Astros capitalized on a walk and two errors
for their third run of the game. Biggio drew a leadoff walk and
stopped halfway to second on an attempted steal. But Phillies
catcher Mike Lieberthal overthrew second base, and Biggio scored
easily when Glanville let the ball roll to the wall in center
field. The bad throw snapped a 100-game errorless streak for
Lieberthal, the longest by a catcher this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falling behind on both nights 4-0 isn't the way we want to be
playing the last month, but with the character of this team we know
we have a job to do,'' Gutierrez said. ``The last two games, we
showed we can come back from a deficit and don't panic. We just
take it inning by inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros fell behind 4-0 after four innings Monday before a
six-run sixth inning rallied them to a 6-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia added a run in the fifth on back-to-back doubles by
Rob Ducey and Abreu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pick my pitches right, especially to Abreu,'' said
Holt, who allowed five runs and eight hits over five innings. ``You
take away that (third) inning, and things are completely different.
Bottom line is we won the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros twice loaded the bases off Phillies reliever Steve
Schrenk in the sixth inning, coming away with two runs to tie the
score at 5. Gutierrez singled, Carlos Hernandez reached on a
fielder's choice, and Biggio walked. Bill Spiers, pinch hitting for
Stan Javier, hit an RBI single, and Jeff Bagwell followed with a
sacrifice fly to right field.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Thompson sent a bases-empty homer to left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want the guys to believe in me,'' said Thompson, who
was recalled from the minors over the weekend. ``I don't want there
to be any question marks as to my heart and desire to win. I just
want to help this team and do whatever it is I can do. That's my
only concern. Nothing less, nothing more.''
</P>
<P>
   After a 1-2-3 sixth inning, Astros reliever Trever Miller,
pitching for the first time since Sept. 1, loaded the bases in the
seventh. Glanville and Kevin Sefcik hit singles, and Abreu walked
to load the bases. Powell entered the game and walked Jordan to
push across the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Astros' bullpen has allowed only two runs in its last
14 innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
