u s BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     09-08 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHILADELPHIA _ If ugly could build a house, what the Astros and
Phillies constructed Tuesday night would have been so big that Snow
White and the Seven Dwarfs could each have their own bedroom,
though Dopey might have to sleep on the front porch.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of performance that doesn't show up in the
highlight reels, just the standings. It was the kind of game that
doesn't win awards for raw appearance but may win, thanks to true
grit, division titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you win games just because you know how,'' said
Astros manager Larry Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   Which is another way of saying the Astros have a pedigree of
back-to-back National League Central titles that mean more than
mere decorative banners to hang from the rafters, while the
Phillies are a truck with no brakes that is rolling backward down a
hill.
</P>
<P>
   Through a season of the unexpected catastrophe and a long summer
of one physical disaster after another, there have been plenty of
nights when Dierker has shown up at the ballpark, looked at the
lineup cards for both teams and had a hard time making a judgment
about which side had more talent from which to draw.
</P>
<P>
   But more often than not, his sprained, broken, bruised, beat-up
Astros have found a way, which is why they are sitting on a
three-game lead over the Cincinnati Reds instead of stewing in a
broth of their own misfortune and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confidence can mean everything in the world,'' Dierker said.
``If you go out there and take the field for two straight years and
you play like you're better than the other guys, that attitude has
a way of getting inside you and staying there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when injuries crop up, even when things conspire to take
pieces out of your lineup, the guys who remain there believe they
can win just because that's what they've grown accustomed to
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   So they fall behind the Phillies by a 4-0 margin for the second
consecutive night and, rather than start to look for excuses, the
Astros search and eventually discover a way to mine a slag heap of
15 runners left on base for an 8-6 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure won't nominate it for best game of the year,'' Dierker
said.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be more typical than anybody wants to let on.
</P>
<P>
   Here was another night when Chris Holt, the poster boy for
buzzard's luck, had good stuff and was firing his pitches with
decent velocity but was victimized by one three-run homer by Bobby
Abreu that put him into a hole.
</P>
<P>
   Here was another night when Jeff Bagwell continued his recent
penchant for not making the most of his opportunities to clear the
bases. He came up with the bases loaded in the sixth inning and
could drive home only one run with a sacrifice fly. He came up
again with runners on second and third in the ninth inning and,
after one mighty swing when he nearly screwed himself down into the
batter's box against the Phillies' Wayne Gomes, struck out.
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros survived because Ken Caminiti immediately
followed Bagwell with a single to drive home Craig Biggio and Matt
Mieske with the winning runs, and all the ugliness was left for the
Phillies to wallow in. It's funny how a team nobody seems to think
is playing particularly well is suddenly in the midst of a
five-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to keep our heads together and win each game
as it comes,'' Biggio said. ``This is different from last year. A
year ago, we went out there every night and just beat people's
heads in. Now we're finding that we have to scrap and hustle. It's
different.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's the same, because the Astros have been there at the top
of the standings twice before and play like they are always going
to find a way. And on the other side, the Phillies are playing like
Wile E. Coyote, wondering when the next stick of dynamite is going
to blow up in their faces.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight it's Mike Hampton vs. Curt Schilling in a sterling
pitching matchup, the kind the Astros will likely encounter in the
playoffs. This one was more the cheap, bold brass that has carried
the Astros through this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was very much an example, I thought, of two teams with
similar talent going for them, but one is still fighting to win and
the other has given up the fight,'' Dierker said. ``There is an
expectation to succeed on our part, and there's a sense of dread on
their part. They don't know about all of our problems, and we don't
seem to care.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies probably didn't know that neither Billy Wagner nor
Jose Cabrera was available to Dierker out of the bullpen after
their stints Monday night. And the Phillies probably didn't know
Bagwell has been struggling mightily to drive in runs of late. All
they know is that the Astros are in first place and they must be
doing something to deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   Which they are. Surviving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
