<HEADER>
A4529 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     09-08 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ Some very strange things come out of Richard Williams'
mouth, as well as from the mouths of his two famous offspring.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Williams might be a tad off the wall _ often to the
point of bouncing off same _ and even if daughters Venus and Serena
have grown cocky beyond the level of their accomplishments to date,
there's nothing dysfunctional about this all-American family, the
new first family of women's tennis.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-age Williams sisters, halfway to claiming half the
spots in the U.S. Open semifinals for themselves, possess an
extreme amount of admiration and affection for each other, as well
as for their parents. Richard, Venus, Serena and mom, Oracene, are
so close they have a tendency to keep the proverbial wagons
circled, shutting everyone else out, which causes problems for them
in tennis circles.
</P>
<P>
   However, given a choice of the many unsavory alternatives on
exhibit in women's tennis, it's hard to get overly chagrined by the
madness in Daddy's admittedly unconventional, nonconforming
methods. (Richard, to cite one example, has been known to root for
his daughters' opponents.) At 18 and 17, respectively, Venus and
Serena are physically healthy, emotionally happy and competitively
hellbent upon becoming queens of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Venus whipped up on Barbara Schett 6-4, 6-3 Tuesday night to
reach the U.S. Open semifinals for the third year in a row. Serena
takes her shot today against Monica Seles, whom she has beaten in
both of their previous meetings. There's a better than decent
chance one or the other will plant her flag on the summit Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If Pops is crazy, it's the harmless variety. Who's the better
parental model, Williams or, say, a Stefano Capriati?
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Capriati was the original heiress to the throne before
the Williamses were out of grade school in a treacherous place
called Compton, Calif. She, not Lindsay Davenport, should have been
the first American-born female to win a major title since Chris
Evert. In 1991, at 16, Capriati twice served for a spot in the
final at Flushing Meadow, only to lose to Seles in a brutal,
bare-knuckled brawl of a match that served as a precursor to what
women's tennis looks like at the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Capriati had it all. Except the right kind of parental
support.
</P>
<P>
   Stefano pushed, prodded, exploited and browbeat. He asked too
much of and gave too little to his kid, who was exactly that, a
kid. While he wasn't physically abusive, his ham-handed methods
left Jennifer covered with welts that are still visible on her
psyche in 1999 as she attempts to recapture, against increasingly
long odds, what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   She went out of the current tournament on Labor Day, again
beaten by Seles in a straight-sets battle that provided brief
flashbacks of their aforementioned long-ago war. But Capriati's
lost years, those spent in open, self-destructive rebellion against
the demands of a stage father, have exacted an expensive toll.
</P>
<P>
   Her once-huge all-court game is nothing special anymore, not
compared to that of the Williamses, Davenport or Martina Hingis,
and her potential for reaching the higher plane they occupy is
minimal despite a 30-pounds-lighter physique and a measure of
renewed competitive fire.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati can't finish a news conference anymore, never mind a
big match. She left Monday's in tears after reading a bizarre,
meandering prepared statement that was intended to put her unhappy
past behind her but led only to the kind of questions she believed
the statement would deter. When asked if she considered the press
an ``adversary,'' she broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish I didn't have to talk about this all the time,''
she said, before being led away by a tour attendant into the arms
of Stefano.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, he's still in the picture, for better or worse (and we
have our suspicions). Nearby, Jennifer's mother and Stefano's
ex-wife, Denise, was weeping. The Capriatis' marriage collapsed, in
large part, because of Stefano's boorish behavior and the
consequences thereof.
</P>
<P>
   Those who live in a fishbowl have to realize the fish around
them have been known to bite. Also, you can shoot the messenger,
but you can't kill it. While Richard Williams frequently loses
sight of these self-evident truths himself, it's never to the
personal detriment of his daughters _ except to make them less
popular with their peers.
</P>
<P>
   As if they care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything he says is very well thought out and intends a
certain result,'' contends Kevin Davis, the family's agent and
legal counsel for 11 years. ``Ninety-nine times out of 100, he gets
that result. Don't ever underestimate Richard.''
</P>
<P>
   And who said the circuit is supposed to be one big, happy family
anyway? It's more important to be part of a big, happy real family,
and that the Williamses definitely are. Bravo for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
