   WACO-LAWSUIT _ WACO, Texas _ Daily coverage leading up to the
opening of the civil trial Oct. 18. (Waco Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-MILITARY _ LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore, addressing
the American Legion's annual convention, talks Wednesday about his
military service during the Vietnam War. In doing so, he contrasts
his military experience with Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who served
in the Texas National Guard during the war, and his Democratic
rival, Bill Bradley, who served in the Air Force Reserves while
playing pro basketball during the war. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ WASHINGTON _ Sens. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, and Christopher
Dodd, D-Conn., heads of the Senate Special Committee on the Year
2000 Technology Problem, will address the National Press Club about
the status of Y2K preparations here and abroad. (Geewax, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-COMPLAINTS _ WASHINGTON _ Airline customer complaints
shot up 87 percent in July to the highest level since March 1988.
Flight delays and missed connections led the list, which also
included complaints about passenger service and mishandled baggage,
according to the Department of Transportation. Southwest had the
fewest complaints among major carriers, and American had the most.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   CHEATING _ WASHINGTON - Claiming that more kids than ever cheat
in school, and that the top kids cheat more than the low-ranking
kids in high school, educators and ethicists have turned for help
to the advertising industry. On Wednesday, they and the Ad Council
unveil public service ads aimed at curbing cheating. (Mollison, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LIFE-IN-AMERICA _ CHEYENNE RIVER RESERVATION, S.D. _ Like the
swallows that signal spring in Capistrano, Guy Jones' 2,600-mile
trip to South Dakota heralds the onset of another harsh winter on
the Cheyenne River and Standing Rock reservations. It also signals
help and hope for the American Indians living there, and another
stop on Jones's journey of racial understanding. (Mong, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED. WITH PHOTOS and locator map.
</P>
<P>
   GENETIC-FOODS _ BELLE GLADE, Fla. _ What if someone offered you
a pristine, nearly pesticide-free ear of corn so yellow and sweet
that it begs for a dollop of butter and a sprinkle of salt. That
would be a good thing. What if they then told you that this corn
looks and tastes so good because of the handiwork of some
scientists who inserted into its cells a gene that repels bugs. The
question of how safe gene-altered foods are is at the heart of an
escalating global food fight. Your answer likely depends on what
part of the world you call home. (Waresh, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/GENETIC-SEEDS _ Gene-altered crops represent a giant new
market for seed companies, but they also pose a vexing business
problem. How is a company to protect its investment when seeds grow
into plants that produce more seeds? (Waresh, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS _ TAMPA, Fla. _ Trying to move into the future, 60,000
Baptist leaders from across the country will elect a new president
tonight for their organization, the National Baptist Convention,
USA. Many insiders consider this year's election one of the most
important happenings in the group's history. We offer a quick look
at the leading candidates and their plans for the future. (Blake,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
