   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NAVY-VIEQUES (Washington) _ The Navy steps up its campaign to
regain use of the Vieques, Puerto Rico, firing range. It warns that
a ship in the battle group led by the carrier John F. Kennedy will
sail next week for the Mediterranean and Persian Gulf with a
significant loss of combat readiness because its crew was not able
to practice gunfire at Vieques. The range has been closed since
April when a U.S. bomb accidentally killed a Puerto Rican civilian.
By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WACO-PROBE (Washington) _ Congressional leaders react
approvingly to the impending appointment of former Republican Sen.
John Danforth to lead an independent investigation into the FBI's
deadly 1993 raid on the Branch Davidian cult outside Waco, Texas.
But they say congressional probes into the matter won't be called
off. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ In a century that has witnessed
great achievements and horrendous tragedies, no event has had a
more far-reaching impact than World War II, which began 60 years
ago this month. A major lesson of that war: Our own well-being is
dependent on that of other nations. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
