<P>
   ISRAEL-WYE (Jerusalem) _ Amid political chaos _ the Shas party
is threatening to quit Barak government _ the Cabinet approves the
revised Wye peace plan, with parliament expected to to the same
later. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ Congress returns to work on
spending bills _ and on turning the coming year's projected surplus
into a deficit. The Congressional Budget Office says the projected
$14 billion surplus will become a $13 billion deficit if House
proposals became law and a $16 billion deficit if Senate's plans
prevail. There is possible floor action (but no final votes
anticipated) in the Senate on an Interior bill with controversial
riders favoring mining and energy industries, and in the House on
Veterans Administration and HUD spending bills. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, we are also monitoring for an announcement of a person to
head an independent inquiry into FBI conduct at Waco.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN (Crystal City, Mo.) _ Kicking off his campaign
with a tour of his boyhood haunts along the Mississippi, Bill
Bradley says he feels an urgent need to seize the moment in
history, and that as president, he would do fewer things, but
essential things, and do them more thoroughly than his opponents.
By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   QUAYLE-PROFILE (Goffstown, N.H.) _ These days, Dan Quayle, whose
slingshot career allowed him to glimpse the heights and depths of
American politics before he turned 45, would seem to be at the
bottom of his personal trajectory. Yet he perseveres, with a
poignant tenacity that he and friends say is grounded in a dogged
belief in the possibility of his own political success and
redemption. A Contenders 2000 profile, by Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-TEACHERS (Detroit) _ With a tentative contract hammered
out between teachers and leaders of the city's struggling school
system, parents were waiting to see if their children would be
called to classrooms this week. Teachers gathered this morning at
Cobo Center to vote on whether to temporarily extend their old
contract, which would allow them and the district's 180,000
students to return to school as soon as Thursday. By Robyn
Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NY-ENCEPHALITIS (New York) _ It was just the kind of call
New York City Health Department officials had been encouraging
doctors to make about cases with a perplexing diagnosis. The Queens
doctor told them that she had two elderly patients showing unusual
forms of muscle weakness and disorientation. She thought it might
be Guillain-Barre syndrome, a form of progressive paralysis, or
botulism, the deadly food toxin. It also sounded like encephalitis,
but it did not fit the profile for Eastern equine, the type
occasionally seen here. That call, on Aug. 23, set in motion
intensive medical sleuthing that is expected to continue for weeks
as baffled Federal and local health officials try to learn why the
outbreak occurred and how to prevent it from recurring. By Lawrence
K. Altman. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VIACOM-CBS &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM-ENTERTAINMENT (New York) _ An examination of what the
proposed acquisition of CBS by Viacom means for the creative talent
behind entertainment programming. Can Viacom resist the kind of
inside-the-company favoritism that has made actors, producers and
directors reluctant to work with Disney and ABC? Will independent
talent be drawn to NBC? By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM-CBS-NEWS (New York) _ A look at what the deal is likely
to mean for CBS's venerable news organization. By Felicity
Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:35 p.m., the industrial average was up
35 points and the Nasdaq index was down 10 points. Stocks were
being pulled in different directions by the rate cut in Britain and
Abby Joseph Cohen's more-bullish forecast for the Nasdaq index.
Elsewhere, prices slipped 0.4 percent in Tokyo and were down 0.3
percent in Hong Kong. They rose 0.2 percent in Frankfurt, fell 1
percent in London, slipped 0.2 percent in Brazil and gained 0.9
percent in Mexico. On the American debt market, at midday the long
bond was up 11/32 point, with the yield at 6.05 percent. By Robert
D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-RATES (London) _ In a move that had not been expected so
soon, the Bank of England raised its benchmark securities
repurchase rate to 5.25 percent from 5 percent, indicating that the
central bank was worried that increased borrowing and spending by
consumers could promote inflation. The increase was the first since
June 1998 and follows a string of seven cuts from 7.5 percent.
Britain's banks moved quickly to raise their mortgage and base
interest rates. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-DRUGS (Undated) _ As the profile of people who have AIDS
broadens _ until the mid-'90s, it was overwhelmingly gay urban men,
but it is now increasingly women, Hispanics and African-Americans _
drug companies are scrambling to introduce AIDS drugs to new types
of patients. On top of awarding grant money to community AIDS
organizations, pharmaceutical companies have stepped up marketing
efforts to inmates and broadened their ad campaigns to reach a
wider market. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   MERGERS-ACCOUNTING (Undated) _ The FASB is expected to propose
eliminating pooling of interests, a very popular method of
accounting for mergers. By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMERS-TREASURY (New York) _ We take the occasion of an
afternoon speech here to take a look at the first few months of
Lawrence H. Summers as Treasury secretary. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   INGRAM-WARNING (Santa Ana, Calif.) _ Ingram Micro Inc., the
world's biggest wholesale computer distributor, warned that its
profit for the third quarter would not meet analysts' forecasts and
said it was seeking a replacement for its chief executive, Jerre L.
Stead, the former AT&AMP;T executive who gained attention by agreeing
to work for no salary, only stock options. The stock, which went
public at $18 and was at $54 last fall, fell below the offering
price Wednesdayday. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-AUTOS (Detroit) _ The Canadian auto workers are expected
to name their target in contract talks. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   SONY-TIVO (Undaterd) _ Sony will invest in Tivo, the maker of
personal video recorders, choosing sides in the battle with Replay.
By Matt Richtel.
</P>
