<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4543 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-RENO-AIR-HNS &LR;      09-08 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-AIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN SEEKS MORE EAST COAST BUSINESS WITH RENO INTEGRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ American Airlines, which recently acquired Reno
Air and its 25 aircraft, is expanding its north-south service on
the West Coast in the hopes of selling more lucrative tickets to
the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   American added the flights this week to increase its presence on
the West Coast and give more flight opportunities to customers _ as
well as take a slice out of United Airlines' market.
</P>
<P>
   American's $124 million acquisition of Reno Air took effect Aug.
31.
</P>
<P>
   Reno Air flies nine daily nonstops from San Francisco to Los
Angeles and five more to Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   American is adding 32 flights a day from San Jose to Las Vegas,
Nev.; Los Angeles; Portland, Ore.; Reno, Nev.; and Seattle. It is
also serving Anchorage, Alaska, via Seattle. In addition, American
now has 32 daily flights to nine destinations from Reno Air's
former hub, Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our own customers have been telling us for some time they want
one airline network to provide all of their travel needs,''
American spokesman Tim Smith said from the airline's headquarters
at Fort Worth, Texas. ``We have wanted to capture that business
that goes north and south, along with the business we had been
getting _ the longer haul (to the East Coast and) to Japan and
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The process has not been seamless. American and its unionized
pilots, members of the Allied Pilots Association, have squared off
over details of integrating the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots object to American's plan to pay Reno's pilots higher
rates as they are retrained by American. The union believes the
contract guarantees that the pilots should be paid more from the
purchase date.
</P>
<P>
   This led the pilots to call in sick over several days in
February, leading to the cancellation of 6,700 flights and
inconveniencing 670,000 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The sick-out cost American $225 million in pretax profit. It
also caused a federal judge in Dallas to levy a fine of $45 million
against the union, which has $38 million in assets, for ignoring
his order to tell pilots to return to their cockpits during the job
action.
</P>
<P>
   The money will go to the airline if the union loses its appeal
of the order.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the integration of Reno Air adds 182 more daily flights
to American's schedule, as well as nearly 2,100 employees. There
were no layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest impact is in San Jose, where American took over
Reno's nine flights to Los Angeles, eight to Orange County, five to
San Diego, three to Reno, three to Seattle, two to Portland and one
to Anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   The new flights are an addition to the service American has long
offered from the San Francisco Bay Area _ to Dallas, Chicago, New
York, Boston, Miami and Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Reno Air was made with the understanding that
the routes themselves will not be significant money-makers, said
Glenn Engel, an airline industry analyst at Goldman, Sachs in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger issue is this issue called presence. What they're
fighting for is the east-west flying, but it helps to be in the
north-south market to get a larger share of the east-west flying,''
Engel said.
</P>
<P>
   The new north-south routes ``in no way, shape or form are
positioned to be a shuttle service,'' said Leo Loane, American's
regional sales manager for Northern California, in a reference to
the United Shuttle, the dominant short-haul carrier at the San
Francisco International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is a major United hub, with 250 daily departures
(there are 20 from San Jose and 16 from Oakland). The 78 daily San
Francisco-Los Angeles United Shuttle flights are flying at 68
percent capacity this year, UAL spokesman Joe Hopkins said from
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with American strengthening its presence in the market,
Engel said, it will be interesting to see if and how fares are
adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passengers still want the cheapest fare,'' he said. ``So, all
things being equal, if American is not offering a fare that is
competitive with the other players, they will choose the other guy.
If all things are equal, they will want to stick with one
carrier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4545 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-CLASSICAL09-COX     09-08 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-CLASSICAL09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For opera lovers and others, fine easy listening
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Classical''? Debatable. The three tenors, together and singly,
are virtual pop icons. Their third ``Concert of the Century,''
recorded at the Eiffel Tower in 1998, is a pleasant blend of the
familiar (''Granada,'' sung by Pavarotti) and the not. The tenors
have just about run out of opera standards, so they've gone back
into the archives for arias from ``Maristella'' (Giuseppe Pietri,
sung by Carreras) and Spanish zarzuela (Domingo, of course). There
are two ``theme'' medleys packed with incompatible tunes (e.g.,
Schubert's ``Serenade'' and ``You'll Never Walk Alone'' from
``Carousel''). Conductor James Levine now gets equal billing and
his photo on the cover _ both undeserved. He must have a good
agent. As for Pavarotti's recital, it's a straight voice-and-piano
program recorded live June 8, 1989, at an 1847 theater in
Barcelona. The tenor was in lovely voice at the time, and the
program is filled with treasures. What a pleasure to hear the
Bellini songs (often given to students as practice pieces) in such
creamy and idiomatic Italian. And where else can you hear Pavarotti
sing Mozart (``Un'aura amorosa'' from ``Cosi Fan Tutte'')? The CD
ends with ``O sole mio'' and ``Una furtiva lagrima,'' the Caruso
standard, which should send everyone home happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luciano Pavarotti: The Recital''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic. 23 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   ``The 3 Tenors''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Carreras, Placido Domingo, Luciano Pavarotti. Atlantic. 26
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Jouirnal
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
