<HEADER>
A4546 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS09-COX     09-08 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini CD reviews
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Steve Dollar and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Murda Muzik''
</P>
<P>
   Mobb Deep. Loud. 20 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   It slips in quietly like a thief who's discovered the unlocked
sliding door in the back of your house. Lulled by the simple piano
(``Streets Raised Me''), church organs (``Allustrious'') and light
taps on the drum head (``Spread Love''), you figure this couldn't
be as menacing as its name, so you get comfortable. Then, in a
conversational tone that varies so little in delivery it's almost
soothing, rappers Prodigy and Havoc calmly relay balanced tales of
choking more people than Latrell Sprewell (``I'm Going Out''),
``packing nothing but the big guns'' (``Where Ya From'') and
``dump(ing you) under a bridge in a cardboard box'' (``Can't
(Expletive) Wit''). An alarm finally goes off, but who do you call?
After all, it's just ``Murda Muzik.''
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Inspiration''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Rivers' Rivbea All-Star Orchestra. RCA/BMG. 7 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Going strong at 69, jazz composer and reed wizard Sam Rivers has
reactivated his career in the midst of a seeming retirement to
central Florida. His important Blue Note albums of the 1960s _
``Fuschia Swing Song'' and ``Dimensions and Extensions'' _ still
sound bold and tuneful today. But it's as a big-band visionary that
Rivers is featured on this new release, his first for a domestic
major label. The results, a sprawling 70-minute performance
featuring 14 of New York's top players and Rivers' Orlando-based
rhythm section, are enjoyable if somewhat less than legendary. The
liberally assigned solos and polyphonic free-for-alls often spark
with a colorful array of voices. Other bonuses include the trombone
section of Ray Anderson, Joseph Bowie and Art Baron, which is
especially gutsy, and Rivers' soprano saxophone, which frequently
bends melody to Middle Eastern tonalities. Yet the session feels
compromised in two regards. Rivers' structural concept calls for
repeated use of massive unison riffs, which become shrill and
predictable. Doug Mathews' electric bass, which makes more sense in
Rivers' range-roving trio, gets to be a drag, as well, though when
the inspiration flows, it's easy enough to overlook.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedals''
</P>
<P>
   The Aluminum Group. Minty Fresh. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Chicago brothers John and Frank Navin must have spent their
early years soaking up all the Burt Bacharach and Carpenters music
they could find. The brothers then spent most of the '90s toiling
in obscurity, forming a band and honing their shimmering pop songs
while the rest of the world was feeling the noise of grunge.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's ``Plano,'' the band's sophomore release, was a
beautiful collection of smart melodic pop-craft and sharp lyrical
observations and one of the year's best. ``Pedals'' suffers in
comparison, but it scores points for artistic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The songwriting prowess is still evident, as are the decidedly
'60s horn and string charts (some courtesy of the High Llamas' Sean
O'Hagan, a definite kindred spirit). The difference comes with
production by Gastr del Sol's Jim O'Rourke and appearances by other
members of the Chicago post-rock pantheon. The combination of
seemingly conflicting styles works surprisingly well, but it's not
as immediate as ``Plano.'' It's a grower.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray, Steve Dollar and Shane Harrison write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
