<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4547 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-POP09-COX     09-08 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A cool sonic landscape
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the main reasons the Athens, Ga., music scene bears close
watching these days is the four-piece rock band Macha. The group
thrives on an unusual fusion of sounds, taking as its primary
influence the Indonesian form known as gamelan _ literally, an
ensemble of tuned percussion instruments whose glimmering
repetitions can cast a floating, hypnotic spell. It's an enthusiasm
that Macha shares with several generations of globe-trotting field
recordists, bohemians in search of the ecstatic all-night groove
and classical composers looking for alternatives to Western
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike, say, composers Steve Reich or Anthony Davis, Macha
frontman Joshua McKay plays in rock clubs. He also came of age in
the 1980s, when ideas about what could constitute rock music became
more flexible, liberated by post-punk experimentation. Macha revels
in this musical interzone, laying a thick, dubby foundation of
drums and bass for the ear-tickling percussive textures that ripple
across the surface of its songs. The arcane instrumentation
(hammered dulcimer, Moog, toy zither and such) keeps things
interesting. But what's cool about ``See It Another Way,'' Macha's
second album, is the things that would be interesting anyway: McCay
and his cohorts (brother Mischo, Wes Martin and Kai Riedl) have
created a sonic landscape as vivid as a waking dream. Lyrics like
random thoughts drizzle down _ ``I had to love your criminal
mind,'' or ``Drop your strong black hair/My favorite trap'' _ and
turn into little tunes and evaporate as temple bells chime. No rock
album this year has sounded so inviting or been as quietly
intoxicating.
</P>
<P>
   ``See It Another Way''
</P>
<P>
   Macha. Jetset. 9 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
