<HEADER>
A4565 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-B-SMITH-MARTHA-STEWAR     09-08 2531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-B-SMITH-MARTHA-STEWART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN B. SMITH BE MARTHA? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JULIA REED  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    It is a hot summer Sunday in the Hamptons, and I am spending the
day with Barbara Smith, the restaurateur and cookbook author, the
host of a nationally syndicated television show, ``B. Smith, With
Style,'' and the editor in chief of an upcoming magazine, that will
bear her brandlike name.
 &HT;    Her house in Sag Harbor, with its stunning views of the water,
its enormous deck and two kitchens, is therefore more than just a
house; it's also a set. But today it is a bit of a mess.
 &HT;    Outside, huge pots are filled with nasturtiums that are
predominantly dead. Inside, Smith, who is preparing for a photo
shoot, runs between the bathroom, where she is doing her own
makeup, and the basement, where she is ironing her own clothes.
 &HT;    ``At the restaurants I call myself the producer, the director,
the casting agent and the star,'' she says.
 &HT;    Lunch consists of cheeses her husband and business partner, Dan
Gasby, has apparently just run out and bought, garnished with some
slightly withered cherry tomatoes, some mostly brown seedless
grapes and an incongruous bowl of seaweed salad. There is nothing
else edible in her refrigerator _ when I check the contents, I find
a jar of French's mustard, a bottle of Wish-Bone Ranch salad
dressing, a bottle of Wish-Bone Fat Free Caesar, beer, bottled
water and a case of Champagne.
 &HT;    It seems that the woman who is struggling to build an empire by
telling people what to cook, how to entertain, how to fix up their
homes and how to become more fashionable is too busy right now to
do it herself _ which is part of her charm.
 &HT;    You can't quite imagine Smith's East Hampton neighbor Martha
Stewart putting out less than pristine (or even store-bought)
tomatoes or, for that matter, ironing her own clothes. Stewart
gives off an air of impenetrable perfection with a whiff of
privilege _ which is not part of her charm.
 &HT;    Smith is more like Everywoman _ except she also happens to be
black. And her success, so far, has reflected the growing influence
of the black professional class. In 1997, black consumers spent
nearly $500 billion annually on goods and services, 54 percent more
than they had in 1990. And the number of black households earning
$100,000 or more nearly doubled from 1988 to 1998, from 220,400 to
414,500.
 &HT;    A writer like Terry McMillan can land on the best-seller list,
as she did with her 1992 novel, ``Waiting to Exhale,'' by appealing
largely to a black (female) audience. All of which may help explain
why American Express Publishing is putting out B. Smith Style, the
magazine, in late October, and why Random House, the same week, is
releasing ``B. Smith: Rituals and Celebrations,'' part of a
four-book deal.
 &HT;    Smith is already a star in the black community. A former model
who began using her initial in the 1970s when she phoned in for
appointments at the prestigious Wilhelmina agency, she was the
second African-American to grace the cover of Mademoiselle
magazine, in 1976.
 &HT;    In the mid-1980s, she became a partner in a Manhattan
restaurant, B. Smith, and now owns two more outright _ one at Union
Station, in Washington, and the other on the wharf in Sag Harbor.
Her book ''B. Smith's Entertaining and Cooking for Friends,''
published in 1995, was among the first on entertaining by a black
author.
 &HT;    ``Her restaurants are the black '21' clubs, the places to see
and be seen,'' says Lawrence Otis Graham, author of ``Our Kind of
People: Inside America's Black Upper Class.'' ``People know that if
they go there, they're going to run into the right people, the
black folks you know from the Links and the Boule and Jack and
Jill,'' the exclusive black clubs. When Graham was researching his
book, he found that ``everybody knew her restaurant. Everybody
watched her show.''
 &HT;    Although Smith has been saddled with the unfortunate, if
inevitable, moniker ``the black Martha Stewart, `` her own plan is
not just to capitalize on her core constituency but also to broaden
it. The model is less Martha than Oprah, the original crossover
figure, who also promises to be her biggest competition.
 &HT;    Smith's TV show, which is entering its third year in 207 markets
nationwide, has an audience that is 75 percent white and 25 percent
black. It was this statistic that helped convince Smith and Gasby
that they could find a partner for a new magazine. Convincing
others, however, hasn't been so easy.
 &HT;    ``There is the assumption,'' Gasby says, ``that because Barbara
is black, she will only appeal to blacks. People follow what she
does; she's beautiful; she's got charisma. And then you sit and
talk to executives and you get the sense they're thinking: 'But
she's black. I don't know if she's going to appeal to a wider
group.' And you say, 'She's done it in the restaurant business, on
the TV show.' You have to say the same thing 50 times differently _
this is not a black magazine.''
 &HT;    Both Smith and Gasby have said they believe that Stewart tried
to stop their show from getting into production. ``We had a deal
with Warner, and that dried up,'' Gasby says. ``Then we had a deal
with CBS, and that dried up.'' (Time Warner has a minority share in
Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia, and a division of CBS syndicates
Stewart's show.) Television executives deny the charge, and Stewart
has replied by wishing Smith well.
 &HT;    ``It's like climbing Mount Everest,'' Smith says. ``You get
really tired of it and you think to yourself, So when does it stop?
But it doesn't stop.''
 &HT;    Hearst ultimately agreed to produce Smith's show, but took a
pass on backing her magazine three times on the grounds that the
timing wasn't right. Last fall, American Express finally took a
flier on Smith. Then Hearst announced in July that it would publish
Oprah's new magazine, which, like Smith's, will be about life
style.
 &HT;    But Oprah's will carry a more bankable (and proven) name on its
masthead. Smith was furious. As she puts it, ``The timing's not
right _ until we get a really rich black woman, someone with a name
and dough.''
 &HT;    Rich Fairfield, vice president for strategic planning and new
media at American Express, says that he's not worried about Oprah.
``That just shows again that this is a good idea.''
 &HT;    Still, American Express is not exactly pouring money into
Smith's venture. The magazine's editor, Julie Bain, formerly of The
Wine Enthusiast, has only two full-time staff members. The first
issue is a newsstand holiday preview. ``The earliest you'd see a
second magazine,'' Fairfield says, ``would be April.'' And then
only if the first is successful. All of which steps up the pressure
on Smith.
 &HT;    ``We see her as a mainstream force,'' says Pamela Cannon,
Smith's Random House editor, who describes Smith as ``glamorous and
approachable and _ perhaps most important _ not just Afrocentric.''
The company is promoting the book heavily on television and sending
Smith to four times the number of cities than the norm for a
lifestyle title.
 &HT;    On the cover, she's decked out in a tight floral cheongsam,
lighting candles on the beach. There are sections on Juneteenth and
Kwanzaa and also on the Chinese New Year. ``She's really
crossover,'' Cannon says.
 &HT;    Black commentators don't necessarily disagree. ``I call that
kind of black woman a super-fabulous white woman,'' says Hilton
Als, an author and a critic. ``She has no real allegiance to the
black culture.'' He says her appeal is found in the market's
assessment of her as ``safe and manageable. She's not Toukie
Smith,'' the louder, larger, more flamboyant former restaurateur.
 &HT;    Certainly, Smith does not fit into the more traditional image of
black caterers and restaurateurs like Sylvia Woods of Sylvia's, in
Harlem, or Leah Chase of Dooky Chase, in New Orleans. Those women
made national names for themselves by dishing out country and
Creole meals like fried chicken or gumbo. ``It's more like Zsa Zsa
Gabor in the kitchen,'' Als says.
 &HT;    But this is precisely why some members of the black elite see
Smith as no less than their liberator. ``She has given the black
upper classes permission to come out of the closet,'' Graham says.
``Everybody in our crowd really watches her show because we live
like this. Until now, we felt as though we had to apologize for the
fact that we had nice homes and nice things.''
 &HT;    Smith, like many middle-class professionals, straddles two
worlds: the one she came from and the one she currently inhabits.
Herein lies her real appeal. Her most powerful message is her own
story, which she tells just about wherever she goes, about the
small-town girl in western Pennsylvania whose mama was a maid and
whose daddy was a steelworker _ ``the original Martha Stewart and
Bob Vila.''
 &HT;    They grew everything themselves, had plenty of food on the table
and plenty of family around to eat it. Even then, she says, her
experience was multicultural.
 &HT;    ``The town was Greek and German and Polish and
African-American,'' she says. ``We weren't Catholic, but if it was
Friday, we had to have fish.'' On Friday nights, her father served
his homemade root beer and fresh buttered popcorn, and they'd all
sit in front of the TV to watch the fights. She learned to cook and
to clean, to grow peonies and change the slipcovers in the summer.
In the summer, she and her three brothers were packed into the
family car for trips to the only black swimming pool nearby.
 &HT;    But Smith wanted to venture farther. She persuaded her father,
who had seen a bit of the world when he was a first lieutenant in
the Army and stationed in Europe, to let her go to modeling school
in Pittsburgh, where she boarded with a caterer.
 &HT;    By the time she was 19, she was in New York leading her own
classes in modeling, pounding the pavement and, she says,
entertaining. ``Nobody turns down an invitation in New York. You
cook; you invite; they come. No matter how small the apartment.''
 &HT;    Now she is 50, with a big Manhattan apartment near her Times
Square restaurant and a house in an exclusive black section of Sag
Harbor, where she lives with Gasby and his 13-year-old daughter,
Dana. Along the way, she says, there were ``some hard knocks.''
 &HT;    Among them was a not entirely successful singing career, in
which she sang in a reggae band with Deborah Harry and hired
Freddie Jackson as a backup singer in her own short-lived nightclub
act. (``I always had a good eye for talent.'')
 &HT;    There was the painful first marriage that was annulled (``he
misrepresented himself''), and the regret of not having a child of
her own. There were also some ``difficult business relationships,''
including a partnership with Ark Restaurants.
 &HT;    By the 1980s, Smith had parlayed her interest in entertaining
into a career in the food industry, working her way up to become a
popular manager at another Ark restaurant, America. With Michael
Weinstein, the president of Ark, she opened a restaurant on Eighth
Avenue.
 &HT;    He hoped her name on the restaurant, and her presence, would
help draw crowds from the nearby theater district. ``Barbara has a
very engaging personality,'' Weinstein says. ``She is quick-witted
and certainly beautiful to look at.''
 &HT;    Enter Gasby, whom Smith first met at the restaurant in 1987 and
married almost seven years ago. He says he loves being ``Mr. B.
Smith'' and is something of a stage husband. He is the creator of
her show (when the credits roll, Smith's voice can be heard, saying
sweetly, ``Thank you, Dan'') and the driving force behind her
expansion. ``I think it's important to see that a black man should
support a black woman,'' he says. ``It's her destiny; my duty, to
fulfill it.''
 &HT;    Gasby describes Weinstein as ``the Milosevic of the restaurant
business.'' When Gasby looked at Smith's partnership, he says, ``I
saw that it wasn't in her favor.''
 &HT;    Weinstein says that the Times Square lease is too valuable for
Smith and Gasby to buy him out, but they did buy him out of the
Washington partnership and have always had full control in Sag
Harbor. Ark's use of the B. Smith name expires in December, and
Smith and Gasby are now looking for new space in Manhattan. Their
plan is then to expand to Philadelphia, Boston and Charlotte, N.C.
 &HT;    ``If I weren't married to him already,'' Smith says of Gasby,
``I'd marry him now.''
 &HT;    They are certainly cut from the same cloth. Gasby was born in
Brooklyn, in Bedford-Stuyvesant, ``about four miles too soon,'' he
says. Like Smith's, his mother was a maid; his father was a bookie.
``When I was about 7 or 8 years old, I was like, I got dropped in
the wrong place. I always wanted to be some place esthetically
beautiful, like Barbara did. I took cold baths _ so the bathroom is
very important to me.''
 &HT;    He went to Colgate, worked at a TV station in Memphis and
created and produced a ``Star Search''-style show with Natalie Cole
in Los Angeles. He met Smith, and in time their plans converged.
 &HT;    When they bought and renovated their house in Sag Harbor, he
made sure it had two 75-gallon hot-water heaters for his baths and
two kitchens for the set of the TV show they did not yet have.
``People thought we were crazy,'' Gasby says, ``But you can't bet
against B., and you better not bet against me.''
 &HT;    And so while Smith may have grown up eating collard greens from
her own backyard, she now sautes them in olive oil and puts them in
Italian frittatas. There's a picture of one in her latest book _
photographed in her new backyard, the one overlooking a private
beach.
 &HT;    Smith is peddling style as an aspirational tool. ``I am more of
a conduit,'' she says. ``I bring in experts, and the audience and I
are in it together.'' This is what attracted Leslie McNeil, the
former executive producer of Martha Stewart's Emmy-winning TV show,
who has just signed on as executive producer of ``B. Smith, With
Style.''
 &HT;    ``Martha is an event unto herself, and you see the world through
her eyes,'' McNeil says. ``B. has a very powerful vision too, but
it has to do with encouraging people to develop their own
imprint.''
 &HT;    In the overcrowded lifestyle market, Cannon says, personality
has become everything, and so ``the key to B. is meeting her,
seeing her. That's why we're putting so much behind her.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Julia Reed  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Julia Reed is a senior writer at Vogue and a contributing
editor at Newsweek.) &LR;
</P>
