<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One `Sister' worth watching
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Other
</P>
<P>
   Sister''
</P>
<P>
   (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   Juliette Lewis brings focus and electricity to a gooey-glossy
film that sometimes plays like a lavish Movie of the Week.
</P>
<P>
   She plays Carla, a mentally challenged woman who returns to her
wealthy family's San Francisco home from a boarding school for
``special'' students. Mom Elizabeth (Diane Keaton) frets when Carla
insists on her own apartment and wants to enroll in tech school,
where she falls for another mentally challenged person, Danny
(Giovanni Ribisi).
</P>
<P>
   The movie unfolds in such a rarified atmosphere, the stakes
never seem very high. Keaton seems uncomfortable playing a fussy
matron. But the movie is surprisingly watchable, mainly due to
Lewis' emotional translucence. She has moments onscreen that are as
breathtakingly truthful as the script is dishonest.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
