<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Usher in the millennium with timely mementos
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The end is near.
</P>
<P>
   But no need to panic. With 113 days left until Jan. 1, retailers
are offering an array of fun, souvenirs _ some of them pricey _ to
help everyone get into an end-of-the-year party mood.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you can count down the seconds with a keepsake
01-01-00 digital clock ($18.99). Or decorate your home with a fat
silver candle in the shape of the numerals 2000 ($14).
</P>
<P>
   And if you are planning to celebrate on the town on New Year's
Eve, you will want to carry Judith Leiber's sparkling silver
crystal bag scripted in black with the date 01012000 ($2,775).
</P>
<P>
   Some items are in stores now; others will start trickling in
Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Although most people regard Jan. 1, 2000, as the beginning of
the new millennium, it technically doesn't start until Jan. 1,
2001. Don't tell that to New York architect Ken Walker, who has
trademarked 01-01-00 for use on all types of merchandise, from
T-shirts and swizzle sticks to inflatable furniture and key chains.
</P>
<P>
   About five years ago, Walker was doodling with numbers and liked
the way 01-01-00 looked. He pursued the legal rights, then obtained
the licensees for the products.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than 1,000 items with this date are available in
stores as well as on the Home Shopping Network.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a time freak, count on the 11:59 millennium
collection for fun items. A Colorado firm, the 11:59 Co. has
trademarked the time and launched apparel and accessories
embroidered with ``Where Are You Going to Be at 11:59?'' Products
include T-shirts, caps and jackets. Information: 1-877-999-1159.
</P>
<P>
   Some lighthearted souvenirs are tied to the Y2K bug _ a software
glitch that some fear may cause your computer to read the new year
date change as Jan. 1, 1900, instead of 2000. The Oregon company
Something Blue is merchandising the Y2K Compliant Survival Kit over
the Internet. It includes a bottle of water, matches, a votive
candle, 2-ounce chocolate bar, a wooden nickel, commemorative
T-shirt and a computer backup system _ a No. 2 pencil. Cost:
$19.99. Information: 1-888-205-6606.
</P>
<P>
   While much millennium merchandise has a short shelf life, one
item meant to last, until, well, the next millennium is Tiffany &AMP;
Co.'s sterling silver Time Capsule box.
</P>
<P>
   Bordered in Roman numerals and lined in vermeil, the 10 3/8-by-6
3/8-by-4-inch collector's box is $15,000; the 15-by-9-by-4-inch box
is $20,000. Each comes with a lock and key and can be engraved with
a name, date or message. It's the perfect place to keep mementos
from that night of nights, Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
