A4576 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATIONS     09-08 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATIONS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Upscale stores find home outside the malls
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARIETTA, Ga. _ Ever wish you could run in and shop at a mall
store without the hassle of dodging traffic jams or hunting for a
parking space in another time zone? That's the concept behind the
Avenue East Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Simmons, director of corporate communications for Cousins
Properties, which owns and manages the shopping center, says that
the Avenue East Cobb in Marietta is within 15 miles of Perimeter,
Town Center and North Point malls.
</P>
<P>
   Avenue East Cobb, which opened last month, is geared toward
consumers who don't have quick, easy access to a major mall but who
want to shop in mall stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were targeting upscale retailers traditionally found in
malls,'' Simmons said, ``looking for the right mix between fashion,
furniture, books and music.''
</P>
<P>
   Looks like they found it.
</P>
<P>
   The Avenue East Cobb is noticeably different from surrounding
strip malls. Anchored by a large, flowing fountain, the
pedestrian-friendly center features lush landscaping and brick
walkways. Benches and planters encourage shoppers to sit and take
in the many life-size bronze statues commissioned specifically for
the center.
</P>
<P>
   A small gated courtyard with a seating area provides space for
events, which will include cooking demonstrations and book
readings.
</P>
<P>
   You'll feel among friends at the Avenue East Cobb because most
of the shops have familiar names found in malls and a handful are
catalog stores. Note that most of the restaurants and some stores
are scheduled to open in the next month or so. However, as it
stands, the center still offers plenty of shopping opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy this place opened up,'' said Anna Moorhead, who
recently moved to Marietta from Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't know my way around that well, and this is so
convenient because I don't have to get on the freeway to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Moorhead is especially happy with the Pottery Barn. ``I've been
shopping in their catalog for years, and it's great to actually
shop at the store. It's beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it is. But then so are most of the shops.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Hawken, a familiar name to catalog shoppers, opened
its second metro store at the Marietta site.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part we carry most of the items in our catalog,
said manager Phoebe Brown. ``We have all the gardening items but
not women's clothing. We're known for our fine-quality teak
furniture from Java and English gardening tools.''
</P>
<P>
   This handsome store also carries home decor items: pots, French
dishes and some indoor furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The whole family can shop at the Avenue East Cobb. Talbot's
stocks a wide variety of traditional women's dresses and suits
while the White House/Black Market boutique offers an elegant
interior showcasing women's casual outfits as well as that perfect
little black dress. As the name implies, most of the merchandise is
black or white. In fact, the right side of the store is dedicated
to black and the left to white, with a smattering of pale gray and
taupe.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for casual clothing will find no shortages at
Banana Republic, Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch and Chico's Casual Clothing.
</P>
<P>
   If something a bit more avant-garde is on your shopping list,
consider Pacific Sunwear, where, along with a huge selection of
cargo pants, you can pick up funky Bullhead black satin jeans set
off by white stitching. Called club pants, these are all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   BabyGap and Gymboree are havens for parents.
</P>
<P>
   For those with a culinary bent, Williams-Sonoma provides a
wonderland ranging from professional-quality cookware, specialty
food items and casual dishware.
</P>
<P>
   During a busy Saturday afternoon at Williams-Sonoma, Harold
Bishop was loading up on some heavy-duty Calphalon pans as a
wedding gift for his sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can't cook very well,'' he said, ``but she wants to learn,
so I figured I'd inspire her with the same pans I use.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucked away near Williams-Sonoma sits V. Reed Gallery, which
just moved to the Avenue from its Virginia-Highland digs. Owner
Barry Rosenstein offers contemporary art and whimsical objects
ranging from domed glass cake plates painted with splashy pink
roses to cockeyed clay dogs.
</P>
<P>
   If you need a little break from the shopping, consider a visit
to Borders Books &AMP; Music, where you can wander among the latest
best sellers, hunt for that classical CD or dig up your favorite
video before settling down with a pastry and a cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From I-75 north take Exit 112 (Ga. 120 Loop)
toward Roswell (east). Exit off 120 Loop to Ga. 120 (Roswell Road).
Turn right and pass through the Johnson Ferry and Roswell roads
intersection. The Avenue East Cobb is on the left-hand side of
Roswell Road across from Harris Teeter.
</P>
<P>
   From Ga. 400 north take the Northridge Road exit and go west to
Ga. 9. Turn right and go to Marietta Highway (Ga. 120) and turn
left. Go about 7 miles just past the Timber Ridge Road traffic
light. The Avenue East Cobb is a quarter-mile on the right. If you
cross Johnson Ferry Road, you've passed the center.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most stores open 10 a.m.-9 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays;
12:30-5:30 p.m. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Plenty of free parking in the center.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Stores are accessible but some of the
sidewalks have steps rather than ramps.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Available in the management office.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: The Avenue East Cobb management office,
770-303-2806.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More restaurants are due to open this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Rockets. Located near the center's splashy water
fountain, this retro eatery serves up '50s-style burgers, fries,
shakes and malteds, along with plenty of oldies on the jukebox. You
can eat inside or get walk-up service and munch on that burger
alfresco. Prices range from $2-$3.25.
</P>
<P>
   Borders Cafe Espresso. Here you'll find mini-pizzas, pastries,
smoothies and cappuccinos when it's time to take a break from
shopping. If hanging out is your thing, the folks at Borders
encourage customers to pull out a magazine from the rack, order a
cup of java and relax for as long as they want. All they ask is
that you replace the magazine when you leave. Prices range from
$1.50-$4.75.
</P>
<P>
   While browsing through the Avenue East Cobb, we found...
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Beaded black sweater, Kroshetta, $64, over Black Market
Spandex dress, $78. The White House/Black Market, 770-971-7315.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tumi expandable black leather carry-on, $595. Bentley's
Luggage and Gifts, 770-321-2408.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ralph, clay pit bull by Chris Menconi. $600. V. Reed Gallery,
770-971-0733.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  All-Clad Ltd. 10-piece cookware set, $629. Williams-Sonoma,
678-560-3660.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Belvedere upholstered sofa. Sand velvet fabric, $1,299.
Pottery Barn, 678-560-3590.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Salt Rub spa in a jar body scrub, 21.2 ounce, $29.50. Origins,
770-578-1151.
</P>
<P>
   Shops at the Avenue East Cobb:
</P>
<P>
   Apparel
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, 770-971-7124
</P>
<P>
   Allen-Edmonds Shoes, 770-509-5549
</P>
<P>
   Ann Taylor, 678-560-1937
</P>
<P>
   Athlete's Foot, 770-565-3440
</P>
<P>
   Banana Republic, 678-560-0597
</P>
<P>
   Chico's Casual Clothing, 770-321-5624
</P>
<P>
   GAP, 770-579-5678
</P>
<P>
   Gap Body, 770-579-5678
</P>
<P>
   Harold's, 770-509-9344
</P>
<P>
   Jos A. Bank, 770-973-3288
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Sunwear, 770-579-1227
</P>
<P>
   Swim 'N Sport, 770-578-4227
</P>
<P>
   Talbot's, 770-578-8988
</P>
<P>
   Victoria's Secret, 770-321-4934
</P>
<P>
   White House/Black Market, 770-971-7315
</P>
<P>
   Books
</P>
<P>
   Borders Books &AMP; Music, 770-565-0947
</P>
<P>
   Children's apparel
</P>
<P>
   BabyGap, 770-579-5678
</P>
<P>
   GapKids, 770-579-5678
</P>
<P>
   Gymboree, 678-560-0527
</P>
<P>
   Home furnishings/decor
</P>
<P>
   Bed, Bath &AMP; Beyond, 770-971-2405
</P>
<P>
   Pottery Barn, 678-560-3590
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Hawken, 770-578-8771
</P>
<P>
   Williams-Sonoma, 678-560-3660
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Morrow writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
