<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNUSUAL-COLLEGE-KID-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY DAD IS A REBEL LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By RANDY KENNEDY  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    It's a familiar, if not typical, situation: a young man living
dirt cheap so he can pay back the costs of a top-flight college
education _ Harvard, magna cum laude; Columbia graduate school,
with honors.
 &HT;    But a simple phone call to the New York City railroad apartment
of Philippe Wamba can blur this snapshot beyond recognition.
 &HT;    Sometimes the call is from a friend who warns him that his
father is, once again, in the sights of an assassination plot. Or
it's his mother assuring him that his father is OK. Or it's
reporters wanting to know what he has heard.
 &HT;    When the phone rings this afternoon, there's just a click on the
other end and then static. ``That was probably my dad,'' he says.
``A lot of times he calls, and it doesn't go through.''
 &HT;    This is because Dad, Prof. Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, is calling
from an unreliable satellite phone in sub-Saharan Africa, where he
