distracted.
 &HT;    But on the subject of his American education as a preparation
for life in African politics, he was quite animated: ``To put it
simply,'' he said, ``I was not radicalized about Africa until I
came to the United States. It is strange, but I became much more
aware of what was going on in Congo in the United States than I had
ever been in Congo.''
 &HT;    About Philippe, he answered my questions indirectly, with a
story. ``When he was in secondary school, I asked him, 'What do you
