<HEADLINE>
STUDENT, 13, ACCUSED OF USING STUN GUN ON PEER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA and SARAH YANG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An eighth-grader who allegedly used a stun gun
on another San Francisco middle school students faces possible
felony charges and expulsion from school.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred in a crowded hallway at Hoover Middle
School just before lunch Tuesday as students were leaving gym
class, the authorities said. The eighth-grader, 13, apparently
grabbed a sixth-grade student and shocked the victim on the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Police Lt. David Oberhoffer said the boy then either dropped the
stun gun or handed it to a friend who didn't know what had
happened, and walked out to the playground.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, 11, and a group of students who witnessed the attack
immediately reported the incident to the principal, who summoned
paramedics, said school district spokeswoman Elaine Koury. The
paramedics found the victim to be fine, except for two welts on his
chest.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth-grader, who was later arrested, was taken to the
Youth Guidance Center and faces charges of assault with a deadly
weapon and possession of a stun gun on school grounds, both
felonies.
</P>
<P>
   He also was suspended from school and the district has
instituted proceedings to expel him. It is against state law to
take a stun gun or any other kind of weapon onto a school campus.
</P>
<P>
   Koury said she wasn't certain what prompted the attack. The two
boys weren't fighting, and may not even have known each other, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like you have something new, you try it out,''
she said. ``It sounds like it was the case of a 13-year-old boy
using very poor judgment, which is part of being 13.''
</P>
</TEXT>
