<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4638 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SCHOOL-CHOICE-HNS &LR;      09-08 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CHOICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SEES LITTLE EVIDENCE THAT CHARTER, MAGNET SCHOOLS WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One in four children has left the neighborhood
school in favor of a magnet, charter or voucher program, despite
lax oversight and scant evidence of academic success, according to
a two-year study released Wednesday by an academic think tank.
</P>
<P>
   The Policy Analysis for California Education (PACE) study,
``Abundant Hopes, Scarce Evidence of Results,'' concludes that
alternatives to traditional schools are wildly popular but
unproven.
</P>
<P>
   The national report analyzed research on the effectiveness of
magnet, charter and private schools, voucher programs and open
enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tidal wave of support for the school-choice
movement,'' said the co-author of the report, Luis Huerta. ``But, I
was surprised and distressed by the scarcity of hard evidence
backing advocates' claims that school choice boosts achievement and
pressures public schools to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   School choice, an umbrella term that encompasses home schooling,
charter schools and public and private scholarships, has become a
rallying call in many parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 percent of children _ some 7 million nationwide _ opt
out of their neighborhood public school, an increase from 11
percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In California, nearly 500,000 students _ 9 percent of the
state's enrollment _ attend alternative schools. Ten percent attend
private schools, a number unchanged since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choice movement is blossoming largely in the dark _ for
the most part ignoring the lessons gained from past educational
successes and failures, and proceeding without a clear research
agenda to evaluate the effectiveness of new incarnations,'' Huerta
said.
</P>
<P>
   PACE is a think tank run by the University of California at
Berkeley and Stanford University. Among the key findings of the
study:
</P>
<P>
   _ Magnet schools, created in the 1970s in response to districts
roiled by mandatory integration, are credited with keeping white
families in urban districts. Magnet programs offer a particular
focus, such as technology or performing arts.
</P>
<P>
   Results, however, are mixed: Test scores from magnet programs in
San Antonio and St. Louis went up, while scores in a New York
program declined.
</P>
<P>
   _ Open enrollment means parents opt out of their assigned
neighborhood school and select another one either within or outside
their district. The research shows no significant gains
attributable solely to open enrollment. In a 1997 study of open
enrollment in California, 70 percent of districts reported no
change in student achievement, while 13 percent reported
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charter schools, which originated in Minnesota in 1991, are
publicly funded and largely free of state regulations and union
contracts. Such schools attract better-educated, more affluent
parents, raising questions about what happens to children left in
failing public schools. While the study found no proof that charter
schools boost achievement _ no study has tracked children for more
than a year _ or provide competitive incentive for faltering public
schools to improve, there is a higher level of parental
satisfaction and involvement with charter schools than public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vouchers and private scholarships, first proposed by Nobel
Prize-winning economist Milton Friedman in the mid-1950s, provide
public or private money for children who enroll in a private
school.
</P>
<P>
   Initial findings suggest that poor children in Milwaukee and New
York City who remain in voucher programs over a few years do
somewhat better in math but not in reading, compared with similar
students in neighborhood schools.
</P>
<P>
   But, because these students come from families that took the
initiative to move their children, it's difficult to know whether
the results are attributable to a motivated home environment or the
voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   ``From breakfast cereals to SUVs, consumers demand choices in a
democratic society,'' said Bruce Fuller, an education professor at
UC-Berkeley and the director of PACE. ``But as market dynamics are
used to energize school reform, we have yet to see solid evidence
of achievement gains.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For advocates of school choice, however, the dismal record of
some public schools is reason enough to create an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley venture capitalist Tim Draper, who lost faith in
California's public education, is crafting a school choice
initiative to go before voters in November. The initiative will
offer $4,000 in taxpayer money to parents who want to remove their
children from public school and enroll them in private or parochial
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer that if people are given a choice, then
both types of schools will improve,'' Draper said. ``Right now,
there's no competitor to the public model.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical of the PACE report, Draper said: ``Researchers often
shape policy to make a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly not enough choice now,'' he said. ``If
you're a child stuck in a failing school, whether in San Francisco
or Oakland, you really don't have a way out. This choice initiative
will give parents a way out and it will cause other schools to
improve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
