<SLUG> BC-LEVI-STRAUSS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEVI STRAUSS ENLISTS A MAN WITH MARKETING MUSCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The appointment of PepsiCo Inc. executive Philip
Marineau to lead the closely held Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. brings an
outsider with marketing muscle to the 149-year-old jeans
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Levi's former president, Peter Jacobi,
wanted to happen when he announced his resignation eight months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for the company. They seemed to get somebody who
had the right credentials for the position,'' said Jacobi, who was
not involved in the selection process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly they brought him in because of his marketing skill and
brand-development experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Marineau _ the head of PepsiCo's PepsiCola
North America unit _ to president and chief executive marks only
the second time San Francisco-based Levi Strauss has picked a
non-family member to run the company. In the first case, Robert
Grohman ran Levi Strauss from 1981 to 1984, but he had come up
through the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobi, 55, said he also thought it would be healthier for the
company to select a chief executive from outside the apparel
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like he's the perfect guy for what the company was
looking for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparel consultants say Levi's selection of an outside means the
jeans maker is serious about turning around its image.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an open acknowledgment on the part of the current
management that they've run out of ideas,'' said Kurt Barnard,
president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report in Upper Montclair, N.J.
``He is an outsider and is not encumbered and encrusted with years
of old ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnard said Marineau needs to resuscitate the Levi brand, which
has been taking a beating from Old Navy, the Gap and Abercrombie &AMP;
Fitch, as well as trendy jeans such as LEI and Mudd.
</P>
<P>
   The key, according to Levi watchers, is Marineau's marketing
background. He is widely credited with helping Pepsi appeal to a
broader audience as well as introducing the Pepsi One brand during
his 20-month tenure as president of the North American beverage
unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Marineau is essentially a marketing professional. As a
marketing professional, it should not make too much a difference
whether the product is a pair of jeans or a glass of Pepsi,''
Barnard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he can refocus the brand image. That's what he's best
at,'' said Harry Bernard, a partner of San Francisco strategic
marketing firm Colton Bernard Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But Bernard was less sure of Marineau's ability to buck the
mentality of what he calls the ``old masters of the 501,'' or some
of the longtime Levi executives still with the company. ``Will he
bring the culture up to his level or will he become engulfed by
that culture?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Marineau, 52, steps in as head of Levi Strauss on Sept. 27,
he will arrive at one of the toughest times in the company's recent
history. Sales last year dropped 13 percent to $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Levi laid off about 7,000 employees, and this year
announced plans to cut 30 percent more of its work force by closing
plants. Much of the company's troubles are blamed on its products'
loss of popularity, especially Levi's trademark five-pocket jeans,
as well as on increased competition.
</P>
<P>
   Marineau also takes the Levi role at a time when he had been
considered the front-runner to succeed Pepsi chairman Roger Enrico.
Steven Reinemund, who on Tuesday was named Pepsi's chief operating
officer, is now considered the likely successor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
