<HEADER>
A4683 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     09-08 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T MEDIA GIVE CAPRIATI SOME PEACE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The media made Jennifer Capriati cry the other day. They must be
so proud of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati is a 23-year-old professional tennis player who is
attempting to recapture the tennis brilliance of her childhood and
also trying to live down the personal mistakes she made as a
rebellious teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   The media have set the ground rules: Capriati can create
whatever future her talent will allow on the tennis court _ but her
past belongs to them.
</P>
<P>
   There is no statute of limitations on youthful indiscretions in
this country, no deferred adjudication program by which a public
person can have some early lapse of judgment erased from his record
and declared off limits to continued media scrutiny. An adolescent
ax-killer can have his juvenile court record sealed and stashed
away forever, but a teen-age tennis phenom's legal and social
misdemeanors are fair game forever.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati was an international tennis star before she was old
enough to drive, and the pressure evidently took its toll. Before
she was old enough to vote, her career was on the skids.
</P>
<P>
   Before she managed to pull herself together and begin the
comeback that carried her all the way to the fourth round of the
1999 U.S. Open, Capriati would be cited for shoplifting and
arrested for marijuana possession as she explored ``a darker side
of my confusion in a confusing world.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``darker side'' quote was part of a statement that Capriati
read to the media after her Labor Day loss to fellow former phenom
Monica Seles. The gist of the statement was that she didn't want to
talk about her messed-up teenhood anymore and wished that the media
would stop asking about it.
</P>
<P>
   Dream on, Jennifer.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati will move on when the media say she can move on _ and
not one minute, one month or one millennium sooner. According to a
column in Monday's New York Times, reporters are still asking the
questions because they are not satisfied with Capriati's answers.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati's failure, it seems, is that she has not been
sufficiently forthcoming, sufficiently confessional, sufficiently
apologetic or sufficiently evangelistic in warning others to avoid
the mistakes she made.
</P>
<P>
   Does this sound familiar? Sure it does; it's the same malarkey
we've been hearing about presidential front-runner George W. Bush
and allegations that he used illegal drugs many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The media's obsession with long-ago stupidities is annoying
enough in the case of a man who wants to be president of the United
States. But Jennifer Capriati is a tennis player, for heaven's
sake.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati isn't asking citizens of the world's lone remaining
superpower to put her in charge the nation's nuclear arsenal. She's
asking sportswriters to let her work on her backhand without
constantly rehashing the day she walked away from a mall jewelry
booth with a $15 ring she hadn't paid for. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And guess what. Tennis fans don't want to hear about that stuff.
What the fans want to know is how fast Capriati's serves zoom
across the net and whether she's physically fit enough to compete
with the uncommonly athletic women who make their living playing
tennis nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   Such are questions that Capriati must answer _ but she must
answer them on the tennis court.
</P>
<P>
   The other questions, the ones that surface in media interviews
and post-match news conferences, are questions that Capriati
needn't answer until and unless she wants to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Where in the world did the media get the idea that they are
entitled to decide what a public person must discuss about his
private life and when he must discuss it? What provision of the
Constitution confers upon the media the authority to establish a
universal standard for self-revelation that must be adhered to by
anyone who dares to step into the public arena?
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, most of us have had it up to here with celebrities
confessing their sins, with public figures blabbing their deepest
secrets and innermost feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who stands up and says, ``I refuse to talk about it''
deserves our undying gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
