<HEADLINE>
GETTING THE MOST FROM A CEILING FAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A ceiling fan can help keep a room cooler in the summer and
warmer in the winter. It uses less power than an air-conditioner,
so it can help keep electrical bills down.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging a fan is not especially difficult, but care should be
taken to situate it where it will do the most good. Ideally, the
fan should be in the center of the ceiling. If this is not
possible, then it should be far enough from the wall so that the
tips of the fan blades will have 24 inches of clearance. If the fan
is closer then this, it will produce noisy air turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   The fan must also be high enough so the spinning blades will not
hit anyone standing in the room. You will need at least seven feet
of space between the bottom of the fan and the floor for this. If
you have a ceiling light fixture, you can remove it and replace it
with the fan; then you can connect the fan to the existing electric
circuit. Otherwise you will have to run a special circuit to power
the fan.
</P>
<P>
   The first step when doing any electrical work is to turn off the
power to the circuit. First, remove the appropriate fuse or flip
the correct breaker at the service panel. After that, you can
remove the ceiling fixture. Some ceiling lights are held in place
with a lock nut that screws onto a central nipple in the junction
box. When you unscrew the lock nut, the fixture will drop down.
Other fixtures may be held in place with two bolts that screw onto
a hanger strap across the junction box. These fixtures can be
removed by unscrewing the bolts.
</P>
<P>
   The fixture will still be attached to the electrical wires
coming through the junction box. Take care when disconnecting
these, because there is a remote possibility that you flipped the
wrong breaker and the circuit is still hot. Unscrew the solderless
connectors, being careful not to touch the bare wires, then probe
the wires with a circuit tester to make sure the power is indeed
off. Now you can disconnect the wires and remove the fixture.
</P>
<P>
   You are now ready to mount the fan. All manufacturers provide
hardware to hang their fans, and while the assemblies may differ
from manufacturer to manufacturer, they are all variations of three
methods. One type uses lag bolts, a J-hook or a ball-and-socket
hanger to attach the fan directly to a framing member like a
ceiling joist. Another uses a special hanger (one model is called
``fan brace'') that expands between ceiling joists. With the third
method, the fan hanger is attached directly to the junction box.
</P>
<P>
   Attaching the fan directly to a framing member can offer a safe
and stable arrangement provided the framing member is secure.
Mounting the fan on an unstable wooden cross brace between the
joists can lead to problems. Before attaching the mounting bracket
to any cross brace, check to make sure the brace is firmly nailed
to both joists. There should be no play when you attempt to wiggle
or twist it.
</P>
<P>
   It is better to drive the mounting screw directly into a joist.
However, it must be positioned in the center of the joist. An easy
way to find the center is by first locating the joist, then
drilling a series of small holes in a straight line until you
locate the sides of the joist then position the screw in between.
Don't worry about the holes; they will be covered later by the fan
canopy.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find a suitable cross brace or if the joists are
not centered in the room, you can use an expansion brace to hold
the fan. Open the brace until it spans the gap between the joists _
that's approximately 14 1/2 inches _ then place it between the
joists. You may be able to do this from above in the attic, or you
can reach through the ceiling hole where the junction box was
positioned. Twisting the horizontal brace will cause it to expand
and lock firmly between the two joists.
</P>
<P>
   The third method, attaching directly to the junction box, is the
least secure method. Basically the fan mount is screwed to the
flanges, sometimes called ``ears,'' in the corners of the junction
box. Many building codes prohibit this type of attachment because
the flanges have only a few screw threads and vibrations from the
rotating fan could cause the bolts to work loose.
</P>
<P>
   Once the hanger assembly is in place, you can position the fan
and connect the electrical wires. Use wire nuts to connect the
fan's white wire to the circuit white (neutral) and the black to
the black (hot). Connect the ground wires as indicated by the
manufacturer. If you have any doubts about making the electrical
hook-up, consult an electrician.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
