<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEGA'S DREAMCAST: A TOY, YES, BUT A PC AT HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sega's new Dreamcast video game console, which goes on sale in
the United States today, is the first of the next-generation home
game machines to arrive on these shores. As a game machine its
power is unrivaled, except by high-end personal computers costing
more than 10 times as much, and it makes the graphics on the
current market leader, the Sony Playstation, appear grainy and
jerky. The Dreamcast is the closest thing to an arcade-quality game
experience you can get at home.
</P>
<P>
   But the $199 Dreamcast is more than just a game console. Unlike
earlier generations of game machines, which were closer to toys
than to computers, the Dreamcast blurs the distinction between PC
and game console. It has a 56K modem, for example, and it comes
with software for connecting to the Internet for activities like
e-mail, Web browsing and online chatting. Oddly, it comes from the
box with Internet software but no games, which have to be purchased
separately.
</P>
<P>
   Some people say that inexpensive, Internet-enabled game consoles
like the Dreamcast, along with its future rivals, the Sony
Playstation II and Nintendo's Project Dolphin, will become an
alternative to PC's for millions of people who want to connect to
the Internet through their television screens.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, people who are already on the Net might be alarmed by
the prospect of millions of Internet newbies whose common bond
appears to be a love of Sonic the Hedgehog (Sega's most popular
game character) and an ability to type with their thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a mistake, however, to dismiss these new game
consoles as frivolous. While the Sega Dreamcast clearly has the
pedigree of a game machine, it has the digital genetics of a
computer. Besides the built-in modem, it has a powerful
microprocessor, fancy 3-D graphics and audio chip sets, a CD-ROM
drive that also plays audio compact disks, 26 megabytes of various
kinds of system memory, and _ surprise _ even a custom version of
the Microsoft Windows CE operating system.
</P>
<P>
   All play and no work makes the Dreamcast a very dull toy. The
presence of Windows CE makes the Dreamcast a very interesting
device because it means that thousands of software developers could
create applications for it with relative ease if the Dreamcast
gains a large enough following.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreamcast console has four high-speed ports on the front,
and it comes with a single game controller that plugs into one of
them. Other options for these ports include extra controllers,
keyboards, steering wheels, force-feedback joysticks, microphones,
guns and fishing reels that jerk in conjunction with the action on
screen and, down the road, digital cameras and other smart devices.
</P>
<P>
   A serial port on the back can work with a printer or a storage
device like a Zip drive, although Sega would have been smarter to
include a Universal Serial Bus, or USB, port instead.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreamcast is built around a 128-bit microprocessor. The
current market leaders for game consoles, the Sony Playstation and
the Nintendo 64, use 64-bit processors. Basically, that means the
200-MHz Dreamcast chip can process twice the information its rivals
can in any tick of the clock, enabling programmers to add
sophisticated software features like the ability to recognize and
exploit patterns in the user's playing style.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the system can learn and adapt to give the
player a greater challenge over time, which is a trait shared by
some of the newer and more advanced PC games.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, about five years ago, Sega sold more game
machines than Sony and Nintendo combined. But for a number of
reasons, few of which were technical, Sega botched the introduction
of its ill-fated Saturn system, the predecessor to Dreamcast,
allowing Sony and Nintendo to take over. Today Sega has less than a
2 percent share of the market, said Kelly Henry, an analyst with
the International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Video game players appear willing to embrace whatever system
gives them the most realistic thrills, and for the next year at
least, that will be Dreamcast. Sega said more than 250,000
Dreamcast systems had been ordered in advance of today's nationwide
rollout, and the company expects to sell 1 million systems by the
end of this year. Even so, Sega has no illusions about toppling the
market leaders. At best, the Dreamcast will keep Sega competitive
for a while.
</P>
<P>
   It is no exaggeration to say that Dreamcast is Sega's last
chance to remain competitive with Sony, Nintendo and perhaps even
Microsoft, which has been exploring the possibility of creating its
own video console machine. (Microsoft is already one of the world's
largest makers of computer games and peripheral devices for PC
games.)
</P>
<P>
   But if Sega has a year's head start on Sony and Nintendo in the
128-bit processor race, that also means that the Playstation II and
Dolphin systems will be a year more advanced in their own
technologies when they finally arrive in 2000. We already know that
the Playstation II will be backward-compatible with existing
Playstation games and that the Dolphin system will use a DVD drive,
which will make possible even better video and sound.
</P>
<P>
   Sega says its Dreamcast system is designed to take advantage of
new technologies that will be developed in the next year or two,
but that may be whistling in the dark. A year from now, Dreamcast
will be toast unless it can lock its customers into the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Like nearly everything else these days, the new Sega system has
been transformed by the Internet. When attached to a phone line,
the Dreamcast console can be used as an Internet terminal. Users
can send and receive e-mail, participate in chat groups or get
game-playing tips on the Sega Dreamcast Online Gaming Network, and
browse the Web. Sega says Dreamcast users can connect through any
Internet service provider, but it lists AT&AMP;T Worldnet as its
preferred service and includes a Worldnet software disk. And AT&AMP;T
offers a special deal on a keyboard that attaches to the Dreamcast
console for virtually thumb-free typing.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Dreamcast owners will not be able to do, however, is
play games against one another over the Internet, a rather
astonishing lapse in what is otherwise an impressive system.
Already, hundreds of thousands of PC users compete against one
another over the Internet or private game networks, making online
games one of the Internet's most popular activities.
</P>
<P>
   A Sega spokesman said the company would offer online competitive
games ``within the next 12 months or so.'' Until then, Dreamcast
users can only taunt one another with e-mails and chat. There's not
much sport in that.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, however, the Dreamcast and its game-console
rivals will emerge as network information devices, ready to slug it
out with low-cost PC's, set-top boxes like Web TV, smart telephones
and other information appliances. Let the games begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
