<HEADER>
A4696 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-CHAPMAN-FOOD-COLUMN-T     09-08 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPMAN-FOOD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESH VEGGIES REVIVE INTEREST IN COOKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There comes a time, usually once or twice a year, when I would
rather be force-fed dry, stale tofu than have to crank up the
stove.
</P>
<P>
   It is a late-summer kind of thing, generally around right now. I
just lose interest under the unrelenting heat and stumble home each
day to huddle near the air conditioner and watch baseball on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Rangers fans know that can cause a different set of
frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   Not cooking isn't a really big deal at our house. We enjoy
take-out. But after a month or so, it gets a little pricey, to say
nothing of redundant.
</P>
<P>
   This malaise, or affliction, if you will, can last interminably
unless I force myself out of the easy chair and onto the road. The
cure is a simple prescription that calls for one 30-mile drive.
</P>
<P>
   I go to the Dallas Farmers Market.
</P>
<P>
   The market, with its rows and rows of produce, hits me like a
sugar rush hits a hyper preschooler. The smells, the colors and
tastes come alive, and slowly they raise my battery levels to fully
loaded.
</P>
<P>
   I always come home energized, carrying bags of vegetables I
didn't know I needed. I can't wait to get in the kitchen. Problem
gone.
</P>
<P>
   I just got back from the market.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Forde works for Pat's Pea Pasture, a Canton produce
company that farms in East Texas. She's been at the market for
about 35 years, she says, and she has a good grasp of what's in and
what's out.
</P>
<P>
   East Texas tomatoes, for example, are on the way out, she says.
The season is getting kind of long in East Texas, and the lack of
rain has taken its toll.
</P>
<P>
   But over at D.L. Stubblefield's stand, there are stacks and
stacks of ripe beefsteak tomatoes from Jacksonville. They are
``slicers,'' meaning it would be criminal to do anything but cut
them into big, thick slices and serve them with just a hint of salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose it would be all right to mound a little goat cheese on
top.
</P>
<P>
   The beefsteaks come four or five big juicy ones to a basket for
$3. The catch is, these aren't the cardboard-tasting grocery-store
tomatoes that can sit on the counter for a week without ripening.
</P>
<P>
   The beefsteaks are cheap because they are fully ripened and
won't last much longer. Of course, they can be sacrificed for
sauces, then frozen. It is a shame to treat slicers that way,
though.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other tomatoes at the market are coming from
Tennessee. Some are arriving from Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Black-eyed peas are still plentiful, but growers warn that the
current supply is about to dry up. The old fields have given about
all they can, and the new pastures won't yield anything until the
rains begin.
</P>
<P>
   Texas onions are still coming into the market, along with sweet
corn and peppers. If you are looking for bargains, red bell peppers
are cheap right now. But they, too, have ripened and must be used
soon, or chopped and frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit, especially watermelons, is plentiful. The melons are from
Texas and Oklahoma. The strawberries are from California; the
blueberries and peaches are from Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Farmers Market is just off Interstate 30 on Pearl
Street, nestled right next to the downtown business district. It is
open every day, all day, with the exception of Christmas and New
Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a recipe for those juicy, ripe tomatoes. It can be made
under the broiler, but better yet, it can be prepared outside on
the barbecue grill. The Bruschetta di Pomodori recipe is from the
newly released ``Savoring Italy,'' a Time-Life Book from
Williams-Sonoma ($39.95). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BRUSCHETTA DI POMODORI (FRESH TOMATO TOASTS)
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   _ 6 fresh basil leaves, torn into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   _ Coarse salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   _ 8 slices coarse country bread, each about 1/2-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 large cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler, or prepare a fire in a charcoal grill.
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, combine the tomatoes, basil, olive oil, vinegar and
salt. Toss well.
</P>
<P>
   Place the bread on a baking sheet or grill rack and broil or
grill, turning once, until lightly toasted on both sides, about 2
minutes total. Remove from the broiler or grill and immediately rub
one side of each slice with the garlic cloves.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the grilled bread, garlic side up, on a serving platter
and spoon on the tomatoes, dividing evenly. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Note: You can add some chopped garlic if you like. A thin slice
of ricotta salata (or a mild feta) laid atop the tomatoes is a nice
addition and can turn this antipasto into a light lunch.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman is a food columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX 76101, or e-mail him: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1601EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
