<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-HOTELS-     09-08 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-HOTELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT TO START NET HOTEL-PRICING SERVICE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imitating a competitor's patented approach, the Microsoft Corp.
is introducing an Internet service that lets consumers name their
own prices for hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The concept was an innovation of the heavily promoted
Priceline.com service, which last year introduced a system to let
people enter the prices they would be willing to pay for airline
tickets. It has since expanded to hotels, cars and mortgage loans.
</P>
<P>
   On both Priceline and the new Price Matcher service that
Microsoft is introducing Tuesday on its Expedia travel site,
consumers specify the city, dates, room rate and hotel rating (one
to five stars) they are seeking. The service picks the individual
hotel, and automatically charges the amount of the full stay to the
buyer's credit card. No refunds or changes are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have become so enamored by the potential of this
system that Priceline, which went public last year, has a market
value of some $9.9 billion, more than any airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is looking for a way to hook onto Priceline's coat
tails,'' said Kenneth J. Orton, chief strategist at Cognititive, a
San Francisco consulting firm, and former chief executive of
Preview Travel, an Internet travel service. He said Microsoft's
move was meant to appeal more to investors than to travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while Wall Street is devoted to Priceline, consumer
reaction has been more tepid because of the restrictions that the
system imposes. If the service can find a hotel room or plane
ticket at the specified price, the consumer must buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Barton, the general manager of Expedia, said that such
restrictions are necessary to get the hotels to agree to take lower
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good for consumers because they can get great deals,''
he said. ``And it's good for hotels because they can put people
into rooms that may go empty while protecting their published price
structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Barton declined to say whether Microsoft would introduce a
similar system for airline tickets and car rentals, but he said
there was no reason that it would not if the hotel offering was
successful.
</P>
<P>
   One factor, however, that might impede Microsoft is that
Priceline has been granted a patent on the central mechanism of its
system: the concept of a ``conditional purchase offer'' in which a
consumer is committed to buy something if the seller can meet their
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Ek, a spokesman for Priceline, said that the company had
not licensed its patent to Microsoft and that the company was still
studying the Microsoft site to see if it was an infringement on its
patent.
</P>
<P>
   Barton, of Microsoft, declined to comment on Priceline's patent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both Priceline and Expedia buy blocks of hotel rooms at
wholesale rates and then sell them to those who bid higher prices.
There is a well-developed market for such bulk purchases of hotel
rooms, since hotels are willing to take less money in return for a
volume purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Meristar Hotels and Resorts, which operates 218 hotels under the
Hilton, Sheraton, Radisson and other brands, now sells 1 percent to
2 percent of its rooms through Priceline, said David McCaslin, its
president. It will also take part in the Microsoft program, but
McCaslin said he did not expect such a sales approach to dominate
the hotel industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do your job properly, you will create your own
demand,'' he said. ``But I don't think any hotel is so good they
are selling out at full rate 365 days a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Expedia already books reservations online through more
conventional models. In the second quarter, it sold $183 million
worth of air travel, hotel rooms and car rentals. In addition to
receiving commissions on those sales _ often $5 or $10 for airline
tickets _ it sells advertising and other promotional opportunities
to travel providers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-07-99 2325EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
