<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SUN-NETWORK-COMPUTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN TO INTRODUCE AN EVEN MORE BASIC NETWORK COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Sun Microsystems Inc. will introduce a
second generation of its network computing business in New York on
Wednesday with a stripped-down ``computing appliance'' for
corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   Like all so-called network computers, the new device, named the
Sun Ray, relies on a central server computer for its processing
power, data storage and most software applications.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sun Ray is extremely basic, even by network computer
standards, with only enough processing power and memory to display
images passed to it by software on the server. It has no disk
drives or other storage devices.
</P>
<P>
   The first widespread commercial availability of the long-awaited
network computer comes three years after the device was made a
rallying cry against Microsoft by Sun's chief executive, Scott
McNealy, and Oracle Corp.'s chairman, Lawrence J. Ellison. The two
executives have waged war against the personal computer, which they
argue is too expensive and complex.
</P>
<P>
   Conceived as a simple and inexpensive alternative to the PC, the
network computer centralizes most of the expense and complexity of
computing in the powerful servers.
</P>
<P>
   The first generation of network computers from Sun and IBM, both
based on the Java programming language, have largely failed as PC
prices fell. But Sun executives said Tuesday that the company had
not given up on its strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Ray will be priced as low as $9.99 a month for a
five-year lease, or it can be purchased for $499. A complete system
including server computers, software and monitors will be leased
for $30 a month for each user.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is network computing 2.0,'' said Ed Zander, Sun's
president and chief operating officer. ``We've learned a lot in the
last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Sun would focus on several corporate markets and
intended to use its recently acquired Star Office business to offer
users PC-type productivity applications like word processing and
spreadsheets as well as network applications like Web browsers,
e-mail and access to corporate data bases.
</P>
<P>
   Zander said it was also possible to link the system with a
Windows NT server so that Sun Ray users could run standard Windows
applications over the network.
</P>
<P>
   Kimball Brown, an analyst with Dataquest in San Jose, Calif.,
called Sun Ray a smart move _ not in terms of killing Windows or
Microsoft's Office suite, but in increasing Sun's corporate market
share. He added that eventually the technology would be well suited
to the growing number of networked homes with high-speed Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Ray itself is a small box that is connected to a
network, a monitor, a mouse and a keyboard. Each unit can be
personalized to the needs of an individual user by means of a Smart
Card that identifies the user's needs and preferences and also acts
as a security device.
</P>
<P>
   A software system called Hot Desk, which runs on the central
server, permits a user to insert his or her Smart Card into any Sun
Ray on the network and instantly personalize that unit.
</P>
<P>
   Zander said that the new Sun computing environment was a step
back toward an era of mainframe computers and so-called ``green
screen'' terminals _ but with a major performance difference. Sun
is guaranteeing that users will not have to wait longer than
one-tenth of a second between keystrokes.
</P>
<P>
   Sun executives said a typical network system would link two
servers and 50 to 200 active computer users.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-07-99 2159EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1620EDT &QL; 
