<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4714 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-REDHAT-     09-08 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-REDHAT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS OF A WAYLAID `GIANT-SLAYER' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients. 
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
 By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To judge by Red Hat Software Inc.'s red-hot stock price and
press clippings, one might conclude that software gigagiant
Microsoft Corp. is in for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat is the little North Carolina company that has run up a
$5.6 billion market capitalization by peddling a version of Linux,
the increasingly popular low-cost computer operating system.
</P>
<P>
   But mention Red Hat and Linux to Aubrey Edwards, group product
manager for Microsoft's forthcoming Windows NT upgrade Windows
2000, and he seems almost on the verge of stifling a yawn. ``When
you look at the hype versus the reality today,'' says Edwards,
``there is a big disconnect.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he is whistling in the dark. But then, Microsoft has been
here before.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Java? That was the radical new technology of four years
ago, an upstart product that threatened to smash Windows once and
for all.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the labs of Sun Microsystems Inc. and intended at first
to run cable TV controller boxes, Java wasn't an operating system
like Windows or Linux. Instead it was a much broader system that
challenged some of the most basic principles of computing.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, computer software is very closely linked to the
hardware running it. The Windows operating system is specifically
designed to work with computers that contain Intel Corp.
processors. Apple Computer Inc.'s Macintosh machines use the
PowerPC chip, a different type of processor made by Motorola and
IBM. Windows software can't work with a PowerPC chip, and Mac
software won't talk to an Intel Pentium.
</P>
<P>
   Java attempts to get around all this by creating a ``virtual
machine,'' a piece of software that can run on all kinds of
different computers, from palm-sized data organizers to room-sized
mainframes.
</P>
<P>
   Java programs run in the virtual machine, and so in theory,
never again would programmers have to write different versions of
the same program for every different type of computer. ``Write
once, run everywhere,'' was the battle cry of Java advocates; Sun
even copyrighted the phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, companies that had been battered by competition from
Microsoft embraced Java as a way to get back into the game. Corel
Computer Corp. said it would rewrite its WordPerfect office
software suite entirely in Java, so it would run on any computer.
Lotus Development Corp. announced eSuite, a set of lightweight
office software programs in Java, for use on corporate networks.
</P>
<P>
   And even Microsoft in late 1995 agreed to license the Java
technology from Sun.
</P>
<P>
   (That license agreement spawned a bitter and still-pending
lawsuit between the two companies, with Sun claiming Microsoft is
trying to make unauthorized modifications to Java.)
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate dream for many computer users was software that
would render Windows irrelevant and shrink the power of Microsoft
forever.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't worked out that way. Corel killed its Java office
suite, and while Lotus officials refuse to provide confirmation,
several computer-industry publications have reported that eSuite is
also getting the ax.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's difficult to find any major Java programs on
business or home desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal, says Sun's vice president of software marketing,
George Paolini. ``It hasn't happened because it hasn't needed to
happen,'' he says. ``There's no reason to rewrite an entire office
suite in Java.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially not when it turned out that Java programs
consistently ran much slower than programs written in the
traditional way. Java also had built-in limitations that made the
programs safer to run on corporate networks, but also less useful.
For example, Java was originally designed to prevent users from
saving files to a computer's hard drive _ a good security
precaution, but worse than useless for word processing.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Java was touted as a key tool in another heavily hyped
movement toward ``network computers.'' Instead of keeping software
on each machine, people would use small, cheap computers that would
get all their software from a central server. Java is well-suited
to this approach.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad nobody wanted to buy network computers. Their
unpopularity was yet another blow to the Java movement. ``I think
that this network computing idea will be a major success, but it
may be years before it becomes a major success,'' says Rick Ross,
president of the Java Lobby, an organization of Java programmers.
``A lot of companies will go bankrupt waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Java is far from dead.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, there are still thousands of software
developers cobbling together Java programs, but for purposes quite
different than the overthrow of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Programs such as WordPerfect and other word processors are
called ``client'' applications, and are run by ordinary users. Java
hasn't caught on in that arena. But it turns out Java is a good way
to write programs that run on servers, the powerful machines that
work behind the scenes, running corporate networks and the
Internet. Server-based Java programs make it easy to exchange data
among many types of computers.
</P>
<P>
   Novera Software Inc. in Burlington, Mass. is one of many firms
that make Java software tools to help companies link up their
networked databases. ``It's an excellent language in which to work
to integrate disparate back-office applications,'' says Novera
cofounder Tim Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Plainly there's no need to mourn for Java's fate. But its
success as a sort of welding tool for computer networks is a long
way from the early visions of Java partisans.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Microsoft executives and they'll tell you that a similar
fate awaits Linux. Charles Fitzgerald, director of business
development in Microsoft's software development unit, says the
Linux hype has already peaked. ``Cold hard reality is coming to
bear,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald points to recent benchmark tests by the research firm
Mindcraft Inc., which found Windows NT performs a variety of tasks
faster than Linux. And he says Linux is notoriously complex and
hard to use, making it a poor choice for any but the most
sophisticated users. And Microsoft's Edwards says that Linux lacks
many advanced capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly are categories where Linux is a strong
competitor,'' Fitzgerald admits. For example, he says it makes a
good server for delivering World Wide Web pages. But Fitgerald says
Linux still isn't ready for the heavy-duty tasks that Windows 2000
is designed to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Troan, director of engineering at Red Hat, freely admits
that the buzz over Linux has gotten a bit too loud as the price of
his company's shares has been bid up from 14 on the first day of
trading last month to 84 1/8 at the end of last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Troan says Linux has already avoided one of Java's biggest
mistakes. The first releases of Java were crude and buggy. ``People
set it up as though the first release of immature technology was
going to go out and take over the world,'' Troan says. Linux, on
the other hand, came to public attention after years of buffing and
bug-fixing. Linux was running successfully on thousands of
computers long before the media hype began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably an adolescent now, instead of a toddler,''
Troan says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Java experience suggests that it's too early to say
what Linux will do when it grows up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-08-99 1334EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
