<SLUG> BC-HARRYPOTTER-BOOK-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL THE THIRD TIME STILL BE A CHARM FOR THE BELOVED BOY WIZARD?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The boy is being educated by wizards, but he's not the Wart from
T.H. White's ``The Once and Future King.''
</P>
<P>
   He's skinny and bespectacled, but he's not Encyclopedia Brown
from that eternally popular series of children's novels.
</P>
<P>
   His parents are dead, and he's sometimes in the clutches of mean
relatives, but he's not Cinderella or Snow White or any other
familiar fairy-tale protagonist.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter is, without question, the hottest character in
fiction, with ``Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban'' certain
to top bestseller lists after it hit bookstore shelves Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect tremendous response,'' said Jackie Goodman, general
manager of Borders Books &AMP; Music in Fort Worth, of author J.K.
Rowling's wildly popular series. ``It's the most anticipated book
of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The orphaned, wizard-in-training Harry is charismatic, lovable,
intelligent and daring. He's often able to work magic, is sometimes
a bit of a klutz, and he always, always tries to do the right
thing, even if it means breaking the rules at his
young-wizards-and-witches boarding school.
</P>
<P>
   But Harry isn't unique. ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's
Stone'' and ``Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets,'' the first
two mega-sellers in Rowling's projected seven-book series, had
shoppers blazing a trail to bookstores even though British author
Rowling _ a former schoolteacher, and divorced single mother who
wrote her first Harry tale while on welfare _ didn't blaze a new
literary path. In these children's stories that adults can enjoy,
too, variations of familiar themes still work, and Harry Potter is
proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorcerer's Stone,'' which introduces us to 10-year-old Harry,
borrows generously from past storytellers. This is far from
criminal. ``The Three Investigators'' series that was popular among
youngsters in the 1980s was influenced by the Hardy Boys and Nancy
Drew, those young crime-stopper heroes of a previous generation of
juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   Harry's world has dragons and an evil sorcerer named Lord
Voldemort, who would wreak havoc if only he could once and for all
finish off Harry (see Sauron in Tolkien's ``Lord of the Rings''
trilogy).
</P>
<P>
   Yet Harry's world also has videogames. And the broomsticks Harry
and his pals fly around on during exciting Quidditch matches are
revved up in high-tech style. Harry's Nimbus 2000 broomstick is
today's equivalent of Nancy Drew's sporty roadster _ cutting-edge
transportation for its literary time.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Rowling has done what T.H. White and J.R.R. Tolkien
did before her. The result is the same: bestsellers. Harry
resonates with readers for the same reasons previous generations
loved the Wart and Frodo. He is decent, well-meaning, and behind
the 8-ball often enough that readers easily identify with him.
</P>
<P>
   Harry attends Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry, where
gifted youngsters are trained to do good magical things. Nonmagical
humans are referred to as ``Muggles.'' Muggles are not supposed to
know about this magical Otherworld that exists within their own
world. Adult wizards and witches spend a great deal of time hiding
traces of prestidigitation that Muggles would never understand.
Thus, secret powers form a large part of Harry's life, something
Superman would understand.
</P>
<P>
   Harry's parents were killed by Lord Voldemort in a confrontation
when Harry was a babe. But somehow, Voldemort's powers weren't
sufficient to kill Harry, although the encounter left the infant
with a lightning-shaped scar on his forehead. This has enhanced his
reputation among his magical kind even though Harry is only a
wizard-in-training (some kids at Hogwarts ask for his autograph).
</P>
<P>
   But Harry is not a celebrity outside school. He must spend
holidays at the home of a nasty uncle and aunt, where he sleeps in
a cupboard. His mean Muggle cousin gets dozens of expensive gifts
at Christmas and on his birthday. Harry gets a box of dog biscuits.
(Cinderella and her wicked stepsisters, anyone?)
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   In his first two adventures, Harry discovers his true identity,
begins his studies at Hogwarts, and risks his life to foil
Voldemortian schemes.
</P>
<P>
   These stories take place in real time; Harry, unlike eternal
teen-ager Nancy Drew, is growing up. From enrollment to
matriculation, his stay at Hogwarts lasts seven years, which lends
itself nicely to Rowling's anticipated seven-book series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prisoner of Azkaban'' (Azkaban being a faraway dungeon for
rule-breaking wizards), then, marks almost the halfway point of the
series. It is already apparent that Harry Potter is a landmark _ if
honorably derivative _ children's literary series. The only
question is whether it will continue to be a bestseller for its
four remaining titles.
</P>
<P>
   The answer may lie with its author, who is almost as mysterious
as the character she created.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling is scheduled to visit America next month for a series of
interviews and public readings. Her publisher, Scholastic, normally
a low-key distributor of educational titles, seems unprepared for
the bestseller spotlight. A book editor's routine request for a
photo of Rowling couldn't elicit an immediate reponse. Scholastic
said it wasn't certain that the author would approve of using her
photo for publicity purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what we know about Rowling must be gleaned from media
reports in her native United Kingdom. She is in her early 30s, and
as mentioned, is a former teacher and a divorced single mother. It
took Rowling several years to find an agent and, eventually, get
Harry into print.
</P>
<P>
   The female author/boy hero is a rare fairy-tale tandem.
Encyclopedia Brown's creator was a man; Mary Poppins was the
brainchild of a woman. Mildred Hubble, whose ``The Worst Witch''
adventures most closely mirror Harry Potter's escapades in modern
fiction, is the product of author Jill Murphy's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone'' (titled ``Harry Potter
and the Philosopher's Stone'' in the United Kingdom) was a British
hit, but no mainstream U.S. publishers were willing to risk even a
modest advance. Scholastic won by default. A measure of the series'
success is that ``Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban'' is
projected to sell 500,000 copies. Consider that sales of
50,000-60,000 will usually guarantee any novel a spot on the
bestseller list.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't stop there. MGM studios has won a hot bidding war for
Harry Potter film rights. Harry probably will be onscreen a year or
two into the new century.
</P>
<P>
   But, by 2001 or 2002, will anyone still care? Extended book
series are risky; Jean Auel's ``Children of the Earth'' novels were
initial smashes in the '70s _ ``Clan of the Cave Bear'' sold in
Harry Potter-type numbers _ but readers gradually tired of its
prehistoric cast. The series has yet to be completed.
</P>
<P>
   Reading ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone'' is great fun;
pages are quickly turned and lots of colorful scenes unfold. But
follow-up ``Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' already has a
certain sameness. It is somewhat darker in tone, perhaps a sign
that Rowling expects her young readers to gradually mature with
Harry.
</P>
<P>
   An educated guess, then, has ``Prisoner of Azkaban'' hitting a
sales peak for the series, with subsequent titles selling less. But
Rowling is an unknown literary quantity; she may have some
intriguing tricks up her sleeve as well as Harry's.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain, though, is that Wednesday was Harry Potter's
day in bookstores across America. Speculation about whether Harry
will enjoy continued popularity in the rest of the series is put on
hold for now as we go onward to Azkaban, and don't fall off your
Nimbus 2000 broomstick on the way.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1624EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4722 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-SCIENCE     09-08 1871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-SCIENCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER STUDIES ECLIPSING PHYSICAL SCIENCES, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Ivy fears that his son Jonathan, a freshman business major
at Pennsylvania State University, will graduate from college
without ever having taken a chemistry course. Montville High
School, the New Jersey school he attended, did not require
chemistry, and his adviser at Penn State says he can skip it there,
too _ provided that he signs on for more computer science courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says computer sciences are mandatory for him, but no
one has ever recommended that he even look at chemistry,'' said
Ivy, the chief executive of Savin Corp., a copier company in
Stamford, Conn. ``It's truly sad that kids can graduate today
without getting exposure to the fun of physical sciences.''
</P>
<P>
   No one questions the need to emphasize computers in education
these days. Nor do they deny the plethora of high-paying jobs that
the computer world offers, from the mundane tasks of fixing
computers to the mind-stretching ones of designing digital code.
Few suggest that basic sciences are disappearing from the
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   But a sense is growing in some business quarters that the sheer
ubiquity of computers has deflected attention from more traditional
sciences and skills.
</P>
<P>
   Experts worry that vocational schools will soon churn out too
many computer repair people and too few refrigerator technicians.
They worry even more that universities will produce scads of people
who can use computers as research and calculating tools but far too
few who can use the scientific method to solve problems. They fret
that the prospect of quick wealth will lure bright students who
might have become research scientists _ or science teachers and
professors _into joining Internet ventures instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to need more HTML coders five years from now.
We're going to need biotechnologists,'' said Paul Saffo, a director
of the Institute for the Future, a research group in Menlo Park,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to start an Internet business today,'' he
added, ``because they don't realize that the science moguls of a
decade down the road will be the biotechnologists. And that means a
good chance that the biotechnology moguls a decade from now will be
foreign-born.''
</P>
<P>
   Others worry that the next generation might not develop the
experimental zeal and creative thinking of the precomputer days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer science courses teach skills and techniques, but they
don't teach critical thinking the way physics does,'' said Gerald
Wheeler, executive director of the National Science Teachers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many computer scientists take umbrage at any hint
that theirs is an intellectually bankrupt field. Indeed, Michael
Hammer, the management consultant who coined the term
``re-engineering'' and who is often cited as a premier management
thinker, has a doctorate in computer science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer science gives you the intellectual grounding to deal
with enormous complexity,'' he said. ``The liberal arts teach
critical thinking, the basic sciences teach the scientific method,
but computer sciences gives you systems thinking skills. It teaches
the value of precision, and it gives you the ability to deal with
tradeoffs and with huge issues of design.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, that idea does not stop science educators from worrying
that their fields are being eclipsed. According to Richard Heckel,
a professor emeritus of metallurgical engineering at Michigan
Technological University, who collects statistics on engineering
enrollments, ``The number of undergraduates going into computer
sciences and computer engineering is growing rapidly, while
enrollments in electrical and environmental engineering is
plummeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Hein, associate executive officer of the American
Association of Physics Teachers, cites a similar trend. ``The
number of undergraduate majors in physics is at a post-Sputnik
low,'' he said. ``Kids are saying, `Why should I go into something
as demanding and rigorous as physics when I can take computer
science and make more money?'''
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Paul Hallee. All through high school he was on
the four-year college track, taking chemistry, biology, physics,
earth sciences _ all the traditional science courses. And he has
always loved the outdoors. So, going for a four-year degree in
environmental law _ the kind of program that trains forest rangers
_ seemed a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until he realized that his hobby, fixing computers,
could be a better career bet. Hallee was accepted into a four-year
program, but instead he took a two-year course in computers and
electronics. Now, at age 20, he is working for Maine Business
Solutions, a computer repair operation in Waterville, and hopes to
carve out a career administering computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have ended up with a fancy four-year degree and no
clue of where to get a job,'' Hallee said. ``Computers seemed a
really viable option.''
</P>
<P>
   Most parents, worried about future jobs, are anxious to give
their children a head start in this computer-oriented world.
According to the Toy Manufacturers of America, some 10 million
scientific toys _ Chem Craft sets and such _ were sold in both 1997
and 1998. Some 32 million electronic toys _ computer games and such
_ were sold last year, up from 28 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The widening interest gap is particularly apparent in vocational
schools, which are often pressed for funds. Many have added
computer skills courses and subtracted courses in, say, automotive
repair, welding and other traditional blue-collar skills. ``If they
are using resources for new computer programs, they have to cut the
ones they see as marginal, or that have low enrollment,'' said
Thomas Holdsworth, director of college and technical programs at
Skills USA-Vica,which creates programs for vocational education.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Within schools, the financial crunch is affecting academic
programs, too. Western Hills High School, in a poor part of
Cincinnati, used to offer anatomy, earth science, botany and
advanced-placement courses in biology, chemistry and physics. Last
year, it abolished all of them and converted many of its
laboratories to other uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all part of a cost-cutting directive, but the computer
labs did not get hit,'' said Louise Gerl, a biology teacher at the
school who says she spends her own money for supplies to do even
rudimentary experiments. ``Local companies bombard us with free
computers, but no one will give me materials to build a laboratory
or conduct experiments,'' Ms. Gerl said.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, industry is trying to fill the gap. Dow Chemical
Co. recently sent a road show, made up of professional actors and
run by a professional director, around to junior and senior high
schools to ``educate children on the importance of science in a fun
MTV singing-dancing-game-show way,'' said William Stavropoulos,
Dow's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago a consortium of automotive companies formed
Automotive Youth Educational Systems, a nonprofit organization in
Troy, Mich., that sets up mentoring and apprenticeships between
high school students and automotive executives and dealers. It has
even begun inviting kindergarten classes in to see how cars are
fixed or sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make good money without a college degree in this
industry, but moms and dads just don't encourage their kids to be
technicians anymore,'' said Donald Gray, the president of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Although such industry-specific efforts can fill some job
pipelines, few educators believe they can do much to stop the
erosion of hands-on science in the schools. ``What corporations do
is a Band-Aid on a hemorrhaging wound,'' said Sylvia Ware, director
of education at the American Chemical Society, which has set up
groups to seek ways to train better science teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Computers and science education are not mutually exclusive, of
course. A growing number of teachers and professors, from the
prekindergarten level through graduate schools, are using software
packages and Web sites as tools to teach sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The American Chemical Society has set up a Web site
(www.chemcenter.org) that enables children to simulate some
experiments. ``Too many teachers are teaching science as something
that is learned from a book, rather than as a way of testing
reality, of looking at the world,'' Ms. Ware said.
</P>
<P>
   Educational associations are running with the computer ball,
too. The National Science Teachers Association, in conjunction with
Toshiba Corp., a leading maker of laptop computers, just sponsored
a contest among teachers to pick the best lesson plans using
laptops to teach scientific principles. Among the winning programs
was one that helped students learn about the human body's response
to physical activity by measuring their pulse rates at various
running speeds at the gym.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers association has also begun a program with textbook
publishers to include, in the margins next to specific topics,
links to its new Web site (www.scilinks.org), which offers expanded
discussions or experiments. Holt, Rinehart &AMP; Winston, a division of
Harcourt Brace, is including the links in two high school chemistry
and environmental science textbooks, and another publisher plans to
do so in new versions of elementary school science books.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many teachers worry that while chemical formulas and
physics equations can be conveyed through a computer screen, the
basic scientific questing that is supposed to accompany them
cannot. ``Computers can teach information, but they don't teach a
way to ask questions or conduct experiments where you don't know
the correct answer ahead of time,'' said Eric Gruenstein, a
professor of molecular genetics at the University of Cincinnati
Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Saffo, the futurist, put it more succinctly. ``Computers done
right can open entirely new educational horizons,'' he said, ``but
computers done wrong will turn our high schools into trade
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor do computers teach that science can be just plain fun. That
is what Sarah Beth Corning is trying to do. She teaches science to
children ages 3 to 7 at the Village Infant Center in New York City.
It is an affluent school, and she has ample access to computers.
She pretty much shuns them.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, computers can simulate the bubbles that will rise if acid
is added to an alkali, but Ms. Corning infinitely prefers letting
the children make ``volcanoes'' by pouring vinegar into a baking
soda solution. ``They'll look at it on a computer once and get
bored, but they'll make the volcanoes again and again, and they'll
even check to see what happens if they add something else,'' she
said. ``They can learn from computers, but they need this kind of
hands-on experience to get hooked on science.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-01-99 2035EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
