</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-TOOLS07-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Feedback on `Solitaire' reveals individual players' preferences 
By Jack Warner  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No column I've written since the one years ago
bad-mouthing the Macintosh has drawn so much response as the recent
one about Microsoft's ``Solitaire'' game, and it was delightful.
</P>
<P>
   So delightful, in fact, that I want to share some of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bunny'' scoffed at my disdain for players who turn one card at
a time. ``I challenge you to score 8634/Time 88,'' she boasted.
</P>
<P>
   Score? Bunny, it matters not whether you win or lose, but how
you play the game.
</P>
<P>
   A wonderful woman who persisted in calling herself a ``little
old lady'' didn't even know she had a ``Solitaire'' game in her
computer and wanted to know how to find it. You ought to try typing
out the entire route from the desktop to ``Solitaire.'' It's easy
to do mouse-wise, but the written directions look something like
the procedure for launching an ICBM.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, the lady found her ``Solitaire'' game and at last
report was well immersed in it.
</P>
<P>
   A man named George, who at the age of 80 is teaching computers
at a senior center, insists we can do better than Windows
``Solitaire.''
</P>
<P>
   He prefers one which, he says, ``I downloaded four years ago
when it had only 150 games and paid $25 for the program. It has
been upgraded at no additional cost and is now at 300 games. It is
flexible and allows you to select how it is to be played, i.e., you
can elect to take back a move you didn't like. One- or three-card
draws and many more. It keeps track of your play and will tell you
your percent of wins for any of the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs nothing to download, will let you play for 30 days
and then turns you off if you don't send $29 in, but you get a good
try. The name is: `Pretty Good Solitaire' with a Web site at
www.goodsol.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``The site is most interesting. You can enter your own games,
talk to others interested or get in competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, George, that sounds very good. I haven't looked at it yet,
but there's no reason why someone couldn't make a better solitaire
game than the one Windows provides. Windows does provide many of
the game play variations you describe. But a young fellow of a mere
72 years has the key to my preference:
</P>
<P>
   ``RIGHT ON, JACK!!'' he begins. ``The Windows `Solitaire' has
given me endless hours of enjoyment and I agree with you; the
graphics are great. There is one other solitaire game similar to
this one that I obtained from some software, and the one advantage
is that you only have to click your mouse to move a card to another
pile; but the graphics leave much to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I also like about the Windows version is that it is
large enough for these old eyes to see.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. We don't have to put our nose to the screen
to tell one card from another.
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur, who must be a youngster since he doesn't provide an age,
reports that, ``I too like Microsoft's `Solitaire.' (Of course, you
can only trust me half the time as I many times turn one card at a
time.) People look at me like I am crazy because I reject `Doom,'
`Quake,' etc., etc. I like the quickness of `Solitaire' _ of
course, it is even quicker when I select the draw-three option and
lose. I have never had a problem running `Solitaire.' I only have
two complaints about Microsoft's `Solitaire': The green background
cannot be easily changed, and moving exposed cards from a pile does
not automatically turn the next card.''
</P>
<P>
   No accounting for taste. It never occurred to me to change the
green background, and games that automatically turn the next card
bother me. It ruins the suspense.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne writes that he's got a problem with the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden it would no longer open. I let it go after a
few attempts. I had to format my system due to various problems.
After I once again entered Windows 98, I thought I could try the
solitaire again. No luck, it would not open even with the system
entered anew. Have you run into any problems such as this with your
system?''
</P>
<P>
   No, but nothing surprises me _ except that reformatting the
drive and re-installing Windows should have cured it. Somebody out
there ought to be able to help, though. If anyone has a solution,
let me know and I'll pass it on to Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have room for all the nice responses, but let me finish
with the brief e-mail from Sue, who sums it up for all of us
computer cabbages:
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the game `Solitaire' because it is a great stress
reliever. I can play a game of `Solitaire' and forget everything
but the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
