 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Just a name needed to find long-lost friend 
By Bill Husted  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the average, Americans move once every four years.
The days of staying in one place _ of a real hometown _ seem to be
slipping away. If you're like most folks, you've lost touch with
some people who were once important parts of your life.
</P>
<P>
   Now that more and more of us are online, the Web and the
Internet have become a great people locator. Today we'll look at
some of the ways you can use the Web to find lost friends and
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with an obvious and easy way _ the Web-based
directories for phone numbers and e-mail addresses. Two of my
favorites are Switchboard (www.switchboard.com) and Bigfoot
(www.bigfoot.com). Using either directory is so simple that
directions really aren't required. Just enter the name and as much
address information as you know.
</P>
<P>
   If you know the city, that sure makes things easy, but you can
do searches with just the state and the last name filled. But when
I tried the search without designating a state or first name _ even
with a name as unusual as ``Husted'' _ I got nearly 200 hits. If
your friend is named ``Smith'' or ``Williams'' you'd just be flat
out of luck if you can't at least supply a state.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be able to find telephone numbers and e-mail addresses
using either search engine. Since these lists aren't universal, try
several if the first one doesn't list your friend.
</P>
<P>
   You may get a list of several people with the same name.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you're not sure which person is your friend, you'll need
to send e-mail to all of them, explaining your search. That's a lot
less intrusive than a phone call and is, of course, free.
</P>
<P>
   Another good way to find someone is by using a general purpose
Web search engine. For searches like this, I prefer AltaVista
(www.altavista.com), since it seems to be more thorough than some
of the others. On AltaVista, you'd simply use the name as the
search words. So, if you were looking for me, you could type in
``+Bill +Husted'' ... the plus signs would tell AltaVista that both
words must be found on the page. Not all search engines use the
same methods, but you'll find a help button on any of them that
explains how to set up a search.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in my case, I have a personal Web page and my columns
appear in several newspapers and also on some Web sites. So that
would be an easy search. But even if the person you are searching
for isn't as publicly visible, you'd be surprised at how effective
this search method is at finding someone.
</P>
<P>
   Even if your long-lost friend doesn't have a Web page, chances
are that he or she has left some tracks on the Web. For instance,
some Web pages have guest books that visitors sign; a friend of
your friend may mention them on a Web page; or your friend's
company or school may include the name on a Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Another place to try _ and it's especially helpful when you
don't know the married name of an old friend _ is a Web site called
Classmates.Com. It has compiled lists of school classmates, listed
by the graduation year. Even if your friend isn't listed, you can
correspond with other classmates and perhaps find the name and
address of your friend.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously there are more sophisticated ways to search on the
Web. Most of these more sophisticated search sites charge a fee,
and some are basically detective agencies. We'll leave those sites
for another day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-06-99 1419EDT &QL;
</P>
