 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Site offers boorish men a way to say `I'm sorry' 
By Mark Clothier  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Are you cursed with a tendency toward moronic behavior
in your relationships and an inability to explain yourself out of
predicaments?
</P>
<P>
   A site called Mark's Apology Note Generator, net.indra.com
</P>
<P>
   /(tilde)karma/formletter.html, is a kind of do-it yourself
doghouse-extraction letter-creator geared toward idiotic men.
</P>
<P>
   Using multiple-choice phrases on pull-down menus, the site
creates an apology letter that can be e-mailed to a wife or
girlfriend for free. (Warning: Skip the link to the women's site.
The language is offensive, and content is meager in comparison.)
</P>
<P>
   The site is included in the September issue of Yahoo Internet
Life magazine's roundup of Incredibly Useful Sites.
</P>
<P>
   The cover story takes an interesting look at how Americans use
the Internet. The story includes a feature on the Web habits of
``regular'' people, including a Pez collector, a biker and a sports
fan.
</P>
<P>
   The story is sprinkled with interesting statistics: half of 1
percent of people who visit Web sites actually click on the
advertisements, and Wednesday is the day most people shop online.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Of the 100.9 million Americans with Internet access, 52
percent are male and 48 percent are female, 80 percent are
Caucasian and 68 percent are older than 40.
</P>
<P>
   America ranks fifth in the world by number of users per capita.
Iceland leads the pack with 320.9 users per 1,000, followed by
Finland, Norway and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Latin-flavored music rumbas onto Web
</P>
<P>
   First came the Summer of Ricky. Now Latin music is staking a
solid claim on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.eritmo.com, will be available to the public
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It features live chats with Latin musicians, fan clubs and pages
devoted to the artists.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the evolving crossover appeal of Latin music,
highlighted by the success of Ricky Martin's CD this summer, the
site's content will be available in English, Spanish and, later
this year, Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and board members include Roland Hernandez, chairman
of Telemundo Group; Michael H. Jordan, former chairman of CBS
Television; and Derek Reisfield, former president of new media for
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Reisfield helped create CBS MarketWatch.com and CBS
SportsLine.com.
</P>
<P>
   The site will be divided into six areas: news; music, which will
include samples and songs that can be downloaded; fans, which will
include links to fan-club sites; chat; concerts, which will include
live Webcasts for concerts, reviews, video archives, schedules and
the ability to buy concert tickets; and videos.
</P>
<P>
   The site will be free to visitors. It will make money from
advertising, promotions and by selling music, merchandise and
concert tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Camcorder fits in your palm
</P>
<P>
   Sharp Electronics' new digital camcorder fits in your palm and
sells for less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The VL-SD20U comes with a 3-inch color LCD screen. The device is
6.4 inches wide, 3.8 inches high and 2.9 inches deep and weighs
1.21 pounds without its battery pack and cassette.
</P>
<P>
   The camcorder also has a feature, called Digital Gamma
Brightness Correction, that darkens the background light of any
image and makes the subject brighter.
</P>
<P>
   The image screen has 660,000 CCD pixels and up to 50 lines of
clear image reproduction. It also lets the user capture still
images and transfer them to a PC, TV or VCR.
</P>
<P>
   The camcorder has an optional PC Connection kit, which sells for
$129, that lets users transfer images to a PC to edit, process and
customize. The connection package includes PixLab Browser software,
PhotoSuite 8.0 and a cable. The PhotoSuite software lets you
manipulate the images using more than 20 filters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-06-99 1420EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
