<SLUG> BC-CHEATING09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW ADS TELL KIDS 'CHEATING IS A PERSONAL FOUL'
 &HT;    600&AMP;add. With CHEATING-TIPS.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With more students than ever saying they cheat,
education groups and advertising agencies Wednesday launched a
$35-million-a-year ad campaign aimed at reversing the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the work, take the test, listen to the ref in your head,''
chant the first two 30-second TV spots, which show several children
10 to 14 as each turns down a friend's offer to share homework or
slip them answers to a test.
</P>
<P>
   The perky, fast-paced ads are punctuated by blasts of a whistle
blown by a referee described by the ad's designers as ``a very much
larger-than-life fantasy.'' Each spot closes with the visual and
verbal message: ``Cheating is a personal foul.''
</P>
<P>
   The public service ads are aimed at children in middle or junior
high schools. That age group was targeted because the Educational
Testing Service (ETS) and the Ad Council concluded that older
students in high school and college resist such messages and
younger students in elementary school don't feel as much pressure
to get good grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our youngest children know in their hearts that cheating is
wrong, but they lose that conviction along the way,'' said Sharon
Robinson, an ex-teacher who is chief executive officer of ETS.
</P>
<P>
   Donald McCabe, a Rutgers University professor who founded the
Center for Academic Integrity, said, ``Cheating unfortunately, is
common in all sectors of our educational system.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that more students than ever acknowledge they have
cheated, but it is hard to sort out how much of the trend is due to
an increase in cheating and how much to an increase in candor about
cheating.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more who just aren't ashamed about cheating any
more,'' McCabe said. ``Some are doing it because it's easy. Some
are doing it because they just don't want to be left out.''
</P>
<P>
   In his survey this year of 593 middle-school and 455 high-school
students in New Jersey, McCabe found patterns that emerged in
earlier nationwide studies:
</P>
<P>
   _ 87 percent in middle school and 90 percent in high school said
they have seen another student cheat on a test or exam.
</P>
<P>
   _ 74 percent in middle school and 78 percent in high school
reported at least one example of their own cheating on a test or
exam.
</P>
<P>
   _ Routine cheating increased by grades. The portion reporting
they had cheated on a test or exam more than three times was 20
percent in 6th grade, 35 percent in 7th grade, 60 percent in eighth
grade and 80 percent among high school juniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``By that point, in my view, you have a student who has made the
decision that when necessary, he or she will cheat to achieve the
goal or the grade they are after,'' McCabe said.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, scheduled to appear on donated air time starting this
month, are based on months of research. Children 10 to 14 were
unmoved by test ads using jingles or hip hop, presenting ``choose
not to cheat'' testimony by other children or adult celebrities, or
showing a medical student whose cheating turns him into an
ill-prepared surgeon whose patient dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't see cheating as a life-or-death matter like
smoking,'' said Paul Kurnit, president of Griffin Bacal Inc. His ad
agency, which specializes in marketing aimed at children,
volunteered to create the sports-oriented ad campaign, , which
includes a Web site (www.nocheating.org), and will expand into
radio, print and give-aways of referee's whistles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports are a way of life for today's kids (that) inspires
talent and tenacity in a forum in which cheating is not
tolerated,'' said Kurnit, who described the referee as ``an
iconization, an impartial symbol, of distinguishing right from
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   McCabe said older children cheat more because they have acquired
more cheating skills. More fundamentally, he said, they are more
likely to view cheating as ``a coping measure to deal with the
pressures of school and, particularly at the high school level,
with the pressure from parents for good grades, because of the
impact that will have on their college admission.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Cole, president of ETS, said, ``The message we're working
against is the message that cheating's okay.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that pro-cheating message can come from the example
offered by adults as close as parents who lie to avoid traffic
tickets or brag about cheating on income taxes, or as distant as
``the indiscretions of the president and the indiscretions of
congressional leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole said the ETS and its allies turned to the Ad Council for
help because, ``If you have an issue that you wish to reach a large
number of people with, there's no alternative but advertising in
this society.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar ad campaigns helped reduce forest fires, increase
recycling and discourage drunk driving and convince more people to
wear seat belts, Ad Council officers said.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-cheating campaign has the support of several ethics
centers, the National Association of Secondary School Principals,
the National Honor Society and the Council of Chief State School
Officers.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
