<SLUG> BC-EMBALMING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAIN UNION OFFICER MADE EMBALMING ACCEPTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DENNIS YUSKO  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MECHANICVILLE, N.Y. _ Kenneth Ellsworth, the closest living
relative of Col. Elmer E. Ellsworth _ the first Union officer
killed in the Civil War _ shrugs when asked to talk about his
fourth cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was crazy about soldiering; he was one of those gung-ho
guys,'' said Kenneth Ellsworth, a 73-year-old former letter carrier
still living in the colonel's hometown. ``In this day and age,
they'd call him a nut.'' Well, Col. Ellsworth may be the best-known
nut in Mechanicville.
</P>
<P>
   The city's stationery contains his profile; the city's VFW post
bears his name; a statue commemorating his actions stands near his
burial site in the Hudson View Cemetery; and now, a new city
historical marker will be unveiled near Ellsworth Avenue in a few
months.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to Thomas Salvadore, a city funeral home owner, and
Susan Kilpatrick, executive director at the Brookside Museum in
Saratoga County, Ellsworth has gained recognition in a whole
different kind of historical light: as the first American ever to
be embalmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned about it back in the 1970s when I was taking a
mortuary science course at Hudson Valley Community College,''
Salvadore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was researching a paper on the modern methods of embalming,
and this history book told the story of a Dr. Holmes, who had been
called the father of embalming because he was the first American to
experiment with it during the beginning of the Civil War,''
Salvadore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then when I read that the first soldier to be embalmed by Dr.
Holmes was a friend of Lincoln's from a small city near Albany
named Mechanicville, everything clicked _ it was Ellsworth!''
Salvadore said.
</P>
<P>
   Salvadore didn't do anything with the information until recently
when Kilpatrick heard of the story, contacted Salvadore, and began
publicizing the new fact about Ellsworth on the Brookside Web site
(www.brooksidemuseum.org).
</P>
<P>
   Americans viewed embalmment _ preventing the decay of remains
with chemical preservatives _ as against the laws of nature and God
during much of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   But ``embalming became more acceptable due to Ellsworth's
wakes,'' Kilpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ellsworth needed to be embalmed because there were four
separate wakes for him held around the country, and his body needed
to be preserved as best as possible for as long as possible,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Without being embalmed, his body wouldn't have lasted through
the heat, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Embalming was already popular in Europe when Dr. Thomas Holmes
traveled to Washington hoping to make his fortune embalming bodies
for transport home.
</P>
<P>
   His calculations paid off. The Civil War proved to be a catalyst
for the increased popularization of embalming because it allowed
bodies to be shipped home year-round.
</P>
<P>
   It cost about $100 to embalm Ellsworth, using zinc chloride with
an arsenic base, Kilpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   These days, ``probably 65 to 70 percent of people get
embalmed,'' said Salvadore. ``It is the preferred method, or `the'
method, for preservation of a body.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elmer Ellsworth, a native of New York state, worked as Lincoln's
law clerk in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ellsworth held a romanticized view of warfare, and he used to
attract 60,000 to 70,000 people in Chicago before the war when he
led a regiment nicknamed the French Zouaves,'' a military drill
team that conducted marching performances and military displays,
said Paul Loatman, the Mechanicville historian.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln took political advantage of Ellsworth's crowds, and the
favors were returned when Lincoln asked him to accompany him to
Washington in 1861.
</P>
<P>
   By May 24, 1861, Confederate troops occupied Alexandria, Va.,
across the Potomac River from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rebel flag could be seen over the Marshall House in Virginia
from Lincoln's bedroom from the White House, something Ellsworth
just couldn't stand,'' Loatman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Ellsworth went across the river and tore down the flag, but
as he was coming down the mansion's stairs, he was shot by the
inn's owner,'' James W. Jackson, Loatman said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson himself was then shot by a Union soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Col. Ellsworth was killed, it sent shock waves throughout
the nation,'' Loatman said. ``It brought home the reality that this
war could get serious, and Lincoln was crestfallen, stupefied at
losing Ellsworth, whom he viewed as a lost son.''
</P>
<P>
   Union troops recovered Ellsworth's body, and he was displayed at
the White House on May 25. That same day, he was taken by train to
New York City Hall, where 10,000 New Yorkers mourned him.
</P>
<P>
   A steamship then took his body to Albany on May 27, where he lay
in the state Capitol. Ellsworth finally arrived home on May 28 by
train, where the fourth and final wake was held, and he was buried
at the Hudson View Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funniest thing about Ellsworth,'' said Kenneth Ellsworth,
``was that he couldn't have even joined his own post because he was
not a foreign war veteran _ all his soldiering was done in the
U.S.''
</P>
</TEXT>
