<HEADLINE>
`SOMETIMES,' YOU SHOULD JUST SKIP A MOVIE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `SOMETIMES THEY COME BACK ... FOR MORE'
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 1999, R, Trimark, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.99
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes producers buy sequel rights that go beyond the force
of their source material.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they come back with more and more movies despite
having less and less of a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   This is such a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes They Come Back ... for More'' is the third movie
based on the same Stephen King short story from his ``Night Shift''
collection.
</P>
<P>
   King's tale first was turned into a 1991 TV movie called
``Sometimes They Come Back,'' then was spun into a knock-off for
video in 1996 dubbed ``Sometimes They Come Back ... Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes this unwanted third thudder, which is no more a true
King adaptation than ``The Lawnmower Man,'' whose absurd liberties
with King's work _ while brandishing his name _ had the author
howling in protest.
</P>
<P>
   At least here King doesn't get misleading prominent billing. His
credit is buried beneath the no-name cast _ which at least has
familiar faces.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a soldier who probes murders at an Antarctic base is
Clayton Rohner. He starred in the underrated ``Modern Girls'' and
once guest-starred on ``Star Trek: The Next Generation.'' Chase
Masterson, a ``Deep Space Nine'' alumnus, plays his fellow officer.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the film they indulge in emotional histrionics over
bumps in the night (but precious little horror) and get all cranky
from cabin fever.
</P>
<P>
   Finally this exploitation film starts exploiting, via
supernatural mayhem from pentagrams, sacrificial altars and zombies
and gratuitous nudity in perplexing flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The script has one good zinger. As an icebound character
complains, ``If you guys are waiting for hell to freeze over,
you're a little bit late.''
</P>
<P>
   Like 1951's and 1982's ``The Thing,'' ``Sometimes'' uses wintry
polar desolation for haunting eeriness. But the ambience is
undercut by production values, which are as meager as the plot is
slow.
</P>
<P>
   In scene after scene amid the bitter polar cold, frosted breath
never appears.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the action was shot on a sound stage in Santa
Clarita, Calif., and the budget didn't allow for adding breath
digitally or ``Exorcist''-style freezing of the sets.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you can allow for cheapness. Sometimes a film succeeds
anyway with guile, wit and inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   But this ``Sometimes'' is no such film. A failed stab at a
wintry ``Night of the Living Dead,'' it's often more lifeless than
living. 1 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FREDDY IN A BOX &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Freddy Krueger is clawing his way onto the pre-Halloween
bandwagon with new boxed sets for his remastered movies.
</P>
<P>
   Due this week for $89.98, the VHS set has all seven ``Nightmare
on Elm Street'' movies, which also are sold separately for $14.98.
(Only individual tapes have a wide-screen option.) Extras include
theatrical trailers and interviews with the directors.
</P>
<P>
   Due Sept. 21, the DVD boxed set offers much more: wide-screen
format, a bonus ``Encyclopedia'' disc, a 36-page booklet of
production notes, photos and essays, and two pairs of 3-D glasses
for watching the 3-D segment of ``Freddy's Dead: The Final
Nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   The DVD set goes for $129.98, while individual films on DVD cost
$24.98.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`FOUR WEDDINGS' ON DVD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also arriving on DVD this week is ``Four Weddings and a
Funeral'' for $24.98. It includes a widescreen option, the
theatrical trailer and an eight-page booklet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`HOME' FINALE ON TAPE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Improvement'' may have ended, but it's now on a 90-minute
videotape called ``The Series Finale'' (Touchstone, $19.99).
</P>
<P>
   Also shown are previously unseen bloopers and outtakes from the
series' eight-year run, as well as cast interviews and a
behind-the-scenes look at the final episode's creation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; VIDEO RATINGS &LR;  &QL; 
4 stars _ Excellent &QL; 
3 stars _ Good &QL; 
2 stars _ Fair &QL; 
1 star _Poor &QL; 
