<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DORA GALITZKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wrong Sunflower
</P>
<P>
   Q. We have a large terrace in Manhattan and each year we plant
sunflower seeds. We always manage to get lovely blooms but the
centers are yellow rather than the black pictured on the packet,
which is somewhat disappointing. Do you know the reason for this?
Is it the soil?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If they grow at all, the soil's not to blame. Unlike
hydrangeas, which can be sweet-talked into changing from pink to
blue or back again by changing the soil pH, sunflowers are stubborn
_ their colors are genetically determined.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jerry Miller, a geneticist at the Agriculture Department's
Northeast Crop Science Laboratory in Fargo, N.D., is one of the
country's foremost sunflower breeders. He said that dark centers,
or disk flowers, are controlled by a gene that produces dark
pigments. Since this is a dominant gene, any sunflower that has it
will have a dark center no matter how you grow it.
</P>
<P>
   Since you don't mention growing a particular sunflower, for
example Sonia or Holiday, which both have dark centers, you may
have ended up with a package of seeds that simply had a generic
photograph of a sunflower on it, but a different seed inside.
</P>
<P>
   Next year don't make it any old sunflower _ choose one (or a
dozen) that will really turn heads among your neighbors. A wide
range of interesting sunflowers, including those with dark centers,
are available from Shepherd's Garden Seeds, 30 Irene St.,
Torrington, Conn. 06790, (860) 482-3638, and Park Seed, 1 Parkton
Ave., Greenwood, S.C. 29647, (800) 845-3369. Both offer free
catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Fall Planting Hazards
</P>
<P>
   Q. I wanted to plant a magnolia but my nurseryman said magnolias
shouldn't be planted in the fall. Why not?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. For most trees, fall is the best time to plant. The soil is
warm but not waterlogged the way it can be in spring, and trees
without leaves make fewer demands on their roots to provide
nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something about a few trees, including magnolia,
birch, hawthorn, black gum, tulip tree and most oaks, that makes
them cranky when planted in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for sure, but researchers think that there is
something that prevents their root structure from taking up enough
water to overcome transplant shock, and that winter comes before
the tree is ready for it.
</P>
<P>
   Studies by Dr. Nina Bassuk at the Cornell University Urban
Horticulture Institute in Ithaca, N.Y., show that transplanting
these trees when smaller increases the fall planting success rate.
She has had much better results with trees that measure less than
two inches in diameter at a point six inches above where the trunk
emerges from the roots than with larger trees. Be sure to water
that new tree in well. Whether it has leaves or not, it needs
water. Watering also settles the soil and helps eliminate any air
pockets. Dormant trees planted in October or early November should
only need that one, deep, soothing watering to last all winter.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Timing, Not the Total
</P>
<P>
   Q. If the current hurricane season is as strong as predicted,
will the additional rain make up for the drought that has
devastated our landscape?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The rain will refill the reservoirs, but as far as trees and
shrubs are concerned, the damage is already done. Leaf scorch,
browning of the edges, is already apparent, and some trees,
especially maples, are showing early fall color as they prepare to
give up and wait for next year.
</P>
<P>
   But many signs won't show up until next spring or even the next
couple of years. Drought-stressed trees and shrubs may become more
susceptible to disease and insects. Twigs and even entire branches
may die. Some maples' crowns may not seem as full as they were
before the drought. And more years of summer drought will do more
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Watering trees slowly and deeply during dry summers is boring,
but during a hot summer, newly planted trees should get 20 gallons
of water every four to five days. One solution being used by some
municipalities is the Treegator Bag, water-filled plastic bags that
zip around a tree trunk (two can be zipped together for larger
trees). Each bag drips 14 or 20 gallons of water into the soil over
a 6- to 10-hour period, depending on the size of the bag. They sell
for around $20. Retail sources are available from Treegator
Irrigation Systems at (800) 800-7391.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
