<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AOL Options for Browsers
</P>
<P>
   Q. I use America Online for my Internet service provider, but
how would I install a Web browser other than the one from AOL?
</P>
<P>
   A. If you have version 3.0 or later of AOL's software, you can
run different Web browsers with it. With these later versions, you
can run just about any Internet program from your AOL connection,
including Telnet, FTP (file transfer protocol, good for downloading
files from remote servers) and Internet relay chat, or IRC.
</P>
<P>
   You can download a copy of Netscape's Communicator or
Microsoft's Internet Explorer browser directly from AOL. Windows
users are advised to use the AOL keyword NETSCAPE to get to the
downloading area for Communicator and BROWSER for Internet
Explorer. AOL advises Macintosh users to stroll through the Mac
Orchard (www.macorchard.com), a Web site devoted to Apple-friendly
Internet applications. AOL's online help area (keyword: HELP) has
more information about how to set each of these up.
</P>
<P>
   After you've installed the new browser software, sign on to AOL
and then open the browser program. You will need to have enough
memory available on your computer to have both these programs open
at once. Cnet, the technology news site, also keeps a helpful page
(home.cnet.com/category/0-3773.html) devoted to Web browsing
software and how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43d
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
