<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4790 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-NINES-DAY-NYT &LR;      09-08 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NINES-DAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEPTEMBER DRESS REHEARSAL FOR THE YEAR 2000 COMUTER TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computer managers are dismissing once-widespread concerns that
Thursday _ the ninth day of of the ninth month of 1999 _ will
provide a nasty preview of the kinds of disruptions expected from
Year 2000 dates.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Year 2000 conferences for computer managers and
industry gatherings regularly featured warnings that a date
represented as 9/9/99 might confuse computers because strings of 9s
can also mean a variety of other things in computer programs, like
``end of program'' and ``this file is filled.''
</P>
<P>
   Some malfunctions are also expected later this month or on Oct.
1 when monthly reports using September data are created.
</P>
<P>
   It is now clear, though, that such problems are far rarer than
Year 2000 date glitches and are largely confined to the world of
giant mainframe computers. They are also easy to locate and
generally a snap to fix.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest reason for confidence is that most computers will
read Thursday's date as 090999, not 9999.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than waste the heightened awareness of computer date
problems created by fears about Sept. 9, North American utilities,
various government agencies and others are using the day to test
their Year 2000 readiness and contingency plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not expecting any problems with 9/9/99, but it's a good
time to test our reporting system for Year 2000,'' said Lisa
Pellegrin, a spokeswoman for the International Y2K Cooperation
Center, a U.N.-sponsored clearinghouse based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The cooperation center is testing its ability to receive updates
on the status of computer systems in crucial sectors like energy,
telecommunications and banking in various countries and to post
those updates on its intranet site.
</P>
<P>
   The utility industry test will assess the operating and back-up
plans of all major institutions in the generation and distribution
of electricity, including simulated loss of important
communications systems. It treated Wednesday as Dec. 31 and
Thursday as the rollover to Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be our major dress rehearsal for the Year 2000,''
said Eugene F. Gorzelnick, a spokesman for the North American
Electric Reliability Council, which is coordinating the test.
</P>
<P>
   In computer programming, number strings like 9999 were sometimes
plugged in where true dates, like when someone was born, were not
known. They were also used when a future date, like when a program
was to be retired, had not been set. In addition to 9999, 123199,
the last day of this year, was also used by some programmers for
such functions.
</P>
<P>
   Such programming tricks seemed harmless 20 years ago, when Sept.
9 and Dec. 31, 1999, appeared very remote.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Year 2000 computer issue gained attention in the past
few years, fears began to rise that computers would be unable to
distinguish the number strings from data representing the actual
date.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmists spoke of the ``dreaded 9s'' as another potential land
mine that could cause the same kinds of malfunctions expected from
Year 2000 glitches.
</P>
<P>
   Both 9999 and Year 2000 malfunctions can shut computers down or
cause them to generate faulty data. But similarities end there.
While two-digit years in dates were standard practice, using 9999
strings without distinguishing them from potential dates was never
regarded as good programming practice.
</P>
<P>
   Year 2000 problems exist in virtually all computer languages,
but 9999 glitches occur almost exclusively in Cobol programs that
were written for older mainframes.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts say that some 9999 failures will almost
certainly occur Thursday but that they will not be surprised if
everything appears to go perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to publicly report such failures,'' said Louis
Marcoccio, director of Year 2000 research for the Gartner Group, an
information technology consulting firm based in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The malfunctions can be kept private because 9999 faults are
generally easy to work around if crucial data is backed up and can
be quickly fixed, Marcoccio said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Several Gartner clients have already run into such
problems, but the faults were handled within an hour or two so word
never got out, Marcoccio said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
