<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4791 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DREAMCAST-GAMES-N     09-08 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DREAMCAST-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY THAT'S SKIN-DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN, on the Dreamcast hardware)  
 (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Sega Dreamcast processor is fast, but a console is only as
good as the games you can play on it. There are two dozen games
scheduled for release before Santa loads up his sled, so the
machine may be worth its $199.99 price tag by Christmas. But after
spending days on end reviewing the debut titles, I didn't see much
that blew my mind. And that's a bad sign because I'm easily amused.
</P>
<P>
   First, the bad news: Sonic the Hedgehog is cheesy and boring,
probably the biggest disappointment of the bunch. Throughout Sega's
history, the blue hedgehog has always harbored a glint in his eye,
an edgy demeanor and a subversive attitude. He was a little bit
bad, and that made him cool. And it made the Sega Genesis console
cool for teen-agers, in contrast with Nintendo's little-kid fare.
</P>
<P>
   For Dreamcast, Sonic has been recast as a cuddly, earnest Dudley
Do-Right adventure hero, complete with gung-ho superhero
voice-overs. He sounds like a walking advertisement _ distinctly
uncool.
</P>
<P>
   He's fast. That seems to be the point of the game: to show off
Dreamcast's frame rate. Unfortunately, 60 frames per second doesn't
guarantee a great game. A lot of the game is scripted _ Sonic just
zooms along without any input from the player.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fantastic technical demonstration. But it's not that
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   That is the case for the bulk of Sega's racing games, almost
half of the debut titles. They're generally much the same racing
games we're used to playing on other consoles, with more resolution
and faster frame rates.
</P>
<P>
   They're prettier, but not necessarily more fun, than Grand
Tourismo or F-Zero X for the Playstation and Nintendo 64,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Of the racing games, two set themselves apart. The first, Hydro
Thunder, is an arcade conversion. Visually, it's more interesting
than CART Racing or Monaco Grand Prix because it's powerboat
racing. Powerboats veer and splash in exciting ways, and water is
prettier than a concrete race track.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Dreamcast racers, the only one that inspires
hardware lust is a futuristic hoverboard game called Trick Style,
which is a perfect, delectably scrumptious bonbon of thumb candy.
</P>
<P>
   The physics of the game are dreamy, which is to say that once
you suspend your disbelief about antigravity hoverboards, you can't
help leaning as they turn. Visually, the game is razor sharp and
achingly hip (cyberpunk ravers trailing ribbons of colored light
behind their high-tech skateboards _ fashion editors, take note).
</P>
<P>
   Trick Style shares the trails-of-colored-light effect with
another standout title, Soul Caliber, the Dreamcast version of the
arcade fighting game. Unlike most hand-to-hand brawlers, Soul
Caliber gives each character a signature weapon, and all of these
weapons leave beautiful trails of colored light as they swoop and
twist through the air.
</P>
<P>
   At times, it's difficult to tell whether you're engaged in
combat or in some deadly form of rhythmic gymnastics. In the
arcade, Soul Caliber was gorgeous, and it is no less gorgeous on
the console.
</P>
<P>
   Gorgeous is not a word one would typically use to describe
Mortal Kombat Gold, another arcade hit burned onto a Dreamcast
disk, gory bits and all. At last, it is possible to see geysers of
blood erupt as a gravel-voiced anti-referee instructs you to
``finish him'' in the privacy of your own home. If you prefer
blowing zombies to gory smithereens, House of the Dead 2 has also
been translated from coin-operated to console with every scrap of
rotting flesh intact.
</P>
<P>
   Two other fighting games, Marvel vs. Capcom and King of Fighters
'99, are old-school 2-D fighting games that are beginning to show
their age.
</P>
<P>
   Power Stone, another arcade conversion, isn't as visually slick
as Sega's other 3-D fighting games, but the game play is much more
dynamic. If you're a seasoned video-game ninja, that means
``exciting.'' If you're a novice, that means ``frantic and
impossible to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready 2 Rumble, the only fighting game not borrowed from the
arcade, is a boxing title with fantastically kitschy graphics and
fight-night ambiance (``Get ready to RUMMMMM-BULLLL!!!!!'') that's
tailor-made for beer-soaked dorm-room parties. As a cartoon boxing
game, Ready 2 Rumble also counts (sort of) as a sports title, as
does NFL Blitz 2000, an arcade version of football with no
penalties and no holds barred (the National Football League meets
the World Wrestling Federation).
</P>
<P>
   Half of Sega's debut titles (the games list for $49.99) are
coin-operated conversions. On one hand, that is a very obvious and
natural thing for a company with a successful arcade division to
do. But it does give the console a case of deja vu because some of
the best games on it have been out for a year, albeit on arcade
cabinets. And the relative mediocrity of the original Dreamcast
titles (Trick Style excepted) is not a hopeful sign.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a ray of light. That ray is called NFL 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It is, without a doubt, the best football game ever. The level
of detail is unprecedented _ you can see fog of the players' breath
in cold-weather stadiums. You can see their facial expressions. You
can read the names on the back of their jerseys as the game unfolds
from a player's-eye view.
</P>
<P>
   This game does not compete with other football games. This game
competes with a live broadcast, and most of the time it wins.
That's largely because football is a brilliantly designed game,
with or without the console. The NFL 2000 team could devote all of
its time and energy and all of Dreamcast's technology to
visualizing situations based on existing rules. It has proved that
Sega's developers can do a great job simulating a game.
</P>
<P>
   If the team can do an equally good job designing games from
scratch, this console will really be a dream.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1648EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4793 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-Y2K19-COX     09-08 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATOR SEES PROGRESS IN PREPARING FOR Y2K BUG
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This year's massive effort by business owners and
government officials to prepare computers for the date change to
2000 has put the country in much better shape to start the new era,
Sen. Bob Bennett, R-Utah, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The awareness has paid off,'' with millions of potential
computer problems being averted, Bennett, chairman of the Senate
Special Committee on the Year 2000 Technology Problem, told the
National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
   But with date-related software flaws so widespread, ``random
problems'' are inevitable and ``fingers still need to be crossed,''
he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Since April 1998, Bennett's committee has been holding hearings
to gather information and spur action on the so-called Y2K bug. The
problem could cause computer programs, especially older ones, to
misunderstand the two digits representing the year and possibly
malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   If the flaw had not been addressed, the problems could have been
catastrophic, with power plants shutting down and banks losing a
century's worth of records.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, and especially in 1999, the progress by
business owners and government officials in fighting the bug has
been ``far more than I would have predicted,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty lingers because too many companies and local
governments have scheduled their remediation work for late in 1999,
creating ``almost dangerous deadlines,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Given how close some are cutting it, Bennett is ``absolutely
certain'' some problems will result. He urged Americans to have
enough food, batteries, warm clothes and drinking water to cope
with a variety of service interruptions for 72 hours, starting at
midnight Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., vice chairman of the Y2K
committee, also spoke, sharing Bennett's generally optimistic
views. But Dodd said he remains deeply concerned about the
preparedness of the U.S. health care industry, and about other
countries' nuclear power industries. If Russia, for example, fails
to fix the software controlling its nuclear plants, dangerous
accidents could occur.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``greatest threat'' from Y2K is possibility that people
will take it too seriously, triggering panicky stampedes to obtain
cash, medicine and food, he said, warning that such hoarding will
``do far more harm than good.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said that while fixing the Y2K bug has been an expensive
and difficult task, it has helped alert lawmakers to bigger
problems that will linger well beyond Jan. 1. Congress now is much
more aware of the vulnerability of the country's computers to
hackers, terrorists, industrial spies or even warring enemy
nations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
