<SLUG> BC-APARTMENT-KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDINGS THAT GIVE CHILDREN ROOM TO PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JILL BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's the whining hour at the Watkins home. Liam, 23
months old, is wailing at an earsplitting decibel, and his parents
are desperate to find a distraction. There used to be few options,
especially on a rainy day. But the Watkinses, like more and more
New Yorkers, are finding that their apartment building now offers
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take him downstairs to the indoor playroom, and he'll run
around and get rid of all that built-up energy,'' said Jim Watkins,
an anchor for WPIX-TV, who lives on Central Park West.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Lauren Thierry, a financial news anchor for CNN,
added: ``What's great is that you don't have to worry about safety,
because it's only for the building's residents. In Central Park,
your kids could run off. Liam can play with all the other kids, and
I can even read a newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Basement storage spaces and maids' rooms, once the gulags of
Gotham, are morphing into romper rooms throughout Manhattan,
complete with the latest array of brightly colored trucks, cars,
slides and fairy-tale castles. Some are Spartan spaces with a slab
of carpeting and scattered toys next to the laundry room, while
others feel like Playland.
</P>
<P>
   At an apartment building at 170 E. 87th St., the indoor-outdoor
playroom not only offers Halloween parties, R.L. Stine book-reading
nights, baby-sitting bulletin boards and chocolate chip cookie
cooking classes, but also outings to museums and aquariums.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm living on a luxury cruise ship,'' Grace Sachs,
a resident of the building and mother of two children, said. ``On
Tuesdays, I'll get a fax under my door telling us of each week's
activities. You're even allowed to schedule birthday parties in it.
You can't put a price tag on what this means for a parent in the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes you can. Barbara Corcoran, chairwoman of the Corcoran
Group, estimated that apartments in buildings with playrooms get an
extra 5 to 10 percent boost in the sale price. ``And that's
conservative,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is definitely a big trend, because more and more families
are opting to live in the city instead of the suburbs,'' Ms.
Corcoran added. ``New buildings are putting them in as a selling
point, and older buildings are spending the money to create them
for their tenants.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are some drawbacks. ``These places can be petri
dishes for germs,'' said Lisa Shawn, who has one boy. ``I've
visited many of my friends' playrooms, since we all like to meet at
them, and some are definitely cleaner than others.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the issue of supervision. Children aren't allowed
in playrooms unsupervised, and nannies or parents are expected to
clean up after Junior (and have the good sense to keep him home if
he's sick). Some buildings have the janitor doing the heavy
cleaning, while others have on-site people running the playroom.
``Each board must decide their own rules and regulations for the
facility,'' said Charles Urstadt, senior managing director of Brown
Harris Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Most parents are euphoric to find play outlets beyond the city
parks, ones where they don't have to worry about the hassles of
getting children dressed to go outside. The commercial playrooms
available, like Gymboree, which has five outlets in Manhattan,
charge a fee but are far from plentiful in a city whose pint-size
population is growing at astounding speed. At 1150 Fifth Ave., the
number of children has increased from 8 to 40 in the last two
years. Other buildings with playrooms house more than 150 children.
</P>
<P>
   More important, these playrooms are giving apartment dwellers
the feeling of a neighborhood where nannies or parents routinely
meet for play dates and fun. Except now the traditional backyard is
a renovated basement or a whimsically designed floor. And buildings
that sponsor them have found they don't need to increase their
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since all buildings insist that the children are supervised,
we don't assume any greater insurance risk than if they were moving
along the corridors or elevators,'' said Patrick Tierney, the
manager of the condominiums at 170 E. 87th St.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle to these playrooms isn't the co-op board
but the building's space shortage. ``It's very inexpensive to
create one,'' Suzanne Waltman, a co-op board member at 333 Central
Park West, said. ``Once you have the space, all you really need is
some paint, carpeting, as well as some toys.'' At her building,
each new tenant gives an initial $200 donation to the playroom, and
parents are also asked to donate toys.
</P>
<P>
   At an Upper West Side apartment on 107th Street, parents turned
a small area near the laundry room into a playroom complete with
handmade doodles on the walls from the littlest tenants.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it is mostly Manhattan dwellers who are benefiting from
this service. ``All good marketing ideas start in Manhattan,'' Ms.
Corcoran said. ``And it's too good of an idea for the other
boroughs not to roll them out soon. I'm sure we'll be seeing them
in the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace Sachs, watching her son play happily on the jungle gym,
said: ``Many of my friends want to move here. As for us, we're
never moving out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
