<P>
   QUAYLE-PROFILE (Goffstown, N.H.) _ Dan Quayle, whose slingshot
career has given him a glimpse of both the heights and depths of
American politics by the age of 52, appears to be back at the
bottom of his political trajectory. Since his eighth-place finish
in the Iowa straw poll some of Quayle's aides have signed on to
other campaigns, his old friends from the White House privately
describe his presidential ambitions as hopeless, and he is drawing
small crowds and perfunctory attention from the news media. Yet
with a tenacity that is poignant, Quayle perseveres, motivated by
the political vindication he has pursued since he was sworn in as
vice president 10 years ago and by the dogged belief that he has a
chance to succeed. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
