<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4806 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-PIRATES-NYT &LR;      09-08 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIRATE LORE AND SALVAGED TREASURES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., N.C., S.C.)   (Eds: The word (equal) in the 3rd graf website should be replaced
with the symbol)  
 (af)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Read ``Treasure Island,'' my sixth-grade teacher told the class,
because if you discover its thrills now, they will stay with you
forever. A lot of people have taken that advice because pirate
sites for young and old abound on the Web. But reliable pirate
sites? They're as scarce as reliable treasure maps.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, with only a few mouse clicks and a few thousand dollars,
you, too, can help finance the search for the hundreds of tons of
gold buried in the Philippines and the West Indies. What? They came
up empty? Well, looks as if you've got to learn about real pirates
after all.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirate Web Ring
(webring.org/cgi-bin/webring?ring(equal)piracy;list) lists 44
sites, but some appear fanciful and many are for role-playing
games. Fortunately, there are also some thoughtful and exciting Web
pages that have navigated the treacherous shoals of legend.
</P>
<P>
   One Web ring site that does justice to both fantasy and history
is ``No Quarter Given'' (www.discover.net/nqgiven/index.htm), a
supplement to a subscription magazine of the same name. This is a
big home port for re-enactment groups, current festivals, new
discoveries and, yes, pirate chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   On sites like Think Quest's ``Pirates: Fact and Legend''
(despina.advanced.org/16438/main.shtml), an enthusiast can read
some hair-raising history and learn about the Golden Age of Piracy,
roughly 1680 to 1725. There is Blackbeard lighting his long hair
before going into battle, and ending his career with his head on a
pike. There is Henry Morgan overcoming a 16-day jungle march, 600
Spanish cavalrymen and a stampede of 2,000 Spanish bulls to plunder
the gold of Panama.
</P>
<P>
   For a look at a real ship, see www.whydah.com, which chronicles
the history and ongoing salvage of the Whydah (pronounced WID-da),
the flagship of Capt. Samuel (Black Sam) Bellamy and the only
documented pirate shipwreck (with documented pirate treasure) ever
recovered. The Whydah's story is also told on The National
Geographic's site, www.nationalgeographic.com/whydah.
</P>
<P>
   Bellamy had a spectacular but short career in the Caribbean and
off the Atlantic coast, capturing more than 50 ships before he was
29. But the Whydah went down with 144 men and much of Bellamy's
treasure in a howling Northeaster off Provincetown, Mass., in April
1717 (according to legend, the captain had detoured into disaster
to see his mistress in Cape Cod).
</P>
<P>
   Barry Clifford, a professional treasure diver, found the wreck
in 1984, and the recovery is still going on. Some of the salvaged
gold, 400-year-old African jewelry, is extremely rare; most African
gold was melted down by European traders.
</P>
<P>
   The treasure, however, is perhaps less important than things
like the ship's bell, shot and pewter tableware, which have allowed
scholars to understand how pirates actually lived and fought.
</P>
<P>
   Off Beaufort, N.C., experts from a private exploration company
and for the state of North Carolina (www.ah.dcr.state.nc.us/qar)
are doing underwater research on a hulk that is strongly believed,
though not proved, to be the remains of the Queen Anne's Revenge,
the flagship of one of history's bloodiest pirates, Edward Teach or
Thatch, known as Blackbeard.
</P>
<P>
   His ship was grounded on a sandbar off Beaufort Inlet in June
1718, a month after leading a pirate fleet that blockaded the
harbor at Charleston, S.C. Blackbeard escaped, but in November
1718, with a price on his head, he was killed by Capt. Robert
Maynard of the Royal Navy at Ocracoke Inlet, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's Underwater Archeology Unit completed a research
dive last fall, and its logs are on the Web site, along with a
trove of pirate history. State divers plan to return to the wreck
this fall, and they will again post their daily logs, said Mary
Cook, director of public affairs for the North Carolina Department
of Cultural Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Any information on the site about Blackbeard, other pirates or
the ship that may be the Queen Anne's Revenge has been researched
for accuracy by the department's historians, she added.
</P>
<P>
   For armchair treasure hunters, the site includes an illustrated
description of the 2,000 artifacts recovered, including gold
flakes, 18 cannon, a blunderbuss barrel, ceramics, hair fragments
and pewterware.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, the researchers identified two baseball-size hand
grenades filled with black powder, designed to destroy a crew but
not property.
</P>
<P>
   These reinforce the case for the ship's being the Queen Anne's
Revenge, Ms. Cook said. ``If you were a merchant ship, would you
have been carrying grenades?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   For pirate pictures, Beej's Pirate Image Archive
(www.ecst.csuchico.edu/beej/pirates) has scores of old maps, prints
and paintings related to pirates, ships, pirate punishments and
``pirate fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a British site, the U.K. Office for Library and
Information Networking (www.ukoln.ac.uk/services/treasure) has the
greatest treasure of all: everything you could possibly want to
know about ``Treasure Island.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
