<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4812 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-2000-TRIPS-HNS     09-08 1468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-2000-TRIPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTS OF DEALS, BUT WHICH ARE THE BEST? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See TRAVEL-EXOTIC) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to touting millennium celebrations, the use of
superlatives has reached a new level. Hotels, cities and tour
providers vying for your time and dollar aren't satisfied with
qualifying their celebrations as simply ``the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the hundreds of festivities and packages advertised, we've
seen ``the ultimate'' and ``the quintessential;'' about a dozen of
``the unique;'' several ``rare opportunities;'' three
``once-in-a-lifetime;'' and too-many-to-recall ``unforgettables.''
Our favorite may be ``the soiree of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   In this sea of adjectives, adverbs and special amenities, how
can you discern what really is a good deal? (And a good deal must
be qualified: Even during a normal holiday period, rates can
skyrocket. But no one likes to feel they are being gouged.)
</P>
<P>
   First, do your homework. Ascertain the normal rates _ or rack
rate _ for a hotel or resort. You can expect that holiday charges
will be higher, but if the price is tripled, you may want to
consider another place to lay your head. (The rack rate is the
highest published tariff, which an informed traveler should never
have to pay.)
</P>
<P>
   Discuss rates with a travel agent, who should be able to give
you a good idea of what prices are during a non-holiday period and
during a non-millennium holiday period.
</P>
<P>
   If you make arrangements on your own, prod the reservationist
for the lowest price. Remember that an ocean-view room will be less
that an ocean-front room. And a garden-view room will be priced
even better.
</P>
<P>
   Remember to ask about taxes and gratuities, which may not be
included in the package price. Many packages require full payment
at the time of booking. Make sure you understand the hotel's
cancellation policy before you confirm.
</P>
<P>
   Be aware of minimum-stay requirements. One Caribbean resort is
requiring a 14-night minimum stay with rates starting at $446 per
room per night. Closer to home, the Hotel Jerome in Aspen is
requiring an eight-night stay with room rates starting at a
budget-busting $740 per night. That rate is more than double what
you'd pay to stay at the historical hotel in early December.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists are accustomed to New Orleans' penchant for minimum
stays during special-event periods. Most hotels there are requiring
New Year's Eve revelers to commit to a four-night stay. And not
just any four nights. In most cases, you've got to be checked out
by Jan. 2 to make way for Sugar Bowl fans (who, by the way, also
will face a required minimum stay).
</P>
<P>
   The smart hoteliers are adding value to their packages by
tacking on such extras as breakfasts, champagne and spa treatments.
But don't assume admission to the hotel's fancy New Year's Eve bash
is included in the package price.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheraton New Orleans offers several millennium packages: The
most economical starts at $399 per night (four-night minimum) and
comes with a bottle of champagne, a limited-edition souvenir and
the opportunity to partake in the ``party to end all parties'' in
the city's fabled French Quarter. For admission to the hotel's New
Year's Eve party, you have to upgrade to the ``Suite Millennium
Experience'' package, which goes for $1,000 per night with the
four-night minimum stay.
</P>
<P>
   Scrutinize the package. The list of add-ons may be long, but if
you are not interested in a sunset cruise or a tennis clinic, you
will be paying for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   We've pawed through hundreds of press releases, reviewed a
gazillion e-mails and surfed the Web until we were queasy to find a
selection of appealing millennium packages. Here are some hotel
packages to ponder. Samplings of city celebrations and cruise
offerings are found elsewhere in this section:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A PRICE FOR PAMPERING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ In California's wine country, the Sonoma Mission Inn marks the
opening of its new 27,000-square-foot spa with a millennium package
that spotlights the spa and its natural hot springs. The
three-night deal provides lodging, two 50-minute spa treatments per
person, two commemorative spa robes, a bottle of sparkling wine and
a pair of etched champagne flutes, New Year's Day Brunch and
admission to the inn's New Year's Eve gala, which will feature
dinner and dancing. Price varies with the accommodations, but
packages start at $3,000 per couple. Call 800-862-4945.
</P>
<P>
   _ While the Walt Disney World properties may be booked to
capacity, many central Florida properties still have room for New
Year's revelers. The Peabody Orlando offers its ``P2K'' package for
$2,400, which includes three nights' lodging, a commemorative gift,
admission to the hotel's New Year's Eve gala (with dinner, wines
and dancing), breakfast daily and use of the hotel's athletic club.
Call 800-732-2639.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Regent Beverly Wilshire in Beverly Hills, Calif., wants to
help you get the year _ and the new century _ off to a good start.
The hotel's two-night millennium package features lodging,
champagne and strawberries on arrival, two spa treatments,
breakfast in bed daily and a seat in the Lobby Lounge on New Year's
Eve, where guests will enjoy a four-course dinner, dancing and
champagne at midnight. Package prices start at $1,500. Call
800-421-4354.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MUSIC TO OUR EARS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Performances by Bernadette Peters and the Temptations headline
a diverse schedule of festivities at the venerable Broadmoor in
Colorado Springs, Colo. With rates starting at $5,000 per couple,
the three-night packages cover lodging, all food and non-alcoholic
beverages and commemorative gifts. Other highlights of the weekend
include a nine-course New Year's Eve dinner and a Big Game Day, an
extravagant ``tailgate'' party where guests can watch football from
11 a.m. until 11 p.m. The hotel also is offering an extensive
children's program. Call 800-634-7711.
</P>
<P>
   _ At Opryland Hotel in Nashville, each evening of a four-night
celebration features plenty of fireworks and star power. On Dec.
30, Ray Charles performs at a champagne reception and dinner; on
Dec. 31, the hotel's 4.5-acre glass-roofed garden will be the site
of ``Midnight Millennium in the Delta,'' with food, drink and music
ranging from jazz to classical; a New Year's Day dinner will
feature entertainment by Dolly Parton and Steve Wariner; and the
celebration concludes on Jan. 2 with ``Comedy Club 2000'' hosted by
Jeff Foxworthy. Prices start at $1,999 per person and include
lodging (double occupancy), all the aforementioned events and
meals, commemorative gifts and souvenir photos and video. Call
888-976-2000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tony Bennett will serenade guests of the Desert Inn in Las
Vegas, performing Jan. 1 and 2 in the hotel's Crystal Showroom.
Tickets for the Bennett show have not gone on sale, but you can
secure reservations to Don Rickles' New Year's Eve show. The
hotel's holiday package is $2,000 per night with a three-night
minimum for lodging, two tickets to Rickles' act and a bottle of
champagne. When you add tax, the total due is $6,540, which may be
the reason the Desert Inn's Web site labels it ``millennium
madness.'' Call 800-634-6906.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MOST INTRIGUING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ A shotgun golf tournament that tees off at midnight in
Malaysia is the centerpiece of a New Year Eve's package designed
for golf enthusiasts. The Pan Pacific Glenmarie in Kuala Lampur
offers three nights' lodging, the golf tournament, a gala dinner
with entertainment and breakfast daily for $555, single occupancy.
Double occupancy rates are $499. For non-golfers sharing a room,
the price is $399. Call 800-327-8585.
</P>
<P>
   _ Guests at the Banff Spring Hotel in Banff, Alberta, will enjoy
a journey through time with the Canadian hotel's Celebration of the
Century on New Year's Eve. After dinner, guests, many in costumes
available for rent at the hotel, will be able to explore five rooms
themed to special time periods: the old West, prohibition, the Big
Band era, the Beatniks and the rocking `60s. A seven-night package
starts at $2,650 per couple and provides lodging, breakfast daily
and the New Year's Eve dinner and festivities. Call 800-441-1414.
</P>
<P>
   _ On Dec. 31, the United States will hand control of the Panama
Canal over to the Republic of Panama. A New Year's Eve cruise down
the famous canal is the highlight of the Bristol Hotel's five-night
holiday package. Other holiday activities include a guided tour of
Panama City, where the hotel is located; a visit to an Indian
village; and a helicopter tour for an aerial view of the canal and
Panama. Cost is $2,860 per person (double occupancy) and it
includes breakfast daily, two lunches, champagne, New Year's
festivities and a welcome gift. Call 888-767-3966.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
