<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4847 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AIRLINE-COMPLAINTS09-     09-08 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-COMPLAINTS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIR PASSENGER COMPLAINTS SOAR TO 11-YEAR-HIGH
 &HT;    360&AMP;add. With AIRLINE-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Air passenger complaints more than doubled in July
compared with a year ago, hitting the highest level since March
1988, the U.S. Transportation Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Delays, missed connections and cancellations were most often
cited along with poor customer service as the complaints filed with
the government reached 2,485, an increase of nearly 87 percent over
the previous month and 169 percent from July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines drew the most complaints, nearly five times
more than last July. The showing kept the Fort Worth, Texas,
carrier at the bottom of the list for customer satisfaction among
the 10 major carriers this year.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based Southwest Airlines rated the highest in pleasing
its customers, and Atlanta-based Delta Airlines was third.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines spokesman Tim Smith traced much of the
complaints to delays in late spring and early summer caused by
unusual weather and renovations being made to the air traffic
control system along its routes.
</P>
<P>
   The company was ``actively working'' on its problems, Smith
said. ``It is not simple to make an overnight change, but we are
actively looking at every conceivable way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith noted that the airlines improved in on-time performance to
third among the major airlines. He predicted that the complaint
level would go down as more flights take off on time.
</P>
<P>
   David Fuscus, spokesman for the Air Transport Association, the
trade group for the major carriers, said that Transportation
Department statistics tell only a fraction of the story, since most
passengers complain directly to the airlines, which don't divulge
the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But Fuscus said, ``We know that complaints have been going up
all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress earlier this year threatened to enact a passenger
rights bill after a winter snowstorm left packed airplanes stranded
on Detroit runways without food or running water. The lawmakers
backed down after the major carriers agreed to produce a voluntary
plan for improving service. That plan is due out next week.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   American's Smith suggested that ``the ease of complaining on
line'' via the Internet could be boosting the count.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, American has been taking a beating on the Internet this
summer. Travel writer Charles Leocha posted a column on an ``AAwful
Flight'' by a 6-foot, 6-inch friend who had been injured in Spain.
He was given a cramped middle seat that wouldn't recline and told
his injury didn't justify special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The passenger suffered throughout the flight while he and his
wife heard flight attendants in the rear ``complaining, in hushed
voices, about the passengers,'' Leocha reported.
</P>
<P>
   The commentary, featured on America Online, drew a flurry of
responses from other travelers with similar complaints. Leocha said
in an interview Wednesday that some American crew members responded
with messages for the passenger such as, ``Crack open the wallet
and buy an upgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Leocha said of American: ``They've
gone from being one of the best airlines in the nation to being one
of the most complained-about airlines, perhaps in the world. It's a
wake-up call to management.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to admit anything, but I bet you they're
scrambling now to figure out what they can do, because they've got
a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who said he was unaware of this particular story, said,
``That disturbs us to hear anecdotal stories'' about passenger
mistreatment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
