<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4852 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-MILLENNIUM-2TA     09-08 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MILLENNIUM-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVELERS SHOWING APATHY FOR BIG PARTY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See TRAVEL-SEAS) 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From New York to New Zealand, it's touted as the grandest party
ever staged.
</P>
<P>
   What's that? You haven't sent your R.S.V.P. to confirm your name
on the guest list?
</P>
<P>
   You aren't alone.
</P>
<P>
   Most travelers have given a collective ho-hum to the
``once-in-a-lifetime'' cruises, tours, hotel packages and banner
events scheduled worldwide to usher in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Or ``pseudo-millennium,'' as one Houston travel agent dubs a
celebration contrived to occur a year ahead of the 21st century's
official debut.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a rash of eye-popping enticements (alas, many with
eye-popping prices), only 8 percent of all consumers have made
plans to leave home during the upcoming New Year's holiday period,
according to a survey conducted by New Jersey-based Plog Research
for Travel Weekly, an industry publication.
</P>
<P>
   Another 9 percent still are exploring the possibility of
millennium-related travel.
</P>
<P>
   Of those numbers, barely one in four say they will attend a
party or event, while almost half intend to visit relatives or
friends.
</P>
<P>
   In the Plog Research/Travel Weekly survey of 405 individuals, 43
percent of probable nontravelers said ``the millennium means
nothing to me.'' Twenty-three percent cited expense as a factor.
Only 7 percent expressed concern about potential Y2K computer
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the root causes of disinterest, the bottom line is
this:
</P>
<P>
   _ Most cruise lines and hotels still offer space over the New
Year's holiday. Some have lowered prices in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Flights remain available to most destinations; the majority
are at the usual high holiday tariffs, but some Internet sites are
promoting discounts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many tour packages are unsold. Maupintour, acclaimed for its
wide range of high-quality packages internationally and within the
United States, canceled seven of 24 scheduled millennium tours
because of slow bookings. The company has availability on all
others.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some major events, including festivals scheduled in Dallas and
Minneapolis and a mega-concert in Southern California, have been
canceled. Many activities in smaller cities have been curtailed or
scaled down.
</P>
<P>
   Dare we declare the millennium celebration a dud?
</P>
<P>
   Let's not rush to judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Optimists within the industry suggest that the
slower-than-anticipated pace of bookings indicates only that the
public hasn't embraced a ``Buy early at our price or you'll get
left out'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   There is still ample time to join in the fun, this position
holds. Holiday vacation planning usually begins after the Labor Day
weekend, which traditionally signals the end of the peak family
travel season.
</P>
<P>
   Not every travel supplier is experiencing disappointment either:
</P>
<P>
   _ Unlike most competitors, Crystal Cruises, the world's
highest-rated large-ship line, has sold out millennium sailings on
both its vessels (at prices beginning at $8,375 and $8,975 for 16-
and 17-day itineraries). The line also reports the longest waiting
list in its history for any cabins that become available.
</P>
<P>
   _ Major concerts are generating high interest: Tickets in three
of four price ranges for Barbra Streisand's much-ballyhooed New
Year's Eve appearance at Las Vegas' MGM Grand Hotel are gone; the
minimum $500 and maximum $2,500 seats sold out quickly, and only a
limited number of $1,500 tickets remain. (The argument could be
made that Streisand's final U.S. concert, as this is billed, would
attract a capacity audience on any date.)
</P>
<P>
   _ New York's Times Square anticipates its biggest New Year's
celebration ever.
</P>
<P>
   _ Good attendance is expected, too, for blockbuster events in
London, Paris, Sydney, Washington and other cities (but it's
uncertain what percentage of partygoers will be locals or
tourists).
</P>
<P>
   _ Some tour companies that specialize in exotic
adventure-oriented itineraries report brisk business. A
spokesperson for Mountain Travel Sobek, an adventure-oriented firm,
says that firm has increased millennium departures on two tours to
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, too, figures can be misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Ritz-Carlton spokesperson Stephanie Platt says only two of the
chain's 35 hotels and resorts _ in Boston and Cancun _ have booked
an innovative, luxury-filled $100,000 ``Millennium Experience,''
available to one couple per property.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're really happy with that,'' says Platt. ``We thought
this would be a fun, over-the-top package to promote but weren't
sure anyone would actually buy it. We've got bites at several other
properties, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, advance reservations place Ritz-Carlton New Year's Eve
occupancy at 49 percent. ``But that's in advance of what we would
normally be doing at this point,'' Platt says.
</P>
<P>
   Maupintour spokesperson Carol Snyder says pricing alone doesn't
explain millennium apathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our rates are only about 15 percent higher than at any other
time, and that's only what is reflected by the higher prices hotels
are charging us,'' Snyder says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Houston travel agents suggest that a surge in
millennium bookings will occur only if companies rethink their
price structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some big mistakes made with pricing,'' says
Eva Holguin, president of Travel Arts/Cruise Gallery and Planet
Honeymoon, Houston agencies, whose business is 100 percent leisure
travel.
</P>
<P>
   Some rates have remained firm for as long as two years, and no
``fire sale'' of millennium offerings appears imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are beginning to get faxes from cruise lines and other
companies offering promotions such as free air as an incentive,''
Holguin says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had any millennium bookings. But we're telling our
clients the truth: Prices are totally out of control on almost
everything. We're steering people away from the millennium, and we
haven't had any objections,'' Holguin says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a few clients who wanted to go to Las Vegas for the
New Year's celebration. But even there, prices are out of line. One
hotel is asking $1,300 per night for a room that normally costs
$250. And they're requiring a four-night minimum stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even some of the run-of-the-mill beach resorts in the
Caribbean have set seven- and 10-night minimum stay requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative, Holguin says, ``We're promoting trips for
what we call the millennium's post-frenzy.''
</P>
<P>
   Others point to bargains earlier in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are looking for a really super cruise deal, the period
right before and after the holidays is a particularly good time,''
says Jennifer de la Cruz, spokesperson for Carnival, the world's
largest cruise line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early December traditionally offers some of the greatest
travel bargains,'' says de la Cruz. ``This year, we're also seeing
that there are some really good deals over Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Linblad Special Expeditions' Sven-Olof Lindblad recently sent
previous passengers a letter offering a 25 percent discount on any
of 22 sailings before and after Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even Crystal is offering a 50 percent discount on the Crystal
Harmony's Christmas sailing in South America and a
$1,000-per-couple reduction on a Crystal Symphony voyage in
Australia and New Zealand during that same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anticipation of New Year's Eve 1999 (at least for Crystal
passengers) has put Christmas plans in the background for many,
resulting in space on cruises which are traditionally booked by
now,'' says Crystal vice president Adam Leavitt.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise industry represents particularly intriguing food for
millennium thought.
</P>
<P>
   Several lines began accepting reservations well before
itineraries and prices were firmed, and they generated tens of
thousands of bookings (with refundable deposits). Encouraged by
this immediate outpouring of interest, the lines then announced
strategies that positioned ships all over the world _ even at the
international date line in the South Pacific _ with big-time
entertainment and guest lecturers aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Once prices were announced, however, many lines had a surprise:
mass cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   Even lines that maintained familiar Caribbean-based itineraries,
without sticker-shock pricing, haven't been besieged by customers.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival, which lowered its initial millennium brochure rates by
15 percent on five cruises earlier this summer, still has space on
12 of its 14 ships, according to de la Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   ``That space ranges from minimal to ample,'' de la Cruz says.
``But we are pleased with the pace of bookings, and we fully expect
that all these cruises will sell out.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnival's current pricing for millennium cruises varies widely,
depending on the ship and itinerary. Examples: Cruise-only per
person rates for a seven-day western Caribbean itinerary aboard
Carnival Destiny range from $3,165-$6,635; cabins for a nine-day
eastern Caribbean sailing aboard the older Inspiration are priced
from $739-$1,909.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not anticipate further price reductions,'' says de la
Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Cruise Line also reports availability on all seven
ships, including the Houston-based Norwegian Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've introduced some passenger incentives for sailings that
have the most space,'' says spokesperson Fran Sevcik.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too late either to reserve space aboard either of
Silversea's two luxury-oriented vessels. The all-suite Silver Cloud
and Silver Wind boast the most elaborate holiday-at-sea
entertainment lineups, with itineraries in the South Pacific, and
where guests will celebrate the first day of the new millennium
twice (when the ships cross the 180th meridian and international
date line in tandem).
</P>
<P>
   Prices are impressive as the itinerary _ $32,195 to $66,195 per
person for 15- or 16-day sailings _ but spokesperson Dale DiBello
says, ``We're about 75 percent full, which is right about where we
thought we'd be at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The line plans no discounting. But DiBello says, ``We've put
together package deals that include the millennium sailings and
others (for only a small extra tariff).''
</P>
<P>
   One theory behind high-end millennium products is this:
</P>
<P>
   A traveler accustomed to paying $15,000 for a product may be
willing (and financially solvent enough) to double that investment
_ assuming the extra charge results in added value (perceived or
real). But an individual normally on a $1,000 travel budget may not
afford to spend $2,000 to welcome the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many with the money and desire to celebrate away from
home don't have that option during this upcoming holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Even if most travelers aren't overly concerned that
transportation services and support systems won't be shut down by
massive computer failures at the stroke of midnight on New Year's
Eve, the corporate world must guard against any surprises.
</P>
<P>
   And most business executives are keenly aware that they had
better be easily reachable _ and not on a remote island or cruise
ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guests are not price-sensitive,'' says Robert Weber,
general manager of the Westin Casuarina Resort on Grand Cayman
Island in the Caribbean, ``but many executives are being required
to be on call just in case there are Y2K problems.''
</P>
<P>
   After speaking with other luxury property managers, Weber says
he believes this is a prime reason why millennium bookings are flat
throughout the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Should travelers be worried about breakdowns?
</P>
<P>
   The Air Transport Association and Federal Aviation
Administration system, following extensive testing, has assured
that potential Y2K problems have been fixed on critical systems
within the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But in late July, a State Department report found that about
half of 161 nations surveyed face a ``medium to high risk'' of
disruptions in their telecommunications, energy and transportation
systems.
</P>
<P>
   In an updated worldwide notice, the State Department cautioned:
``On or about Jan. 1, 2000, some automated systems throughout the
world may experience problems, including unpredictable system
malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governments or businesses with more limited resources or
expertise, or those that are not paying appropriate attention to
the problem, may experience more significant difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   (The notice in its entirety, and related Y2K matters, can be
accessed via the Internet at travel.state.gov; by Oct. 1, the State
Department plans to provide country-by-country reports on this Web
site. Reports by the Aviation Millennium Project, coordinated by
the Air Transport Association, are available at
www.aviationmillennium.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Those discouraged from turn-of-the-century travel because of Y2K
_ or because of apathy _ can take heart in the awareness that some
celebrations aren't fixed to our New Year dates.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's official millennium festivities begin Nov. 27 with
the ``world's largest tea party'' and peak Feb. 5 with a ``Parade
of the Dragons'' welcoming the Chinese New Year. Italy and Israel
will celebrate throughout 2000. Closer to home, Disney World has
decreed that its millennium celebrations, which begin in October,
will last 15 months. Philadelphia started an 18-month schedule of
events even earlier, in July.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel executive Weber says he anticipates a boom in travel to
the Caribbean once Y2K concerns abate. He foresees higher tourism
for New Year's 2000 when the true millennium turns.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Weingart, president of Carlson Wagonlit Utopia Travel in
Houston, seconds that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling that the real millennium may end up doing
better than the pseudo-millennium,'' Weingart says.
</P>
<P>
   It's a safe wager that cruise lines, hotels and others in the
industry _ perhaps after learning a few valuable lessons from this
experience _ will adopt that philosophy as a mandate, come Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
