A4869 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     09-08 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV26-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., SEP. 26, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I just bought a wallpaper that is not pre-pasted so I will
have to brush on my own paste and cannot simply dip each strip into
water. Unfortunately, I don't have a long table that will enable me
to unroll the full length of each strip when I want to apply paste
on the back, so I am not sure how to do this without rolling it out
on the floor and then working on my knees. Isn't there a better
way?
</P>
<P>
   A: There certainly is. You need a table that is only about five
or six feet long because each strip will be folded as you paste it.
</P>
<P>
   Start by unrolling the strip and then placing the top end of
this strip on one end of the table. Let the rest of the strip hang
down over the other end of the table while you spread the paste on
over the portion that is on the table. Then fold that end over as
shown here so that the pasted side is touching itself and so that
the folded area is now about one-third the total length of the
strip. Be sure you fold loosely without creasing at the fold.
</P>
<P>
   Next, slide the pasted end off the table (let it hang down over
the end of the table) and then finish pasting the rest of the
strip. Fold this part over in the same way so that the two ends are
almost touching _ again without creasing.
</P>
<P>
   You can now carry the folded strip over to the wall by draping
it over your arm. Unfold the top end first and apply this to the
wall, after which you can unfold the bottom end.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My bathroom vanity is stained with what looks like cigarette
burns and rust marks left by the previous tenant. How can I remove
these stains without damaging the plastic laminate top?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rust stains can often be removed by using a commercial rust
remover of the kind sold in hardware stores and home centers. You
can also try scrubbing with a scouring cleanser that contains
bleach, using a kitchen-type abrasive pad.
</P>
<P>
   Burn marks are seldom removable _ unless they are very shallow,
in which case the scorched material may come off by rubbing with a
very fine abrasive pad. However, if the burn is deep then it is
likely you will be left with a discolored or off-color stain.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a problem with leaves accumulating in our roof
gutters because there are lots of trees around the house. Cleaning
out these gutters involves a great deal of ladder climbing. Is
there any way to simplify this job or minimize the need for doing
it so often, without pruning our beautiful trees?
</P>
<P>
   A: Cover the gutters with a protective mesh or ``gutter guard.''
Sold in most home centers and hardware stores this consists of
strips of a plastic or metal mesh that are shaped to fit over the
gutters.
</P>
<P>
   They are usually installed by slipping one edge under the bottom
row of roof shingles while the other edge snaps onto the outside
lip or rim of the gutter. The mesh traps leaves so they cannot fall
into the gutter. After the leaves dry out they get blown away by
the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our fairly new house has no basement and is built on a
concrete slab with wood parquet flooring on top of the slab. This
flooring often buckles and also squeaks badly in some places. What
do you think causes this, and what if anything can we do to correct
these problems?
</P>
<P>
   A: The buckling is probably due to the fact that when the
flooring was put down the installer did not leave proper clearance
space around the edges and next to the walls. This clearance is
needed to allow for expansion of the wood in humid weather so that
it will not buckle.
</P>
<P>
   The squeaking is probably another result of this same faulty
installation _ when the flooring buckles it also works loose, and
loose boards are the most frequent cause of squeaking. I suggest
hiring a flooring contractor or carpenter to see if trimming some
boards around the perimeter will solve your problems.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``FOLDING PASTED WALLPAPER'' goes with
this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Pasted strip of wallpaper is folded so that pasted side
is against itself. This eliminates need for a long table and
simplifies carrying and handling the pasted strip.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
