<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4883 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DANCE-NEWSEASON-KISSE     09-08 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-NEWSEASON-KISSELGOFF-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROVOCATEUR WHOSE LANGUAGE IS THE ABSURD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Sweden)   (For release Sunday, Sept. 12)  
(DW) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is one thing you can say about the Swedish
choreographer Mats Ek: at his best, he is outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   The provocative image, its basic truth leavened with absurdity
and dark humor, is his forte. In his dance treatment of ``Carmen,''
for instance, the heroine symbolizes her independence by acting
like a man. When Don Jose stabs this Carmen in the tummy, a cigar
pops out of her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Ek's frequent reinterpretations of the classics
(drawn from ballet, opera and literature), Matthew Bourne's recent
``Swan Lake'' with male swans looks positively namby-pamby. Ek is
not as polite or as tame. Long known as a social-protest
choreographer, he aims less for the applause meter than the gut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carmen'' and ``Solo for Two'' make up the all-Ek program that
the Lyons Opera Ballet from France will perform at the Brooklyn
Academy's Harvey Theater (formerly the Majestic) from Oct. 19 to
24.
</P>
<P>
   Other troupes that dance Ek's works have already shown why he is
one of Europe's most talked about choreographers. At the Edinburgh
Festival this month, the Cullberg Ballet from Sweden presented his
modern-dress ``Sleeping Beauty'' with the heroine as drug addict.
Carabosse, the wicked fairy, is a dope pusher; the prince, a
racist, reforms by accepting the overdosed beauty's black baby.
</P>
<P>
   The sensationalist streak in Ek's work was already apparent in
1982 at the Metropolitan Opera House when the Netherlands Dance
Theater performed his ``House of Bernarda Alba.'' Ek portrayed
Bernarda, the Spanish matriarch of Lorca's play as a hypocritical
tyrant obsessively confusing erotic and religious ecstasy. The
dancers thrashed around the stage with cannonball force and Ek,
tall and powerful in his cassocklike dress, galvanized the piece,
never afraid to provoke _ or offend _ to make his point.
</P>
<P>
   Long before updated modern-dance versions of the ballet classics
came into vogue, Ek, now 54, set the pace. His best-known recension
is a ``Giselle'' (1980) whose second act is set in an insane
asylum. The usual white-clad wilis (ghosts of jilted maidens) are
now madhouse inmates with Myrtha, the wili queen, as their head
nurse. For Europeans attuned to themes of individuals whose spirit
is crushed by a social milieu, the Ek ``Giselle'' remains a
milestone. The Paris Opera Ballet staged it in 1993 alongside the
traditional 1841 version and revived the Ek production last year.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers saw this ``Giselle'' when Ek and his mother, Birgit
Cullberg, Sweden's celebrated modern-dance pioneer, presented it
during the Cullberg Ballet's U.S. debut at the Brooklyn Academy
Opera House in 1982. Americans have yet to see the Ek ``Swan Lake''
(1987), a nasty piece, with bald (plucked) and bare-legged male and
female swans.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ek knows that clever remakes of the classics go only so
far. In ``Solo for Two'' and ``Grass,'' which American Ballet
Theater performed in 1992, he offers original duets that explore
male-female relations.
</P>
<P>
   That Ek tends to think more like a theater director than a
choreographer is not surprising. His father was Anders Ek, one of
Sweden's leading actors. Although Ms. Cullberg, now 91, is world
famous (her ``Miss Julie'' was a Ballet Theater staple), Ek did not
immediately follow his brother Niklas Ek, 56, into dance. Like his
twin sister, the actress Malin Ek, he opted for drama, working as a
theater director in several troupes from 1966 to 1973. Early on he
was an assistant to Ingmar Bergman at the Royal Dramatic Theater.
</P>
<P>
   At 17, he had spent three months studying Martha Graham's
technique from Donya Feuer, an American modern-dance choreographer
living in Stockholm. But his formal dance training began in earnest
surprisingly late, when he was 27. In 1973, he joined the Cullberg
Ballet, founded by his mother in 1967 and directed by him from 1985
to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   To his admirers, Ek is a humanist, defending the oppressed in
the widest sense. But it was also once easy to see him as a message
choreographer whose concepts were better than his actual
choreography. His ``Soweto,'' in 1982 at the Brooklyn Academy, did
not show us anything new except that King Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden
could maintain a Bjorn Borg-like cool in his box when a female
dancer turned to him and bared her breasts.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Ek is an artist to take seriously. The king
notwithstanding, he shakes up audiences. While purely formal pieces
do not interest him, much of his choreography looks abstract and is
open to interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   One example is ``Solo for Two,'' originally titled ``Smoke''
when created for television with Sylvie Guillem and Niklas Ek. The
piece can be seen as a study in desire: a surprisingly tender image
has the woman doing a breast stroke as the man carries her
horizontally on his hip.
</P>
<P>
   A freelance choreographer since 1993, Ek showed off his
explosive style in his witty and strange ``Carmen.'' I saw it with
the Cullberg Ballet at the 1992 Lyons Dance Biennial. It is not
surprising that he is confident that the Lyons Opera Ballet has
mastered his eclectic and energetic idiom. This French company,
familiar here from past appearances (including Lincoln Center
Festival '96), specializes in contemporary choreographers. When I
saw it last year in Lyons, its sleek and committed dancers, many of
them new, looked more versatile than ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
