<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-CULLMAN-RENOVATE-ART-     09-08 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULLMAN-RENOVATE-ART-940(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PROUD: MOVING MODERN AHEAD BY THE POWER OF TWO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two things are likely to transform a landscape or change a
house: a force of nature or people. Dorothy Cullman is a bit of
both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love change,'' said Mrs. Cullman, 75, with visceral relish,
as though she were describing her favorite food, the kind you have
to dig out of a shell. She sat on her new porch in Sag Harbor,
N.Y., relaxed but by no means retired after the year of renovations
that created the home _ her third. A Mexican silver earring flashed
at her ear like a glimpse of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's an adventurer,'' said Diana Vinoly, an interior
designer, who, with her husband, the architect Rafael Vinoly,
helped Mrs. Cullman and her husband, Lewis, 80, transform three
modest buildings on two narrow lots in the town's historic district
into a contemporary country compound: a house that, with two
discrete guest wings, looks as if it's gone for a stroll in the
park.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an unusual sympathy between Mrs. Cullman and Ms.
Vinoly, the house also advances the moment in modern interior
design.
</P>
<P>
   It is eclectic, but collaboratively so. The client's impeccable
confidence informed the designer's sophisticated choices. Ms.
Vinoly picked out the 1950s Paul McCobb ladder-back dining chairs;
Mrs. Cullman put a 1930s French glass table at the center, like
throwing open a window.
</P>
<P>
   The house is not shy of architectural surprise, either: at Mrs.
Cullman's direction, Vinoly removed four ship's-cabin-size rooms
upstairs, installing a single suite of bedroom and bathroom that is
a minimalist's interpretation of a traditional Japanese inn. For an
18th-century seaside community like Sag Harbor, it is as if
Melville became a monk instead of a mariner.
</P>
<P>
   The Cullmans are no strangers to transformation. With a history
of philanthropic funding that has changed the cultural landscape of
New York City, they constitute a two-person Who's Who at
institutions like the New York Public Library and the American
Museum of Natural History. They are also collectors and inveterate
travelers: they have skipped the globe like stones.
</P>
<P>
   At home, their interests never rest. Rough, lustrous Oaxacan
ceramics had come out for coffee; a Saul Steinberg drawing sat
waiting for a wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at how we connected,'' Ms. Vinoly said, barefoot in
plum-colored toenail polish at the house, recalling how she met the
couple. Mrs. Cullman, in Issey Miyake, had admired Ms. Vinoly's
dress, by Miyake, at a dinner party. ``We became friends, and
suddenly I was doing her house. She met my youngest son, who is a
filmmaker, with his girlfriend; liked him, invited him to a party.
She invited Brook Astor _ same level. Very few people are like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Married for 36 years, the Cullmans disagree consistently enough
in conversation to constitute the kind of Pat and Mike agreement
good teams reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lewis is so resentful about coming out here,'' Mrs. Cullman
said, with the tease of truth.
</P>
<P>
   Cullman, the chairman of Cullman Ventures Inc., which includes
the At-a-Glance Group, the calendar publisher, waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a pretty nice house in Darien,'' he said, smiling.
``What do we need another house for?'' The Connecticut farmhouse
was built in 1720; Cullman modernized it in 1950. They also have a
New York apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That house is part of his being,'' Mrs. Cullman said. ``He has
so much emotionally invested in it. I wanted to get out of Darien
for a long time. I had offered him Martha's Vineyard, South of
France.''
</P>
<P>
   Cullman added, ``London,'' as though he were clocking his pulse.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cullman seized her chance last summer, on a visit to the
Vinolys' house in Water Mill, N.Y. She recalled Vinoly, whose
projects include the Tokyo International Forum and the Princeton
Stadium, being asked how, as a modern architect, he could live in
an old house.``He said, `You think I would live in a modern house?
I am not crazy. If you buy a house, I'll remodel it.' And I
thought, what a marvelous opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cullman found the 3,000-square-foot main house listed in
the newspaper; friends and family treated the find as if it had
come wrapped in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who lived in East Hampton or Southampton said, `Sag
Harbor!' '' Mrs. Cullman said. ``I wanted a small house. I did not
want to be on Lily Pond, in the midst of the glitz.''
</P>
<P>
   The little white house had its own kind of glamour. ``It was
turquoise inside,'' Mrs. Cullman said. ``Every doorway was painted
malachite, with shells.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vinoly said, ``Very chi-chi.''
</P>
<P>
   The two women were sitting on the porch, like sisters,
discussing what to wear to the September wedding of Kitty Hawks,
the decorator.
</P>
<P>
   ``End of the summer, five o'clock,'' Mrs. Cullman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so in-between,'' Ms. Vinoly said. ``It's almost like she
wants to see what we'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   The two shopped for the furniture together, in Ms. Vinoly's
fire-engine red 1961 MG convertible, stopping for picnics in the
car. Mrs. Cullman crystallized her vision of African, Japanese and
contemporary influences, she said. Ms. Vinoly took her to favorite
stores like Ruby Beets and Mary Ann Lembo in Bridgehampton,
Aesthetics Home Furnishings in Water Mill and Youngblood in Sag
Harbor, and to dealers like Tucker Robbins, Donzella, Frank Rogin,
Palumbo and Zero to Sixties in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want you to buy a pin without me seeing it,'' Ms.
Vinoly recalled her saying.
</P>
<P>
   Their dialogue produced a fresh, informal vocabulary for modern
interior design, recently popular but increasingly formulaic. In
turn, the house at the shore has the subtle coolness of modern
design's crisp, clean lines. It is a kind of low-key high style.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the Cullmans' living room, nothing is what it seems _ the
furnishings are an intelligent parlor game. There are new
Jean-Michel Frank-like square sofas, but they are sea-grass
versions, upholstered in white cotton. Mrs. Cullman wrapped the
back cushions in her collection of Indonesian sarongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many sarongs I thought I was going to wear,''
she said. ``They ended up in a drawer.''
</P>
<P>
   On the wide-planked floor are natural fiber mats, but they are
vintage Mauretanian examples, patterned with woven leather. Two
rattan garden chairs were designed by Pierre Chareau in the 1930s.
A pair of free-form, rosewood coffee tables look like the work of
George Nakashima, the celebrated woodworker. They are African
driftwood that Mrs. Cullman had mounted like sculpture on
wrought-iron bases. The rope-seated side chairs that flank them are
from Nakashima's studio. Clover-leaf end tables have an early
American profile: they are 1940s, by Dunbar Furniture Co. Ms.
Vinoly gave them red leather lamps, stamped to look like handbag
crocodile.
</P>
<P>
   The two women were an education to each other. ``I'm a
modernist,'' Ms. Vinoly said. ``When I do a city project, it's very
urban. When I do a country house, it's more country. For Dorothy,
it's completely irrelevant. I am eclectic, but with her, I learned
you can be really eclectic.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cullman said, ``I have a theory: no matter when it was
made, if you can find the best of the period, you can mix it with
any other period.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Mrs. Cullman watched her personal instincts
implemented as signatures of the Vinolys' design.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, the stripped space was refitted with precisely planed
raw pine and maple. Vinoly created a wooden-box bathroom that sits
inside the gabled bedroom like a sauna. The exterior provides a
headboard wall, which Mrs. Cullman hung with a set of Robert
Mangold prints. Ms. Vinoly chose a Nakashima bedroom set.
Attic-like eaves are enclosed by sliding shoji screens, veiled by
linen, that provide storage. Noguchi silk lanterns light the room
at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can turn out looking like a Japanese restaurant,'' Mrs.
Cullman said. ``One wrong move and you're finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, guests arrived for lunch. Cullman led them past the
Scott Burton sculptures into the parklike garden and grounds,
landscaped by Bayberry Nurseries in Amagansett.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cullman shared a secret. Though it was their second weekend
in the house, change was in the air. The terrace dining furniture
was living on borrowed time; two Kiki Smith collages were coming
out from the city, as centerpieces for the living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men think, if they buy something, they're going to have it
forever,'' she said, descending the stairs to rejoin her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cullman adjusted an earring before greeting her guests.
``Women don't,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
