<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4901 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-MENDES     09-08 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NEWSEASON-MENDES-$ADV12-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN BEAUTY'S' WUNDERKIND DIRECTOR DISCOVERS THE WONDERS OF
FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 12)  
(Eds: First graf should appear in italics.) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ My name is Lester Burnham. This is my neighborhood.
This is my street. This is my life. In less than a year I'll be
dead. Of course I don't know that yet. In a way I'm dead already.
</P>
<P>
   These are the opening words of the ``American Beauty''
screenplay, the ones that startled Sam Mendes, the 34-year-old
Englishman who directed the Broadway hits ``Cabaret'' and ``The
Blue Room,'' and turned him into a film director.
</P>
<P>
   ``From those first words,'' he said, ``I couldn't put it down. I
read it three times in quick succession.''
</P>
<P>
   The script was by Alan Ball, a first-time screenwriter with an
off-Broadway play and television sit-coms on his resume _ none of
which hinted at the dark, phantasmagoric view of suburban life
revealed in ``American Beauty.'' It's the story of a desperately
dissatisfied middle-aged man married to a grasping, equally
dissatisfied real estate broker. Their family life is a sham, their
teen-age daughter despises them and her sultry best friend has the
father's sexual fantasies going full-time. The movie, with Kevin
Spacey and Annette Bening in the lead roles, opens on Wednesday.
Its director, seated in the coffee shop at Shutters on the Beach, a
hotel in Santa Monica, is still unable to articulate exactly what
the film is about.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a mystery at the film's core,'' Mendes said. ``Yet I
felt a very, very personal reaction to it. Somewhere in the film is
a lot of anger and rage on the part of Alan Ball. And the biggest
pitfall for me was to make a serious film that could also be funny
and emotional and move you.''
</P>
<P>
   The director, regarded as a wunderkind of British theater since
his early 20s, is friendly and unpretentious, a somewhat cherubic
figure with an easy laugh. But the normally voluble Mendes shies
away from discussing the ways in which the film's story resonates
with his own. He will identify one element of the ``American
Beauty'' plot that personally stirred him: the love affair between
the daughter, played by Thora Birch, and the drug-dealing son of
the tyrannical ex-Marine who lives next door. ``I'm an only
child,'' he said. ``This was about dysfunctional families. And
without wanting to sound rude about it, my family was not entirely
functional.''
</P>
<P>
   By his own account, his middle-class, north London childhood was
lonely. His parents divorced when he was 5. His father, Peter
Mendes, who is of Portuguese ancestry, is a retired university
lecturer in English literature. Young Sam lived with his mother,
Valerie Mendes, who writes children's books and was in the
publishing business.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes likes to find a personal dimension in his projects. His
mother is Jewish, and the realization that both she and he would
have been marked for death during the Holocaust was one reason
Mendes wanted to take on ``Cabaret.'' Being a bachelor _ albeit one
who has been linked to the actresses Jane Horrocks, Rachel Weisz
and Calista Flockhart _ Mendes has been drawn in recent years to
works about the search for love. In 1996, he directed an acclaimed
revival of Stephen Sondheim's single-guy musical, ``Company,'' at
the Donmar Warehouse, the nonprofit theater Mendes runs.
</P>
<P>
   He spent his childhood becoming a skilled cricket player,
reading books and watching movies. ``I was a troubled fantasist,''
he said. ``Well, most fantasists are troubled. I was escaping from
my parents' divorce. It was just me and my mother, and so I lived
in my head a great deal of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   At Cambridge, he toyed with the idea of becoming a journalist.
But after his graduation, in 1987, he took a low-level job at the
Chichester Festival Theater. He says he was hired largely on the
strength of his cricketing ability _ the director of the Chichester
Festival at the time, John Gale, was looking for cricket players
who could beat the team fielded by the Royal Shakespeare Co..
</P>
<P>
   His rise was startling. When a veteran stage director suddenly
dropped out of a production of ``London Assurance,'' Mendes was
asked to step in. By the time Mendes was 24, ``London Assurance''
had transferred to the Theater Royal, Haymarket, and a second play
that he directed, ``The Cherry Orchard,'' starring Dame Judi Dench,
had opened at the Aldwych.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that I loved directing. I loved the company of other
people, because I had so little of it when I was a kid,'' he said.
``When I walked in and did it, I thought, `Oh, this is so great.'
And it combined the company of people and the visual arts, which I
had studied. I was able to paint, to a degree, on a stage. And I'm
not a very gifted painter.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Mendes became artistic director of the Donmar, where he
directed _ and rethought _ ``Cabaret,'' ``The Glass Menagerie'' and
``Company.'' The work on ``Company'' led to a friendship with
Stephen Sondheim, and Mendes is now preparing the new Sondheim
musical, ``Wise Guys,'' due this spring on Broadway. He is also
ready to sign a film-directing deal with Dreamworks.
</P>
<P>
   What surprised Mendes about filmmaking? ``The biggest surprise
was how mundane filmmaking is in many ways, how it's a mosaic and
you polish every little piece and it was very slow, very
practical,'' he said. ``Even bigger than that was the sheer joy of
editing. I mean, it was the most creative thing I've ever done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing about theater is the creative thing is
at the very beginning of the process. The rehearsals are great.
With movies, the creative thing was at the end. I didn't realize
the incredible pleasure of, once you've got your footage,
manipulating it and beginning to tell a story and cutting to a
close-up or adding a music track. That astonished me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendes was also surprised at the results of his inexperience. In
fact, his filmmaking career almost ended before it began. Mendes'
first three days directing ``American Beauty'' were, by his own
account, disastrous. After watching the dailies, Mendes felt
himself sinking in quicksand. The director asked Dreamworks whether
he could reshoot those scenes. The obviously nervous Dreamworks
executives agreed to start all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were more than a couple of sleepless nights when I
thought, `Just help me out here,''' said Mendes. ``I started with a
wrong scene, actually, a comedy scene. And the actors played it way
too big. And I thought, `Oh my God.' And it was my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was badly shot, my fault, badly composed, my fault, bad
costumes, my fault,'' he said. ``And everybody was doing what I was
asking. It was all my fault. You can't slough off responsibility as
a movie director. Everybody's hanging on every word.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendes regained his footing; the reshoots worked.
</P>
<P>
   As a novice film director, Mendes said he depended heavily on
his director of photography, 72-year-old Conrad L. Hall, the master
cinematographer who won an Academy Award for his work on ``Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'' (1969). ``I made a very conscious
decision early on, if I didn't understand something technically, to
say, without embarrassment, `I don't understand what you're talking
about, please explain it.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are great similarities between the theater and films if
you have a visual imagination,'' he said. ``But theater emerges
through the mists in rehearsal. It's slow and rather social, it's a
collaboration. In theater if you say, `I don't know,' it leads to a
chat, it opens many doors, the beginning of a journey. If you say,
`I don't know' on a film set, you're dead. Because everyone's
going, `Well, if you don't know, who does?' You have to have it in
your head at all times.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Even highly experienced British and Australian filmmakers have
fumbled when they came to the United States to make movies that
deal with the specifics of American life. Yet ``American Beauty''
seems fully conversant with the nuances of suburban life.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes discounted the notion that the film was, specifically,
about American life. Yes, he had spent time driving through New
York, New Jersey and Los Angeles on his trips to the United States.
But, he said: ``I don't think I tried to make a film about America.
But sometimes as an outsider, as an observer, you can see things
more clearly. Look at `Midnight Cowboy,' `Chinatown,' `The Truman
Show.' These were not made by American directors. The most accurate
depiction of Berlin in the 1930s was written by an Englishman,
Christopher Isherwood.''
</P>
<P>
   Before filming began, Mendes said, he and Spacey _ who was his
first choice for the role _ watched a videotape of Jack Lemmon in
the Billy Wilder film ``The Apartment.'' Mendes said, ``The way
Jack Lemmon moved, the way he looked, the way he was in that office
and the way he was an ordinary man and yet a special man _ that's
what I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   He also watched several other films for the heightened sense of
style that he sought: Martin Scorsese's ``King of Comedy,'' Bob
Fosse's ``All That Jazz'' and Roman Polanski's ``Rosemary's Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendes almost didn't get the job directing ``American Beauty,''
an assignment coveted by a number of well-known filmmakers. Ball's
script had begun circulating in March 1998. Most top studio
executives found it riveting but uncommercial. Robert Cooper, the
former head of production at Dreamworks, was given the script by a
Dreamworks development executive, Scott Williamson. Cooper
remembers Williamson's telling him, ``It's about a dysfunctional
family, but believe me, you've got to read it.''
</P>
<P>
   That night, Cooper phoned his boss, Steven Spielberg. By the
next morning, Dreamworks had purchased the script for $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The directors Robert Zemeckis and Mike Nichols wanted to make
it, but other projects got in the way. Experienced directors
lobbied for the job. In the interim, the film's two producers, Dan
Jinks and Bruce Cohen, had seen ``Cabaret'' in New York and invited
Mendes to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes met not only the producers and Ball but also Spielberg
and Walter Parkes and Laurie MacDonald, two top film executives
there. He was offered the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very un-English thing to do, but I kind of pitched
myself,'' Mendes said with a laugh. ``I said these people in it had
to be real and it had to have a very distinct style and I would get
a great cinematographer and I'd storyboard it and I'd have Kevin
Spacey and Annette Benning and not stars like Costner or
Travolta.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg insisted that he wasn't deeply concerned about Mendes'
inexperience. ``I had seen his production of `Oliver' on the London
stage while I was making `Saving Private Ryan,''' Spielberg said.
``I still remember the way he used lighting and the sets and
entrances and exits. It was a visual candy store. I sort of banked
his name in my mind. And then I saw `Cabaret.' It was so visually
splendid. Watching his plays _ he controlled the focus of my lens.
And it left you with an emotional impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Spacey, an Academy Award winner for his supporting role in ``The
Usual Suspects'' (1996), said he read the script in London while
appearing in ``The Iceman Cometh'' and was surprised that Mendes
wanted him for the role of Lester. ``I usually play characters who
are very quick, very manipulative and smart,'' he said. ``I usually
wade in dark, sort of treacherous waters. This is a man living one
step at a time, playing by his instincts. This is actually much
closer to me, to what I am, than those other parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Spacey said that Mendes' theatrical background _ and his lack of
film experience _ actually benefited the movie. ``One of the
advantages of working with first-time directors is that they don't
have rules, they're not entrenched in their own style,'' Spacey
said. ``And as a theatrical director, Sam knows about story, about
words, about arc. He knows how to handle the emotional terrain. Add
to that he's a visual stylist. What more could you want?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bening, who burst into tears after seeing the film for the
first time, said that Mendes' theatrical training overlapped with
an unusual level of confidence for a first-time movie director.
``He was constantly focused on the story, and that comes from the
theater,'' she said. ``The camera never calls attention to itself.
This is someone who didn't go to film school. You can tell. There's
nothing fancy about the way the story is told. It's simple in the
best sense of the word.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Mendes is planning the Sondheim musical and
nervously awaiting the release of ``American Beauty.'' Over the
years, he had toyed with the idea of directing other films _ but
backed out because of his inexperience. ``I got cold feet on a
couple of occasions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then came ``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendes said, ``The script took the decision out of my hands,
because I wanted to do it so much.'' He added, ``I went out and
said, `Please, this is what I want to do.' And they let me do it.''
He grinned. ``And now let's see what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
