<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4905 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-TALKING-CAR-2TAKE     09-08 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TALKING-CAR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKING AUTO COMPUTERS OFFER DIRECTIONS, DRIVING TIPS AND MORE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mich., Nev.)   (nk) 
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I've made the 16-mile trip from my apartment on
Manhattan's Upper West Side to a favorite restaurant on City Island
in the Bronx dozens of times. Yet a recent drive there over the
asphalt spaghetti of parkways and interstate expressways was,
thanks to the latest injection of digital technology into our
lives, like no other.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the voices of my wife and 3-year-old daughter in the
car, there was a robotic voice emanating from the automobile's
in-dash personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have four new messages,'' it said calmly when I asked
about the day's events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Read,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From news, received August 26th, '99, 7:58 p.m., hijacking in
Spain ends peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of promises and hands-off demonstrations at computer
and consumer electronics shows, the talking car is finally falling
into the hands of consumers. One of the first, the Clarion Auto PC,
is the result of a four-year collaboration between Microsoft and
the Clarion Corp., which makes car audio systems. The computer,
which was intentionally designed to fit into the slot in which car
stereo systems are installed in the factory, is on the market. And
its makers say it can be used in practically any car.
</P>
<P>
   This car system can say a lot more than just ``door ajar.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clarion Auto PC is about the size of a standard car stereo
and looks a lot like one, too. While I was driving along, it read
aloud short e-mail messages (drawn from the air by way of a special
FM radio receiver), real-time weather updates, news headlines and
reports on traffic conditions while spinning my CD's at a lowered
volume. It even plotted a series of detailed and often stunningly
accurate directions to the restaurant, gently guiding me with voice
prompts _ in its own oddly abbreviated style _ linked to the
computer's optional Global Positioning System receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two-and-a-half miles, bear right to on-ramp Cross-Bronx
Expr slash 178 Street slash Geo Washington B R,'' it said in a
clipped chirp (a voice I choose by adjusting the PCs pitch and tone
controls) after leading me to the Henry Hudson Parkway from my
apartment building near Columbus Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, PCs have become remarkably mobile and compact,
moving rapidly from desktop, laptop and handheld to coat pocket and
pocketbook. Now PCs are popping up in cars, offering their services
while threatening to take away a haven where a driver can sit and
essentially do nothing (other than concentrate on the road &UR;  &LR; _
unless the driver breaks that concentration by talking on a cell
phone, of course).
</P>
<P>
   ``Commuting in your car is the last piece of unconstructed time
left,'' said Jukka Rissanen, a Clarion project marketing
specialist. He noted that more than  &UR;  &LR; 80 million people traveled to
and from their jobs in cars. More than a quarter of them spend more
than two hours crammed into cars each workday, with little else to
do but listen to their stereos and stare through their windshields.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a huge untapped market for connectivity and
productivity,'' Rissanen said.
</P>
<P>
   The market is untapped largely because the car is one of the few
places left that isn't wired. As Rissanen pointed out, all it would
take to extend the office and living room into the car's front seat
would be a car-based computer that can, as the Auto PC
does, &UR;  &LR; retrieve and read e-mail; dial a number on a cellular
telephone, using an address book database; record memorandums; and
transfer information through wireless connections from palm-size
personal data assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Will that also mean a loss of the freedom that Americans in
particular have always associated with the automobile? What will it
mean to be on the road but within easy reach of anyone through
e-mail _ and, thanks to the GPS receiver, perhaps one day be easily
located by anybody?
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Frady, executive director of the National Automobile
Museum in Reno, Nev., predicted that car-based PCs would become as
common as car radios in the near future. ``We are finding that cars
are becoming home offices,'' she said. ``I think the car as family
transportation to go out for a Sunday drive and have ice cream and
a picnic belongs to a day gone by.''
</P>
<P>
   The Auto PC is not the only talking computer rolling down the
road. A voice-activated computer system developed by Visteon is
already offered with the new Jaguar LS. It manages the car's
heating and air-conditioning controls and radio and offers
hands-free dialing for cell phones. ``We think consumers are
looking for a way to optimize their time spent in a vehicle, be it
a better form of entertainment or business professionals needing to
check up on their e-mail,'' said Lori Markatos, the product team
leader for multimedia systems at Visteon Automotive Systems in
Dearborn, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The Visteon computer is installed at the factory and cannot be
easily moved into another car. The Auto PC, however, is a
60-megahertz computer (a Hitachi SH3 microprocessor with 16
megabytes of DRAM and 8 megabytes of ROM) that is made for the
``after market,'' which means that it &UR;  &LR; can be installed in almost
any car or even removed from a car its owner intends to sell, then
reinstalled in another car. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   With a price that starts at about $1,300, the Auto PC costs
about the same as a low-end desktop PC. But while it does have a
few handy buttons and a trackball, this is a computer that was
mostly built to be talked to instead of touched.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But before drivers turn over the inside of their cars to these
dashboard cousins of Hal 9000, there are some bugs to be worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   On my test drive, the Auto PC, which uses a simple and intuitive
version of Windows CE, responded to most of my voice commands. When
I said, ``Radio,'' the radio played. When I said, ``CD player,''
the first of six compact disks I had loaded began playinc. When I
said, ``Normal,'' the volume of the music settled on a pleasant
level.
</P>
<P>
   The command ``Auto PC,'' brought the unit to life. It indicated
its readiness with a dotted green line along its eight-color,
liquid-crystal-display screen. A different wake-up command can be
added to the basic 200 commands the computer can understand by
going to its set-up screen. I reset the computer to awaken whenever
it heard me intone, ``Computer.'' I couldn't resist pronouncing
``computer'' with a hint of a Scottish lilt, much like the way
Scotty spoke on the starship Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   If the computer fails to respond, you're in trouble. On a
previous test drive in New Jersey, the computer crashed for no
apparent reason, other than perhaps demonstration fatigue. Because
the Auto Clarion PC doubles as the car's AM-FM radio and CD player,
I had to drive back in total silence. It's a good thing it is not
tied to the car's brakes and ignition system. When Rissanen hit the
Reset button, the computer came back online with its default
settings.
</P>
<P>
   When the Auto PC does work, it requires little training. When I
began my trip to the restaurant, I asked the computer where I was.
For about 10 seconds, &UR;  &LR; it consulted its satellite system.
``Somewhere near Central Park and West 86th Street,'' it informed
me as I sat by the curb and punched in my destination information.
The information is entered on a small telephone-like keypad to the
right of the display screen. To enter the letter C for instance,
you press the 2 key four times (one press equals 2, two equals A,
three equals B). Before beginning, the computer warns the driver
that this procedure should never be done while the car is in
motion. To punch the keys while watching the display to make
certain that all the information is correctly entered takes all the
driver's attention anyway; driving at the same time would be
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  A special directional microphone mounted on the sun visor on
the driver's side picks up the commands. While the powered
microphone is designed to screen out background noises, I noticed
that the computer was much more attentive when the car's windows
were up. While I was idling with the windows down next to a
rumbling city bus, I had to practically scream at the computer
before it would acknowledge me.
</P>
<P>
   When the Auto PC becomes hard of hearing, you can awaken the
computer to receive commands by pushing a small button _ in my test
car, it was beneath the emergency brake handle. I found myself
mashing that button quite a bit when I had the car's stereo cranked
up to a salsa-friendly volume. Even under the best of conditions,
the Auto PC is most responsive when it is spoken to with a stern,
clear tone.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes that meant barking orders in a voice loud enough to
startle drivers waiting next to me at stoplights. But hey, it's a
machine. Politeness doesn't count.
</P>
<P>
   Still, enough commands were understood to make the trip
interesting, like the time when I tired of my CDs and shouted,
``Radio.'' When a random station came up, I simply said, ``Jazz,''
and my favorite jazz station (which I had preset) began to fill the
car with an early Miles Davis solo. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While I was fascinated by the machine's ability to understand
the human voice, I felt at points more like Jerry Van Dyke in ``My
Mother the Car'' than William Shatner in ``Star Trek.'' A bit more
kooky than cool.
</P>
<P>
   And even though a user doesn't have to look at the computer when
speaking to it, it's hard to not look at it _ as if it were a
person _ when making a request. From time to time, I found myself
defeating the purpose of the computer's interface engineering by
taking my eyes off the road to address it.
</P>
<P>
   There is a tiny keyboard of sorts for more complex functions,
like punching in destination information for GPS-assisted
navigation. And if the driver doesn't feel like asking, the
keyboard can be used for some simple jobs, like calling up the next
preset station on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   For the makers of car computers, the possibilities are almost
endless. Designers are talking about having a computer linked to a
car's fuel gauge so that when fuel runs low, the computer can
search its database for the nearest (and perhaps the cheapest)
gasoline station and guide the driver there. Car PCs could also be
tied to the car's vital systems _ engine, transmission, suspension
_ and warn of trouble before something breaks down, then transmit
that information through a wireless connection to a waiting
mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   The car computer's wireless communications _ which Ms. Markatos,
of Visteon, calls telematics _ may someday be more important than
roadside billboards. Restaurants, shopping centers and motels could
beam word of their blue-plate specials, basement bargains and room
rates to cars as they approached. And the car-based computers could
let passengers browse menus, place orders and register for a
night's rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``All kinds of companies want to be involved in that kind of
thing,'' Ms. Markatos said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, because the Auto PC (and the many others that will
probably follow it to the marketplace) is a personal computer, it
can be personalized by deciding what programs to install into it. I
can foresee an application that would wirelessly connect to my
son's business college in Ohio so that I could have the computer
read me information about his scholarship possibilities as I drive
to see him.
</P>
<P>
   Mundane? Perhaps. OK, it might be some time before I can cry,
``More power!'' to rev up a starship's computer. But telling the
Auto PC to read my e-mail while I prepared to play my favorite
Charlie Parker CD as I steered into a New York nightscape felt a
lot like the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1737EDT &QL; 
