<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MANA-MUSIC-NYTR &LR;      09-08 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANA-MUSIC-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANA CROSSES BORDERS AND LANGUAGE BARRIERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BILL DEAN   The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In their native Mexico and other parts of Latin America, the
Spanish-language rock group Mana has been about as popular in their
native tongue as The Beatles were in theirs. And the four-man rock
group did it the hard way: eschewing traditional Latin instruments
for the guitars, bass and drums of mainstream rock 'n' roll while
keeping their vocals in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Mana and its ``combination'' approach has
mushroomed to become the world's most popular and best-selling of
such acts, dubbed ``rock en espanol.''
</P>
<P>
   Of its 6 million albums sold worldwide, more than 2 million of
those have been bought in the United States alone.
</P>
<P>
   And Mana (pronounced ``ma-NAH'') remains the only true rock
group from Latin American to have an album certified gold (for
sales of 500,000 copies) north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Its new album, ``MTV Unplugged'' _ which breaks another barrier
by becoming the only Spanish-language album to achieve that status
_ was the first-ever rock en espanol album to debut at No. 1 on
Billboard's Latin charts.
</P>
<P>
   So Ricky Martin may get much of the hype and mainstream name
recognition in the United States, but Mana's status as the
most-successful rock en espanol group in the States makes it
equally significant in the Latin pop crossover phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Mana now crosses English-language barriers as easily
as it crosses the American border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time the tortilla flipped,'' Fernando ``Fher''
Olvera, Mana's lead singer and chief songwriter, told Latina
magazine. ``For Years, Latinos have been listening to rock in
English, and singing words to words they don't even understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Olvera, who started Mana 13 years ago in Guadalajara with
drummer Alex Gonzalez, knows what he's talking about.
</P>
<P>
   In their youth, Olvera, Gonzalez and bassist Juan Calleros may
have come from poor families. But they were just as influenced by
the Beatles and the Rolling Stones and the Police as many of their
northern counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The original goal of the group, called Sombrero Verde when it
began in 1986, was just to put food on the table. ``I began the
band to make money to eat, frankly,'' Olvera told the Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us came from wealthy families. Sometimes we had huge
problems. We sold no records, we had no concerts. But thanks to
Sombrero Verde, I paid my way through college.''
</P>
<P>
   The turning point came in 1992, when an early album called
``Donde Jugaran Las Ninas?'' (``Where Will the Little Girls
Play?'') became a hit and sold more than 3 million copies
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the band, which changed its name to Mana (for
``godsend'') when guitarist Sergio Vallin joined in 1994,
popularized rock en espanol and became its de facto definition.''
</P>
<P>
   The group has always incorporated Latin musical influences with
its guitars, bass and drums, however, despite the fact that Olvera
draws comparisons with English singer Sting because of his high
vocal range.
</P>
<P>
   So just because nine of the 15 songs on ``MTV Unplugged'' have
their lyrics translated to English in the CD booklet, doesn't mean
Mana plans to record an album in English anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it doesn't mean it won't, either.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dean writes for The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla., which is a
member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This article
was distributed by The New York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
