<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WACO-CONGRESS09-COX     09-08 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-CONGRESS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXAS RANGERS WILL GIVE HOUSE PANEL MATERIAL ON WACO
 &HT;    480&AMP;add. With WACO.
 &HT;    By REBECCA CARR and JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional investigators expect to receive new
evidence as early as Friday in their latest probe of the fiery
federal siege of the Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas six
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers, the state's police force, has informed the
House Government Reform and Oversight Committee that it will turn
over material in response to a subpoena seeking documents, videos
and audio tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The material is from the Rangers' investigation of the standoff
between law enforcement agents and Branch Davidian leader David
Koresh and his followers.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional investigators hope the material will offer insight
into the FBI's recent admission that agents launched potentially
flammable tear gas canisters at a concrete outpost near the cult's
compound on April 19, 1993. That admission is controversial because
the agency had steadfastly denied for six years that it used any
devices that could have started the fire that day.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Texas Rangers spokesman Mike Cox said the Rangers
expected to comply with the subpoena on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to the committee and were told it was a friendly
subpoena and to take as long as we needed,'' Cox said. ``Our
present plan is to get it to them by Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the committee requested documents and would receive ``a
report, as I understand it, a summary of the investigation and
maybe some support matter,'' but no physical evidence.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a keen congressional interest in the role played
by the U.S. Army's elite Delta Force and other military groups
during the 51-day siege that left 76 people dead inside the cult's
compound, two dozen of them children.
</P>
<P>
   The House investigation marks the third time that chamber has
investigated the incident. That fact in itself has spawned concern
among Democrats that this investigation will fan the same partisan
tempers that flared during the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question isn't whether a competent non-partisan
investigation is needed, it's whether this Republican-led Congress
can investigate anything without turning it into a political
circus,'' said Philip Schiliro, chief of staff to Rep. Henry
Waxman, D-Calif., the ranking minority member of the Government
Reform and Oversight Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans don't see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason why we have to have Round Three of Waco is the
Justice Department lied about the use of pyrotechnic devices for
six years,'' said Mark Corallo, spokesperson for the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The material supplied by the Texas Rangers is only the first
round of subpoenas issued by the panel's chairman, Rep. Dan Burton,
R-Ind. Burton has requested information from the White House,
Justice Department, FBI, Department of Defense and William
Johnston, the assistant U.S. attorney who prosecuted the surviving
Davidians. Those materials are due on Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., a member of Burton's committee, said
congressional hearings are inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress fails to hold hearings, we will assure the rest of
the executive branch we are not serious about reasserting the
oversight powers that have been so flagrantly ignored by Justice
and the rest of the Administration for the past six years,'' Barr
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., agreed that congressional hearings
were warranted, but he said those hearings should avoid the
partisanship that has become so commonplace on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should not be a partisan issue,'' Hutchinson said.
``There is no reason for it to be that way. No gain to either side.
It's a law enforcement issue, a credibility issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
