<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-ECOMMERCE-ART-NYT &LR;      09-08 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING ONLINE TO BUY FURNITURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Calif.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TIMOTHY JACK WARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're not just buying books anymore. Internet customers have
quickly moved past life insurance and airplane tickets and are
surfing for furniture: poufs and pillow-back sofas, writing desks
and ergonomic office chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Marie Pagano, a Hollywood decorator, has E-shopped for
high-profile clients, including Nicholas Cage, from New York to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go on the Web for a big-ticket item, it's a risky
thing,'' she said. She can't just carry a lamp or an ottoman to a
client's house to try it out, leaving a credit card behind at a
shop.
</P>
<P>
   But she does turn to the Internet when she's stumped, say, by a
star's request for three huge antler chandeliers for his screening
room. (``They're very popular out here,'' she said.) At
www.Widerview.com, a Northern California site, she found Paul
Bunyan-size elk chandeliers and ordered $20,000 worth. ``They came
in crates that were as big as cars,'' she said. ``I would have paid
three times as much in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Furniture shopping on the Web is growing by the day, with
manufacturers and electronic marketers offering speedier downloads,
easier navigation and slicker sites to attract and retain
customers. While some industry analysts have doubts whether surfers
will spend $10,000 on a dining room sight unseen, others note that
customers in stores are already making a giant leap of faith by
leaving hefty deposits on furniture 12 weeks in advance. But there
is no debate that the furniture business is making a bet on the
Web. Witness the current ``.com clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until a few months ago, people had virtually no choices,''
said Michael May, a digital commerce analyst at Jupiter
Communications, a new-media research company. What has limited the
growth of furniture sales online, he said, ``is simply a lack of
supply, not of demand.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news _ and bad news _ is that more of everything is
suddenly available. Hundreds of mom-and-pop digital retailers like
Fred Friar, who sells handmade sassafras chairs from his West
Virginia farm, now have the opportunity to be seen (in his case, at
www.home.earthlink.net/ffriar/). For the style-starved, there are
small shops showing well-designed wares, classic and new. Big
retailers like Crate and Barrel, Smith &AMP; Hawken and Restoration
Hardware are testing the water with online stores; Ethan Allen is
plunging in: the company, with sales of $756 million for the last
fiscal year, is to unveil a site in October offering 4,000
furniture choices. (A guide to the most compelling sites is on page
F5.)
</P>
<P>
   ``With $300 million in venture capital being thrown at
home-furnishing Web sites this year, something big is going to
happen,'' said Brian Carroll, online editor for Furniture Today, a
High Point, N.C., trade newspaper. ``But who the winners and losers
will be is unknown. The consumer will decide. She'll shop; we'll
adapt.''
</P>
<P>
   Reversing the gender bias among shoppers on the Web, women now
top the 50 percent mark, according to Media Metrix, which measures
online shopping behavior.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, many Web retailers and analysts sense that
men are more comfortable shopping for furniture online than in a
store. But just how much anyone is really spending remains unclear.
Carroll estimated that of furniture-store sales for 1998, which
totaled $45.3 billion, maybe 3 percent of sales were generated on
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manufacturers themselves don't know how the products are
purchased, whether from a retailer or a site,'' Carroll said.
(Internet stores have noticed that the peak hour for shopping in
the Northeast is 11 a.m., with people apparently buying lamps and
sofas from the office.)
</P>
<P>
   New Internet shoppers say they were first emboldened by small
purchases at Amazon.com. Elizabeth Dettoni, who works for an online
brokerage, took to the Internet to arrange much of her recent move
from a 600-square-foot studio in Manhattan to a two-bedroom condo
in Westchester County. Five days before her move, she spent about
$800 on a mission-style armoire, bookshelves and a table from
Sauder, at www.sauder.com.
</P>
<P>
   As promised, the furniture was delivered ready to assemble the
day she moved in. When she found a chipped part, the company
replaced it and sent it to Ms. Dettoni's home via priority mail.
``These people went the extra mile,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pagano, the Hollywood decorator, also savors the
convenience. She downloads images from Web sites and sends them via
e-mail to clients on movie sets, or they ``conference shop''
online, linked by cell phones and laptops. ``Instead of jaded
people in Los Angeles or New York showrooms, people with major
attitudes, I deal with lovely, homespun people who are very happy
to spend time with you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, traditional stores fear that their business will be
destroyed by online transactions; having invested in display,
advertising and sales help, they worry that shoppers will
test-drive recliners in the stores, sample the store service and
then use the Internet to find the best price. ( Carroll, who has
price-shopped himself, argues that ``furniture on the Net is no
different in price than it is in most stores, although the
perception is that it is.'')
</P>
<P>
   The field is so new, there is no reliable measurement of
shoppers' habits yet, but the tea leaves read differently to Linda
Lewi of Homeportfolio .com, an online clearing house for consumer
information about high-end appliances and furniture. Based on a
sampling of site visitors, she said, ``Consumers are using the
Internet for information and service, then turning to retailers to
buy.''
</P>
<P>
   For shoppers, the ultimate empowerment may come the day digital
retailers end ``showroom shutout,'' the decades-old ``to the
trade'' system that has kept some haut designers behind closed
showroom doors. Throwing down the gauntlet, Homeportfolio.com, has
plans for a new digital shopping area in October featuring products
of companies that once sold only to architects and designers.
</P>
<P>
   Opening a Web site means there is no big-box store to rent or
stock. For companies selling $2,800 Knoll sofas, circa 1965, from
Antwerp, Belgium, (at www.fiftie-fiftie.be) or $4,600 boardroom
tables (from www.dwr.com, a site in San Francisco), it feels less
like the grand opening of a retail store than a eerie new kind of
fishing _ like rowing out onto a vast etherous pond, casting with a
quiet plunk and waiting for a customer to bite.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m. on July 12 from his office in San Francisco, Rob
Forbes went fishing. His lure was www.dwr.com, otherwise known as
Design Within Reach, a new home furnishings catalog and Web site,
both designed by Pentagram, the international design firm, which is
a partner in the venture.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, the former director of inventory management at
Williams-Sonoma, did not anticipate catching much of anything the
first day, though he advertised in Metropolis magazine and threw
out some bait: photographs of hundreds of modern furnishings from
classic to new designs, including the hot Cricket outdoor chair
from Italy for $45. Lo, there was soon a frenzy of orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in battle mode,'' he said, recalling the 80 e-mail
messages and more than 200 phone calls the first day.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first customers was Ronald Fiore, who designs
showrooms for Baker Furniture. He spotted a dining chair by Charles
Eames for $140 and ordered two for his Greensboro, N.C., loft. They
were delivered exactly when promised, the next week. ``I thought it
would be a deal where you'd have to buy a container full from Italy
to get that price,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
