<P>
   AIRLINE-COMPLAINTS _ WASHINGTON _ Airline customer complaints
shot up 87 percent in July to the highest level since March 1988.
Flight delays and missed connections led the list, which also
included complaints about passenger service and mishandled baggage,
according to the Department of Transportation. Southwest had the
fewest complaints among major carriers, and American had the most.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   w/DELTA-COMPLAINTS _ ATLANTA _ Delta in the second quarter
maintained its dubious distinction for bumping more passengers
involuntarily than any other carrier _ in fact, more than all 9
other major airlines combined, according to DOT figures released
Wednesday. But the airline said remedies to the problem are now
taking effect and promised dramatic improvement in the current
quarter. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM _ ATLANTA _ In merging, Viacom and CBS are following the
ploughed footsteps of such media giants as Disney and Time Warner.
Many industry oberservers have come to see such mergers as almost
natural, leading to a day in the near future when four to six
companies control most of what the world hears on the radio, sees
on television and views in the movie theaters. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
