<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4937 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-MILITARY09-COX     09-08 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MILITARY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE EMPHASIZES WAR RECORD IN SPEECH TO AMERICAN LEGION
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Vice President Al Gore paraded his Vietnam war
experience before the American Legion national convention
Wednesday, a subtle reminder that his two major rivals for the
presidency avoided America's longest military conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in a speech largely tailored to appeal to the American
Legion's interest in a strong defense and improving veterans's
benefits, repeatedly referred to his military service in Vietnam.
In addition, he was accompanied to the event by Robert Dalabar, a
Seattle engineer who served in Vietnam with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was honored to wear my country's uniform during the Vietnam
War,'' said Gore, sporting the military-styled American Legion cap
that signifies his membership in American Legion Post 57 in his
home state of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   He did not mention Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
front-runner in the Republican presidential campaign, or former
Sen. Bill Bradley, the vice president's sole challenger for the
Democratic nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But the contrast was clear as he declared that his commitment to
veterans is ``more than a policy position'' taken by a politician.
``It is a personal and moral standard to bear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Gore enlisted in the Army and volunteered for service
in the Indochina conflict. He was one of the few children of
privilege to do so at the time. He was a Harvard graduate and his
father, then a U.S. senator, was an outspoken critic of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, himself conflicted over the increasingly unpopular war,
went to Vietnam as an Army journalist assigned to a non-combat
engineering brigade about 25 miles from Saigon. He spent about five
months in the war zone, less than the typical tour of nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Bush got a coveted spot in a Texas Air National Guard unit after
graduating from Yale University in May 1968, the year that troop
levels in Vietnam reached 525,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley received a rare slot in the Air Force Reserve in May
1967 just before signing a $500,000 contract to play professional
basketball. From 1966 to 1967, U.S. troops in Vietnam increased
from 215,000 to 400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Guard and reserve units were rarely pressed into duty during the
Vietnam war. Manpower needs were met mostly through the draft of
young men without college deferments. Consequently, Guard and
reserve units became havens for men who lost their deferments and
wanted to avoid combat.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's route into pilot training with the Texas Air National
Guard has been a source of controversy, with suggestions mounting
that he received preferential treatment because his father, former
President George Bush, was a member of Congress at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy erupted anew this week after a report by the
Dallas Morning News that former Texas House Speaker Ben Barnes had
told friends that longtime Bush family friend Sidney Adger asked
him to help Bush get into the National Guard in the late 1960s.
Bush has denied any knowledge of any such help by Adger, now
deceased.
</P>
<P>
   Less examined has been Bradley's opportunity to join the Air
Force Reserve in April 1967, just before he signed a four-year
contract to play with the New York Knicks in the National
Basketball Association. At the time, there were only 45,000
reservists, the vast majority with prior active duty experience.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley served five months on active duty, then spent six years
as an active reservist, requiring service one weekend a month and
two weeks every summer. But during the the 1968-69 basketball
season, Bradley did not miss a single Knicks game, even on
weekends, according to an examination of Bradley's military
experience by the Star-Ledger newspaper in Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   According to Selective Service records, Bradley received four
deferments from military service while a student at Princeton and
Oxford from 1964 to 1967, when he joined the reserves. He was
listed as 1-A, available for military service, on Dec. 11, 1970,
just 15 days before Gore arrived in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in 1970, the Knicks, with Bradley as one of the stars,
had won their first-ever NBA championship. Two years later, with
the Vietnam war still raging, the Knicks returned to the NBA finals
and lost. The Knicks won another championship in 1973, two years
before Saigon fell to a North Vietnamese invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Bradley's presidential campaign did not
respond to telephone calls seeking comment about the former New
Jersey senator's military record. Bradley formally announced his
presidential candidacy Wednesday in his boyhood home of Crystal
City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
