<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Business Week profile says McColl facing last hurdles
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Calling him a ``feisty ex-Marine,'' Business Week
(Sept. 13) profiles Hugh L. McColl Jr., chairman of Bank of America
Corp., the $614 billion megabank formed from the merger of
Charlotte, N.C.-based NationsBank and San Francisco-based
BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to his savvy dealmaking, McColl stands atop an empire
of 4,500 branches and 14,000 ATMs holding 8.6 percent of the
nation's deposits,'' the magazine says. ``But ... McColl has found
the footing far more treacherous than he expected 17 months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Business Week says McColl, 64, confronted defections from former
BankAmerica executives in his first year, a $372 million write-down
on a hedge-fund deal by the former BankAmerica management and ``a
bad bet on interest rates'' that saddled the company with more than
$2.4 billion in paper losses in its bond portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   But the magazine says there's no turning back ``for McColl and
his troops.''
</P>
<P>
   With just under two years until his retirement, his final hurdle
is to tie together his various acquisitions ``and deliver the
elusive payoff from two decades of aggressive dealmaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The next Silicon Valley?
</P>
<P>
   The under-40 crowd is the target audience of Atlanta's newest
magazine from the Leader Publishing Group, Catalyst
(September/October).
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural issue considers Atlanta a potential ``Silicon
Valley of the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Before that can become a reality, it says, Atlanta ``first has
to grapple with a dearth of talent, increase its venture capital
and learn to take big risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboy capitalism
</P>
<P>
   A new breed of debt-laden, swashbuckling owner is changing the
professional football business, Forbes (Sept. 20) reports, giving
top honors for that role to Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine describes him as ``a risk-taking former oil
wildcatter who wants to dismantle the revenue-sharing of (National
Football League) branded merchandise, now controlled by NFL
Properties.''
</P>
<P>
   He has already broken the league's hold on promotional deals by
selling ``pouring rights'' to Pepsi and making American Express the
``official'' Cowboys charge card.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes estimates the Cowboys take in $24 million a year from
promotional deals, or more than three times any other team. Forbes
also says the Cowboys topped the league in 1998 operating profit at
$57 million and revenue, $162 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
