<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: The following text accompanies the weather map for Thursday,
September 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first substantial outbreak of autumnal air will invade the
northern Great Lakes on Thursday behind a cold front pressing
toward the Atlantic seaboard. A testament to the early season chill
will be found across northern Minnesota, where mid-afternoon
readings only reach the 50s. As the cool air crosses the still
tepid Great Lakes, narrow bands of intense showers will form east
of Lake Superior and Lake Michigan. The unstable combination of
cold air overlying the warmer water may spawn isolated waterspouts
over the Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   A narrow corridor of scattered showers and thunderstorms will
erupt from western New York to the central Appalachians as the
eastward-moving cold front undercuts and lifts moderately humid
air. Later Thursday night, these showers will move to the Eastern
Seaboard and strengthen as the front intercepts exceptionally humid
air near the coast.
</P>
<P>
   A jet stream disturbance will spark a cluster of thunderstorms
near Alabama and the eastern Gulf Coast on Thursday. Meanwhile,
partial sunshine and sultry conditions will cover the Southeast
Coast and Florida with spotty afternoon thunderstorms, especially
across southern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant sun will occur an expansive area from the northern
Rockies to the central Plains as a large high pressure system and
its associated sinking currents of air cover the region. Patches of
high clouds will stream into the Southwest as limited moisture from
Tropical Storm Greg drifts north from the east-central Pacific.
Meanwhile in the Atlantic, Tropical Storm Floyd will move steadily
west toward the Windward Islands.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Hurricane Controller  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A group of islands 700 miles east of the Carolinas lends its
name to a prominent summer weather system, the ``Bermuda high.''
Clockwise winds around this sprawling high pressure zone in the
central Atlantic not only direct sultry air to the East Coast, but
also play a role in steering hurricanes. A typical hurricane moves
west along the southern part of the Bermuda high before veering
north along its western flank. Thursday, Tropical Storm Floyd, 500
miles east of the Windward Islands will move steadily west. Its
ultimate path will be shaped by the strength and position of the
Bermuda high. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
