<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PREVIEW-NEWSEASON-$ADV12-7TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE FROM `WHITEBOYS' TO `X-MEN' TO `MY MOTHER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Sept. 12)  
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `AMERICAN BEAUTY'
</P>
<P>
   The film debut of the hot Broadway director Sam Mendes
(``Cabaret,'' ``The Blue Room'') is a scalding, darkly funny satire
of American suburban affluence and its discontents. Kevin Spacey
and Annette Bening are a bickering couple, Thora Birch is their
surly daughter, and Mena Suvari a high-school Lolita. A right-wing
gun nut (Chris Cooper) lives next door with his drug-dealing
teen-age son (the newcomer Wes Bentley). ``The Ice Storm'' meets
``Election'' meets ``Happiness'' meets ``The Opposite of Sex.''
Release date: Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   `BREAKFAST OF CHAMPIONS'
</P>
<P>
   If Kurt Vonnegut Jr.'s novels haven't translated readily into
film, perhaps that master of mood Alan Rudolph can turn the trick
with his adaptation of the author's 1973 best-selling novel. Bruce
Willis is Dwayne Hoover, the Midland City mogul facing a midlife
crisis, and Albert Finney, the town art festival's guest of honor.
With Nick Nolte and Barbara Hershey. Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   `FOR LOVE OF THE GAME'
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has been very good to Kevin Costner (``Bull Durham''
and ``Field of Dreams''). And in his latest movie, he returns to
the playing field as Billy Chapel, a fading, about-to-be-traded
pitcher for the Detroit Tigers who sorts through his past while
pitching a perfect game. Directed by Sam Raimi (``A Simple Plan''),
with Kelly Preston as the love of Costner's life. Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   `ROMANCE'
</P>
<P>
   In the French director Catherine Breillat's searing erotic
drama, a young woman struggles for sexual autonomy and a
non-oppressive connection with a man. Groundbreaking in its graphic
explicitness, the film has created a sensation in Europe. Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   `BLUE STREAK'
</P>
<P>
   A convicted jewel thief (Martin Lawrence) discovers on leaving
jail that he hid his stash of diamonds in what is now a Los Angeles
police station. Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   `GET BRUCE'
</P>
<P>
   A behind-the-scenes portrait of Bruce Vilanch, the comedy writer
and television personality (``Hollywood Squares'') who supplies
pearls of wit for Billy Crystal, Bette Midler, Whoopi Goldberg and
other awards show presenters. Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   `SUGAR TOWN'
</P>
<P>
   The contemporary music scene with its hangers-on and clawingly
ambitious aspirants is unromantically scrutinized in the film
co-directed by Allison Anders (``Grace of My Heart'') and Kurt
Voss. With Rosanna Arquette, Ally Sheedy, John Taylor (of Duran
Duran), John Doe, Michael des Barres and Jade Gordon. Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   `THE BIG TEASE'
</P>
<P>
   Glasgow's finest hairdresser (the popular Scottish comedian
Craig Ferguson) travels to Los Angeles to compete in an
international hairdressing competition. The mockumentary has been
nicknamed ``Rocky in Curlers.'' Sept. 22.
</P>
<P>
   `MUMFORD'
</P>
<P>
   Loren Dean plays an enigmatic ``psychologist'' who descends upon
a sleepy rural town and cures the residents of their psychic ills.
Lawrence Kasdan (``The Big Chill'') directs an ensemble cast that
includes Alfre Woodard, Hope Davis, David Paymer, Jane Adams, Mary
McDonnell, Ted Danson, Jason Lee, Martin Short, Pruitt Taylor Vince
and Robert Stack. Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   `DOUBLE JEOPARDY'
</P>
<P>
   After being framed for the murder of her unfaithful husband and
spending years in jail, a woman (Ashley Judd) discovers her husband
is actually alive and living with another woman. When she wants to
seek revenge, a cynical parole officer (Tommy Lee Jones) tries to
prevent her from committing a crime for which she has already been
convicted and served time. Bruce Beresford directed. Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   `DOG PARK'
</P>
<P>
   Romantic comedy about young singles and their pooches stars Luke
Wilson, Janeane Garofalo, Natasha Henstridge, Kathleen Robertson
and Mark McKinney. Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   `GUINEVERE'
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Polley (``The Sweet Hereafter,'' ``Go'') is a 21-year-old
who becomes sexually involved with a much older photographer
(Stephen Rea). Written and directed by Audrey Wells, the film
created a buzz at the 1999 Sundance Film Festival. Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   `JAKOB THE LIAR'
</P>
<P>
   In the first of the season's two Holocaust comedies, Robin
Williams plays a Polish cafe owner in the Jewish ghetto who boosts
his neighbors' hopes up by pretending to have a radio that
broadcasts reports that the war is nearing an end. Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   `ONE MAN'S HERO'
</P>
<P>
   Lance Hool's historical drama features Tom Berenger and Joaquim
De Almeida as Irish immigrants who desert the U.S. Army to fight
with the Mexicans in the Mexican-American War. Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   `THREE KINGS'
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the Gulf War, four soldiers in occupied Kuwait
embark on an illegal search for a cache of gold bullion. The movie,
which is critical of United States policy in Kuwait, stars George
Clooney as the mastermind and Mark Wahlberg, Ice Cube and Spike
Jonze as his treasure-hunting recruits. Not your standard adventure
movie. David O. Russell (``Flirting With Disaster'') directed. Oct.
1.
</P>
<P>
   `HAPPY, TEXAS'
</P>
<P>
   An audience favorite at the 1999 Sundance Film Festival, Mark
Illsley's comedy traces the adventures of two escaped prisoners who
travel to a small Texas town where they are mistaken for gay beauty
pageant directors. With Jeremy Northam, Steve Zahn and William H.
Macy. Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   `THE ADVENTURES OF ELMO IN GROUCHLAND'
</P>
<P>
   From the world of ``Sesame Street'' and the Jim Henson Muppet
Workshop comes the film debut of Elmo, who goes on a mission to
retrieve a blanket from the owner of a garbage dump (Mandy
Patinkin). Big Bird, Oscar the Grouch, Bert and Ernie, and Vanessa
Williams are among those on hand. Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   `DRIVE ME CRAZY'
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Joan Hart (from ``Sabrina, the Teenage Witch''), a high
school senior, embarks on a campaign to transform her neighbor
(Adrian Grenier) into a presentable prom date. Oct 1.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `MYSTERY ALASKA'
</P>
<P>
   A publicity stunt spins out of control when the New York Rangers
play a hockey match against the ragtag local team from Mystery,
Alaska, a tiny hockey-loving village. With Russell Crowe, Hank
Azaria, Mary McCormack, Lolita Davidovich and Burt Reynolds. Oct.
1.
</P>
<P>
   `PLUNKETT AND MacLEANE'
</P>
<P>
   Jake Scott's debut film reunites Robert Carlyle and Jonny Lee
Miller from ``Trainspotting'' in a tale of two notorious
18th-century highwaymen who conspire to stage holdups of
aristocrats' coaches. With Liv Tyler, Alan Cumming, and Michael
Gambon. Oct. 1
</P>
<P>
   `SIEGFRIED AND ROY: THE MAGIC BOX'
</P>
<P>
   IMAX film of the world-famous Las Vegas illusionists. Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   `THE GRANDFATHER'
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Garci's drama, Oscar nominated for best foreign film,
is set in turn-of-the-century Spain and follows the return from
Peru of a penniless, nearly blind aristocrat determined to find out
which of his two granddaughters is illegitimate. Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   `RANDOM HEARTS'
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Pollack directed the romantic drama about an internal
affairs cop (Harrison Ford) and a New Hampshire congresswoman
(Kristin Scott Thomas) who become involved after the bodies of
their spouses are discovered seated together on a crashed
Miami-bound plane. Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   `THE LIMEY'
</P>
<P>
   In the contemporary thriller directed by Steven Soderburgh,
Terence Stamp plays an ex-con (a character resurrected from Ken
Loach's 1967 movie ``Poor Cow'') investigating his daughter's death
in Los Angeles. Peter Fonda is a sleazy record executive. Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   `SUPERSTAR'
</P>
<P>
   Mary Katherine Gallagher (Molly Shannon), the popular ``Saturday
Night Live'' character, will go to any lengths to receive a
romantic Hollywood-style smooch. When a Roman Catholic teen
magazine sponsors a talent contest whose grand prize is a free trip
to Los Angeles to appear as a movie extra, she seizes her
opportunity. Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   `WHITEBOYS'
</P>
<P>
   The gifted performance artist and master of urban dialects Danny
Hoch stars as a white hip-hop poet from Iowa who moves to Chicago
hoping to write gangsta rap hits like his black idols. Directed by
Marc Levin (``Slam''). Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   `BOYS DON'T CRY'
</P>
<P>
   Already the subject of a 1998 documentary, Brandon Teena, a
charismatic transsexual lesbian in Falls City, Neb., who was raped
and murdered by two male friends when they discovered her true
gender, is played by Hilary Swank in Kimberly Peirce's devastating
movie, a selection of the New York Film Festival. Chloe Sevigny is
Lana, the loyal girlfriend who stuck by Brandon even after the
truth came out. Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   `L'ENNUI'
</P>
<P>
   The French contemporary update of Alberto Moravia's novel is
jam-packed with frantic simulated sex. The more energy Charles
Berling (skinny and intense as ever) spends ``possessing'' his
bovine teenage lover (a remarkable performance by Sophie
Guillemin), the more unpossessible she becomes. Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   `BEEFCAKE'
</P>
<P>
   Thom Fitzgerald's witty documentary movie looks deeply into the
1950s physique-magazine and bodybuilding culture. Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   `CREMASTER 2'
</P>
<P>
   The art-world enfant-terrible Matthew Barney's latest adventure
in erotic symbolism, ritual and pageantry. Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   `FIGHT CLUB'
</P>
<P>
   The pitch black comedy directed by David Fincher (``Seven'')
follows the descent of a mild-mannered automobile-recall
coordinator (Edward Norton) into a violent, secret world of
bare-knuckle fight clubs, under the tutelage of a charismatic
psychopath (Brad Pitt). Hanging around the pair is a nihilistic
rebel, Marla (Helena Bonham Carter). A movie that starts out as a
nasty social satire turns into a metaphysical reflection on
American machismo and the lure of violence. Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   `THE STORY OF US'
</P>
<P>
   The romantic comedy, directed by Rob Reiner, stars Bruce Willis
as a writer and Michelle Pfeiffer as a crossword puzzle editor,
married for 15 years, who decide on a trial separation. Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   `BODY SHOTS'
</P>
<P>
   Was it rape or wasn't it? As a group of swinging singles
reassemble the pieces after a night of wild drinking and rough sex,
conflicting views of what happened emerge. With Tara Reid, Brad
Rowe and Jerry O'Connell. Directed by Michael Cristofer. Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   `MAN OF THE CENTURY'
</P>
<P>
   The farcical comedy, which won an award at the 1999 Slamdance
festival, looks at a Manhattan newspaper reporter who believes he's
living in the 1920s. Directed by Adam Abraham. With Gibson Frazier,
Susan Egan and Anthony Rapp. Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   `THE BOYS'
</P>
<P>
   Critically lauded in Australia, Rowan Woods' film, adapted from
a stage play by Gordon Graham, follows the tense homecoming of an
angry, unstable ex-convict (David Wenham) who has served a year in
prison for deadly assault. Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   `A GIRL CALLED ROSEMARIE'
</P>
<P>
   The German film directed by Bernd Eichinger recalls a scandal
involving prostitution and political intrigue in mid-1950s
Frankfurt. Nina Hoss, in a star-making performance, is Rosemarie.
Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   `THE STRAIGHT STORY'
</P>
<P>
   David Lynch (``Blue Velvet'') directed the true story of Alvin
Straight (Richard Farnsworth), who traveled 260 miles from Iowa to
Wisconsin by lawn mower to visit his ailing brother (Harry Dean
Stanton). Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   `JULIEN DONKEY-BOY'
</P>
<P>
   Harmony Korine, the screenwriter of ``Kids'' and the director of
``Gummo'' gives us another splat of urban anomie in this movie
about a teenage rebel (Ewen Bremner of ``Trainspotting'') from
Queens, his tyrannical father (Werner Herzog), and pregnant sister
(Chloe Sevigny). The camera work takes digital video into a new
realm of electric hallucinatory colors. A selection of the New York
Film Festival. Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   `SAME OLD SONG'
</P>
<P>
   Alain Renais directed the movie musical set in contemporary
Paris that pays affectionate tribute to Dennis Potter. The score,
lip-synched by the characters, combines French music hall classics
and contemporary ballads. Among the topics addressed by this
buoyant, oddball songfest featuring an ensemble cast led by Pierre
Arditi are real estate, agoraphobia, hypochondria and Parisian
tourist landmarks. Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   `ANYWHERE BUT HERE'
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Wang's screen adaptation of Mona Simpson's 1986 novel,
about a brooding teen-age girl (Natalie Portman) and her flaky,
flamboyant mother (Susan Sarandon) who move from Wisconsin to
Beverly Hills, burrows deeply into their complicated love-hate
relationship. With her mixture of beauty and talent, Ms. Portman
suggests the young Elizabeth Taylor crossed with a teen-age Meryl
Streep. Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   `BRINGING OUT THE DEAD'
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Cage is a tormented paramedic in New York's Hell's
Kitchen, and Patricia Arquette is the daughter of a heart-attack
victim. Martin Scorsese directed and Paul Schrader adapted the
screenplay from Joe Connelly's novel. ``Taxi Driver'' meets
``Affliction''? Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   `THE BEST MAN'
</P>
<P>
   Taye Diggs is a writer whose about-to-be published novel reveals
a past affair with his best friend's fiancee on his friend's
wedding eve. Trouble ensues. With Morris Chestnut, Nia Long, Monica
Calhoun and Melissa DeSousa. Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   `CRAZY IN ALABAMA'
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Banderas makes his directing debut in the civil
rights-era drama of a Southern housewife (Melanie Griffith) who
murders her abusive husband and flees to Hollywood with dreams of
stardom. Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   `HOLY SMOKE'
</P>
<P>
   In the Australian director Jane Campion's newest film, a
selection of the New York Film Festival, Kate Winslet is an
Australian who joins an Indian cult and Harvey Keitel the American
hired by her family to de-program her. They fall in love. Steamy,
as well as thought-provoking. Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   `JOE THE KING'
</P>
<P>
   The directorial debut of the actor Frank Whaley won a
screenwriting award at the 1999 Sundance Film Festival. A
14-year-old boy (Noah Fleiss) with an abusive father (Val Kilmer)
and a dysfunctional mother impulsively commits a crime, with
far-reaching repercussions. With Ethan Hawke and Camryn Manheim.
Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   `THE CITY'
</P>
<P>
   David Riker's debut film (in Spanish with English subtitles)
consists of four vignettes about disenfranchised Latin American
immigrants living in New York City. Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   `SHOW ME LOVE'
</P>
<P>
   The feature film debut of the Swedish writer-director Lukas
Moodysson follows the growing pains of two teen-age girls
(Alexandra Dahlstrom and Rebecca Liljeberg) in a small Swedish
town. Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   `BEING JOHN MALKOVICH'
</P>
<P>
   The wildly inventive surreal comedy (and New York Film Festival
selection) directed by Spike Jonze follows the adventures of a
puppeteer who takes an office job (John Cusack) and discovers a
portal through which he can enter the mind of the actor John
Malkovich (playing himself) for 15 minutes. Things get complicated
when he falls for his scheming co-worker (Catherine Keener), who
wants to exploit the portal as a tourist attraction. Cameron Diaz
(almost unrecognizable here) plays Cusack's frowzy wife. Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   `MUSIC OF THE HEART'
</P>
<P>
   The match of the horror director Wes Craven and Meryl Streep is
an odd one. In the drama adapted from the 1995 documentary ``Small
Wonders,'' Ms. Streep plays Roberta Guaspari, a violin teacher in
East Harlem who fights back when the school board cancels her
funding. Angela Bassett is the principal and Gloria Estefan (in her
dramatic film debut) one of the teachers. Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   `THE LEGEND OF 1900'
</P>
<P>
   Giuseppe Tornatore's first English-language film is the mystical
story of a piano prodigy named Nineteen Hundred (Tim Roth) who was
abandoned on a trans-Atlantic steamer and has never set foot on
land. One day he is challenged to a piano duel by Jelly Roll
Morton. Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   `DREAMING OF JOSEPH LEES'
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Graves is the title character in the psychological drama
of an Englishman vacationing in Italy who is injured in an accident
and becomes the obsessive object of desire of a woman named Eva
(Samantha Morton). Eric Styles directed. Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   `THE HOUSE ON HAUNTED HILL'
</P>
<P>
   The update of the 1958 Vincent Price camp horror classic follows
five strangers who have been offered $1 million each to spend one
night in a house that has been rigged to scare the guests away.
Unseen forces take over. Geoffrey Rush, Famke Janssen and Peter
Gallagher star; William Malone directs. Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   `PRINCESS MONONOKE'
</P>
<P>
   Hayao Miyazaki, Japan's leading animator, directed this violent
story of war between human civilization and the beast gods of the
forest. A huge hit in Japan, this import features the voices of
Claire Danes, Billy Crudup and Billy Bob Thornton. A selection of
the New York Film Festival. Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   MY BEST FIEND
</P>
<P>
   In Werner Herzog's personal documentary, the noted German
director analyzes his intensely volatile love-hate relationship
with the late actor Klaus Kinski. Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   `THE INSIDER'
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mann (``Heat'') directed the based-on-true-events story
of how the CBS program ``60 Minutes'' was pressured to drop a story
about tobacco-industry whistleblower Jeffrey Wigand (Russell Crowe)
because the network feared a major lawsuit. Christopher Plummer is
Mike Wallace and Al Pacino his longtime producer, Lowell Bergman.
Based on Marie Brenner's Vanity Fair article with a screenplay by
Eric Roth (``Forrest Gump''). The most media-insider movie since
``Primary Colors.'' Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   `THE BONE COLLECTOR'
</P>
<P>
   Denzel Washington plays a retired quadriplegic forensic
detective in New York City who teams up with Angelina Jolie to
track down a serial killer. Based on a novel by Jeffrey Deaver, the
thriller was directed by Phillip Noyce. With Queen Latifah and Ed
O'Neill. Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   `THE MESSENGER: THE STORY OF JOAN OF ARC'
</P>
<P>
   Coming right on the heels of Leelee Sobieski's television Joan
of Arc is this screen biopic, directed by Luc Besson (``The Fifth
Element'') and starring Milla Jovovich and John Malkovich (as the
King of France). With Faye Dunaway and Dustin Hoffman. Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
