<SLUG> BC-NASA-ASTRONAUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA PULLS ASTRONAUT FROM STATION CONSTRUCTION FLIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unusual move, NASA has pulled a key astronaut from a
high-priority international space station construction flight next
spring, an agency spokesman confirmed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Astronaut Mark Lee was bumped from the five-member shuttle crew
that is to deliver the bus-sized U. S. research laboratory to the
new station in late May. He was to join a shuttle colleague for at
least three spacewalks to connect the laboratory module to already
orbiting station components.
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration did not
disclose the reasons for its actions, and efforts to reach Lee, a
47-year-old Air Force colonel, were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this a disciplinary action? The answer is no,'' said NASA
spokesman Ed Campion. ``It's an internal astronaut office matter.
This is being done essentially to maintain a high level of
professionalism necessary for the overall integrity of the space
flight program.``
</P>
<P>
   Lee is eligible for a future flight assignment, Campion said.
</P>
<P>
   Astronaut Robert Curbeam, a 37-year-old Navy lieutenant
commander who logged a previous shuttle mission in 1997, will take
Lee's place. Curbeam had been assigned as a spacewalker to a
mid-2000 station assembly flight.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining NASA's astronaut corps in 1984, Lee has flown in
space four times.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Lee served as the payload commander on a mission to
upgrade the Hubble Space Walk, logging three successful spacewalks.
In 1994, he participated in the first untethered spacewalk in a
decade as he and a colleague test flew a new back-mounted jet pack
developed as a space station rescue device.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Lee became half of the first married couple to fly in
space when he wed a fellow crew member, Jan Davis, before their
launching.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was among 13 astronauts assigned to early station
construction missions in August 1998. At the time, the flight
commanded by former chief astronaut Ken Cockrell was to lift off
this October.
</P>
<P>
   However, Russian financial difficulties that have delayed the
launching of the station's crew module and more recently the
electrical wiring flaws that have forced a suspension of U.S.
shuttle flights have prompted rescheduling.
</P>
<P>
   Though as a rule NASA does not assign backup flight personnel,
the need for astronaut replacements has been limited primarily to
rare instances when a crewman died during training or was
confronted with an urgent family matter.
</P>
<P>
   However, in 1990 the space agency temporarily grounded a pair of
veteran shuttle commanders for flight safety infractions. Later,
both men resumed their space flight duties.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
