<HEADER>
A4963 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-PREVIEW-NEWSEASO     09-08 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PREVIEW-NEWSEASON-$ADV12-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Nov. 5. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `AMERICAN MOVIE'
</P>
<P>
   The documentary, acclaimed at Sundance, follows Mark Borchardt,
an intrepidly confident Wisconsin filmmaker, family and hangers-on
as he scrapes together enough money to make a grade-C horror movie.
Its real-life characters, like the director's octogenarian uncle,
couldn't have been invented. Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   `MANSFIELD PARK'
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian director Patricia Rozema's austere film adaptation
of the Jane Austen novel incorporated Austen's journals and letters
into its screenplay. No fluffy Merchant-Ivory-style romanticizing
of the past here. With few exceptions, these 19th-century Brits are
a hard-bitten bunch of money-grubbing imperialist Puritans. Frances
O'Connor is the fiercely independent heroine, Fanny Price, who
flouts convention. Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   `LAST NIGHT'
</P>
<P>
   The end of the world is at hand, and everyone has a different
idea of how to spend the final hours. Don McKellar, who wrote
``Thirty-Two Short Films About Glenn Gould'' and ``The Red
Violin,'' directed the serious romantic comedy starring himself,
Sandra Oh, Callum Keith Rennie, Sarah Polley, David Cronenberg and
Genevieve Bujold. Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   `THAT'S THE WAY I LIKE IT'
</P>
<P>
   A young man with a dead-end job and a mania for Bruce Lee films
enters a disco competition and finds his life changing
dramatically. Set in the 1970s in Singapore. With Adrian Pang and
Madeline Tan. Early November.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: RECENT FILMS
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Modern Art's survey includes roughly a dozen films
introducing a new generation of filmmakers working in both features
and documentaries. Nov. 5-14.
</P>
<P>
   `LIGHT IT UP'
</P>
<P>
   A group of students takes a wounded high school security guard
(Forest Whitaker) hostage when their favorite teacher (Judd Nelson)
is fired. With Usher Raymond, Sara Gilbert and Rosario Dawson. Nov.
5.
</P>
<P>
   `TRAIN OF LIFE'
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of ``Life Is Beautiful'' comes another Holocaust
comedy, this one written and directed by Radu Mihaileanu, a
French-Romanian. When the news arrives that the Nazis are coming, a
village buys a fake deportation train and creates fake Nazi
uniforms for those citizens assigned to pose as German soldiers.
Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   `COTTON MARY'
</P>
<P>
   Set in post-independence India, Ismael Merchant's film uses the
conflicts surrounding a woman's newborn daughter to examine the
complicated, painful relationships between British colonials and
Anglo-Indians. With Greta Scacchi and Madhur Jaffrey. Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   `ROSETTA'
</P>
<P>
   Luc and Jean-Pierre Dardenne, the Belgian filmmaking brothers
responsible for ``La Promesse,'' won top honors at Cannes for the
bleak story of a 17-year-old girl who struggles to keep a menial
job. Selected for the New York Film Festival. Nov. 10.
</P>
<P>
   `THE BACHELOR'
</P>
<P>
   In this remake of the Buster Keaton silent classic ``Seven
Chances,'' Chris O'Donnell discovers he has 24 hours to find a
bride if he is to inherit a $100 million fortune. With Renee
Zellweger and cameos by Brooke Shields and Mariah Carey. Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   `FELICIA'S JOURNEY'
</P>
<P>
   The director Atom Egoyan's followup to his masterpiece ``The
Sweet Hereafter'' is based on a novel by William Trevor. A pregnant
Irish teen-ager (Elaine Cassidy) searching for her lover travels to
England, where she becomes involved with a caterer (Bob Hoskins)
who is also a serial killer. The closing night selection of the New
York Film Festival. Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   `THREE TO TANGO'
</P>
<P>
   In the romantic comedy, a jealous Chicago tycoon (Dylan
McDermott) assigns his friend (Matthew Perry), whom he wrongly
assumes to be gay, the job of spying on his possibly unfaithful
mistress (Neve Campbell). Sparks fly. Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   `PLAY IT TO THE BONE'
</P>
<P>
   Ron Shelton (``Bull Durham'') wrote and directed the story of
two fading boxers (Antonio Banderas and Woody Harrelson) and close
friends who are pressured into fighting each other in Las Vegas.
Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   `POKEMON: THE FIRST MOVIE'
</P>
<P>
   The popular Japanese television series and video game about
pocket monsters comes to the big screen. Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   `42 UP'
</P>
<P>
   The latest installment of Michael Apted's extraordinary
documentary series in which every seven years he examines the lives
of 14 British children he originally profiled in 1964. Nov. 17.
</P>
<P>
   `ALL ABOUT MY MOTHER'
</P>
<P>
   The great Spanish director Pedro Almodovar makes a huge leap
forward with the tragicomedy about a single mother (Cecilia Roth),
whose beloved 17-year-old son dies in a car accident. Leaving
Madrid, she returns to Barcelona, the city of her youth, to search
for the boy's father who abandoned her when she was pregnant and
then changed his name from Esteban to Lola. The opening night
selection of the New York Film Festival. Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   `SLEEPY HOLLOW'
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Depp is Ichabod Crane, the strait-laced New York City
constable who investigates a series of beheadings in an upstate New
York village in Tim Burton's fanciful adaptation of Washington
Irving's 18th-century tale. Christina Ricci is a damsel in
distress. Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   `THE WORLD IS NOT ENOUGH'
</P>
<P>
   In Pierce Brosnan's third outing as Agent 007 (and the 19th film
of the series), James Bond battles a Bosnian madman (Robert
Carlyle) who wants to control the world's oil supply. Michael Apted
directed. With Denise Richards, Sophie Marceau and Judi Dench. Nov.
19.
</P>
<P>
   `TUMBLEWEEDS'
</P>
<P>
   A single mother (the British actress Janet McTeer) from the
working-class South, fleeing a disintegrating relationship, hits
the road with her 12-year-old daughter (Kimberly Brown) and they
wind up in San Diego. Adapted by Gavin O'Connor from Angela
Shelton's childhood memoirs. Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   `ANNA AND THE KING'
</P>
<P>
   Jodie Foster is Anna Leonowens, the 19th-century British tutor
to the children of the King of Siam (Chow Yun-Fat) in the movie
directed by Andy Tennant and filmed in Malaysia. Adapted from the
same material that inspired ``The King and I,'' expect lavish
spectacle. Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
