<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4964 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-PREVIEW-$ADV12-5     09-08 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PREVIEW-$ADV12-5THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Nov. 24.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `TOY STORY 2'
</P>
<P>
   The sequel to the 1995 animated blockbuster is about as surefire
a hit as a movie can be. This time, Woody the cowboy doll is
kidnapped and rescued by his fellow toys in a mission organized by
Buzz Lightyear. Among the voices are Tom Hanks (Woody), Tim Allen
(Buzz), Kelsey Grammer, Don Rickles and Joan Cusack. Directed by
John Lasseter, with Ash Brannon and Lee Unkrich. Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   `RIDE WITH THE DEVIL'
</P>
<P>
   Ang Lee's first movie since ``The Ice Storm'' is a Civil War
drama set on the Kansas-Missouri border and details the deadly
skirmishes between abolitionists and Confederates. With Tobey
Mcguire, Skeet Ulrich, and Jewel (in her movie debut). Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   `END OF DAYS'
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Schwarzenegger is a recovering alcoholic ex-cop who saves
the world when Satan (Gabriel Byrne) appears with plans to
impregnate a woman (Robin Tunney) and produce the Antichrist just
in time for the millennium. Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   `FLAWLESS'
</P>
<P>
   An ex-New York security guard (Robert De Niro) recovering from a
stroke engages a drag performer (Philip Seymour Hoffman) for speech
therapy in the form of singing lessons. A change of pace for Joel
Schumacher, who has overseen the last two ``Batman'' movies. Nov.
24.
</P>
<P>
   `ANGELA'S ASHES'
</P>
<P>
   Alan Parker (``Evita'') directed the screen adaptation of Frank
McCourt's best-selling memoir about an impoverished Irish family
with an alcoholic father (Robert Carlyle) and depressed mother
(Emily Watson). Three young actors portray the author at different
ages. Much-loved books don't necessarily make great movies, but
this one at least has the advantage of brilliant actors in the lead
roles. Nov. 26.
</P>
<P>
   `LIBERTY HEIGHTS'
</P>
<P>
   The director Barry Levinson returns to his native Baltimore for
the fourth time in this semi-autobiographical mid-1950s coming of
age story centered on a local restaurant. ``Diner'' redux? With Joe
Mantegna, Bebe Neuwirth, Adrien Brody and Justin Chambers. Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   `DOGMA'
</P>
<P>
   Religious controversy (and a showing at the New York Film
Festival) precede the release of the serious comedy by Kevin Smith
(``Clerks,'' ``Chasing Amy''), which reunites Ben Affleck and Matt
Damon as two rebellious angels and includes Linda Fiorentino as a
savior who works in an abortion clinic. Alanis Morissette plays
God. With Chris Rock, Salma Hayek and George Carlin. Nov.
</P>
<P>
   `WISCONSIN DEATH TRIP'
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Michael Lesy's 1973 pictorial history of the same
name, ``Wisconsin Death Trip,'' the film uses archival photos,
newspaper articles and hospital records to recreate life in 1890s
Black River Falls, Wis. The bizarre behavior of the people in this
Protestant community of merchants and farmers makes today's tabloid
headlines seem tame. Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   `THE END OF THE AFFAIR'
</P>
<P>
   The second screen adaptation of the 1951 Graham Greene novel of
jealousy, romantic obsession and memory (Deborah Kerr starred in a
weak 1955 movie version) was directed by Neil Jordan and features
Julianne Moore, Ralph Fiennes and Stephen Rea. Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   `DEUCE'
</P>
<P>
   The comedy finds the ``Saturday Night Live'' veteran Rob
Schneider working as a male escort. Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   `AGNES BROWNE'
</P>
<P>
   An Irish widow (Anjelica Huston) struggles to bring up seven
children in 1967 Dublin. Ms. Huston also directed the film based on
Brendan O'Carroll's 1999 novel ``The Mammy.'' Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   `SWEET AND LOWDOWN'
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen's latest, set in 1930s New York, stars Sean Penn as
a jazz guitarist. With Uma Thurman and Samantha Morton. Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   `MAGNOLIA'
</P>
<P>
   Many characters crisscross in a Robert Altman-like tragicomic
patchwork of intersecting lives set in the San Fernando Valley.
William H. Macy, Julianne Moore, Philip Baker Hall, John C. Reilly,
Jason Robards, Felicity Huffman and Tom Cruise (briefly) appear in
Paul Thomas Anderson's first film since ``Boogie Nights.'' Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   `CRADLE WILL ROCK'
</P>
<P>
   The 1937 populist left-wing opera ``The Cradle Will Rock''
created quite a stir during a time of labor unrest and a burgeoning
cultural revolution. Tim Robbins' movie, which features Susan
Sarandon, Vanessa Redgrave, Emily Watson, Hank Azaria, John Cusack,
Joan Cusack, Bill Murray and John Turturro, remembers the show and
the furor surrounding it. Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   `THE WAR ZONE'
</P>
<P>
   The actor Tim Roth's directorial debut stars Ray Winstone and
Tilda Swinton in a story of family upheaval and a dark secret
revealed after they move from London to the windswept cliffs of
Devon. Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   `THE CIDER HOUSE RULES'
</P>
<P>
   Lasse Hallstrom's screen version of John Irving's historical
novel (with a script by the author) stars Tobey Maguire as the
runaway orphan, Homer Wells; Michael Caine as the abortionist Dr.
Wilbur Larch, and Paul Rudd and Charlize Theron as the soldier and
his pregnant girlfriend who befriend Homer. Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   `STUART LITTLE'
</P>
<P>
   E.B. White's beloved mouse has been animatronically brought to
the screen in a live-action realization of the classic children's
book. With Geena Davis, Hugh Laurie and Jonathan Lipnicki and the
voices of Michael J. Fox, Gene Wilder, Jennifer Tilly, Steve Zahn
and Chazz Palminteri. Directed by Rob Minkoff. Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   `GALAXY QUEST'
</P>
<P>
   Tim Allen and Sigourney Weaver are stars of a defunct '70s
sci-fi series who find themselves mistaken for actual space
gladiators by real-life extraterrestrials. A comedy directed by
Dean Parisot. Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   `SCREAM 3'
</P>
<P>
   The horror franchise rolls on, with Wes Craven supervising. Neve
Campbell, Courteney Cox, David Arquette and Parker Posey star. Dec.
10.
</P>
<P>
   `THE GREEN MILE'
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hanks stars in the film adaptation by Frank Darabont (``The
Shawshank Redemption'') of Stephen King's 1996 serialized novel. In
a heavy-duty drama set in the South in the 1930s, Hanks plays a
death row prison guard and Michael Clarke Duncan a gentle, hulking
7-foot black prisoner (with mystical powers) convicted for
murdering two white girls. Dec. 17.
</P>
<P>
   `BICENTENNIAL MAN'
</P>
<P>
   The comedy, which stars Robin Williams as a robot who turns
human, re-teams the star with Chris Columbus, who directed him in
``Mrs. Doubtfire.'' Based on a short story by Isaac Asimov. Dec.
17.
</P>
<P>
   `GIRL, INTERRUPTED'
</P>
<P>
   James Mangold (``Cop Land'') directed the screen adaptation of
Susanna Kaysen's memoir of her enforced stay in a mental hospital.
With Winona Ryder and Angelina Jolie. Dec. 21.
</P>
<P>
   `THE NINTH GATE'
</P>
<P>
   Roman Polanski, one of the all-time masters of screen
creepiness, directed Johnny Depp in the thriller about a rare-book
dealer hired by a scholar of demonology (Frank Langella) to find a
legendary manual that reveals how to contact Satan. Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
