<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release THURSDAY AMs, September 9, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton declared last
year in Rwanda the United States would never accept mass killing
again. Now the Rwanda speech echoes as the president and his
advisers put pressure on Indonesia to stop the violence in East
Timor. By John Donnelly. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY (Crystal City, Mo.) _ As Bill Bradley formally
announces his campaign, he faces many perils in his longshot
effort. What he thinks and what he would do as president. By Bob
Hohler. 950 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-RATES (Undated) _ The Bank of England raises interest
rates in the United Kingdom, as the maverick nation that bowed out
of a unified Europe isolated itself further in setting a stiff
course for its monetary policy. By Kimberly Blanton. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS-PARCELLS (Hempstead, N.Y.) _ All this babble about Tuna
Bowls and one-upmanship and poetic justice. That's somebody else's
game. Bill Parcells isn't playing. By Bob Duffy. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-USOPEN (New York) _ By Allen Lessels.
</P>
<P>
   w/
