<HEADLINE>
`DELTA JEWS': SOME SPECIAL SOUTHERNERS, CHOSEN AND UNCHOSEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss.)  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(bl) 
 By ANITA GATES  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bettye Sue Kline remembers going to Methodist Youth Fellowship
and Vacation Bible School as a child. ``I could sing `Yes, Jesus
Loves Me' with the best of them,'' she says. Ben Lamensdorf stands
in his cotton fields, weathered face under a baseball cap, and says
in a soft Southern accent: ``People are surprised that you're
Jewish and a farmer. But we were farming a long time ago. In
Israel.'' Leanne Silverblatt affectionately calls her husband,
Alan, ``a good ol' Mississippi Delta Jewish redneck.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the voices of ``Delta Jews,'' an intelligent,
reflective one-hour documentary on PBS on Thursday night. The film
was written, directed and produced by Mike DeWitt in Ken Burns
style: talking heads from the present, photographs from the past,
shots of sweeping land or empty streets when there are no
photographs and evocative music that comment on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta Jews'' is not as inspired as Burns' work; at times it's
even a little ragged around the edges. But it covers its subject
nicely and with balance. The playwright Alfred Uhry, best known for
``Driving Miss Daisy,'' is the narrator.
</P>
<P>
   The point that DeWitt makes is that, yes, there are Jews in the
South, even in the rural South, even in the Mississippi Delta,
which runs from Memphis to Vicksburg and has been called, as the
voice-over declares, ``the most Southern place on earth.'' And this
is their story.
</P>
<P>
   David Orlansky of Greenville, Miss., tells about an ancestor
who, not knowing a word of English, ``managed to get from Eastern
Europe to Ruleville, Miss.,'' with the help of a tag around his
neck with the address that was his destination.
</P>
<P>
   Many immigrants, as ``Delta Jews'' shows, began as peddlers and
ended up as merchants with general stores. They operated
essentially on credit, which was a necessity for farmers. Today
storefronts with names like E. Weinberg, Fried's and Kline still
line the streets of small Mississippi towns, and their owners may
be heading for the Delta Jewish Open, an annual golf tournament now
in its eighth year.
</P>
<P>
   Acceptance within the white Christian (mostly Protestant)
Southern culture is still a matter of opinion. Earl Solomon Jr. of
Greenville says, ``I believe I've been discriminated more in my
lifetime, in my experiences, because I'm from the South than
because I'm Jewish.'' Others talk of having the feeling that they
didn't quite belong.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the film, Clifton Taulbert, an author who is black,
says of the Jews in his hometown, ``They may have thought they were
white, but we never did.'' Which brings us, and ``Delta Jews,'' to
the civil rights years. ``It was like a moment of truth,'' says
Jerry Himelstein, who grew up in Greenwood, Miss. ``Which side were
you on?''
</P>
<P>
   One opinion expressed in the film is that Jewish Southerners,
because they or their relatives had suffered oppression, tended to
have more sympathy for the plight of blacks. But almost 40 years
later, others express strong opinions on camera about white
Northern Jewish civil rights workers who came South: ``They were
crude; they were loud.'' ``They had no business down here.''
</P>
<P>
   These comments, of course, seem to come from the Southern side
of the speakers' identities, rather than the Jewish side. ``It's
all mixed up and intertwined together,'' says Ms. Silverblatt of
Indianola, Miss. ``We  &UR; are &LR;  Jewish, but we're Southern. Sometimes
we feel more comfortable with Southern Christians than with Jews
from another part of the country. And yet we have a very strong
sense of Jewishness.''
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining that sense of Jewish identity and passing it along
to the next generation appears to require real effort. Paul
Kossmen, single father of three sons in Cleveland, Miss., says: ``I
just kind of feel like it might be a bit easier in the big cities.
I think my children would have the benefit of numbers. Here they
are so few.''
</P>
<P>
   So few that the only tombstone carver in the area who does
Hebrew letters has decided to go ahead and carve his own stone. He
figures when he's gone, there won't be anybody else to do it.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DELTA JEWS'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Thursday night
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 10)
</P>
<P>
   Produced, written and directed by Mike DeWitt; Mary Perica,
editor and associate producer; Stuart Math, director of
photography. Alfred Uhry, narrator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
