<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4975 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV16-     09-08 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV16-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SESAME STREET'S SUSAN SAYS BURY LEARNING IN FUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for fix release date)   (For release Thursday, Sept. 16)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Are you one of my children?'' asked Dr. Loretta Long, in the
beginning of our interview. Yes, I admitted, I was.
</P>
<P>
   One of the millions who grew up watching Elmo, Cookie Monster
and the Grouch. Who sang along when asked, ``Will you tell me how
to get, how to get to Sesame Street?''
</P>
<P>
   I was 6 when Big Bird first walked out of the house, in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Long, also known as ``Susan,'' has been a regular on the
Children's Television Workshop's most acclaimed show for more than
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Sesame Street has long understood what every parent finds out:
</P>
<P>
   ``You're better off burying the education deep down under the
fun so children just think they're playing,'' says Long, who is
also a parent educator and teacher. ``If the kids aren't having
fun, they aren't going to do it. It's the same thing with us. If
the kids turn the channel, it doesn't matter how wonderful the show
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Long is a spokeswoman for Vtech's line of electronic ``smart''
toys that talk, light up and play music. She loves these
razzle-dazzle toys, especially the portable ones that have several
activities to keep traveling toddlers entertained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't they great?'' she says. ``When a child has his own
little backpack filled with stuff, that's a child who's not going
to be screaming from Newark to L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, today's kids are more sophisticated as to what they
expect from toys.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Long says, ``I grew up on a farm and was a real tomboy. I
believe in balance. All these years I spent on television, I would
never tell a parent to use TV as a baby sitter, anymore than video
games or high-tech toys replace walks or trips to the playground.''
</P>
<P>
   Team sports are great for older children, Long says, since they
crave camaraderie and an outlet for their boundless energy.
</P>
<P>
   Long has learned from her six nieces and nephews that a bored
child is a noisy, fidgety child.
</P>
<P>
   She suggests having a special car toy that children can play
with only after they're seated safely in their car seats or while
waiting in a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   And while Long likes toys that educate and challenge, she
believes parents can make a mistake in buying toys that are
designed for older children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be sure to pay attention to the age-appropriateness of the
toy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She sees computers in children's lives as both a great learning
tool and a real danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't let a kid of mine isolate themselves and talk on
the computer: They're living a parallel life in your own house,''
she said. ``You've got to wake up and pay attention to what your
kids are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to Long's two main rules for parents:
</P>
<P>
   1. Be encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   2. Be involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking of moving `Be involved' up to No. 1,'' she says.
``It's inconceivable to me that anything could have gone on in my
mother's house without her knowing. We used to call her the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a feature writer for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers feature writer.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
