<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-WEB-HOME-FURNISHINGS-     09-08 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-HOME-FURNISHINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME FURNISHINGS, MODERN AND ANTIQUE, FROM THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., S.C., Minn., Texas, Mass., Mich., Calif., The
Netherlands, Belgium)  (See also ECOMMERCE) 
(DW) 
 By TIMOTHY JACK WARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Touchy-feely, persnickety and an Internet novice _ it would take
a lot of handholding to get me to buy a sofa without first
karate-chopping the pillows.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm at least tempted. In the last four weeks, I sampled
about 80 home-furnishings sites, from Fred Friar's front-porch
location to Homepoint.com, a megasite with the virtual heft of a
Spiegel catalog.
</P>
<P>
   To find furniture e-tailers, I usually started with the
www.37.com search engine. I spoke with consumers who had shopped at
many of the sites and questioned the sales staff as if I were a
potential buyer. Generally, they were well informed, personable and
low-key. There was no pressure to buy; in fact, many collegially
shared information about other sites.
</P>
<P>
   At night on a home computer, surfing can be slow as molasses,
and frustrating. One tip: Do something else while shopping.
</P>
<P>
   There are half a dozen or so big players _ including
Homepoint.com and Living.com. Personally, I found these new
megasites overwhelming: they test the bounds of how much is too
much. Mike West, the founder of Homepoint.com in Greenville, S.C.,
says his company offers ``anything and everything from America's
3,700 furniture manufacturers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For our customers, quality is not a driving force,'' he said.
``We offer a tremendous selection and choice for customers who are
concerned with `Will it fit in my home?'''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a guide to some of the better sites:
</P>
<P>
   blindambition.com A leading site among the competitive miniblind
suppliers on the Web; plug in window dimensions, and order wooden
Venetian blinds, delivered in days at low prices (30 by 60 inches,
$88). Almost everything is in stock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   bludot.com Hip storage from a small furniture design cooperative
in Minnesota. Text can be too cute (``sawing logs'' for a maple
bed). But see Modulicious, the site's mix-and-match modular system
made of maple veneer and painted steel, well priced at $399 to
$899. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   dwr.com Design Within Reach is a professional-looking, fast,
concise site with modern classic pieces for home and office. Offers
a huge inventory and quick delivery. Prices appear to be fair,
often lower than in a Manhattan store; there are discounts for
large orders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.eckhart.nl
</P>
<P>
   This Rotterdam site offers a huge inventory from European
furniture manufacturers. The problem is getting prices for some of
the pieces. Try calling 011-31-10-414-1616 during business hours in
the Netherlands. There is warm customer service in English. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.fiftie-fiftie.be A Belgian dealer in vintage furniture,
objects and rare books. The site is in English, the prices in euros
(about one to a dollar) or in Belgian francs (100 of them equals
about $262). American collectors are heading here for the selection
of midcentury furniture and objects from Europe and Japan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   formdecor.com This Los Angeles dealer of vintage furniture is
favored by production designers and foreign collectors; a site for
high-end collectibles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   f-u-p.com A site based in Portland, Ore., with modernist
classics; prices and shipping fees are high, but the look of the
page is fashionable, and the product mix is intelligent.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   georgesmith.com Very fine handmade English sofas and chairs from
the company's New York and Los Angeles showrooms, offered at 40 to
50 percent off; smart sales help. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   hmhome.com A beautiful, efficient site, from the 75-year-old
Herman Miller company, offers a professional room planner.
Consumers can buy directly from the factory here, with a discount
on seating and home-office products (but not classic designs by
Charles and Ray Eames, George Nelson and Isamu Noguchi). Some
quick-ship items (click I Want It ) include the Aeron ergonomic
office chair, $749 fully loaded, which undercuts some dealers'
prices. The Web site's customer-service phone lines close at 5 p.m.
Eastern time. The phone number is (888) 520-7646. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.industrial-home.com A homespun site that offers
one-of-a-kind modern furniture and accessories for collectors. See
the vintage 1960 Viscontea lamp by Achille Castiglioni for Flos,
$650.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   marthastewart.com Martha Stewart's Wweb site is appropriately
pastel-colored.
</P>
<P>
   noguchi.org An intelligent blockbuster and a real find: the
Isamu Noguchi Foundation Web site is soft-sell, and the best source
for the designer's Akari paper lamps _ you get thumbnails of all
the styles, but you then have to call or send an e-mail for prices.
Sales benefit the foundation and its museum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   simplymodern.com A small, speedy site for desks, accessories and
objects straight out of ``The Jetsons.'' There's a nice Finnish
plywood trash can for $42.
</P>
<P>
   www.shakerworkshops.com A source long favored by European
collectors, this Massachusetts maker of authentic Shaker
furnishings has a site that offers settees, chairs, tables,
dressers and beds, in kits or assembled. Skip the bric-a-brac and
the Shaker recipe of the month, and move on to furniture.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   store.moma.org The Museum of Modern Art's collection is in many
ways the definition of modern design, but the site can be
surprisingly slow. &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.unicahome.com At this site, operated by a Birmingham, Mich.,
store, you will find Philippe Starck office supplies, Droog laundry
baskets and a $250 coat rack from Christophe Pillet. Verner
Panton's Phantom chair is $250 at this site, which has nice links
to other design sites.
</P>
<P>
   widerview.com A reputable, site for country and traditional
styles, antler chandeliers, matelasse bedcovers, fair prices and
warm, knowledgeable service. Urbane shoppers will have to dig a
little to find the pearls: go to Urban Scapes, then to Take a Seat
and to Mike Room Service. Keep clicking to view the collection of
upholstered furniture. The best dining tables I've found for under
$700 are at this site. You will find European farmhouse tables of
recycled wax-finished pine; shipping is not free, but there is a
$150 cap.
</P>
<P>
   www.ziahouse.com A crisp, punchy Web site from a tiny Berkeley,
Calif., store that has a tightly edited collection of modern
furnishings. On the home page, click on Products. Objects here tend
toward a ``crafty'' look, but there are plump sofas covered with
colorful Tricia Guild fabrics, hard-to-find Santora Melone storage
cabinets and a $1,000 Peter Sandback coffee table. There is no way
to order except by calling the store's number, prominently
displayed on every page.
</P>
<P>
   MEGARETAILERS www.furniture.com In July alone, 600,000 different
visitors clicked on this huge site, according to Media Metrix.
Based in Framingham, Mass., the site offers middle-of-the-road
contemporary furniture &UR;  &LR; and a room-planner tool. There's an online
magazine with a story called ``When His Meets Hers,'' a smart idea,
since Web sales are are almost evenly split between men and women.
</P>
<P>
   www.goodhome.com  &UR;  &LR; A cooperative venture from Hearst, Mattel,
Broderbund and the Thomas H. Lee Co. (which built the Snapple
brand), www.goodhome.com is expected to announce Thursday that it
is merging with another ``not yet running'' Web site,
www.nhabit.com to form a mega-megasite called Goodhome. With $50
million in start-up money, the site, based in San Rafael, Calif.,
will go live on Sept. 21, and will offer 50 room scenes. ``Every
item of the room works together and is for purchase, including the
fresh flowers,'' said Douglas Mack, the chief executive of
Goodhome.
</P>
<P>
   www.homepoint.com The mother ship of mass marketers, it has
crisp, hyperactive pages. Featured recently was Fire-N-Ice, a $52
gooseneck desk lamp, but the site also sells chairs, beds, tables,
you name it. Almost everything takes four to six weeks for
delivery. There is usually no charge for shipping.
</P>
<P>
   www.living.com Can be slow to download, but there are 299 lamps,
213 sofas &UR;  &LR; and lots more, from manufacturers like Natuzzi and Lane.
Furniture from the site, which is based in Austin, Tex., may take
from six to 12 weeks for delivery, and any purchase above $300
requires a 33 percent deposit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
