<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH VOWS TO `REBUILD' ARMED FORCES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDHAM, N.H. _ Republican presidential candidate George W.
Bush, in a preview of another major policy address next week, said
Wednesday he would rebuild and revitalize the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Republican candidates, Bush's remarks suggested he
believed the U.S. military has deteriorated during the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush plans to deliver a major address on military and defense
policy next week in Charleston, S.C., aides said. But he gave his
New Hampshire audience a preview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to about 500 people at a chamber of commerce
breakfast in Windham, Bush said he intends to ``revitalize'' and
``rebuild'' America's armed forces and assure that they are
``well-paid, well-housed and well-trained.'' As he has before, he
advocated the development of a new system of ``theater-based,
intermediate-range'' anti-ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   He also vowed, ``I will never, ever commit U.S. forces to United
Nations control.``
</P>
<P>
   He said while an international peacekeeping force may be
necessary to quell the violence in East Timor, the Indonesian
province that is seeking independence, the peacekeepers should not
include U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor said the biggest, long-term foreign threat to
the United States is China. He said the United States should
continue to trade with China and open up new markets there for U.S.
products.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``I know the next president must deal strongly
with China.``
</P>
<P>
   He said the next president must convince China to respect
individual freedoms and not to distribute weapons around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must look at China as a competitor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he also was concerned about the former Soviet Union,
whose remaining arsenal of nuclear weapons and internal unrest
posed a particularly critical problem. He promised to work to
continue reducing nuclear weapons in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's preliminary discussion of his defense policies should he
win the White House came amid another small flurry about whether
his family connections influenced his admission into a National
Guard unit during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Morning News reported Wednesday that the late Houston
oilman Sidney A. Adger, a Bush family friend, asked Lt. Gov. Ben
Barnes in 1968 to help George W. Bush gain a slot in the National
Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Barnes said he told them that one of his staff
members forwarded Adger's request to Brig. Gen. James Rose, who
died in 1993. Barnes is scheduled to testify in a deposition on the
matter Thursday in a lawsuit related to Texas' lottery contract
with Gtech Corp., for whom Barnes lobbied.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Wednesday that neither he nor his father had sought
help from Adger or anyone else in gaining a National Guard slot for
the future governor. ``Not at all. That's what President Bush said,
and that's what I say,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No George Bush ever asked for anyone to help me,'' Bush said.
``People (should) listen to the commander of the unit that
instructed me as a pilot. He says that there was no special
favoritism. They were looking for pilots, and I was honored to
serve. I became an F-102 pilot and proudly served.``
</P>
<P>
   Asked if people should weigh whether a presidential candidate
avoided going to Vietnam, Bush replied: ``No. I think what's
important now is (whether) a candidate served, and I did. I became
an F-102 pilot, and had my unit been called up, I would have gone
to Vietnam.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
