<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRIDGE-OPERA(TRIMS)-A     09-08 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGE-OPERA(TRIMS)-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOMMODATING CADENCES OF DRAMA, `VIEW FROM THE BRIDGE' NEARS
COMPLETION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By BRUCE WEBER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In the Civic Opera House here, where Lyric Opera of
Chicago will present the world premiere of ``A View From the
Bridge'' on Oct. 9, the singers gathered in a rehearsal room
Tuesday for the first time, singing through the score accompanied
by two pianos. The composer, William Bolcom, was on hand to hear a
young tenor he had never met, Gregory Turay, move the assembled
company to applause with his rendering of a melodic aria. And the
director, Frank Galati, delivered an impassioned lecture on the
history of the Arthur Miller play on which the opera is based
before winding up with a flourish: ``Let us give thanks for the
privilege of working together on this first great opera of the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   So this is how the staging of an opera begins: With bravado and
the power of communal, artistic enterprise, right? Well, not quite.
The staging of an opera, in the end magnificent and grand, begins
before the bravado, with a charade that is almost comic.
</P>
<P>
   The real work of staging began last week in the Civic's
3,600-seat auditorium where a portable tape player sat on a long
table about two-thirds of the way back in the orchestra. From it,
played in fits and starts, came the strains of ``View.'' It sounded
a little pathetic, actually, with the score played on a piano and
all the parts, male and female, earnestly sung by Lyric chorus
master Donald Palumbo, the music rising sadly in the vaulting
heights of the vast, hall and dying long before it hit the rafters.
</P>
<P>
   Because no orchestra had yet played the score, and because the
singers had yet to sing a note, the recording was made to help Mr.
Galati and the production's chief designers with the painstaking
task of creating the physical look of the opera. The single set is
by Santo Loquasto, who also designed the costumes. It's a tiny
apartment surrounded by an industrial landscape suggesting the
shipyards of Red Hook, Brooklyn, in the early 1950s, the opera's
setting. And though it is largely complete, the set needs to be
effectively lighted (by Duane Schuler, the designer) and to work
dramatically in tandem with enormous projections, on three screens,
by projection artist Wendall K. Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   This phase of preparation, known as tech week, places special
emphasis on accommodating and underscoring the shifting cadences of
drama that any theatrical presentation requires. Which is why the
tape-recorded score was both necessary _ in an opera it is the
music that controls the onstage tempo _ and insufficient. Because
``View'' is a new work and has never been recorded with a full
roster of musicians _ the first orchestra rehearsal isn't until
next week _ the designers are working, thus far, without their
complete palette of clues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely hard to work when you can't hear the music
because we're trying to create rhythmic sequences and transitions
and patterns of composition that are related to the score,'' Galati
said. In a fully orchestrated work, Ms. Harrington said, ``the
color is all in the music.'' And Schuler added: ``The cueing is all
in the music, too. When you hear the music, you hear the cues.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was not the only feat of imagination the designers had
to cope with. Onstage, as the tape played, stand-ins for the
singers, known as lightwalkers, served as human design elements.
Opera fans who volunteer for the task, which offers minimal pay,
they spent hours walking through a kind of slow-motion
choreography, responding to Galati's suggestions as he began to
envision what the set would look like with performers on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob, would you be so kind as to move upstage,'' Galati said,
at one point, through a microphone from the table in the orchestra,
and the beefy, middle-aged man who was standing in for Catherine,
the opera's 17-year-old virgin ingenue, did so.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a perfect system; Galati complained, with a laugh, that
one fat guy had to pretend to be 24 female chorus members. But this
is how many operas coalesce, in a process that would seem to defy
logic. The main reason is that Lyric, like other large companies
including New York's Metropolitan Opera and the San Francisco
Opera, works in repertory and must prepare and rehearse several
shows at once. Unlike a Broadway show, which has the luxury of
commandeering a theater and can thus bring together cast and crew
for weeks of rehearsals and previews, an opera in repertory must
share the spotlight, not to mention the stage and rehearsal room.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, much of the fundamental work is done long in
advance. Each summer Lyric techs its entire season; for 1999-2000,
there are eight operas, including ``Tristan und Isolde,'' which
won't be performed until next year but finished teching more than a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird to be sitting here in July working on a show you're
not going to see again until February,'' said Lyric technical
director Drew Landmesser, who is responsible for coordinating all
the variables of staging and oversees a staff that can reach nearly
100 in complicated times of the year.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One moment, he recalled, emphasized the eccentricity of it all;
a lightwalker, a middle-aged woman standing in for Isolde, began to
feel weak after standing onstage for hours. When she took a break
to sit down, she was replaced by a stagehand, only to stand up and
cry out, ``in a very theatrical voice,'' Landmesser said: ``I must
go back! They need my Isolde!''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``View,'' the second production of Lyric's season, was the next
to last to be teched. Loquasto's set was removed from the stage
Friday and part of it was reinstalled in a rehearsal room for the
singers' arrival Tuesday. Meanwhile the set of Lyric's opening
production, Verdi's ``Falstaff,'' was erected on the stage. Its
first staged rehearsals and teching are this week, for an opening
Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   When ``View'' opens, ``Falstaff'' will still have a handful of
performances before its run is complete. By that time, the season's
third production, Handel's ``Alcina,'' will be rehearsing, and
before ``View'' closes in November, a fourth opera, Verdi's
``Macbeth,'' will be clamoring for stage time as well.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The first onstage rehearsal of `Falstaff,' a huge moment in
the life of a production, happens at the exact same moment as the
first offstage rehearsal of a world premiere,'' Landmesser said.
``Sometimes you feel like you're leading a double life, married and
with two or three mistresses.''
</P>
<P>
   The process is obviously complicated when a work has never been
heard or staged before. For the designers of ``View,'' much of the
work involved Ms. Harrington's projections, the presence of which
were first suggested to Galati by Loquasto because the life of the
Carbone family, at the center of Miller's play, ended up aswim in
the judgments of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this play, this material, was perfect for
projections,'' Loquasto said. ``It wants things to be happening
around a space that is completely static.''
</P>
<P>
   The screens are so enormous that they each require two
projectors. Two on a back wall are 35 feet high and 40 to 45 feet
across, and one, a trapezoid angled across the stage, is 32 feet
high and 28 feet across on top and 20 feet across at the bottom.
(They cost $20,000 apiece, a huge chunk of Landmesser's
half-million dollar budget, which also includes about $100,000 for
Loquasto's costumes.)
</P>
<P>
   The images to be shown on them consist of both archival photos
and newly created images. A mixture of giant cityscapes and
oversize urban details _ both exteriors, like close-ups of
apartment facades photographed at vertiginous angles and interiors
like hallways and kitchen corners _ they are meant, in aggregate,
to suggest a small world of crowded apartment living and an
enclosed neighborhood dwarfed by a mammoth city.
</P>
<P>
   As the tech rehearsals proceeded, the photos were matched to
scenes, the timing of changes and scrolls adjusted. Several images
were discarded; a decision was made to add a dark scrim in front of
the two screens that are on the back wall of the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to make about 30 more slides and that's something I
couldn't have known until I saw how it all spooled out,'' Ms.
Harrington said. ``A lot of the landscapes that we had built don't
seem appropriate now. We'll be making things darker, more night,
making things slightly more scary. That's a melodramatic step
that's hard to take initially.''
</P>
<P>
   A key element of the set is the angled screen, which serves as
the roof of the apartment and creates a dramatic and unsettling
visual line on the stage. It may be more effective as a simple
design element than as a screen; unlike those on the back wall,
this screen is actually a scrim, somewhat transparent, and during
tech week, it was evident that it was not holding the projected
images clearly.
</P>
<P>
   The projector sits above it, above the proscenium arch, pointing
upward at a plastic reflecting surface, which turns the image
downward onto the screen. Some improvement in the image resulted
when the plastic was replaced by glass, but there is a safety issue
in suspending a heavy glass mirror above the stage, and the
production will have to go back to plastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tilt screen has a complicated psychological effect on the
space and the story, even though it's not yet always alive,''
Galati said. ``There's something about the slice and the lean, an
action in it. It's kinetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harrington and Loquasto said they hoped the clarity of the
images could be improved by changing the images. But in any case,
both said it was a minor imperfection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the way it dims the center of the stage,'' Ms.
Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   Schuler likes it, too. He designed the palette with darkness in
mind, and though many of the exact cues for the show will have to
wait until a full staging rehearsal not long before the opening, he
was pleased that the palette was apt.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is take the model and plan and this week hope I
get the angles and all that figured out,'' he said. ``Then you have
to be able to react quickly to the way things are going when we get
started. I have to pick all the colors and that worked well. It was
the right palette: a lot of sepia tones, a lot of cool in it, not a
lot of vivid color at all. It's all very muted.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lighting elements changed during tech week. ``We were
talking about some red: red clouds, right?'' Ms. Harrington said.
``But as soon as we saw them, we knew it wasn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuler responded: ``Yes, but you have to bring them to the
theater, because otherwise you never know for sure. That's why this
week is so valuable. You can experiment with everything, and then
go back if you have to.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end all the participants were pleased. There were no
major squabbles; personalities didn't clash. It was a tech week
that accomplished what tech week can.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know, it doesn't matter how well we get along or how
well we do our jobs,'' Ms. Harrington said last week, looking ahead
to this one. ``Bill Bolcom is not taking the phone call that says:
`You know, honey, that number in the second act? The one that's a
little dreary? Well, right about now we could use something peppy.'
That's a conversation that's not going to take place, and this
thing will live or die with the music.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4988 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CD-PIRACY-ART-NYT &LR;      09-08 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CD-PIRACY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 THE PIRATES OF POP MUSIC FILL STREETS WITH $5 CDs  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)(bl) 
 By BRIAN E. ZITTEL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Under the scaffolding on the southwest corner of
Fulton and Nassau Streets in lower Manhattan the other day, a man
at a folding table tried to entice passers-by with what has become
an increasingly common pitch: ``CDs, $5. CDs, $5.'' On the
northwest corner another man offered the same deal. People crowded
around as if someone was giving out free food.
</P>
<P>
   The recordings bore the earmarks of illegally produced copies of
legitimate CDs. Those who buy them said they sound like the real
thing, and in their slick packaging they resemble the CDs for sale
in stores. But the tight-fitting plastic wrappers of the authentic
CDs, along with the pullout sections of art and lyrics, are
missing.
</P>
<P>
   The disks themselves have a slight blue-green tint on the bottom
side, and they list the name of the artist _ often misspelled,
apparently in an attempt to maneuver around copyright laws _ and
the CD in simple block letters rather than in the logos of the
legitimate versions. These nondescript products have become the
latest vehicle for street-level music piracy, replacing cassettes
and costing the music industry tens of millions of dollars. Recent
arrests hint at how quick the profits can be for what in all
likelihood are a growing number of low-cost, computer-based rings
that can operate out of a small basement or living room.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, consumers seem quite happy with the product. ``In a
store, the last CD cost me $14, so this was $5,'' said Alex
Salguero, referring to a CD by hip-hop artist Eminem that he bought
from a sidewalk stand in the Wall Street area. ``For $15, I can buy
three on the street. And it's good quality.''
</P>
<P>
   While the record industry has been concentrating most of its
anti-piracy efforts on music that can be downloaded from the
Internet, advancements in CD technology have opened up this new
front in the piracy war. It is relatively easy to produce multiple
CD copies of high quality for little money.
</P>
<P>
   Cheap graphics software allows some operators to copy album
covers in a way that makes their products look authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Peddlers are taking advantage of the market for pop and hip-hop
music. The common selection on the street includes artists like
Cher, Britney Spears, TLC and the Backstreet Boys. Popular hip-hop
artists like Nas, Jay-Z, Puff Daddy and DMX are available at almost
every stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when we were getting our arms around the mass replication
of counterfeit and pirate cassettes is when we started to see the
evolution of the CD-R and CD plant piracy problem,'' said Frank
Creighton, the director of anti-piracy operations for the Recording
Industry Association of America, in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the Queens district attorney and the Suffolk County
Police announced the arrests of 12 people in connection with a
counterfeit CD ring. Along with cassettes, computers, recording
equipment and dubbing machines, authorities seized 98,000
counterfeit CDs. Officials called it the largest one-time
confiscation of counterfeit CDs in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In making the announcement with the authorities, the Recording
Industry Association of America, representing record companies,
estimated that the Queens and Suffolk ring was taking more than
$100 million a year from legitimate sales.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, three years after CDs were introduced in the United
States, record companies had to decide if it was worth investing
$25 to $30 million to open a factory to manufacture them. Now, for
an investment as low as $180, anyone can walk into a computer store
and buy a small CD copier, called a CD burner, to accompany a
computer. Larger CD burners that can make multiple copies are
available through the Internet for roughly $3,000. The burners,
made by major electronics companies, copy CDs onto blank disks
called CD-recordables or CD-Rs through a digital process that
maintains the quality of the recording. The CD-Rs sell for $1 each
in retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   With this technology available, pirates can set up CD factories
in living rooms. A street-corner peddler in lower Manhattan, who
readily acknowledged that his merchandise was pirated, said one of
his suppliers copies ``thousands and thousands of CDs'' in a tiny
office space packed with CD burners. ``It's like having a room
filled with rack stereo systems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This salesman, in his late 30s, said he works for a middleman
who deals directly with a supplier. The suppliers generally don't
sell CDs themselves, he said, because ``they're too busy burning
CDs.''
</P>
<P>
   Data released in August show that 155,496 pirated CDs had been
seized by law enforcement officials tipped off by the Recording
Industry Association in the first half of 1999, up from 23,858 for
the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen the shift from the counterfeit cassette rings to
the CD-R rings,'' said Creighton of the RIAA.
</P>
<P>
   With cassettes, however, reproduction quality was not very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``There definitely were quality control issues in the cassette
arena that don't exist in the CD arena,'' Creighton said.
</P>
<P>
   In July, authorities in Prince George's County, Md., seized
nearly 59,000 CDs. Police described the action as the end of a
counterfeiting ring that involved illegal videos and CDs that were
produced in New York and shuttled to the Washington area for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The RIAA is developing encrypting technology that it hopes will
curb the production of pirated music by preventing it from being
played on the next generation of audio equipment. But the new
technology may not eliminate the law enforcement difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, peddlers have the appearance of legitimacy because
they often have permits for sidewalk sales of legal goods. In some
spots, the trade is so stable that vendors accept returns or
exchanges from regulars. One customer who works for a private
delivery service pulled up recently to a table on Houston and
Varick Streets in Greenwich Village and handed the CD peddler a
recording by Latino pop artist Manny Manuel, saying it skipped. The
seller readily exchanged it, saying the new one could be returned,
too, if there was a problem. The vendor later said that he was on
the delivery man's route, so it paid to keep him happy.
</P>
<P>
   One customer, who did not want to give her name, talked about a
salesman on Seventh Avenue near her office as if he was the manager
of her supermarket. ``Everybody buys from him,'' she said. ``The
quality is very good. He's reputable and he's honest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
