<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OLDS-POETRY-ART-2TAKE     09-08 1363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDS-POETRY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXAMINING THE CREATIVE MIND OF POET SHARON OLDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Look at this,'' Sharon Olds said while flipping through her
new poetry collection, ``Blood, Tin, Straw,'' to be published next
month by Alfred A. Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so awful,'' she said. ``Omigod, it's all stories. I
just can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I wish I were better,'' Ms. Olds said of her poems, which
chronicle the daily life of a wife and mother not unlike herself.
``Why not just keep a diary?'' she asked, repeating a question from
her critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does this woman think anyone wants to read about her
private life?'' Ms. Olds asked. ``I have a prejudice that narrative
poetry is not as high an art as dense, mysterious, imagistic
poetry.'' But then, she points out, one always admires the things
one can't do oneself.
</P>
<P>
   There is almost no major American poet whose work is as sexually
explicit, and as intimately evocative of a distinct father, husband
and children as Ms. Olds, who is the New York State Poet Laureate
and who won a National Book Critics Circle Award for 1984 for her
collection ``The Dead and the Living.'' The critic Helen Vendler
famously referred to her poems as pornographic. Ms. Olds has
written poems about a son urinating, about a daughter on the brink
of puberty. She is particularly known for her 1992 collection ``The
Father,'' which chronicles in pitiless detail the death of an
abusive, alcoholic father from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   She has also written many poems about making love to a husband.
In her new collection, ``The Spouses Waking Up in the Hotel
Mirror,'' one poem reads:
</P>
<P>
   The man looked like himself, only more so,
</P>
<P>
   his face lucent, his silence deep as if
</P>
<P>
   inevitable, but the woman looked
</P>
<P>
   like a different species from an hour before,
</P>
<P>
   a sandhill crane or a heron, her eyes
</P>
<P>
   skinned back, she looked insane with happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the autobiographical flavor of her work, to
interview Sharon Olds is to play a kind of cat and mouse game. She
has agreed to cooperate, and yet she refuses to discuss her
personal life. She will not discuss her children; she has a son and
a daughter. She will not discuss the ending of her 32-year marriage
to a psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a pain,'' said Mrs. Olds, 56, apologizing when she
refused to say even what her father's occupation was. ``It makes me
seem like such a sensitive person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought anyone would read anything I'd written,'' she
said. ``If I'd known the number of readers I would have, I would
have used a pseudonym.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the privacy is to protect her family, she said.
``I promised I'd keep them out of this.'' She made a vow, she said,
many years ago, not to talk about them: ``Outing them is morally
wicked.'' But in a way, the wall she forms around herself also
enables her to continue to mine domestic life for the material of
her art.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, even though her poems have been called diaries, ``I
don't think of it as personal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not messages in a bottle about me,'' said Ms. Olds.
``No!''
</P>
<P>
   She is often called a confessional poet, in the tradition of
Robert Lowell, Sylvia Plath, and Anne Sexton. Her work has a robust
sensuality, a delight in the physical that is almost Whitmanesque.
She has made the minutiae of a woman's everyday life as valid a
subject for poetry as the grand abstract themes that have
preoccupied other poets.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Olds has also been praised for her technique, her superb
attention to detail, for the pulse of her fast moving verse. ``Her
autobiographical material strikes, shines, deepens, spreads,'' Glyn
Maxwell wrote in The Times Literary Supplement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a boldness in her poetry,'' said the poet Galway
Kinnell, a teaching colleague in the graduate writing program at
New York University. ``She seems to speak where others are
silent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a very direct way she is using herself as subject matter,''
Kinnell said, comparing her to Emily Dickinson, a poet for whom
``inner experience is primary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no attempt to portray the outer world without one's
self in it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Olds is believed to be one of the best-selling literary
poets. She estimates that her collection ``The Dead and the
Living,'' published in 1984, has sold 50,000 copies, an enormous
amount for a serious poet. She is also a dedicated teacher. For the
last 15 years she has run poetry workshops for the severely
disabled at the Goldwater Hospital on Roosevelt Island in New York.
Audiences flock to her readings.
</P>
<P>
   She and Kinnell are known for giving riveting readings,
including one about sex, in which they stood side by side onstage,
reciting bits of poetry in counterpoint. Ms. Olds: ``In the middle
of the night, when we get up/after making love, we look at each
other in/complete friendship, we know so fully/what the other has
been doing.'' Kinnell: ``Now we lie together,/after making love,
quiet, touching along the length of our bodies,/familiar touch of
the long-married.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting for an interview full of feints and indirections
recently in a restaurant in Manhattan, Ms. Olds conceded that she
was born in San Francisco and that her background was ``middle
class.'' She was reared in Berkeley, Calif., in a ``medium-high
Episcopalian'' family, she said, going to church twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hearing about hell and God,'' she said. ``I was bringing
my own poor sick little head to it.'' Consequently, said Ms. Olds,
``I'm haunted by the fear of doing evil.''
</P>
<P>
   With her delicate features free of makeup and her straight, gray
hair, there is a Calvinist look about her.
</P>
<P>
   She refers often in conversation to Satan and God. A few years
ago, she said, she realized that her poetry, which she reads with
four stressed syllables to a line, and which she sees as
conceptually falling into quatrains, was an unconscious imitation
of hymns that she sang as a child. It was a shock, she said. ``I
thought I was writing free verse.'
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Olds was sent east to the Dana Hall School in Wellesley,
Mass. She returned to California for college at Stanford, where she
met Elaine Pagels, future author of ``The Gnostic Gospels,'' who
became a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s she came to New York to Columbia University to get
a doctorate. Her dissertation was on Emerson's prosody. She felt an
affinity with Emerson, she said, because he did not always follow
conventional rules of poetry. ``Emerson couldn't pour what he had
to say into a smooth bottle of iambic pentameter form,'' said Ms.
Olds. ``Rather than being a sloppy and careless prosodist, he was a
forerunner of new forms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I write the same way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not always so. All the time she was studying Emerson
she was trying to write her own poetry. ``I was an artist trying to
be a scholar.'' She was ``stymied,'' trying to imitate the poetry
of Gary Snyder, ``all that white space, the immersion in nature,''
she said. ``Nonnarrative, a lot of times phrases instead of
sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one day, walking down the steps of Low library at Columbia,
she had an epiphany. ``It came to me as a vow to Satan,'' she said.
She would give up everything she had learned, and ``just write my
own stuff.'' Another epiphany occurred when she heard the poet
Muriel Rukeyser read. She was moved by her ``accessibility'' and by
the beauty of her voice, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Only when she began to write about the passionate, messy
experiences of childbirth, mothering and sex, did she find her own
voice. ``Ordinary, understandable poems,'' she said. ``Other
artists may think it's nothing. There is something about wanting to
record what ordinary reality is like.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I started enjambing,'' she said, that is, carrying over
sentences from one line to the next, instead of completing them at
the end of the line, ``giving up end rhymes, and using sentences
with no comma, no period, no dash at the end of the line.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the late '60s Ms. Olds married. She will not even give her
husband's name. ``Such a circumstance is devastating,'' said her
friend, Ms. Pagels, of the breakup of Ms. Olds' marriage. ``She is
coming through a difficult time with a great deal of strength and
resilience.''
</P>
<P>
   Today Ms. Olds lives in the same rent-controlled apartment that
she has had ``forever,'' she said. The lobby is faded, the plaster
on her ceilings is crumbling, but the apartment is filled with
light, with a wide view of the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, when Ms. Olds is alone, she dances around her
apartment, she said, ``to late Beethoven or early Aretha.'' A poem
will come to her, usually out of ``ordinary life.'' In her new
book, for instance, there is ``The Native'':
</P>
<P>
   This touching of him, on the borders of sleep,
</P>
<P>
   my breasts and hip bones fitted to his long
</P>
<P>
   back, my lap curled to him,
</P>
<P>
   folded around him like a wing with a dark
</P>
<P>
   eye-spot,
</P>
<P>
   it feels to me like the most real thing
</P>
<P>
   ``Possibly it might have come to me as a thought like, `This is
the real thing,''' she said about the poem's origins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're narratives,'' she said of her poems. Ms. Olds paused,
and then she added, almost wistfully, ``I wonder if they're art.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
