<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVY-VIEQUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY BLAMES LOWER WARSHIP READINESS ON VIEQUES TRAINING FREEZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Navy said Wednesday that a warship sailing to
the Persian Gulf next week will be handicapped by a ``significant
degradation'' of its combat readiness because of a five-month ban
on target practice on the Puerto Rican island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure was the latest effort by the Pentagon to crank up
pressure on President Clinton to allow the Navy and Marine Corps to
resume practicing air-to-ground bombing and naval gunfire at the
Caribbean bombing range used since 1941.
</P>
<P>
   The destroyer USS John Hancock will sail Sept. 17 as part of the
USS John F. Kennedy carrier battle group without having completed
training with its two 5-inch guns, a senior Navy official told
Hearst Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The JFK is being escorted by 11 warships, including six guided
missile warships, two destroyers, two attack submarines and a
combat support ship. The battle group will be accompanied by a
Marine combat assault force on three assault ships.
</P>
<P>
   The Hancock, which was not permitted to practice firing its
5-inch guns in support of Marine troops landing on Vieques, is
``deploying with a significant degradation in combat readiness,'' a
Navy official said. ``It's not the way we like to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Combat rehearsals, including amphibious assaults by Marines,
have been suspended on Vieques since April when a Marine Corps'
bombing mishap killed a civilian Puerto Rican security guard and
injured four others.
</P>
<P>
   Military commanders are increasingly complaining that the freeze
on training at Vieques is jeopardizing U.S. combat readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Adm. Harold W. Gehman Jr., commander of the U.S. Atlantic
Command, told Defense Secretary William Cohen in an Aug. 27 letter
that Navy and Marine Corps training on Vieques is ``part of a
complex training regime that allows us to send our men and women
into harms way with a clear conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Gehman urged efforts to ``retain the Vieques training area and
to continue this mission essential training.''
</P>
<P>
   Marine Gen. Anthony C. Zinni, commander of all U.S. operations
in the Persian Gulf, said continued suspension of air-to-ground
bombardment on Vieques would lead to ``less effective air-to-ground
weapons delivery accuracy'' by carrier-based U.S. warplanes
enforcing the no-fly zone across southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``This training is an absolute necessity to prepare our ships,
aircraft and aircrews for ongoing operations (Southern Watch) (and)
short notice contingencies,'' Zinni wrote Gen. Henry H. Shelton,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Both letters were obtained by Hearst Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Hancock, the Navy official who discussed the
ship's combat readiness said he would only discuss the militarily
sensitive issue on the condition that he not be publicly
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Navy headquarters at the Pentagon and at Atlantic
fleet headquarters in Norfolk, Va., said they could not remember
the Navy deploying a warship on a routine six-month operation with
such a low rating for combat readiness in one of the ship's
``mission categories.''
</P>
<P>
   The 563-foot destroyer, commissioned in 1979, failed to meet
Navy standards for deployment in ``naval surface fire support,''
the use of the 5-inch guns to destroy surface targets and support
amphibious landings by Marine forces.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the Hancock had qualified for seven other mission
categories, including anti-air operations and surface combat
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Zinni said in his letter that U.S. forces in the Persian Gulf
``will experience the first effects'' of the training moratorium on
Vieques when the Hancock arrives on Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``The degradation of this ship is not significant in terms of
present operations and can be partly mitigated by other means,''
Zinni wrote. ``However, this shortcoming will continue to grow and
will degrade our standard of readiness for combat operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Navy Lt. Cdr. Mark McDonald, a spokesman for the Atlantic Fleet
in Norfolk, Va., said the Hancock and its crew of 376 will practice
firing the ship's two 5-inch guns at a range in Scotland en route
to the Persian Gulf assignment in an effort to increase the ship's
readiness rating.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald declined to discuss details of the ship's readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Adm. William J. Fallon, the Atlantic fleet officer who
assesses naval forces' readiness for deployment, warned a Pentagon
review panel on July 23 that warships will begin to face ``serious
deficiencies'' in combat readiness unless live-fire training
resumes on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we say, `This is all too hard, we're not going to do it,' I
know in my heart we put people's lives at risk,'' Fallon testified.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The armed forces' lobbying came as the White House awaits a
Pentagon recommendation on the future use of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders in Puerto Rico, their allies in Congress and
Puerto Rican political leaders in New York are demanding a
permanent cessation of live fire operations and the Navy's
withdrawal from 22,000 acres of land on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   With an eye on persuading First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton to
take up the cause in her prospective New York Senate race, Rep.
Jose Serrano, D-N.Y., and New York City Council member Jose Rivera
are organizing a three-day campaign in New York beginning Friday to
rally public support for demands that the Navy leave Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
