<SLUG> BC-WACO-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT QUESTIONS FBI ROLE IN 1993 SIEGE; DANFORTH BACKED TO LEAD
PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Majority Leader Trent Lott expressed doubts
Wednesday about who caused the huge fire that killed some 80 Branch
Davidian cult members in 1993. Other Congressional leaders said
they support the appointment of former Sen. John Danforth to lead
an independent probe of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders said congressional investigations into the
Davidian siege near Waco, Texas, will not be called off despite
Danforth's appointment Wednesday by Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Lott referred to the FBI's admission on Aug. 25 that, despite
previous denials, its agents fired two incendiary tear gas
canisters during the final government raid on the Davidian compound
on April 19, 1993. The bureau and its parent agency, the Justice
Department, still maintain that those canisters were fired several
hours before the conflagration and did not cause it.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott told reporters, ``There are doubts (about the cause)
because questions have been raised.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi senator, a frequent critic of Reno, added, ``I
am beginning to think that the attorney general should resign.''
Reno has said the FBI had consistently misinformed her about
whether it had ever used flammable tear gas during the 51-day
siege.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota, defending Reno,
said Wednesday that she ``deserves commendation rather than
criticism,'' and that ``under no circumstances'' should she resign.
</P>
<P>
   Other congressional leaders expressed strong approval of
Danforth's appointment. Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., who chairs the
House Government Reform Committee, said, ``I have nothing but the
highest regard for Mr. Danforth and believe he is an excellent
candidate to run the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton added, ``We would be happy to work with Mr. Danforth, but
his appointment won't alter or change our investigation into what
happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton's panel has already begun subpoenaing witnesses on why
the FBI denied for six years that it had used any flammable
canisters.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional and other investigators are expected to focus on
whether the denials resulted from a bureaucratic slip-up or a
cover-up. The probers also will look into why military special
operations officers were on the scene with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department insists it was cult leader David Koresh
and his followers who started the fatal fire. The department also
says that military special operations officers were at the siege
only as observers and advisers, and not in an illegal capacity as
participants in the raid.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Lopatto, spokeswoman for Sen. Orrin Hatch, who heads the
Senate Judiciary Committee, said, ``We're moving forward with our
investigation regardless of what the Justice Department does.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, 63, a former Missouri senator, brings to the outside
probe strong credentials as both an independent Republican and as a
law enforcement official for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Yale University's Law School and its Divinity
School, Danforth, whose grandfather William Danforth founded the
pet food empire Ralston Purina, became an ordained Episcopal priest
in 1968. That year he also his public-service career as Missouri
state attorney general and was known for hiring Democrats as well
as Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 he was elected to the Senate, where he developed a
reputation as a moderate who was willing to compromise in order to
get legislation passed.
</P>
<P>
   Ever polite and even-tempered, he also became known as the
``conscience of the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth was a familiar face on television in 1991 when he
championed the nomination of conservative Court of Appeals Judge
Clarence Thomas to the Supreme Court during the turbulent
confirmation hearings that centered on law professor Anita Hill's
charges that Thomas had sexually harassed her. Thomas _ and
Danforth _ strongly denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, his last year in the Senate before retiring, Danforth
worked with Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., on a commission to shrink
ballooning federal entitlement programs such as Social Security and
Medicare. Kerrey praised him afterward as ``someone who can't be
pushed around.''
</P>
<P>
   Other former Senate colleagues said Wednesday that Danforth will
bring instant credibility to the independent investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., said he has ``an excellent
reputation and the highest integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, called Danforth ``a straight
arrow ... who (will) give people confidence that everything will be
looked at in a completely fair manner.''
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of Reno's tenure, the White House has stood behind
her, but President Clinton has declined to give a similar vote of
confidence to FBI Director Louis Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Dallas Morning News reported Wednesday that Texas
Rangers have found flares that were apparently fired by federal
officials during the Davidian siege. The newspaper said the Rangers
discovered the expended military illumination flares amid tons of
evidence recovered last Friday from a storage facility near Waco.
Evidence logs showed that the flares were recovered in the weeks
after the Davidian compound burned.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5014 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TIMOR-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      09-08 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMOR A TEST OF CLINTON RESOLVE TO HALT DEADLY VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton visited Rwanda last year on
the fourth anniversary of the genocide that left more than half a
million dead, he apologized to survivors and said the world should
have intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never again must we be shy about the evidence,'' Clinton said
then.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor is shaping up as a test of the president's word.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rwanda speech set the parameters for intervention on
humanitarian grounds,'' said an administration official, speaking
on the condition of anonymity. ``We'll see how this one unfolds.''
</P>
<P>
   The violence that has engulfed East Timor in the past week
apparently continued unabated Wednesday, as United Nations and
Australian officials said Indonesia's declaration of martial law
had not stopped the violence. So far, according to UN officials, as
many as 200,000 East Timor residents have fled, a quarter of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in violence began after East Timor residents
overwhelmingly voted for independence from Indonesia. The United
Nations, which sent a large team to observe the elections,
announced an almost complete pullout by Friday of the remaining
international and local UN staff in the East Timor capital of Dili.
</P>
<P>
   UN Secretary General Kofi Annan said a skeleton crew would stay
behind to protect 2,000 East Timorese who have sought safe haven at
the UN compound. Starting Friday, they will be almost the only
foreign observers left in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Ramos-Horta, co-winner of the 1996 Nobel Peace Prize and a
longtime advocate for East Timor's independence, made a chilling
prediction at the National Press Club in Washington, three blocks
from the White House:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next few days, thousands of people in East Timor will
die. Hundreds already have been shot dead. Thousands will die in
the next few days of summary and arbitrary executions.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``If there is not going to be in the next few
hours, a strong, determined decision by the US administration . . .
and the other members of the Security Council to commit
unequivocally to sending a peace enforcement mission to East Timor
. . . the people of East Timor are doomed. And let me say, the UN
will never again recover from this tragedy. Rwanda was one, Bosnia
one. And here, on the issue of East Timor, where the international
community could have succeeded, it is failing yet again.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal called for the immediate dispatch of international
peacekeeping troops to its former colony, but Indonesian President
B.J. Habibie said he would not approve any outside intervention,
and said the military would soon control the paramilitary forces
that have terrorized residents.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Clinton administration and the United Nations
reiterated that they would not intervene without Indonesia's
permission.
</P>
<P>
   US Defense Secretary William S. Cohen, who has been a strong
supporter of Indonesian interests dating to his days as US senator
from Maine, said the United States ``is not planning on any
insertion of peacekeeping forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said US officials have been ``talking and coordinating''
with Australian officials on a possible international force but had
not committed any troops.
</P>
<P>
   A second Clinton administration official, however, said there
have been long debates at the White House over the Pentagon's
strong recommendation against sending in peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The only conclusion was that the administration and the UN
Security Council should give Indonesia an unspecified amount of
time to see if its military could end the rampages by the militia
forces. Late Wednesday, Habibie was set to meet with a five-member
Security Council team to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Clinton will be in New Zealand at the annual Asian
Pacific Economic Conference, which could be dominated by the
upheaval in East Timor if the violence remains unchecked. Habibie
said he and other top Indonesian officials will not attend the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the violence, Mahendra Siregar, the first secretary at
the Indonesia Embassy in Washington, said the first two days of
martial law ``showed some improvement in Dili. No has been killed
there in the last 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Indonesia has legal authority under a UN agreement signed
May 5 to look after security in East Timor, Siregar said no country
should be considering intervention. ``Pressuring Indonesia on this
issue will not solve the problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens if the violence escalates?
</P>
<P>
   Several US senators and representatives called for economic and
military penalties, including ending US military assistance to
Indonesia and opposing any international financial assistance to
Habibie's government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indonesia cannot expect continued international financial
support unless it takes immediate steps to end the violence in East
Timor,'' said Senator John F. Kerry, a Massachusetts Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Others argued for immediately dispatching international
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and Security Council, of course,
didn't heed Ramos-Horta's call, and his was one of many voices
raising comparisons between East Timor, Rwanda and the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   In East Timor, said Hurst Hannum, a professor of international
law at the Fletcher School of Diplomacy at Tufts University,
``there is a much stronger case for intervention than the case for
Kosovo. In East Timor, the motivation to intervene would be purely
humanitarian.''
</P>
<P>
   US officials have dismissed any comparison to NATO's war over
Kosovo, pointing out that other diplomatic avenues were closed with
Yugoslavia and that the Kosovar Albanians had never been permitted
to vote for independence _ two key differences from the current
East Timor situation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rwanda comparison, and Clinton's earlier words, isn't so
easily brushed aside.
</P>
<P>
   The first administration official said there has been much talk
among top policymakers about Rwanda, and not Kosovo, when it comes
to East Timor. ``Kosovo is the underbelly of Europe, where our
strategic interests are unquestioned,'' the official said. ``Here,
like Rwanda, it's farther afield, and the strategic importance
isn't so clear. Here, too, are people of color.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, said the official, is keenly aware of Clinton's
words in Rwanda in March 1998, and some wonder whether his pledge
then carries over to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton to Rwandans: ``We did not act quickly enough after
the killing began. We should not have allowed the refugee camps to
become safe havens for the killers. We did not immediately call
these crimes by their rightful name: genocide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
