<HEADLINE>
GROUP OPPOSES $1 BILLION IN PROPOSED NASA BUDGET CUTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A small group of lawmakers joined forces Wednesday
in opposition to nearly $1 billion in proposed NASA funding cuts as
Congress resumed work on a number of year 2000 appropriations
measures that President Clinton has threatened to veto.
</P>
<P>
   Returning from their monthlong summer recess, a half-dozen
lawmakers from affected states, such as Maryland and Texas, said
that the NASA budget reductions would force significant cutbacks in
space exploration and scientific research, slash up to 7,000 jobs,
and ultimately ``endanger the life of the nation.'' The lawmakers
cited the nation's dependence on NASA-funded research breakthroughs
in aeronautics and other fields as reasons they oppose the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers blamed Republican leaders in the Senate and the
House for the ``shortsighted'' budget proposal, charging that NASA
was singled out ``to take a hit'' as part of the Republican plan to
cut taxes by $792 billion over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The funding reduction, already approved by the Senate and to be
voted Thursday in the House, would cut the space agency's budget by
nearly $1 billion below its current $13.7 billion level. Democrats
charged that the cut would betray a 1997 understanding between
Congress and the White House to keep the agency's funding at around
$13.5 billion a year through 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ralph Hall, D-Texas, said the agency had already made
cutbacks of 34 percent over the past decade, ``more than any other
agency,'' and could not afford to lose any more funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a critical cut that we absolutely can't take,'' said
Hall, the ranking Democrat on the House subcommittee that oversees
NASA operations.
</P>
<P>
   That view was echoed by Democratic Reps. Ken Bentsen and Sheila
Jackson Lee of Texas. In a bitter attack, the two Houstonians
accused Republican leaders of playing politics with NASA in order
to help fund a tax cut measure that they know does not stand any
chance of becoming law because Clinton's has vowed to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee said the cuts would only end up punishing an agency
in a time of anticipated budget surpluses, despite its efforts to
curtail unnecessary spending in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gotten where we wanted to go (in balancing the budget)
and beyond. That's why this is a punitive measure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen also questioned why the Republicans would even propose a
cut to NASA funding when Clinton has promised to veto any bill
containing reductions in the agency budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just political posturing ... for an election 15 months
from now,'' Bentsen said, referring to efforts by Republicans to
appear as if they are still holding the line on spending while
cutting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican, Rep. Connie Morella of Maryland, agreed in part
with Bentsen. She said NASA funding would likely be restored in the
end and called on her GOP colleagues to acknowledge that spending
limits set in 1997 should be lifted in order to fully fund
important scientific research and development efforts, as well as
other needed programs.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed cut in the NASA budget, she said, ``just points out
that these caps have just got to be moved.''
</P>
<P>
   While he favors holding the line on spending, House Majority
Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, is pushing for restoration of NASA
funding. Ironically, DeLay voted for the cuts last month in the
Appropriations Committee as part of a larger spending measure
designed to stay within the 1997 balanced budget agreement. But he
has promised to help restore the funding in conference with the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over NASA erupted as Congress and Clinton began
wrestling Wednesday with a number of contentious 2000 spending
issues, many of which are likely to be unresolved when the new
fiscal year begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to veto the Republicans' $792 billion tax
relief package when it reaches his desk next week. And he has vowed
to veto several appropriations measures as well because of the NASA
reduction and cuts in other programs favored by the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders planned to meet Thursday to consider how to
respond to the veto threats. In the meantime, Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., called on Clinton to at least open
negotiations with Congress on the tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen any indication that the president wants to work
with us,'' Lott told reporters. ``What the president wants is more
spending, more spending, more spending for everything. He is not
for tax relief for working Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
