<HEADER>
A5021 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WACO09-COX     09-08 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DANFORTH TO HEAD JUSTICE DEPARTMENT'S WACO PROBE
 &HT;    550&AMP;add. With WACO-CONGRESS.
 &HT;    By BOB DART and JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Sen. John Danforth of Missouri has accepted
Attorney General Janet Reno's offer to head an independent
investigation of FBI actions during and after the fatal 1993 Branch
Davidian siege near Waco, Texas, Justice Department officials
confirmed Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Danforth were scheduled to appear at a news conference
Thursday morning at the Justice Department to officially announce
his appointment. The officials declined to discuss any details of
the investigation, such as how long it would last or the scope of
Danforth's powers.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also declined to comment on reports that an
assistant to Danforth would also be named Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Reno tapped Danforth, a Republican who earned wide bipartisan
respect in the Senate, after acknowledging that her credibility had
been damaged by recent FBI admissions that it had used flammable
tear gas grenades in the siege.
</P>
<P>
   Both Reno and FBI officials had denied for six years that such
grenades had been used at Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi said Wednesday
the belated disclosures have caused him to question who started the
fatal fire, and said Reno should resign.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had doubts about who started the fire, Lott replied,
``There are doubts because of the questions that have been raised.
... How did that happen? Who did it? And why were we not given full
information or accurate information?''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's top Republican said the nation is worried that
``you cannot rely on information you get from the attorney general
or the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about that incident (at Waco). It's about a
bigger question,'' Lott told reporters at the Capitol. ``We have
the Justice Department ... not showing competence or probity. That
really concerns people. It scares people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott pointed to ``the pattern now that has developed over six
and a half years and the events involving not only the appointment
of independent counsels, her refusal to provide information or
answer questions by the Congress, the problem with the Waco
investigation, the situation with the Puerto Rican pardons. All of
that leads me to conclude that the attorney general should
resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if a thorough probe is conducted by Danforth, Congress must
also hold hearings, Lott said. ``We have a responsibility here to
the American people, as elected officials, to conduct our own
investigation and ask questions.''
</P>
<P>
   While agreeing that Congress should take an investigatory role,
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., rushed to the defense
of the beleaguered attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Janet Reno deserves commendation, not criticism,''
said Daschle. ``She deserves every bit of the benefit of the doubt
here until all the facts are known. But under no circumstances do I
believe the attorney general should resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the top Democrat in the Senate indicated that Justice
Department officials will be testifying soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to ensure that all the facts are out,'' said Daschle.
``I do believe there is a constitutional role for the Congress to
be involved. But I hope it can be non-political or nonpartisan,
objective and swift.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, 63, was regarded as politically independent during his
three terms in the Senate. After serving for two years as
co-chairman of the Bipartisan Commission on Entitlement and Tax
Reform, he left the Senate after the 1994 election.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Several committees are already looking into the Waco incident in
which 76 Branch Davidian members, including 21 children, died in a
fire that the FBI contends was set by leaders of the sect.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, federal officials have admitted that that two
incendiary tear gas grenades were fired but maintained that they
could not have caused the fire. The grenades were shot at a
concrete bunker more than 100 yards from the wooden compound and
several hours before the fire broke out, the FBI said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Lott became perhaps the highest-ranking official
in Washington to publicly express doubts about who started the
fatal fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a clear answer,'' he said. ``And I think we need
to find that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott is also the top Republican to call for Reno to step down,
albeit tentatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that when you have an attorney general that has
developed a pattern of not acting when she should with regard to
investigations or, in this case, apparently not getting to the
truth'' the situation ``puts her in jeopardy in terms of her
ability to do the job,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait for more information and some final
conclusions, but I'm beginning to think that she should resign,''
Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
