<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; MURDOCH CHEERLEADS FOR CHINA IN EVERY GAME &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Media mogul  &UR; Rupert Murdoch &LR; , who's eager to do business in
China, told Vanity Fair that the  &UR; Dalai Lama  &LR; of Tibet _ whose
struggle is to oust the Chinese there _ is said by some to be a
``very political old monk shuffling around in Gucci shoes.''
Murdoch said that before the Chinese occupied Tibet, it was ``a
pretty terrible autocratic society out of the Middle Ages.''
</P>
<P>
   As to China, Murdoch opined that ``the average Chinese person
doesn't care about democracy, he cares about his next bowl of rice
and getting a better standard of living.''
</P>
<P>
   Tibetan activists called Murdoch's remarks ``ignorant,''
``cynical'' and ``self-serving.'' ``Rupert Murdoch knows nothing
about Tibet. ...,''  &UR; Tashi Tsering &LR;  of the Tibet Fund told the
Daily Telegraph of London. `He is definitely not someone to make
moral judgments, particularly about someone like the Dalai Lama. He
should stick to making money.''
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch recently married 31-year-old  &UR; Wendy Deng &LR; , a Chinese
woman. Last year, his publishing company, HarperCollins, canceled
plans to publish the memoirs of former Hong Kong governor  &UR; Chris &LR; 
 &UR; Patten &LR;  because the book was critical of China; and five years ago,
Star TV, which he owns, stopped using the BBC because it was
critical of Chinese actions in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   P.S.: In a story about China's new women, Marie-Claire magazine
says that the ``most exclusive residential compound in Beijing is
``Beijing Riviera Villas.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SORRY, WRONG NUMBER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; 's planned itinerary for a trip to Asia and
Australia was faxed to a New Zealand chicken farmer instead of the
organizers of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum, reports
the Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   The document was ``ultra top secret,'' said the newspaper, but
was received by  &UR; Saji Philips &LR;  of South Auckland. A policeman
eventually showed up and took the document from the chicken man.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. In other duh news,  &UR; R.S. Bolton &LR;  forwards a Washington
Times story about President Clinton being handed a cordless drill
while helping out at a school renovation this week, upon which he
proclaimed his wonder. ``Now that I'm a homeowner, I'd better get
one of these,'' said the president. ``I've never seen one.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BERGMAN ADMITS NAZI SYMPATHIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ingmar Bergman &LR; , 81, was attracted to Nazism as a youth,
reveals the Swedish film director in journalist &UR; Maria-Pia &LR; 
 &UR; Boethius &LR; ' forthcoming book, ``Honor and Conscience,'' about
Swedish neutrality in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   After spending the summer of 1936 as an exchange student in
Germany, Bergman said he thought the German leader ``had incredible
charisma.'' When he returned home, Bergman says he didn't protest
when his brother painted a swastika on the house of a Jew.
</P>
<P>
   The first time he saw pictures taken in concentration camps, he
thought they were Allied propaganda. ``When I realized the truth,
the shock was incredible. Brutally and violently, my innocence was
removed in one stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Jewel &LR;  was in the lobby lounge of the Ritz-Carlton on
Saturday night and asked the pianist if she could join him for a
few songs. By the end of the first song, there was standing room
only.
</P>
<P>
   - So you went to a Labor Day barbecue and all you got was a
mustard stain on your T-shirt?  &UR; Mia Minnelli &LR;  of San Francisco
called to say she was at  &UR; Puff Daddy &LR; 's exclusive ``white party''
in the Hamptons _ with  &UR; Donald Trump &LR; ,  &UR; Chevy Chase &LR;  and  &UR; Christie &LR; 
 &UR; Brinkley &LR;  _ and got to take home a gift pack containing his new CD,
his new magazine and a set of underwear, briefs and tank top, in
all-white, in keeping with the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   - The Hollywood Reporter says that  &UR; Sean Penn  &LR; will star in
``The Assassination of Richard Nixon,'' an independent movie about
Samuel Byck, a furniture salesman who believes he is Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   It is said to be based on the true story.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; ``Sometimes if my voice is not right, if I know it's not
there, then I won't do it, because I know they're not going to get
what they came for. And that's not fair. ... So there are moments
when I say, `No, I can't do this,' because I can't do it to them
and I won't do it to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Whitney Houston  &LR; in the Times of London, explaining why, for
instance, she pulled out of a recent performance at the Concord
Pavilion shortly before show time.
</P>
