A5026 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-WACO-PROBE-1STLD-WRIT     09-08 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-PROBE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT QUESTIONS FBI ROLE IN SIEGE; DANFORTH BACKED TO LEAD PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (EDs: CORRECTS lede to say Senate (not House) Majority Leader;
makes minor change in headline.)  
 By MARK HELM and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott expressed doubts
Wednesday about who caused the huge fire that killed some 80 Branch
Davidian cult members in 1993. Other Congressional leaders said
they support the appointment of former Sen. John Danforth to lead
an independent probe of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders said congressional investigations into the
Davidian siege near Waco, Texas, will not be called off despite
Danforth's appointment Wednesday by Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Lott referred to the FBI's admission on Aug. 25 that, despite
previous denials, its agents fired two incendiary tear gas
canisters during the final government raid on the Davidian compound
on April 19, 1993. The bureau and its parent agency, the Justice
Department, still maintain that those canisters were fired several
hours before the conflagration and did not cause it.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott told reporters, ``There are doubts (about the cause)
because questions have been raised.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi senator, a frequent critic of Reno, added, ``I
am beginning to think that the attorney general should resign.''
Reno has said the FBI had consistently misinformed her about
whether it had ever used flammable tear gas during the 51-day
siege.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota, defending
Reno, said Wednesday that she ``deserves commendation rather than
criticism,'' and that ``under no circumstances'' should she resign.
</P>
<P>
   Other congressional leaders expressed strong approval of
Danforth's appointment. Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., who chairs the
House Government Reform Committee, said, ``I have nothing but the
highest regard for Mr. Danforth and believe he is an excellent
candidate to run the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton added, ``We would be happy to work with Mr. Danforth, but
his appointment won't alter or change our investigation into what
happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton's panel has already begun subpoenaing witnesses on why
the FBI denied for six years that it had used any flammable
canisters.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional and other investigators are expected to focus on
whether the denials resulted from a bureaucratic slip-up or a
cover-up. The probers also will look into why military special
operations officers were on the scene with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department insists it was cult leader David Koresh
and his followers who started the fatal fire. The department also
says that military special operations officers were at the siege
only as observers and advisers, and not in an illegal capacity as
participants in the raid.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Lopatto, spokeswoman for Sen. Orrin Hatch, who heads the
Senate Judiciary Committee, said, ``We're moving forward with our
investigation regardless of what the Justice Department does.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, 63, a former Missouri senator, brings to the outside
probe strong credentials as both an independent Republican and as a
law enforcement official for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Yale University's Law School and its Divinity
School, Danforth, whose grandfather William Danforth founded the
pet food empire Ralston Purina, became an ordained Episcopal priest
in 1968. That year he also his public-service career as Missouri
state attorney general and was known for hiring Democrats as well
as Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 he was elected to the Senate, where he developed a
reputation as a moderate who was willing to compromise in order to
get legislation passed.
</P>
<P>
   Ever polite and even-tempered, he also became known as the
``conscience of the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth was a familiar face on television in 1991 when he
championed the nomination of conservative Court of Appeals Judge
Clarence Thomas to the Supreme Court during the turbulent
confirmation hearings that centered on law professor Anita Hill's
charges that Thomas had sexually harassed her. Thomas _ and
Danforth _ strongly denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, his last year in the Senate before retiring, Danforth
worked with Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., on a commission to shrink
ballooning federal entitlement programs such as Social Security and
Medicare. Kerrey praised him afterward as ``someone who can't be
pushed around.''
</P>
<P>
   Other former Senate colleagues said Wednesday that Danforth will
bring instant credibility to the independent investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., said he has ``an excellent
reputation and the highest integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, called Danforth ``a straight
arrow ... who (will) give people confidence that everything will be
looked at in a completely fair manner.''
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of Reno's tenure, the White House has stood behind
her, but President Clinton has declined to give a similar vote of
confidence to FBI Director Louis Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Dallas Morning News reported Wednesday that Texas
Rangers have found flares that were apparently fired by federal
officials during the Davidian siege. The newspaper said the Rangers
discovered the expended military illumination flares amid tons of
evidence recovered last Friday from a storage facility near Waco.
Evidence logs showed that the flares were recovered in the weeks
after the Davidian compound burned.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm and Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
the e-mail address mark(at)hearstdc.com and judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
