A5028 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w BC-STATES-OSPREY-PA     09-08 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-OSPREY-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        BOEING TILT ROTOR TECHNOLOGY TAKES OFF
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Ted Monoson   c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 8 -- A futuristic looking plane-helicopter
aircraft wowed defense officials and Congress members as it flew
over the nation's capital region Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Officials who attended the flight demonstration of the aircraft
known as the V-22, which was in-part developed by Boeing of Ridley
Park, Pa., said it is about to take off in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Defense officials say it will have a huge impact on the future
of the military. Secretary of Defense William Cohen and a
contingent of congressmen including Curt Weldon, R-Pa. were
passengers on the flight. The Pentagon used the demonstration to
show off the aircraft that can take off and land like a helicopter
and fly like a turboprop airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``This technology epitomizes what our forces are going to need
in the future,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was developed jointly by Boeing and Bell Helicopter
Textron in Fort Worth, Texas. The team created the V-22 tiltrotor
for the U.S. Marine Corps, Navy and Special Operations Forces.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing handles the fuselage and all subsystems, digital avionics
and fly-by-wire flight control systems. Meanwhile, Bell Helicopter
Textron produces wing, transmissions, empennage, rotor systems and
engine installation. When the aircraft accelerates after the rotors
are shifted from a vertical position to a horizontal position, it
transforms the Osprey from a maneuverable helicopter-like aircraft
to a high-speed, high altitude aircraft that resembles a turboprop
airplane, according to Lance Cpl. Karen Bertrand. At the moment it
changed, the momentum sent water bottles on board flying,
passengers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seemed to be real impressed with the Osprey,'' Bertrand
said of the high-ranking passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Mac Thornberry, R-Texas, who was part of the
congressional contingent aboard the Osprey, confirmed Bertrand's
observation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told what the aircraft can do,'' Thornberry said,
``But to experience it first hand is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to the Osprey on a parade ground beside the
Pentagon, Thornberry extolled the benefits of the aircraft for the
military and for the city of Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   The Osprey will be ideal in situations where soldiers have to be
brought into an area quickly, said, who is a member of the House
Armed Services Committee. He added that conflicts and peace keeping
missions requiring rapid deployments will crop up often in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The implications for strategy are tremendous,'' Thornberry
said. ``This is clearly the future for all the services.''
</P>
<P>
   The Osprey was accompanied on its brief flight by XV-15, the
initial tilt-rotor aircraft which was built 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not old technology,'' Stinson said. ``What happened
was that the concept was way ahead of the technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The V-22, which can carry 24 combat equipped personnel or a
15,000 pound external load, is significantly larger and faster than
XV-15.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the Marine Corps to purchase 360 of the V-22s,
the Air Force to purchase 50 and the Navy to purchase 48, according
to the Department of Defense. The aircraft built for each branch
will be slightly different.
</P>
<P>
   The Wednesday demonstration was also attended by military
officers from several foreign countries, including Poland, Ukraine
and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Defense Department has not yet given Bell
permission to sell the aircraft abroad, Stinson said the company
has already been approached by several foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   Most foreign countries will wait until the United States has
used the technology for several years, Stinson added.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gaffney, an assistant defense secretary in the Reagan
administration questioned how many foreign countries will be able
to afford the V-22s, which sell for approximately $30 million
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will not be able to afford it,'' Gaffney said. ``But they
will lust after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaffney, who is currently the president of a Washington,
D.C.-based think tank, the Center for Security Policy, said the
V-22's future is in civilian uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have an aircraft that can fly like a plane but also
land in midtown Manhattan, that is going to be a huge attraction,''
Gaffney said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bell has already sold a modified version that carries
six to nine passengers for civilian use, Gaffney predicted that
orders will increase significantly after the military has proven
the aircraft's reliability.
</P>
</TEXT>
