<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5033 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BAPTISTS09-COX     09-08 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National Baptist Convention gathers to elect president
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ It was business as usual _ political power plays,
backstage deals and bickering _ as the nation's largest black
church group gathered here Wednesday to elect a new leader.
</P>
<P>
   Politics and religion not only mixed, but seemed inseparable as
candidates for the presidency of the National Baptist Convention
USA Inc. kicked their campaigns into overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   The Ice Palace Arena, home for this year's annual national
convention, is sporting all the trappings of a political convention
_ campaign hats, banners and buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 50,000 delegates are playing a wait-and-see game as
candidates jockey for position, hoping to capture the leadership of
the organization when the new president is elected late tonight.
The convention _ festive and light, intense and serious _ has been
touched by moments both funny and bizarre since opening Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   One presidential candidate brought a baseball bat to a public
forum Tuesday _ he said it was to honor his father who had played
in the Negro baseball league. Several other candidates and their
followers have stayed busy exchanging charges of fraud and
distortion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another candidate, E.V. Hill of Los Angeles, managed to
inject a note of levity, a freudian slip that nonetheless had a
sinister edge.
</P>
<P>
   Hill floored the convention crowd when he accidentally told them
that he had the ``sexual'' experience to lead the convention. He
quickly recovered by saying he had the ``secular'' experience to
become president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most critical election in the last 50 years,'' said
the Rev. Wyatt Tee Walker, a delegate from New York city and a
former colleague of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   This week's session comes seven months after the resignation and
imprisonment of the organization's last president, the Rev. Henry
Lyons. Lyons was convicted on state and federal charges that
included bank fraud, tax evasion and stealing $4 million from
charities and companies trying to do business with the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debacle created by the corruption of Henry Lyons effected
every black church in America, irrespective of denominations,''
Walker said. ``All black churches were scarred by the behavior of
Henry Lyons. That is why it is so critical for this convention to
get a president who has integrity and a vision of where we will go
in the next millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven candidates are running for the five-year post, but three
_ Hill; the Rev. W. Franklyn Richardson of Mount Vernon, N.Y.; and
the Rev. William J. Shaw of Philadelphia, Pa. _ are considered
front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   Both Richardson and Shaw ran against Lyons in 1994, when Lyons
became president. Some delegates insist that race was fixed.
</P>
<P>
   During a forum Tuesday, most of the candidates emphasized the
need for reform. Several said the organization should hire
independent auditors and fiscal officers in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problems today are not the problems of one man's mistake
but of a system,'' Richardson said. ``The presidency of the
National Baptist Convention is an imperialistic institution. The
president is the chief executive officer, the chief operating
officer, he appoints two thirds of the board of directors. That's
too much power for one person.''
</P>
<P>
   Although politics have dominated the first few days of the
convention, there are plenty of other distractions to amuse and
entertain delegates and visitors.
</P>
<P>
   At least 1,000 vendors have turned Tampa's convention center
into a Baptist bazaar. Delegates with enough money and daring can
buy purple suits, alligator shoes, derby hats, jewelry, choir
robes, hair care products and, yes, even Bibles.
</P>
<P>
   The convention center was full of massive, gray-haired preachers
in suspenders, throwing back their heads in laughter as they met
with friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like coming to a family reunion,'' said Georgia Tolbert,
a delegate from Detroit. ``When I go to the convention, it's like
seeing what heaven is going to be like. People are going to be
coming from all nations, all tribes to walk on the streets of
gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
