<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-VIACOM09-COX     09-08 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Viacom, CBS merger in tune with trend
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In merging, Viacom and CBS are following in the
well-ploughed footsteps of media giants such as Disney and Time
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street and many industry observers have come to view the
big media mergers of the past decade as the natural course of
things.
</P>
<P>
   The mergers, they argue, are part of an evolutionary process
leading to a day in the near future when four to six companies
control most of what the world hears on radio, watches on
television and sees on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger is part of the natural state of things, of the
natural trend of the industry,'' says Tom Wolzien, a media analyst
at Sanford Bernstein &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wolzien believes, the process is nearly complete.
``There isn't much left to buy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the combination of Viacom and CBS will create the
second-largest media company in a deal valued at between $35
billion and $37 billion. It combines the Paramount film studio and
cable TV channels of Viacom with the television network and radio
holdings of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The new combined company knocks Disney back down to No. 3 but
the largest media company will remain Time Warner, which owns
Atlanta-based Turner Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   The only media asset Time Warner doesn't own in its vast
portfolio is one of the big four television networks. It does own
the fledgling WB network, which caters to young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I compare this latest merger to that of Time Warner and Turner
Broadcasting three years ago,'' says Paul Raymond, a Atlanta-based
media consultant. ``There a lot of synergies between Viacom and
CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   More mergers to come
</P>
<P>
   Raymond and other observers believe the Viacom and CBS merger
will prompt yet another wave of consolidation within the media
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always get a wave of mergers following a big deal like
this,'' says Nick Trigony, president of Atlanta-based Cox
Broadcasting, a unit of diversified media company Cox Enterprises
Inc. Cox also owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The last big network unaffiliated with a Hollywood studio is
NBC, owned by General Electric, which has been rumored for years to
be trying to sell it. Indeed, Time Warner Vice Chairman Ted Turner
has tried several times to persuade General Electric to sell the
network to his company.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives declined Wednesday to comment on the
Viacom-CBS merger and its implications for their many news and
entertainment businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Time Warner, others with the motive and the money, such
as Sony and Bertelsman, are foreign companies prohibited from
owning a U.S. Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the mere size of a deal like (CBS and Viacom)
brings people from across the media industry together to talk,''
says Leland Westat Sanford Bernstein &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wolzien believes, the process is nearly complete.
``There isn't much left to buy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the combination of Viacom and CBS will create the
second-largest media company in a deal valued at between $35
billion and $37 billion. It combines the Paramount film studio and
cable TV channels of Viacom with the television network and radio
holdings of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The new combined company knocks Disney back down to No. 3 but
the largest media company will remain Time Warner, which owns
Atlanta-based Turner Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   The only media asset Time Warner doesn't own in its vast
portfolio is one of the big four television networks. It does own
the fledgling WB network, which caters to young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I compare this latest merger to that of Time Warner and Turner
Broadcasting three years ago,'' says Paul Raymond, a Atlanta-based
media consultant. ``There a lot of synergies between Viacom and
CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   More mergers to come
</P>
<P>
   Raymond and other observers believe the Viacom and CBS merger
will prompt yet another wave of consolidation within the media
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always get a wave of mergers followin The last big network
unaffiliated with a Hollywood studio is NBC, owned by General
Electric, which has been rumored for years to be trying to sell it.
Indeed, Time Warner Vice Chairman Ted Turner has tried several
times to persuade General Electric to sell the network to his
company.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives declined Wednesday to comment on the
Viacom-CBS merger and its implications for their many news and
entertainment businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Time Warner, others with the motive and the money, such
as Sony and Bertelsman, are foreign companies prohibited from
owning a U.S. Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the mere size of a deal like (CBS and Viacom)
brings people from across the media industry together to talk,''
says Leland Westerfield, a senior media analyst at PaineWebber.
``But there is nothing compelling about the merger that adds a new
competitive pressure that wasn't already there.''
</P>
<P>
   Westerfield and others doubt that the merger will change the
competitive landscape in local media markets in places such as
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet may be where the impact is felt.
</P>
<P>
   CBS CEO Mel Karmazin has made a number of major purchases lately
in the industry and has said CBS will become a major Internet
player.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the combined Internet assets of Viacom and CBS make the
new company a dominant player in the online distribution of music.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a company wants to promote, market and sell music online,
it needs to deal with the new Viacom,'' Jordan E. Rohan, an online
media analyst at Wit Capital, told the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Rise of new media kingpin
</P>
<P>
   The Viacom-CBS combination also marks the rise of a new media
kingpin in Karmazin, a New Yorker who began his career as a street
peddler. He rose to become chief executive of CBS, engineering a
turnaround of the television and radio broadcasting company. CBS is
now rated No. 1 among the four big networks.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the merger, Karmazin has become heir apparent
to Sumner Redstone, the legendary chairman of Viacom. Under his
reign, Viacom had become the third-largest media company in the
past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin will serve in the new Viacom as Redstone's second in
command, with the title of president and chief operating officer.
All units of the combined company will report to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Redstone has put in place the guy who is going to replace
him,'' says Cox Broadcasting's Trigony. Indeed, the two men will
receive identical compensation packages.
</P>
<P>
   Trigony described Karmazin, a friend and colleague for 30 years,
as an executive who focuses on revenue growth. He's also a
proponent of synergy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll enlarge the sales force and have them sell advertising
time across all of the combined companies outlets as a single
buy,'' says Trigony.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good idea, in Wall Street's point of view. ``Wall
Street believes in Karmazin,'' says Trigony.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the stock of both companies initially rose. That's
unusual. The stock of the acquirer, in this case, Viacom, usually
falls in a big merger. But Viacom's stock closed off slightly
Wednesday at $47.31.25. CBS's shares also fell slightly to
$50.1875.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
