<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-WYE-ART-NYT &LR;      09-08 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WYE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL PREPARES LAND TRANSFER; TO FREE 200 PALESTINIANS THURSDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Moving to carry out its latest agreement with the
Palestinians, the Israeli government Wednesday approved the
transfer of more West Bank land to Palestinian rule and prepared
for the release of Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabinet vote, followed by an overwhelming endorsement of the
agreement in parliament, cleared the way to start carrying out the
accord before the Jewish New Year, which begins on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The first land handover will put another 7 percent of West Bank
territory _ about 147 square miles _ under Palestinian civil
control; Israel retains security responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The latest agreement, which was signed on Saturday, revived the
Wye River land-for-security accord reached last October.
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement calls for Israel to withdraw from a further 11
percent of the West Bank. Together with previous pullbacks, this
will leave the Palestinians in full or partial control of 40
percent of the territory. The pullbacks were halted in December by
Benjamin Netanyahu, then the prime minister, who accused the
Palestinians of failing to keep their security commitments.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabinet approved the first land transfer by 17 to 1, with
one abstention. Construction Minister Yitzhak Levy of the National
Religious Party, which supports the Jewish settlers in the West
Bank, cast the only nay vote. Interior Minister Natan Sharansky,
whose Russian immigrant party is also sympathetic to the settlers,
abstained.
</P>
<P>
   Settlers have criticized the planned withdrawals, arguing that
they will expose their communities to possible attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to his right-wing critics, Prime Minister Ehud Barak
asserted that ceding West Bank territory was a difficult step.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are separating from parts of the land that are dear to us
all,'' he told the Cabinet in remarks made public by his office.
``But we are a responsible government, and we must move toward a
permanent settlement and peace agreements throughout the region in
order to consolidate Israel's security and future.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking later in parliament, Barak struck a similar chord.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep in our hearts, there is deep pain,'' he said, but he
added, ``In order to insure the future, sovereignty and strength of
Israel, we must make difficult, sometimes painful decisions to
separate peacefully from the Palestinians, to no longer rule over
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Sharon, the leader of the opposition Likud party, urged
lawmakers to reject the latest agreement, calling it a
``disgraceful diplomatic failure'' that included new and dangerous
concessions to the Palestinians. But the accord was endorsed by a
wide margin, 54 to 23.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoner release will be the first step in carrying out the
accord. Israeli officials said the 200 Palestinians to be freed
first include people who had killed suspected informers or had
wounded Israelis. Their release is a break with longstanding
Israeli practice of not freeing prisoners ``with blood on their
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as Barak forged ahead with his agreement, he faced a
threat by the ultra-Orthodox Shas party to bolt his coalition, a
move that would leave him without a majority in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Shas members boycotted Wednesday's votes in the Cabinet and
parliament, demanding that the government approve funds for
Shas-run schools, which are deep in debt. Education Minister Yossi
Sarid, leader of the secular Meretz Party, has withheld the money,
saying Shas must first correct financial mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
