<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA-COMPLAINTS09-CO     09-08 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-COMPLAINTS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta's involuntary bumping rates continue to soar
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines continued to lead the industry in
involuntary passenger bumpings by a wide margin during the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based carrier, embarrassed by a similar ranking last
winter, has vowed improvement. But a spokesman said programs to
correct the problem didn't start in time to be reflected in the
April-June quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting in July we've seen major progress that will be
reflected in the next set of numbers,'' spokesman John Kennedy
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, Delta reported 5,519 involuntary bumpings
_ nearly half the total of 11,908 for all 10 major airlines. Delta
ranked worst in the industry with a rate of 2.07 involuntary
bumpings per 10,000 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines had the fewest involuntary bumpings, 170, and
the lowest rate, 0.13.
</P>
<P>
   Involuntary bumping occurs when planes are overbooked and some
passengers are forced to wait for later flights.
</P>
<P>
   Most bumpings are voluntary, with passengers agreeing to take
later flights in exchange for credits toward future flights. Delta
reported 45,221 voluntary bumpings in the second quarter. That was
second to American, which had 64,664 voluntary bumpings but only
717 involuntary.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Transportation Department compiles quarterly bumping
figures as part of its Air Travel Consumer Report, with airlines
ranked by their rates of involuntary bumping.
</P>
<P>
   Delta does better in other categories in the DOT report. It was
third in on-time performance for July, sustaining a marked
improvement over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   It usually places among the best three or four airlines in
consumer complaints to the DOT and lost luggage. But Delta's
involuntary bumping rates have soared in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said new computer programs to better manage overbooking
are being installed after several delays. He also said the airline
is trying to do a better job of anticipating overbooked flights
before boarding and offering incentives to generate volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
