<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Creating a street life downtown a passion for head of Turner
sports department
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You think you've got a tough commute? Try Janet Marie
Smith's. Her office is in Atlanta, her home is in Baltimore, she
flies coach (with occasional frequent-flier upgrades to first
class) and her door-to-door time is three hours.
</P>
<P>
   That's the easy part. Fridays through Mondays in Baltimore Smith
raises three children under age 6 (who spent much of their prenatal
lives in flight over the Eastern seaboard), picks one of them up
from school, works out of her home via phone and e-mail, and with
luck gets reacquainted with husband Bart Harvey, a businessman who
builds homes for low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesdays through Thursdays, Smith is at her CNN Center desk as
president of Turner Sports &AMP; Entertainment Development. She reached
the post after getting raves for turning ballparks _ Baltimore's
Camden Yards and Atlanta's Turner Field _ into veritable funtowns
with enough bars, restaurants and touches of traditional charm to
entice even the most casual baseball fan, spouse and child.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's current duties include redesigning the CNN Center and
overseeing construction of the $213 million Philips Arena, which is
due to be unveiled in 10 days to a curious universe. That and
taking flak in the local and national press for the gargantuan
``Big Ted'' billboard whose design she supervised. In a moment,
Smith will have more to say about this so-called ``abomination,''
which will loom over Centennial Olympic Park and shout the praises
of the arena's ``PHILIPS'' sponsor in the same subtle way that,
say, Russian leaders' faces presided over Red Square.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the 42-year-old native of Jackson, Miss., is giving a
bottle of Tabasco a good hard shake over a bowl of Oriental-style
chicken salad. Pretty in a willowy way, with light blue eyes and
brown hair so fine that it wafts around her ears, Smith is
conveying two key ideas about herself.
</P>
<P>
   First, on the rigors of the long-distance commute: ``I'm
uncomfortable with being held up as a superwoman _ it's the people
at either end of my spectrum who deserve the credit: my husband,
our deep bench of baby sitters, the Turner folks who carry the ball
for me,'' says Smith. ``The median age of Bart and me was
40-something when we married, so we're used to being on our own,
and he's very committed to his work in Baltimore. It's hard to say
how my kids will feel about it when they're older, but for now
they're easy with it. There's no confusion about who's Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   And second, on her job: ``I don't think of my work the past 10
years as being about sports so much as being about cities,'' she
declares. ``Sports are the avenue to something bigger _ this love I
have for America's cities. I'm passionate about the Philips because
it will be great for bringing street life to downtown Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Say what? Can this be the same person who masterminded the
55-by-150-foot billboard, with its electronic bulletin board of
video screen, clock, CNN logo and news ``zipper''? How does Smith
reconcile her urbanist soul with the seemingly soulless ``Big
Ted''?
</P>
<P>
   The more you talk to Smith and look at her work _ the way
``Eutaw Street,'' her food-retail-entertainment row at Camden
Yards, nuzzles comfortably between the ballpark and old warehouses
_ the more she appears sincere about her respect for urban
tradition. She says she'll continue to walk the walk, so to speak,
with Hawk Walk, a similar re-creation of a bustling city street
that she mapped out under the Philips roof.
</P>
<P>
   As Smith leads a hard-hat tour of the arena, which is nearing
completion, another surprisingly urban feature pops up: 96 private
suites filling an entire vertical wall, resembling the side of an
apartment building. The all-in-one-wall idea wasn't Smith's _ it
came from Stan Kasten, her boss _ but Smith can't stop talking
about how much she loves the innovation. It allows Hawk Walk to
come smack against the opposite wall of the arena, and the upper
deck of general seating to be low enough that, Smith says, ``the
worst seat in the house is closer to the action than it was in
Omni, even though there's 4,000 more seats: 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is simply,'' Smith says, proudly opening her arms, ``a
better place for Joe Fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Joe Fan gets a clear view of all the corporate execs and
guests lounging in their motorized chairs in their suites. In this
age of see-and-be-seen and unapologetic wealth, the audience
becomes part of the show, as in a turn-of-the-century opera house.
In this age of convergence, urban renewal means sports fans can be
converted into entertainment fans who are also eaters, drinkers and
shoppers, coaxed into a new ``downtown'' as attractive to the
cappuccino-sipping non-sports fan as the basketball purist with a
frank in his fist.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps no one understands all these connections better than
Smith, whose notion of sports facility as a multi-pleasure dome is
the wave of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a single team in the country that doesn't want
Janet's services at some point,'' says Kasten, Braves and Hawks
president and chairman of Philips Arena. ``And she works so hard
that she was practically in labor before we could get her to slow
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith herself is a kind of convergence: a blend of talents in a
job of her own invention.
</P>
<P>
   She's the daughter of a medical-records technician mother and an
architect father who ``always had a game on the radio. My dad
idolized Joe DiMaggio.'' The elder Smith stopped at unexpected
moments to walk around a new building, ``And I can still remember
sitting in that hot car thinking, `I'll never be an architect,'''
the daughter recalls with a rueful smile.
</P>
<P>
   Drive and charm
</P>
<P>
   Though she holds a master's degree in urban planning from City
College of New York and pulls down an estimated $200,000 per year,
Smith can still stretch vowels in a down-home way. She sounds like
a true good ol' girl when male execs greet her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks good, dunnit?'' she drawls, as cool as if the Philips
opening were a year away. (In fact, the first ticketed event, a
Thrashers exhibition, is Sept. 18).
</P>
<P>
   The blend of hard-headed drive and Southern charm began to
emerge in New York in the early '80s, when Amanda Burden, now a
member of the board New York City Planning Commission, hired Smith
to assist her on building Battery City Park. Burden used to arrive
at her office at 8:30 a.m to find the young Mississippian had
already been on the construction site for over an hour _ even
though she was studying for her master's degree at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Janet Marie asked a crew to pour a concrete sidewalk five
times, until they got it right,'' says Burden. ``The fact that she
looked great in 3-inch heels didn't hurt.'' ``I always knew I
didn't want to just make drawings of buildings, but I didn't know
there could be a job like I have now,'' Smith says. ``Luckily there
were those along the way who were willing to hear this long-winded,
disconnected description of what I wanted to do ... putting the
pieces together to create spaces full of energy, where people want
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   As a longtime fan of the then-hapless Braves, Smith was curious
to see the one team that was contending to lose more games in 1988:
the Baltimore Orioles. Sitting in the Birds' old Memorial Stadium,
``I got to thinking: How can I make going to a stadium a wonderful
experience even if your team loses? The newer stadiums then were
concrete shells marooned in the suburbs. When I heard the Orioles
were building their new one downtown, I said, `That's for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lucchino, then part owner of the Birds, recalls, ``The
first question that I asked Janet was, `Which league uses the
designated hitter?' and she shot back, `Are you kidding? How can
you ask a question like that!' She never did answer _ it could have
been a grand bluff! But she had so much spunk, I hired her.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucchino cites ``a million details'' in Smith's Camden Yards
triumph, including her discovery of an 1891 Orioles logo that
became a park motif.
</P>
<P>
   Cool leader or good soldier?
</P>
<P>
   Which, again, doesn't sound like the person who'd erect the
high-tech ``Big Ted.'' Could it be that Philips, which is paying
close to $200 million over 20 years for its arena sponsorship,
threw its weight around and demanded such a billboard _ and Smith
is taking the heat for her Turner bosses?
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding? Heat is my middle name!'' barks Kasten.
``Janet can be a good soldier, but that's not the case here. She
believes in that design, and she's very, very disappointed that a
few assassins in the media are presenting it unfairly.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she's teed off at the criticism, Smith takes a long
pause and says, ``I was irritated. No one took time to understand
it in context. The alternative would be for people to look at a
parking garage! I'd hoped that Turner would get credit for spending
some money it didn't have to spend, putting some street life out
there. Instead, people took an easy potshot at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to clarify what ``it'' is, Smith refuses to say
``billboard'' or ``sign'' and instead keeps repeating, ``the retail
building,'' meaning the low shedlike structure to which the
billboard is attached. This little building will be ready for shops
and an indoor-outdoor cafe by the end of the year, and will indeed
serve street life. But of course that's not what people are irked
about. For Smith to keep referring to the shed and huge sign
collectively as ``the retail building'' is like saying ``trunk''
and trying to pretend there's no elephant. By making it sound as if
the billboard critics are also against street improvements, Smith
seems like a spinmeister, and not a very deft one at that.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, the building's awning-covered entrances and
tree-studded plaza do look better in her architect's original
drawings than the somewhat misleading rendering that she supplied
the Journal-Constitution, which made the sign appear to rise out of
an empty sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who bunks in a hotel suite overlooking Centennial Park on
her Atlanta nights, sees herself as helping a bad urban situation _
with a billboard that will present event information _ not wrecking
a good one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The park is so beautiful, and there's nobody in it,'' Smith
says with a note of regret. ``We're trying to change that, letting
people know that there are all these wonderful events happening in
the park and close by.''
</P>
<P>
   She's still as cool as the polished granite floor tiles being
installed in the CNN Center. Does anything rattle Smith?
</P>
<P>
   ``I once rode in car with Joe DiMaggio,'' she says with a laugh.
``I was so overwhelmed, after the way my dad used to talk about
him, that I couldn't think of one single thing to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
