<HEADLINE>
BANK OF ENGLAND RAISES RATES IN A STEP AGAINST INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bank of England raised interest rates in the United
Kingdom &UR;  &LR; Wednesday, as the maverick nation that bowed out of a
unified Europe isolated itself further in setting a stiff course
for its monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   Following the lead of the US Federal Reserve Bank, Britain's
central bank raised a key interest rate from 5 percent to 5.25
percent, the first of what economists predicted would be a series
of rate hikes aimed at reducing the heat in an economy that has
started to boil. The surprise move, the first for the Bank of
England in more than a year, was meant to nip the threat of
inflation in the bud.
</P>
<P>
   But across the English Channel, the rest of Europe has been
extremely sluggish. There's little sentiment for higher rates
within the European Central Bank, which was established to set
monetary policy for a unified Europe. Such an action, economists
say, would stall growth just as the continent's economy showed the
first signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly true the UK has more monetary independence,''
said Nariman Behravesh, an international economist Standard &AMP;
Poor's DRI. The Bank of England's move ``is an indication of that
independence.''
</P>
<P>
   The rate hike is a reaction, he said, to strong data coming out
of the British economy, including a gangbusters housing market and
strong consumer confidence and retail sales. Also industrial
production in July grew at annual rate of nearly 4 percent.
``That's pretty strong,'' Behravesh said, explaining the Bank of
England's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, like the US Federal Reserve, is seeking to undo a
series of rate reductions prompted last year by an unraveling world
economy that bounced back more quickly than was expected.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Fed's Open Market Committee voted to cut rates
three times last fall, the Bank of England's Monetary Policy
Committee in a similar time frame reduced rates seven times to
protect an economy viewed as more vulnerable than the robust US
economy.
</P>
<P>
   But, like the United States, Britain kept going. Its annual
inflation rate is now running about 2.2 percent, and its jobless
rate, at 6 percent, is one of the lowest in Europe. Inflation on
the continent is running at a much tamer 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conditions look more threatening on the inflation front in UK
than they do anywhere else in the world, including the US,'' said
Bruce Kasman, chief international economist for J.P. Morgan in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the Bank of England has moved today, and it's
probably why you'll see more rate hikes coming from Bank of England
than from any other central bank,'' said Kasman, who recently
relocated from London.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of England in a statement to explain Wednesday's rate
increase said it had considered both the housing and labor markets
in making its decision to raise the base rate by a quarter-point.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rise in interest rates was necessary to keep inflation on
track further ahead,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   British businesses doubted the wisdom of the bank's move. ``This
decision threatens to put a still tentative recovery into
reverse,'' said Ian Peters, an official of the British Chambers of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that kind of thinking has led global economists to
predict that any rate increases by the European Central Bank may be
months away.
</P>
<P>
   If the rest of Europe follows, American investors may see their
already unimpressive returns on European mutual funds continue to
drag. And US tourists who have enjoyed a long period of extremely
weak currencies in Europe might also start paying more for hotels
and meals across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, that may be months away, economists said. Across Europe,
first-quarter growth across hasn't recovered to the levels
experienced in early 1998, before Asia's currency crises began.
Economic growth in Germany and France, the biggest economies, are
weak though production has increased. Germany's growth, based on a
sluggish second quarter, would be only 1 percent this year,
compared with modest 2 percent growth for the region overall.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a ``pattern of improvement'' in the Continent's economic
indicators, Kasman said, a rate hike by the European Central Bank
``stands a little ways away, possibly toward the end of the first
quarter of next year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
