<HEADLINE>
CONCERTS TO INTRODUCE   HUMANITARIAN WEB SITE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn; N.J., England, Switzerland)   By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three all-star pop stadium concerts on Oct. 9 _ in New Jersey,
England and Switzerland _ are to introduce Netaid.org, a Web site
that seeks to end poverty by bringing together relief organizations
with donors and volunteers. In a news conference Wednesday, Bono of
U2 described Netaid as ``the Yellow Pages of aid in cyberspace.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerts, produced by the people who assembled the Ethiopian
famine-relief benefit Live Aid in the 1980s, are to take place at
Giants Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J.; Wembley Stadium outside
London, and the Palais des Nations in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   At Giants Stadium, the performers are to include Puff Daddy,
Celine Dion, Sting, the Algerian singer Cheb Mami, Mary J. Blige,
Busta Rhymes, Jimmy Page of Led Zeppelin, Counting Crows, Jon Bon
Jovi and the Italian rock singer Zucchero. Wyclef Jean of the
Fugees and Bono are to perform a song they wrote in honor of
Netaid, ``New Day.'' Giants Stadium tickets go on sale Friday
through Ticketmaster.
</P>
<P>
   At Wembley the lineup includes David Bowie, Bryan Adams, Bush,
the Coors, George Michaels, Robbie Williams and the reunited
Eurythymics. A private concert in Geneva, where many of the relief
organizations have headquarters, is to feature Bryan Ferry, Des'ree
and the Scottish group Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Jewel and Sheryl Crow have both agreed to perform, but their
location has not been decided. The concerts are to be televised on
VH1, MTV and, in Britain, on the BBC. Radio stations will carry the
events to 60 countries, and there will be an Internet Webcast.
</P>
<P>
   The concerts are not primarily for fund-raising, although the
immediate proceeds will be dedicated to aid refugees in Kosovo and
for relief work in Africa. Donations from listeners will be
directed to the Netaid Foundation, which will distribute
contributions under the direction of the United Nations Development
Program, its antipoverty agency.
</P>
<P>
   But the main purpose of the events is to draw worldwide
attention to Netaid, a novel alliance of the United Nations,
Internet entrepreneurs and musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about a billion hits against poverty, and we want to
punch that sucker out,'' Quincy Jones, the musician and producer,
said at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Netaid will provide information and eventually direct
connections for people working on projects as diverse as
environmental problems, disaster relief or lobbying to cancel the
international debts of the 52 poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is for it to become the largest portal and directory
for antipoverty organizations in the world,'' said Bob Chlopak, a
spokesman for Netaid. After the concerts, the site will be overseen
by the U.N. Development Program.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, the networking company that has built the Web
site and donated $10 million to the Netaid Foundation, announced
that Netaid was 10 times larger than any other Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Kofi Annan, the secretary-general of the United Nations,
appeared at the news conference. By satellite, President Clinton
and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain activated the Web site in
North America and Europe. Nelson Mandela, the former president of
South Africa, also appeared by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the Internet reaches more and more communities,'' Mandela
said, ``they will gain access to new information and resources they
can use to uplift themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
