<HEADER>
A5045 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     09-08 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTAIN MAC AT THE HELM OF US DAVIS CUP TENNIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Were those seismic rumbles you may have heard
Wednesday morning the aftershock of Dwight Davis (1879-1945) doing
situps in his tomb?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Davis Cup patriarch got the word via celestial fax
that John Patrick McEnroe Jr. _ the Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde of
tennis _ has been named United States captain.
</P>
<P>
   In 1900 Davis, the epitome of gentlemanly bearing and
sportsmanship, donated the Cup that 129 countries pursued this
year, and was the initial US captain as well as a player. He could
no more have imagined McEnroe, a one-man conflagration in short
pants, as his 36th successor than, say, a contemporary, Jack the
Ripper.
</P>
<P>
   Davis sent the Cup into circulation in the hope of advancing
international good will. That has not quite been McEnroe's
strongest point, although he may have broken down the will of a
goodly number of umpires in more countries than any other man.
</P>
<P>
   However, this is 1999, and his first captaincy will be a century
up the road from Davis's, in a culture far different. Despite all
previous acts as a walking (and running) international incident,
Mac's time has surely arrived to lead the US out of a Cup mire.
Like that earlier headstrong and patriotic Mac, General Douglas
(``I shall return!'') MacArthur, he has reappeared to direct
campaigns on his old battleground, to turn around four years of
losing.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe at 40 deserves this shot. It's his to fly or flop with.
</P>
<P>
   After years of yearning for it, seven years beyond his fifth and
last Cup-lifting triumph, a doubles cameo, Mac is back on the
scene, and in charge.
</P>
<P>
   It took a longshot lady to rescue this longshot captain from a
limbo in which he chafed. Julia Levering, the lone female president
of the not particularly progressive US Tennis Association in its
119 years, made the decision to fire six-year pilot Tom Gullikson
and install McEnroe, considered too hot to handle by her male
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lady showed some guts,'' says McEnroe, and he's right.
</P>
<P>
   But boil it down to this: Gullikson couldn't persuade the
world's two best, Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi, to do singles for
him at the same time. So Gullikson actually fell in Boston two
months ago, the 4-1 quarterfinal defeat by Australia. Then, for
whatever reason, Sampras's refusal to play singles or the coolness
toward the idea of teammates Todd Martin and Jim Courier, Gully was
cooked. McEnroe would have had to wait longer if the US had beaten
Australia and gone on to the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the right time for John. He's the best person for
this. A passionate, outspoken advocate of Davis Cup,'' says
Levering, who had talked it over with the players _ a first for a
USTA boss.
</P>
<P>
   Levering may be taking a chance in believing McEnroe has matured
sufficiently to handle this sporting ambassasdor role. She's
gambling that the divinely performing but demonically behaving
Cupster has reformed enough to sit coolly in the captain's chair.
If she wins the gamble, Levering ought to consider commuting to Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe admits, ``I have a 10-15 percent dark side lurking, and
I make mistakes. But I'm working on it. I feel I can be intense,
and an ambassador, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would one of my captains, Arthur Ashe, say to me today?''
McEnroe smiles. ``Calm down.''
</P>
<P>
   Deportment aside, this is the leading question: Can McEnroe
deliver Agassi and Sampras to the lineup, thus guiding the US to
contention for two or three Cups?
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, yes. Andre's enthusiastic. ``He'll be the best captain
yet. Now all we need is to get Sampras on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete, who has said he would not play for McEnroe, is currently
noncommittal. His coy statement: ``It's something John's wanted for
a long time . . . he'll do a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe, often knocking Sampras's avoidance of the team, says,
``I just can't understand anyone who wouldn't want to play for his
country.'' Mac always did as one of the most illustrious to show up
for the USA: 12 years, five Cups; 41-8 in singles, 18-2 in doubles.
``Pete said he loved me after we won the doubles and beat
Switzerland in the 1992 final. I hope he still does. We'll talk in
person.''
</P>
<P>
   The salary is to be about $100,000, but Mac concurs with Todd
Martin's belief that the players (getting a minumum of $50,000 per
engagement) shouldn't be paid for patriotic duty. ``Maybe I'll have
to set an example by being a dollar-a-year man.'' Excellent idea.
</P>
<P>
   Hyper, very bright and imaginative, complex, erratic, insisting
he's mellowed as the father of six, McEnroe has a new baby-sitting
job here. Davis Cup captains have seldom been controversial, but
that changes now. Will he be Calamity John, shooting from the hip
and lip too often? Or Johnny Appleseed, spreading the seeds of good
cheer and wisdom?
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Davis, who served a stint as Secretary of War under
President Coolidge, might be wary of McEnroe on the international
scene. But China isn't in the World Group with his Americans, and
the US could probably handle any other war he might start.
</P>
<P>
   It will be intriguing. Fasten your seat belts. Captain Mac is
the new boy in the cockpit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
