<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WELCOME TO `KREMLINGATE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Surprise, surprise: corruption has been rampant in
the Kremlin.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Swiss investigators are finding funny money in secret bank
accounts of President Yeltsin's personal and official family
members. In the United States, the Bank of New York is being forced
to explain the laundering of billions ripped off by favored
oligarchs.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago,'' says Grigory Yavlinsky, the reformist leader
who has long been blowing an unheeded whistle on the grandest
larceny of the century, ``you could have asked any little child in
the smallest village in Siberia about this, and he would have told
you all about the criminal conspiracies. Why is it news today?
Because of your elections and ours.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Gore-Chernomyrdin Commission, with its hundreds of
junketeering bureaucrats, treated the corruption as a mere bump on
the road to a market economy. Vice President Al Gore even famously
scrawled a barnyard epithet across a CIA memo warning of the
diversion of foreign aid into the pockets of Yeltsin's clique. (Why
doesn't Al enliven his speeches with such colorful expressions?)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As 2000 approaches, the time ripens for exposure of the blind
eye Gore turned to ``Kremlingate.'' We Republicans smack our lips
here in the run-ups to our primaries, and the would-be successors
to Yeltsin rub their hands before elections to their Parliament
this December and their White House next June.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Russia's second contested national election is similar in some
ways to our own tumultuous contest in 1800, when the established
Federalists John Adams and Alexander Hamilton fell out and deals
were made in Congress to help the anti-Federalist Thomas Jefferson
squeak in.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Russian politics, three main forces are also taking shape: On
the left is the Communist Party, its members aging and dying, its
Stalinists and Agrarians splintering off. Though it holds nearly
half the Duma seats now, that could drop to below a third in
December's elections.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the sinister center is the front-running team of the old
spymaster Yevgeny Primakov and Moscow's mayor, Yuri Luzhkov. They
have the main money men and the media moguls behind them. Cozy
corruption would most likely continue in this ``Yevgeny and Yuri
Show.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the right is Yabloko, the democratic party headed by
Yavlinsky, the only reformer not to have been suckered and dumped
by Yeltsin. He's just been joined by Sergei Stepashin, also 47, one
of the revolving-door prime ministers; this cop expands the party
base by bringing along not-nutty nationalists. Yavlinsky insists
he's clean, and should help Yabloko in its goal of doubling its
strength to a fifth of the Duma seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's also an Inconsequential Right, ranging from the grumpy
economist Yegor Gaidar to the attractive young reformer Boris
Nemtsov to Yeltsin's cunning Anatoly Chubais. But this segment even
trails the sidelined Gen. Aleksandr Lebed and the wild Vladimir
Zhirinovsky.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beyond corruption, political Russians have to deal with a wild
card: the war in Dagestan. Even reformers who condemned the war in
Chechnya are calling for Russian action to repel the Islamic
fundamentalist invaders said to be helped by the terrorist
financier Osama bin Laden. Wars create unexpected heroes and
scapegoats and will affect the Russian elections. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What should America do to advance the cause of freedom in the
coming Russian elections? Should we pull our investigative punch
into Kremlingate lest ordinary Russians think we are abusing them
when their country is down ? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We should butt out of their politics. We have shown we do more
harm than good to genuine reform. At the same time, we should butt
into their predators' thievery _ following every lead to help
Russia recover funds spirited out by corrupt officials and Western
co-conspirators.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If it embarrasses President Clinton and Yeltsin, or if it means
we must wait six months for Communists to be replaced in the Duma
so that Russia can ratify our arms limitation treaty, so be it.
Both countries will be in business under new management in 18
months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yavlinsky's advice on what America should do: ``Relax. You are
still looking for partnerships with people who may be shown to be
corrupt. Please _ just relax.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
