<HEADER>
A5048 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-MICHIGAN-HNS &LR;      09-08 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MICHIGAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ Lloyd Carr would love to stand by his man. The
only problem facing the Michigan coach one game into yet another
season of high hopes and great expectations is which one?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Brady or Drew Henson? The question is as annoying as it is
incessant in and around Ann Arbor these days.
</P>
<P>
   It dominated the spring. It was all the rage in summer camp, and
it only intensified in the week leading up to the opener against
Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Even a dramatic 26-22 win over the Fighting Irish failed to
provide an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how it goes,'' Carr said as he looked ahead to this
week's game against Rice. ``I like 'em both.''
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, Carr would like one of his quarterbacks just
a little bit more. Instead, what in some ways is an ideal situation
shapes up as a weekly headache for a coach and program with a Big
Ten championship _ and perhaps more _ on the '99 agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to the Notre Dame game, Carr got
downright cranky when the talk turned to the quarterback spot, as
it often did. This week, his tone seems more resigned than
combative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most coaches like to go with one guy,'' he said. ``Sometimes
situations warrant that you do other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to let this thing play itself out. They may dictate
what I do. They probably will dictate what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady made the stronger case in Game 1. The fifth-year senior
started and finished, completing 17 of 24 passes for 197 yards and
leading the Wolverines to the game-winning touchdown in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that final drive, he played with poise like the senior that
he is,'' Carr said.
</P>
<P>
   But Henson, the highly regarded sophomore, had his moments, too.
Playing the second quarter, he completed three of eight passes for
40 yards and presided over a drive that produced a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henson showed you a little bit of why he's capable of being a
great quarterback,'' Carr said. ``He's a guy who can make a lot of
plays. He gets better every day.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching them split time for 30 minutes, Carr went with
Brady to start the third quarter, and the senior played well enough
to stay in the game. He'll get the start again Saturday when the
Owls visit The Big House, but Henson once again is scheduled for a
second-quarter audition that could lead to a longer stay.
</P>
<P>
   Intense? You bet, Brady says.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, he insists the competition between The Veteran
and The Next Great Thing has remained amicable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very good relationship,'' Brady said. ``I respect
Drew immensely. He's young, and people have such high expectations
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Not just football people, either. Henson, a third-round draft
choice of the New York Yankees, received a $2 million signing bonus
from George Steinbrenner as part of a five-year contract. If
Michigan fans envision Henson as their next All-America
quarterback, Steinbrenner sees him instead as a future All-Star
third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   For Carr, that's part of the problem. With an attractive option,
a frustrated or unhappy Henson might decide to hang up his shoulder
pads for good. Should that prove to be the case, Michigan could go
from two good alternatives to none by this time next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People try to tear this team apart, and that's not what we
need,'' Brady said. ``We're going to need Drew this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going to go on next week, and I'm not
concerned about what's going to go on next week. I'm going to go
out and prepare for Rice like I'm the starter, and Drew's going to
do the same, and (third-teamer) Jason Kapsner is going to do the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Carr and his staff try to balance the present,
the immediate future and the long term at a school where last
year's 10-3 finish is considered a near-disaster and 1997's
national co-championship is ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   Hope the matter resolves itself as painlessly as possible, Carr
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both handled a difficult situation,'' he said. ``These
guys are 21, 22 years old, and every time they turned around they'd
get questioned. They handled it all with tremendous poise and
class, and I appreciate that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd competed and performed to a point where I didn't think
it was fair to start one guy and not play the other. I could have
made one guy happy, but it wouldn't have been right not to play the
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how close it was.''
</P>
<P>
   And still is, for the moment at least.
</P>
<P>
   Round 2 comes Saturday. At Michigan Stadium, the jury of 111,000
reconvenes to continue the debate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
