<HEADER>
A5050 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY09-COX     09-08 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley brings campaign home to proud supporters in Show-Me
state
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRYSTAL CITY, Mo. _ Bill Bradley took his surging presidential
campaign to his hometown on the banks of the Mississippi River on
Wednesday, highlighting his small-town roots and storybook rise to
fame.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in front of the high school where he spent hours
playing basketball as a teen-ager, the former NBA star pledged a
new kind of presidential leadership ``that puts people front and
center, not the president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel an urgency to seize this moment in history, to
strengthen the weak and challenge the strong to lead us into our
full greatness as a nation,'' the Democrat told about 1,500 people
in front of Crystal City High School.
</P>
<P>
   If elected president, Bradley said he would reduce childhood
poverty, make health care affordable to more Americans, enact gun
control and take big money out of politics. ``We will do fewer
things, but they will be essential things, and we will do them more
thoroughly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what Bradley said was not new, and he steered clear of
offering specific proposals. But the trip home was less about
substance and more about creating a presidential image that he
hopes will capture the public's imagination and help propel him to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton had Hope, Ark. Former Sen. Bob Dole had
Russell, Kan. And former President Harry Truman, another native of
the Show-Me state and a role model of Bradley's, had Independence,
Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley clearly sees Crystal City, a town of 4,000 about 30
miles south of St. Louis, as his version of such Norman Rockwell
settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a small-town boy,'' he said. ``I had a paper route and
every day I delivered copies of the Daily News Democrat to the
doorsteps of my neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Crystal City, whose sole industry was a Pittsburgh Plate Glass
factory that closed in 1991, could indeed have been the backdrop
for the portraits of Americana that Rockwell popularized in the
1940s. Almost every house has a front porch. Leafy oak trees line
the main street, Mississippi Avenue, and residents say it's mostly
true that everybody knows everybody.
</P>
<P>
   And everybody knows of Bradley, whose basketball prowess and
subsequent election to the Senate in his adopted state of New
Jersey have become part of local folklore. Bradley, the son of the
local bank president, lived in a single-story limestone house
across the street from Grace Presbyterian Church. Both his parents
are dead, but Bradley still owns the house.
</P>
<P>
   Following his speech, Bradley escorted residents _ many of whom
had never seen Bradley before _ into the gym where he led the
Crystal City Hornets to two state championship tournaments. From
the elevation of the gym stage, childhood friends, former teachers
and coaches offered folksy testimonials to the boy they claimed
would become the nation's 43rd president.
</P>
<P>
   Hardeman Bond, Bradley's aunt and the only surviving relative
from his mother's family, said that Bradley had learned from his
mother, a school teacher, ``to move quickly ... to be a good
Samaritan ... and to be a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Long before basketball, Bill had learned how to live life on
the run,'' Bond said, alluding to Bradley's book about his 10 years
with the New York Knicks called, ``Life on the Run.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Thuesen, Bradley's second grade music teacher, declared
Bradley had the ``same twinkle in his eye, the same smile he had
when he was in second grade, 7-years-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Evans, the catcher on Bradley's little league baseball
team, described how Bradley led the team out of a St. Louis
restaurant that had refused to serve the team because Evans was
black. ``Bill made a believer out of me,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   And so it went.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign billed Wednesday's speech here as his
``campaign kickoff'' speech, even though Bradley formally announced
his candidacy in December. Since then, Bradley has managed to make
something of a contest that many predicted would be a lost cause
against the better-funded incumbent, Vice President Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, a Boston Globe poll found that Bradley was in
a statistical dead heat with Gore among likely Democratic primary
voters in New Hampshire, the nation's first primary state. A
Washington Post poll this week, however, found that Gore still
maintains a nearly three to one advantage over Bradley nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to residents, Bradley cast himself as a political
maverick who would run a different kind of campaign. ``I'm
listening to America, not to the pundits,'' he said. ``I'm hoping
that by Election Day, we will be choosing between two people we
esteem, not the candidate we can still tolerate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was warmly applauded by those gathered, many of whom had
decked their homes with signs such as, ``From Crystal City to the
White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Crystal City Mayor Grant Johnston, who called Bradley a role
model, seemed to sum up the sentiments of the town when he
introduced Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator, we have waited a long time for this day,'' Johnston
said. ``Welcome home. We are all very proud of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
