<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-THRILLER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANK PERETTI: THE FATHER OF THE CHRISTIAN THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By DEBRA LESTER   Herald-Journal, Spartanburg, S.C.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Peretti is not sure what his duties are as the father of a
literary genre, the Christian thriller.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call me the father of the genre. What does that mean?''
he asked with a laugh during a recent telephone interview from his
Pacific Northwest home.
</P>
<P>
   It may mean that Peretti, a former Pentecostal preacher, has
novels that have sold more than 8 million copies. ``The Oath,''
published in 1995, sold more than half a million hardcover copies
within the first six months of release, a phenomenon in Christian
publishing circles.
</P>
<P>
   But most likely it's because Peretti showed publishers there is
a market for Christian fiction. His new novel, ``The Visitation,''
was published in August.
</P>
<P>
   Peretti was a co-pastor with his father at an Assemblies of God
church when he had the idea to write a Christian novel. He shelved
the notion. He was having difficulties with his ministry and, in
1983, he left the pastorate, a victim of burnout.
</P>
<P>
   He went to work in a ski factory, but didn't forget his idea. He
wrote the spiritual warfare novel, ``This Present Darkness.'' It
was published in 1986 and, three years later, Peretti was able to
quit his factory job and write full time. ``Piercing the Darkness''
was published in 1989, ``Prophet'' in 1992 and ``The Oath'' in
1995. He also found time to write eight books for upper grade
school and junior high age students, ``The Cooper Kids Adventure
Series.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Visitation,'' Peretti admits, ``is somewhat
autobiographical, it's more a reflection of what's going on in my
own heart. It made the book more difficult to write. I had to write
from the heart, write what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the banjo-playing-former-Pentecostal-pastor
character Travis Jordan isn't a self-portrait of
banjo-playing-former-Pentecostal-pastor author Peretti. He insists
Jordan is drawn from his experiences and composites of people he's
known.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Visitation,'' published by Thomas Nelson, has a different
format from Peretti's other books.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a building-suspense type of story, but it's written
in the first person and more than any of the other books it depends
on the characters. More than what's going on outside, it's what's
inside the main character,'' Peretti said.
</P>
<P>
   Once again the author didn't realize he was on the cutting edge
of a mainstream trend. Speakers at a recent meeting of the Southern
chapter of Mystery Writers of America stressed character-driven
novels as the thing publishers are looking for right now.
</P>
<P>
   Peretti's earlier books met with criticism about his theology.
``I don't think about that criticism,'' he said. ``I want people to
read my books, enjoy them, then decide their own theology.''
</P>
<P>
   Peretti writes a solid five hours a day, using a kitchen timer.
If he's interrupted or takes a break, he stops the timer, then
starts it again when he resumes writing.
</P>
<P>
   He said it takes him about two years to write a major novel.
Once he recovers from his book tour he'll be working on four new
books for young readers similar to the Cooper Kids series but with
new characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be glad to quit touring and do some actual writing,''
Peretti said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
