<HEADLINE>
BOND PRICES RISE AFTER FED'S STEPS ON Y2K 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices rebounded Wednesday as traders covered
short positions after the Federal Reserve took measures to insure
that there will be enough money in the banking system to counter
any year 2000 computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   The market's tone improved and remained firm after Fed Chairman
Alan Greenspan spoke at Grand Valley State University in Michigan
but did not comment on interest rates, the economy or policy, as
had been expected. Remarks by other Fed officials Wednesday,
including Laurence Meyer, a Fed governor, in Philadelphia and
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers at the New York Economic Club
had little market effect and failed to put the market in a
defensive stance.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond rose 3/32, to 100 26/32. Its yield
was unchanged at 6.07 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the market was also aided by the announcement of a
Year 2000 program that will allow banks to use expanded forms of
collateral for repurchase transactions within 90 days, which will
add liquidity to the banking system. It eased concern that trading
Treasuries or other fixed-income paper might be difficult at the
end of the year. Some investors have had concerns the financial
markets might freeze up, causing some to postpone selling until
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's sparse economic data was virtually ignored, which
only goes to show that the market gave an inordinate amount of
attention to the Fed news, said Andy Bischel, director of investing
at Spare, Kaplan, Bischel &AMP; Associates in San Francisco. ``The Fed
is probably going to raise rates as soon as October,'' he said,
``but in the meantime the market has been in and out discounting
the increase.''
</P>
<P>
   July wholesale inventories rose 0.9 percent, another hint that
the change in business inventories during the third quarter could
add noticeably to growth in the gross domestic product, some
economists said.
</P>
<P>
   Bond market participants have begun to focus on the scheduled
release Friday of the government's report on producer prices, or
inflation at the manufacturing level, a key indicator of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   However, the economic reports scheduled for release next week
will play a much larger role in determining whether the Fed will
raise rates again at its policy-making meeting Oct. 5, said Donald
Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management. ``Market
participants will certainly pay particular attention to retail
sales, housing starts, industrial production, and capacity
utilization, but most keenly awaited of all will be the CPI, the
Fed's benchmark inflation measure.''
</P>
<P>
   A robust Consumer Price Index, coupled with retail sales data
that indicate continued momentum in consumer spending, would create
a considerable amount of consternation among Fed members and could
prompt another increase, Fine said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
