<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEXICO-CREDIT-NYT &LR;      09-08 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO IMPORTS AMERICAN-STYLE CREDIT REPORTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mexico, Ga., Ill.)   By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The usual reason given for the failure of about a
third of Mexico's bank loans since 1995 is soaring inflation.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly all loans pegged to the inflation rate, which at
times approached 100 percent, it was not long before many Mexicans
owed more in interest than they had borrowed. So many borrowers
have merely walked away.
</P>
<P>
   But many Mexican bankers now acknowledge that even without
inflation, touched off by a sharp devaluation of the peso, many of
the loans would probably have gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   A key reason was that bankers had made many of the loans with
little information about the borrowers. The kind of nationwide,
computerized credit reporting companies that have been standard in
the United States for decades simply did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   But now two of the biggest U.S. credit reporting companies, the
Trans Union Corp. of Chicago and Equifax Inc. of Atlanta, are at
work building files and computer systems in Mexico that will give
bankers here the same instantaneous credit profiles that bankers in
New York and Miami and Los Angeles take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Starting from scratch in late 1996, Trans Union, in a joint
venture with most of Mexico's banks, has compiled files on 25
million Mexican loans, representing most of the market, according
to Trans Union. Equifax says it has 8 million files and hopes to
have 20 million by this time next year.
</P>
<P>
   While Mexico's economy has been recovering nicely, thanks to a
surge in manufacturing and relatively high oil prices, its banks
are still limping along, collecting what they can on old debts and
lending very little. The few mortgages that are being issued are at
interest rates of nearly 30 percent, with credit cards charging
more than 50 percent. Small and midsize businesses are starving for
cash. Housing construction is down.
</P>
<P>
   So the government is eager to strengthen the banks. Just a few
months ago, it made the credit reporting agencies a formal part of
Mexico's financial system, for the first time mandating that
bankers check out all prospective loans through one of the
agencies. In the United States, credit reporting has been integral
to lending for decades. But, industry executives say, it is
entirely discretionary for U.S. lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to inject discipline into lending in Mexico, the
government went on to require that, in the case of a bad credit
report, a loan of say $100,000 or any other amount, could only be
made if the bank were willing to set aside an equal amount in
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   It was a blunt sanction, that Federico Castro Rosas, the general
director of BC Buro de Credito, the joint venture in which Trans
Union is the largest investor, said would surely stop any lender in
his tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Like much of the rest of Latin America as well as Africa and
parts of Asia, Mexico had gotten along for decades with very little
credit reporting. There had been a credit reporting agency in
Mexico _ at least in name _ starting in the early 1970's. But it
was never really taken seriously and was eventually done away with.
Banks and other lenders refused to share their credit information
with the agency, and what little the agency could gather was
fragmented, often outdated and considered unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very poorly managed,'' said Ernesto Gomez-Gallardo, an
executive vice president at Banamex, the country's largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   Few felt an urgent need for better credit reporting, partly
because, in Mexico as in many other developing countries, the banks
lent to a fairly small elite. The bankers either knew their
customers or worked on referrals.
</P>
<P>
   But bank lending and the credit card business in Mexico exploded
in the late 1980s and early 1990s as the banks were reprivatized
after a decade of state control. Bankers who had paid high prices
to get into the business were eager to put their money to work and
began lending to almost anyone.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, one banker said, ``you just didn't check people's
credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were questions on the application form,'' the banker
said, ``but the customer could lie and tell you he hadn't had any
problems. And you would never know. The credit bureau wouldn't have
the information.''
</P>
<P>
   After the value of the peso was cut in half in late 1994,
inflation soared, and the banks and the government recognized that
big changes had to be made.
</P>
<P>
   As one measure, the Mexican Association of Bankers deputized the
five largest banks to begin negotiations with Trans Union, Equifax
and the other industry giant in the United States, Experian Corp.
Trans Union won the contest and three years ago began issuing
credit reports as part of the joint venture with the banks. Equifax
says it withdrew from contention and decided to go it alone before
the banking association announced its choice. Experian is not doing
business in Mexico. While Equifax has a few bank customers in
Mexico, its greatest following so far has been among retailers. But
it has its eyes on a stronger position with the banks. Equifax, the
only one of the three companies that is publicly traded in the
United States, had revenues in 1998 of $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexicans are interested in competition,'' said Bill
Phinney, a senior executive for Equifax in Latin America. ``They
want more than one player in their markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Both U.S. companies have brought in sophisticated computer
systems that blend information from several sources and, in
seconds, produce reports on a person's debt history, the types and
amounts of loans, the timeliness of payments and any defaults or
repossessions. The companies charge corporations a negotiated fee
for each report. For individuals in the United States, the fee is
$8, except in a handful of states where one report a year will be
provided for free.
</P>
<P>
   For both Trans Union and Equifax, the move into Mexico was part
of a plan to expand from the saturated U.S. credit reporting market
into Latin America and other parts of the world. ``We see very good
growth potential in Mexico,'' said Phinney of Equifax.
</P>
<P>
   Lending has become a much more cautious and restrictive business
in Mexico. The bankers say, it is a tough adjustment for many
customers. ``This is a big shock to Mexican culture,'' said
Gomez-Gallardo. ``If you have a bad loan or a default, you won't be
getting credit. That is something new.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, when one lender did not know what the other was
doing, he said, ``People didn't pay and nothing happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
