<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MAKING KIDS SAFER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When kids pull out their guns at school and open fire on
classmates and teachers, it tends to get our attention. Which is
why school safety has trumped academic quality as the top concern
of parents whose children are returning to school this month.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and school board members are clamoring for metal
detectors, armed guards, see-through knapsacks, whatever it takes.
Some of the wackos at the National Rifle Association want to arm
teachers and administrators. Kids are being thrown out of school
for trafficking in violent fantasies and _ in the case of a second
grader in Maryland _ making a gun out of construction paper.
</P>
<P>
   Please, a little perspective.
</P>
<P>
   James Alan Fox, a professor of criminal justice at Northeastern
University, reminds us that despite the tragedies in Littleton and
Jonesboro, the public schools are just about the safest places
available for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the school shootings for last year and the year
before, there were about four dozen homicides a year,'' he said.
``When you consider that there are about 50 million schoolchildren,
the chance that your child will get killed in school is literally
one in a million.''
</P>
<P>
   His point was not that we should be unmoved by the four dozen
homicides that occur annually at schools, but that we should be
taking steps to cut down on the violence that threatens youngsters
wherever they might be. And the most effective way to do that,
according to Fox and a sensible group in Washington called Fight
Crime: Invest in Kids, is to look beyond the quick fixes (metal
detectors and the like) to those difficult, long-term preventive
efforts that can bring about wholesale reductions in the amount of
youth crime and violence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to saving lives, you can enrich the environment of
enormous numbers of children by investing in early childhood
education programs like Head Start, by providing after-school
programs that give children and teen-agers something valuable to do
during the peak crime hours for juveniles (2 p.m. to 7 p.m.), and
by offering parenting programs and other assistance to young
mothers and fathers whose children are at high risk for getting
into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Fight Crime: Invest in Kids is a group of 550 law enforcement
officers and crime victims. Many of its members are fiscally
conservative, but the group is committed to public investment in
crime prevention programs that have been shown to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 40 kids being killed a week, 98 percent of them
outside of schools,'' said the group's president, Sanford Newman.
``We know how to dramatically reduce that violence.''
</P>
<P>
   After-school programs are among the easiest and most effective
crime prevention efforts. As Fox put it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring back the `frills' in school _ violins rather than
violence. In the wake of various taxpayer revolts, many of the
extracurricular options _ band, chorus, drama, various sports,
computer clubs, etc. _ were eliminated in a return to the basics.
This has made school increasingly distasteful and unpleasant for
those kids who fail to excel in academics, but could feel good
about their achievements in other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Some school districts have restored after-school programs in
recent years but have undermined their effectiveness by placing
them off limits to the kids who need them most. In some cases
youngsters who do not maintain a C average are barred from
extracurricular activities. Or kids whose parents cannot provide
transportation at the end of the extended school day are excluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done,'' said Fox, ``is made after-school programs a
privilege for the good kids as opposed to a necessity for the
marginal kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Fight Crime: Invest in Kids sponsored a poll in which 47 percent
of respondents said their chief concern as kids headed back to
school was the problem of crime and violence. Nineteen percent
cited academic issues as their top concern.
</P>
<P>
   Both Newman and Fox said the concern over school violence
presented an opportunity to generate support for programs that
target violence in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can understand the anxiety over violence in the schools,''
said Fox. ``What we should do is build upon that anxiety to do some
really meaningful things for children.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
