<HEADER>
A5062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-HERMAN-INQUIRY-NYT &LR;      09-08 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERMAN-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TESTIFIES AT INQUIRY INTO ALLEGED ILLEGAL SOLICITATION OF
FUNDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Cameroon)   By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton testified for an hour Wednesday
in the independent counsel investigation of allegations that Labor
Secretary Alexis M. Herman illegally solicited campaign
contributions for Clinton's 1996 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel, Ralph I. Lancaster, interviewed Clinton
under oath at the White House Wednesday morning as part of an
ongoing investigation into accusations of campaign finance
violations and influence peddling by Ms. Herman.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was represented by his chief private attorneys, David E.
Kendall and Nicole Seligman, as well as three lawyers from the
White House counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster was joined by two lawyers from his office, David Barry
and John T. Kotelly. Kotelly last year represented Larry Cockell,
the lead agent in Clinton's Secret Service detail, during his
appearance before the federal grand jury investigating the Monica
Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   The White House would give no details of the president's
testimony and Kendall declined to comment. Calls to Lancaster's
office were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer involved in the case said that Clinton was interviewed
as a witness and was neither a subject nor a target of the
investigation. The lawyer said that the interview of the president
suggested that Lancaster was moving toward a conclusion of his
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interview lasted one hour and was conducted under oath,''
the White House said in a terse statement. ``Consistent with prior
practice, no further statement about the interview will be made.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of Ms. Herman has been virtually invisible
since Lancaster was named in May, 1998, as the fifth independent
counsel to investigate allegations against the president and senior
members of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   W. Neil Eggleston, Ms. Herman's attorney, said that contact with
Lancaster's office has been sporadic over the past year and that
inquiry has required little of his time and virtually none of the
labor secretary's.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said last year when she approved the
appointment of an independent counsel that she had found no
evidence clearly demonstrating wrongdoing on Ms. Herman's part. But
she said the allegations and the law compelled her to initiate the
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation arises from accusations from Laurent Yene, a
businessman from Cameroon, that Ms. Herman took cash kickbacks from
a client of his seeking a federal license for a satellite telephone
system.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster is also looking into allegations that Ms. Herman used
her position as White House director of public liaison in Clinton's
first term to illegally solicit campaign contributions from clients
of the consulting firm she ran before joining the administration in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herman was appointed secretary of labor in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of Ms. Herman is the last to pose a threat to
a member of Clinton's cabinet. Henry G. Cisneros, the former
housing secretary, pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor count of lying
to federal investigators on Wednesday and agreed to pay a small
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Espy, Clinton's former agriculture secretary, was acquitted
on bribery charges. The investigation of Bruce Babbitt, the
interior secretary, is winding down and the independent counsel
inquiry into former commerce secretary Ronald H. Brown ended when
Brown was killed in a plane crash in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth W. Starr, the independent counsel who investigated the
Lewinsky matter and business dealings of Clinton collectively known
as Whitewater, chose not to seek indictments of Clinton or Hillary
Rodham Clinton. Staff members are preparing a final report for
Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
