<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-U.N.(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNAN ORDERS, THEN POSTPONES, EVACUATION OF U.N. MISSION IN EAST
TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the Security
Council walked up to the brink of confrontation with Indonesia on
Wednesday, then backed away when President B.J. Habibie and his
army chief, Gen. Wiranto, begged for more time to put East Timor in
order.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday, after violence in the territory showed little
sign of abating despite two days of martial law, Annan decided to
evacuate the U.N. mission in East Timor _ several hundred foreign
and local employees and their families. He also asked officials at
the United Nations in New York to begin contingency planning for an
outside military force for the territory, a step the Indonesians
have rejected repeatedly in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot stand by and allow the people of East Timor to be
killed,'' a visibly drawn Annan said Wednesday morning after a
night of telephone conversations with world leaders, including two
with Habibie.
</P>
<P>
   But a few hours later, the Security Council was told that plans
for evacuating the United Nations' East Timor mission had been
suspended, to be reviewed in 24 hours. An official at the United
Nations in New York said that Wiranto had told Annan's top
political adviser that he needed another day to negotiate with
military chiefs in the territory _ an admission that he could not
insure even the safety of a U.N. withdrawal, or what would happen
after the mission left.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Security Council, meeting in private,
rejected a strong plea from Portugal to hold a formal, open Council
debate on the issue Wednesday, which would have forced the 15
member nations to state their positions in the face of the crisis.
Portugal, which is not a Council member, could not call the open
meeting, only request it.
</P>
<P>
   Peter van Walsum, the Dutch representative and this month's
Council president, said there was no consensus among members for
such a meeting. The Council, he said, preferred to wait until a
five-member mission that it sent to Indonesia on Monday had a
chance to meet Habibie and possibly Wiranto on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto, who replaced his commander in East Timor on Wednesday,
has very little control in the territory, said John Bresnan, an
expert on Indonesia at Columbia University's East Asian Institute,
who recently returned from Indonesia. In East Timor, he said,
officers connected to the former chief of Indonesia's most powerful
commando unit, Lt. Gen. Prabowo _ a son-in-law of Indonesia's
deposed president, Suharto _ have almost all the local power in
their hands, and they could defy Jakarta's efforts to end the
violence for essentially political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and officials at the United Nations in New York, like
Bresnan and other academic experts, said the East Timor crisis has
hit Indonesia at its most vulnerable political moment in decades.
There will inevitably be political fallout, they say, but they add
that no one can predict what it will be.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Monteiro, Portugal's representative at the United
Nations, said Wednesday that an acute awareness of this unstable
political situation plays a significant role in the thinking at the
United Nations during these tense days. ``There is a real crisis of
leadership in the country,'' said Bresnan, a former Ford Foundation
director in Jakarta and author of ``Managing Indonesia'' (Columbia
University Press). ``Nobody is really in charge very much. All the
institutions are down, including the army. They are divided by
factions, personalized factions. So you have people acting as
individuals, dealing with other individuals, and no institutions
functioning at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``People speak of the government,'' he said. ``There is no
single government. ``Habibie is still trying to get elected. He
needs the army's votes to get elected. He has to be very cautious
of General Wiranto. General Wiranto is very cautious because he is
also a survivor of the Suharto regime, like Habibie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to be primarily concerned with preserving what unity he
can within the army itself,'' Bresnan said. ``That is his top
priority, not what the IMF does, not what the Security Council
does.'' This partially explains why Indonesia seems to care so
little about public opinion as militias roam East Timor,
vandalizing towns and driving frightened people into exile, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people in Indonesia don't care about East Timor,'' he
added. It is a very small part of a large nation trying to deal
with a political revolution and economic collapse.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the Security Council, there is growing support for
international intervention, with China and Russia joining in
condemning the violence and asking for action. China's deputy
representative, Shen Guofeng, told reporters that his government
believed that the situation in East Timor was out of control. But
China later succeeded in toning down a sense of threat in the
Security Council statement that followed. However, all governments
continue to insist that Indonesia be given every possible chance to
reassert control.
</P>
<P>
   This poses a dilemma for the United Nations, which fears for the
safety of not only its own officials and local employees in East
Timor but also the 2,000 East Timorese who fled to the U.N.
compound in the capital, Dili, for protection. Annan said Wednesday
morning that their fate was also on his mind as he decided what to
do. Wednesday, officials were calling for volunteers to stay behind
if an evacuation was necessary.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The U.N. mission in East Timor had been expected to remain well
into next year, by then bolstered with peacekeeping troops, to ease
the region's transition to independence. Officials have considered
asking Indonesia to move to that phase now, allowing international
troops into the territory without admitting a loss of control. But
government leaders seem insistent that this phase must wait until
after the newly elected Indonesian Parliament assembles in November
and chooses a president.
</P>
<P>
   Those steps, too, are surrounded by uncertainty now. Officials
here are watching the statements of Megawati Sukarnoputri, the
Indonesian opposition leader whose party finished first, but
without a clear majority, in national legislative elections. In the
past, she has opposed letting East Timor go, echoing the strong
nationalism of her father, Sukarno, who as Indonesia's first
president attacked and bombed rebels in Sumatra and Sulawesi when
they tried to secede.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mrs. Megawati has since changed her approach slightly,
saying Sunday that she is sorry about what the East Timorese are
going through at the hands of Habibie, she may be more acceptable
to the military than he is. Then, some diplomats ask, would the
entire East Timor agreement be in jeopardy?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
