   SUMMERS-TREASURY In his two months as treasury secretary,
Lawrence H. Summers has tried to leave no daylight between his
policies and those of his predecessor, Robert E. Rubin. Given that
Rubin's approach was judged stellar both on Wall Street and in
Washington it seems a logical approach. The question now, though,
is whether an evolving economic situation and intensifying
political pressures will allow Summers the luxury of leaving policy
on autopilot. By Richard W. Stevenson.
