<P>
   VANKAMPEN-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Wednesday, the Securities and
Exchange Commission censured and levied a $100,000 fine against Van
Kampen Investment Advisory Corp., the nation's 16th-largest mutual
fund group, for marketing the growth fund's hot track record
without disclosing how those advertised returns were actually
obtained. In the first case of its kind, the SEC said Van Kampen
improperly failed to disclose to investors that the fund's
spectacular 1996 return of 62 percent was highly unlikely to be
repeated. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Another giant airline is changing
agencies. Delta Air Lines in Atlanta ended a two-month review late
Wednesday by dismissing its agency of two-and-a-half years, Saatchi
&AMP; Saatchi in New York, and shifting its worldwide account to Leo
Burnett Co. in Chicago. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Grab it. So say many economists,
referring to the bold trade deal that China offered the United
States in April and President Clinton rejected in what many deem a
serious foreign policy blunder. China wants to enter the World
Trade Organization in time for the group's next meeting in Seattle
in November. But before China can join, it needs the approval of
Clinton and Congress. So it offered huge ``concessions'' on nearly
every front. Clinton can reverse course when he meets President
Jiang Zemin on Sunday in Australia. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
