<HEADLINE>
LOTT CALLS FOR RENO RESIGNATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republican leader Trent Lott said Wednesday
that he doubts the FBI's claim that it did not ignite the fire that
killed more than 80 Branch Davidians in the 1993 showdown in Waco,
Texas, and said Attorney General Janet Reno should resign.
</P>
<P>
   If ``these fires were caused and it should have been known they
were going to be caused, that is very bad,'' said Lott. ``There's
doubts because of the questions that have been raised.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno is set to announce Friday that former senator John
Danforth, a Republican, will head an independent inquiry into the
federal government's actions at Waco. Danforth has accepted the
responsibility and, barring any eleventh-hour glitches, is
scheduled to join the attorney general at the news conference,
government sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's counterpart, Senate Democratic leader Thomas Daschle of
South Dakota, called Lott's suggestion ``irresponsible'' and
defended Reno and FBI Director Louis Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about politics, once again, overriding the real,
honest, objective fact-gathering,'' said Daschle. ``Before we
comment publicly on any actions taken by federal officials, we
ought to know what the real facts are, and it's premature at this
point to come to any conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange between the two Senate leaders came as Congress
returned from its summer break and considered news reports that the
FBI had used two military-style tear gas canisters in the early
morning of April 19, 1993. Four hours later, the Branch Davidians'
wooden compound erupted in flames.
</P>
<P>
   The tear gas canisters, under certain circumstances, had
flammable properties. The FBI said the rounds were fired at a
concrete bunker away from the main compound, as videotapes released
last week confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said last week she has no intention of resigning over the
Waco matter. Congressional leaders are considering the format and
scope of their planned probe into the Waco affair.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, 63, is a former senator from Missouri and an
Episcopalian priest, with a reputation for probity and
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said Congress should go ahead with its own investigation of
the Waco matter. He asked Wednesday why the FBI's disclosure of the
two tear gas canisters came six years after the fiery showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Lott cited other run-ins that the Republican Congress has had
with Reno, over matters like the 1997 campaign finance probe, and
said, ``All of that leads me to conclude that the attorney general
should resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous investigations, including those conducted by
Republican-controlled congressional committees, have concluded that
the Branch Davidians started the fire themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said Reno ``has done an extraordinary job under very,
very difficult circumstances. . . . Under no cirumstances do I
believe the attorney general should resign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
