<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5072 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-2000-HNS &LR;      09-08 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY OFFICIALLY ENTERS PRESIDENTIAL RACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRYSTAL CITY, Mo. _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley officially offered
himself as the Democratic Party's fresh option for president
Wednesday by saying the nation has failed to convert the soaring
economy into better living for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shouldn't we be fixing our roof while the sun is shining in?''
he said in a speech delivered to a hometown crowd from the front
steps of the Mississippi River hamlet's only high school.
</P>
<P>
   It was a criticism by inference of the nation's performance
under President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore. Bradley is
Gore's sole challenger for the 2000 Democratic presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley presented his fix-up plan: Expand health care and gun
control, speak out against racial prejudice, do more to relieve
child poverty and ``mute the voice of big money in our elections.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do these things we will be safer, healthier and more in
control of our future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old red brick school, built four years before
Bradley's birth, was decorated in patriotic bunting in one of the
day's many small-town, heartland touches.
</P>
<P>
   At this school, Bradley launched a basketball career that led to
a 10-year stint with the New York Knicks. He parlayed sports
stardom into an 18-year stretch as a U.S. senator from New Jersey,
ending in 1996 when he declined to seek re-election and declared
that the American political system was seriously flawed.
</P>
<P>
   As if addressing his own kiss-off from three years ago, Bradley
said Wednesday that voters have a right to be skeptical about
politics and the influence of campaign contributions from special
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have a right to try to change that skepticism,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while Bradley loaded his campaign kick-off speech with
biographical details and policy matters, the biggest applause from
his audience of about 2,500 rewarded his assertion that, in his
low-key and brainy way, he is different from the average
politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we need a new kind of leadership,'' he said. ``A
leadership that puts the people front and center _ not the
president . ... a leadership that respects the people as well as
challenges them.''
</P>
<P>
   Vague as it was, the statement underscored some of Bradley's
perceived political advantages in his underdog race against Gore.
In contrast with the vice president, Bradley has no connections to
Clinton's personal scandals or to the campaign fund-raising
scandals that have shadowed Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts say the scandals and so-called Clinton fatigue
partly explain why Gore has been unable to blaze a clear path to
his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore posts substantial leads over Bradley in national surveys of
Democratic voters, but a recent Boston Globe poll put the two in a
statistical tie in New Hampshire, site of the first primary
election early next year. Another independent poll of New Hampshire
voters showed Bradley in a tie with Gov. George W. Bush, the
leading Republican candidate, in a hypothetical general election.
The same poll showed Gore would trail Bush in such a match-up.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's event Wednesday was a close copy of Gore's June
announcement in scene and culture. Gore declared his candidacy in
front of the red brick courthouse in Carthage, Tenn., surrounded by
old friends in the town where he spent summers as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   Even though both candidates are known for inducing naps during
their speeches, the addresses were as different as Missouri and
Tennessee. Unlike Gore, Bradley did not use his speech to praise
Clinton, jab at Republicans, showcase education policies, propose
detailed new programs or warn about the threat of foreign
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that by Election Day we will be choosing between
two people we esteem, not the candidate we can still tolerate,''
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his ``different kind of presidential campaign'' included
raising money from ordinary people rather than political action
committees of special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   But an analysis by the nonpartisan Center for Responsive
Politics of the $11.7 million Bradley raised through mid-year shows
that his leading contributors are lawyers and investment bankers.
All but 3 percent of his contributions were of the larger kind,
between $200 and the limit of $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has raised $19.5 million in a similar pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has staked out a few policy differences from Gore. He
said, for instance, that all handguns should be registered onto a
national list and that the Democratic Party should ban ``soft
money,'' or unlimited contributions to the party that can be used
on behalf of candidates. Bradley also opposed the welfare reform
bill championed by Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is expected to unveil a health-care plan later this
month that expands the federal role in providing health insurance
to millions of uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps mindful of the impression that he is more liberal
than Gore, Bradley said Wednesday that the government ``cannot be
all things to all people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in self-reliance and I think initiative deserves its
reward,'' said Bradley, who grew up in a Republican household as
the son of the town's banker. ``But I also know that disaster can
strike any of us, and when it does, it's important to know that
someone's there to help.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Crystal City High School was built by the federal
Works Project Administration, which helped create jobs after the
Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Racial unity has been one of Bradley's themes since he went into
politics after playing as a white man on a mostly black
professional basketball team. He returned to the theme Wednesday by
recalling that his Crystal City Little League team walked out of a
Missouri restaurant that refused to serve the team's black catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racism disturbed me then, and still angers me now. For me the
only thing deserving of hate is hate itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he provided no details about using the thought as the basis
for government action.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, his almost exclusively white audience
adjourned to a reception in the gymnasium where Bradley became
famous as a methodical, hard-practicing basketball player. There, a
black named Eddi Evans praised Bradley as a leader for racial
equality ever since they played baseball together as children.
Evans joined Bradley's second-grade music teacher, his aunt and
others in providing testimonials about the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, Bradley took reporters on a tour of his
childhood home, church and other haunts.
</P>
<P>
   He has spent most of his campaign shunning TV appearances and
has declined to answer questions about his personal thoughts and
personal history. In his 1996 book ``Time Present, Time Past,'' he
used a chapter to upbraid the press for digging into candidates'
backgrounds, stating that ``the information gleaned from snippets
of biography ... cannot provide an adequate psychological profile,
much less determine that someone is unfit for office.''
</P>
<P>
