<HEADLINE>
COLLONS BACK IN PATRIOTS LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Defensive end Ferric Collons, who was let go
by the Patriots after last season, is back in the New England fold
after signing a one-year deal Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Collons, who had played parts of four seasons
with the Patriots, had his contract terminated after last season
when the Patriots decided against paying his $2 million salary for
1999. The team felt that was too much money for a part-time player
and elected to let him become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Collons signed with the Oakland Raiders but was among the team's
final cuts last weekend. Collons, who lives in the Bay Area where
his wife works as a physician, wanted to return to New England
rather than an unfamiliar situation. Collons signed for the veteran
minimum of $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Collons started 11 of the 14 games he played in last season and
had 25 tackles. He always has been considered a good run stopper.
</P>
<P>
   Collons's agent, Angelo Wright, said Collons was in shape and
would be able to fit right back into the Patriots' defensive
scheme. The Patriots had signed veteran Bob Kuberski to add
interior depth on the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Collons, who stands 6 feet 7 inches and weighs 300 pounds,
attended defensive meetings Wednesday and will undergo a physical
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A few Patriots players recommended to the coaching staff and to
the front office that Collons be resigned. Chad Eaton, who was
clearing out a adjacent locker for Collons Wednesday, was one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great news,'' said Eaton. ``Ferric is a professional who
understands our defense. He's going to make quite a difference to
our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Collons has had several lives as a Patriot. After the 1997
season, Collons was signed to an offer sheet by the Philadelphia
Eagles as a restricted free agent. The Patriots kept Collons by
matching the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will have to cut a player from their 53-man roster
to accommodate Collons. Veteran Sterling Palmer, out of football
the last two seasons, could be axed.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had been working with about $800,000 of available
cap room prior to signing Collons, but about $350,000 is allocated
toward the five players who were signed to the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   The team also signed supplemental draft pick J'Juan Cherry. He
was also on hand Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
