<HEADER>
A5074 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-1STLD     09-08 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-$ADV12 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD WAR II, SEMINAL EVENT OF THE CENTURY, TAUGHT A VITAL LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
 (For release
Sunday,-HNS  
 &HT;    Sept. 12)   (EDs: CHANGES democracies in lede to democracy.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the evil forces of fascism swept through one
European country after another in 1940, a young John F. Kennedy
contemplated the weakness of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it competes with a system of government which cares
nothing for permanency, a system built primarily for war,
democracy, which is built primarily for peace, is at a
disadvantage,'' Kennedy wrote in a book extrapolated from his
Harvard honors thesis.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, ``Why England Slept,'' he sought to explain why a
great democracy, with an empire stretching around the globe, buried
its head, ostrich-fashion, while Germany's Adolf Hitler and his
fellow malefactor, Italian dictator Benito Mussolini, gobbled up
other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Little did Kennedy, then just 23 years old, realize that one day
he would be president of the United States and have to cope with
democracy's weaknesses as he confronted a belligerent,
nuclear-armed Soviet Union in Cuba, Berlin and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   As a student and the son of Ambassador Joseph P. Kennedy, who
was emerging as a pillar of American isolationism, he had lived
briefly in England. But his views were at odds with those of his
father.
</P>
<P>
   John Kennedy recognized the need for America to play a major
role in Europe once the war was over and to maintain an ``armed
guard that will wake up when the fire first starts or, better yet,
one that will not permit a fire to start at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the young student had some question about the
survivability of democracy. He therefore admonished Americans to
``profit by the lesson of England and make our democracy work.''
</P>
<P>
   While any system of government will work when ``everything is
going well,'' he noted, ``it's the system that functions in the
clinches that survives.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, he was prescient. He had no idea how long the
war would last, whether England could survive the nightly air
assault of German bombers or that the United States eventually
would be drawn into the conflict. He did, however, recognize that
the world was undergoing a monumental transition that would change
life as he and millions of others had known it.
</P>
<P>
   An old way of life was yielding to a new, as yet uncharted, way
of life.
</P>
<P>
   In a century that has witnessed great achievements and
horrendous tragedies, no event has had a more far-reaching impact
on the world than the war that began 60 years ago this month.
</P>
<P>
   As dawn broke over Poland on Sept. 1, 1939, German tanks and
troops blasted their way across its borders, and German planes
peppered the landscape with bombs.
</P>
<P>
   England and France, which until then had appeased Hitler,
decided they no longer could slumber in silence while the vicious
dictator conquered lands occupied by peaceful peoples.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler, after he had subdued much of Czechoslovakia in 1938,
told British Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain and French Premier
Edouard Daladier that that was ``the last territorial claim I have
to make in Europe.'' But he lied. One year later, when he invaded
Poland, England and France declared war on Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months after that, Mussolini, who had subdued Ethiopia and
was about to invade Greece and British Somaliland, declared war on
England and France.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, imperial Japan had invaded Manchuria and was seeking
to control China. The Soviet Union moved its troops into eastern
Poland while Germany took control of western Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the war raged across Europe and North Africa. It eventually
spread around most of the globe, ushered in the Atomic Age and set
the stage for a 40-year Cold War that ultimately would end with the
downfall of communism and the rise of the United States as the
world's single super power.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1941 Japanese attack on America's fleet at Pearl
Harbor, the deadly conflict engaged the United States and enveloped
large sections of Asia and the islands of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier, especially when the war began in 1939 and even when
Pearl Harbor was bombed, America was deeply divided between
isolationists and interventionists. Had it not been for Franklin D.
Roosevelt's leadership in providing arms to England and other
allies, including the Soviet Union, and in building America's own
arsenal, the United States, like England, would have been asleep
when Japan propelled it into war.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, its men went off to war, its women went into war
production plants, and Americans as a whole proved they had the
character and courage to face any adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Lives of people everywhere have been changed in the 20th century
by the automobile, the airplane, radio, television, computers,
atomic power, dramatic breakthroughs in medical research, motion
pictures and other great discoveries and inventions.
</P>
<P>
   But World War II was the seminal event of a century crowded with
momentous happenings.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 20, 1945, less than three months before his death,
Roosevelt defined one of the most enduring lessons of World War II.
Taking the presidential oath for the fourth time, the ailing FDR
declared: ``We have learned that we cannot live alone, at peace;
that our own well-being is dependent on the well-being of other
nations far away. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We have learned to be citizens of the world, members of the
human community. We have learned the simple truth, as Emerson said,
that `the only way to have a friend is to be one.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Americans have learned that lesson. But fortunately
every president, Democrat or Republican, since FDR has understood
that America cannot survive as an island isolated from the rest of
the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
