<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5076 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TIMOR-OBSERVER-BOS &LR;      09-08 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-OBSERVER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSERVER RECOUNTS EAST TIMOR TERROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Burning houses. Predatory militiamen. Refugees so
terrified that they flung themselves over razor wire in a frenzied
attempt to reach safety. These and scores of other images from a
month of living dangerously in East Timor crowded in on Michael
Bhatia Wednesday as he rested at his parents' home in Medway.
</P>
<P>
   Bhatia, 23, who graduated from Brown University this year with a
degree in international relations and nw is a researcher at Brown's
Watson Institute for International Studies, was one of 600
foreigners monitoring, under United Nations auspices, last week's
referendum on the future of the tormented Indonesian territory. He
arrived home around midday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was smoke, burning . . . gunfire everyhere,'' he said.
As panicky civilians realized events were spinning out of control,
their pell-mell flight from East Timor by any means possible was
``like those pictures of the fall of Saigon.''
</P>
<P>
   Bhatia said the referendum in favor of East Timorese
independence, ``was clean, a free and fair election.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were signs from well before the voting began that
Indonesian police and armed forces personnel were on friendly terms
with the militias, who turned murderous after the vote went against
them. On Aug. 17, when Indonesian forces paraded through Dili, the
East Timorses capital, in celebration of Indonesian independence,
militiamen were close by them, forcibly affixing pro-autonomy
stickers to civilian vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, referendum day and the days immediately following
were calm, and full of hope that the situation would be peacefully
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was such joy in people's faces,'' Bhatia said, recalling
two old men who walked into a voting place confused, figured it
out, and emerged, smiling broadly, to hug and shake hands with
foreign observers. ``There was so much faith in the international
community,'' he said, ``and a sense that finally their hour had
arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian police did a good job of maintaining order during the
balloting, Bhatia said, and ``you could sense their indecision,
their sense that the tide was turning on them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions rose steadily during the days while the ballots were
being counted, and attacks on independence advocates and their
homes gradually increased.
</P>
<P>
   After the UN announcement last Friday of the overwhelming vote
in favor of independence, attacks by the militias swiftly
intensified, and the heavily armed Indonesian police and armed
forces did nothing to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Mahkota, where the announcement was made and where
many foreign media and observers were lodged, came under heavy
attack, and thousands of people sought refuge in the bishop's
residence, the International Committee of the Red Cross compound, a
Silesian nunnery, and a school near the UN compounds, and other
religious sites and schools. Bhatia was in a nunnery, then moved to
a UN compound.
</P>
<P>
   ``The militias had complete control of the streets, and the
(Indonesian) soldiers were applauding them,'' Bhatia said. ``It was
clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Around 10 Sunday night the compound came under massive fire, and
people in a neighboring refugee camp panicked. ``Terrified refugees
were climbing over razor wire to get in'' to the compound, Bhatia
said. ``They were screaming, crying, pushing down the gates.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, he and a colleague from Brown rode to the
airport in a UN convoy and began the long flight home. ``God only
knows what happened to the rest of the people in those areas of
asylum,'' he said Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
