<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-WACO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANFORTH ACCEPTS JOB TO HEAD WACO PROBE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
and STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Sen. John Danforth agreed Wednesday to lead
an independent investigation into the government's final assault on
the Branch Davidian compound and information the FBI withheld about
the attack for six years, government officials said late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, a Missouri Republican, earlier had responded favorably
to Reno's request that he lead a team of investigators and early
Wednesday finalized negotiations with her deputies about the scope
of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Reno plans to announce Danforth's appointment at a news
conference scheduled early Thursday, according to officials who
spoke only on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, who retired from the Senate in 1995, was unavailable
for comment. His law office in St. Louis declined to discuss his
immediate plans.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, 63, was state attorney general of Missouri from 1968
until he was elected to the Senate in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The Danforth-Reno agreement was reached as Republican members of
Congress stepped up pressure on the attorney general to appoint an
independent investigator with broad authority to examine the Waco
case and alleged cover-up by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau recently disclosed information _ which had been
withheld for six years _ that conflicts with sworn testimony by
Reno and FBI officials about the April 19, 1993, assault in which
more than 80 people died.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., joined
the chorus of Republicans calling for Reno to resign, saying he now
has doubts about who started the fire that ended the siege near
Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general is ``apparently not getting to the truth
and not supervising adequately what happened,'' Lott said. ``The
combination of a series of events puts her in jeopardy in ... her
ability to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said his doubts about the origins of the fatal fire stem
from revelations that the FBI may have fired incendiary devices at
the Branch Davidian compound.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and FBI Director Louis Freeh, while acknowledging that
potentially flammable tear gas canisters were used, continue to
maintain that the fire was started by members of the Branch
Davidian religious sect.
</P>
<P>
   Lott was skeptical. ``There are doubts because questions have
been raised,'' Lott told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping to Reno's defense was Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D. He said Reno ``deserves commendation rather than
criticism,'' and that ``under no circumstances'' should she resign.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, an Illinois Republican who chairs the House
Judiciary Committee, called Danforth's appointment ``an important
first step to getting the truth'' about the FBI's final assault on
the Branch Davidian compound and warned Reno not to limit the
inquiry's range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Danforth must be afforded total independence and given
the necessary latitude so that his investigation will be
comprehensive and can earn the full confidence and support of the
public and Congress,'' said Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Danforth's investigation is truly independent, Hyde said
he will seek creation of a five-member, bipartisan commission to
examine the Waco incident and the FBI's withholding of information
from Congress and the federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six years has been too long to wait for the truth,'' Hyde
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., whose House Government Reform and
Oversight Committee has begun subpoenaing witnesses as part of an
inquiry into the Waco case, endorsed Reno's selection of Danforth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing but the highest regard for Mr. Danforth and
believe he is an excellent candidate to run the investigation,''
Burton said. ``We would be happy to work with Mr. Danforth, but his
appointment won't alter or change our investigation into what
happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, an ordained Episcopal priest, has been associated with
the St. Louis law firm Bryan Cave since leaving the Senate. He is
an heir to the Ralston-Purina fortune and had a blue-chip
education, including undergraduate work at Princeton and law and
divinity degrees from Yale.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Danforth was on the Finance, Commerce and
Intelligence committees. He was a ranking member of the dwindling
group of Republican moderates in the Senate. At the end of his
three terms he was perhaps best known for his strong defense of the
nomination of conservative Clarence Thomas, a former aide, to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
