<HEADLINE>
REEBOK LAYS OFF 120 IN MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reebok International Ltd. laid off some 120 employees Wednesday,
about 10 percent of its work force in Massachusetts, as the
second-largest shoe manufacturer in the United States cuts costs
and attempts to restructure its business.
</P>
<P>
   More layoffs among Reebok's international work force _ about 10
percent _ may be announced later this month, according to company
spokesman Dave Fogelson.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok had employed about 6,600 employees, about 1,200 of them
in Massachusetts. Total layoffs of 10 percent company-wide would
bring the total layoffs to 660.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had some very, very difficult conversations with
people in Stoughton today,'' Fogelson said, referring to Reebok's
headquarters. ``This remains part of our continuing effort to get
costs down more within industry norms. We are trying to become a
much more focused organization that will put resources up against
those components that are going to directly effect sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Reebok declined to specify who was layed off. Fogelson said the
layoffs occurred ``at all levels, from vice president down through
the work force.''
</P>
<P>
   Reebok's market share has declined from about 25 percent to 10
percent in the 1990s, while Nike, Reebok's chief competitor, has
risen from about 25 to 47 percent market share, according to
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Reebok reported a net income of $4.6 million or 8 cents
per share for the quarter ending June 30, down from $6.1 million or
11 cents per share for the year previously. Net sales were $697.4
million for the quarter, a decline from $760.6 million in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales, general and administrative costs totaled $243.4 million,
or 34.9 percent of sales in the second quarter, and those costs
were singled out by Reebok's Chairman and Chief Executive Officer
Paul Fireman as an area of concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``While our overall spending did decline, we recognize the need
to lower our SG&AMP;A spending to more acceptable levels,'' Fireman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Market analysts, who have questioned Reebok's comparatively high
costs, are likely to be pleased that the company is now moving to
control them.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok stock closed unchaged at 11 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Observers of the athletic apparel industry had said their
concerns about Reebok's performance were heightened recently when
other companies, including Nike and New Balance, began showing
evidence that the two-year soft market for athletic shoes was
turning around.
</P>
<P>
   Fogelson said it would be ``premature'' to discuss how much
money the company is saving in any of the cost-cutting measures now
being instituted or under consideration. He emphasized that not all
of the spending reductions are coming from layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok is engaged in a new effort to refocus its business toward
women's fitness products, its so-called classic lines of shoes and
styles that appeal to youths, he said, and more of the strategy
will become clear over the next several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Yankowski, president of Reebok, said in a written statement
released last week that ``a number of actions'' are being taken by
the company to turn around its performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of utmost important,'' Yankowski said, ``we're returning to
our roots in fitness and women, and to our heritage of providing
the most comfortable, stylish athletic footwear on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   One industry observer, who asked not to be named, said: ``Right
now, this all seems like it is heading toward Reebok looking more
like the company it was in the 1980s, when its pitch was more to
women and kids and less to high performance shoes for the serious
athletes; the basketball players, the cross-trainers and the
runners.''
</P>
<P>
   Reebok began shedding expensive, major sports figures as
endorsers two years ago. But Fogelson made it clear that any
de-emphasis on high performance shoes will not result in the loss
of two high-profile athletes currently under contract, the tennis
player Venus Williams and the National Basketball Association
player Alan Iverson. Both Williams and Iverson are viewed by sports
marketing experts as emerging, young stars who are much coveted by
other shoe and apparel manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venus and Alan will continue to be part of the company
throughout their careers, and as we continue to move forward,''
Fogelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Substantial severence packages, employment counseling and help
with job hunting has been offered to all of the employees, he said.
``I think the company is doing the best it possibly can given the
circumstances,'' Fogelson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
