<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-CEEDEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S CHOICE: COMPOSERS WHO DEFY CLASSIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Songs of Life'
</P>
<P>
   For many musicians, the American composer Ralph Shapey, now 78,
is a towering master, a composer of flinty, astringent and utterly
original works. The larger public has never caught on to Shapey in
the same way. But his advocates keep making the case, notably the
cellist Joel Krosnick and the pianist Gilbert Kalish, who are the
principal performers on a new disk of chamber works called ``Songs
of Life'' on the Arabesque label (Z6728).
</P>
<P>
   Shapey's ``Evocation II'' for Cello, Piano and Percussion from
1979 demonstrates how hard it is to classify his music and how hard
it is to resist. The work opens in a fit, with a grumpy, skittish
cello line and some crash-bang piano chords. But the percussion
intrudes, as if to quell the fracas.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't exactly work. The piano gets stuck on a series of
pungent treble-range chords, and the cello plays almost obsessively
as the percussion surrounds them both with volleys of drums and
cymbals. Throughout its three movements this is viscerally powerful
music, especially in this performance, with the percussionist
William Trigg joining Krosnick and Kalish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs of Life'' for soprano (the excellent Lisa Saffer), cello
and piano sets portions of Walt Whitman's poems, but the words are
boldly rearranged, inverted, and combined with those of other
authors. The work is really a wondrously imaginative trio with the
voice as just one instrument. There is brash humor in the work as
well. In an extended section for hushed soprano and plucked cello
line, you would think you were at a moody jazz club of Shapey's
mind. The finale of the ``Evocation IV'' for violin (Joel
Smirnoff), cello, piano and percussion gets wild and ornery. But by
then you may have gotten the point. This music is difficult in an
exuberant way.
</P>
<P>
   `Riff and Transfiguration'
</P>
<P>
   Lee Hyla's new disk on the Tzadik label, ``Riff and
Transfiguration'' (TZ 7048), presents recent piano works by another
hard-to-classify composer, now 47 and in his creative prime. Hyla
wrote ``Third Party'' for his friend, the superb pianist Judith
Gordon, who wanted a piece to precede the Liszt Piano Sonata in a
recital she was planning. But this ear-opening, head-clearing
five-minute work is no mere curtain-raiser. It beings with eruptive
frenzy, a modernistic answer to Liszt's transcendental pianistic
visions. But it then settles into a reflective episode of
shimmering, ethereal chords, with wisps of restless figures trying
to break in here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basic Training,'' written for the prodigious pianist Stephen
Drury, is a 13-minute work that tries to depict in music the
development of this intense and uncompromising pianist from
elemental early ages of pounding thuds through increasingly
expressive, searching musical flights. Drury's performance is by
turns captivating and terrifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Riff and Transfiguration,'' written for the pianist Mia Chung,
is an 18-minute suite of seven movements. In its 12-tone-like
riffs, keyboard-spanning leaps, crunchy chords and atmospheric
colors you can hear Hyla foraging through his musical storeroom for
this and that remembered item. Yet the result is music of
tremendous imagination. The disk also offers a wonderfully eclectic
work for clarinets, hammered dulcimer, violin, viola, cello and
piano, ``Amnesia Variance,'' conducted by the versatile Drury.
</P>
<P>
   `Human Gestures'
</P>
<P>
   Four recent works by Scott Lindroth, 41, a composer on the
faculty of Duke University, are offered on a new recording, ``Human
Gestures'' (CD 808), from the invaluable CRI label. Clearly, being
original for originality's sake is not Lindroth's purpose. Each of
these works is steeped in some older music that fascinates him. Yet
his ear and mind are so keen that he cannot help being fresh.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Light,'' which sets excerpts from a text by Hildegard von
Bingen, the vocal line, sung here with shimmering presence by the
mezzo-soprano D'Anna Fortunato, is arching and urgent. But it is
folded into an ecstatic instrumental piece where skittish lines
chase one another impishly, and the game comes close to getting out
of control. The Dinosaur Annex Music Ensemble, conducted by Scott
Wheeler, give a vibrant performance.
</P>
<P>
   Lindroth consciously tries to pay homage to the past in his 1997
String Quartet. If you listen just to its surface, it may sound
like Janacek or Ravel. But the music is filled with quirky touches
and pulsating figures that display Lindroth's inventiveness.
``Terza Rima'' for oboe (Libby van Cleve) and electronics finds
Lindroth in a more spacious and roomy mode. The duo for Violins
(played by Curtis Macomber and Veronica Macchia-Kadlubkiewicz) has
echoes of the Italian Baroque, with its playful hocketing between
the violins. This is engrossing music, but only for listeners who
can forget about placing Lindroth in some compositional category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
