<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT CHINA'S OFFER OF CONCESSIONS TO JOIN WTO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grab it. So say many economists, referring to the bold trade
deal that China offered the United States in April and President
Clinton rejected in what many deem a serious foreign policy
blunder. Clinton can reverse when he meets President Jiang Zemin on
Sunday in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   China wants to enter the World Trade Organization in time for
the group's next meeting in Seattle in November, when the member
nations are expected to embark on a new round of world trade talks.
But before China can join, it needs Clinton's approval. So it
offered huge ``concessions'' on nearly every front.
</P>
<P>
   Concessions is the lingo of tradespeak. But the term is wholly
misleading. China's promise in April to open its economy to foreign
goods and investment would serve its own self-interest yet would be
largely irrelevant to the economic fortunes of the United States.
Some concession.
</P>
<P>
   Critics make three arguments for rejecting the offer. Delay
could achieve better terms in the future. The deal's nice-sounding
terms are unenforceable. And China's entry into the trade group
would flood U.S. markets with cheap textiles and apparel.
</P>
<P>
   But judging from an analysis of Daniel H. Rosen and his
colleagues at the Institute for International Economics, the first
criticism appears weak, the second misleading and the third
misguided.
</P>
<P>
   The precise terms of China's offer remain unpublished, though
the administration published a summary. The breadth of the offer is
stunning. China would drastically cut tariffs to levels less than
those of most United States trade partners. It would eliminate
export subsidies, phase out quotas on industrial products and
comply immediately with World Trade Organization rules for
protecting foreign investors and intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   China also agreed to phase out regulations that restrict foreign
companies from importing, exporting, wholesaling and retailing. The
offer would permit foreign companies to buy substantial stakes in
insurance and telecommunications companies. China also agreed to
have its state-owned enterprises make purchases on
nondiscriminatory terms, based solely on price, quality and other
commercial considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Schott of the institute said that these terms were
``substantially more liberal than those the United States had hoped
to get out of negotiations and substantially more liberal than
those which a number of existing WTO members, like India, currently
adhere to. You can't say that the terms of the agreement don't
measure up.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Mastel of the New American Foundation, a prominent critic,
says that the deal is deficient on telecommunications and financial
services. He has a point. There is, for example, no firm provision
to eliminate nonperforming loans from banks, which serve as
disguised subsidies to state-owned enterprises. This omission
raises questions about China's commitment to run its state-owned
enterprises on a commercial basis.
</P>
<P>
   Mastel also criticizes the deal because, he says, it cannot be
enforced. China is not, he warned, ``a rule-based society'' that
makes decisions in ways that can be monitored and challenged. He
points to China's repeated violations of patent and copyright
protections.
</P>
<P>
   But here the administration must ask, what is the alternative?
In the absence of membership, China could continue many of its
protectionist ways with impunity. But as a member, China becomes
subject to the trade group's disciplinary process that has proven
to be impartial and unflinching.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. would lose the right to impose unilateral trade
sanctions against China once it joins the organization. But in
return, the U.S. would gain international backing for trade
sanctions so that every dispute does not turn into a bilateral
foreign policy spat. Also, China would be held responsible for
meeting market-opening commitments that go well beyond anything the
U.S. can now demand.
</P>
<P>
   Critics point to the fact that as a member of the World Trade
Organization, China would escape restrictions now in place on its
exports of textiles and apparel to the United States. But Marcus
Noland of the institute estimates that most Chinese sales here come
at the expense of imports from other countries, not U.S.
manufacturers. Indeed, the institute estimates that U.S. exports to
China under the trade deal would rise by about $3 billion. Imports
from China would rise by slightly more, so the overall effect on
the $8 trillion U.S. economy would be minute.
</P>
<P>
   The United States already provides China nondiscriminatory
access. So why does China bother to fight for admission to a club
whose benefits it largely enjoys already? Jiang apparently needs
the weight of international commitments to help overcome domestic
opposition to his ambitious plan to drive his economy away from
state controls and toward markets. That would appear to be an
ambition that Clinton would want to propel rather than sabotage. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
