<SLUG> BC-BKW-COMETS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
60,000 CELEBRATE COMETS' THIRD STRAIGHT TITLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By JANETTE RODRIGUES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Red, white and blue confetti coated downtown Wednesday
as thousands of basketball fans congratulated the Houston Comets on
their third straight WNBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   They simultaneously celebrated the life of feisty point guard
Kim Perrot, who lost her battle with cancer in August.
</P>
<P>
   A party atmosphere permeated the parade from start to finish,
and the rally that followed, despite the crowds and the relentless
midday heat. The city Parks and Recreation Department estimated
that 60,000 people flooded downtown for the events.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd kicked it up a notch when the players _ holding the
three, Tiffany-designed trophies _ passed by, atop a fleet of fire
engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got goosebumps,'' said Jessica Pompa, 26, who took a break
from cutting hair at Mueller's Barber Salon in downtown Houston to
watch the parade. ``This is so exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyesha Campbell, 15, a Furr Senior High School basketball
player, was too emotional to talk after she caught a Comets cap
forward Sheryl Swoopes threw to the crowd from her perch on a fire
engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came back to where we were, crying and shaking,'' said
Margie Martinez, 40, head coach of the school's girls basketball
team. ``I thought something had happened to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was still visibly moved, shaking like a leaf and her
eyes welling up with tears when anyone asked about the cap, signed
by Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Tezano, 37, did a little dance to a jock-jam song being
played by one of the high-stepping high school marching bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm dancing,'' he said, unembarrassed about his public
display of affection for the Comets. ``Why not? This is good. We
got a three-peat!''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Lee Brown gave all the players keys to the city,
proclaiming Wednesday ``1999 WNBA Champions Houston Comets Day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it bears repeating that the Houston Comets are our
hometown heroes,'' he said. ``They built a dynasty. They put womens
sports on the map, and in doing so, they have forever, forever, and
ever, linked womens sports to the city of Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd roared loudest when Brown touched on how the Comets'
singular accomplishment has put Houston in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I said that the Houston Comets were the best in the
game,'' he said. ``This year, I want to say that I believe that we
can all say that the Houston Comets are one of the greatest teams
in sports history!''
</P>
<P>
   Office workers dumped bags of plastic foam packing peanuts from
the upper stories of skyscrapers, so much so that it looked like it
was snowing along some sections of the eight-block parade route.
</P>
<P>
   But there were solemn moments as well. Near the beginning of the
parade, the memory of Perrot was evoked by a fire engine with huge
white ribbons on the doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a sparkplug,'' said Barbara Wade, 55, who was wearing
a T-shirt with ``Three for Kim'' written on the back. ``I thought
her death would affect them, but they came through for her. I'm
sure she's here in spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   As a basketball coach and former player, Martinez marveled at
how the team persevered over its trials and tribulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consider everything they had to overcome, and still take it to
that next level,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown also mentioned the Comets season of triumph and tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The road to the WNBA championship was a bittersweet journey
for the Comets with the loss of our dear, beloved friend, Kim
Perrot,'' he said. ``But it was apparent, it was clear, that her
spirit was very much alive throughout this championship series.''
</P>
<P>
   When guard Cynthia Cooper stepped forward to speak at the rally,
the first thing she did was hold the index finger of one hand up,
and make a fist with the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does anybody know what that means?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd knew that it was the symbol for 10 _ Perrot's
jersey number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well then raise your hand and don't be shy, I want to see
everybody all the way in the back, all the way in the back,''
Cooper said. ``That's right, Kim will always be with us.''
</P>
<P>
   She said of the championship, ``This was a tribute to Kim.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the irrepressible Cooper said, ``Can I get a boom
shakalaka!''
</P>
<P>
   And the crowd gave her one.
</P>
<P>
   Other players took the microphone in turn, to thank the fans for
their support.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the rally, the fans seemed reluctant to go. Some
stayed to hear a high school band play, while others lined up to
buy souvenir t-shirts from a vendor with the words ``three-peat''
emblazoned across the front in Comets colors.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps diehard fan Christen Crawford, 22, of Houston, said it
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get any better than the Houston Comets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
