<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SACKLER-CHINESE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE SINGER COLLECTION OF CHINESE ART IS BEQUEATHED TO THE
SMITHSONIAN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Austria, Hungary)  By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Smithsonian Institution announced Wednesday
that its Arthur M. Sackler Gallery had been left one of the leading
collections of ancient Chinese art still held privately, 5,000
pieces from the estate of Dr. Paul Singer, a New York psychiatrist
who died in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Milo Beach, the director of the Sackler, said that a preliminary
estimate put the value of the collection at $50 million to $60
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It places us in a position of extraordinary strength in terms
of the culture of ancient China,'' Beach said.
</P>
<P>
   To mark the bequest, the Sackler has displayed 18 objects from
the Singer collection, including a 3,000-year-old bronze bell, a
4,000-year-old jade disk, a marble sculpture of a bear, wine
containers in animal shapes and ceramic burial jars made to look
like farm buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell K. Hearn, the curator of Asian art at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art in New York, who knew Singer well, said of the
collection, ``It is an assemblage that is distinguished by its
breadth of interest and exquisite quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearn said that the Met was not surprised that Singer had left
his collection to the Sackler. ``We realized that Singer's
intention was always to see his collection placed with that of
Arthur Sackler, whom he admired a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sackler, who died in 1987, was also a psychiatrist, a colleague
of Singer's and a leading collector of Asian art.
</P>
<P>
   Singer was born in Pressburg, Hungary, and started acquiring
Asian art as a boy in Vienna, where he grew up. He became a
neuropsychiatrist there, fleeing Austria in 1938 to escape the
Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   He went first to London, to await an American visa, and then New
York, where he was found after six weeks to be suffering from
tuberculosis and spent the next two years recuperating in the
Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He acquired Chinese art with renewed fervor in his adopted
country,'' Thomas Lawton, the former director of the Sackler, said,
adding, ``The Singer gift is the largest and most important group
of Chinese archeological material from a private American
collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer died at the age of 92 at a nursing home in New Jersey,
leaving no family members as survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Hearn, the Met curator, said that there was barely a space in
Singer's apartment not taken by an exquisite piece of art.
</P>
<P>
   Singer purchased his first East Asian object at the age of 17,
which Lawton described as a ``finely detailed bronze image of the
Bodhisattva Manjusri with a multicolored lacquer surface.'' Lawton
said that Singer kept the object in a prominent position on his
desk the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   The young collector, the Smithsonian said, ignored the
prevailing popularity for late Chinese porcelains and instead
collected early archeological objects that were just beginning to
appear on the international art market.
</P>
<P>
   He later became an authority on the antiquities of the state of
Chu in southern China from the eighth to the third century B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The objects in his collection were displayed in museums and
galleries around the country. and he was the curator of two shows
at the China Institute in America.
</P>
<P>
   Singer served as senior consultant to the Far Eastern Department
at the Met, where Hearn described him as ``a real mentor figure,''
and he was the author of scholarly papers and several books on
Asian art, including ``Early Chinese Gold and Silver'' (1971) and
``Early Chinese Miniatures'' (1977).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5103 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-QUAYLE-PROFILE-ART-2T     09-08 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE, AGAINST ODDS AND ADVICE, DOGGEDLY PURSUES GOP BANNER 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOFFSTOWN, N.H. _ By the time Dan Quayle made it to the Rotary
Club breakfast here at 7:30 a.m., he had already finished two radio
interviews and was bursting to offer this latest audience his
distinctive conservative refrain: an embrace of family values, a
call for a 30 percent tax cut and his lamentation over what he
views as the dark spiritual legacy of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   But when the former vice president concluded his remarks, he was
met with another variation of the question he encounters at almost
every turn these days: Why, given his weak showing in last month's
Iowa straw poll, and the overwhelming signs of Republican support
for Texas Gov. George W. Bush, is Quayle staying in the race at
all?
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it is over,'' Quayle said, displaying just a slight
edge of frustration at hearing the question again, this time from a
Rotarian. ``It is NOT over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plead with my party members, `We need to have a serious
debate,''' Quayle continued, adding: ``The Republicans are on the
verge of saying to the Republican Party and the primary voter that
we're going to have a coronation, that we're not going to have a
serious primary. That would be most unfortunate, and it would
diminish our chances in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, whose slingshot career has given him a glimpse of both
the heights and the depths of American politics by the age of 52,
appears to be back at the bottom of his political trajectory. Since
his eighth-place finish in the Iowa straw poll _ only two
candidates fared worse, one of whom did not even compete in the
nonbinding contest _ some of Quayle's aides have quit for other
campaigns, his old friends from the White House privately describe
his presidential ambitions as hopeless, and he is drawing small
crowds and perfunctory attention from the news media. Even a
signing for his new book in Boston on Tuesday that was advertised
to last for 90 minutes petered out after 20, as the lunchtime line
of autograph seekers dwindled away.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, with poignant tenacity, Quayle perseveres, motivated by the
political vindication he has pursued since he was sworn in as vice
president 10 years ago, and by the dogged belief in the possibility
of success.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate's daybreak schedule here over Labor Day was
typical: He managed two television shows, a parade and two picnics,
all before dinner. There is, it seems, no invitation that he will
not accept. Labor Day morning found the former vice president of
the United States hustling down a set of stairs into a basement
entrance to the Milford Town Hall, which was closed except for the
cramped room serving as the studio for the local cable television
show that was giving Quayle an hour of time.
</P>
<P>
   For Quayle, the prospect of becoming the Republican nominee for
president in 2000, as fanciful as that seems to many in his party,
remains a realistic goal, if admittedly a difficult one. It is
simply a matter of conservatives rallying around him as their
ideological alternate to Bush, Quayle said. And then, he continued,
it is simply a matter of Bush's campaign collapsing,
notwithstanding its continued signs of health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, the conservatives will have to take a deep breath
and ask themselves this question: Who is the conservative candidate
that is most qualified, and has the best chance of defeating George
Bush and ultimately prevailing against Bradley or Gore?'' Quayle
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, if I didn't think I had a good chance of winning _
why spend 18 hours a day, six, seven days a week doing this?'' he
asked. ``There are other things in life. The moment I'm convinced
that I can't win, then I won't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt, as Quayle asserts at every chance, that
he brings a strong resume to the race. He has far more governmental
experience _ he is a former representative, senator and vice
president _ than any of his Republican opponents. Indeed, he was
serving as vice president to Bush's father when the younger Bush
had shown hardly a glimmer of interest in public service.
</P>
<P>
   Alone among the conservatives in the race, Quayle has won
election to public office. And he has a cogent ideological appeal
that impresses his audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, that does not seem to be enough. As Quayle turns all his
attention to this state and its first-in-the-nation presidential
primary, he is finding that his most daunting opponent is not the
Texas governor, but himself _ or rather, the frozen image of
himself as a hesitant and intellectually slight figure that even
Quayle acknowledges is the legacy of his vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt about it: The introduction that I had to the
American people, that was totally unfair, is something that I have
to deal with today,'' Quayle said, bristling at the memory. ``The
unfair, outrageous, false coverage. From day one, from the
introduction, it was all BOOM _ totally, 100 percent negative.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Quayle is reminded of this more often than he would like. As he
marched cheerfully along the parade route in Milford on Labor Day,
Beverly Simpson, 75, met his smiling glance with a stern shake of
her head, turning away as he sought to greet her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he ought to drop out and let Bush have it,'' Mrs.
Simpson said. ``I don't think he is the man for the job. Mark my
words _ I don't think he has the makings of a president.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's most enthusiastic supporters, after ticking off what
they say should make him a particularly attractive candidate in
this conservative state, acknowledge that his candidacy remains
extraordinarily problematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I call the next-door-neighbor-people problem,'' said
John H. Sununu, a former governor of New Hampshire and Quayle's
biggest supporter. ``They say, `I really think he's great, but how
are you going to convince my neighbor to vote for him?' And you
talk to the neighbor and they say, `I think he's great, but how are
you going to convince my neighbor to vote for him?'''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle suggests that the only way to counter the argument that
he cannot win is, obviously, to win. Yet he acknowledges that there
are people who will not vote for him because of the perception
cited by Sununu, and seems flummoxed as he considers this
contradiction of his political situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't rely on others to go back 10 years ago, or whatever the
case may be, to some false caricature that we know is totally not
true,'' Quayle pleaded to listeners on WGIR-AM in Manchester on
Tuesday morning. ``Go with what's in your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the candidate shows no signs of flagging,
offering an energetic and ideologically distinctive agenda that
inevitably invites a comparison with the more general agenda
offered by Bush. Quayle supports a 30 percent cut in taxes. He
advocates 12-year term limits for members of Congress or,
alternately, a constitutional amendment that would stop the
pensions and health-care benefits of lawmakers after 12 years. And
he believes students should be allowed to grade their teachers
anonymously, as a way of improving education.
</P>
<P>
   But Quayle's overwhelming theme is a return to what he describes
as traditional values. It is what has come to define his political
views since he gave a speech assailing the television character
Murphy Brown after she decided to give birth out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, Quayle said, are understandably jubilant about the
state of the economy and their material lives. ``But ask them how
are they doing inside,'' Quayle said. ``Their hearts ache. They can
see the cultural decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to reclaim values that made America great in the first
place,'' he continued. ``Reclaim values like respect. Integrity.
The value of faith. The value of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Quayle's words have some appeal here.
``I like everything he stands for _ family values,'' said Kevin
Currie, 32, a forklift operator. ``I don't think the press treats
him fairly at all.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In pushing his quest for the presidency, Quayle takes solace in
his own history of come-from-behind victories, and he often
suggests comparisons to another once-discredited vice president who
went on to become president, Richard M. Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   But Nixon succeeded because he spent eight years creating a new
public image for himself; Quayle has resisted friends' advice that
he do the same thing, arguing that to attempt that would be to
affirm, in effect, an unfair caricature.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who have advised Quayle over the years think that
given the crowded current field, which includes a number of
candidates who have Quayle's ideology without his history, it is
unrealistic to think that the former vice president could succeed
even if Bush were to fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid I think that's fanciful,'' said William Kristol,
who was Quayle's chief of staff in the White House and is now
editor of The Weekly Standard, a conservative magazine. ``That's
wishful thinking in the extreme. But I can see how he believes it.
I mean, maybe it should be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   And these days, as Quayle makes his last stand in New Hampshire,
it seems hard to quarrel with Kristol's assessment. As Quayle was
stepping briskly around a turn in the Milford parade, he came upon
a marquee. It was scattered with a jumble of letters, but one word,
evidently a greeting for Quayle, stood out: ``potatoe.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle looked toward the sign, and then his gaze floated away as
he turned to the other side of the street with a wave to the crowd,
and quietly finished his march to a van waiting to take him to his
next stop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
