<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PLANET-HOLLYWOOD-NYT &LR;      09-08 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANET-HOLLYWOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE MENU AT PLANET HOLLYWOOD: BANKRUPTCY AND RESTRUCTURING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Ill., Saudia Arabia, Singapore,)   By DENNIS BLANK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Despite complaints about its food and
difficulties attracting younger people and repeat customers, the
glitzy Planet Hollywood restaurant chain can still flourish, by
closing unprofitable outlets and by ``going back to the basics,''
says Robert Earl, its co-founder and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Then, again, Earl does not see why the chain, which is known for
its celebrity tie-ins and movie memorabilia, has not flourished
yet. ``I can't give you one reason,'' Earl said when asked why the
chain, which also operates Official All-Star Cafe restaurants, had
suffered huge losses. ``I am the largest loser. I haven't sold one
share of stock from day one, but I am still as infused with it as I
was when we started.''
</P>
<P>
   According to documents filed with the Security and Exchange
Commission, Earl owns more than 22.8 million shares of stock that
traded at $32 each at their highest point in 1996 but are now
virtually worthless. Keith Barish, producer of the movie ``The
Fugitive'' and a co-founder, sold half of his 12 million shares at
a big loss. He resigned in March as chairman but is still a
director.
</P>
<P>
   Earl is still paid an annual salary of $600,000 plus expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Trading on the New York Stock Exchange was halted last week as
the price of Planet Hollywood dropped to 75 cents a share after the
company said it would file for bankruptcy by the end of the year.
The company has lost more than $306 million in the last year and a
half, including a loss of $28.2 million in the quarter that ended
in June.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Walid bin Talal of Saudi Arabia and Ong Beng Seng of
Singapore have also both invested heavily in the company. As part
of its restructuring plan, they and Earl will each put $10 million
in cash equity in exchange for a 70 percent stake in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Banks and lenders that hold $160 million in notes will be paid
off with $47.5 million in cash, $60 million in secured
payment-in-kind notes and new common stock representing a 26.5
percent equity state in the reorganized company.
</P>
<P>
   The company will cancel all existing shares of common stock and
issue stockholders 200,000 three-year warrants that will allow them
to buy stock at an undisclosed future price.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago Earl brought in William Baumhauer, a former
accountant and chief executive of Unique Casual Restaurants in
Boston, to streamline operations and menus after complaints that
customers were not coming back to buy more $8 hamburgers. The
hamburger now costs $8.95, and Baumhauer left abruptly in June
after clashes with Earl. He did not respond to calls seeking
comment for this article.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is getting them to come back the second time,'' said
Arnold Ursaner, an analyst with CJS Securities. ``They have got to
get consumers in local markets to come and continue to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl acknowledges that critics often cited the food quality, but
he maintains that the customers never complained. ``We are
attempting to upgrade,'' he said. ``Our basic menu is tried and
tested and is just what the consumer wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Lombardi, executive vice president of Technomic Inc. in
Chicago, a restaurant consulting firm, said: ``It is hard for them
to be competitive just as a restaurant. If you took out all the
movie stuff, would it still be a viable, competitive restaurant?
What has been their strength has also been a liability.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty in getting repeat customers is like getting
someone to watch a movie more than once. By the fourth time, the
patron is not interested, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Isadore Sharp, founder of the Four Seasons Hotels based in
Toronto and a Planet Hollywood director until he resigned in April,
believes the downfall came from expanding too quickly. ``I think it
spread out too fast,'' he said, ``and there are many stores that
are still very profitable.'' He said the company needed to
eliminate the outlets that are not profitable and do some
``retrenching.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl would not say how many of the 80 restaurants would be
closed. It is expected that most of the nine All-Star Cafes,
including the one in Manhattan, which have promotional ties to
Tiger Woods, Andre Agassi and other sport celebrities, will be shut
down or sold.
</P>
<P>
   Ursaner, who is pessimistic about Planet Hollywood's chances of
recovery, is advising investors to seek ``better investment
opportunities.'' He also questions Earl's ability to manage
business operations when he is better at promotions and celebrity
connections. When Baumhauer left, Earl lost his ``operations
experience,'' the analyst said. ``Running the store day to day is
not his strength,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
