<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DETROIT-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETROIT'S TEACHERS END STRIKE SENDING 180,000 STUDENTS BACK TO
SCHOOL   
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBYN MEREDITH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Detroit's public school teachers voted Wednesday to
end the strike that had kept the schools from opening this fall.
They, and the city's 180,000 students, will return to the
classrooms on Thursday, more than a week later than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome the teachers back to school,'' said David Adamany,
leader of the Detroit School Board. ``We believe that the return to
schools will allow Detroit Public Schools to maintain the momentum
that was developed for improvements in the school system.''
</P>
<P>
   The teachers voted Wednesday morning by an overwhelming measure
to return to work after their union and the school board reached a
tentative, three-year contract agreement on Monday night. They will
vote later this month on whether to ratify the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who had been scrambling to find child care breathed a
sigh of relief, and the union was also pleased that teachers voted
Wednesday to head back to the classroom, having received higher pay
and concessions on other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll have a staff that is much happier,'' predicted John M.
Elliott, president of the Detroit Federation of Teachers, the union
representing 11,500 public school workers, including 8,000
teachers. ``The kids aren't going to miss any days because we're
going to have to make it up,'' probably at the end of the school
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers voted 10 days ago to strike rather than to allow a
contract extension while negotiations continued between their union
and the school board.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers got some of what they wanted. Teachers with less
than 10 years' experience will get raises of 2 percent a year for
the next three years. Last week, when teachers were asked whether
to extend their contract so bargaining could continue, the school
board had offered raises of 1.75 percent in the first year, without
determining what raises would be in the second and third years.
</P>
<P>
   Because the most senior teachers in Detroit are paid less than
those in the surrounding suburbs, those with bachelor's degrees
will get raises of 4 percent and those with master's degrees will
get raises of 5 percent in the first year to bring them up to par.
In the second year, those teachers will get raises of 2.4 percent
and in the third year of the contract, they will get raises of 2.5
percent, Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   The school board agreed to reduce some class sizes starting next
year, rather than only to study the issue, which it promised last
week. There are as many as 41 students in some classes now, and the
board agreed to bring class size down to 17 students, where
possible, in elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers have not formally ratified the contract and could still
reject it. The vote Wednesday only determined whether they would
end the strike. They are scheduled to vote on whether to accept the
contract over several days later this month, with results due on
Sept. 24. Because of the strong support displayed Wednesday for
ending the strike, Elliott said, ``I expect it to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled State Legislature earlier this year
transferred control of Detroit's 263 schools from an elected school
board to one appointed by Mayor Dennis W. Archer and Gov. John
Engler. Archer, a former special education teacher in the city's
public schools, said that he was pleased with the end of the strike
and that the tentative contract terms were fair.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle A. Zdrodowski, the mayor's spokeswoman, said Archer
believed the vote showed ``the teachers of the city of Detroit do
care about the kids, but they had some valid issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
