A5109 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     09-08 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEYERS MOVING ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ I heard Terry Bradshaw the other day on a
radio show reflect on the fraudulence of public perceptions, and
how he himself throughout his career couldn't shake a widespread
belief that he had limited intellectual capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed up at the Pittsburgh Steelers' training camp my first
season with a heavy Louisiana drawl, and made a few mental mistakes
and the word got out that I was pretty dumb,'' said Bradshaw, who
turned out to be smart enough to lead the Steelers to four Super
Bowl titles and is now a high profile television personality. ``I'm
sure there are people who still think I'm dumb. Once someone hangs
a label on you, it's difficult to get rid of.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, I constantly notice such a weird phenomenon. Jim Leyland
and Tony LaRussa have remained ``genius managers'' no matter how
badly their teams have played throughout the seasons, while
counterparts like Boston's Jimy Williams and San Francisco's Dusty
Baker haven't been similarly anointed even though the magic they've
performed with their teams has been infinitely more impressive in
recent times.
</P>
<P>
   I've read the prose of sporting authors who can't get out of
first gear and don't have even the faintest grasp of humor, and yet
such tedious types are revered figures on the national scene by the
fortuitous quirk of fate of being employed by a large-circulation
newspaper in a metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   I see people with big reputations on TV reading news that I
wouldn't hire to call out numbers at a bingo parlor. I've been
informed year after year by our elitist critics what unique
filmmakers Woody Allen and Spike Lee are, and the best thing I can
say about most of their work is that such rubbish is the perfect
antidote for insomnia.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   In our image-obsessed society in which people go hopelessly in
hock to wear flashy clothes, drive fancy cars and live in homes
that will inspire envy among friends, perception too often trumps
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Meyers, an All-Pac 10 guard and third team All American a
year ago for the UCLA football team, steadfastly believes that
perception is the reason he isn't playing in the NFL today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tag the pro scouts put on me was that I was slow and
didn't have the right kind of body,'' says Meyers, recently cut by
the Buffalo Bills. ``It didn't matter that I started 36 straight
games at UCLA, and graded out very high. It didn't matter that I
always did the job and seldom made mistakes. It didn't matter that
I was 6 foot 6 and weighed 315 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to the Bills' mini-camp in the spring, they
checked my fat content and told me to lose weight. So I came to
training camp in the summer weighing 295, and felt great. But I
didn't have the same power and strength I possessed when I weighed
315.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to be a free agent in the NFL. Oh, there are some
who make it, but not very many. I know all the free agents I came
in with on the Bills are now gone. I think a team looks for ways to
get rid of you because of the fact you weren't drafted in the first
place and therefore you must not be that good. The guys drafted are
given all the opportunities at your expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, this is not sour grapes on my part. I'm not bitter
about my NFL experience. But it certainly wasn't enjoyable. I can't
believe how much politics is involved in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Meyers, Cade McNown's closest friend at UCLA and one of his
chief bodyguards for three seasons, understood that his chances of
sticking with the Bills were faint when he signed for a modest
$7,000 bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I lost money trying to hook on with the Bills,''
says Meyers, who had a 3.5 GPA in earning a political science
degree at UCLA and is now weighing a couple of lucrative business
offers. ``You know what a free agent's pay is during the preseason?
Six hundred and seventy five dollars a game, which comes out to
four hundred and eighty dollars and eighty four cents after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no regrets about my NFL experience because I know I
gave it my best. In our team's opener at Seattle, I played the
entire second half at tackle, and I thought I did a pretty good
job. I never got beat for a sack, and I graded out well. But it
made no difference. I was with the team for three more weeks, but
never got into a game again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved my line coach, Karl Mauck, who gave me great
encouragement and I think really liked me. If Mauck what have
gotten his way, I think the Bills would have kept me on the
practice team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was honest with me. He said team officials felt my legs
were too thin for my frame, and that they would be a hindrance when
a defensive lineman bull rushed me. Can you believe that?
Certainly, I don't have the perfect body. I'm not Jonathan Ogden
(former UCLA star now with Baltimore). But I can play this game,
and I think I showed it during that half I played against
Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Meyers isn't exactly shedding tears about his brief NFL
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time for me to get on with the rest of my life
without football, anyway,'' he says. ``I've been playing the game
long enough as it is. I'm finished. No way I'm going to try again,
or play up in Canada, or in Europe, or in the Arena Football
League. I'm not going to chase a dream that's a dead end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw guys out there playing ahead of me who made one mistake
after another, and just weren't doing the job. But they were
drafted, and that's why they were kept. I guarantee you had I been
drafted, I'd still be with an NFL team. But I wasn't, and I was cut
without being given much of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I really don't mind that much. I hated Buffalo. I'd rather
live in an outhouse in L.A. than a mansion in Buffalo. I have my
health. My knees are in one piece. I think getting cut was the best
thing for me. It didn't hurt a bit. Actually, I was relieved. But I
know in my heart I can play in the NFL despite what other people
think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0329 </DOCNO>
