u w BC-CLINTON-TRIP-HNS &LR;      09-08 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LEAVES TO ECONOMIC SUMMIT AS CRISIS SIMMERS IN EAST TIMOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As trouble brews in Asia, President Clinton leaves
Thursday for the region's annual economic summit where security
issues may dominate now that the Pacific Rim's trade engines are
humming again.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders from 21 nations will arrive this weekend in New Zealand,
which is hosting the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation forum. But
trade talks may take a backseat to the crisis in East Timor, the
recent China and Taiwan scrape and the renewed missile threats from
North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The United States wants to press its Pacific Rim neighbors to
continue economic and political reforms that began with the Asian
economic crisis and could be slowed as the region shows renewed
vigor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news makes it all the more important yet also harder
to avoid complacency. This will be an important part of the
president's message at APEC. The work begun in crisis must be
completed, or Asia's bounce back may yet be the prelude to another
breakdown,'' said Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, the president's national
security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, for instance, warned Indonesia it could face a loss of
international support for its economic reforms unless it quells the
violence aimed at independence-minded East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resolution of this crisis matters, not just for East
Timor, but for Indonesia as a whole. It is a test of whether
Indonesia is genuinely moving towards democratic rule and political
stability,'' Berger told reporters as he discussed the president's
APEC agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian President B.J. Habibie and State Secretary Muladi
canceled plans to attend the APEC session because of the violence.
Marauding pro-Indonesia militiamen have murdered hundreds of East
Timorese and forced thousands from their homes since the
independence vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrives Saturday morning in Auckland after an 18-hour
flight and a move across the international dateline. Clinton plans
a series of sessions with other world leaders after his arrival,
beginning with Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   He also will hold three-way talks with the South Korean
President Kim Dae Jung and Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi. He
will meet later in the day with Russian Prime Minister Vladimir
Putin, Boris Yeltsin's latest choice in a string of premiers.
Clinton also will meet with New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny
Shipley.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's session with Jiang will be his first since the United
States mistakenly bombed the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia in May.
After the bombing, Jiang initially refused to accept Clinton's
telephone calls of apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will seek in that meeting to restore momentum to our
relationship, to urge an easing of tensions between China and
Taiwan, and to resume discussion of China's accession to the (World
Trade Organization),'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   The American and Chinese relations have been damaged by a series
of allegations such as accusations China tried to improperly
influence the 1996 election with illegal campaign donations and
that China stole U.S. nuclear secrets. China has denied these
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   China also renewed its saber rattling aimed at Taiwan, which it
considers a renegade province, after its leaders suggested
independence for the island. China and Taiwan also are at odds over
admission into the WTO. China wants the island admitted after its
acceptance; others want the two admitted at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will talk to the leaders of South Korea and Japan about
the situation in North Korea. Berger said the United States wants
to maintain a concerted approach with South Korea and Japan and to
discuss responses should North Korea again test a long-range
missile.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in three years, economic issues may not be at
the fore of an APEC session. The Asian economic crisis _ which
forced many nations into a deep recession _ appears to have faded
in most quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lasting economic recovery in Asia depends on more than open
markets. It will also require continued stability in the region,
which can never be taken for granted,'' Berger said. ``This is
where the United States plays an especially vital role, and it will
be an important part of our agenda at APEC, as the president's
schedule will make clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the president's economic adviser, said the United
States and APEC leaders must ``send a strong message of support''
for launching a new round of World Trade Organization discussions
set to begin in Seattle this November. APEC members represent 45
percent of the global trade.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling said a new WTO round ``would be one of the most
significant things that could be done worldwide for keeping up the
benefits that come with open markets in terms of growth,
innovation, competition and the free flow of ideas and freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   After APEC concludes, the president, traveling without first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, will fly to New Zealand's south island
to visit a Queenstown resort. He also may make an official state
visit to Prime Minister Shipley in Chirstchurch. The president will
return to Washington on Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
