<SLUG> BC-ACADEMY-BUFFY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, ACADEMY, WHERE'S `BUFFY'? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  An open letter to the Academy of Televison Arts and Sciences (the
Emmy people): 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the first statuette is presented, before David Hyde
Pierce and Jenna Elfman blow their first air kiss, even before Joan
Rivers dresses down an overdressed celebrity, the 51st Annual Emmy
Awards (Sunday night on Fox) will go down in my book as a major
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   My ``Buffy'' isn't even a nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Neither are Sarah Michelle Gellar, Joss Whedon, Michelle
Williams or Joshua Jackson. Keri Russell was good enough to win a
Golden Globe, but she couldn't even muster a nomination for an
Emmy.
</P>
<P>
   Major oversights all, I say. ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,''
produced by Whedon and starring Gellar, was only the most
impressive series of the year on broadcast television. Russell and
her show, ``Felicity,'' created as much water-cooler talk as any
series on the air. And in 1999, Jackson and Williams settled once
and for all who the real stars of ``Dawson's Creek'' are.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these were deserving of the Academy's attention on Emmy
night, and that means more than as presenters. But the Academy,
either by oversight, geriatrics or lunacy, failed to honor these
worthy talents and their shows in major categories.
</P>
<P>
   Take notice, Academy: Your biases are showing. You waited a
long, long time to so honor anything on the young people's network
of a decade ago, Fox, until ``The X-Files'' came along. The Academy
still doesn't know what to do with one of the true classic series
of the '90s, Fox's ``The Simpsons.'' It gets shooed to animation
categories when it has deserved to be recognized as the best comedy
on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the advent of the teen drama on the young people's
network of this decade, the WB, may have sneaked up on those
dolting Academy members who don't know a ``Party of Five'' from a
restaurant reservation. But the simple, un-adult-erated fact is
that some of the most compelling shows during the 1998-1999
television season were dramas aimed at teens: ``Dawson's,''
``Felicity'' and my beloved ``Buffy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Academy, please read this and take notes: Gellar, who
portrays Buffy, happens to be one of the best actresses on
television. Your daytime counterparts thought so, too, which is why
she already has an Emmy on her mantle for her work on ``All My
Children.'' On ``Buffy,'' she has more than the shenanigans of a
mother like Erica to deal with; she is called on to carry a
prime-time show, spit out pages and pages of dialogue, cry and
laugh and, oh yeah, kick some vampire butt, and she handles it with
such command that it amazes me you haven't noticed.
</P>
<P>
   And you haven't noticed, because if you had, Gellar would be a
nominee this year, and Julianna Margulies or Gillian Anderson would
not.
</P>
<P>
   Gellar happens to work on one of the most inventive,
best-written shows on the tube. Which is why I was disappointed
(but not surprised) that ``Buffy'' was not nominated for best
drama. Creator-producer-writer Whedon, the most deserving ``Buffy''
person of all, deserves the right to take down all your names and
cast you as demons during Season 4.
</P>
<P>
   If you were paying attention, Academy, then Jackson and Williams
would be heavy favorites to win Emmys in supporting actor roles.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy, as I understand it, nominates by peer group.
Producers and actors submit examples of their work, and their names
and shows are placed on a big ballot. Actors vote for actors,
directors for directors, etc., then return the ballot to the
accounting firm of Ernst &AMP; Young. The results are tabulated and the
five top vote-getters receive nominations. The process is
fool-proof.
</P>
<P>
   Except for one thing: Most of the people who vote aren't teens
and obviously aren't watching all the nominees. If they were,
``ER'' or ``Law &AMP; Order'' would be off this year's list, and the
more deserving ``Buffy'' would be on.
</P>
<P>
   Academy, are you listening? Short of initiating teen Emmy
categories _ a slap in the face, if you ask me _ it's up to you to
DO YOUR JOB. The best deserve to be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Earnestly,
</P>
<P>
   Mike McDaniel
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle TV Editor &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
