<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANFORTH CHOSEN TO LEAD INQUIRY OF WACO RAID 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno has selected John
Danforth, the former Republican senator from Missouri, to lead an
independent re-examination of the FBI's tear-gas assault in 1993 on
the Branch Davidian compound, government officials said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After a hurried five-day search, Reno prepared to formally
announce Danforth's selection on Thursday, after meeting with him
on Wednesday at the Justice Department to complete discussions
about the scope and authority of his inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Wednesday, when Danforth was interviewed briefly by
Fox News after arriving in Washington, he said that the
investigation ``would be very daunting.'' Of his negotiations with
the Justice Department, he said, ``We've got to tie up some loose
ends,'' but did not discuss any details.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, who during his three terms in the Senate established a
reputation for rectitude and independence, is said by officials to
have sought and received a broad grant of legal authority that will
permit him to look into any aspect of the tear-gas operation. He is
likely to have full prosecutorial powers to compel testimony,
demand documents and convene a federal grand jury if he decides it
is necessary to complete his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Reno turned to Danforth, after recent disclosures badly undercut
her credibility by showing, despite the agency's denials, that FBI
agents had fired combustible tear-gas rounds into a concrete bunker
near the cultists' ramshackle compound.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's choice of Danforth represented an attempt to quell the
bitter chorus of Republican criticism in Congress, an outcry that
grew louder on Wednesday when Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the
majority leader, told reporters: ``I am beginning to think that she
should resign.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats quickly rallied to Reno's side. Sen. Thomas
Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic leader, said: ``I think
Janet Reno deserves commendation, not criticism. She has done an
extraordinary job under very, very difficult circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have kept up an almost daily battering of the
attorney general, accusing her of failing to aggressively dig out
the facts about who started the deadly fire at the Davidian
compound and misleading them about the ill-fated tear-gas
operation.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism followed a succession of disclosures in the last
two weeks, including the fact that for more than six years the FBI
failed to say that it had infrared videotapes that clearly showed
that agents had sought and obtained approval to fire the
military-style tear gas rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Reno had said repeatedly in news conferences and
congressional testimony that the government had done nothing during
the 51-day siege of the Davidian compound that could have ignited
the deadly fire. Reno took responsibility for the government's
actions, but has steadfastly blamed the Branch Davidian leader,
David Koresh, and his followers for starting the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   None of the new evidence indicates that Reno has ever withheld
any information from Congress or that the FBI intentionally misled
anyone about the use of flammable tear gas rounds, although the law
enforcement agency has yet to officially explain how the new
evidence remained unnoticed for more than six years in the files of
the Hostage Rescue Team, the unit that carried out the assault.
</P>
<P>
   The new information has prompted Republican lawmakers to begin
plans to hold hearings on the Waco assault that could conflict with
Danforth's review by focusing on the same witnesses and evidence.
But on Wednesday, the leader of one inquiry said he would put off
his investigation. Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and chairman of the
House Judiciary Committee, said he would withhold his planned
legislation to establish a five-member commission to study the
assault if the Justice Department cooperated with the Danforth
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But the House Government Reform and Oversight Committee, headed
by Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., has issued subpoenas in preparation for
hearings. Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah and chairman of the Judiciary
Committee, has said he had also planned to hold hearings.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, on the Senate's first day back after the August
recess, Lott criticized the Justice Department and the FBI for an
apparent lack of communication over the new information showing
that FBI agents fired the military-style canisters at the bunker
several hours before the main compound burst into flames.
Investigators later recovered the bodies of about 80 people from
the building.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott singled out Reno for his harshest remarks, saying that
the Waco revelations, as well as the president's decision on
Tuesday to offer clemency to 16 Puerto Rican nationalists over the
objections of law enforcement officials, ``lead me to the
conclusion that the attorney general should resign.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest Waco developments culminate a long series of
Republican complaints about Reno. Lott, for example, has sharply
criticized Reno in the past for her refusal to refer a Justice
Department investigation of how the Democrats financed the 1996
campaign to an independent counsel. But never before had Lott
called on the attorney general to step down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
