<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5118 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-LOVE-STINKS-LADN     09-08 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVE-STINKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A MAN HATES A WOMAN ... IT CAN BE FUNNY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating: 2 stars  
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Love Stinks'' is proof that even an awful,
poorly executed idea can be borderline entertaining if it has
enough funny jokes. This self-described un-romantic comedy will
make you feel dirty in the morning for laughing at it. But laugh
you probably will.
</P>
<P>
   A hateful little number that pretends to possess insight into
modern mating rituals, the film is basically an excuse for someone
_ our guess would be writer-director Jeff Franklin, who
incongruously also created the vanilla sweet TV series ``Full
House'' _ to work out rage against women. There's nothing merry
about this would-be ``There's Something About Mary.'' Still, the
consistently bilious wit at work here exerts a certain fascination.
</P>
<P>
   Not straining his imagination, Franklin cast the comically deft
French Stewart as sitcom creator Seth Winnick, a sweet-natured,
Elvis-loving boychild of a bachelor. He meets the charming, sexy
but ferociously marriage-minded Chelsea Turner (Bridgette Wilson)
at the wedding of his writing partner and best friend Larry Garnett
(MTV's Bill Bellamy). Chelsea is good pals with Larry's bride,
Holly (Tyra Banks), and the two women conspire to manipulate Seth
into proposing, like Holly did Larry.
</P>
<P>
   Two big differences, though: Larry was ready to settle down with
his lady, and Holly wasn't a borderline psycho.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, after redecorating his bungalow, buying him a puppy,
moving in and seducing him with a drag number out of ``Viva Las
Vegas,'' Chelsea can't understand why Seth won't pop the question.
Frankly, neither could I; sure, she requires maintenance, but
Chelsea gives as good as she asks for, and she actually exhibits
more patience than Seth or the screenplay give her credit for.
</P>
<P>
   But since the story is told overwhelmingly from a male point of
view, Chelsea's tagged as the villain from the start. When matters
take a turn for the nasty at the movie's midpoint, her pranks are
portrayed as the cruelest and least reasonable. Our hero tossing
her cat off a pier and engineering a particularly vicious (but
pretty hilarious) bedtime gas attack is looked at as good, vengeful
fun.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is presented through anything like cinematography;
the visuals are pure sitcom setup (and the sound quality probably
doesn't even reach broadcast standards).
</P>
<P>
   But despite the movie's profound drawbacks, Stewart, Wilson and
Bellamy give the material all the commitment and comic zest they
can muster, former network executive Warren Littlefield makes an
amusing cameo as a network executive, and however unappetizing this
rancorous battle of the sexes gets, at least it sticks to its guns
and never goes soft-hearted.
</P>
<P>
   Soft-headed, maybe, but the ticker from which ``Love Stinks''
sprang is frozen to the consistency of battleship steel. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The film: ``Love Stinks'' (R; language, sex, mild violence). &QL; 
The stars: French Stewart, Bridgette Wilson, Bill Bellamy, Tyra
Banks. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Jeff Franklin. Produced
by Adam J. Merims and Todd Hoffman. Released by Independent
Artists. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 33 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
