<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-ART-NY     09-08 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS SPENDING SURPLUS IS SLOWLY TURNING RED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Alaska)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By TIM WEINER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Congress resumed the lifting on its spending
bills again Wednesday, what once looked like a spreading sea of
black ink in the federal ledger, the first surplus in 30 years, was
slowly turning to red.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are turning a projected surplus into a deficit, the
nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office says. They may do so
despite cutting billions of dollars in pet projects and politically
popular programs, many members say.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to ``a ridiculous budget situation,'' Rep. David
Obey of Wisconsin, the ranking Democrat on the House Appropriations
Committee, said Wednesday on the House floor. No one rose to debate
that point.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the House majority whip, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas,
said Republicans intended to empty the surplus and then force
President Clinton to sign their spending bills. The Republicans
were already using creative accounting to try to avoid appearing to
run the surplus into a deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans spent the August recess talking about a
projected 10-year budget surplus that they said would underwrite
their proposed tax cut. But now Dan L. Crippen, the director of the
CBO, says no surplus is coming soon. The developing plans of
congressional Republicans could drain away at least $25 billion,
wiping out next year's projected $14 billion surplus and creating
an $11 billion deficit, he calculated during the recess.
</P>
<P>
   Making up that deficit could require tapping into Social
Security funds. Nevertheless, Republican leaders said Wednesday
that they were honor-bound to keep their hands off the Social
Security surplus. Meanwhile, Democrats are trying to restore
billions cut by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   They are at an impasse with 15 working days to go until the new
fiscal year begins on Oct. 1. And Congress may not be able to pass
all 13 spending bills that finance the government before then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone expects us to get through all these bills
by Sept. 30,'' the chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee,
Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of the bills are incomplete; two remain in draft. Beyond
that, the White House has threatened to veto seven bills because of
deep cuts made by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   With the deadline coming, the Republicans have three choices,
none pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   They can restore the cuts, and use billions of dollars of Social
Security funds to finance them. They can pass stopgap bills, called
continuing resolutions, temporarily financing federal agencies _ a
form of life-support system that can go on for months, but not
forever. Or they can shut down the government, and hope that voters
will not blame them next year.
</P>
<P>
   How did Congress arrive at this juncture?
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers blame themselves for passing the 1997 Balanced
Budget Act, which imposed strict spending limits on Congress and
has squeezed the spending bills, except the one financing the
military, uncomfortably.
</P>
<P>
   Out of a total federal budget of $1.75 trillion dollars, roughly
one-seventh _ about $268 billion _ has been allocated under the
caps to pay for the operations of every government agency beyond
the Pentagon. The military will get about $270 billion, and the
rest goes to mandatory programs like Medicare and interest on the
federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   Congress may have to resort to an extensive use of accounting
gimmicks to pass the bills. Wednesday Sen. Stevens said he favored
``an expanded use of an old mechanism'' that would juggle billions
of dollars to make the numbers appear to add up under the caps.
</P>
<P>
   He gave a hypothetical example of this mechanism. Say Congress
appropriates $12 billion for education. With a little legislative
legerdemain, Congress could say that $1 billion was spent in
September 2000, and $11 billion in the following 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   Then only $1 billion would count in fiscal 2000, and the rest in
fiscal 2001, the senator explained. This is perfectly legal. It is
also like putting credit card debt on another credit card.
Eventually, the bills come due.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the House began debate on a $92 billion bill
financing the Veterans Administration, the Department of Housing
and Urban Development and other agencies. It cuts about $7.6
billion from the White House's budget request, including $2 billion
from HUD, $1 billion from the space agency, and millions more from
various environmental programs.
</P>
<P>
   And the Senate once more took up a $14 billion Interior
Department spending bill. Several Republican senators have been
trying to amend the bill with measures favoring the oil, gas and
mining industries; Democrats have opposed them. Final votes on both
bills are expected on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
