<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT MEETS WITH CHINESE OVER RESUMING TRADE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ After a period of high tension between
the United States and China, the two sides met here Wednesday to
set the stage for the resumption of negotiations for China's entry
into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Five months ago, the Clinton administration rebuffed an offer
that the Chinese thought would be acceptable, and Washington has
been trying to get the talks to resume almost ever since. But
tensions only grew worse with the accidental bombing by NATO of the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, and the renewed tensions
between China and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   In the first concerted activity to get the talks going again,
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshevsky arrived here from
Washington, along with the two chief American trade negotiators who
came directly from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met with the Chinese
foreign minister, Jiaxuan Tang, for 90 minutes Wednesday morning,
for an encounter that was described by an administration official
as ``free of any acrimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Barshevsky emphasized Wednesday morning that meetings between
the Americans and the Chinese over the past day and a half in
Beijing on the trade accord were an ``ice-breaking session'' and
``very general'' in nature.
</P>
<P>
   Substantive talks about China's membership in the body that
governs world trade _ a membership that the Clinton administration
very much wants but on what it calls commercially viable terms _
had not resumed, she said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and the Chinese president, Jiang Zemin, are
scheduled to meet here on Saturday, their first face-to-face
meeting since Clinton was in China in 1998. Since then the
relationship between Washington and Beijing has plummeted to its
lowest depths in years.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials hope that the presidential discussions
on Saturday will help right the course of the relationship and
result in the resumption of serious and speedy negotiations that
would allow China to enter the trade body. A new round of global
trade talks is being held in Seattle in November. If China fails to
enter the WTO before those talks, the Chinese would most likely
face more stringent entry requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting between the two leaders has become the most
significant event of the annual economic summit of leaders of the
Asian region. They may be able to announce a resumption of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But Barshevsky said that despite the visit of her team to
Beijing this week it was still not clear what the Chinese
intentions were. ``Do they want to re-engage for the look of it or
because they want to substantively re-engage to conclude an
agreement?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   To pursue the resumption of talks further, Barshevsky was to
meet here Wednesday night with her Chinese counterpart, Foreign
Trade Minister Shi Guangshang.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, buffeted by criticism from the business
community and from some quarters in Congress for its failure to
seal a deal with China when it seemed possible in April, has been
pushing to resume the negotiations with the Chinese almost since
Clinton turned down the Chinese offer on April 8.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration has been blocked by a series of unrelated
setbacks, chiefly the bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade
and the Taiwan-China spat.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most difficult tasks for the negotiators now,
officials said, would be how to overcome the appearance that each
nation had caved to the demands of the other.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton chose not to forge a deal when Prime Minister Zhu Rongji
was in Washington in April and when an agreement was very close,
officials said, because he wanted several more concessions from the
Chinese, particularly stronger safeguards for the American textile
apparel industry and concessions in the area of insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
