<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5122 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GM-LAWSUIT09-COX     09-08 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-LAWSUIT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM hid evidence, judge says
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ General Motors Corp. defrauded the courts and
obstructed justice by withholding damaging documents in high-stakes
product liability litigation over the safety of vehicle fuel tanks,
a Fulton County judge has ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The order implicates GM's two lead law firms _ Atlanta's King &AMP;
Spalding and Chicago's Kirkland &AMP; Ellis _ because it suggests GM's
attorneys may have aided the automaker in committing fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``In certain instances GM, by and through its counsel, toyed
with and ignored court orders, ethical constraints and legal
barriers,'' Fulton County State Court Judge Gino Brogdon wrote in
an order issued late Tuesday. ``Plaintiffs have exposed a shameful
scheme by GM to defraud and mislead several courts, to thwart and
obstruct justice and to enjoy the ill-gotten gains of likely
perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   Brogdon's findings stem from a controversial collection of
lawyers' notes and memos about a crash-safety report written by GM
engineer Edward Ivey 26 years ago. GM withheld these documents from
plaintiffs for years, citing attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Brogdon ordered GM to produce the documents within five days and
said they can be used at a wrongful death trial scheduled to begin
Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Motors is disappointed by the ruling issued today by
the court,'' Atlanta lawyer William Hill of the firm Paul,
Hastings, Janofsky &AMP; Walker, which also represents GM, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Motors emphatically denies that either Mr. Ivey or
counsel for General Motors engaged in fraud on the court or
obstruction of justice,'' Hill said. ``General Motors intends to
pursue every available appellate avenue with respect to this
order.''
</P>
<P>
   The wrongful death lawsuit was filed by the widow of George Yaw
Bampoe-Parry, whose 1985 Chevrolet Chevette was allegedly clipped
in the rear on May 21, 1997, by a Volvo while he was driving north
through Atlanta on Interstate 85. The crash caused Bampoe-Parry's
fuel tank to leak and the car burst into flames, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Bampoe-Parry, a native of Ghana who operated a clothing business
and delivered pizzas, died almost three weeks later of burn-related
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Jim Butler of Columbus, who filed the suit, hailed
Brogdon's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens now is that the reckoning begins,'' he said.
``Two decades of concealing the truth and lying are coming to an
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler has contended that former GM lawyer Kenneth Starr _ the
independent counsel who investigated Whitewater and President
Clinton _ participated in concealing the Ivey-related documents.
</P>
<P>
   Before resigning as a partner at Kirkland &AMP; Ellis, Starr
represented GM in product liability litigation and successfully
argued that certain Ivey-related documents be shielded by the
courts under the attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkland &AMP; Ellis has strongly denied Butler's allegations about
Starr. In his order Tuesday, Brogdon made no mention of Starr.
</P>
<P>
   But in an unusual motion filed before Brogdon last week, GM's
legal team asked the judge to prohibit Butler from referring to
Starr during the upcoming trial. Butler filed a reply strongly
opposing that request.
</P>
<P>
   In his order Tuesday, Brogdon said the evidence of GM's conduct
in fuel-tank fire product liability litigation ``soars beyond'' the
legal threshold that must be cleared before finding that the
automaker committed fraud on the court and obstructed justice.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Ivey conducted a cost-benefit analysis of fire-related
deaths in GM vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The company engineer estimated that 500 people died annually in
GM autos ``where bodies were burnt'' and that GM could prevent such
fires and the resulting fatalities by spending $2.40 per vehicle in
safety improvements.
</P>
<P>
   After interviewing Ivey in 1981 about the analysis, one GM
lawyer wrote: ``Obviously, Ivey is not an individual whom we would
ever, in any conceivable situation, want to be identified to the
plaintiffs in a (fuel-tank fire) case and the documents he
generated are undoubtedly some of the potentially most harmful and
most damaging were they ever to be produced.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivey's analysis and notes of his interviews with lawyers have
been presented at trial on only a few occasions. In July, a
California jury that was presented with evidence on Ivey's analysis
awarded $4.9 billion in damages _ the largest product liability
verdict in U.S. history _ in a lawsuit over the explosion of a
Chevrolet Malibu gas tank in a crash. The judge presiding over that
case later reduced the jury's award by more than $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a case in Florida, a jury that considered the Ivey documents
declined to award punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   In the Fulton County case, plaintiffs attorney Butler contended
GM directed Ivey to conduct the cost-benefit study and that Ivey
shared it with other employees in GM management. GM has countered
that Ivey's report was an independent intellectual exercise riddled
with crucial flaws and errors. For this reason, GM has argued, it
has never been adopted by the company and should not be put before
a jury.
</P>
<P>
   But Brogdon expressed concern with the engineer's apparent
memory loss.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, eight years after he prepared the analysis, Ivey could
recall who likely asked him to prepare it and who at GM received a
copy of it, the judge noted. Three years later, when interviewed by
GM lawyers, Ivey's memory was still largely intact, Brogdon said,
citing lawyer notes of the interview that indicate Ivey could
recall that the analysis was not solely his idea and that it was
sent to other GM employees.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven months after those interviews, Ivey gave pre-trial
testimony on the issue for the first time. During this deposition,
Ivey ``suffered a complete memory lapse'' as to why he prepared the
report and whether the report ever left his desk, Brogdon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Common sense, logic and mother wit demand the conclusion that
something happened to prompt Ivey to abandon information he had
retained regarding the Ivey report for 14 years,'' Brogdon wrote.
``Only Ivey knows what in fact caused him to scarlet his memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivey would give similar pre-trial testimony about a dozen times
over the next decade in other product liability cases across the
country. ``The circumstances surrounding his evolving recollection
strongly suggest that Ivey willingly and unabashedly abandoned his
relationship with the truth,'' Brogdon wrote. ``The preponderance
of the evidence weighs heavily in favor of the conclusion that Ivey
lied.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Wednesday, Ivey said he was not
surprised that Brogdon's order was critical of him.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he intentionally forgot the critical information
about his analysis or whether someone persuaded him to forget it,
Ivey declined comment. ``I've been advised not to talk to the
press, as frustrating as that is to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his order, Brogdon said the record offers no proof that GM or
its lawyers put Ivey up to lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``There exists strong evidence in the record that GM, through
its lawyers, intended to explore every conceivable means of
secreting Ivey's recollection of his report from plaintiffs,''
Brogdon wrote. ``Necessarily, this universe of possible means would
include unethical and illegal means.''
</P>
<P>
   Brogdon said the record ``is simply void of any evidence that GM
or its lawyers took some specific action ... to cause Ivey's memory
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brogdon did say that GM ``covertly'' defied court orders as
to the existence of many of the documents at issue.
</P>
<P>
   When GM's lawyers initially interviewed Ivey about his
cost-benefit analysis, ``GM, by and through its counsel,
contemplated frauds,'' he wrote. In concealing the notes of these
interviews from court orders, Brogdon said, ``GM acted upon its
intent of concealing evidence regarding Ivey's memory and
successfully deprived the court of full opportunity to administer
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
