<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5125 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-600&AMP;     09-08 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY EXTOLS SMALL-TOWN VALUES IN START OF CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (js) 
 By JAMES DAO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRYSTAL CITY, Mo. _ Returning to his hometown on the banks of
the Mississippi River, former Sen. Bill Bradley formally opened his
campaign for the Democratic nomination for president Wednesday,
pledging to fight racial strife, restore trust in government and
spread the nation's prosperity to the most downtrodden Americans.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the dark sky rumbled threateningly but held back
its rain, Bradley delivered a 30-minute speech that was a paean to
small-town life, asserting that lessons learned in the classrooms
and basketball courts here had prepared him to be a more humble,
caring and selfless leader in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, above all, is not the time for complacency,'' he said,
standing outside his red-brick high school and before a crowd of
more than 2,000 banner-waving residents. ``I feel an urgency to
seize this moment in history, to strengthen the weak and to
challenge the strong to lead us into our full greatness as a
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   To many Democrats, Bradley faces an uphill fight against his
only rival for the Democratic nomination, Vice President Gore, who
has built a formidable network of party supporters in seven years
in the White House. But Bradley's campaign kick-off comes at a time
when there are indications that he is gaining steam. Gore's lead
over Bradley, a former three-term senator from New Jersey and Hall
of Fame basketball player with the New York Knicks, had narrowed to
less than double digits in two polls of New Hampshire voters
released in the past week. One was by a Dover, N.H., television
station and the second by The Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign has unsettled the vice president's advisers,
who say he has collected more money than they expected and
assembled a talented staff. ``He's gone through an important
initial phase where he has clearly gotten himself in the game,''
said Geoff Garin, a Democratic pollster. ``But there's a very big
next step in putting the substance into his themes.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bradley makes a strong run at Gore will depend heavily
on how he manages the next phase of his campaign, when he will come
under more intense public scrutiny and will be expected to release
a more detailed agenda than he has been willing to do so far.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's relatively low-key campaign may have helped him avoid
damaging controversy or criticism. But his aides say that in the
next few weeks, he will begin releasing more detailed policy
prescriptions. And those proposals, the aides hope, will lead to a
more lively debate with Gore, who has studiously avoided engaging
his Democratic rival so far, preferring to set his sights on the
leading Republican candidate, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's celebratory homecoming, Bradley avoided
mentioning Gore, at least directly. But in describing his desire to
help working families, he took what could be viewed as a veiled
shot at the Clinton administration, which has been attacked by some
liberal critics as offering too many small-bore programs to solve
big problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do fewer things,'' Bradley said. ``But they will be
essential things, and we will do them more thoroughly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley will also try to differentiate himself from Gore on
character issues, his aides say. Though his camp does not bring up
Clinton's impeachment and repeated ethical travails, they sense
that Gore will be hurt by his association with a scandal-plagued
administration. Indeed, a poll published in The Washington Post
Wednesday suggested that voters are tired of Clinton and are
looking for a president who will take the country in a new
direction.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With that in mind, Wednesday's event was intended to present
Bradley as the antithesis of a polished Washington insider _ as he
has described Gore.
</P>
<P>
   From start to finish, there was an almost studied homeyness to
the day. Many of the town's clapboard and stone houses had
home-made ``Bradley for President'' signs on their trim lawns. The
high school band that performed before Bradley's speech
occasionally played out of tune. And at a reception for in the
school gymnasium, home-baked cookies were served with iced tea.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was something paradoxical about the way Bradley's
campaign sought to cast the day as a natural outpouring of support
for a hometown favorite while also trying to orchestrate it as a
huge media event.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the morning, campaign officials wandered through the
high school halls barking orders through portable radios and cell
phones. Before the event started, aides distributed copies of
Bradley's nostalgic description of Crystal City in his memoir,
``Time Present, Time Past,'' along with a fact sheet noting the
precise number of stop lights in town: five.
</P>
<P>
   And at sunset, Bradley led reporters and town residents on a
guided tour of his boyhood haunts, including the house where he was
reared, the church where he worshiped, his father's bank and the
local baseball fields.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's parents are both dead, but he still owns the family's
house, as well as a 100-acre farm.)
</P>
<P>
   But amid all the media management, it was also clear that
Bradley has remained a revered figure here since he left 38 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could do it all on the basketball court, but he didn't try
to do it all,'' said Ralph Boyer, 65, a retired teacher and
basketball coach at the local Catholic school who saw Bradley play
in high school. ``And what made him a great ball player will make
him a great president.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Bradley described himself as a ``small-town boy''
who learned about hard work and discipline from his father and
about honesty, courage and integrity from his mother, a school
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   In the Little League, he said he learned about racism when a
black teammate was denied service at a restaurant. ``Racism
disturbed me then and still angers me now,'' Bradley said. ``For
me, the only thing deserving of hate is hate itself.''
</P>
<P>
   As president, Bradley said, he would try to redirect some of the
nation's wealth toward reducing childhood poverty and providing
affordable health care to working class and poor people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In so many ways, we have failed to use our prosperity to
improve the well-being of all our citizens,'' he said. ``Shouldn't
we be fixing our roof while the sun is shining?''
</P>
<P>
   But like many other candidates this year, including Gore, he
also spoke of his desire to address the nation's spiritual
yearnings as well as its material needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need in America is a deeper prosperity,'' Bradley
said. ``Deeper in the sense that we have a prosperity that adds up
to more than the sum of all our possessions; a prosperity that
makes us feel rich inside as well as out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
