<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5141 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-KIDS:Y2K-CLASSACTS-NY     09-08 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:Y2K-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K: COMING SOON TO A COMPUTER NEAR YOU 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By JESSAMY BROWN 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What does ``Y2K'' mean?
</P>
<P>
   It stands for ``year 2000,'' and it has come to be associated
with the potential computer problems that will occur when 2000
rolls in. (The letter K is used as shorthand for ``thousand.'')
</P>
<P>
   The terms ``millennium bug'' and ``millennium virus'' are also
nicknames for the Y2K problem, used even though the potential
problems have nothing to do with a computer virus (a computer virus
is something that is deliberately inserted into software to be
destructive.)
</P>
<P>
   What is the problem?
</P>
<P>
   When clocks around the world reach midnight on Dec. 31, 1999,
the internal clocks of computers will change from 99 to 00.
(Computer programs were made to calculate dates for years using two
digits instead of four digits; for example, instead of using 1996,
computers use ``96,'' and systems are programmed to recognize the
date as 1996.) Some computer programs might interpret the change to
00 to mean that the year is 1900, not 2000, say some computer
experts, including Doug White and Alan Rea, professors at Western
Michigan University who issued a Y2K report in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows what exactly will happen: Even experts disagree on
how severe computer malfunctions might be. But what is clear is
that society relies on computers. And if a computer doesn't
``understand'' the date, it could go haywire or get confused and
shut things down, according to Rea and White.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, major problems may occur in the United States if
computers that help control the supply of electricity, telephone
service, banking records and airline travel are affected.
</P>
<P>
   Computer glitches could knock out school crossing lights, shut
down school heaters and disable classroom computers.
</P>
<P>
   And computer chips used in household appliances such as
microwave ovens and televisions could malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   How did the problem come about?
</P>
<P>
   Computer programmers began using the two-digit year system (99)
rather than writing out the full year (1999) to save computer
memory space, which in the early years of computers was scarce and
expensive. Programmers continued this after the need for saving
space diminished. Also, because technology was advancing at such a
rapid pace, some people thought that the software would be obsolete
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't think the technology would last,'' Rea explained
in a recent phone interview. ``There are no easy answers to give.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not just change the date on every computer?
</P>
<P>
   It's not that easy. Every reference to a date in every program
and file that is in use or stored in every computer must be
changed. This is a major undertaking, and computer programmers have
been working feverishly for the past few years to meet the Dec. 31
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some computer glitches have already started. As early
as 1996, the credit-card company Visa had to recall 12 million
cards with expiration dates of 2000 after authorization systems
refused to accept the card, according to Ed Yourdon, a software
engineering consultant and Y2K activist.
</P>
<P>
   How are people preparing for problems?
</P>
<P>
   Some people expect small-scale inconveniences, like not being
able to get money from cash machines for a day or two. Others are
concerned that the problem will create major disasters, essentially
crippling government, law enforcement, medical care and other
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be neither,'' Rea said. ``I'm not so
much worried about the technology (in the United States,) but about
other countries. Internationally, there are many countries that
aren't ready. I don't think people realize how interconnected we
are and how dependent we are on technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Some families are stockpiling months' worth of food and water
and buying electric generators and guns to protect their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Elenburg has been storing food and water for about two years
and has a generator. Elenburg, who heads the Dallas Area Y2K
Preparedness Group, has converted most of his money into precious
metals and cash instead of stocks and bonds, because he is
concerned that computerized records could be wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government recommends that families prepare as they
would if a storm knocked out electricity for a few days. According
to the U.S. General Services Administration, items to have on hand
include flashlights, batteries, a battery-powered radio, food,
water and candles.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross recommends storing enough food and water
to last three days to a week.
</P>
<P>
   What is being done to prevent problems?
</P>
<P>
   Cities and businesses across the world are working to make their
computer systems ``Y2K-compliant,'' meaning fixing them to
recognize 2000 as a date. The federal government's computers and
the nation's infrastructure are in good shape, says John Koskinen,
head of the White House panel on Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
