<SLUG> BC-KIDS:BOOK:SEEDFOLKs-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK REVIEW: ``SEEDFOLKS'' 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By JANE AUSTIN, High School Student Reporter 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``SEEDFOLKS''
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: Harper Collins, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Ages: 10 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $13.95 hardcover.
</P>
<P>
   Kim wants to honor her father's memory and make him proud of
her, so she plants lima beans in the vacant lot near her house. She
wants to show him that she can be a farmer, as he was.
</P>
<P>
   Young Kim is one of 13 voices that come together to tell one
story about a community garden.
</P>
<P>
   Readers hear from Curtis, who risks being made fun of by his
friends when he grows tomato plants in the garden to win back his
girlfriend. Then there's Maricela, a pregnant 16-year-old, who
grows radishes so she can learn to take care of living things.
</P>
<P>
   I thought this was an inspiring story of motivation,
determination and teamwork. It is also interesting because each
chapter tells a first-person account of how working in the garden
helped or changed them. This book has a distinctive point of view
and vivid characters.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewer's 1 - 10 score: 7.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
