<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:MUSIC:VERVE-PIPE-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC REVIEW: CD: ``THE VERVE-PIPE'' 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By JESSAMY BROWN, with Student Reporter KATE STRICKLAND 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CD: ``THE VERVE-PIPE''
</P>
<P>
   Band: The Verve Pipe.
</P>
<P>
   Don't repeat our mistake by confusing this group with The Verve,
a British pop band that hit the charts in 1997 with a single,
``Bitter Sweet Symphony,'' from their album ``Urban Hymns.'' That
group has since broken up.
</P>
<P>
   The Verve Pipe, fronted by lead vocalist Brian Vander Ark, has a
style that's more alternative/rock than pop. The Michigan band had
a 1996 hit, ``The Freshmen,'' on the CD titled ``Villains.''
</P>
<P>
   On The Verve Pipe's album, overall, the tunes are perfect to jam
to, but a few of the topics are inappropriate for kids under 12.
There's a whole song all about a bad word. There's a nice song
about a young guy waiting for his girlfriend so the couple can
share their first kiss. It's called ``Kiss Me Idle.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't waste your allowance buying this CD. You can download the
songs from the Internet at www.thevervepipe.com.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewers' 1 - 10 score: 3.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
