<HEADER>
A5146 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-KIDS:FACES:JALEEL-WHI     09-08 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:FACES:JALEEL-WHITE-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 
 FACES: MEET JALEEL WHITE (Urkel on ``Family Matters'')  World rights. 
 By JESSAMY BROWN 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JALEEL WHITE
</P>
<P>
   Age: 22.
</P>
<P>
   Claim to fame: You knew him as Urkel. Now he stars in and
produces a new TV show, ``Grown Ups,'' on the UPN network.
</P>
<P>
   Give geeks a chance.
</P>
<P>
   As Steve Urkel on ``Family Matters'' in the early 1990s, Jaleel
White was the ultimate geek, a 5-foot-tall skinny kid with
Coke-bottle-thick glasses. His voice squeaked. He wore a bow tie,
suspenders and high-water pants.
</P>
<P>
   But White, today 5 foot 11, is all grown up now _ and he's
looking pretty, well, cool. ``Grown Ups'' is, in fact, the title of
his new fall show in which he plays J. Calvin Frazier, or ``J,'' a
single young man living in an apartment in the same building as his
longtime best friend, Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   White, who graduated from the University of California at Los
Angeles, says he's not worried about his Urkel-esque image trailing
him into the new project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I have an image that I have to outgrow or
anything,'' says White. ``I think that the bottom line is you're in
a constant state of reinventing yourself if you're in Hollywood.
Period. And I have many characters inside of me.''
</P>
<P>
   White says he gets his inspiration from watching regular,
everyday people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never taken an acting lesson in my life,'' he explains.
``I basically watch people.''
</P>
<P>
   What's his character like in the new show? Will he be doing
slapstick comedy, as he did for 215 episodes as Urkel?
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This show is less slip-on-a-banana-peel kind of comedy,'' he
says. ``So because of that, the comedy will be more verbal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
