<HEADER>
A5149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-NYT &LR;      09-08 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS-PATRIOTS: IT'S NOT JUST ANOTHER GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By GERALD ESKANAZI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Just the other day Pete Carroll conceded, in
his still boyish fashion, that, yes, the Jets do matter more than
most teams for Patriots fans.
</P>
<P>
   But what about for Carroll, the Patriots' coach, who once led
the Jets?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing to say,'' he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While that hardly echoes the general reaction regarding Sunday's
opening game at the Meadowlands, a meeting between the teams simply
does not have the revenge factor it once had for both coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a Jets-Patriots game has enough going for it now: a
season opener between division rivals, one of them picked by many
oddsmakers to go to the Super Bowl. The Jets don't need motivation
to prove themselves anymore, as they did just two years ago, when
Bill Parcells took them over after having led the Patriots to the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was New England's new coach then, his first top job
since the Jets dismissed him three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Jets have captured three straight games from the
Patriots. The Jets toppled them as division winners. The Jets are
more highly regarded these days, and are the favorites for Sunday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   So is this game different now, Carroll was asked. ``The Jets are
high-flying and on top right now,'' he answered. ``They're
obviously the team to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have enjoyed the highest percentage of season-ticket
renewals in club history, about 98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The team has sent players to the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It will star on three ``Monday Night Football'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   Keyshawn Johnson is going to be profiled in Sports Illustrated
and Parcells has been part of a cover story in GQ magazine.
</P>
<P>
   So the Jets are no longer defined by games such as the one
coming up Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But the other parts of the Jets-Patriots drama _ the revenge
factor, the hunger to defeat their old coach _ are points that
Carroll has addressed in the past, but he won't address them now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to make sure we're mentally right,'' he said,
which was as close as he would come to touching the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of time has passed from now and from when Bill
was here,'' quarterback Drew Bledsoe said Wednesday. ``There is
still some of that there _ where you want to beat your old coach
and what is now a very good football team.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is still emotion in this game, no matter how hard
Carroll tried to sidestep the overriding issue of Parcells' past,
and no matter how many times Parcells repeated Wednesday that he
was preparing for Sunday just as has for any other game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you the truth and you have to believe it,''
Parcells said Wednesday. ``I'm thinking about one week, one game,
this practice.''
</P>
<P>
   But is this game less personal now? ``Hey, I never said it was
personal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's more personal for some players than others. Ray Lucas broke
into the league at New England in 1996. ``I know that if I were
them,'' Lucas said, ``I'd want to be beating me.'' And Jets punter
Tom Tupa, the most recent former Patriot on the Jets, said ``Of
course,'' when asked whether New England players still had special
feelings playing the Parcells-led Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said of his first meeting against the Jets, in 1997: ``I
was off a little bit and was a little too pumped up for it. But
there has been some time between that and a little bit of it has
died down.''
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of people care, besides the players and coaches. The
New England news media, for instance, has requested 55 press box
seats for Sunday _ more than double the usual demand and the
highest number in club history for a regular-season road game. The
Boston Globe alone is sending six reporters to the game.
</P>
<P>
   And for members of the Jets' family, there will be an additional
boost for the game. The team will unveil a special logo on the
front of the jerseys memorializing their late owner, Leon Hess.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets manhandled the Patriots in the regular-season finale
last year at the Meadowlands. But this is a significantly different
Patriots team from that one, which started Scott Zolak at
quarterback for the sidelined Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   For Bledsoe, this will be his first regular-season appearance
since Game 14 last year. Bledsoe's shattered index finger on his
right (throwing) hand is fine now, the quarterback said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe noted that Larry Bird once had a similar injury. ``And I
guess he was an OK player,'' said the quarterback who has thrown
more passes in his first six seasons than any other player in
history. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2118EDT &QL; 
