r a BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-TEX     09-08 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY GOES HOME TO ANNOUNCE CANDIDACY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRYSTAL CITY, Mo. _ He stood at the front entrance of his old
high school Wednesday, a middle-aged valedictorian giving a
different kind of commencement address.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, a native of the ``Show-Me'' state, showed that you
can go home again when he formally launched his campaign for the
presidency Wednesday before hundreds of admirers who live in his
small hometown and consider him part of the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised here in Crystal City _ I'm a small-town boy,''
Bradley said. ``I have come back to my hometown because, for me,
this is where the world of possibility and hope all began, a world
I want to open for all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's small-town roots stand in sharp contrast to a career
spent in the spotlight. He was an All-America basketball player and
Rhodes scholar at Princeton, then was an integral part of two world
championship teams in 10 years with the New York Knicks. He entered
politics in New Jersey in 1979 and served three terms as a U.S.
senator from his adopted state.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-year-old Democrat did not seek a fourth term in 1996 and
has spent the past four years preparing for a presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   His hometown of 4,000 was decked out in a sea of red, white and
blue Wednesday, with flags, bunting and Bradley campaign signs
decorating storefronts, trees and homes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a holiday for the people of Crystal City and neighboring
Festus as their daily routine came to a halt. ``You can feel the
electricity; there is a festive air,'' said Bettie Easter, a
Crystal City resident for 12 years. ``They love Bill around here.
He belongs to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, during a reception in the school gymnasium where Bradley
honed his basketball skills, childhood friend Eddi Evans remembered
a conversation he had with Bradley during their youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 13, Bill was 12, and we were walking down Mississippi
Avenue one day,'' Evans said. ``He told me that one of these days,
`I'm going to become president of the United States.' He made me a
believer, and he's going to make believers out of all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who is often criticized as short on oratory spit and
polish, looked relaxed and at ease in front of a sea of familiar
faces that included boyhood friends, teachers and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   His speech borrowed heavily from his second book Time Present,
Time Past, as he described his affection for his hometown, his
parents (both deceased) and the values they instilled in him.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and his wife, Ernestine, spent Tuesday night in the
house on Taylor Street where he was raised. It is across the street
from Grace Presbyterian Church and a stone's throw from the
overpass that leads into quaint downtown Crystal City.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley grew up comfortably in this blue-collar setting. His
father worked his way up to bank president and his mother was a
schoolteacher, but their son is admired for his politics of
inclusion and idealism.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the American Dream is not just for the lucky among
us,'' Bradley said. ``It is not just an ideal to wish on; it should
be a possibility available to all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the American Dream for all of us _ at last.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley offered no specifics on issues Wednesday. His advisers
said he will deliver specific proposals as the campaign unfolds
this fall. Wednesday was for setting a campaign theme, and Bradley
emphasized integrity, honesty and moral fiber..MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also said that even in this time of unprecedented
prosperity, not enough Americans are reaping the benefits. He
questioned the state of the health care system, schools and the
quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``In so many ways, we have failed to use our prosperity to
improve the well-being of all our citizens,'' Bradley said.
``Shouldn't we be fixing our roof while the sun is shining?
Shouldn't we be shoring up our foundation before the rain gets in?
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel an urgency to seize this moment in history, to
strengthen the weak and to challenge the strong to lead us into our
full greatness as a nation.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
