<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      09-08 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV PROVES MOST POTENT CAMPAIGN TOOL IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By SAM DILLON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A few weeks back, when four politicians who were
seeking the governing party's presidential nomination made a joint
appearance in a sleepy town on the Pacific Coast, one candidate
stood out from the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the man we've seen on television?'' a woman asked,
arriving in a clamorous throng to see Roberto Madrazo Pintado, a
former governor of a backwater state whose television campaign had
transformed him almost overnight into the current leader of the
primary race by a narrow margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they saw Madrazo, they practically jumped him,'' recalled
a party official who attended the event in Tepic, Nayarit. ``They
didn't remember his name, but they wanted to be with him. It was
all because of his TV campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's first presidential primaries are rupturing traditions
after decades in which presidents chose their own successors.
Equally stunning, however, has been the emergence of the television
campaign commercial, a tectonic shift that is rattling the entire
system.
</P>
<P>
   The race for the governing party primary on Nov. 7 and for the
general election in July is the first nationwide campaign in which
all major parties are communicating with voters primarily through
television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Although televised presidential campaigns have been common in
the United States since the 1960s, the governing party here
introduced television campaign commercials only in 1994, and
Mexico's opposition had been unable to buy airtime until recently.
</P>
<P>
   But the government now appears to be relinquishing some control
over the airwaves, as part of a broader move toward competitive
politics and a loosening of the political system.
</P>
<P>
   The effects have rippled through the political system.
Newspapers and the government-influenced television news programs
are losing their monopoly on political information. Traditional
power brokers like labor and peasant bosses are being stripped of
their influence.
</P>
<P>
   Telegenic politicians like Madrazo and Vicente Fox Quesada, the
strongest opposition candidate, are gaining important advantages.
Also winning influence are the millionaires who are financing the
commercials. Campaign laws allow them to remain anonymous. Perhaps
the biggest winners are the media consultants and advertising
wizards who are producing the electronic campaigns. Some
presidential candidates have begun to seek media advice from
prominent American consultants, although the extent of the
foreigners' influence to date appears limited.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the standout has been Carlos Alazraki, 51, a Mexican
publicity agent who created Madrazo's commercials and whose
prestige has soared along with his client's. Rival candidates are
seeking to hire him away, and talk show hosts are soliciting his
punditry.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians and intellectuals are complaining that
television is debasing political discourse into a cacophony of
American-style sound bites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Combine money, television and the large number of Mexican
voters who are nearly illiterate, and you could elect a cow as
president,'' said Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador, a leader of the main
leftist party. Similar criticisms are being hurled at Alazraki.
</P>
<P>
   ``How valid is it to play with the ignorance of a hungry people
just to help some candidate?'' one questioner asked in a recent
Internet chat discussion with Alazraki.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican people are more intelligent than many
intellectuals and pseudo-intellectuals believe,'' Alazraki shot
back. ``You can't fool people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been attacked a lot for my campaigns,'' he said in an
interview later at his Art Deco office. ``But a publicist has to
make sure his candidate or his product wins market share. You've
got just 20 seconds to work magic, to make consumers react and make
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Because newscasts tend to flatter the president and belittle the
opposition, some analysts applaud the new television campaigns,
arguing that voters will now receive information unfiltered by
pro-government commentators. But the awesome cost of television
campaigning is another concern, because airtime is just as pricey
as in the United States, said Rafael Gimenez, a leading pollster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is going to play an even greater role, because the
plutocrats can now back candidates without deferring to the office
of the president,'' John Womack, a Harvard University historian who
studies Mexico, said. ``Candidates will have to negotiate with the
people paying for their TV time.''
</P>
<P>
   The first politician made over by television advertising was
Fox, the governor of Guanajuato from the center-right National
Action Party. Broadcasting a two-year stream of commercials that
portray him as a down-to-earth leader who is defying an
authoritarian regime, Fox has built a sweeping advantage over his
opposition rivals in public opinion. When he started, he was known
mainly by a national elite. Today more than eight of 10 Mexicans
recognize Fox's name.
</P>
<P>
   But Alazraki has worked an even more dramatic makeover on his
candidate. The son of a Mexican film director, Alazraki founded his
own agency in 1977, attracting corporate clients that include
Telefonos de Mexico and the National Lottery. His first political
race was in 1994, when he produced the commercials for Ernesto
Zedillo's victorious presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But he has attracted more attention over his work for Madrazo,
who had been mainly known because of a confrontation in 1994 with
President Zedillo over reports of fraud in his election to the
Tabasco state house. That changed after August 1998, when Alazraki
began producing commercials in which Madrazo extolled his own
efforts to build roads, comfort orphans, and nurse the sick.
</P>
<P>
   The ads turned Madrazo into a national leader, recognized by 9
of 10 Mexicans. The extraordinary success of that campaign spurred
Madrazo and other candidates to seek the advice of foreign experts
in television image making. Last month, Madrazo hired three
American media consultants, including Douglas Schoen, who has
conducted polling for President Clinton, Alazraki said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play a minor role, because they know television and
polling, but they don't know the mentality of the Mexicans,''
Alazraki said.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's preferred candidate, former Interior Minister
Francisco Labastida Ochoa, has also begun to seek television image
makers. In May, Labastida met Alazraki to sound him out about
switching candidates, but Alazraki declined. Francisco also has met
James Carville, who led Clinton's 1992 campaign, and other media
experts, but has not hired any foreigner, a campaign spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Labastida hired a Mexican company to produce
commercials that highlight his assertions of personal honesty, an
indirect jab at Madrazo's checkered ethical reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 37 years of public service, my hands are clean, and
they'll be clean all my life,'' Labastida says in his most recent
commercial. Polls show, however, that few people remember
Labastida's slogan, ``I have the will, together we'll have the
power.''
</P>
<P>
   But everywhere Madrazo goes, Mexicans greet him with his
television jingle, ``Who says it can't be done?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5154 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VIACOM-ENTERTAINMENT-     09-08 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-ENTERTAINMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS-VIACOM DEAL RAISES COMPETITION QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   King-sized media mergers like the $37.3 billion one that Viacom
Inc. and the CBS Corp. announced on Tuesday immediately provoke
cries of concern about the stifling of creativity and competition.
</P>
<P>
   Will independent producers and small studios have slimmer
chances of getting a show onto the prime-time schedule at CBS now
that CBS has three big production studios _ Paramount, Viacom and
Spelling Entertainment _ in its corporate family?
</P>
<P>
   When a hit Paramount film like this summer's ``Runaway Bride''
gets auctioned for future showing on television, will CBS have a
nepotistic edge over rival bidders?
</P>
<P>
   Television executives said Wednesday that while tinges of
favoritism might color certain deals, experience shows competition
will prevail, and they cited two reasons. One is that networks are
best served when they can choose from a smorgasbord of offerings.
The other is that Mel Karmazin, the president and chief executive
of CBS who will become the chief operating officer at the new
Viacom when the deal is concluded, has a track record of
encouraging competition within his companies.
</P>
<P>
   When he melded the Infinity radio empire with the CBS radio
network, he found himself owning competing stations in big markets.
For example, WINS-AM and WCBS-AM, the two dominant all-news radio
stations in New York, are both owned by CBS, but they continue to
operate independently and to compete with each other as they did
before the merger.
</P>
<P>
   In the elaborate food chain of network television, though,
competition is more complicated, and favoritism can be subtle.
</P>
<P>
   If CBS were to buy only Paramount shows, or if Paramount and the
other Viacom studios were to tailor their shows only for CBS,
financial disaster would be a more likely result than financial
windfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't consolidate creativity,'' said one television
industry executive. ``At the end of the day, is it a fair deal?
That's got to be the test, or nobody can succeed. You can't get too
cute.''
</P>
<P>
   But for CBS, getting cute with such Viacom partners as Spelling,
MTV or Nickelodeon Studios has to be tempting. Although the CBS
network, under Leslie Moonves' leadership, has rebuilt itself and
was the most-watched in the Nielsen household ratings this last
season (September 1998 to May 1999), it lags way behind ABC, Fox
and NBC in the competition for young viewers, the 18-to-49-year-old
audience that advertisers covet.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Paramount Television makes ``Frasier,'' one of the
biggest hits on NBC, especially with 18-to-49-year-olds. Now six
years old, ``Frasier'' has already been sold into syndication. But
say, for argument's sake, that ``Frasier'' was coming up for
renewal at NBC after the coming season.
</P>
<P>
   Would Paramount be tempted to sell it to CBS instead, to help
bolster the earnings of a Viacom corporate sibling? Or would
Paramount be better off keeping the show at NBC, where, as the
centerpiece of that network's popular Thursday-night lineup, it is
likely to fetch a greater price when sold in syndication?
</P>
<P>
   Syndication is where the producer makes a profit. Most
prime-time shows are so expensive to produce that the studios
cannot make a profit unless the show goes into syndication, meaning
its rerun rights are sold to local stations or to cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast networks _ ABC, CBS, NBC, Fox, WB and UPN _ must
keep a show on the air for four years or more to accumulate enough
episodes for syndication. If the network broadcasting the show also
has an ownership stake, then the network is more likely to pick
that show up for a fourth season and protect its syndication
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``If two shows are equal,'' one studio executive said, ``the
show you own is going to get favored when you're deciding whether
to pick up for a fourth year. But as an outsider, you only have to
fear favoritism if all other things are equal. If you have a hit
show, these things won't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``E.R.,'' the most popular show on television, were owned by
NBC instead of Warner Brothers, NBC would still have to pay
handsomely to renew it, because the others who make money from the
show's success _ producers, actors, writers _ would squawk
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   That is what happened with Tim Allen, the star of ``Home
Improvement,'' whose production company, Wind Dancer Productions,
sued Walt Disney Co. Disney had co-produced the show with Wind
Dancer, and when it came up for renewal at ABC, Allen and his
company charged that Disney, which owns ABC, gave ABC a favorable
deal and did not try to sell the show to the highest bidder. (The
litigants settled the case earlier this year, under terms that were
not disclosed.)
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Disney moved its television production studio and
its ABC network entertainment division into a joint operation,
under the same two executives (prompting Jamie Tarses, president of
ABC Entertainment, to resign), and has made it clear the studio's
first priority is to supply ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's Twentieth Century Fox Television, by contrast, and Time
Warner Inc.'s Warner Brothers Television, make a point of producing
a variety of shows for a variety of networks. And Paramount
supplies the biggest hit on the WB network, ``7th Heaven,'' even
though WB is a major rival to Paramount's corporate sibling, the
UPN network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be more like Fox than like Disney,'' said Moonves, the
president of CBS Television and former chief of Warner Brothers
studio.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Twentieth Century Fox's chief executive, Sandy
Grushow, Moonves said: ``Sandy has about 20 shows, and they're not
all on Fox. He has two with us, he has two with NBC, he has three
with ABC.''
</P>
<P>
   Paramount has shows on NBC, UPN and CBS (it already has five on
CBS, even before the merger). Viacom Productions has shows on ABC,
CBS and UPN, as well as ``Oz'' on HBO. Spelling Entertainment,
which is 80 percent-owned by Viacom, has shows on Fox, WB and UPN.
</P>
<P>
   The new Viacom will also be a powerful force in syndication
sales. Viacom owns Paramount Domestic Television. CBS owns Eyemark
Entertainment and is in the process of buying perhaps the most
powerful syndicator, King World Productions Inc., which sells
``Oprah,'' among other shows. King World's shareholders were
scheduled to vote on the deal Tuesday, but put that vote off
because of the Viacom-CBS announcement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
