<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-FRONTPAGE-1STLD-WRITE     09-08 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (EDS: Subs to add new story, U.S.-RUSSIA-LAUNDER. See skedline
below. All other Page One stories have moved.)  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, Sept. 9, Page 1. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   WACO-INQUIRY (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno has
selected former Republican Sen. John Danforth of Missouri to head
an independent investigation into the FBI's 1993 assault on the
Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (With WACO-DANFORTH, a profile of the former senator.)
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-U.S. (Washington) _ Determined to preserve its
relationship with Indonesia and support early moves towards
democracy, the United States is warning Indonesia's military leader
to end the chaos in East Timor within days or face a disruption in
relations that could undermine Indonesia's economic recovery,
according to senior administration officials. (Developing) By
Elizabeth Becker and Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN-CLINTON (Washington) _ Russian President Boris
Yeltsin told President Clinton in a telephone conversation
Wednesday that accusations linking Yeltsin and his family to a
corruption inquiry involving high-level Kremlin officials were
politically inspired, the White House said Wednesday evening. By
David Stout. (See also RUSSIA-BRIBES-YELTSIN, which will move by 10
p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 10 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TAX (Washington) _ Majority Leader Trent Lott said
Wednesday that President Clinton's promised veto of the
Republicans' $792 billion tax cut bill will likely doom any
tax-relief legislation this year. Firing the opening salvo in the
biggest legislative and political issue in Washington this fall,
Lott virtually ruled out any compromise, saying there is too little
time to negotiate a new plan for taxes and spending. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: See also CONGRESS-SPEND, which has a photo (NYT16) of
Trent Lott and other leaders.)
</P>
<P>
   QUAYLE-PROFILE (Goffstown, N.H.) _ Dan Quayle, whose slingshot
career has given him a glimpse of both the heights and depths of
American politics by the age of 52, appears to be back at the
bottom of his political trajectory. Since his eighth-place finish
in the Iowa straw poll some of Quayle's aides have signed on to
other campaigns, his old friends from the White House privately
describe his presidential ambitions as hopeless, and he is drawing
small crowds and perfunctory attention from the news media. Yet
with a tenacity that is poignant, Quayle perseveres. By Adam
Nagourney. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Dan Quayle is being sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-CLASSNOTES (Undated) _ A new Internet venture,
Studyfree, is hiring students at each of 62 universities and paying
them to take notes in about 50 core courses. The note-takers then
post their jottings on a central Web site. The 25-year-old founder
of Studyfree said he intended the service to help students augment
their own notes or to help them catch up after a sick day. But he
concedes that his wares could easily be abused by those with less
legitimate excuses, like chronic oversleeping or lingering
hangovers. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-RDP (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Indonesia on Wednesday rejected
international pressure to allow a foreign peacekeeping force to
restore order in East Timor, even as a high-level U.N. delegation
met with officials to press for action to end widespread violence
there. Despite a declaration of martial law in the territory on
Tuesday, witnesses said the situation was still worsening, five
days after an announcement that East Timor's 800,000 people had
voted overwhelmingly for independence from Indonesia. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-TRANSFORMATION (Lagos, Nigeria) _ Three months after
Africa's most populous nation inaugurated its first civilian
government in 16 years, gas stations offer perhaps the clearest
promise of what could become one of the most remarkable political
transformations on the continent. Only 15 months ago, Nigeria was
in the grip of a rapacious military regime that had turned the
country into an international pariah. Now most gas stations operate
the way an Agip station on Iju Road here does: motorists pull up to
a pump and drive away a minute later. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN (Crystal City, Mo.) _ Kicking off his campaign
with a tour of his boyhood haunts along the Mississippi, Bill
Bradley says he feels an urgent need to seize the moment in
history, and that as president, he would do fewer things, but
essential things, and do them more thoroughly than his opponents.
By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   SACKLER-CHINESE-ART (Washington) _ The Smithsonian Institution
announced Wednesday that its Arthur M. Sackler Gallery had been
left one of the leading collections of ancient Chinese art still
held privately, 5,000 pieces from the estate of Dr. Paul Singer, a
New York psychiatrist who died in 1997. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HERMAN-INQUIRY (Washington) _ President Clinton testified for an
hour Wednesday in the independent counsel investigation of
allegations that Labor Secretary Alexis Herman illegally solicited
campaign contributions for Clinton's 1996 presidential campaign. By
John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
