English as Kolkata, which is how the name is pronounced in the
Bengali language. In July, the West Bengal state assembly
unanimously agreed. (Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) CHICAGO -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- BRIDGE-OPERA-3, 09-08 --
Discussing the upcoming production of Lyric Opera's ``A View From
the Bridge,'' from left, Bill Mason, executive director; Frank
Galati, director; Amy Hutchison, assistant stage director; Wendall
K. Harrington, projection artist, and Santo Loquasto, production
designer. Lyric is preparing to stage the world premiere on Oct. 9.
(Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) CHICAGO -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- BRIDGE-OPERA-2, 09-08 --
Frank Galati, director of ``A View From the Bridge,'' addressing
the opera's cast at its first rehearsal. Lyric Opera of Chicago is
preparing to stage the world premiere on Oct. 9. (Todd Buchanan/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) CHICAGO -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- BRIDGE-OPERA-1, 09-08 -- At
the Lyric Opera of Chicago, Dennis Russell Davies, conductor,
right, with Donald Palumbo, chorus master. Lyric will present the
world premiere of ``A View From the Bridge'' on Oct. 9. (Todd
Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CD-PIRACY, 09-08 -- Buyers
examining $5 CDs at a street vendor's stand in lower Manhattan. The
recordings bore the earmarks of illegally produced copies of
legitimate CDs. (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- TEN-DAVIS-MCENROE-B&AMP;W,
09-08 -- John McEnroe strikes a triumphant pose after winning the
U.S. Open for the fourth and final time in 1984. McEnroe, perhaps
the most successful player in Davis Cup history, got his wish
Wednesday when he was appointed captain of a U.S. team that has not
won the title since 1995. ``It's one of the proudest moments of my
life,'' he says. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- OLDS-POETRY-2, 09-08 --
Sharon Olds in the study of her apartment on the Upper West Side.
Ms. Olds has written poems about a son urinating, about a daughter
on the brink of puberty. She is particularly known for her 1992
collection ``The Father,'' which chronicles in pitiless detail the
death of an abusive, alcoholic father from cancer. (George M.
Gutierrez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- OLDS-POETRY-1, 09-08 --
Sharon Olds in Riverside Park. There is almost no major American
poet whose work is as sexually explicit, and as intimately
evocative of a distinct father, husband and children as Ms. Olds,
who is the New York State Poet Laureate and who won a National Book
Critics Circle Award for 1984 for her collection ``The Dead and the
Living.'' (George M. Gutierrez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ST. CHARLES, Mo. -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CIR-INVENTORS,
09-08 -- Gary Kellmann wishes that he had had the Internet when he
tried to sell his first invention, an alarm clock that could be
turned off with a remote control. Kellmann, 30, now has four
inventions on the market, including adhesive ``belly buttons'' that
give a pierced look without the pain. (Bill Stover/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- NY-POLITICS, 09-08 -- Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani of New York escorts Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
into a restaurant in Little Italy on Wednesday. Giuliani, who plans
to run for the U.S. Senate seat from New York, is flirting
politically with several Republican presidential candidates.
(Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CONGRESS-SPEND, 09-08 --
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, center, meets with some of his
Republican colleagues to discuss the upcoming legislative agenda on
Capitol Hill, Wednesday. Senators at table from left: Craig Thomas,
R-Wyo., John Ashcroft, R-Mo., Rick Santorum, R-Pa., Jon Kyl,
R-Ariz., Lott, Bill Frist, R-Tenn., Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, Spencer
Abraham, R-Mich., and Rod Grams, R-Minn. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SAG HARBOR, N.Y. -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CULLMAN-RENOVATE-4,
09-08 -- Dorothy and Lewis Cullman posing with Scott Burton
sculptures on the lawn of their newly renovated Sag Harbor home.
The house is eclectic, but collaboratively so. (Pieter
Estersohn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SAG HARBOR, N.Y. -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CULLMAN-RENOVATE-3,
09-08 -- The newly renovated Sag Harbor home of Dorothy and Lewis
Cullman. ``Everyone who lived in East Hampton or Southampton said,
'Sag Harbor!' `` Mrs. Cullman says. ``I wanted a small house. I did
not want to be on Lily Pond, in the midst of the glitz.'' (Pieter
Estersohn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SAG HARBOR, N.Y. -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CULLMAN-RENOVATE-2,
09-08 -- The living room in the newly renovated Sag Harbor home of
Dorothy and Lewis Cullman includes Italian 1950s floor lamps,
driftwood tables and Nakashima side chairs. The Cullmans are no
strangers to transformation. With a history of philanthropy that
has changed the cultural landscape of New York City, they
constitute a two-person Who's Who at many of Manhattan's finer
institutions. (Pieter Estersohn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) SAG HARBOR, N.Y. -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CULLMAN-RENOVATE-1,
09-08 -- The saunalike bath in the newly renovated Sag Harbor home
of Dorothy and Lewis Cullman. ``I love change,'' says Mrs. Cullman,
75, with visceral relish, as though she were describing her
favorite food, the kind you have to dig out of a shell. (Pieter
Estersohn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CIR-GEEK-NOTES, 09-08 --
Daniel Shiffman, computer ``geek,'' in his Canal Street loft.
Shiffman is a financial planner and a freelance computer consultant
who likes to play video games. In today's computer-driven culture,
the once-derogatory term ``geek'' has been proudly reclaimed.
(Susan B. Markisz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 09-08
-- A ceiling fan can help keep a room cooler in the summer and
warmer in the winter. It uses less power than an air-conditioner,
so it can help keep electrical bills down. (Edward R. Lipinski/New
York Times Illustration) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- ECOMMERCE, 09-08 -- Internet
customers are not just buying books anymore. They have quickly
moved past life insurance and airplane tickets and are surfing for
furniture: poufs and pillow-back sofas, writing desks and ergonomic
office chairs. (Montage by Tony Cenicola and Shelley Camhi/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 8, 1999 --
BOOKS-POTTER-ART-BOS, 09-08 -- Terri Schmitz, of Children's Book
Shop, organizes copies of ``Harry Potter and the Prisoner of
Azkaban'' on Tuesday which have already been sold but were not
allowed to be released to the public until Wednesday. Created by
author J.K. Rowling, Harry Potter may be more than a fictional boy
wizard whose adventures beguile children and adults alike; the
Potter books are also an Internet phenomenon, one that may change
the way books are marketed and sold, and one that has given some
British Internet booksellers an advantage over brick-and-mortar
rivals in the United States. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WILMINGTON, Mass. -- Sept. 8, 1999 --
HKN-BRUINS-BURNS-BOS, 09-08 -- Boston Bruins Coach Pat Burns, left,
and Harry Sinden, the team's general manager, watch their team
practice from the stands earlier this week. When asked if he was
worried about his players turning a deaf ear to Burns's instruction
at any point this season, Sinden replied: ``He's kind of hard to
tune out.'' (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) EAST THETFORD, Vt. -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- VERMONT-ADOPT-BOS,
09-08 -- Paul and Charlene Chatot hold up a photo of Tesfalem, a
four-year old boy from Ethiopia they are trying to adopt. Throught
the Ethiopian Adoption Project, dozens of families from across
Vermont, like the Chatots, have agreed to adopt 60 children
orphaned by Ethiopia's war with neighboring Eritrea. (Mark
Wilson/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CIR-TWILO, 09-08 -- Steve
Dash by his sound equipment at Twilo, a club he owns along with
Phil Smith in Manhattan's Chelsea neighborhood. Dash and Smith not
only run Twilo, but in the past 15 years, through their affiliated
company Phazon, have also designed and installed sound systems in
more than 200 dance clubs around the world. (Thomas Dallal/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) QUINCY, Mass. -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CIR-EBAY-LIVING-2,
09-08 -- Chris Gwynn with his action figures. Gwynn, who quit his
job as a marketing analyst with the Yankee Group in Boston to sell
refrigerator magnets on line, has now branched out to auctioning
new action figures and has created his own site to sell them. More
and more people are making a living from on-line auctions, often
closing their brick-and-mortar stores or quitting jobs to vend
bric-a-brac electronically at auctions like the ones at Ebay,
Amazon.com and Yahoo. (Michael Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BALTIMORE -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CIR-EBAY-LIVING-1, 09-08 --
Fred Parks in his studio last week. For eight years, Parks sold all
manner of antiques and collectibles from several stores in
Baltimore. Now, he has lowered his expenses and increased profits
by selling exclusively on Ebay, the online auction house. More and
more people are making a living from on-line auctions, often
closing their brick-and-mortar stores or quitting jobs to vend
bric-a-brac electronically at auctions like the ones at Ebay,
Amazon.com and Yahoo. (Ann Grillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CIR-TALKING-CAR, 09-08 --
The dashboard component of the Clarion Auto PC which reads you the
news, tells you when to turn left and lets you know if email has
arrived. Of course, someone at the wheel would have to read this
admonition to keep their eyes on the road in order to be warned.
(Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW York -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- AGUILERA-POPSTAR, 09-05 --
Christina Aguilera before a performance at RCA Records in
Manhattan. At 18, Ms. Aguilera has had the No. 1 pop single in the
nation for five weeks, ``Genie in a Bottle.'' Her first album,
named after herself, is now making its debut, coupled with a
autograph signings, television appearances and interviews in New
York and Los Angeles, all intended to make her a major star.
(Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
