<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- INGRAM-WARNING, 09-08 --
Ingram Micro Inc., the world's biggest wholesale computer
distributor, warned that its profit for the third quarter would not
meet analysts' forecasts and said it was seeking a replacement for
its chief executive, Jerre Stead, the former AT&AMP;T executive who
gained attention by agreeing to work for no salary, only stock
options. The stock, which went public at $18 and was at $54 last
fall, fell below the offering price on Wednesday. Stead is seen in
an undated file photo. (Ingram Micro Inc./New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) CALCUTTA, India -- Sept. 8, 1999 -- CALCUTTA-NAME, 09-08
-- Sunil Gangopadhyay, a novelist and poet, at his home.
Gangopadhyay is part of a determined clique of Bengali
intellectuals who recently proposed that the city be known in
English as Kolkata, which is how the name is pronounced in the
Bengali language. In July, the West Bengal state assembly
unanimously agreed. (Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
