<HEADLINE>
A PAINSTAKING WEEK IDENTIFYING RARE ENCEPHALITIS IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was just the kind of phone call the New York City
Health Department welcomes, however troubling: Dr. Deborah S.
Asnis, an infectious disease specialist at Flushing Hospital in
Queens, called to report she had two elderly patients with symptoms
suggesting neurological illness. It might be botulism, a deadly
form of food-borne illness, or Guillain-Barre syndrome, a form of
paralysis. But it looked more like encephalitis, a potentially
fatal inflammation of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Health Department officials encourage calls like this, in hopes
they will reduce chances of missing an outbreak of an unusual or
dangerous disease. This call set in motion intensive medical
sleuthing that led to the discovery of the first cases of St. Louis
encephalitis ever in New York City. The detective work is expected
to continue for weeks as baffled federal and local health officials
seek an explanation for how the outbreak occurred and how to
prevent its recurrence.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the Health Department said another death
from the virus had been confirmed, bringing the total to three. In
all, nine cases of St. Louis encephalitis have been confirmed, and
48 more cases are under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marcella Layton, the head of the Health Department's Bureau
of Communicable Diseases, took that first call on Monday, Aug. 23.
Dr. Asnis told her that tests of the patients' spinal fluid
suggested a viral infection, either meningitis or encephalitis. Dr.
Layton urged Dr. Asnis to send specimens of the patients' spinal
fluid and blood to the New York State Health Department laboratory
in Albany for additional tests to detect a virus.
</P>
<P>
   Summer is the season for certain infections of the central
nervous system caused by viruses like ECHO or Coxsackie. One
possibility was Eastern equine encephalitis, a type occasionally
seen near New York. That afternoon, Dr. Layton sent an
epidemiologist to the hospital to review the charts of the two
patients and to try to find a link between them.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Aug. 24, Dr. Layton's staff discussed the cases at
its regular weekly meeting to review ongoing investigations of
outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
   But even as they were reviewing the information they had, more
cases were occurring, unbeknown to them.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Aug. 27, Dr. Layton and her associate, Dr. Annie
Fine, called Dr. Asnis to discuss her two patients. There has been
a third, Dr. Asnis told them, and even as the three doctors were
speaking, another doctor interrupted to tell Dr. Asnis of a fourth
case.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, Dr. Layton called the Federal Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta to discuss the
possibility of botulism. Dr. Layton considered the diagnosis
unlikely because most of the patients had a fever, which generally
is not a feature of botulism. CDC experts agreed. But a test was
done to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Aug. 28, a fifth case was reported from another
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Layton and Dr. Fine, concerned about the small but growing
number of cases, went to Flushing Hospital to review the patients'
charts. ``As we were sitting in the hospital we heard of another
case,'' the sixth, Dr. Layton said.
</P>
<P>
   The six patients' symptoms were not identical. Nevertheless, Dr.
Layton and Dr. Fine said they were struck by certain similarities
of clinical and laboratory findings. All the patients had been
active and healthy with only minor medical problems before this new
illness. Now muscle weakness was a striking feature. Fever and
mental confusion were also present, but in varying degrees.
</P>
<P>
   By now the Health Department doctors were worrying about a
possible widespread problem. They issued an e-mail bulletin asking
doctors at other hospitals in New York City to report patients with
a similar illness.
</P>
<P>
   That Saturday, Dr. Layton and Dr. Fine interviewed patients'
families. But there were no common threads _ no other illnesses in
the same household or among their friends, no recent travel, trips
to the same beaches, or shopping, eating or socializing at the same
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only common thread was they spent time outdoors in their
backyards,'' Dr. Layton said. ``Some were gardeners.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Layton went to her office that Saturday night to consult
textbooks for information on encephalitis, so she and Dr. Fine
could review it.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, St. Louis encephalitis virus became a strong suspect
in part because of its tendency to cause more severe illness among
older people. It is most common in the Southern and Western states,
although a small number of cases have been reported in upstate New
York as far north as the Canadian border over the years. But it had
never been reported in New York City. The infection is usually
transmitted by certain breeds of mosquitoes that usually feed on
migratory birds. Humans are infected as bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, Aug. 29, Dr. Layton and Dr. Fine were on the
phone to the CDC's emergency number, and then to Dr. Duane J.
Gubler, an expert in arboviruses, which are spread by insects, at
CDC's field station in Fort Collins, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
