<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5173 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-NY-ENCEPHALITIS-N     09-08 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NY-ENCEPHALITIS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: Fort Collins, Colo.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their suspicions were focusing on St. Louis encephalitis, and
tests of blood and spinal fluid confirmed them last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Now that they know what caused the outbreak, the doctors want to
know why it happened here, and why now. ``Queens is not where you
expect it to occur,'' Gubler said in an interview. ``The key
question is: Why did it occur in the summer of 1999?''
</P>
<P>
   To help solve the mystery, the federal center is joining with
New York State and City health officials to expand the team of
epidemiologists, virologists, entomologists and other scientists.
This week they are studying the ecology of mosquitoes and birds and
trying to determine the extent of the outbreak in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, such investigations are aided by information from
Health Department surveillance programs aimed at detecting unusual
activity of birds and the insects that transmit viral diseases to
them and humans. New York City, however, has not had an arbovirus
surveillance system in place because of the rarity of transmission
of such viruses in the city, the health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists will go into the areas of known and suspected viral
transmission to determine the density and distribution of
mosquitoes there and to collect a variety of bird species. The
collections will be sent to Albany and Fort Collins for viral
tests.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of all the testing is to document the species of
mosquitoes and birds involved in the transmission of the virus,
determine whether spraying efforts have been effective, and find
out what environmental factors might have led mosquitoes to breed
in larger numbers this year.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely culprit is the Culex pipiens mosquito, Gubler
said; the hypothesis is that mosquitoes in New York City bit
infected birds migrating from Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   Textbooks say that the following climatic scenario favors the
transmission of St. Louis encephalitis virus: a relatively mild
winter, wet spring and hot, dry summer. Although they fit the
conditions in New York City this year, many places have had similar
weather, abundant mosquitoes and no encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Global warming has nothing to do with'' the outbreak in New
York City, Gubler said.
</P>
<P>
   Although infected mosquitoes can carry the virus during the
winter and transmit it next year, it is impossible to predict
whether St. Louis encephalitis will reappear next summer, Gubler
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
