<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5174 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VIACOM-CBS-NEWS-ART-N     09-08 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-CBS-NEWS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS NEWS MAY FACE MORE CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For people at the news division of CBS, corporate
takeovers and the attendant cost-cutting are nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   They saw it in 1995, when Westinghouse Electric bought the
network. And they saw it during the nine-year reign of the man who
made that deal with Westinghouse, Laurence A. Tisch, whose Loews
Corp. was a major stockholder of CBS. So when it comes to cutbacks
in newsgathering operations, CBS News has been there and done that.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the news division will have to do it
again, now that Viacom and CBS have announced their $37.3 billion
merger. ``The news division suddenly becomes very small slice of a
very large corporate pie,'' said Ken Bode, who was a national
political correspondent for NBC when it was acquired by GE in 1986,
and, who is now the dean of Northwestern University's Medill School
of Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The president of CBS News, Andrew Heyward, ``is putting a good
face on it,'' Bode said. ``But privately, he has to be worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyward, though, does not sound worried. ``If you look at
today's media world,'' he said in a telephone interview, ``the
survivors and the thrivers are going to be those companies that
operate successfully across many media. Very clearly this company
has a track record that indicates it's going to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, since big corporations began to take over the three
major broadcast networks _ including GE's acquisition of NBC, and
ABC's sale, first to Capital Cities in 1985 and then to the Walt
Disney Co. in 1995 _ network news divisions have been gradually
recast as profit centers.
</P>
<P>
   The new emphasis is on the prime-time news magazine genre of
journalism, and there is a disinclination to underwrite the
expensive infrastructure of foreign bureaus and full-time
investigative or documentary news units that once were centers of
prestige, if not profit. CBS, in particular, has been through at
least two painful bouts of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is becoming pretty old hat for those of us in the
television news business,'' said one journalist who has worked at
both ABC and CNN, a unit of Time Warner Inc., and spoke on
condition that his name not be used. ``We've all been taken over
and merged so many times, we're used to seeing a lot of our old
friends go off and do something else for a living.'' What is most
unsettling, he added, ``is the fear of what might happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Heyward at CBS indicated that, if anything, the network's
news division has been more stable lately than in much of the past
decade. And he noted that, even with Viacom's acquisition of CBS,
the same people will continue to determine the news division's
destiny: Leslie Moonves, the president of CBS television, and Mel
Karmazin, who became the chief executive of CBS last year and is to
serve as president and chief operating officer of the proposed new
company, under Viacom's chairman, Sumner M. Redstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maintaining an editorially independent news division is easier
to do when the company is thriving,'' Heyward said. ``And Les and
Mel have been respectful of our goals and out editorial
integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate about the future of network news divisions in the
corporate era between pessimists and optimists is not a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Bode, argue that the best days of the news divisions
were in the era before corporate cost controls, when each network
sent correspondents to 8 or 10 foreign postings and the evening
news broadcasts were heavy with news from branches of the federal
government and from foreign capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, argue that it was a waste of money to have all
three networks getting the same film from the same news conference
in the same foreign capital, when the video now often supplied by
Reuters or APTV would suffice.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating that kind of redundant coverage, they argue, was no
loss, and the savings can be channeled into other coverage. More
broadly, they say, news itself has changed, particularly in the
years since the Cold War ended.
</P>
<P>
   With the rise of three all-news cable channels and the Internet,
``there are more different kinds of news and information available
to viewers than there ever were before,'' Heyward said. ``Even in
the so-called golden days of network news, there were huge areas of
life that were being woefully undercovered _ like the women's
movement. I think there was a very narrow definition of what was
considered news.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, point to episodes in recent years when network
news decisions have seemed to serve the interests of a division's
corporate parents.
</P>
<P>
   One well-publicized example was the decision in November 1995 by
the CBS news magazine ``60 Minutes'' not to broadcast an interview
with Jeffrey S. Wigand, the former head of research for the Brown &AMP;
Williamson Tobacco Co. CBS lawyers feared the prospect of a
multibillion-dollar lawsuit from Brown &AMP; Williamson at a time when
Tisch was in the final stages of selling CBS to Westinghouse. The
interview was broadcast three months later.
</P>
<P>
   But Don Hewitt, the executive producer of ``60 Minutes,'' said
in an interview Wednesday that the Wigand episode was atypical.
``With the exception of the tobacco story, which was so out of the
mainstream of anything that's happened here, I've never seen us
knuckle under to anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At ABC News last year, an investigative report intended for the
``20/20'' broadcast, involving accounts of pedophilia and lax
security at theme-park resorts, including Walt Disney World, was
derailed. The network remained close-mouthed about its reasons, and
executives at ABC's owner, Disney, said in a statement they had no
role the the decision.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, with two corporate takeovers behind it, ABC News
provides fodder for both the pessimists and the optimists.
</P>
<P>
   Like its rivals, ABC News has closed foreign bureaus and
investigative units over the years. But it has continued to plow
resources into its highly regarded ``Nightline'' program, and its
evening news broadcast, ``World News Tonight'' once a perennial
ratings laggard, has been the top-rated news broadcast for most of
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have discontinued the Close-Up unit and closed a couple
of foreign bureaus,'' said Eileen Murphy, a spokeswoman for ABC
News. ``But there are many, many units of our news division that
have grown significantly in the past 10 or 15 years, including our
huge presence on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   At NBC News, Alex Constantinople, a spokeswoman said, ``There is
no major news story anywhere in the world that a viewer would miss
watching any of our programs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
