u f BC-SUMMERS-TREASURY-NYT &LR;      09-08 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMERS-TREASURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGING THE DOLLAR WILL BE SUMMERS FIRST BIG TEST AT TREASURY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In his two months as secretary of the Treasury,
Lawrence Summers has tried to leave no daylight between his
policies and those of his predecessor, Robert Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Rubin's approach was considered stellar both on Wall
Street and in Washington, and that Summers was his deputy for four
years, it seems a logical approach. It was on full display
Wednesday when Summers made his first major speech in his new job,
to the Economic Club of New York, and broke no new ground on
domestic or international issues.
</P>
<P>
   The question now, though, is whether an evolving economic
situation and intensifying political pressures will allow Summers
the luxury of leaving policy on automatic pilot.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration faces a showdown with the
Republican-controlled Congress in the next two months over how to
apportion projected federal budget surpluses. The administration
will have to make tough choices about how hard to push its free
trade agenda, balancing a growing trade deficit against its desire
to bring China into the world trading system and start a new round
of trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
   The White House will work to help keep the political
deterioration and repression in Indonesia from derailing the
nascent economic recovery in the rest of Asia, while trying to
defuse criticism from Republicans that it has turned a blind eye to
Russian corruption.
</P>
<P>
   In all these debates, Summers will be in the middle and will
have considerable opportunity to put his own stamp on the job.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue where he is most on the spot is in managing the
administration's policy on the dollar, which is shaping up as the
first big test of his ability to step into Rubin's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin's tenure as treasury secretary was marked as much as
anything by his advocacy of a strong dollar, an approach that
contributed to the economic prosperity and bull market of recent
years by helping to keep import prices low and to attract a flood
of capital to the United States from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some doubts on Wall Street about Summers' commitment to
keeping the dollar as strong as it has been, he has so far given no
indication that there will be the slightest change in policy.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Wednesday and in a separate interview, Summers
repeated word for word Rubin's mantra that a strong dollar is in
the interests of the United States, and said that policy would not
be determined by short-term considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the secrets of our success has been that we have not
tried to manage economic policy to the markets, but instead have
focused on strengthening economic fundamentals,'' he said in the
interview. ``Certainly that is the approach I will take.''
</P>
<P>
   But when speaking generally about the process of emerging from
Rubin's shadow, Summers suggested that while his goals remained the
same, the course he will take to get there might have to be
adjusted along the way. Events in the real world, he said, could
ultimately force him to reassess the way he approaches all the big
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important themes and principles that have guided our
policies _ fiscal discipline, international engagement, a
commitment to making the economy work for people, managing
government well _ those principles require constant new application
as circumstances change,'' Summers said in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Circumstances are certainly changing in the economic backdrop
for dollar policy. As a result, questions on Wall Street about
Summers' commitment to a strong dollar are being joined by
questions about whether it is possible or even desirable to keep
the dollar strong _ through intervention in foreign exchange
markets, higher interest rates or other tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin was able to keep the dollar strong over the last few years
without much difficulty because the economies of most other big
nations were weak or weakening, making the United States the
logical place for investors to keep their money. Now, most of the
rest of the world, including Japan and Europe, is rebounding
economically _ attracting capital that would have been invested in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the nation's trade and current-account
deficits are rapidly increasing, creating an imbalance that many
investors and analysts fear could eventually lead to a weaker
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   With the trade deficit growing _ and the 2000 election campaign
already heating up _ there is bound to be pressure from exporters
and labor groups to fight the loss of sales and jobs to foreign
competitors by weakening the dollar, which would make American
goods cheaper to foreign buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 111.08 Japanese yen in late trading Wednesday,
up slightly for the day but down from its 1999 peak in May of more
than 124 yen to the dollar. After strengthening through the first
half of the year against the major European currencies, the dollar
weakened over the summer against the euro before leveling off
again. Wednesday, it settled at $1.0595 to the euro, compared to
its strongest level just over $1.01 in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamentals do not line up for the dollar they way they
did before,'' said Allen Sinai of Primark Decision Economics. ``The
question for Summers, from a market point of view, is whether what
he says about the dollar, if he says anything at all, is credible
against the reality of the changed situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, investors seem to be testing Summers, pushing the
dollar down against the yen as if to dare him to back up his words
with action and disprove their doubts about his resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the influence of Rubin, Larry Summers has
credibility,'' said David Hale, an economist at Zurich Kemper
Investments. ``But the dollar is a sensitive area for him. There
are a large number of people out there who believe that in his
heart of hearts, Larry Summers wants to devalue the dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Hale said that some of the suspicions about Summers' resolve
stemmed from a historical pattern in which Treasury secretaries who
came from backgrounds on Wall Street, like Rubin, presided over
periods of dollar strength, while secretaries from other
backgrounds saw the dollar fall on their watch. Summers is an
academic economist.
</P>
<P>
   By this theory, those from outside Wall Street _ people like
James A. Baker III, the Texas lawyer who served under President
Reagan, and Lloyd W. Bentsen, the former senator from Texas who was
Rubin's predecessor under President Clinton _ are more sympathetic
to arguments that a weaker dollar can help stimulate exports and
protect jobs at home.
</P>
<P>
   If the dollar is shaping up as a test of Summers' economic and
financial acumen, dealing with economic policy toward Russia may
prove to be the first big test of his ability to operate in a
political minefield.
</P>
<P>
   A federal investigation into whether money from Russia was
laundered through the Bank of New York has prompted criticism from
some Republicans that the administration, and the Treasury
Department in particular, have not been tough enough in demanding
that government in Moscow crack down on corruption. With elections
next year, analysts say the issue could well lead to pressure on
the administration to scale back Russian financial aid through the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``To quarantine Russia, or to write it off as some have
suggested, would I think be a potentially disastrous error,''
Summers said. ``The policy challenge is to find a balance between
being supportive of the Russian people, in whose support for market
democracy we have an enormous stake, while at the same time
protecting our own basic interests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
