<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGERS-ACCOUNTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTING BOARD MOVES TO BAN `POOLING' IN MERGED COMPANIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By MELODY PETERSEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite opposition from Wall Street investment bankers and
numerous big companies, the Financial Accounting Standards Board
released a proposal Thursday that would ban an accounting method
used in many of the largest recent corporate mergers and
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The board, which sets the nation's accounting standards, said it
planned to eliminate the accounting method, which is known as
pooling of interest, because it had confused investors and been
abused by some companies.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the pooling method, including federal securities
regulators, say that by employing pooling, corporate executives can
use shareholders' money to make expensive acquisitions, but never
disclose the price of those decisions in the company's financial
reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a pooling,'' said Edmund L. Jenkins, chairman of the
accounting board, ``an investor can't tell what price was actually
paid for the companies to merge, nor can they track the
acquisition's subsequent performance.''
</P>
<P>
   But many companies and Wall Street deal makers have come to rely
on pooling accounting because it allows merging companies to avoid
expensive charges that reduce future earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Those charges must be reported in the only alternative method,
known as purchase accounting. They relate to the intangible asset
known as goodwill, which is the difference between the price paid
for a company and the value of its assets. The goodwill can amount
to billions of dollars in mergers of large companies and must
slowly be written off over the years, hurting the acquiring
company's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Under pooling accounting, on the other hand, rather than record
the price paid for a company, the acquiring company combines the
other company's financial statements with its own.
</P>
<P>
   Pooling accounting has been used in deals like those between
Exxon and Mobil, Daimler-Benz and Chrysler, and Allied Signal and
Honeywell.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accounting board's proposal, companies now get 90 days
to comment. In an unusual move, the board said it would hold public
hearings on the plan in February in both New York and San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting board said it expected the new rules to be
effective for mergers or acquisitions announced after Jan. 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts and investment bankers contend that a ban on
pooling would slow the whirlwind of mergers and acquisitions now
taking place.
</P>
<P>
   In a report this summer, Merrill Lynch said the elimination of
pooling would be a ``serious mistake'' that could discourage
mergers that were otherwise strategically sound.
</P>
<P>
   However, some analysts say that if pooling accounting is banned,
the impact will not be so great. Gabrielle Napolitano of Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co. said that she did not believe that a ban on pooling
would significantly slow the overall pace of mergers and
acquisitions. Only a few industries may be affected, she said,
including advertising, health-care information technology, medical
devices and precious metals.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting board appeased some of its critics recently by
proposing changes to purchase accounting and the related reporting
of goodwill to make it more appealing to companies.
</P>
<P>
   It proposed allowing companies to show the annual reductions to
earnings caused by the amortization of goodwill as a separate line
on their financial statements. That means that investors will be
able to see how much the company earned from its daily business
activities before that amount is reduced by the goodwill charges.
</P>
<P>
   The board also recently proposed that companies be allowed to
write off the value of the goodwill over 20 years; earlier it had
suggested a 10-years. Allowing a longer write-off period lessens
the hit to companies' bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Willens, a managing director at Lehman Brothers, another
Wall Street investment bank, said that he believed that the board
had quieted many of its opponents by allowing for the separate
disclosure of goodwill amortization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposition will be strong,'' Willens said. ``Many people
are saying, `Why fix the present system? It's served us well.' But
I don't think it will be nearly as vociferous as it might have
been.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
