<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5184 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CARROLL-     09-08 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CARROLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETE PLAYS THE MEDIA GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Pete Carroll has never wanted to act the
same way as Bill Parcells at daily Patriots press conferences.
Carroll just wanted to coach and not worry about the media or the
fans.
</P>
<P>
   But he must now realize there was a method to Parcells's
madness: If he entertained the media and gave them all they wanted,
the players would be left alone and free of the hype that surrounds
big games.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Carroll became that act.
</P>
<P>
   It probably wasn't planned or contrived. In fact, three-quarters
of his press conference Wednesday consisted of many short, concise
answers. He appeared unwilling to give any details on subjects he
felt were top secret just a few days before Tuna Bowl V at the
Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   But Carroll grew animated when questions were asked about his
demeanor, his growth as a coach, and his new style. It was a
relatively old topic, one which had been discussed aplenty during
training camp, but his responses this time were different and
entertaining. Nothing the players could have said would have
matched or topped it. It was just like Parcells used to act.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his comfortable manner and high confidence,
Carroll asked, ``There's no deer in the headlights here?''
</P>
<P>
   some Carroll detractors have used that phrase in describing the
look on his face on the sidelines or after a loss.
</P>
<P>
   He boldly said he doesn't care what the media or the fans think
because he feels he's doing the job he was hired to do. He's acting
confident and cocky and even predicted, ``We're gonna win this.''
He's carried this bulldozer mentality throughout the offseason and
into the preseason, and he's not backing off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are saying how come you're not backing off of it;
aren't you afraid of it? Uh . . . uh. I'm feeling a little
dangerous right now. A little dangerous,'' said Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get into their (the players') minds and do a great
job with these guys. I have a part and they have a part. If we
connect real well and collaborate the way it's necessary to, we
have enough good things around here to make great things happen,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a really good offseason for me,'' Carroll continued.
``It's been . . . I'll tell you this quite frankly . . . a
tremendous offseason of introspection . . . of evaluation. The
process of getting right before the season to present myself to
this team and the tasks which are ahead. I'm excited about what
we're doing, I'm excited about what we're up against this season.
</P>
<P>
   I like the tone . . . it sounds like the odds are stacked
against us. I'm pumped about it. If you're seeing something that
you see is different, I told you a while ago, each year we grow
with this and there's no question that you grow with this community
that follows us, the fans and the media and all of that. I've come
to highly regard them and I respect where they're coming from and
what they want. And I kind of dig what we're up against right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're seeing that . . . I hope you're seeing me at my best
and what I best represent. I'm looking forward to the thing and I
don't care how tough it is, or how challenging it is, or what the
odds are, I think we're going to get something great done. That's
how I'm going about it and I don't care what you think, or what you
feel about that, you can't change me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Carroll is ``fired up,'' why aren't his players always
following? Will this highly excitable version of Carroll rub off on
the players?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to ask them. I've been jacked and fired up about
eerything we've done about this season. I don't know if they sense
it, but in time they will. If that helps them good. If it doesn't,
I don't care about it. That isn't important to me. I know I'm going
to do a great job at what I'm doing. I'm excited about it and what
a great way to get started, is this great or what? We'll see how it
turns out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The oddsmakers don't give Carroll's team much of a chance this
week _ already, the Patriots are 6 1/2-7 point underdogs. The
Patriots have lost the last three meetings against Parcells, and
one would think with only 24 of his old players remaining he would
not have such an effect on them anymore. But who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has to avoid either a letdown after a win or a letdown
before the game. He needs to be able to transfer the fire he feels
to his team. If he can do that, he'll have succeeded in ridding the
noose around his neck that has been there since he took the
coaching reins in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out fine the first year. We came out fine from the
Denver problem,'' said Carroll, whose '97 Patriots started 4-0 and
then lost to the Broncos, 34-13. In 1998, the Patriots lost, 27-21,
at Denver and then won four straight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned that loss into four wins or whatever after that.
We'll find out how strong we are mentally. Looking at things from
the bright side; we look at this like we're getting a great win on
the road, I'm concerned about us coming back and being focused and
playing the next game (vs. Indianapolis) at the same level as that
one and better. It's not a one game season and we can't approach it
that way. Everybody else can, but we can't,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that he expects Drew Bledsoe to lead the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be an exciting time for the Patriots, and Drew
will be leading the charge and if he doesn't, I'll be surprised,''
said Carroll. ``Drew will have to have a good game. In preseason he
threw a touchdown pass to Terry (Glenn) and he got hammered as he
threw it. I said, `You got hit pretty good,' and he responded,
`Sometimes you've got to take a hit like that.' That showed me a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Carroll well, such as Carolina coach George
Seifert, claim this is the Carroll he knew as his defensive
coordinator for two years in San Francisco calling him ``one of the
most energetic coaches I've ever been around.''
</P>
<P>
   But will that energy transfer? Will the players ever get it as
much as he does?
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is do the best I can about the stuff I'm doing .
. . and I feel really good about it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
