<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5186 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-BOOKS-AZR     09-08 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-BOOKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
``A STAR CALLED HENRY'' &QL; 
By Roddy Doyle (Viking, $24.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You'll forgive us if we cut to the chase: This is one of the
best novels we've read all year, and better than Doyle's previous
books, although they were fine indeed. It's broader, richer than
``Paddy Clarke Ha Ha Ha,'' and less introspective than the somber
``The Woman Who Walked into Doors.'' Doyle's narrator is Henry
Smart, who tells us the story of the first 20 years of his life. He
begins just before the turn of the century with the meeting of his
parents, a teenage maker of rosary beads and a one-legged bouncer
who turns lowlifes away from a Dublin brothel. They are doomed, and
we know it _ babies arrive sick and die, poverty closes in, and we
see their love fade into the dirt and disease of the Dublin slums.
But before it does, Henry Smart is born, handsome, inexplicably
healthy and full of a promise that is too bright for such a dark
place. By the time he is 5, he is living on the streets, smart but
illiterate, and aware of his own gritty charm. When he is 14, he
takes part in the Easter Rising of 1916, and later becomes a
terrorist for the Irish Republican Army. Through it all, Henry's
savvy, rock-confident voice gathers us in. We know he is telling us
a true story, and yet at the same time spinning a tale _ he
survived childhood, after all, by dazzling and conning the adults
around him. In the end, ``A Star Called Henry'' is not just a novel
about one man but about Ireland itself, from a gifted writer who
knows that misery and laughter are not strangers to one another,
and that even the most rancorous place is not a hell if dreams are
still alive there. This is the first volume of a trilogy that will
take readers through modern Irish history by way of the life of
Henry Smart _ and won't we be glad to see him again. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``FOOTBALL'S GREATEST PLAYERS'' &QL; 
(Sporting News, $29.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `Make sure when anyone tackles you he remembers
how much it hurts,' '' John Mackey said. ``He lived by that
philosophy and I always followed that advice.'' Mackey was talking
about Jim Brown, the Cleveland Browns' offensive powerhouse from
1957 to 1965 and the man this book calls ``the greatest pure runner
in the history of the NFL.'' Brown is top dog on the list of the
100 best football players of all time, compiled by editors of the
``Sporting News.'' Unlike its counterpart, last year's ``Baseball's
100 Greatest Players,'' this volume doesn't dabble much in the
early days, although the list has Jim Thorpe (at No. 88), Bronko
Nagurski (35), Don Hutson (6) and Otto Graham (7). Among the top 10
are Joe Montana, Jerry Rice, Johnny Unitas, Lawrence Taylor and
Dick Butkus. There are photos and a brief overview of each player's
career, and it's all football _ there's only a mention of the
acting career for which Brown left the game at 29, and no notice at
all of O.J. Simpson's retirement activities. Best of all are ``Top
10'' lists (they range from ``Best Players I've Ever Seen'' to
``Defensive Linemen I Admire'' and ``Smartest Quarterbacks'')
solicited from some of the great players themselves, including
Merlin Olsen, Deacon Jones, Charley Taylor, Lance Alworth, Jack Ham
and Troy Aikman. Clear some time before you pick this one up,
because you won't put it down any time soon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``THE RIGHT SET'' &QL; 
Edited by Caryl Phillips (Vintage, $14) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We began to enjoy this anthology of writings on tennis round
about Page 45, when James Thurber suddenly appeared and described,
delightfully, the 1926 match between France's Suzanne Lenglen and
American Helen Wills, which caught the world's attention at the
time (Thurber's piece is followed by an essay from Wills herself,
which is also great fun). Earlier essays on the history of the game
have interesting titles (``Lawn Tennis: The Sturdy Bastard'') but
are for tennis zealots. For a more general audience, Phillips
includes excerpts from books by John McPhee, Arthur Ashe, Martina
Navratilova, Billie Jean King and Althea Gibson, and writings on
Chris Evert, Jimmy Connors, Boris Becker and Andre Agassi. There's
a section on tennis etiquette, with a preponderance of attention
paid to the nasty demeanor of the young John McEnroe, although
there's a short essay by Martin Amis in which those other bad boys,
Connors and Ilie Nastase, are mentioned. It ends with a few pages
from Alistair Cooke, titled ``My Life with Gabriela Sabatini,''
which are blissfully free of bad manners _ just what tennis should
be. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``WORDS FAIL ME: WHAT EVERYONE WHO WRITES SHOULD KNOW ABOUT
WRITING''By Patricia T. O'Conner (Harcourt Brace, $18.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The best writer may not follow every rule every time,''
O'Conner says, ``but they follow most of them most of the time. And
even if you're a Tolstoy or a Balzac, a Thurber or a McPhee, it
doesn't hurt to learn the rules before you break them.'' O'Conner
was an editor at the ``New York Times Book Review'' before she
wrote her first book, the very popular ``Woe Is I: The
Grammarphobe's Guide to Better English in Plain English.'' Now,
she's a self-described ``grammar maven'' (she's kidding) who
sometimes writes the ``Times' ''``On Language'' column when William
Safire is on vacation. She's obviously following her own advice _
know your audience _ because her approach to words and writing is
as engaging as it is authoritative, and she quotes lots of her
(and, presumably, your) favorite writers. Her justification for
writing this book, oddly enough, is the Internet _ we're all
writing more now that we have laptops and send e-mail, so we need
to brush up our skills. But truly, no hook was necessary. O'Conner
can be our grammar maven any day. &QL; 
You can reach Anne Stephenson at amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
