<HEADER>
A5192 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     09-08 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS, RED SOX KEEP THE FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ There has never been a Red Sox manager like
Jimy Williams. Joe Morgan comes closest, but folks in New England
understood Tollway Joe because he spoke their language, delivered
their fuel oil, and plowed their streets.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy is different. He's a Californian, but his is not the
California of surfboards or the Grateful Dead. Jimy's California is
is the land of fruits and valleys. The man has a bachelor of
science in agribusiness, which we all know is the study of animal
science.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful that Pinky Higgins or John McNamara ever studied
animal science. Jimy is different. He's a Sox manager born without
a predisposition for self-promotion, paranoia, or last call. He's
never going to be a darling of the electronic media, but maybe
that's not such a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife likes listening to him give interviews,'' chuckles Sox
closer Derek Lowe. ``She thinks he sounds very plain.''
</P>
<P>
   He does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too simple,'' admits Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. Jimy might be dumb like a fox, but he is not dumb
like a Butch Hobson. There appears to be a lot more going on inside
his head than he wants us to know about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know about that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way he likes it. Have a good laugh, everybody. Play
those funny sound bites (``if a frog had wings''). Paint him like a
character from Green Acres. Dis him in Manager of the Year voting.
The man doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they have sports radio shows in Boston?,'' he asks. ``I
don't know about that. But to say I don't read the paper, that's
not true.''
</P>
<P>
   So why not fight back? When he's proven correct after we call
him a nitwit for skipping Pedro in Game 4 against Cleveland, why
not gloat a little, or take critics to task?
</P>
<P>
   ``We leave in in the clubhouse,'' he says, flatly _ as flat as
the boring bill of his cap. ``I'm not trying to be right. I'm
trying to do right.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimy had a Baby Ruth candy bar during the Seattle series and
claimed it represented the Curse of the Bambino. He won't say if he
still has the chocolate treat in his possession.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's 6-2 loss to the Athletics, the Red Sox are 4-2
in the first half of what was supposed to be a make-or-break,
killer trip. They are 18 games over .500 and have won 10 of their
last 13. Going into Wednesday's games, they were as close (5 1/2
games) to the Yankees as they were to the Blue Jays. Despite losing
their slugger and their closer, the '99 Sox were supposed to be
average, or below average, but have been in contention all season
and are on a pace to win 90 games and make the playoffs for the
second straight season.
</P>
<P>
   There has been only one major, off-field crisis in this season,
and that came when Williams stood up to Pedro Martinez and pitched
Bryce Florie on a day when Pedro was late for work. Fallout lasted
several days, and it's fair to guess that Pedro still resents the
move by his manager. But it's interesting to note that no teammate
came to Pedro's defense. The manager probably helped himself by
standing up to the ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that situation,'' says Jimy. ``All it was was
Pedro showing up late. It's behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask him if the tough stand helped him (Pete Carroll, like
McNamara and Kevin Kennedy before him, prefers to bully the
rookies), Williams issues the usual, ``We take care of things in
the clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Darren Lewis has been in the big leagues since 1990 and played
for Tony LaRussa and Dusty Baker. Like most of the Red Sox, Lewis
is a Jimy fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thinking last night about how he's underrated as a
manager,'' says the outfielder. ``His style is low key. But he
knows all facets of the game and he's very consistent as a person.
He keeps everybody in the mix, so you don't have guys rotting on
the bench for two weeks. You have to show up prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams gives more instruction than most major league manager.
He loves to work with middle infielders and knows a lot about
hitting for a man who only had 13 big league at-bats (he played one
game with the 1967 Cardinal team that beat the Red Sox in the World
Series). Veteran lefty Kent Mercker says Williams could be a great
pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy likes his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what they bring to the park every day. I believe in
them. I never asked them if they believe in me, but I do believe in
them.''
</P>
<P>
   There will always be unhappy faces in a 25-man clubhouse, but
Williams says, ``That doesn't bother me. If a guy is maybe not
smiling because he's not in there, all that tells you is he
believes in his own skill and that's good. That's not a negative to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe says, ``Jimy doesn't ever panic. I came in playing for one
of the toughest managers for young players _ Lou Piniella _ and now
I have one of the best. I may have a bad game or two but Jimy puts
you back in there. Everyone in here respects him and goes out and
plays hard for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got us together in spring training and said, `Mo's not
here. We know that.' But he got it in our heads that we're gonna be
OK, and here we are 20 games over .500. He trusts us. He trusts
that we'll find a way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And they usually do.
</P>
<P>
   It's simple.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
