<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-WACO-DANFORTH-NYT &LR;      09-08 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-DANFORTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURNING TO PUBLIC LIFE: JOHN CLAGETT DANFORTH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)   (With WACO-INQUIRY) 
(nk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On most Tuesday mornings in his tenure in the
Senate, Jack Danforth would slip away from Capitol Hill and travel
a few miles to the small St. Alban's parish church at the National
Cathedral to preach.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly sermon away from Congress, he told friends, was an
opportunity to indulge an unquenchable ecclesiastical urge. In
preparation for what would turn out to be a career as a successful
lawyer and politician, Danforth collected not only a law degree but
also one in divinity studies from Yale University. He went on to be
ordained as an Episcopal minister.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cathedral he would deploy the same splendid baritone in
delivering small-scale homilies about God that he used in speeches
on the Senate floor about trade and finance.
</P>
<P>
   To the delight of some and the dismay of a few, he retained some
of the same preachiness when dealing with earthly matters in his
three terms in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he was widely respected by his colleagues for his
earnestness and principled approach to issues. He was even admired
by those who often disagreed with him, like Sen. Russell B. Long,
the guileful Louisiana Democrat who served for years as the
chairman of the Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Long became as much a mentor to the young Republican from
Missouri as an adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth was sometimes called ``Saint Jack'' by his colleagues
and others, a nickname that embodied both general admiration for
his undeniable rectitude but also a whiff of annoyance at his
occasional moralizing tone.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth retired from the Senate in 1994 with only a few
specific intentions. He wanted to practice law, quietly support a
few St. Louis charities, go fly-fishing on the stream that crossed
his Missouri farm and watch from afar as events unfolded in
Washington, his friends said. He told The New York Times that he
was leaving the capital because he ``did not want to end my days in
government'' where one is ineluctably consumed by politics.
</P>
<P>
   With the decision by Attorney General Janet Reno to have
Danforth head an investigation into the events of the Branch
Davidian compound near Waco, Texas, in April 1993, he will be
returning not only to public life, but to an issue where the glare
is expected to be intense.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hilton, who was a senior aide to Danforth in the Senate
for 13 years, described him as someone who would take on the task
because ``he is a person who cares deeply that justice is done and
that the public has confidence they know the truth about important
events.''
</P>
<P>
   John Clagett Danforth was born Dec. 5, 1936, in St. Louis, into
the family that started and still owns much of the Ralston Purina
company, a family whose wealth was founded on cereal and maintained
by kibble.
</P>
<P>
   In his 18 years in Congress he would be known for such issues as
favoring free trade while trying to limit the number of Japanese
auto imports, his relentless support for increasing U.S. aid to
countries for hunger relief, and his independence from Republican
congressional leaders, as when he joined with Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., to enact a civil rights bill.
</P>
<P>
   He championed airbags in autos and drug testing for
transportation workers, a campaign he undertook after his daughter
almost boarded a train that crashed because of an engineer high on
narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end he would become best known for his emotional
defense of Judge Clarence Thomas, who was nominated in 1991 by
President George Bush to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth's devotion to Thomas was almost familial. When he was
Missouri's attorney general, he hired Thomas just out of Yale Law
School and they had forged a close bond.
</P>
<P>
   When Thomas' confirmation hearings turned from difficult to
tumultuous after Anita F. Hill accused him of sexual harassment,
Danforth displayed an unexpected ferocity. He prayed with Thomas
and loudly complained that Thomas was being unfairly smeared.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission he went overboard, joining in Republican
attempts to paint Ms. Hill as a possible psychopath who had
imagined the accusations she made against Thomas. ``I believe I
went too far,'' he wrote in an account of those difficult weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth had almost single-handedly created a flourishing
Republican party in Missouri. When he was elected attorney general
in 1968 he was the first Republican to hold statewide office there
in more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   He came close to achieving the impossible two years later, when
he came within three percentage points of unseating Sen. Stuart
Symington. When Symington retired in 1976, Danforth was elected to
the seat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
