<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5196 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-COURT-SPINA-BOS &LR;      09-08 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-COURT-SPINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI COURT NOMINEE IN QUESTIONABLE DEAL WITH INMATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Francis X. Spina, whom Governor Paul Cellucci
nominated to the state's highest court last week after praising his
conservative views on criminal justice, paid $20,000 in public
funds to a convicted murderer to perform paralegal work on a
Mafia-related case Spina took on as a court-appointed lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The payment to Jerome A. Napolitano, who is serving two life
sentences for killing two people, violated Department of
Corrections regulations, and caused the state's court-appointed
lawyers' agency to revise its policies to ban such arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Legal observers called the payment _ which Napolitano collected
while imprisoned in Norfolk _ highly unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Spina said Wednesday he hired Napolitano on the recommendation
of his client, convicted cocaine trafficker Francesco (Frank)
Campiti of Agawam, who was serving a sentence alongside Napolitano
at the Bay State Correctional Center in Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you are sensationalizing this,'' said Spina now a
state appeals court judge.
</P>
<P>
   Spina described Campiti's case as ``factually convoluted'' and
said it was convenient to hire Napolitano because he could devote
time to it while in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't do it alone,'' said Spina, noting that he lived 100
miles away from the prison. ``I needed someone who could work with
Campiti and could go over the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's legal counsel, Leonard L. Lewin, who helped the
governor screen nominees for the Supreme Judicial Court, said
Spina's 1991 hiring of Napolitano did not come up during his
interview for the court vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   When told of the facts Tuesday, Lewin said he did not think they
were relevant to Spina's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Spina, 52, who has served on the appeals court since 1997, said
he was not aware at the time he hired Napolitano that paying
inmates for legal services was prohibited by the Department of
Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   Some criminal justice experts said the hiring of Napolitano,
whose victims included a 16-year-old boy, could be troublesome to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is rare and it will look outrageous to people,'' Jack
Levin, director of the Brudnick Center on Violence at Northeastern
University. ``We are in a punitive mood when it comes to inmates.
We want to take their color televisions away and their exercise
facilities. So I can't help but think many citizens are going to
feel it is inappropriate to pay a murderer so much money for this
kind of work.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement also runs counter to Celluccis' emphasis on
law-and-order in his administration's policies.
</P>
<P>
   Spina, a former assistant district attorney who was practicing
law at a Pittsfield firm in 1991, was given the Campiti case by the
Committee for Public Counsel Services.
</P>
<P>
   Campiti, a Mafia associate has been convicted in 1988 for
operating a cocaine-importing ring and sentenced to 40 to 60 years
in prison. Campiti was appealing the conviction, arguing taped
recorded conversations should not have been allowed as evidence at
trial. The conviction was eventually upheld in the state appeals
court and is now before a federal judge in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   After accepting the case, Spina hired Napolitano as a paralegal,
paying him $10 an hour. By 1993, Spina had paid the inmate $19,907,
according to CPCS records. Spina, who was paid $25 an hour,
collected $16,906 for his work during the same period. He dropped
the case in 1993 after he was appointed by then Governor William F.
Weld to the Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Spina said he had received written DOC approval for Napolitano
to work as a paralegal, but the issue of compensation was not
raised. He said he only learned it was a violation of the DOC rules
well over a year after he dropped the case.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano remained on the case when another lawyer took over
the appeal, but in 1993, William Leahy, the CPCS general counsel,
raised questions about a $4,902 payment to the inmate. In the
process of reviewing the bills, Leahy and his staff were informed
by the Department of Corrections that regulations bar inmates from
being paid for legal work.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy said records indicate the DOC disciplined Napolitano for
accepting the fees, but a DOC spokesman had no comment. The CPCS
decided it was not worth litigation to seek recovery of the
payments.
</P>
<P>
   The case prompted CPCS to issue new guidelines requiring any
paralegals hired to have completed formal training.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation that Spina paid Napolitano with public funds
could undermine the tough-on crime image that Cellucci promotes for
himself and his administration.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference last week, Cellucci praised Spina as a
conservative jurist who, he said, supported his criminal justice
positions, including the death penalty and tougher sentencing. He
said Spina and his other nominee for the two vacant SJC seats,
Judith Cowin, display ``uncommon good sense.''
</P>
<P>
   However, under death penalty bills repeatedly filed by Cellucci,
a double murder like that Napolitano was convicted of could be
grounds for execution.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano was convicted in 1978 in the brutal shooting deaths
of Thomas Willett, 16, and Hugh Maguire, 21, both of Jamaica Plain,
and given two concurrent life terms.
</P>
<P>
   According to witnesses, Willet and Maguire and several other men
were engaged in a wild street fight near a Brighton nightclub when
an apparent stranger appeared from the darkness and pumped 14 shots
into the head, chest and groin areas of the two victims.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano claimed he was in his Beacon Hill apartment at the
time of the killings. But several eyewitnesses, including a man
involved in the fight who said he lay at the feet of the assailant
at the time of the shootings, identified him as the gunman. They
said Napolitano coldly fired several times into both victims and,
as one victim pleaded for his life, reloaded and fired again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Kurkjian of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
