<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARMEDIA:ESPUELAS-INTVU-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKET MAN: Q&AMP;A WITH STARMEDIA FOUNDER AND CEO FERNANDO ESPUELAS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By SERGIO R. BUSTOS 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    StarMedia founder and CEO Fernando Espuelas is the hottest of a
growing number of Latin American Internet entrepreneurs. The
high-strung digital maverick has raised more venture capital than
anybody else, has taken his company public and has led the firm to
a market cap in excess of US$2 billion. Espuelas spoke with Latin
Trade associate editor Sergio R. Bustos.
 &HT;    Excerpts of their discussion:
 &HT;    
 &HT;    LATIN TRADE: You were recently quoted as saying, ``I was 29 and
making really good money but really unsatisfied.'' You are now 33
and making even better money. Are you satisfied?
 &HT;    ESPUELAS: It has never been about the money for me. StarMedia
represents an opportunity for me to build a new Latin America for
the new century.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    What do you mean ``build a new Latin America?''
 &HT;    The Internet is comparable to the French Revolution. Before the
revolution, the individual in French society had no role unless he
or she was a nobleman. After the revolution, every individual
became important. That's what the Internet will do in Latin
America. We are talking about a complete and permanent shift at
every level of society. For me to be in the middle of it all is a
very exciting opportunity.
 &HT;    The name StarMedia seems an odd name for a company that targets
people who speak Spanish and Portuguese. There are very few words
that translate both into Spanish and Portuguese. We wanted to have
one brand that could be identified in both languages. In fact, we
wanted to have a name with no meaning, so that we could create the
meaning.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Everybody's launching Spanish-language sites. With the field so
crowded, who's gonna make a buck?
 &HT;    That's the million dollar question. If you want to know how it's
going to shake out just look at the U.S. market. You have five top
brands that control 65 percent of the audience and collect 85
percent of the (advertising) dollars. I see four or five brands in
Latin America: StarMedia, AOL, Yahoo! en Espanol and Telefonica.
Everybody else is either going to be acquired or will go out of
business.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    You didn't mention billionaire Carlos Slim's Telefonos de
Mexico.
 &HT;    I believe they will be a successful ISP (Internet Service
Provider). But being a strong monopoly is no guarantee you can be a
strong and successful portal site. Not to pick on Telmex, but these
companies have a brand problem.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Projections show e-commerce in Latin America doubling on average
over the next five years to $8 billion. How will StarMedia get in
on this market?
 &HT;    At StarMedia, we simply want to connect buyers and sellers of
goods and services. To do this, we need three things: First, we
need to bring more merchants that communicate in Spanish and
Portuguese because Latin American consumers want information in
their own language. Secondly, we need a uniform credit card
acceptance system. We are currently working with banks and others
to create that. Finally, we need to give Latin American users a
one-stop system to ship goods through customs in a predictable way.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    What is your biggest fear?
 &HT;    Are we organized the right way? Can we execute our plans as well
as we did in the past? For example, last year we had 30 people on
staff, but by the end of the year we could have 400 to 500. I'm
very focused on internal organization.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    You raised millions of dollars with your IPO in May. Why not
simply sell StarMedia, move on and pursue other ambitions? Like
becoming president of Uruguay?
 &HT;    I always wonder why I'm asked about being president of Uruguay
so often. For me, there is absolutely no challenge greater than
running StarMedia.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
