<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN SAYS CORRUPTION CHARGES ARE POLITICALLY INSPIRED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-BRIBES-YELTSIN.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin told President
Clinton in a telephone conversation on Wednesday that accusations
linking Yeltsin and his family to a corruption inquiry involving
high-level Kremlin officials were politically inspired, the White
House said on Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, the president's national security adviser, said
Clinton specifically asked about reports that Yeltsin's credit card
bills and those of his two daughters had been paid by a
construction company that did vast renovation work on the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Yeltsin denied those reports,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   But another White House official, who commented on the condition
that he not be named, said on Wednesday evening that the Russian
president's repudiation of the accusations was less categorical.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin did not state his total innocence in so many words, the
official said; rather, he insisted that the accusations were not
substantive.
</P>
<P>
   The corruption inquiry, which is focusing on allegations of
international money-laundering and bribes to Russian politicians in
exchange for lucrative construction contracts at the Kremlin
itself, came up during part of a 40-minute telephone call, White
House spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin called Clinton to discuss a variety of topics, including
disarmament negotiations and the Asian economic summit meeting in
New Zealand this weekend, according to Berger.
</P>
<P>
   As Berger recounted at a news briefing, Clinton broached the
subject of money-laundering and corruption by commenting that it
would be good if Yeltsin could sign money-laundering legislation
recently passed by the lower house of Russia's Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin said he was prepared to sign a money-laundering bill if
the Parliament passes one that is consistent with the Russian
Constitution, Berger said. Yeltsin said he had doubts about a law
passed this summer, and vetoed it for that reason.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, responding to a question, said Clinton then got to the
point, asking Yeltsin about the reports that Swiss authorities have
copies of receipts purporting to show that the credit card bills
were paid out of accounts of Mabatex Project Engineering, a
Swiss-based construction company.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Yeltsin's press aides have categorically denied that
Yeltsin has anything to hide. And even people who detest Yeltsin
personally and politically agree that he has plenty of enemies
happy to say damning things about him.
</P>
<P>
   The White House official said about 40 percent of the total
conversation was devoted to government-corruption issues. The two
national leaders _ neither of whom speaks the other's language _
spoke through interpreters. The official said Yeltsin called
Clinton late Wednesday morning, which was early evening in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   A team of Russian law-enforcement officials is coming to the
United States early next week to take part in the continuing
multinational investigation, whose scope now includes allegations
that money from Russia was laundered through New York banks. The
Russian contingent will include a high official of Russia's
equivalent of the FBI, tax investigators and the Kremlin version of
a national attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   The White House official who commented on Wednesday evening said
Clinton did not indicate whether he felt totally reassured by
Yeltsin's assertions. The American president did not disagree when
his Russian counterpart said that the odor of scandal could damage
relations between the two countries, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Swiss authorities investigating suspected
money-laundering by powerful Russians ordered Swiss banks to
provide information on two dozen Russians thought to have accounts
in Geneva. The Swiss have frozen at least 59 bank accounts in the
past two months in the search for evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Russians known to be under scrutiny include the head of
Yeltsin's property-management team; his wife, daughter and
son-in-law; and a former deputy prime minister involved in the
military industry and arms exports.
</P>
<P>
   And though no definite link has yet been established between the
Swiss investigation and the one in the United States, American
authorities are looking into possible laundering of Russian money
through the Bank of New York. The bank has said it is cooperating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
