<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5221 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ATHLETICS-     09-08 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ATHLETICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX DROP ONE TO A'S, 6-2 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ There would be no executioner's song here
Wednesday. The Athletics live for another day, and may yet be
drawing breath in October.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox? On an afternoon in which a killer's instinct would
have been as welcome in Boston as it always is here in nearby
Alcatraz, the Sox spared the A's, making three errors in a 6-2 loss
to Oakland that kept the wild-card differential at three games with
22 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three errors, five hits _ you know it's going to be a long
day,'' said center fielder Darren Lewis, whose fifth-inning
overthrow of third base was sandwiched between misdirected
offerings from rookie Donnie Sadler in the first and rookie third
baseman Wilton Veras in the sixth, the three errors leading to four
unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm human, I make mistakes,'' said Lewis, who has made a
career of keeping those mistakes to a minimum and has the Gold
Glove to prove it. ``That's just the way the game goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this was going to be a tough trip. Up to this point
it's been great. We've been playing good baseball. Today was a bad
day. You can't look ahead and you can't look behind. You've just
got to take it on a game-to-game basis. We're going to New York,
looking them right in the eye, and will just be ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox could have headed to New York and the Yankees with a
five-game cushion over the A's, whose clumsy play in Tuesday
night's 5-3 Sox win was as embarrassing as the cartwheeling
streaker (supposedly an aspiring Lutheran minister, no less) whose
only concession to decency was the Minnesota Twins cap he wore on
his head.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sadler, in untimely mimicry of Oakland shortstop Miguel
Tejada, who opened Tuesday's game by dropping a popup, threw high
to first base on Rich Becker's routine grounder to open the A's
first Wednesday. Sadler started at short in place of sore-ankled
Nomar Garciaparra, who sat out after fouling a pitch off his left
foot Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Velarde followed Sadler's error with a base hit, and two
outs later, Oakland DH John Jaha, whose ugly feet scared off the
Sox last winter but who has left big footprints all over the Sox
ever since, doubled over Lewis's head for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Stairs singled home a run in the fifth, and another scored
when a charging Lewis fielded his base hit on the second hop and
nearly threw it over the A's dugout. Olmedo Saenz homered to lead
off the sixth to make it 5-0, and Becker doubled following Veras'
two-base throwing error for the final Oakland run.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just a team you can't give four or five outs to, and
there were a couple of innings we gave them extra outs,'' said Sox
pitcher Pat Rapp, who hadn't lost since June 17 but couldn't escape
a beating Wednesday. ``I tried to pick us up, but it wasn't to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Appier saw to that. The pitcher who wouldn't be on the
Left Coast if Dan Duquette had had his way _ the Sox tried since
last fall to talk Kansas City into trading Appier to Boston, only
to see him shipped off to their wild-card rival for three
minor-league pitchers _ stymied the Sox on four hits in six
innings. Lewis's bloop single in the fifth made it a 4-2 game, but
when the Red Sox put the tying runs on base in the sixth after
walks to Scott Hatteberg and Veras, Appier struck out rookie Trot
Nixon and pinch hitter Reggie Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is right up there in importance for me,'' Appier
said. ``I've been in the hunt before (the Royals made a bit of a
run in '95), but not this close or this late. I didn't focus on the
pressure, but on the task at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, whose RBI double Tuesday had jump-started the Sox,
worked Appier to a full count before going down swinging at an
Appier slider.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fools people,'' Jefferson said of the decisive pitch, which
broke down and in. ``It acted like a splitter. The rotation was so
tight, it looked like a fastball. I had no chance. I had a good
at-bat until that pitch. I missed it by four feet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox would have just one baserunner the rest of the way. Mike
Stanley singled off A's reliever Doug Jones in the eighth, but was
erased on Troy O'Leary's double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great, great big shot in the arm,'' said A's manager
Art Howe, who will be splitting Manager of the Year votes with Jimy
Williams. ``We have to go hard in the last three weeks, but we're
in a better position than I thought we'd be in going into (the
final stretch).''
</P>
<P>
   The A's, of course, have surprised almost as many people as the
Red Sox, who won four of six games in the West Coast portion of
this 12-game road swing. Three games apiece in the Bronx and
Cleveland remain before the Sox touch down again at Logan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good team, we're a good team, these things happen
sometimes,'' said a tight-lipped Williams, who never barbecues
anyone for making an error. ``It's not for a lack of effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams refused to offer any mid-voyage perspectives when asked
if he were pleased with his pilgrims' progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied with the way we played basically all year,''
Williams said. ``I didn't see any of our kids back off, regardless
of the situation or the score. That's all. We'll keep doing that.
We're going to be just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who never has treated this game as kids' stuff, had no
room in his duffel bag for this one as he packed up for the trip to
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened (Wednesday), you don't expect,'' he said. ``But
the key is to bounce back. That's what we've been doing all year,
and that's what we expect to do in New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
