<HEADER>
A5222 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-WOLFCOL-LADN-(SLA     09-08 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WOLFCOL-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOT OF BLAME TO SHOULDER IN BOULDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere in Seattle on Saturday night was the happiest coach
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Washington coach Rick Neuheisel hadn't coached a game yet, but
you can bet he was savoring Colorado State's 41-14 thumping of his
former employer, Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Colorado like a scoundrel in the midst of its
biggest recruiting weekend _ and in the opinion of many,
dismantling a once-powerful program _ Neuheisel was no doubt
thrilled to see the Buffaloes stumble.
</P>
<P>
   But where does this leave new Buffs coach Gary Barnett, who is
trying to clean up this mess?
</P>
<P>
   Barnett said quarterback Mike Moschetti's game-week comment to a
Denver television crew should have raised a red flag. Moschetti
said Nebraska was Colorado's rival and not Colorado State, a sound
bite that played nicely in Fort Collins.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing that, Barnett believes he ``should have been more
perceptive.''
</P>
<P>
   Moschetti, however, said his coach merely sought to shoulder
responsibility: ``I said it last year, and we went out and beat
(Colorado State) up pretty good. . . . I think we knew it was a big
game. It's the first game of the season. We didn't execute. He's
not playing, we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss has led to much soul-searching in Boulder. Colorado's
defense tackled poorly, failed to shed blocks and lined up wrong on
eight plays.
</P>
<P>
   Most puzzling to Barnett was why his team reacted with almost
complete surprise to Colorado State's offensive and defensive
schemes. Barnett said his position coaches and coordinators have to
``sit down and talk to players and determine why we had trouble
handling what we prepared for, then find out if we have any
inadequacies in our offensive and defensive schemes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's probably commonplace to stand here and say, `Well,
we'll just move on to the next game.' But it won't be that easy. We
have to find out why this happened. It's going to hurt a lot _ as
it should _ and it will. I'm fully aware of that. We have to assess
everything that happened. You just can't write it off as a bad day
at the office. . . . We need to feel the hurt. Maybe that'll drive
home a point.''
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, Colorado's players had to leave the field
through a tunnel and were pelted with debris. Denver police in riot
gear first sprayed fans hanging over the mouth of the tunnel, then
tossed a couple of canisters of tear gas into the stands. At least
two canisters were tossed back onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   __ Unusual punishment: Georgia Tech coach George O'Leary coached
his team against Navy from the press box. Not because he wanted to
but because he had to.
</P>
<P>
   This was part of the NCAA's punishment for O'Leary providing an
improper loan to former Tech running back C.J. Williams. He was
also barred from Tech's final spring scrimmage and could not
recruit off campus in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wrong. I shouldn't have done what I did,'' O'Leary said.
``I thought it was over with, but it's still here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we have seven ecstatic coaches and three coaches who
are down in the dumps because they found out I was going upstairs
(with them). The coaches down on the field feel pretty good about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Scott drops: Neuheisel named true freshman Cody Pickett as
Washington's backup quarterback, ahead of third-year sophomore J.K.
Scott of Burroughs High.
</P>
<P>
   During training camp Scott was having trouble with the
center-quarterback exchange and was benched during one scrimmage in
favor of Pickett. Scott has said he won't transfer.
</P>
<P>
   __ Beaver fever: Oregon State brought nearly 7,000 fans _ about
10 times its usual traveling party _ to its victory over Nevada in
Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Season-ticket sales are at a record 10,600, and officials are
expecting a crowd of nearly 30,000 (capacity is 35,362) for
Saturday's game against Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   Even stranger, the Beavers have won eight straight nonconference
games and could be 3-0 when they play USC on Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   __ Boller update: Former Hart quarterback Kyle Boller entered
his first college game for Cal to the chants of his name from the
student section, then promptly fumbled on his first play.
</P>
<P>
   Boller completed his first pass attempt, a bullet to Ronnie
Davenport that covered 26 yards. Boller hit on his first five
attempts for 60 yards and a touchdown, then was 3 for 10
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Asked who would start vs. Nebraska, Cal coach Tom Holmoe said:
``It'll probably be Sam (Clemons), but Kyle will play, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite it being Boller's first game he wasn't shy about taking
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Senior center John Romero recalled this scene when Boller
returned to the huddle during at the end of a timeout: ``The guys
were all talking in the huddle. He came in and said, `Everybody
quiet down.' Then he called the play and told the receivers to be
sure to hold onto the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The Little Ten: When Miami knocked off Ohio State in the
Kickoff Classic, it extended an interesting streak. The Big Three
in the state of Florida (Miami, Florida State, Florida) are 16-0
against the Big Ten going back to the 1987 season. This includes
games against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Point guard vs. point guard: When Indiana plays North
Carolina on Saturday, two unique athletes will be in the spotlight.
Both quarterbacks _ Indiana sophomore Antwaan Randle El and North
Carolina sophomore Ronald Curry _ also play point guard for their
college teams during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   __ Lateral career move: New Northwestern coach Randy Walker
might regret his decision to take the job after the Wildcats' 28-3
loss to Miami of Ohio. Walker coached Miami for nine years before
replacing Gary Barnett in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
