<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BULLPEN IS SHAKY, BUT BENITEZ REGROUPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Armando Benitez received the ball from Mike Piazza
and began circling the mound, head down, mind working. He wiped his
brow with his forearm, squatted behind the pitcher's rubber and
stared at home plate. There were two outs and a man on first, and
Benitez had just fired consecutive balls to J.T. Snow, who
represented the tying run for the San Francisco Giants. The Mets'
hard-throwing closer had two strikes on Snow but was losing control
of his overpowering fastball and needed to reel himself back in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little wild,'' Benitez said. ``I needed to get stable.
I needed to relax, step back and calm down. I told myself to take
my time, to take the pressure off, to do what I know I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking a long thought and a deep breath, Benitez showed
some savvy by tucking away his signature fastball and slipping an
88 mph splitter past Snow for the game's final out Wednesday. With
the pop of the mitt, 26,499 relieved fans at Shea Stadium rose and
cheered, and a thankful group of Mets players exhaled.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez's 18th save of the season secured the Mets' 7-5 victory
over the Giants and kept their suddenly appetizing bullpen from a
second straight collapse. Tuesday night, the Mets' vaunted relief
corps had failed to protect an eighth-inning lead and tied the club
record for most relievers used in a game at seven.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the typically reliable Pat Mahomes and Dennis Cook
inserted tension by allowing four runs in the eighth inning in what
had been a six-run cushion for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every part of the team is going to misfire once in a while and
it's good to see people pick each other up,'' said Manager Bobby
Valentine, whose Mets begin a seven-game West Coast trip Thursday
in Los Angeles. ``Armando picked up the other two guys and the
offense came out swinging. The signature of this team is that they
do whatever it takes to pick each other up. And that's what this
was.''
</P>
<P>
   After notching only four hits in each of the last two games, the
offense arrived just in time. Shawon Dunston keyed a four-hit,
three-run third inning with a two-run single, and Piazza smacked
his 33rd home run off the reliever Miguel Del Toro in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's 377-foot blast over the right-field wall brought home
Edgardo Alfonzo and John Olerud, both of whom had singled, and gave
the Mets what they thought was a comfortable 7-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a tough homestand for Piazza up to that point. He
had gone two for 17 and had stranded six base runners in his first
three at-bats Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was taking good swings but obviously didn't have
anything to show for it,'' said Piazza, who pinch-hit in Tuesday's
7-4 loss to the Giants. ``I was just trying to get a base hit, but
he gave me a pitch that I could drive and I stayed on it pretty
well. I didn't think it would mean anything. I thought it was just
some good insurance for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets coasted while the starter Octavio Dotel (7-1)
controlled the Giants through the first seven innings. Scattering
four hits _ he allowed no more than one in an any inning _ the
right-handed rookie won his seventh straight decision. Though Dotel
was cruising and looked capable of completing the game, Valentine
opted to replace him with Mahomes at the start of the eighth
because of his high pitch count (120).
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes, who threw well the night before, had nothing. With his
ball moving all over the place, he walked the first two batters he
faced, then gave up a single to Bill Mueller that scored the
Giants' second run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Cook entered and was not much better. After getting Snow to fly
out, he was tagged for a three-run homer by Ellis Burks. Two
batters later, he walked Rich Aurilia, forcing Valentine to summon
Benitez an inning earlier than he usually does.
</P>
<P>
   While Benitez closed out the game, he was not dominating.
Mueller singled in the top of the ninth before Benitez got Barry
Bonds out on a fly ball and struck out the game's last two batters.
Acknowledging that the bullpen might be tired after being used so
heavily throughout the season, Piazza expressed concern about
things falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been outstanding the whole year, and hopefully we can
score enough runs to give them that insurance,'' Piazza said.
``They are tired and they are struggling, so we hope we can score
some runs and give them that margin for error, but that's not
always going to be the case. We sure hope it's just a bump in the
road for them and that they can straighten it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
