<SLUG> BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DOTEL PASSES A TEST OF FIRE IN 3 PITCHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three pitches. Three strikes. Three auspicious demonstrations of
a live-armed rookie who has no fear, and chose the final out of the
visitors' fifth inning at Shea Stadium to make his boldest bid yet
for a post-season start.
</P>
<P>
   Fastball, at the knees, outside corner, strike one. Breaking
ball, down and in, fouled straight down, into the dirt, strike two.
Fastball up, inside part of the plate, a handcuffed checked swing,
strike three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I throw the fastball on the outside and the umpire called it a
strike,'' Octavio Dotel said. ``Then I don't want to come back with
the same pitch because that's when they say, `I got you,' so I
throw the curve. Then I just want to come back with my high
fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody really got to Dotel Wednesday, least of all Barry Bonds,
the challenge he faced in the crossroads sequence of a 7-5 victory
over the Giants that featured Dotel at his seven-inning, one-run,
four-hit, nine-strikeout best. The startling aspect of the
confrontation with Bonds wasn't that Dotel got him out, or that he
even struck him out with two on in the fifth, with Dotel and the
Mets holding a 3-1 lead. It was that he went after a man on the
All-Century list as if he were the opposing pitcher, wasting not a
moment or a pitch. No fear, none at all, and maybe
English-as-a-second-language explains why Dotel generically
referred to Bonds as ``they'' but Al Leiter was willing to guess
not.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of Dotel's leap from the minor leagues to the heat
of the pennant race reminded Leiter of a dugout conversation he had
a couple of summers ago with Livan Hernandez, the Cuban defector
who was then a Florida Marlins rookie on his way to post-season
glory. They were watching San Diego take batting practice from the
dugout one day when Hernandez turned to him and said, ``Al, Ken
Caminiti, he have power, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at him at first like he was pulling my leg,'' Leiter
said. ``I mean, you're in the major leagues and you have to ask if
Ken Caminiti has power? Then I realized he wasn't kidding and it
also hit me that none of these guys made all that much of a
difference to him. His focus was on making pitches, on execution,
on that catcher's glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Greg Maddux has been the best pitcher in the decade, it's
because all he thinks is the next pitch. If you're a young pitcher,
if you've got talent and you're able to block out the distractions,
you have a reasonable chance to throw a good game. I look at
Octavio, and he reminds me of Livan. There's the barrier of being a
young Latin American player, so he's probably not driving in his
car, turning to his radio dial, right to the FAN. He may not be
reading every word about himself in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, on a shelf in Dotel's locker stall was a thin stack of
newspaper clippings, and if his English isn't perfect, it was
certainly good enough for a post-game appearance Wednesday on
``Kiner's Korner.''
</P>
<P>
   He says winter ball in the Dominican Republic, pitching against
major leaguers there as a 20-year-old, has removed any sense of
awe.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone around Dotel in the clubhouse, from Leiter to Mike
Piazza, says this 23-year-old from Santo Domingo is a good
listener, a fast learner. Orel Hershiser, off to Los Angeles early
Wednesday for his start Thursday night against Kevin Brown and the
Dodgers, appointed himself mentor upon Dotel's arrival from the
minor leagues in June, and has counseled him on everything from how
to deal with a disappointing start to packing his long underwear
for a trip to chilly San Francisco last month. It was Hershiser who
tracked Dotel to the clubhouse after he lost a no-hitter in San
Diego, helped to calm him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orel comes to me and says, `Forget it, that happened to me,'''
Dotel said. ``He talks to me all the time, about everything. I say,
`I appreciate that and thank you.'''
</P>
<P>
   He is baby-faced, bright-eyed, with a peach-fuzz mustache and an
affectionate air that runs contrary to his manager's claim that
Dotel ``doesn't fool around,'' and that he has a fearlessness that
``I've seen right along.''
</P>
<P>
   He has the toughness, the talent and a 7-1 record. The Mets are
10-3 in games Dotel has started. In deciding how to factor Dotel
into a post-season equation, Bobby Valentine only has to talk to
Leiter about Livan Hernandez, or remember that Joe Torre handed the
ball to the other Hernandez, Orlando, for the Yankees' pivotal
playoff game last year at Cleveland. Then consider that no one on
his staff has Dotel's golden arm, and the answer should come as
easy as Dotel disposed of Bonds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
