<SLUG> BC-WACO-LAWSUIT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plaintiffs in Branch Davidian lawsuit ask for status conference
 &HT;    By Mark England and Tommy Witherspoon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Plaintiffs in the Branch Davidian lawsuit against
the government Wednesday asked for a status conference to find out
when they can look at stored evidence and whether the trial date
next month is likely to be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Mike Caddell of Houston, who represents several
plaintiffs including fire survivor Misty Ferguson, asked U.S.
District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. of Waco to approve a conference
as soon as possible. Caddell's motion also laid out other issues
for discussion, such as whether there should be separate trials for
liability and damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government asked to bifurcate the trial, separate it into
two parts,'' Caddell said. ``Try only the liability in the first
part; damages in the second part, if necessary. The judge never
issued a decision on that. We need to know if we go to trial
whether we have to present our whole case or just the case on
liability.''
</P>
<P>
   A Department of Justice spokesman did not return a telephone
call requesting an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said he is not opposed to splitting up the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, when you've been burned to death or committed
suicide or shot to save you the agony of burning alive, I don't
think a lot of time has to be spent on the issue of damages,''
Caddell said. ``It's not a sore back case where you have to worry
if the guy is faking it.''
</P>
<P>
   Splitting the liability and damage phases of trial could save
both sides time and money, Caddell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all would save time if we didn't have to put on damage
claims for someone the court eventually decides has no claim to
liability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell also asked Smith for a chance to discuss an earlier
motion for a continuance. The plaintiffs would like to move the
trial date from Oct. 18 to either Dec. 6 or Jan. 10, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The government filed a motion Tuesday asking Smith to either
strike all expert witnesses for the plaintiffs _ claiming they have
not been given enough information on the expert witnesses' proposed
testimony to even know whether to seek rebuttal witnesses _ or
grant a continuance.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said he discussed the issue of having a status
conference with Marie Hagen, a Department of Justice attorney, who
was not opposed to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides agree there should be a delay in the trial,''
Caddell said. ``We disagree as to the length. We think we could be
ready to go to trial in December. The government would like at
least six months to get ready. I think six months is way too long.
If anyone could use six months, it's not the government, who has
had access to the evidence for six years. Really, that argument is
kind of laughable.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
