<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANADIAN AUTO WORKERS TO BARGAIN WITH FORD FIRST
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor will be the pattern-setting company in labor
negotiations with the Canadian Auto Workers Union, the union
announced. The union will first try to reach a deal with Ford, then
it plans to follow the industry tradition of demanding that GM and
DaimlerChrysler accept its terms.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian union said it chose Ford in part because the leader
of the American union, Stephen P. Yokich, had narrowed his choices
to General Motors and DaimlerChrysler. Industry and labor experts
are betting the United Automobile Workers will name DaimlerChrysler
as its lead company.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN TALKS, BUT NOT OF RATES
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, suggested
in a speech that the U.S. economy's expansion could continue,
thanks to advancements in technology. But he did not discuss his
views on interest rates, inflation or current economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS END MIXED AHEAD OF REPORT
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended mixed as investors remained cautious ahead of the
producer price index. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 2.21
points, to 11,036.34. The Nasdaq composite index fell 28.52 points,
or 1.02 percent, to 2,808.74, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index declined 6.30 points, or five-tenths of a percent, to
1,344.15.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices edged up as traders covered short positions after
the Federal Reserve took measures to insure there would be enough
money in the banking system to counter any Year 2000 computer
problems. The yield on the 30-year issue was unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   SEC FINES VAN KAMPEN $100,000
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission censured and fined Van
Kampen Investment Advisory $100,000 for marketing the Van Kampen
Growth fund's hot track record without disclosing how its returns
were actually obtained. The SEC said Van Kampen improperly failed
to disclose to investors that more than half of the fund's 1996
return of 62 percent came from hot initial offerings. The fund was
able to buy these initial offerings while it had only a few hundred
thousand dollars of assets and was closed to the public.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN RAISES KEY INTEREST RATE
</P>
<P>
   Britain's central bank raised a key short-term money rate for
the first time in more than a year in a pre-emptive move against
inflation. The quarter-point increase in the securities repurchase
rate, to 5.25 percent, broke a series of seven modest rate cuts. In
response, the pound rose, settling in London at $1.6209 and in New
York at $1.6192, up from $1.6049. Stocks moved lower, closing down
slightly less than 1 percent in London.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA AIR SWITCHES AD AGENCIES
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines ended a two-month advertising review by
dismissing its agency of two and a half years, Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi,
and shifting its worldwide account to Leo Burnett. Trade
publications have reported billings at $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   SONY BACKS TIVO DIGITAL FORMAT
</P>
<P>
   The next generation of video recorders _ digital devices that
save programs on a hard drive instead of on a video cassette _
received a lift when Sony announced it had agreed to make the
device using a platform from Tivo, one of three competing designs.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT PROFILING COMES TO MEXICO
</P>
<P>
   Two of the biggest American credit reporting companies, Trans
Union of Chicago and Equifax of Atlanta, are building files and
computer systems in Mexico that will give bankers there the same
instantaneous credit profiles that bankers in New York and Miami
and Los Angeles take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   PLANET HOLLYWOOD DOWN BUT NOT OUT
</P>
<P>
   Despite complaints about its food and difficulties attracting
younger people and repeat customers, the Planet Hollywood
restaurant chain can still flourish by closing unprofitable outlets
and ``going back to the basics,'' says Robert Earl, its chief
executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
