<HEADLINE>
WITNESS IN RUSSIAN-SWISS PROBE LINKS YELTSIN AND KIN TO
CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-YELTSIN-CLINTON.) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE and CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZURICH, Switzerland _ A central figure in an investigation of
corruption in the Kremlin said Wednesday that he had seen credit
card bills and photocopies of credit cards bearing the signatures
of Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his daughters, and that the
cards had been provided by a Swiss construction company that has
done $1.5 billion worth of work for the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   The informant, Felipe Turover, a Soviet emigre who carries
Spanish and Israeli passports and who worked for a Swiss bank as a
debt collector in Russia, also said senior officials of the bank
had described to him a Kremlin meeting at which senior Russian
officials accepted money and gifts from the Swiss company, Mabetex
Project Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   He said one of those receiving a gift was Pavel Borodin, the
powerful property management director for the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
   The executives of the bank, Banca del Gottardo, ``said they were
a little surprised,'' Turover said, ``and asked, was this the
normal way of doing business there?''
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin has denied that Yeltsin or his daughters ever
received such credit cards or similar favors. In a telephone
conversation with President Clinton on Wednesday, Yeltsin denied
any involvement in the broadening money-laundering scandal, White
House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Banca del Gottardo spokesman Massimo Antonini said the bank
would not comment on Turover's claims. But in the past it has
firmly denied such allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Borodin has denied ever having pocketed bribes from Mabetex. In
a statement issued by the Kremlin on Wednesday, he described the
allegations against him as ``rubbish.'' He said some might be based
on forged documents, saying it was ``very easy to falsify credit
cards and signatures on them.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, no charges have been filed land _ A central figure in an
investigation of corruption in the Kremlin said Wednesday that he
had seen credit card bills and photocopies of credit cards bearing
the signatures of Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his
daughters, and that the cards had been provided by a Swiss
construction company that has done $1.5 billion worth of work for
the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   The informant, Felipe Turover, a Soviet emigre who carries
Spanish and Israeli passports and who worked for a Swiss bank as a
debt collector in Russia, also said senior officials of the bank
had described to him a Kremlin meeting at which senior Russian
officials accepted money and gifts from the Swiss company, Mabetex
Project Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   He said one of those receiving a gift was Pavel Borodin, the
powerful property management director for the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
   The executives of the bank, Banca del Gottardo, ``said they were
a little surprised,'' Turover said, ``and asked, was this the
normal way of doing business there?''
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin has denied that Yeltsin or his daughters ever
received such credit cards or similar favors. In a telephone
conversation with President Clinton on Wednesday, Yeltsin denied
any involvement in the broadening money-laundering scandal, White
House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Banca del Gottardo spokesman Massimo Antonini said the bank
would not comment on Turover's claims. But in the past it has
firmly denied such allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Borodin has denied ever having pocketed bribes from Mabetex. In
a statement issued by the Kremlin on Wednesday, he described the
allegations against him as ``rubbish.'' He said some might be based
on forged documents, saying it was ``very easy to falsify credit
cards and signatures on them.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, no charges have been filed against any Russian officials
or others involved in the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Turover, 35, has been a key witness in the Swiss investigation,
which was opened this year in response to a request by Moscow Chief
Prosecutor Yuri Skuratov, who was later fired by Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Although Turover boasts of broad past acquaintances in the
Kremlin, including reformers like Anatoly Chubais and Yegor Gaidar,
and of visits to the President's office in days gone by, he makes
no secret of his contempt for Yeltsin, whom he accuses of presiding
over corruption and decline.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Turover has been questioned several times in
Moscow by Russian magistrates, including Skuratov and Georgi
Chuglazov, who was prevented last week by the Kremlin from
traveling to Switzerland to investigate further.
</P>
<P>
   Turover has also been questioned by Swiss Prosecutor-General
Carla Del Ponte. Officials in Mrs. Del Ponte's office said it was
in part in response to information that Turover provided that
Skuratov sent his detailed request for help.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians under investigation, in addition to Borodin,
include members of his family and about two dozen other senior
Kremlin officials.
</P>
<P>
   But the most serious charges raised by Turover regard the credit
cards reportedly issued to Yeltsin and his daughters, Yelena
Okulova and Tatyana Dyachenko. Mrs. Dyachenko is considered to hold
considerable influence in Kremlin affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov said Tuesday that an estimate of how much Mabetex had
paid Russian officials in bribes _ about $10 million _ was supplied
by Mrs. Del Ponte in March when she visited Moscow to discuss the
case. He said part of the money was managed by Mabatex head Beghet
Pacolli, who used Mabatex-controlled accounts to pay credit card
bills for Yeltsin and his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov also said Yeltsin and his daughters should be
questioned about the credit cards. ``Naturally, the president
should be asked whether he knew about the situation,'' Skuratov
said in a television interview. ``And his daughters should be asked
as well. How did they look at this money? Why did they consider it
possible to spend it? These are basic questions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Turover, who left the Soviet Union in 1982, when he was 18, to
move to Spain, worked in the early 1990s with Banca del Gottardo in
Lugano, Switzerland, collecting corporate debt for Western
companies in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   About 1994, he said, a Banca del Gottardo executive responsible
for Eastern Europe, Franco Fenini, showed him photocopies of the
Yeltsin family's credit cards, including the signatures of Yeltsin
and his daughters, and copies of credit card bills that Fenini said
were paid from Mabetex accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Turover could not recall the amounts or creditors on the bills.
According to published reports, Yeltsin had an American Express
card and his daughters had Eurocards. Yeltsin reportedly used his
card only for minor purchases and largely out of curiosity, while
his daughters made some larger purchases through a Swiss shop.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss magistrates have confirmed that in a raid on the Mabetex
headquarters in Lugano in January, they confiscated credit card
records and copies of the cards themselves in Fenini's office
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Reymond, Mrs. Del Ponte's spokesman, said Wednesday
that all the confiscated documents had been sent to Moscow in two
shipments this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Turover, sipping beer and puffing cigarillos during an interview
Wednesday, said he had met Fenini about 1990 through an Italian
businessman, a mutual acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union, foreign companies'
inability to collect debts in Russia prompted Banca del Gottardo,
which specializes in trade finance, to start a collection
operation. For this, the bank hired Turover, who worked in Moscow
and reported to Fenini.
</P>
<P>
   Turover said he is not afraid to speak out, and said that if he
is threatened, he will release documents from an ``archive,''
although he insisted that he has never illegally stolen or copied
confidential documents.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Turover spends much of his time these days at an expensive hotel
in the hills above Zurich, and his phone book bulges with the
numbers of important people in Russia and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Turover's own career is fraught with conflict and
recriminations.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of his relationship with Fenini, according to
Filippo Ferrari, Fenini's lawyer, the men got along well. They
traveled together to Mexico, where Turover had lived for several
years after leaving the Soviet Union. When Turover was in Lugano,
he often stayed at Fenini's house.
</P>
<P>
   But the two men's friendship and business relationship broke up
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of Banca del Gottardo's debt-collection program,
Turover said, about 40 percent to 50 percent was destined for the
company that was owed the money, while 10 percent to 15 percent
went to the bank and the rest to him.
</P>
<P>
   But almost from the start, Turover said, Fenini had demanded and
received from Turover a share of his commission. In 1995, when
Turover complained to the bank's management, Fenini was fired _ and
was quickly hired by Pacolli at Mabatex to work as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Turover would not say how much he earned collecting debts for
Banca del Gottardo, only that the figure had `'more than six
zeros.'' But someone familiar with his work said he had made about
$6.5 million. Now, Turover says, he is demanding that the bank
repay him the money Fenini took from his fees, which he estimates
at more than $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Pacolli denies that his company paid any kickbacks, and says he
has no knowledge of the Yeltsin family credit cards. At a news
conference in Lugano last week, he threatened to bring charges
against Turover for violating Swiss bank secrecy, implying that
Turover had supplied investigators and perhaps others with
confidential documents from Banca del Gottardo.
</P>
<P>
   As he describes it, Turover's role helps illustrate the dynamics
of the cooperation in fighting organized crime that has developed
between Swiss and Russian investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Turover said he was interrogated by Mrs. Del Ponte before the
Russians made their request for legal assistance. In April last
year, Mrs. Del Ponte and Skuratov signed an agreement to supply
each other with better information about Russian organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of testimony given by Turover, officials in Mrs.
Del Ponte's office said, she suggested to Skuratov that he
formulate a clear request for legal help, a move that enabled the
Swiss to move energetically with their investigation of people
suspected of money laundering and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   In his effort to recover the money he says Fenini skimmed from
his fees, Turover has sued Fenini for extortion and forgery,
accusing him of forging his signature on withdrawal slips. Fenini
is countersuing.
</P>
<P>
   If he gets the $3 million, Turover says, he will donate it to
handicapped children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
