<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DO DOGS GO TO HEAVEN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday, Sept. 10)  
(bl) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   c.1999 N.Y.
Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those who haven't already screamed themselves hoarse over
the creationism/evolution thing, Dog Fancy magazine offers an even
more controversial topic in its September issue: ``Do Dogs Go To
Heaven?''
</P>
<P>
   Religious leaders from a variety of denominations were posed the
question, as was Mary Buddemeyer Porter, author of ``Will I See
Fido In Heaven?'' and Stephen H. Webb, author of ``On God and
Dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   As with the jokes where the priest, the rabbi and the minister
are stranded in a lifeboat, there was plenty of disagreement. A
priest, the Rev. Brian McSweeney of New York, said that a dog had
to have a relationship with a human in order to get into heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious follow-up question is: What kind of relationship are
we talking about here? Are we talking about a dog that chews shoes
and pees on the furniture or a dog that pulls children from burning
buildings and digs mountain climbers out of snowbanks?
</P>
<P>
   What about the vast majority of dogs that fall somewhere between
the two extremes? Are they like minor-league baseball players who
get called up to ``The Show'' for a ``cup of coffee'' (or, in this
case, a doggie biscuit) every few years but spend the vast majority
of their time riding in a hot bus with a bunch of mutts?
</P>
<P>
   A minister, the Rev. Andrew Linzey of England, thought the whole
good dog/bad dog question was irrelevant in terms of getting into
heaven, if not in terms of shoe-destruction and furniture-staining.
He said that dogs, like other animals, are incapable of making
moral choices. Buddemeyer Porter agreed, saying that dogs will get
to heaven regardless of their behavior on Earth because dogs are
innocent of any sin.
</P>
<P>
   My personal opinion is that if there is a heaven, dogs will
certainly get into it, though what they will do once they get up
there (out there? over there?) is anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   I'm imagining a place where dogs outnumber people, oh, about
10,000 to 1, so it will be plenty noisy and probably not smell all
that great. To pass the time (assuming that concept has any meaning
in heaven) there will be garbage cans to knock over and angel
mailmen to chase.
</P>
<P>
   The random oxygen molecules that some dogs, like mine, like to
bark at so much on Earth will be visible in heaven and will have
the shape and flavor of cheese curls. Dogs in heaven will be able
to eat as many of these snack molecules as they want without being
scolded or gaining weight.
</P>
<P>
   I will leave it to the theologians to decide whether cats get
into heaven, but I'm inclined to think that if they do, it will be
a heaven separate from dogs. After all, what kind of heaven would
it be to be chased for all eternity by a pack of slobbering
Rotweillers? A mighty fine heaven for the Rotweillers, I'd think,
but considerably less so for the cats.
</P>
<P>
   Whether only dog-lovers will be allowed to join dogs in doggie
heaven is another thorny question. Some people love dogs, some
people hate dogs and some go back and forth depending on whether
the dog is sleeping or crotch-sniffing. This raises the possibility
of a compartmentalized heaven, sort of like modern doctor's offices
where you get shuttled into ever-smaller, ever-colder rooms until
you finally find yourself alone in something the size of an Amana
freezer, naked save for a paper napkin across your lap, staring at
a color photograph of a smokers lung for the remainder of eternity
or until the doctor arrives, whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   So what we're looking at here is a vision of doggie heaven
that's devoid of cats, light on people, is cold, harshly lit and
smells like a doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Not much of a reward for a lifetime without sin, if you ask me.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
