<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BOWDEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIRLEY BOWDEN, ADVOCATE OF MIDDLE-INCOME HOUSING PROJECTS, DIES AT
88  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shirley F. Bowden, an early advocate of middle-income housing in
New York, died Tuesday at a nursing home in Valhalla, N.Y. He was
88.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden was founder and president of the Association for Middle
Income Housing, which became the Metropolitan Mutual Housing
Association. He was responsible for building large racially
integrated housing co-ops in Manhattan, the Bronx and Brooklyn in
the 1960s and 70s.
</P>
<P>
   One project, Morningside Gardens, changed the landscape north of
Columbia University with 1,200 units of middle-income housing. At
the time, it was one of the largest cooperative housing ventures in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, a Methodist, worked with religious and educational
groups. He helped the Archdiocese of New York build the Christopher
Court project in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Fenwick Bowden was born in Rochester on April 14, 1911.
A conscientious objector, he worked in a psychiatric hospital
during World War II. After the war, he joined the United Housing
Foundation, then founded the Association for Middle Income Housing
in 1958. He also founded the Cooperative Housing Foundation in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Cynthia, a sister, Janet Thayer of
Rochester, two daughters, Phyllis Thompson of Houston and Joyce
Hundley of Washington, and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
