<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE VISION BEHIND THE CBS-VIACOM MERGER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A merger like the one announced Tuesday between CBS and Viacom
is usually accompanied by bold predictions and the release of a
flock of superlatives. This merger was no exception. Listen to
Viacom's press release: ``The union of the two companies offers a
dramatic opportunity to drive revenues and enhance shareholder
value. Reaching the greatest number of viewers and listeners of any
media enterprise, spanning all ages and demographics, the new
Viacom will be the premier outlet for advertisers in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   This is tall talk, but it offers a glimpse of how Sumner
Redstone and Mel Karmazin, the chief executives of Viacom and CBS,
imagine that the media world, which has been reformulating itself
rapidly, now looks.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, all that will happen when CBS and Viacom merge is
that two self-referential systems will become one system with a
wider range of self-reference, directing a larger, more diverse
audience to a broader array of entertainment products and services,
all of them owned by Viacom. Like other recent media mergers, there
is something almost hydraulic about the vision underlying this
merger.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been talking about this union as though it were
the solution to a jigsaw puzzle, a matter of pieces fitting. But
what is really at stake is distribution, the ability to create a
seamless pipeline that delivers advertising, properly diluted with
programming, all across the demographic spectrum, where it will at
last ooze into the presence of the audience, young (MTV) and old
(CBS), through its medium of choice: movies, broadcast television,
cable, radio, billboards, the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This is indeed synergy _ not from the creative side of these
companies, the side where synergy is always being touted, but from
the business side. Obviously, advertising sales depend to a certain
degree on the quality of a television show, for instance, as well
as its distribution. But the audience this merger most clearly
serves is the shareholders. On the creative side, synergy is still
largely an illusion. On the business side, it is just common sense.
</P>
<P>
   In a different business climate, less relentlessly focused on
short-term stock performance, the scale of the new Viacom might
guarantee creative independence, even experimentation. One
anonymous television executive, quoted in Wednesday's Times, said:
``They've now created a company so big that the relative
performance of next week's new movie and next week's television
show is diminished. You've insulated the stock from weak
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   What this executive means is that shareholders are protected
from the effect of unpopular shows. But that same insulation from
stock market pressures could also be used to encourage and protect
creativity. That, however, is not a likely outcome of this kind of
merger.
</P>
<P>
   It seems almost hopelessly old-fashioned to worry about the
consolidation of media outlets at a time when, so the accepted
wisdom goes, media outlets are being created faster than they can
be consolidated. Cable and now the Internet have dramatically
unsettled what was once a stable, familiar media landscape. The
Internet, especially, creates the illusion that mergers of the
CBS/Viacom kind will inevitably be offset by a radical, almost
uncontrollable independence on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But the furious capitalization of Internet companies tells us
that they too are game for consolidation, as does Internet usage,
which is driven more and more by fewer and fewer Web sites of the
kind already owned by Viacom. When it comes to media companies,
bigger does not necessarily mean better. It merely means more of
the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
