<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MILITARY-POLITICS-1ST     09-08 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-540(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY OF MILITARY AND CIVILIAN VIEWS FINDS GAP IN POLITICS,
VALUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs lede graf for smoothing) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
(bl) 
 By ADAM CLYMER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A deep gap over politics and values has opened over
the last two decades between the nation's increasingly conservative
military elite and prominent civilians without military service,
sowing latent distrust despite the respect each group professes for
the other.
</P>
<P>
   These are the first findings of a major study of military and
civilian attitudes, focusing on a problem that Defense Secretary
William Cohen has called a major challenge for him: ``to somehow
prevent a chasm from developing between the military and civilian
worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   While there were few disagreements about foreign policy among
the two groups, the single most striking finding was political.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Americans divide about evenly between calling
themselves Democrats or Republicans, but the study found that 64
percent of elite military officers called themselves Republicans.
Only 8 percent said they were Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   A more modest gap on political identification had been measured
before. Comparable 1976 data found that 33 percent of military
officers identified themselves as Republicans and 12 percent as
Democrats. The 1976 survey did not cover values.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder, in both surveys, said they were independent or
had no political affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   The most startling differences were found between the military
leaders and the potential military leaders, like students at
advanced schools like the war colleges, and prominent civilians who
had never served in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   The civilians were selected at random from ``Who's Who'' and
from other lists, like prominent women, the clergy, foreign policy
experts, labor leaders and the news media. Prominent civilians with
military service fell in between.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 45 percent of the military group favored barring
homosexuals from teaching in public schools, while only 17 percent
of the nonveteran civilian group did. Only 10 percent of the
military leaders supported a ban on the death penalty, while 37
percent of the civilians did. And 74 percent of the military group
backed permitting prayer in public schools, compared with 46
percent of the civilian group.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the differences can be explained by the fact that the
officers were almost all male, while the nonveteran civilian group
was two-fifths female.
</P>
<P>
   The results were taken from nearly 4,000 interviews conducted in
late 1998 and early 1999 as part of a $500,000 study that will
ultimately produce at least 20 academic papers. The study is
coordinated for the Triangle Institute for Security Studies, a
North Carolina foundation, by Richard H. Kohn, a professor of
history at the University of North Carolina, and Peter D. Feaver,
associate professor of political science at Duke University.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first findings were the hot topic last weekend at the 95th
annual meeting of the American Political Science Association in
Atlanta. Further data are to be made public at a conference by the
Triangle Institute in late October in Caughny, Ill., including a
comparison with the views of the general civilian public that may
show the nonveteran elite more at odds with ordinary Americans than
is the military elite.
</P>
<P>
   In papers presented at the Atlanta meeting, scholars had more
fear of potential dangers than evidence of any impact of the gap
thus far. Professor Ole R. Holsti of Duke, who longed for the days
when generals like George C. Marshall never even voted, said, ``A
political military is worrisome if it just becomes another interest
group.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Charles Stevenson of the National War College said it
was ``scary'' to have ``an officer corps so overwhelmingly
Republican.'' ``In the 19th century, officers frequently had
political alignments,'' Stevenson said, ``but they did not favor a
single party consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin O. Fordham, assistant professor of political science at
the State University of New York at Albany, said the gap in beliefs
had not affected either military spending or the rates of
enlistment and re-enlistment. But the professor said he worried
that Democrats might not take seriously warnings from a military
establishment that they perceived as overwhelmingly Republican.
</P>
<P>
   One clear finding was a widespread unhappiness in the military
with current trends in civilian society. But despite the generally
high regard the public holds for the military, there were some
clear measures of latent civilian distrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Support for the military drops, even precipitously, as
connections to the military disappear,'' wrote Feaver and Paul
Gronke, assistant professor of political science at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one percent, for example, of the civilian nonveteran
elite said they would be disappointed if a child joined the armed
forces. Just 7 percent of the military officers felt that way. On
the other hand, 77 percent of officers agreed with the statement
that ``civilian society would be better off if it adopted more of
the military's values and customs;'' only 43 percent of civilian
elites with military experience agreed and just 25 percent of the
nonveterans agreed.
</P>
<P>
   One simple explanation for some of the gap is the differing
attitudes of men and women. Women comprise 41 percent of the
civilian nonveteran elite, but only 8 percent of the military
elite. Feaver said in an interview that on many of the issues
examined, as much as half the difference between military and
civilian opinions could be attributed to the relative conservatism
of men.
</P>
<P>
   But the difference between the Republicanism of the more than
600 almost all-male officers surveyed and the nearly 700 nonveteran
civilians is only marginally related to the preference of women for
the Democratic Party. The most recent New York Times/CBS News Poll
showed that 29 percent of the public were Republicans and 31
percent Democrats. Among men, 29 percent also said they were
Republicans but just 26 percent identified themselves as
Democrats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the nonveteran civilian elite, 30 percent called
themselves Republicans and 43 percent Democrats, while among
veterans, 47 percent identified themselves as Republicans and 23
percent Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The veterans averaged nearly 60 years old, while the nonveterans
averaged around 50.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Two other military groups were also surveyed, nearly 400
officers in the active reserves and 1,700 students in the Reserve
Officers Training Corps in colleges and cadets and midshipmen at
the service academies, who were identified as ``pre-commissioned''
respondents. Among the reservists, 63 percent said they were
Republicans and 10 percent identified themselves as Democrats,
while 47 percent of the students said they were Republican and 12
percent Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Holsti said it was clear that the Republican trend in the
military began well before President Clinton took office. There is
considerable tension between the administration and the military
over Clinton's avoiding the draft, his attempt to remove barriers
to homosexuals in the services, and the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Holsti also said the Republicans in the military were not
extremists; only 13 percent called themselves ``very
conservative.'' They rejected propositions such as removing books
attacking religion or promoting communism or homosexuality from
library shelves by the same sort of overwhelming majorities as
others in the study.
</P>
<P>
   On military and foreign policy questions, there were a large
number of agreements between the nonveterans and the military
elite. Both overwhelmingly supported using the United Nations to
help settle international disputes and felt the American public
would not tolerate large numbers of casualties in military
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups heavily rejected the idea that military, rather than
political goals, should govern the use of force. Both disagreed
sharply with the statement, ``We shouldn't think so much in
international terms but concentrate more on our own national
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were also clear differences. Among the nonveterans, 59
percent agreed with the statement that ``American national security
depends more on international trade and a strong domestic economy
than on our military strength.'' Only 37 percent of the officers
agreed. And 65 percent of the officers but only 43 percent of the
nonveterans agreed with the proposition that ``There is nothing
wrong with using the CIA to try to undermine hostile governments.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohn said in an interview that when the study is completed, ``We
are likely to have a set of conclusions that are complex.'' He said
the current level of discussion of the issue ``tends to be one of
extremes,'' either arguing that the differences between military
and civilians are of no consequence, or that they raise the threat
of a breakdown in civilian control.
</P>
<P>
   The professor said it was important to identify the differences
that were new, and also those that did not simply represent the
fact that the military was an ``unusual and very different
profession.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DELTA-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-08 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELTA AIR LINES DISMISSES SAATCHI &AMP; SAATCHI  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ill., Minn.)   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Another giant airline is changing agencies. If only
the planes would move as fast as the accounts do.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines in Atlanta ended a two-month review late
Wednesday by dismissing its agency of two and a half years, Saatchi
&AMP; Saatchi in New York, and shifting its worldwide account to the
Leo Burnett Company in Chicago. Delta has spent $45 million to $50
million annually on advertising in recent years, but trade
publications have reported billings on the account at an estimated
$100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very sad,'' said Jennifer Laing, North American
chairwoman and chief executive at Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, part of
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC. ``We have great affection for the brand, and
we wish Delta well.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a new broom sweeps clean,'' she added, referring to a
shake-up in top management at Delta that left ``no one there who
hired us'' in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have at Delta is a brand in transition with management
change,'' Ms. Laing said. ``They wanted their own team. I've won
and lost on those before; it's common in our industry. That's life
on the fast track.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Burnett referred calls to Delta. There was no
response to several messages left for Delta public relations
executives.
</P>
<P>
   The decision returns Burnett to the lofty ranks of agencies with
big, blue-chip airline accounts. Burnett was blindsided in 1996
when it lost one of its flagship clients, the United Airlines unit
of the UAL Corp., which left for Fallon McElligott in Minneapolis
and Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A familiar theme of Burnett's popular campaigns for United,
which began in 1965, was ``Fly the friendly skies.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi's work for Delta did not seem to
strike similar chords with consumers. A theme that the agency
introduced in 1997, ``On top of the world,'' was recently
discontinued, airline executives said, because research among
flyers showed that they perceived the slogan as a boast by Delta
about its status in the airline industry rather than the intended
meaning that Delta lifted its passengers, as the song goes, up
where they belong.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta review began in July, when the airline disclosed that
it was holding talks with Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, the incumbent, and two
other agencies, Burnett and TBWA Worldwide in New York, part of
Omnicom Group. Last month, there were also meetings with two
additional shops, Grey Advertising in New York and the J. Walter
Thompson Company in New York, part of WPP Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson subsequently withdrew from consideration, leaving four
finalists: Burnett, Grey, Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi and TBWA. Burnett had
been considered a front-runner because Leo F. Mullin, Delta's chief
executive, became familiar with top managers at that agency when he
was a top banking executive at the First Chicago Corp., now part of
the First Chicago NBD Corp..
</P>
<P>
   The saying ``When it rains, it pours'' apparently applies to
advertising as well as to salt because Burnett, which had been
without an airline client since United's departure, will now have
two. The agency's Stockholm office was named in July to handle the
account of Scandinavian Airlines System, with billings estimated at
$13 million. The trade publication Advertising Age reported that
SAS would not consider it a conflict for Burnett to work on its
account as well as Delta's.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi will try to keep in place the employees who
have worked on the Delta account, Ms. Laing said, because ``we hope
to stay in the airline industry.'' That worked before, when the
agency landed Delta after losing the British Airways account.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCHOOLS-JEWS-HOLIDAYS     09-08 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-JEWS-HOLIDAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACLU SUES A SCHOOL DISTRICT FOR CLOSING ON THE JEWISH HIGH HOLY
DAYS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, N.J., N.Y.)   By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLUE ASH, Ohio _ It began with Good Friday. Seven years ago a
group of Jewish parents here in the Sycamore Community School
District asked why the schools were closed for Good Friday and not
for the Jewish High Holy Days.
</P>
<P>
   When the school board eventually voted to cancel classes for the
High Holy Days, a group of Muslim and Hindu parents asked why the
schools did not also close for the most holy of their holidays. But
they got no satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in escalation of a fight that portends further growing
pains as the nation becomes more religiously diverse, the American
Civil Liberties Union is suing the Sycamore schools on the ground
that they are favoring one religion over others.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU says the district is giving preference to Jewish
families, and so violating the First Amendment. For its part, the
district says it closes on the High Holy Days only to avoid the
disruption of high absenteeism.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict poses a challenge to the standard religious pecking
order that has evolved in many American cities and suburbs, where
Christians are the dominant majority, Jews a vocal minority, and
those of other faiths so few or unorganized as to be virtually
invisible. Here, parents of various minority religions have
asserted their presence by uniting and demanding treatment equal to
that of Jews _ holidays for all, or for none.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to give a holiday to the Jews, you ought to
give holidays to the Muslims, to the Hindus, to the Buddhists, to
the Sikhs _ and that is impractical,'' said Zeinab Schwen, a Muslim
parent with three children in Sycamore schools. ``If we're all
minorities, we're all minorities together. We shouldn't have
degrees of minority.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish High Holy Days bracket a 10-day period of
introspection and repentance that begins with Rosh ha-Shanah, which
this year starts this Friday at sundown, and ends with Yom Kippur.
Officials of the Sycamore schools, a well-heeled suburban district
15 miles northeast of Cincinnati, say they decided to close for
those two days only because so many students had been absent on
them. Bruce Armstrong, the superintendent, said about 15 percent of
the district's students, who number more than 6,200, did not go to
school on Rosh ha-Shanah or Yom Kippur before the policy of
shutting down then began. On major Muslim and Hindu holidays, he
said, only about 6 percent of students are absent, including a 3.5
percent routine rate of absenteeism.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, other school districts, including New York
City's and some in New Jersey and Connecticut, also close for the
Jewish holidays. If the reason for the closing is that a high
proportion of teachers or students will be absent and cause
disruption, then that is fine, said Marc D. Stern, a lawyer with
the American Jewish Congress. ``You don't have to be a majority,''
Stern said. ``You just have to be enough of a minority for your
absence to disturb education.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``I have argued in districts that used to have
large numbers of Jews and don't anymore that it makes no sense, nor
is it morally right, to close down and leave the other kids with no
school, their parents working, and nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of the lawsuit has alarmed school superintendents
elsewhere, concerned that their districts could also be sued
because they too close for the High Holy Days, ACLU officials said.
``I have been explaining to superintendents all over the east side
of Cleveland that this case is highly fact-specific, and it does
not mean anyone else is going to be sued,'' said Raymond Vasvari,
legal director of the ACLU of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The civil liberties union says the particular history of how the
schools came to be closed in the Sycamore district is evidence that
the reasons were not purely educational or secular.
</P>
<P>
   After Jewish parents first petitioned seven years ago for a High
Holy Days closing, the board appointed a calendar committee to
examine the issue. But the committee, whose members included
rabbis, a Protestant minister and parents of various religions,
recommended that the schools stay open, because ``an effort to
select some religious days as holidays while ignoring others does
not equate to equal treatment or religious sensitivity.'' The
schools did stay closed on Good Friday, because a day off on that
holiday had been written into the staff's union contract years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The High Holy Days issue remained a cause among some Jewish
parents, however. So in 1995 the board decided that if absenteeism
on a holiday reached a threshold 18 percentage points above the
average student absentee rate of about 3.5 percent, the schools
would be closed on that holiday as of the following year. In a
concession to Jewish parents, the board recommended that on the
High Holy Days, teachers not give tests or introduce new material.
</P>
<P>
   But ``it didn't work,'' said Armstrong, the superintendent. The
students who did attend were not provided ``a quality school day,''
he said, and some parents agree. They say their children spent the
day in class reading or reviewing. Even some non-Jewish parents
started keeping their children home.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1997 the board again revisited the issue, which was
introduced this time by Renee Roth, who by now was the board's
president. Ms. Roth, a former teacher, was one of the Jewish
parents who had initially petitioned the board to close for the
High Holy Days. In this 1997 vote, the board decided to try what it
called a ``pilot program'' in which the schools would shut on Rosh
ha-Shanah and Yom Kippur for the next two years. The vote was 3 to
2.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim and Hindu parents complained, and were joined by some
Jewish parents. The opponents presented the board a petition with
90 signatures. When that did not work, they hired a lawyer. The
ACLU got wind of the episode, and took the case on. The volunteer
lawyer is Stephen R. Felson, a Jew who lived in Israel for 14
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea of using a governing body to vote in your
religious preference is bad in general,'' Felson said, ``and even
worse for minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   But none of the Muslim or Hindu parents, or their Jewish or
Christian allies, were willing to sign on as plaintiffs, Felson
said. (Instead, the sole plaintiffs are the ACLU of Ohio and its
members.) Few of those parents were willing to be identified by a
reporter. They said they did not want to be seen as anti-Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roth and the other board members are all named as defendants
in the ACLU's lawsuit, and said they had been advised by the
district's lawyer not to give interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the case brought by the civil liberties union is
that the absenteeism rate never hit the 18-percentage-point
threshold the board itself had set, said Vasvari of the Ohio ACLU.
``The threshold policy is a sham,'' he said. ``Having set a
standard, they chose to disregard it.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside an open house at Sycamore Junior High School one recent
evening, there were Christian parents who favored the closing, and
those who opposed it. There were also Jews who supported it, and
Jews who opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   Several Jewish parents said they understood why the Muslims and
the Hindus felt offended. But one Jewish father saw the lawsuit as
hate-mongering by Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take it as a personal kick in the face,'' he said. ``They'll
do anything to bash a Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Among many Jews, though, the issue is a difficult one, and the
prevailing sentiment is one of ambivalence. Waiting for school to
start one morning recently, a Jewish parent, Linda Rosner, said she
had always kept her daughter Margo home for the High Holy Days.
Margo added that in her elementary school class, 6 of the 21
students were Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it would cause disruption,'' Ms. Rosner said, ``that's a
good enough reason to close.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, ``I wouldn't think it's right to put any
religious group ahead of the other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
