<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MRS. WHITMAN WITHDRAWS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Sept. 9:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman's decision not to run for the U.S. Senate
stunned New Jersey politicians and disappointed those who had hoped
that a successful Senate campaign would give this personable,
middle-of-the-road Republican broader national exposure. Her
decision does not necessarily end her career in politics. By not
running for the Senate she leaves herself available should George
W. Bush want her as his running mate or, if he wins, in his
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Her decision also opens the door for an entirely different kind
of Senate contest in New Jersey. Democrats are abruptly cheerful at
the prospect of a primary brawl between Jon Corzine, a wealthy
political neophyte, and Jim Florio, a former governor. A half-dozen
state and congressional Republicans are grabbing for the banner
that Mrs. Whitman dropped. The entire spectacle is a reminder that
many prominent Senate careers have been forged by unknowns who
darted through an unexpected opening.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about Mrs. Whitman's action will probably last until
Election Day. Her stated reasons about unfinished business and
fund-raising seem plausible but incomplete. So while the mystery
may linger, Mrs. Whitman has assured that the history of the 2000
race in New Jersey will be written on an entirely new and
unexpected page.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
