<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BRADLEY ENTERS THE RACE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, September
9:
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, who announced officially Wednesday that he is a
candidate for the Democratic nomination, has toyed with the idea of
a presidential campaign before. In 1992 his name appeared on the
long list of Democrats that finally narrowed down to Bill Clinton.
Almost four years later, after resigning from the Senate and
declaring the political system ``broken,'' Bradley briefly flirted
with presidential possibilities again, hinting at a run as an
independent candidate. Now, as a suddenly prominent alternative to
Vice President Al Gore, Bradley's timing is finally right. Since
all the other plausible Democrats were scared away, Bradley will
get more than a fair chance to test Gore's staying power.
</P>
<P>
   To counter the vice president's inevitability card, Bradley is
playing the outsider card. His kickoff was designed to underscore
his theme that he grew up in the kind of small town that Gore only
visited on summer vacation. As for message, the studious former
basketball star seems to be speaking to Americans who are wary of
Washington, weary of Clintonism or still stirred by the belief
system of the old Democratic Party. He spoke Wednesday of directing
national wealth toward child poverty and health care. He labeled
race relations a pressing issue. But most of all he wants Americans
to believe that a life started outside Washington, and his
rejection of Senate life, would make him and Gore ``very different
presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, for all his early stumbling, still has a solid foundation
of party support that will be difficult to overturn in this
concentrated primary season. Still, the very polls Bradley
dismissed in his announcement speech now show him virtually even
with Gore in the first primary in New Hampshire. That is not a bad
place to start in a state that likes to surprise front-runners. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
