<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTL-NOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tourney format change valuable
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The misnomer that is the European Champions League has
an initial draw unkind to many of the reigning champions. But the
future of the world's richest club tournament rests not on
rewarding teams who prevail at home, but with ensuring that the
biggest and most glamorous sides show up and therefore enhance an
increasingly lucrative revenue stream.
</P>
<P>
   Once open only to the winners of Europe's domestic leagues, the
expanded Champions League begins the first phase of group play
Tuesday, features 32 teams, eight more than last year. Two years
ago, the number was 16. Included in the field are the top four
finishers in Germany, the top three in Spain, Italy and England and
the top two in France, Holland, Norway and Portugal. The two
minnows still alive, Maribor Teatanic of Slovenia and Molde of
Norway, had to go through three qualifying rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new format, the top two teams in each of the eight
groups will advance to the second round, starting in November.
</P>
<P>
   UEFA, the European soccer federation, revised the competition in
response to the threat of a breakaway European league spearheaded
by AC Milan owner and broadcasting mogul Silvio Berlusconi. The
Champions League will earn an estimated $750 million, and the pot
of gold for the winner is about $60 million, compared with the $22
million victorious Manchester United took home from Barcelona in
May.
</P>
<P>
   United should be able to handle a Group D field that includes
Olympique Marseille, Croatia Zagreb and Sturm Graz. But the Red
Devils have an English Premier League and international schedule
and have injuries that could sap their depth. Bayern Munich, which
United defeated in the final moments of their thrilling 2-1
European Cup title match, has stumbled out of the gate in Germany
and will have a battle in Group E with Valencia, Glasgow Rangers
and PSV Eindhoven.
</P>
<P>
   AC Milan won Italy's Serie A but opens on the road Wednesday
against Chelsea _ 2:30 p.m., ESPN2 _ in Group H. Barcelona, which
cruised to the Spanish Primera Division crown, got no favors in
Group B with Arsenal and Fiorentina. The latter two square off
Tuesday in the best match of the opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Euro 2000: France, England hang on
</P>
<P>
   Norway, Spain and Sweden on Wednesday clinched berths in next
summer's European championships, but defending World Cup champion
France will need some help in the final round of qualifying next
month to advance. The French defeated Armenia 3-2, with Zinedine
Zidane breaking a 1-1 deadlock in the 67th minute. France is tied
with Russia for second place in Group 4. The Ukraine took a
one-point lead by edging Iceland 1-0, while Russia had a tough time
beating lowly Andorra 2-1. On Oct. 9, France hosts Iceland, while
Russia meets the Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   England is on the brink of elimination after finishing its
qualifying slate with a 0-0 draw at Poland. The only way England
can reach the playoffs is if Sweden beats the Poles next month.
</P>
<P>
   The game matched the mood beforehand, as riot police were
dispatched in Warsaw to quell disturbances between rival fans. Nine
people were injured.... Italy blew a chance to win Group 1 as Jon
Dahl Tomasson scored in the 63rd minute to give Denmark a 3-2
victory. Italy, which led 2-0 in the first half, is tied with
Denmark at the top with 14 points apiece as both teams secured at
least playoff spots.
</P>
<P>
   The other photo finish is in Group 8, which Yugoslavia leads
with 16 points after a 4-2 win over Macedonia on Wednesday. Savo
Milosevic scored in the first 10 seconds, one of the quickest goals
in international history, to set the pace. Ireland is a point
behind after edging Malta 3-2, thanks to a late free-kick goal from
Steve Staunton. Croatia has 14 points after beating Ireland 1-0
Saturday on a goal by Davor Suker in the fifth minute of injury
time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
