<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Davenport outslugs Pierce after rain delay
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mary Pierce isn't known for her mental perseverance,
but this was not a choke Wednesday. It was the best women's match
of the U.S. Open so far.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce, pegged as dangerous but fragile during her erratic
10-year career, served for the match at 5-4 in the third set
against defending women's champion Lindsay Davenport. When Pierce
didn't capitalize on two match points, Davenport escaped to the
semifinals with a 6-2, 3-6, 7-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``She won this tournament last year, she's No. 2 in the world,
was No. 1, and I had two match points; I have to look at it that
way,'' Pierce said. ``My game is coming along, and I need to work
to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The final three games were classic baseline slugfests. Pierce
struck three winners in each game, but Davenport played the first
24 points without an error.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who says they don't get nervous is lying,'' Davenport
said. ``You know what to do: Hit the ball hard but don't aim for
the lines and don't go for a winner return. Go for deep and down
the middle. Make first serves.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce missed her first match point at 5-4, 40-30 when Davenport
hit a winner on the 14th stroke of the point. Another match point
got away when Pierce hit a backhand just wide, close enough to
initiate a brief victory leap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went for that shot, which I really didn't need to do,''
Pierce said.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce, seeded fifth, then made a pair of backcourt errors that
evened the set at 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   Then it began to rain, delaying play for one hour. It was
reminiscent of the 1994 French Open, when Pierce, a French citizen,
gave up just 10 games in her six matches to the final, and that
included a 6-2, 6-2 wipeout of Steffi Graf.
</P>
<P>
   The final against Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario didn't start until
6:22 p.m. and was stopped again after three games. Pierce couldn't
hold a 3-1 lead and lost 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping it wasn't going to rain,'' Pierce said.. ``I just
went back to the locker room and tried to focus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have been home when the rain came,'' Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport opened game 11 with consecutive aces and went up 6-5
after Pierce had brought it back to deuce.
</P>
<P>
   Serving to stay in the match, Pierce twice hit winners to stay
in the match, but Davenport won a game of four deuces when Pierce
double-faulted on match point. Next for Davenport is Serena
Williams, who defeated Monica Seles 4-6, 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
