<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY DENIES ROLE IN CLINTON'S CLEMENCY OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAY SHORE, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton said Wednesday that she
had played no role in any of the decisions that led to President
Clinton's offer of clemency to 16 Puerto Rican militants, a move
that has created problems for her campaign for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said she heard of the conditional commutation
only after the president announced it a month ago, and learned from
her campaign press secretary Saturday that the White House on
Friday had given the terrorists a week to meet Clinton's demands.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton made her remarks at the first full-fledged news
conference she has held since announcing in June that she was
considering a race for U.S. the Senate. She met with reporters in
the orchestra room of the high school here, in a 32-minute session
that was dominated by questions about Clinton's offer of clemency
to 16 members of the FALN.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of statements by Mrs. Clinton on the clemency issue,
she has come under attack both by Puerto Rican leaders in New York
and groups that opposed the release of the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the news conference Mrs. Clinton said she stood by
her statement of last Saturday, when she said that the militants
had been given enough time to meet the conditions set in Clinton's
offer, which required that they renounce violence. At that time,
she called on the White House to rescind the offer immediately.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton, who is known as a quick learner and for her
command of policy, said she was not familiar enough with the
details of the FALN case to offer an opinion on whether her husband
should have offered the clemency in the first place. The FALN, the
initials for the Spanish name of the Armed Forces of National
Liberation, is a terrorist group that advocates independence for
Puerto Rico and that had been linked to 130 bombings in the 1970s
and '80s. None of the 16 offered clemency were convicted of crimes
that resulted in injuries or deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton did not suggest that any steps should now be taken
to revoke the commutations that have been granted to 12 of the
imprisoned FALN members who met Clinton's demands.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said she would not share with the public the
details of her conversation with her husband on the matter.
``There's one thing I'm not going to talk about and that's my
private conversations with the president,'' Mrs. Clinton said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the first lady then said that when she sat down with Clinton
at Camp David on Saturday to alert him that her campaign was
putting out a statement, the president made no mention of a letter
the White House had sent the night before setting the one-week
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The juxtaposition of events _ Clinton setting a deadline of
Friday, and Mrs. Clinton saying that the White House should act
immediately _ seemed to undercut Mrs. Clinton's attempts to deal
with the issue. Several of her supporters said that had she known
about the deadline, she probably would not have intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said the first that she learned of the White House
deadline was after she had issued her statement, when a reporter
called her press secretary, Howard Wolfson, to inquire about it,
and Wolfson then called her.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are funny ways of finding things out,'' Mrs. Clinton
said. Asked if she believed that her husband knew about the
deadline when she spoke to him that morning, Mrs. Clinton responded
with a slip of a smile: ``I think that that's a fair bet. Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   The 16 who were offered clemency had gained support from a
number of New York's Hispanic leaders, and such figures as former
President Jimmy Carter and Cardinal John O'Connor. In the days
since Mrs. Clinton demanded that the offer be renounced, 12 of the
prisoners, acting under the pressure of deadline set by Clinton,
met his demands for clemency. The first lady demurred when asked if
she thought those commutations should be rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand by what I said on Saturday,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the Republican who is
likely to oppose Mrs. Clinton in next year's Senate race, called
upon the president to withdraw the offer, as survivors of FALN
attacks held news conferences to denounce the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, at City Hall, poked fun at the first lady for what
even Democrats have come to see as a clumsy attempt at separating
herself from her husband. When a reporter started a question by
saying that Mrs. Clinton stands by her statement on the subject,
Giuliani cut him off. ``Stands by her husband?'' the mayor asked
mischievously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, this is on the terrorist thing. OK, all right, you know I
get confused. Sometimes it's stand by him, sometimes it's stand
against him. It's getting confusing now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990908.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     09-08 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NOT TOO NICE TO WIN ANOTHER OPEN TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They say that Lindsay Davenport didn't have a mean
bone in her body; she was too nice to be a champion. Davenport was
not nice Wednesday. She cornered Mary Pierce and then snatched
victory by forcing Pierce to beat herself. On the day that Serena
Williams cruised past Monica Seles, this would be the best women's
match so far in the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, the defending champion, conceded that her 6-2, 3-6,
7-5 victory was not so much a case of her winning but of Pierce's
losing. For two and a half sets, Pierce and Davenport fought a
tremendous battle.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the first set easily, Davenport suddenly lost her
form; she reverted to being the tall bashful player whose
confidence was like the tide: sometimes high, sometimes low.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had me playing off my back foot,'' Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   She dropped the second set and was playing weakly going into the
third and final set. Davenport trailed, 5-3, and faced double match
point. From somewhere deep inside, Davenport made a great shot,
deep down the middle past a lunging Pierce. Pierce then
double-faulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next thing I knew it was 5-4,'' Davenport said, still
amazed at how the events unfolded. ``Everything moved so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The final puzzle for Davenport: how could she break Pierce? For
long stretches of the match Pierce was serving strongly, not like
the fragile, frightened player who once lost winnable games, but
like a player who had her game and her emotions under control.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Davenport pulled off the tennis equivalent of Ali's
rope-a-dope: she decided to let Pierce break herself. She made a
great shot to save match point. Pierce double-faulted, then missed
wide. Two unforced errors _ a backhand long and a forehand in the
net _ then cost Pierce the game and tied the set at 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce was contending with a surging Davenport, as well as
nature. It was raining lightly and, with visions of Mary Joe
Fernandez lying on the court two days earlier, Davenport motioned
to the officials. ``It's too wet,'' she said. The umpire agreed and
suspended play.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce fumed, walked off and slammed her racquet on the court as
she sat and crossed her legs. Then she put her head in her hands
like someone who had just been told her house had burned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could tell myself was that I should have been home,''
Davenport said. ``When the rain came, I should have been on my way
to Manhattan packing my clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she sent Pierce packing.
</P>
<P>
   During the delay, Davenport's coach, Robert Van't Hof, reminded
her that she couldn't revert to being the shy, retiring player she
was before winning her first Open. She had to take this match; she
couldn't keep waiting for Pierce to self-destruct. Davenport had to
make Pierce self-destruct.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he didn't like to see me get dictated to all over
the court, and she was doing that,'' Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment of truth, Pierce finally obliged. With the game on
the line and in her hand, she double-faulted on match point.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a sad way to way to end it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the 23-year-old Davenport learned a lesson that the
24-year-old Pierce had not and possibly will not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today,'' she said, ``I felt so much better about playing tight
matches than I did two or three years ago. I learned not to try to
hit the ball harder or go for winners when I was down. Just go for
deep shots down the middle. I was enjoying the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce, for her part, admitted that she caved in to her own
desire to achieve something that has eluded her for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you want something so badly that you put extra
pressure on yourself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Davenport went on about how sweet it was to shed old
labels, to force critics to look at her in a new light, to use the
Open as a launching pad for bigger and better conquests. But
Wednesday she said defending her championship was far more
satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about how I handled myself today,'' she said.
``I've had a good time defending my title, whether it ends here
Friday or Saturday. Pulling out a match like this makes this title
even more special.''
</P>
<P>
   They say Lindsay Davenport is too nice to sustain her
championship. Wednesday, thanks to a shower, she proved she was
tough enough. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
