<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CARDINALS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves slip past Cardinals to complete sweep
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves have brought the Cardinals little but
frustration this season, so why should Wednesday night have been
any different?
</P>
<P>
   Five times this season the Cardinals had suffered losses in the
Braves' final at-bat. Oddly, Wednesday night's Braves win _ 5-4 to
complete a three-game sweep _ was pretty well decided in the sixth
inning when rookie pitcher Rick Ankiel got wild, walked four and
gave up three runs to snap a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   But the frustrating thing was that the Cardinals were finally
scoring on Kevin Millwood _ something they couldn't do in 10
innings on Aug. 28 _ and they got a hit from Mark McGwire, who
ended an 0-for-20 spell with a single in the third. But it was all
ultimately for naught, despite Craig Paquette's two-run homer in
the eighth off Russ Springer that accounted for the final margin.
</P>
<P>
   Ankiel walked Andruw Jones, Jose Hernandez and Brian Hunter to
set up a bases-loaded situation for Tuesday night's hero Howard
Battle, who came through with patience this time, drawing a
run-scoring walk. He was followed by a two-run Gerald Williams
single to all but seal Ankiel's first major-league loss in the
Cardinals' seventh defeat in eight games against the Braves this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves kept their 3 1/2 game lead on the Mets, who beat the
Giants 7-5 in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Ankiel, the 20-year-old phenom of the striped red-and-white
socks and nasty repertoire, was making his fourth big-league start.
His first three lessons were mainly in futility as he left with a
lead or a tie each time and came away without a decision in three
Cardinals losses.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones, who added to Ankiel's woes with a 12th-inning
home run in a 4-3 win over the Cardinals Aug. 29, hurt him a little
more directly this time with his 39th home run of the season to
start the Braves' scoring in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Jones his 12th homer from the right side in 124 at
bats this season. He'd had 12 in 678 career at-bats from the right
before this season.
</P>
<P>
   So Millwood wasn't the near-perfect pitcher he's been lately,
and had his major-league-leading .202 opponents batting average
take a bit of a hit. But that still left him room to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood gave up seven hits in six innings _ the same number
he'd allowed in his previous two starts _ but allowed only two
runs, which he has done in each of his last six starts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
