<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NINES-DAY(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
9-9-99: A LUCKY DAY, OR ONE TO DREAD? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thursday could be your lucky day. It's the ninth day
of the ninth month of the ninety-ninth year; the ninth inning of a
star-crossed century and, for many astrologers, an auspicious day
for new beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   A day to play the lottery? Nein. The numbers 9-9-99 sold out
just hours after they went on sale last Thursday, according to the
New York State Lottery. (Hey, there are nines still available in
New Jersey.)
</P>
<P>
   But before you pour your savings into the Dow, soothsayers with
one eye on the devil warn that Thursday might be better spent in a
well-stocked bunker. Note what happens to those nines when they are
turned upside down and you'll understand the apprehension.
</P>
<P>
   Software savants call the date ``the dreaded nines,'' a Y2K-like
event that could gum up some operations, especially programs
created before the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're a woman at the end of your third trimester or a
cat on its ninth life, you probably have little affinity for the
number nine. The ancient Greeks had 9 muses, there are 99 names for
God in Islam and many real estate leases run for 99 years, but all
in all, the number cannot be pigeonholed.
</P>
<P>
   It's no lucky eight, nowhere near as sinful as seven and far
from a perfect 10, yet it is hard to find consensus on whether nine
is a figure to be cherished or banished.
</P>
<P>
   For the Japanese, nine is something of a headache. Because it's
pronounced like the word for pain, it is a number you won't find
anywhere in Japanese hospitals. But to confuse matters more, a
string of nines is a good thing, and on Thursday, a group of 99
Japanese tourists are celebrating the day by arriving here on a
package tour that costs 99,999 yen, about $909.
</P>
<P>
   To the Chinese, nine is the ultimate number, a masculine figure
and metaphor for the emperor. It is also triple the number three,
which is the No. 1 number in Chinese culture. Traditional
architecture frequently includes a parade of nine columns, nine
courtyards and nine bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Zuchowski, a Wiccan priest who practices numerology at
Enchantments, a purveyor of pagan goods on, yes, Ninth Street in
Manhattan, explains that every number has negative and positive
aspects. In general, though, nine tends toward altruism, unlike
one, which can be egotistical and unyielding.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a good day to go forward, to start something
new,'' he said. But even if your stars are well aligned on
Thursday, he had this advice for anyone with an urge for wanton
investing: ``Consult a good broker.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathematicians don't get very excited about nine. Sure, it is
the final single digit, and who can forget its starring role in
``casting out nines,'' that trick for checking multiplication. But
Anthony V. Phillips, chairman of the mathematics department at the
State University of New York at Stony Brook, struggled to find some
greater meaning. ``I guess there is something cute about nine,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Jacob Hill, the third-generation owner of Nine
Ninety Nine Kosher Provisions on Manhattan's Lower East Side. Hill
was born on May 9, and the birth dates of his three children all
end in nine. ``I guess we have a thing for nine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It started with Hill's grandfather, Elja, who in the 1930s asked
the Department of Agriculture if he could be the nation's 999th
licensed meat processor. ``In those days, the USDA was very nice
and they cooperated with him,'' Hill said. ``He could have been the
1,000th, but for some reason he wanted 999.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Moses Tendler, a professor of Talmudic law at Yeshiva
University, explains that although omens and portents have no place
in Jewish theology, many Jews subscribe to gematria, a
numerological tradition that assigns a number to every letter of
the Hebrew alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, the ninth letter, tet, is the first letter for
the word tov, or good. Many religious Jews consider 18 the finest
of all numbers, and charitable donations are often given in sums of
18, which is the numerical equivalent of chai, or life. Not to
mention nine plus nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, Jews are not permitted to involve themselves in
such nonsense,'' he said dryly.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the world, the sequence of numbers is purely
arbitrary. Hamid Dabashi, a professor of Iranian studies at
Columbia University, pointed out that most of the Asian and Islamic
worlds do not use the Gregorian calendar. ``There are 20 different
kinds of calendars being used today in the world,'' he said. ``So
for them, this hoopla over nines is another form of cultural
imperialism.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, some people can't help themselves. Leo Icarangal and
Catherine Banting are getting married this afternoon in Queens.
``We got a lot of grief from people because it's a Thursday, but I
think everyone is enjoying the theme of nine,'' said Icarangal, 29,
a computer specialist.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the gimmick, he said, a silver nine will be stuck
beneath a chair at every table. ``You know how at weddings, whoever
has the most chutzpah takes home the flower arrangement?'' he
asked. ``Well, at our wedding, the person sitting on the nine gets
the centerpiece.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lest the optimists rule the day, some astrologers say that Satan
may use the day's batch of upturned sixes to make trouble. Tom
Chase, a New Age writer and theorist, said today could be a tease
of more seriously apocalyptic events forecast for early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might have some small power glitches, some Chernobyls
going off in Russia, but it shouldn't be too bad,'' said Chase, who
stockpiled flashlights, food and water just in case.
</P>
<P>
   But other evidence suggests that the number nine is largely
benign. A well-tailored person dresses to the nines, cloud nine is
evidently a good place to be, and a stitch in time saves nine. So
at the risk of provoking Satan's ire (and the reader's patience),
it seems appropriate to end this treatise at word 999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
