<SLUG> BC-BLOCK-TAKEOVER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAREHOLDERS QUESTION BLOCK'S PLANNED PURCHASE OF OLDE FINANCIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Shareholders' questions about H&AMP;R Block
Inc.'s planned takeover of the nation's fourth-largest discount
brokerage chain dominated the Kansas City firm's annual meeting
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for Block shares fell 18 percent in two days last week on
the New York Stock Exchange after the Kansas City firm announced
plans to buy Olde Financial Corp. for $850 million.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Bloch, Block's chairman and co-founder, and Frank L.
Salizzoni, the company's chief executive, described the acquisition
as key to Block's plans to provide a wider range of year-round
financial services to middle America.
</P>
<P>
   Block's traditional tax preparation services, which last year
handled a record 18 percent of the federal and state income tax
returns Americans filed, fills only part of what Bloch described as
a large void in service to millions of mainstream Americans and
small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a company and as shareholders, I believe we can take a
measure of pride in our increasing ability to serve as a trusted
adviser _ to help families build equity in their homes, save for
their children's education and create a more secure retirement,''
Bloch said.
</P>
<P>
   Salizzoni told shareholders that acquiring privately held Olde
Financial would significantly accelerate Block's efforts to expand
its network and offer a wider range of financial products and
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``And more importantly to our shareholders, we expect the Olde
acquisition to contribute to earnings immediately,'' Salizzoni
said.
</P>
<P>
   One major shareholder, Howard Berghoef of Harris &AMP; Associates LP
in Chicago, seemed unconvinced, however. Harris is a mutual fund
company that owns about 9 percent of Block's shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market took $1 billion off your capitalization two days
after you spent $850 million,'' said Berghoef, referring to the
steep drop in the aggregate value of Block shares last week.
</P>
<P>
   Berghoef said he thought Block could use the money it is
spending on Olde Financial more constructively by buying back Block
shares to increase their value.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a terrific company, probably worth close to 75
(dollars a share), not 46 (where it currently is trading),''
Berghoef told Salizzoni.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why spend $850 million for a brokerage company you know very
little about?'' Berghoef said.
</P>
<P>
   Salizzoni said Block's shares had hit similar air pockets before
and recovered _ most noticeably when troubles at the company's
former CompuServe Corp. subsidiary cut Block prices by almost half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy is in place,'' Salizzoni said. ``We believe it
will succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Block closed Wednesday at 45 15//16, down 7//16.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, Block also announced the appointment of Mark A.
Ernst as president, succeeding Salizzoni.
</P>
<P>
   Salizzoni, who originally planned to serve temporarily as
Block's president when he took the job in 1996, will remain as
chief executive. However, Ernst, 41, now appears to be Salizzoni's
most logical successor to that job. Salizzoni is a retired airline
president and longtime Block director.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders also overwhelmingly approved two proposals to
increase the number of Block shares that can be used as performance
incentives for seasonal employees and for company executives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
