<HEADLINE>
KRAJICEK'S BIG SERVE NOT ENOUGH AGAINST KAFELNIKOV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLUSHING MEADOWS, N.Y. _ Richard Krajicek, a darkhorse as the
No. 12 seed, showed why he was included on Yevgeny Kafelnikov's
short list of men who could win the U.S. Open. He unleashed 48 aces
in his quarterfinals match Wednesday night, a record for a tennis
tournament of any time.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek, however, did not win. He was beaten by another man on
Kafelnikov's list. Namely, Kafelnikov himself.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 3 seed survived the barrage of aces to prevail, 7-6
(7-0), 7-6 (7-4), 3-6, 1-6, 7-6 (7-5).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the best matches I've played in my career,''
Kafelnikov said. ``And one of those days I was fortunate enough to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov moved into the semifinals against the winner of the
late match between Andre Agassi _ the third man on the list _ and
Nicolas Escude, and kept alive his goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do it because I want to be No. 1 at the end of the
year,'' Kafelnikov said. ``It's a simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   With top-ranked Pete Sampras out for the tournament and
sidelined at least a month because of a back injury, winning the
Open would make it happen. It can only happen, though, because he
repelled Krajicek's charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing good tennis,'' Krajicek said. ``I was serving
big.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed he was. The 48 aces were a record for a Grand Slam or ATP
Tour-level event, two more than the previous mark set by Goran
Ivanisevic against Magnus Norman in the second round at Wimbledon
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Ivanisevic lost that match, and so did Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   The difference was Kafelnikov's play in the tiebreakers. He
dominated the first one, winning all seven points, and controlled
the second one to take a commanding lead.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek rallied, though, breaking Kafelnikov twice in the third
and fourth set while holding his without much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starting to feel a little bit tired,'' Kafelnikov said.
``That's why the next two sets went pretty easy. When I was fresh I
was able to read his serve perfectly. Then he started to play
unbelievably. He was serving 130 miles per hour, 135 after 21/2
hours of playing.''
</P>
<P>
   As the match headed for the fifth set Kafelnikov knew he had
just one chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like there wasn't going to be many opportunities to
break Richard's serve,'' he said. ``I was hoping I could hold on
until the tiebreaker and take my chances there.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players held serve six times to force the tiebreaker. Once
there, Krajicek's potent serves let him down. He missed a couple of
first serves and Kafelnikov, whose service return rivals Agassi's
for the best in the game, hit a couple of returns for winners.
</P>
<P>
   He took a 6-2 lead then, after Krajicek saved three match
points, ironically won it with an ace, his 10th of the match.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek had the record, but Kafelnikov moved on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather hit as many as he hit and be in the semis,''
Krajicek said.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov is glad to be there, and hoping to play Agassi, the
other man with a chance to finish the year No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are going to go crazy,'' Kafelnikov said. ``Having
the No. 2 and No. 3 seeds in the semifinal, it's going to be
wonderful because the match is going to be important for both of
us.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
