<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: KEY JUDGE QUITS WAR PANEL
</P>
<P>
   One of the most senior judges of the Yugoslav war crimes
tribunal, Antonio Cassese, will resign in February, the third key
figure to quit the United Nations court in recent months. Cassese,
an Italian, who has served on the court since its creation in 1993,
said he would go back to being a law professor at Florence
University, nearly two years before the end of his term. Gabrielle
Kirk McDonald, the tribunal president, will leave in November and
Louise Arbour, the chief prosecutor, steps down Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: QUAKE DEATH TOLL
</P>
<P>
   The death toll in last month's earthquake has reached 15,303,
and 23,954 were injured, the government announced. Newspapers have
reported that 30,000 or more people are still missing. About
250,000 survivors are homeless.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: SPOOFING SCHREODER
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder has appeared on German television
as a kinky hermaphrodite complete with pierced breasts, a dog
collar and a loony grin _ and he is not pleased. The Munich-based
RTL-2 network faces possible legal action from Schroeder after
airing an ``interview'' with a leather-clad Schroeder lookalike
puppet on an erotic show called ``Peep.'' Schroeder said the show,
about his sexual preferences, was ``worse than overstepping the
boundaries of taste.''
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: HISTORIC PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Parliament held its first session in the renovated Reichstag in
Berlin, and weathered its first protest. Doctors built a wall of
ice 20 feet long by 10 feet high outside the building to protest
government health care changes, which they say could usher in a new
ice age for the health service, threatening 19,000 jobs this year.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: IMAGE MAKEOVER
</P>
<P>
   The government wants to make a major effort to improve
Switzerland's image abroad, especially in the United States. The
Foreign Ministry is asking lawmakers to approve a $31 million
program to promote the country's humanitarian work, its cultural
diversity and democratic traditions. ``Switzerland's image abroad
has suffered quite a bit recently,'' said Foreign Minister Joseph
Deiss.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: MILOSEVIC MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Two months after Switzerland agreed to freeze any assets
belonging to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, the government
said no firm evidence of any Swiss bank accounts had turned up.
Acting on a request from the International War Crimes Tribunal in
The Hague, Swiss authorities had promised to block bank accounts or
other assets belonging to Milosevic, four Serbian leaders indicted
for war crimes and 300 other senior Yugoslav officials.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: PINOCHET INVITED TO COURT
</P>
<P>
   Judge Baltasar Garzon, who is seeking the extradition from
Britain of Gen. Augusto Pinochet to answer charges of human rights
abuses, has given the former Chilean dictator until Sept. 27 to
voluntarily appear in Madrid court. The move comes in response to a
motion by Pinochet, who is under house arrest outside London, to
defend himself in Spain _ and gain access to court papers _ while
fighting extradition in Britain, where the next hearing is set for
Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: SUIT OVER BANK PAPERS
</P>
<P>
   Overriding President Ernesto Zedillo's political party, the
opposition in Congress voted to sue in the Supreme Court to force
the government to turn over bank documents from his 1994
presidential campaign. Investigators are looking into whether
Zedillo received illegal donations from Carlos Cabal Peniche, a
banker embroiled in fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: EXILE MAY BE MOVED
</P>
<P>
   The government said it is considering moving Gen. Lino Oviedo,
the former Parguayan army chief who fled his country and lives
outside Buenos Aires as a political exile, to a ranch on an
isolated pampas in central Argentina. The move is in response to
growing tensions with Paraguay, which has twice called for Oviedo's
extradition to face charges he was involved in the assassination of
Vice President Luis Maria Argana last March.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: QUEEN'S NEW REPRESENTATIVE
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jean Chretien named Adrienne Clarkson, a former
television journalist, as the country's new governor-general, the
representative Queen Elizabeth in Canada. Ms. Clarkson, who was
evacuated from Hong Kong as a child during World War II, is the
first immigrant to hold Canada's top ceremonial post.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: SEARCH FOR TRUDEAU SON
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Mounted Police divers started searching a high-altitude
British Columbia lake where Michel Trudeau, a son of former
Canadian Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau, drowned Nov. 23. The
23-year-old was traversing a steep snow slope on skis when an
avalanche swept him and a friend into the waters of Lake Kokanee.
The friend managed to get out, but Michel was last seen struggling
in the water. Two days after he disappeared, ice sealed the lake.
The ice melted only two weeks ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
