<HEADLINE>
NO EASY WAY TO DEAL WITH OFFICE JERKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Whenever, wherever workplace training sessions are
held, one of the biggest draws is a seminar called ``How to Deal
with Difficult People.''
</P>
<P>
   Front-line workers and top management alike crowd the room,
desperate for quick fixes to their daily vexes. Most leave
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't with the trainer. And there usually is nothing
wrong with the audio or visuals. The problem is the message, which
always is the same:
</P>
<P>
   (ital)You can't change the other person. You can only change
your response to that person.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Dandy. Just dandy.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost see the little thought balloons wafting above
participants' heads. Wait a minute here. (ital)I'm(end ital) not
the problem. (ital)He's(end ital) the complainer. (ital)She's(end
ital) the conniver. I need to know how to deal with (ital)them(end
ital).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the attendees dare to say as much out loud. They argue
that it's in their co-worker's self-centered, obnoxious nature to
argue; if they could just get the arguer to stop arguing, work
would be Eden.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the trainers, nodding sympathetically at the speaker,
try to stuff their own thought balloons back in their heads before
everyone can read them. (ital)Look in the mirror, buddy(end ital),
you just know they're thinking.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's harsh. Credit is due the workers who go to these
seminars. At least they're looking for cures while the boors and
bemoaners are ulcerating the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there is no finger-snap solution to interpersonal
relationship or communication problems. There's only conflict
management and self-control.
</P>
<P>
   When somebody at work acts like a jerk, instinct says we'll
react in one of three ways: We'll lash back, give in or flee. If
any of these instincts is acted out without thinking it through
first, the consequence is escalation of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, everyone grows up emotionally, too. But the
work world is populated with folk who lug all kinds of familial and
psychological baggage. In the vernacular, (ital)I don't know where
you're coming from, man.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The best, if not the only, way to deal with co-workers who seem
difficult is to act like a VCR: Pause, rewind, replay.
</P>
<P>
   The trainers' advice: State _ calmly _ what you think the
``difficult person'' said or did. Ask if your perception was his or
her intent. Don't yell, swear, argue, belittle or say, ``Yes,
but...''
</P>
<P>
   Ask for his or her suggestions or solutions. In the words of one
trainer, ``flatter their emotional child.''
</P>
<P>
   First, though, we have to manage our own childlike reactions. We
have to control the (ital)Oh, yeah?(end ital) and the
(ital)nyah-nyah(end ital) responses.
</P>
<P>
   We have to slow down, listen and ask questions. Sometimes,
trainers say, it requires playing dumb like a fox: ``I'm not sure I
understand what's bothering you,'' or ``Did you mean to insult
me?''
</P>
<P>
   And _ this is the hardest of all _ we need to avoid assuming we
know it all and they don't know grits from granola. We can't assume
we're interpreting them correctly. It's a good bet their emotional
child has taken over, and everyone needs a time out before mature
discussion can occur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
