<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT OVERCOMES PIERCE, FACES SERENA WILLIAMS IN SEMIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLUSHING MEADOWS, N.Y. _ The difference between Lindsay
Davenport and Mary Pierce is inches and miles: inches in physical
talent, and miles in temperament.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce almost pulled off one of the biggest surprises of the
U.S. Open on Wednesday, missing a line by inches on match point
against the defending champion and second seed. Instead, Davenport
moved on when Pierce double-faulted with a second serve that was a
long.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport prevailed, 6-2, 3-6, 7-5, at Arthur Ashe Stadium to
move into the semifinals, where she will meet Serena Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Williams advanced to the final four of a Grand Slam event for
the first time in her career with a 4-6, 6-3, 6-2 winner over
Monica Seles, and kept alive father Richard Williams' prediction of
a final between Serena and sister Venus, who plays Martina Hingis
in the other semifinal Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always a goal, and it's really coming true,'' Serena
Williams said. ``I'm very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams looked like she might be in trouble after losing the
first set but cruised in the final two in stark contrast to
Davenport, who won the first set and then struggled late.
</P>
<P>
   ``To pull it out like this is really exciting,'' Davenport said.
``I'm getting closer to defending. A little stumble today, but I
got through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport didn't stumble at all in her first four matches,
dropping just 10 games. Match No. 5 looked like it would be just as
routine when she broke Pierce twice to win the first set in 28
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Then Pierce began playing some of the best tennis of her career,
smacking winners and forcing Davenport into mistakes. Pierce won
the second set, then broke in the seventh game of the third set to
close in on the upset.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce always has had the talent to beat the best players in the
world. Her serves are hard to handle and her groundstrokes are as
powerful as anyone's on tour.
</P>
<P>
   That talent translated to a 1995 Australian Open championship,
and runner-up finishes at the 1994 French and '97 Australian Opens.
It's also made her a fixture in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't, however, translated to much success against the best
players in the world. Before Wednesday she was a combined 8-22
against Hingis, Davenport, Venus Williams and Seles.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the talent came a reputation for tightening up in big
games, on big points.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce came within inches of shedding that reputation when, on
match point, she ripped a cross-court backhand.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce thought it was on the line, and raised a fist in triumph.
The linesperson thought otherwise, and called it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good,'' Pierce said. ``But it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't because Pierce hit it too hard and too close to the
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little bit nervous and a little tight,'' she said. ``I
went for that shot, which I really didn't need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport went on to break when Pierce plunked a forehand into
the net, and then play was suspended because of a light rain.
Pierce had a little more than an hour to think about what might
have been.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport held when play resumed, and broke to win the match
when Pierce hit that second serve well over the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in that position before,'' Pierce said. ``You just
sometimes want it so bad, you put a little bit extra pressure on
yourself instead of just playing the points like any other point.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport also admitted to being nervous, but she's learned to
deal with it. That's why she won the Open last year and Wimbledon
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so much better about playing tight matches now than I
did two or three years ago,'' Davenport said. ``You hit the ball
hard, but don't aim for the lines. You don't go for a winner
return, but go deep and down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   She did that against Pierce, and moved into the semifinals.
Pierce missed by inches, and remains miles away. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
