<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENARD METHODICALLY EXPANDING EMPIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Menard doesn't go to the races brandishing a
spit-and-polish nickname, like Roger Penske's ``The Captain.''
</P>
<P>
   Menard doesn't cart around 67 Indy-car victories, like legendary
Texan A.J. Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike fellow race car-owners Paul Newman and David Letterman,
Menard is neither an actor nor a comedian.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want to contend for an oval-track Indy-car
championship _ not to mention replace a leaky shower head or
rebuild a deck _ John Menard probably is your best friend.
</P>
<P>
   Menard unquestionably is the lowest profile high-roller in
Indy-car racing, only because that's how he wants it. Pep Boys Indy
Racing League points-leader Greg Ray knew that much about Menard
last summer, when the Texan and crew chief/engineer Thomas Knapp
launched a campaign that eventually saw them replace Tony Stewart
and Larry Curry at Team Menard.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, the IRL's original poster boy, and sidekick Curry
helped deliver the 1996-97 IRL driver and entrant championships to
Menard, a self-made millionaire, courtesy of a chain of lumber/home
improvement stores based in Eau Claire, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep expanding all the time,'' said Menard, whose business
empire consists of 144 stores in a nine-state area of the upper
Midwest. ``We're on a very methodical expansion plan. We'll
probably expand like a paint spill. We have to be very cautious in
our expansion, but we'll probably be national one day.''
</P>
<P>
   While the employees at Menard's continue to fight the battle on
the home front, his latest IRL team is closing in on a second
championship. Ray, of Plano, has won three of the past four races
to forge a 44-point lead over Scott Goodyear with events at Las
Vegas Motor Speedway and Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth
remaining. Ray's most recent victory, in the Colorado 200 at Pikes
Peak International Raceway on Aug. 29, was a league-record seventh
for Team Menard.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say we're leading the championship and won three of the
last four races, it's almost like you're talking about somebody
else,'' said Ray, who began his stint at Team Menard inauspiciously
with three consecutive 21st-place finishes. ``John has put together
a great team. Team Menard has a great heritage. A lot of people
questioned just how competitive and `together' we would be early
on. I already had high expectations as a driver. To have such a
strong team around me has made things really pleasant.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray and Knapp, of course, spent 1997 and 1998 as a single-car
team that ran as long and hard as its cubic dollars allowed. Elite
Team Menard stood at the opposite end of the IRL spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a place I wanted to be from Day One,'' said Ray, a
perfectionist who began talking with fellow-perfectionist Menard
after the 1998 Indianapolis 500. They eventually entered into a
``long-term'' contract last fall. While the 1999 IRL championship
remains the immediate target, Menard acknowledged there are other
opportunities to explore. The rival Championship Auto Racing Teams
FedEx Series and even NASCAR Winston Cup might be future good fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm partners in a CART team, and I wish that team was doing as
well as my IRL team,'' Menard said of his venture with driver Robby
Gordon. Menard also has announced plans to enter the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series with driver Bryan Refner next year, as a
prelude to running Winston Cup. Perhaps with Ray behind the wheel?
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg and I want to be competitive in anything we do,'' Menard
said. ``The thought of us going down to a Winston Cup race and not
doing well isn't very appealing to me and Greg. We're going to have
to weigh everything we do very carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this will be a methodical expansion. Like a
paint spill.
SPOTLIGHT ON... Goodyear's IRL teams seek blistering cure The short
history of the Pep Boys Indy Racing League at Texas Motor Speedway
has been notable for blistering speeds and, sometimes, blistering
tires.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers with the Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co. are attempting to
correct the latter problem for its clients before the season-ending
Lone Star 500 on Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Blistering conditions during the IRL events here last September
and in June prompted another round of tire tests at the 1.5-mile
quad-oval yesterday and today. Scott Goodyear won the Longhorn 500
night race in Fort Worth on June 12, but a number of championship
contenders were unable to run flat-out.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Foyt Racing teammates Kenny Brack and Billy Boat were
forced to pit less than 20 laps into the June race because of
blistering right rear tires. The same fate also sidetracked Scott
Sharp and pole-sitter Mark Dismore of Kelley Racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last race here, we had a good tire, but I think it was too
soft,'' said Boat, winner of the IRL night event here in June 1998.
``They've \RGoodyear\S brought us a tougher compound. What we're
trying to do is two things _ first, make sure that it's durable,
and we've gone a little conservative so we don't have any problems
with the tire. And then we'll start to work back and try to regain
some grip and build speed back into the tire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary objective is to make sure we have a tire we're not
going to have any problems with.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp said his strategy was rendered useless by the blistering
he encountered in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't race,'' Sharp said. ``We were conservatively
leading the race, running 213s and 212s, came in for a pit stop 26
or 27 laps into the race and realized the car had blistered tires.
We went back out on a new set of tires and blistered them in about
15 laps. At that point, we ran a conservative pace, 205 or 206 the
rest of the race, because we didn't want to take any chances of
putting it into the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack, who won the 1998 IRL championship on Goodyear Racing
Eagles, noted that the tire manufacturer has made a ``positive
gain'' during the past two races at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   ``September last year, the tires blew up on us,'' Brack said,
``and now they're only blistered. So, they're going in the right
direction. But for sure, we cannot afford to have a race like that
again here.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS New car blues NASCAR Winston Cup team-owner Felix
Sabates recently told ``National Speed Sport News'' that a
wind-tunnel test of the 2000 model Chevrolet Monte Carlo indicated
it was a piece of junk. Or words to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, crew chief Ryan Pemberton said the new Ford Taurus 2k
is ``a truly good car,'' but not without its flaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem we have with it is it has a little more
drag than we need,'' said Pemberton, crew chief for the No. 2
Miller Lite Fords driven by Rusty Wallace. ``On speedways like
Daytona and Talladega, that's the biggest problem we've got.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ford is a little bit behind on the introduction of the car _
probably two months behind for sure. We'll start working on it hot
and heavy when we get pieces and parts from NASCAR.'' Montoya the
`rainmeister' Rookie Juan Montoya bagged a maximum of 22 points at
rainy Vancouver, B.C., last weekend to widen his lead in the
Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Series. Montoya, driver of the
No. 4 Target Honda-Reynard, will carry a 23-point advantage over
Dario Franchitti into Round 17 at beautiful and challenging Laguna
Seca (Calif.) Raceway this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya's three victories from the pole are the most since Alex
Zanardi _ the driver he replaced at Target Chip Ganassi Racing _
also won three times from the pole in his rookie season in 1996. A
memorable move As reported last week, the NHRA has moved the
Castrol Nationals at the Texas Motorplex in Ennis to Memorial Day
weekend (May 25-28) beginning next season.
</P>
<P>
   Motorplex owner Billy Meyer wants to make the move permanent,
and allow the NHRA to showcase its product on the already busy
weekend featuring the Indy Racing League's Indianapolis 500 and
NASCAR's Coca-Cola 600.
</P>
<P>
   The NHRA's 2000 schedule will grow from 22 to 23 national events
with the inaugural Las Vegas Nationals at Bruton Smith's Las Vegas
Motor Speedway. Both the Motorplex and Houston Raceway Park in
Baytown again will play host to two events for the fourth
consecutive year. But there will be a three-race gap between the
O'Reilly Nationals at HRP on April 13-16 and the repositioned
Castrol Nationals at Ennis in May. Last laps NASCAR Winston Cup
points-leader Dale Jarrett will carry a 168-point lead over Mark
Martin into Richmond, Va., on Saturday night _ a loss of 146 points
during the past two races.
</P>
<P>
   Indy 500 veteran Willy T. Ribbs was among several IRL drivers
testing at Las Vegas Motor Speedway last week. Ribbs, the only
African-American to qualify for the Indy 500, drove 20 laps for PDM
Racing but did not attempt to begin his IRL rookie test.
</P>
<P>
   Former NHRA Top Fuel champion Kenny Bernstein failed to qualify
for the most prestigious race of the season, the U.S. Nationals, at
Indianapolis Raceway Park last weekend. It was the first DNQ for
Bernstein's Budweiser King Dragster since February 1998 at Firebird
International Raceway in Phoenix. And it marked the first time
Bernstein did not compete in the U.S. Nationals since 1980.
\Nsubheds:Bliss job hunting Mike Bliss, a veteran in the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series, is a candidate for the No. 30 Jimmy Dean
Pontiac Grand Prix formerly driven by Derrike Cope.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss has discussed the job with crew chief and friend Barry
Dodson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say a whole lot,'' said Bliss, driver of the No. 99
Exide Batteries Ford fielded by Jack Roush. ``I don't know exactly
what I'm doing next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss scored his first victory of the season, and seventh of his
five-year truck series career, on the road course at Heartland Park
Topeka, Kan., on Aug. 28. Last words ``There are times I get sick
of being politically correct. I got into Winston Cup because I
wanted to be a race car driver. If I wanted to be a politician, I
would be in Washington.'' _ Tony Stewart, NASCAR Winston Cup rookie
star
