<HEADLINE>
HEARING-IMPAIRED LINEMAN'S MESSAGE COMES THROUGH LOUD AND CLEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ The ominous nightmare of the man holding a gun
in his face came often to the young boy in those days. Sometimes
reality was even more terrifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about it,'' urged Eric Thunander, now a freshman
linebacker at Oklahoma who has already worked his way onto the
two-deep chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're 7 years old and your second father gets mad at you
because you didn't hear him _ because I don't hear a lot of things
all the time _ and he tries to get your attention by sticking a gun
into your face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always thinking, `What happens if that gun goes off?' I
wouldn't be here if it had. So I live every day to its fullest.''
</P>
<P>
   Life may yet throw curves at Eric Thunander. But the guess is
that he will meet them straight on. Obstacles are nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   Thunander emerged on the other side of the physical and
emotional abuse inflicted by two of his mother's three husbands to
become an outstanding athlete and a member of his high school's
National Honor Society. He also has overcome a congenital birth
defect that left him with less than 17 percent hearing _ in his
good ear _ to become a counselor and role model for other
hearing-impaired and emotionally disturbed youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see kids who come from normal families who complain about
how hard it is in life,'' Thunander said. ``Their lives have never
even come close to mine because my life has never even come close
to being normal. I would do anything to turn back time and wish I
had had a normal life and not to have had to live through all the
hardships growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I grew up too long in fear. Now, I don't fear anything.
There's nothing else for me to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months after he moved to Norman this summer from
his hometown of Lee's Summit, Mo., and before he reported for
Sooners football practice in August, Thunander already had visited
the nearby Oklahoma School for the Deaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted those kids to know that they can do anything they
want to do because I've made it,'' said Thunander, whose speech,
though paced, is surprisingly crisp for one who was
hearing-impaired at birth. ``And I want to be the proof _ because
sometimes you have to see it to believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may not help everybody. But I want to give the drive and
determination to believe they can do whatever they put their mind
to to at least one person. And I've told our coaches that whenever
there is a community service thing that involves kids, I want to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Thunander's visit to the school didn't surprise
Tony Willis, a former speech pathologist and special education
teacher in language arts with the Lee's Summit school district who
first began working with Eric when he was a moody, underachieving
student in the sixth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric has probably moved further than any student I have ever
worked with,'' Willis said. ``I will say I'm a little nervous about
this college experience. But I believe it is going to be very good
for him. I just hope he continues to use all the skills he has,
because he's very capable, a very intelligent young man. Sometimes
I forget Eric is deaf because he is so articulate.'' \Nsubheds:No
limits to potential Thunander represents more than just a nice
story on the perimeter of the Sooners football program. Though his
character and determination were factors, OU recruited the
6-foot-2, 225-pound linebacker because he was a player. Thunander,
who also ran on his high school's 1,600-meter relay team that set a
state record, has a slot on all the OU special teams and is listed
No. 2 at outside linebacker for OU's opener Saturday against
Indiana State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the talent to be an All-American before it's all said
and done,'' said co-defensive coordinator Brent Venables, who left
a job at Kansas State to join new OU coach Bob Stoops' staff. ``And
I say that having worked with two All-Americans (Jeff Kelly, Mark
Simoneau) the last couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   On the field, Thunander does not wear his twin hearing aids. He
communicates by reading lips or through hand signals. Members of
the secondary will occasionally move him one way or the other if he
doesn't immediately pick up an adjustment after the offense has
broken the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't notice the limitation of his hearing at all,''
Stoops said. ``Eric is extremely bright learning what he's supposed
to be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing his hearing aids, Thunander sits in the middle of his
classrooms. Though he can't hear high-pitched sounds very clearly,
he likes music. Metallica is his favorite group.
</P>
<P>
   Venables said he believes Thunander has a bright future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy athletically is the real deal,'' Venables said.
``He's one of the top guys I have. He'll be a great player because
of how driven he is. You might find someone who is as driven as
this guy, but you won't find anyone who is more driven.''
</P>
<P>
   Venables and others marvel at Thunander's work ethic. He moved
to Norman on June 18 and paid for his own living expenses. He got a
job at a local bank. After hours, he worked out with his new
teammates, then went home armed with videotape.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already earned the respect of his teammates,'' Venables
said. ``Whatever's in the dictionary under role model, Eric's
picture is probably right next to it. And I say that very
sincerely.''
</P>
<P>
   Long days are nothing new. While in high school, after either
football or track practice, Thunander worked at a grocery store _
frequently until midnight or later _ to help buy food and pay
family bills. Then, he studied and caught a few hours sleep before
starting over again.
</P>
<P>
   Athletics became a release, an escape. At first, however,
football was more a way to strike back at life's hand than
something he did for the pure enjoyment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was younger, I'd take my aggressions out on the
football field,'' Thunander said. ``That was my way of (hitting
back) for a while, until about my junior year, when I started
playing for fun.'' \Nsubheds:Finding refuge Thunander finally broke
away from his family when he was a sophomore in high school. He
first lived with his head football coach, then in a foster home
during his junior and senior years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a point where I wanted to get control over my own
life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was always depressed. I took a lot of abuse from my
mother's second husband. He was a drug dealer and a gun dealer. I
thought that stuff was normal _ because I was always around it _
but now I know it's wrong. I also know it's wrong to beat a kid,
because I've taken a lot of beatings.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric said he never hit back because he was afraid he'd be kicked
out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother's third husband wasn't as bad,'' he said. ``He would
hit me occasionally for something I did. Most families would just
send their kids to their room.''
</P>
<P>
   Thunander found the support and the positive male role models in
three people _ Willis, high school football coach Mike Spiegel and
in Dick Mathews, his girlfriend's father. Thunander is still in
contact with all three.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to me growing up was having these people who cared,''
he said. ``There were times when I needed help, and they were there
for me. My mother hardly ever was.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never showed up for the football games. She never came to
any of my track meets. I won all these awards. I was inducted into
the National Honor Society and she wasn't there. It used to hurt a
lot. But these other people started being there, and that was the
greatest feeling in the world _ just to have someone there for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The transition to a world of kindness didn't always come easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My coach helped me so much,'' Thunander said. ``But one time
when was I (living with Spiegel's family), I did something wrong
and he was coming at me to talk to me (face to face so Eric could
read his lips). I put my hands up because I thought he was going to
hit me. Because that's what I was used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathews hired Eric to work at his electrical contracting firm
after the grocery offered him only a 15-cent-an-hour raise.
Thunander says their relationship is much like father and son, as
are the bonds between him and Willis and Spiegel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric is a great kid,'' Mathews said. ``He's come a million
miles from where he was when we first met him, but that's a
situation we don't look back at.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see the strides, the attitude change, the looking forward
to life and putting the past behind is tremendous to see. If over
the next four years he can accomplish what he has the past four
years _ getting over the steppingstones he's gotten over _ Eric
will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Thunander says he no longer communicates with his mother. But he
understands she has found help for her depression and that a
younger brother and sister have moved back in with her after
spending some time in a group home.
</P>
<P>
   Eric shares his troubled past with surprising candor. But he
says that finally being able to talk about his problems helped him
overcome them. He advises other youngsters who have suffered from
some kind of childhood abuse to do the same, however hard it might
be initially.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would advise them to talk to someone about it,'' Thunander
said. ``To never hide their feelings. You'll eat yourself up if you
hide it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like a lot of things (that happened) were my fault and
they never were. Because I was able to go to the people I've talked
about, it made me feel better about myself because they were
supportive and they wanted to help me in any way they could.''
</P>
<P>
   Thunander is determined to repay the favor in kind, and in
kindness. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
