<HEADLINE>
INJURIES LEAVE TEXAS TECH'S OFFENSE IN DISARRAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suddenly, the continued success of a Texas Tech football program
that has won at least six games per year for the past six seasons
swings precariously in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   That can be the only conclusion to draw from yesterday's medical
updates that foreshadow rough sledding ahead for the Red Raiders'
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Ricky Williams, the team's Heisman Trophy candidate, is
out for Saturday's game at Louisiana-Lafayette. A magnetic
resonance imaging test showed a severe sprain to the anterior
cruciate ligament in his left knee. Further tests have been ordered
for later this week, after the swelling subsides, to determine
when, or if, Williams can return.
</P>
<P>
   Williams already is listed as doubtful for Tech's Sept. 18 game
against North Texas, with a best-case scenario for his return
likely to be the team's Big 12 opener against Texas A&AMP;M on Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to see this happen for Ricky, and I hate it for our
team,'' Tech coach Spike Dykes said. ``This is a big blow to our
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   And the blows keep coming.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Sammy Morris, a standout blocker who doubles as the
team's best pass receiver, is doubtful for Saturday because of a
bone bruise in his right shoulder. Right guard Jason May (sprained
knee) won't play Saturday and right tackle Matt Heider (hamstring)
is doubtful. That's four offensive starters, all expected to be out
this week with tenuous timetables for their respective returns.
</P>
<P>
   The only good news on the Tech injury front is that none of the
three players who underwent MRIs after getting hurt in Monday's
31-13 loss to Arizona State _ Williams, Morris and May _ have been
scheduled for season-ending surgery. None have been ruled out for
longer than this week, although Tech officials concede they may be
looking at a long-term absence from Williams if additional tests
are not more encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, in turn, does not sound like someone who expects
immediate playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what happens, I'm still thankful for the chance to
come back,'' said Morris, a senior who missed the 1997 and 1998
seasons because of academic ineligibility. ``I hope to be back as
soon as I can. But my shoulder hurts real bad.''
</P>
<P>
   How much will the Raiders miss Williams, who rushed for 1,582
yards last season, and Morris, who has career averages of 7.4 yards
per carry and 18.1 yards per catch?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're about 85 or 90 percent of our offense,'' quarterback
Rob Peters said. ``We need to have those guys out there. They're
huge keys for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mix in the loss of two starting offensive linemen, said Peters,
and, ``That's going to make it tough on us. I hope those guys mend
and get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Until they do, the Tech ground game rests in the hands of
tailbacks Rickey Hunter, James Easterling and Shaud Williams. They
have combined for 472 rushing yards in Division I-A, with 336 of
that from Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Easterling, a Crowley High School graduate, was listed No. 1 on
yesterday's depth chart but coaches said all three will probably
play. Shaud Williams, an incoming freshmen, led Tech rushers
against Arizona State with five carries for 40 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need our No. 1 guys back, but it's not bleak behind them,''
Peters said. ``Shaud Williams can play at this level, no question.
I think we've got the people who can fill some holes.''
</P>
<P>
   For the short term, that may be true. But if the injuries to
Tech's starting running backs linger into October, look for the Red
Raiders' record to take a beating once they begin facing Big 12
teams on a weekly basis.
spotlight
Duane A. Laverty After seeing the success the walk-on program had
at Nebraska when he was an assistant, Kevin Steele hopes to do the
same at Baylor.
Baylor trying to build top walk-on program
Having cut his coaching teeth on the staff at Nebraska, where the
Cornhuskers traditionally have more walk-ons than scholarship
players suited for practices, Baylor coach Kevin Steele has sought
to emulate that model in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   He has aggressively spread the word that extra bodies are
welcome at practice, above the NCAA-mandated limit of 85
scholarship players. Steele said the response, thus far, has been
``beyond my expectations, considering this is a private school.''
</P>
<P>
   As allowed under NCAA rules, Steele welcomed 20 walk-ons during
two-a-days. When classes began in August, 32 more volunteers
arrived, giving the Bears 137 players for daily workouts.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest boost to building the Bears' walk-on efforts may
have come in last week's 30-29 loss to Boston College. The Bears'
first touchdown under Steele was scored by wide receiver Lanny
O'Steen, a former walk-on from Keller who was put on scholarship in
August. O'Steen, a redshirt freshman, recovered a fumble in the end
zone after teammate Melvin Barnett lost the handle near the Eagles'
goal line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to building a non-scholarship program is making sure
that, if one of those guys does contribute, you'd better give that
guy a scholarship,'' Steele said. ``With Lanny, we were already
lacking depth at wide receiver and we had two scholarships
available. When we sorted things out at the end of two-a-days, he
was still in the mix. We decided we'd have a hard time recruiting
another wide receiver to do as well as he was doing as a freshman
next year. So, he earned a scholarship. And that sent the message
that, if you're a walk-on and you play your way into the mix, we'll
reward you.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele said fullback Chris Crosby, a freshman from Bellevue,
Wash., has caught his eye since joining the squad after the start
of classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``From his first day of practice, he's been blocking folks
better than most guys we've got out there,'' Steele said.
QUICK HITS \Nsubheds:Gimme four Texas wide receiver Montrell
Flowers displayed what will become his signature touchdown salute _
a high four, rather than a high five _ after grabbing a 54-yard
scoring strike in last week's 69-17 rout of Stanford. For the
speedy sophomore from Dallas, four fingers held aloft in the end
zone represents a tribute to his grandfather, Robert Flowers, who
died on Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Before his death, Robert Flowers asked Montrell to flash four
digits after touchdowns as a show of solidarity between the player,
his maternal grandparents and his mother, who raised Montrell as a
single parent with help from her parents, Robert and Frances
Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a victory, that we bonded together,''
Flowers said of his end-zone salute. ``It symbolizes, `I made it.'
'' \Nsubheds:Late-arrving Raiders Suffering multiple injuries to
key players, not to mention a 31-13 loss to Arizona State, will not
cause Texas Tech coach Spike Dykes to adjust his longstanding
policy of traveling on game day _ when feasible _ for night games
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in five days, the Red Raiders' travel plans
include a morning flight on game day for Saturday's 7 p.m. contest
at Louisiana-Lafayette. After the contest, the team will fly back
to Lubbock in order to allow players to sleep in their own beds
that night.
</P>
<P>
   Dykes' theory is to minimize disruption in established routines
and to eliminate potential distractions involved with travel
logistics. The practice is unique, but there is no arguing with the
results. Tech is 7-1 when traveling on game days, with the lone
loss on Monday night to Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   Under Dykes, Tech has enjoyed triumphant, late-night return
flights from venues such as Texas (1997), Baylor (1997), Oklahoma
State (1989) and New Mexico (1995, 1990).
</P>
<P>
   But the longest game-day flight the team has taken was Monday
night to Arizona State, where players struggled to adapt in the
105-degree heat. Several players, including defensive end Devin
Lemons, had stomach troubles or suffered from dehydration during
the game. Tech prepares to embark on its second-longest, game-day
flight under Dykes, to hot, humid Louisiana, where the Raiders will
be without star tailback Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that \Rlate arrival in Arizona\S was any factor
in the outcome,'' Dykes said. ``I think we lack a little
conditioning and we probably played a few guys too long. Getting
there a day ahead of time wouldn't have made any difference. I like
what we're doing and it's been good for us.'' \Nsubheds:Early
believers Oklahoma has not enjoyed a winning season since 1993. The
Sooners will be playing for their fourth coach in six years when
they open Saturday night at home against Indiana State. Yet, the
team still received 14 votes this week in The Associated Press' Top
25 poll.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain the phenomenon, first-year coach Bob Stoops
said: ``I can't. It may be related to having a new coaching staff
in place. I don't know. Hopefully, by the end of the year, we can
live up to that and pick up some more votes. I'd like to be a team
that's in \Rthe Top 25\S at the end of the season.''
Burch's picks Staff writer Jimmy Burch picks (against the line)
this week's Big 12 football games:
</P>
