<HEADLINE>
STARS COACH HITCHCOCK SHEDS A PAINFUL LIFE WITH POUNDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ This was how Stars' coach Ken Hitchcock rewarded
himself for winning the Stanley Cup: Pain.
</P>
<P>
   Lots and lots of pain.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks after that fateful night of June 19 in
Buffalo, when the Stars brought the Cup home to Texas, Hitchcock
secretly checked himself into Baylor Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   He used an assumed name because this was a private battle, one
that needed no headlines, no film at 11, no nightly updates on
``Sports Center.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the surgery that was performed on July 2, wasn't
something Hitchcock even felt comfortable talking about publicly
because, for the most part, his war against obesity has been fought
behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   It is an intensely personal struggle, fought hand-to-mouth,
every day, every hour, every minute. You win a battle here, lose
one there, hoping to survive and fight another day.
</P>
<P>
   Always, the unforgiving, merciless scales are there to report
how the conflict is progressing.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock ``is'' winning the war. Since topping out at almost
500 pounds five years ago, he has lost more than 200 pounds. That's
what necessitated the first surgical procedure he has ever
undergone just under 10 weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a complicated 91/2 hour operation, doctors made two separate
incisions, each completely encircling Hitchcock's abdomen, and
removed 30 pounds of dead skin and tissue. They also discovered and
repaired a hernia no one knew was even there.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's attitude was positive: He approached the surgery and
the six weeks of pain-filled recovery that followed as a reward,
not so much for winning the Cup, but for the major progress he has
made over the past five years. From almost eating himself to death,
he has become husband, father and one of the premier coaches in the
NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd made a lifestyle change and I really felt like I'd earned
the right to have this take place,'' said Hitchcock, 47. ``I'd
reached a plateau physically and I needed to take the next step.
This was the next natural step. It was something that had to be
done, physically.''
</P>
<P>
   He sat at an outdoor cafe, enjoying the cool mountain air just
before dark the second day into camp, wearing a gray sweatshirt and
loose-fitting athletic shorts. He'd just finished a long walk, his
second of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Each morning here at 5:30 he joins half a dozen other Stars
coaches and front-office officials for a 25-minute walk to a local
fitness center. They work out for an hour, walk back and, after
showers, reconvene for breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you'd have had to be where Hitchcock was 200 pounds ago to
understand just how good it makes him feel to be able to do this
and so many other things he didn't think he'd ever do again in his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little things that you think about at the end of the day,''
Hitchcock said, ``and you say to yourself, `Jeez, I did this
today.' When you're a confident individual, you seem to make a lot
of right decisions at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even for Hitchcock, never at a loss for words, it is difficult
explaining how much better he feels, both physically and
emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some scary times afterward for me,'' Hitchcock
admitted. ``It was a hard fight, because you're dealing with
discomfort every minute, every second of every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a process of going through it. It's something I feel I
could do again. I feel mentally stronger. I feel like, `Man, I went
through a lot.' I can deal with a lot now.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing the dead weight has given Hitchcock the energy to
increase his workouts and he's started to lose pounds again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this burning desire to be a healthy person,'' he said.
``I don't eat carelessly (he ordered a turkey-vegetable wrap for
dinner that night). I have my cravings, like anybody else, but I've
learned how to live, I've learned to change my eating habits, I
train and work out. From a physical and overall health perspective,
this was really important.''
</P>
<P>
   More important even, than winning a Stanley Cup. For Hitchcock,
it was never about the hardware anyway. It was always about the
quest to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take anything away from what we accomplished,
because it's a great accomplishment, but my thrill comes from
watching people come together,'' he said. ``I've got rings and
trophies and I don't know what drawer they're in. They're not
hanging on walls. That's not who I am. I love watching, developing
and helping people come together. It doesn't matter what level,
that's the fuel. If your team is bareass naked _ no politics, no
hidden agendas, no defense mechanisms up _ you can perform at a
very high level. That's what pushes my buttons.''
</P>
<P>
   At heart, Hitchcock is a teacher. Next to his family, it's what
he loves most in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult time I'll have is when someone tells me,
`Hitch, you can't teach any more.' The wins, the losses, the
awards, the Stanley Cup, that's all window dressing. The day
somebody tells me I can't do that anymore will be a very tough day
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock had an emotionally tough day two years ago in the
playoffs. When Edmonton coach Ron Lowe told his players, ``The Fat
Man wants us, he's got us!'' Hitchcock never blinked, but he nearly
bled to death inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're unbelievable at masking that stuff, but that cut
big-time deep,'' Hitchcock said. ``When you're walking down the
road and somebody whispers something, you pretend you don't hear
it, but you hear it. You learn to block it out instead of using it
to motivate yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's comment, though, cut Hitchcock like none other ever had.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was embarrassing because it drew other people into the
fight,'' Hitchcock said. ``All of a sudden the fans are in the
fight, the media's in the fight, and (Lowe) has to defend himself
and it's all because of how I look physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe later apologized ``in his own way'' but Hitchcock always
blamed himself more than the man who had made the insensitive
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look back on it, I'm more disappointed in my
stubbornness in not addressing the (obesity) situation earlier,''
Hitchcock said. ``I should never have put myself in that position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the life I have now and if I hadn't done something
to change, I would have thrown it all away. I wouldn't have an
opportunity to sit here in Vail. I wouldn't have had a chance to go
to Dallas. I wouldn't have my family. Some days I just shake my
head and say, `You stupid ass.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Hitchcock has made so much progress in his journey back
from obesity, he now serves as a benchmark for others fighting the
same battle. He gets 10 to 15 phone calls a year from people
needing help. He tries to share his own experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back and the lesson that I've learned is, when you have
to make a change, you have to make that change 100 percent or it
never works,'' he said. ``You can't play catchup. You can't tell
yourself, `Oh, I ate five hamburgers today, but I'll catch up
tomorrow.' It won't work. You get in and you stick with it and go
the best route you can and never allow yourself to play catchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you understand that you're in a daily battle and
you're prepared to live in that daily battle, you're fine. But if
you think you're not in it, and you're on the outside and you say,
`I don't have that problem and I don't have to worry about it,'
you're just hiding your head in the sand. Eventually you're going
to gain all the weight back.''
</P>
<P>
   Like alcoholics, Hitchcock said, people with eating disorders
have to learn to like themselves again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided that I'm important,'' Hitchcock said. ``I'm
important to me. I've got a family and I've got to take care of
them. I've got obligations there. I can't afford not to be good to
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goals are small ones and for some people they might be
humorous, but they're mine. I've started to lift weights and to be
able to do that and structure my body back is a goal. I want to be
able to run, to jog. I can run a hundred yards maybe. But to be
able to jog around the track a few times, that's going to be
tremendous. That's a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Hitchcock understands that he hasn't won the war and
probably never will.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never going to be over,'' he said. ``It's always going to
be a part of my life, part of my legacy, part of who I am and who I
was. But the nicest part about it now is that people are judging me
on the job that I do as a husband, as a father, as a hockey coach
and as a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's pretty cool.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
