<HEADLINE>
KARALAHTI CAN'T CROSS FINNISH LINE 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By ROGER PHILLIPS 
c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ When Jere Karalahti signed with the Los
Angeles Kings in July, it gave the 24-year-old Finnish defenseman
two months to prepare for his first NHL training camp, and two
months to prepare for his move to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   With a 1996 arrest for heroin possession on his record, it was
clear from the day Karalahti signed that special efforts would be
required to enable him to enter the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But as training camp's fourth day concluded Wednesday, Karalahti
remained in Finland, unable to join his new team because of
difficulty obtaining a work visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing new,'' said Don Baizley, Karalahti's agent.
``The expectation is we'll hear by the end of the week. Obviously,
we're hoping and expecting things will be resolved favorably by
that time. But we won't know until the end of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings general manager Dave Taylor sounded a bit annoyed by the
situation Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, we'd like to have him,'' Taylor said of the 1993
sixth-round draft choice. ``I think (Karalahti) understood back in
July (when he signed) what was required. Unfortunately, it's
dragged on, but we have to deal with it. With his history, we were
aware there could be some complications. ... If you have a prior
record, as he does, my understanding is you need a waiver. He
doesn't have it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have gone to great lengths to add Karalahti to their
roster because he has been considered in recent years one of the
best players in the world not playing in the NHL. After his arrest,
Karalahti reportedly underwent eight months of drug therapy, and
tests since his arrest have shown him to be heroin free.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are protected in the event Karalahti is unable to
enter the United States. His one-year, $700,000 contract contains a
$200,000 reporting bonus, the other $500,000 to be paid for
playing. Taylor said that assuming Karalahti ultimately is able to
join the Kings, he does not anticipate difficulty when Karalahti
has to make trips with the team across the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more a U.S. issue,'' Taylor said. ``He is working for a
U.S. club, and will be paid in U.S. dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   __ First scrimmage: After three days of drills, the Kings held
their first scrimmage Wednesday, with Team B defeating Team A, 5-4.
Goal scorers for Team B were Aki Berg, Bryan Smolinski, Steve
McKenna, Glen Murray and Donald MacLean. Scoring for Team A were
Ziggy Palffy, Luc Robitaille, Len Barrie and Kevin Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Andy Murray, who watched from the stands at Iceoplex, said
he liked what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I challenged a couple of players pretty assertively (before
the game) because I wasn't happy with them,'' Murray said without
naming names. ``It's nice to see you can challenge them and they
raise the level of their play.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Loose pucks: All-Star defenseman Mattias Norstrom remains
unsigned and is at not camp. Taylor said he and agent Don Meehan
have been speaking every day. ``We've had discussions and are going
to continue to work at it,'' Taylor said. ``But we don't have a
deal yet.'' ... Right wing Scott Thomas, destined for a
minor-league assignment, suffered a right knee injury during the
scrimmage. The extent was not disclosed. ... Murray said he plans
to trim his roster Sunday. ... The Kings open exhibition play
Saturday in Las Vegas against Phoenix and Tuesday at the Forum
against Colorado, both games at 7:30 p.m., both televised by Fox
Sports West.
</P>
</TEXT>
