<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MOTOR SPEEDWAY ADDS WEEKEND ON NEW COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A fourth weekend of racing, featuring exotic
prototype and production-based sports cars of the American Le Mans
Series, has been booked for a road course to be constructed at
Texas Motor Speedway for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   The ALMS-sanctioned Grand Prix of Texas is scheduled for Sept.
2, the Saturday of Labor Day weekend, on a road course that will be
carved through the east side of the track's sprawling infield. Like
the Daytona International Speedway, the road-course at TMS also
will incorporate portions of the 1.5-mile quad-oval and its
24-degree banked turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most asked question we get here is, `When are you going to
build a road course?' '' said Eddie Gossage, executive vice
president and general manager of TMS. ``There's a lot of
road-racing fans here and I answer e-mails every day about a road
course. We've decided to go ahead and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ALMS road race _ which Gossage plans to run primarily at
night _ will be the only single-day, stand-alone package on the
2000 TMS calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennzoil World of Outlaws, NASCAR Busch Grand National and
NASCAR Winston Cup Series are scheduled to open the season March
30-April 2. The renamed DIRECTV 500 Winston Cup race is set for
April 2, and will be preceded by the Texas 300 Busch GN race on
April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Outlaws' inaugural Spring Sprint Classic is scheduled for
March 30-31 on a four-tenths-mile dirt track that will be
constructed north of the speedway's offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Pep Boys Indy Racing League and NASCAR's Craftsman Truck
Series will compete on the 1.5-mile speedway June 8-10. The trucks
will run the Pronto Auto Parts 400 on June 9 under the lights, with
the IRL's Longhorn 500 night race scheduled for June 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Outlaws, Craftsman Truck series and IRL will be showcased
during the final race weekend Oct. 12-15. The Outlaws will compete
in the Texas World Finals Oct. 12 and 14. NASCAR's trucks will run
in the Bluebonnet 300 on Oct. 13 and the IRL's Lone Star 500 is
booked for Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said TMS' season-ticket package will cover the same six
races as in 1999 _ the NASCAR Winston Cup/Busch events and the two
IRL and Craftsman Truck races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Season-ticket holders don't have to buy tickets to the
American Le Mans Series, don't have to buy tickets to the World of
Outlaws,'' Gossage said during a news conference at The Speedway
Club. Season-ticket packages go on sale today at 9 a.m. at the
speedway, which continues to diversify its racing menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have events,'' said Gossage, who has signed a
three-year contract with the ALMS. ``We are first and foremost an
oval track that runs Winston Cup and Indy-cars. We don't want to
lose that focus, but we want to be able to offer a little bit of
everything to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said the design and length of the road-course, and the
distance of the ALMS race that will be run upon it, has yet to be
decided. Most events in the fledgling ALMS series are contested in
three hours or less. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
