<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR TO BEAR DOWN ON RUSHING DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Baylor's defensive difficulties against the run
have ceased to be news.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears surrendered 275 rushing yards a game in 1997. They
improved an average of 61 yards last season, but ranked 98th in
Division I-A.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new coaching staff in town. But has anything changed?
</P>
<P>
   Not measured by the 350 rushing yards the Bears surrendered in a
30-29 overtime loss to Boston College on Saturday. The Bears in]
hadn't given up that much since being for 410 yards by Nebraska in
'97.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's changed?'' Baylor defensive tackle Dwight Johnson
asked. ``After our first loss, we're not down. We're really
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   A new coaching staff does a lot for attitude, and perhaps
Johnson's outlook is testament to that factor. But new coach Kevin
Steele maintains there is nothing wrong with Baylor's defense that
smarts can't fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to play better run defense,'' Steele said. ``The
positive thing is (against Boston College) it was not the calls,
not the plan. We just needed to see things full speed. We need to
eliminate the mental errors and the alignment mistakes, which we
can do. When I first came off the field, I thought we were
manhandled a little more than we had been.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele will be looking for improvement in Saturday's home opener
against Nevada-Las Vegas, though Wednesday's suspension of senior
defensive end Charles Foster robs the Bears of front-line depth.
Help may be on the way, however. Senior defensive tackle James
Calvin is expected to return to the lineup for the Big 12
Conference opener against Oklahoma on Sept. 18. He underwent
arthroscopic knee surgery three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense of urgency after the last snap of the
(Boston College) game,'' Baylor defensive coordinator Andrea
``Brick'' Haley said. ``I do see us being a pretty good defense.
The kids believe in what we're doing; they understand what's going
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not backing down from anyone, not changing anything. We
have a plan, and we're going to work it. This is a great league for
running backs. We need to make it a great league for Baylor's
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Haley said he takes blame for Boston College's inflated rushing
total, chalking it up to halftime adjustments he made that weren't
carried out. Boston College gained 142 yards rushing in the first
half and 208 in the second half. And Haley points out that 350
yards rushing often means a 50-point game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about all this is all the things we saw are
correctable, and that's a positive,'' Haley said. ``We've got them
playing hard. The key is to get them playing smart.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-08-99 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
